<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBS-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT EASY, BUT THE CUBS FIND THEI WAY INTO THE POST-SEASON
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Sammy Sosa dd not hit four home runs to share the
record with Mark McGwire. Steve Trachsel did not pitch a no-hitter.
But the Chicago Cubs did gain a chance to win their first
post-season series since 1908.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs, who last won the World Series in that post-season 90
years ago, advanced to the first round of this year's playoff by
defeating the San Francisco Giants, 5-3, Monday night and winning
the first playoff for the National League wild-card spot in the
four-year history of the wild-card format.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs, who last played post-season games in 1989, will play
the Braves in Atlanta on Wednesday afternoon. They were put on the
plane to Atlanta chiefly by Trachsel, who did not allow a hit until
he had one out in the seventh inning; by Felix Heredia, who retired
Barry Bonds on an inning-ending grounder with the bases loaded in
the seventh; by Terry Mulholland, who held Bonds to a sacrifice fly
with the bases loaded and none out in the ninth; and by Gary Gaetti
and Matt Mieske, 1998 newcomers to the Cubs, who each drove in two
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa did not hit a home run, leaving him with 66 and officially
putting McGwire into the record book as the single-season
record-holder with 70 home runs. Sosa batted 15 times without
hitting a home run since he hit No. 66 last Friday night and
slipped ahead of McGwire for all of 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, however, continued his most valuable player contribution
to the Cubs, stroking a pair of singles and scoring the final two
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many other seasons when the Cubs disappointed themselves
and their fans, pregame preparations did not become washed away in
the tears of another failure. Clubhouse workers had rolled up heavy
plastic covers on the tops of the players' lockers, waiting there
to be dropped over the fronts of the lockers to spare their
contents from a Champagne celebration. Jimmy Bank, the traveling
secretary, had prepared travel itineraries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We leave tomorrow afternoon for Atlanta,'' Bank said before
the game to one player who had asked. ``I'm going to give out the
itinerary after the game tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   And he was able to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Trachsel, a 27-year-old right-hander, had labored recently _ in
fact, since he threw the pitch that became the home run that broke
Roger Maris's record. In four starts beginning with that game on
Sept. 8, Trachsel had been battered for 19 earned runs in 212/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner, on the other hand, had not lost a game since July 30,
winning 5 of his 10 subsequent starts. Yet it was Gardner whose
string of shutout innings ended first.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Rodriguez opened the Cubs' fifth inning with a single to
right-center field, and Gaetti followed with a home run, a fly ball
on an 0-2 fastball that sent Barry Bonds drifting back toward the
ivy-covered wall in front of the left-field bleachers. But when
Bonds reached the wall, the ball kept going.
</P>
<P>
   Gaetti, whom the Cubs signed on his 40th birthday, Aug. 19,
after St. Louis released him, thus produced the first runs in a
rare playoff game for the playoffs. Only three times since division
play began in 1969 had teams played an extra game for the right to
play post-season games.
</P>
<P>
   But this was the first time in the four-year history of the
baseball wild card that teams had to play an extra game to
determine the winner of that spot in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants reached this juncture even though they had not led in
the wild-card race since July 18. A six-game winning streak last
week catapulted them into position to win this trip to Wrigley
Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs had led most of the time since July 18, let the lead
slip away to the Mets with a week remaining in the season, then
rallied just enough to retain a chance to play October games.
</P>
<P>
   Trachsel certainly was intent on getting an October start.
</P>
<P>
   The team leader in walks, he exhibited his customary wildness
with walks in the second, third, fourth and fifth innings. In the
fourth, in fact, he walked two batters and hit another, loading the
bases with two out. But with a chance to put the Giants ahead,
Brian Johnson, their catcher, took a third strike.
</P>
<P>
   Trachsel did not allow the batters who walked in the other three
innings _ two with two out, one with one out _ to advance beyond
first base.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Cubs cracked through Gardner's shutout shell, they
widened the gap.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Johnson led off the sixth inning with a single to left
field and, one out later, Sosa stroked a single to center, sending
Johnson scampering to third and Gardner trudging to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Rodriguez, a left-hander, replaced Gardner and walked the
left-handed-hitting Mark Grace, loading the bases. Jim Riggleman,
the Cubs' manager, then pulled Rodriguez, a left-handed hitter, and
used a right-hander, Matt Mieske, who had gone to the plate only
110 times in 76 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   But the rust did not impede Mieske's swing. A .292 hitter, he
lined a single to right, and Johnson and Sosa raced home with the
third and fourth runs. John Johnstone then relieved Rodriguez and
induced Gaetti to ground into an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Fortified with a second pair of runs, Trachsel went out in the
seventh to extend his hitless pitching. He did so with the first
batter as Charlie Hayes lined to Mickey Morandini at second base.
But six and a third innings would be as far as he would take his
no-hit effort because Brent Mayne, batting for Johnson, swung at
the first pitch he saw and lined it to right for a single.
</P>
<P>
   When Trachsel, after receiving an ovation from the crowd of
39,556, walked another pinch-hitter, Armando Rios, Riggleman
decided six walks would be as far as he would go. He called for
Matt Karchner in a double switch that sent Orlando Merced to left
field in place of Mieske, who had replaced Henry Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   There was still no sign of Brant Brown, who was playing left
field last week in Milwaukee when he dropped a two-out,
bases-loaded fly ball that cost the Cubs a victory that might have
obviated the need for this playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Merced, however, turned out to be in the right place at the
right time because Stan Javier lofted a foul fly near the
left-field stands that Merced leaped against the wall to catch.
</P>
<P>
   After Shawon Dunston, the third pinch-hitter in the inning, got
an infield single with a grounder over second base, the left-handed
Felix Heredia replaced Karchner to pitch to the left-handed-hitting
Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds has had no success in four post-season series in his
career, and though this game was considered part of the regular
season, his difficulty continued. With no hits in his first three
at-bats, Bonds took a ball and a strike, then hit a grounder to
Grace at first for the third out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
