<SLUG> BC-SENIOR-SEX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY: SENIORS FINDING LIFE GOOD UNDER THE COVERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Grandma and grandpa might be mum about it, but if
they're sexually active, the odds are that after 60 they enjoy sex
as much or more than in their 40s, according to a national study.
</P>
<P>
   ``The study goes against one of the myths that it's all downhill
after age 50,'' said Michael Reinemer, a spokesman for the National
Council on the Aging, which sponsored the senior sex survey
released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Three out of four people surveyed who are 60 or older and are
sexually active said their sex life is as good or better than when
they were younger, Reinemer said. To be deemed sexually active, the
participants had to have sex at least once a month. Fewer than half
of all senior citizens are sexually active, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also shows that sex continues to be important in
relationships with people over 50,'' Reinemer said.
</P>
<P>
   Kess Kessler, 61, a resident of the L.A. suburb of Woodland
Hills, couldn't agree more. Married for 40 years, he believes sex
is even better than when he and his wife were in their 20s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just better quality, two to three times a week. The
children are out of the house and I'm retired,'' he said, during a
break from shopping in Woodland Hills. ``It's true. It's better now
because we know each other better and physically I haven't
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Whitehead, 65, visiting her daughter in the L.A. suburb
of Tarzana on Monday, echoed Kessler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say sex is better when you're older because you don't
have all the worries about pregnancy and also about AIDS, if you
stay with the same person,'' Whitehead said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of all Americans age 60 or older engage in sexual
activity at least once a month, according to the random survey of
1,300 older Americans conducted by Roper Starch Worldwide, a market
research and public opinion firm.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer Inc., the manufacturer of the anti-impotence drug Viagra,
paid for the study.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which included respondents from the Los Angeles
area, also found that four in 10 desire sex more frequently,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Woodland Hills resident Mike Gard, 76, said the frequency of sex
with his wife of 26 years might not be as high as in their 40s, but
``it's equally as good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's really important or not, but it's been
there. It's something you get used to, I guess,'' said Gard, who
said he still engages in sex with his wife about once a month.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-nine percent of those surveyed said they are satisfied
with the amount of sex they currently engage in, while another 39
percent said they want more.
</P>
<P>
   Men were more than twice as likely as women to report wanting
more sex. And only 4 percent said they desire less sex.
</P>
<P>
   And 61 percent of men, as compared with 37 percent of women,
reported that they were sexually active, according to the study.
The gap partially results from a woman's longer life expectancy.
</P>
<P>
   Those surveyed who said they had sex less than once a month also
said they have less emotional satisfaction in their sex lives
compared to when they were in their 40s.
</P>
<P>
   When older people were not sexually active, it was usually
because they lacked a partner or had a medical condition, said Neal
Cutler, the National Council on the Aging's director of survey
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``This study underscores the enduring importance of sex among
older men and women _ even among those who report infrequent sexual
activity,'' Cutler said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the qualities Americans look for in their partner in
their more seasoned years? Nine out of 10 pointed to a high moral
character, pleasant personality, sense of humor and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Widowed and over 55 years old, Jan Sayre of Woodland Hills said
she opts for the gentleman over the stud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if he's a dude. He can be bald,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The respondents were interviewed by mail from June 19 to Aug.
11, rather than by phone because of the sensitive nature of the
questions. The margin of error was 3.5 percentage points. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
