<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-NIIZUMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORU NIIZUMA, 67, SCULPTOR AND TEACHER
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minoru Niizuma, a sculptor and educator who taught at the
Brooklyn Museum Art School and Columbia University, died on Sept. 5
at the University Hospital and Medical Center at Stony Brook, N.Y.
He was 67 and lived in East Hampton, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a stroke, a family member said.
</P>
<P>
   Niizuma was born in Tokyo in 1930 and graduated from the
National Tokyo University of Fine Arts in 1955. He moved to New
York in 1959 and had his first solo show in New York City at the
Howard Wise Gallery in 1966. He had retrospectives at the Seibu
Museum of Art in Tokyo in 1976 and at the Gulbenkian Museum in
Lisbon in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Niizuma taught at the Brooklyn Museum Art School from 1964 to
1970, then at Columbia University for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   He worked predominantly in stone, especially marble, and was
known for his sensitive use of its textures and veins. His designs
ranged from the geometric to the organic and sometimes used
patterns reminiscent of folk art, fabrics and ritual vessels.
</P>
<P>
   His work is in public collections in the United States, Europe
and Japan, including the Museum of Modern Art and the Solomon R.
Guggenheim Museum in Manhattan, the Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture
Garden in Washington, the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art and
the National Museum of Modern Art in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Niizuma's two marriages ended in divorce. He is survived by
three sons: Ta Andre of Tokyo, and Ko Christopher and Arata Peter,
both of New York City, and one grandchild.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 0012EDT &QL; 
