<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACING NOTEBOOK: SKIP AWAY BACK AT WORK; LIL'S LAD FINISHES LAST;
NEW DIRECTIONS FOR BARTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nine days after his sweeping score in the Woodward Stakes for
his ninth straight victory, Skip Away went back to work Monday
morning and was up to his old tricks. He breezed half a mile at
Belmont Park in a snappy 46 3/5 seconds in his first workout for
his next performance, in the Jockey Club Gold Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-year-old gray superstar of racing had Jerry Bailey riding,
with his trainer, Sonny Hine, monitoring every move. He needs to
win $500,000 to pass Cigar's record total of $9.9 million in
earnings, and he can do it if he wins one of the last two races of
his career: the $1 million Gold Cup and the $4 million Breeders'
Cup Classic. The winner's share for the Gold Cup is $600,000; for
the Classic, about $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry thought he went in 47 or 48 seconds,'' Hine said later,
clearly impressed with his horse's fast time. ``You hate to breeze
a horse too much, but there's nothing else you can do with him. He
came out of the Woodward sharp, and he got too hard to gallop. He
is just an amazing horse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jockey Club Gold Cup will be run one week from Saturday as
the centerpiece of Belmont's Breeders' Cup Preview Day. The
Breeders' Cup, with seven races and combined purses of $12 million,
will be run three weeks later at Churchill Downs in Louisville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Lil's Lad Flat Again
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Bailey returned in the afternoon to ride Lil's Lad, who
was one of the favorites for the Kentucky Derby last spring before
being forced to withdraw because of bone chips in an ankle. When he
made his comeback one month ago, Lil's Lad ran fourth in an
allowance race at Saratoga. When he ran again Monday, he went off
as the 1-5 favorite in an allowance at Belmont, and finished fifth
and last. What is happening?
</P>
<P>
   His trainer, Neil Howard, seemed not only puzzled, but also
speechless. ``There's not much I can say,'' Howard said. Where will
he run next? ``I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said: ``He just couldn't keep up. It was a pretty flat
performance, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Flashing Tammany won the race, followed by Wouldn't We All.
</P>
<P>
   A Change of Pace for Barton
</P>
<P>
   Donna Barton, who rode 1,131 winners during her 11-year career
as one of the leading female jockeys, gave her farewell performance
Sunday at Turfway Park in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old rider from New Mexico said she would become a
student next spring at the University of Louisville. She also
announced that she would be married on Nov. 16 to Frank Brothers,
the trainer.
</P>
<P>
   She is the daughter of the pioneer female jockey Patti Barton,
and was the jockey for Hennessy and Boston Harbor as well as the
regular work rider for Thunder Gulch, Serena's Song and Timber
Country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became a jockey so that I could make money to go to
college,'' Barton said. ``This is one of the happiest and saddest
days of my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
