A9303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     09-29 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ONE NIGHT TO CELEBRATE THE CUBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Half past three Monday afternoon, they pulled up the
gates at the intersection of Clark and Addison and rolled out the
old kiosks from which the Wrigley Field programs are hawked at a
modern-day miracle price of 75 cents. There was one last ball game
in a remarkable baseball season, and no team was more entitled to
this prime-time slot than the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   They deserved their mini-World Series, their wild-card victory
over the stubborn Giants, for Ernie Banks, for Billy Williams, for
all the proud Cubbies who never experienced the thrill of looking
up at the center field scoreboard to see no out-of-town results.
They deserved it for Harry Caray, for contributing to the season
young Kerry Wood, for the enthusiasm they showed as the competitive
bystanders when Mark McGwire clubbed his 62nd home run in St. Louis
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Trachsel, server of the most memorable of all 70 McGwire
blasts, deserved to have the Cubs' bullpen not blow _ barely _ his
six and one-third innings of one-hit shutout ball. Most of all,
Sammy Sosa deserved this night, this 5-3 victory, for 66 home runs,
for pushing McGwire to astonishing heights, for sharing his spirit
and saving McGwire from his sullen self of early summer.
</P>
<P>
   All this anticipation, all this anxiety, all this energy, for
the likelihood of being first-round fodder for the Braves. The
Yankees and the Red Sox fought for the genuine division
championship in 1978, not to be the best of those who also ran.
Good for them. Every team lives with its own history of success and
failure. Every team has its own unique set of expectations,
priorities and perspective. This was so much more than a playoff to
join the playoffs for the Cubs. It was a chance to win the race _
any race _ knowing that the snickering masses believed all along
they would collapse, drop out, simply because of who they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spring training, a lot of people were picking the Cubs to
be the first sixth-place team in a five-team division,'' said Mark
Grace. ``We persevered. This is the most fun I've ever had playing
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace, the only remaining Cub from the 1989 team that lost to
the Giants in the playoffs, claimed beforehand that he had
exorcised the horrific defeats of the past 10 days, pronounced the
glass half full. If the Cubs could win, then they could drink to
beating the prohibitive odds of having the Brant Brown-like
calamity that sure seemed possible when Michael Jordan fired the
ceremonial first pitch over the catcher's head. Imminent disaster
has always been the Cubs' companion, which is why Grace tried to
explain to Gary Gaetti and Rod Beck a few weeks ago that this was
no ordinary chase they had stepped into. ``I know you guys have
been in the post-season,'' he told them. ``But until you do it in
Chicago, you don't know what a great feeling it is.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, win or lose, last night belonged to Cub lore.
For this one game, it was easy to ignore the fact that beyond their
charming logo and timeless home, the Cubs are owned by a rich media
company, just like the Dodgers, and they have one of baseball's
highest payrolls. Only history, at this point, has the right to
define the Cubs as lovable losers trying to conquer all odds, but
this has been a historic season. On this occasion, the slipper fit.
</P>
<P>
   Gaetti gave the Cubs the lead by lofting a two-run homer to left
off the Giants' Mark Gardner in the fifth. Sosa, free of McGwire at
last, cut down on his swing and stroked a key single in another
two-run flurry in the sixth. When the Giants loaded the bases with
two out for Barry Bonds in the seventh, a November chill enveloped
the ball park. In came a southpaw, Felix Heredia. Bonds grounded to
Grace. Bill Murray grabbed Harry Caray's old microphone to sing
baseball's most famous song, but it was the late-inning Wrigley
crowd roars that were music to Billy Williams's ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been there, but when you make it to the World
Series, I know there has to be less pressure than trying to get
there,'' said the Cubs' bench coach and resident Hall of Famer.
``Not as much pressure as this.''
</P>
<P>
   This game, of course, was more about September than it was
October, a month that will belong to the Braves and the Astros and,
of course, the Yankees. There is a big, bad baseball world out
there, but for one night, its eyes were upon Sosa and his Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   No scoreboard to watch. One game left, sudden death, Cubs win,
Cubs win! Good for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
