<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' DESTINY MIGHT BE TRACED TO 1997 SURRENDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ We've talked about ``The Play,'' when broken-toed
Will Clark beat out the slow roller to second base for the base hit
that crystallized this Texas Rangers season, with proper awe and
reverence.
</P>
<P>
   We've offered homage to ``The Home Run'' that followed Clark's
play, when Pudge Rodriguez smoked a two-run shot into the Baltimore
ether to complete the comeback that would fuel the run for the
title.
</P>
<P>
   We've analyzed and pinpointed Doug Melvin's flurry of
trading-deadline deals as the ultimate difference-makers down the
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   None of those, however, set off the chain of events that will
put the Rangers on the field Tuesday night at Yankee Stadium for
the first game of the Division Series against the American League
East champion Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The stage was set for the Rangers to capture the 1998 AL West
title not by some aggressive play, not by some mighty stroke of the
bat, not even by Melvin's July 31 blockbusters.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers won the West in '98 when they raised the white flag
in '97.
</P>
<P>
   Surrender then led to victory now. Strange how history works,
isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   It was in July 1997, when Melvin began retooling his team for
this season and, ironically, it paid off in a champagne shower in
the stadium the Rangers hate most in the world Friday night at the
Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Would the Rangers be at Yankee Stadium on Tuesday if Melvin
hadn't decided to trade free agent-to-be third baseman Dean Palmer
for center fielder Tom Goodwin after the All-Star break in '97?
</P>
<P>
   Palmer's early departure cleared the way for young Fernando
Tatis to get major-league experience at third. Tatis became the
major piece in the deal that would bring pitcher Todd Stottlemyre
and shortstop Royce Clayton to the Rangers two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Or what if Melvin hadn't sent Ken Hill to the Angels for pitcher
Matt Perisho and catcher Jim Leyritz, who would then be packaged
off to Boston along with outfielder Damon Buford for future 19-game
winner Aaron Sele?
</P>
<P>
   Or if in August of '97, he hadn't made perhaps the deal of his
life by sending useful left-handed reliever Ed Vosburg to the
Marlins for young right-hander Rick Helling? Who knew that Helling
would blossom into an immediate 20-game winner?
</P>
<P>
   ``The alternative \Rin '97\S was to just sit back and play it
out,'' Melvin said the day after the Rangers had clinched their
second division title in three years. ``I don't know what we'd have
done then.''
</P>
<P>
   Safe to say, they wouldn't be where they are now, facing the
team that just broke the American League record for most victories
in a regular season.
</P>
<P>
   If this was a fairy tale, then this would have been a magical
season for the Rangers. It was not and there may not be an
``everyone lived happily ever after'' at the end of this story.
</P>
<P>
   Their starting rotation _ with the exception of Helling and Sele
_ was abysmal until the final month.
</P>
<P>
   Their defense was sloppy and mental errors drove manager Johnny
Oates up the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Offense carried this team this far. But to beat the Yankees _ or
anyone else in the playoffs _ the Rangers must pitch and play
defense.
</P>
<P>
   After his team had clinched, Oates made positioning his starting
rotation and resting his regulars his top priorities. For the
Rangers to win, Stottlemyre and Helling must repay that faith by
producing at least one victory in the first two games here Tuesday
and Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers cannot leave New York down 0-2 and expect to be
back.
</P>
<P>
   They must play this anticipating a full five-game series. Win
one of the first two here, win one of the two games at The Ballpark
in Arlington, then come back to Yankee Stadium for Game 5 and take
their chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience we gained from the playoffs against the Yankees
two years ago will be invaluable,'' Clark said. ``We've been
through this before. We know what it's going to be like. Let's play
some baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   No looking ahead. No thinking about tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went into the last week of the season as if we were facing
seven one-game series,'' Oates said. ``Each game represented a
chance to be a step closer to where we wanted to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have to do the same thing in this series. We can't
worry about what's going to happen tomorrow night or when we get
back to Texas. We have to play this game right here, right now, and
play it as if it's the last one we'll ever play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will be perhaps the most decisive underdogs in
playoff history. The Yanks are the ones who have been magical this
season. The Rangers, according to most of the experts, should be
happy just to be on the same field with them.
</P>
<P>
   Fate, though, has a way of arranging these monumental collisions
when you least expect them. A lot of pieces have had to fall into
place over the last 18 months for the Rangers to be here.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of quirky, what-if path that historians often look
back on later and call destiny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
