<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-FANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUB FANS SAVOR A RARITY: A GAME THAT IS DECISIVE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The red-brick temple at 1060 West Addison Street is
what baseball lost and has tried to get back. Wrigley Field is a
neighborhood ball park with green grass, green ivy and green seats,
every one filled with a baseball fan.
</P>
<P>
   Working the hand-operated scoreboard at the 84-year-old Wrigley
was an easy job Monday night, as only one game was played in the
baseball world: The Cubs beat the Giants, 5-3, for the National
League wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, the old and the young were in old Weeghman
Park, all giddy with anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Dusty B., are you a gambling man?'' yelled Billy
Williams, the Cub coach and Hall of Famer, giving a hug to Giants
Manager Dusty Baker. ``Winner takes all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is incredible,'' said Jason Maxwell, a 26-year-old Cubs
infielder with a total of three career at-bats. ``I've never seen
anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrigley was rocking at 8:22 p.m., but not from the El rumbling
past right field. Gary Gaetti lofted a home run into the wire
basket, barely into the right-field bleachers. Brian Helmus, the
scoreboard operator, posted a yellow 2 on the Cubs' line for the
fifth inning, while the Giants still did not have a hit.
</P>
<P>
   A woman was thrown out of Wrigley for throwing her beer onto the
field during the celebration, but that wasn't the last baseball
memory of the evening for her 6-year-old son. Her husband made the
decision any Cubs fan and father would make, staying at the game
with their son and giving Mom cab fare home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody got extras?'' was the plaintive cry out on Sheffield
Avenue, Wrigleyville's Main Street, where all the 39,000 seats and
standing-room tickets were long gone. Brad Staab had his $12
bleacher ticket, waiting all day with his carefully lettered sign,
``Next Year Is Tonite.'' He knew the unwritten rules: keep the
souvenir of a lifetime if Sosa hits one; throw it back if the
Giants do.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan knew where Chicago's attention was focused. He
was here to throw out the ceremonial first pitch, wearing a Sammy
Sosa jersey. Jordan proved again that baseball is not his sport,
sailing the pitch over Sosa's head.
</P>
<P>
   In Section 118, Sosa's brothers were ready with their Dominican
flags. The steel girders shook when Sosa came to bat for the first
time, but he hit a checked-swing grounder to the pitcher for an
inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Sammy! Give me five,'' one sign read, pleading for Sosa
to surpass Mark McGwire's 70 home runs, despite the wind blowing
in.
</P>
<P>
   The joke of the day at Wrigley went this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, did you hear what happened?'' one fan says to another.
``McGwire hit two more.''
</P>
<P>
   A pith-helmeted fellow known as the Bleacher Preacher wandered
Waveland Avenue with a Giants voodoo doll, allowing fans to stick
in hundreds of pins.
</P>
<P>
   Long-suffering Cubs fans had hoped this game would help exorcise
the ghosts of a century of Cubs failure. ``'69 Mets,'' read Mike
Young's sign, ``'89 Giants, '84 Padres.'' He had marked through the
Mets and had his pen ready for the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   The Rolling Stones were blaring on the stadium speakers, with a
chorus that could be the Cubs' theme song: ``You make a grown man
cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Here baseball is no pastime, it's a religion. This is where Babe
Ruth hit his ``called shot'' in the 1932 World Series, where Ernie
Banks hit his 500th home run, where Sosa hit Nos. 61 and 62.
</P>
<P>
   The old pink house beyond the right-field bleachers at 1038 West
Waveland Avenue, where so many home runs have landed on the porch,
has its own yellow foul pole, 461 feet from home plate. ``To be
demolished Oct. '98,'' a sign on the house read. ``Thanks for the
memories.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
