<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERAL GROUP SAYS IT IS PREPARING AD CAMPAIGN DEFENDING CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A liberal political group plans to spend hundreds
of thousands of dollars on an advertising campaign that extols the
accomplishments of President Clinton and attacks Republicans for
neglecting everyday issues while chasing the Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're planning an ad campaign that focuses on the fact that
Congress has not been working on issues that matter to the American
people,'' said Mike Lux, political director of the Washington-based
group, People for the American Way. ``They're obsessed with
scandal, cynicism and partisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Lux said the group was working on scripts now and hoped to have
the television advertisements produced by the end of the week. He
said the group had not determined where the advertisements would be
broadcast, although it hoped to buy air time in national and local
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign would serve a dual mission _ trying to generate
support for the beleaguered president and trying to bolster
Democratic candidates' successes in the midterm elections. The
organization alerted the White House this week of its plans, which
were reported on Monday night in early editions of The Washington
Post.
</P>
<P>
   The group is scheduled to meet later this week with James
Carville, who was Clinton's campaign manager in 1992 and is one of
his most outspoken defenders. Carville declared on television on
Sunday that he was going to war with House Speaker Newt Gingrich _
a statement that worried some moderate Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising strategy closely follows the course taken by
Clinton and other Democrats within the past week. They suddenly
emerged from a posture of contrition and apology to take a
combative stance against Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks during a three-day fund-raising trip over the
weekend, Clinton accused Congress of ignoring issues like
education, classroom size and Social Security to pursue scandal.
Hillary Rodham Clinton, on a separate trip for Democratic
candidates, echoed that theme.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans retorted that Clinton had left town on a political
junket while many legislative issues remained unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders and Clinton allies have been trying to
persuade Republicans in Congress to accept a deal in which Clinton
would be censured by Congress, and perhaps fined, rather than face
impeachment. Republicans have resisted any effort at compromise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 0018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0012 </DOCNO>
