r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RANGERS-WETTELAND-TEX     09-29 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-WETTELAND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WETTELAND READY TO CLOSE 1996 VOID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Perhaps this will be the season when right-hander
John Wetteland becomes ``the final piece of the puzzle.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin, whose Texas Rangers oppose New York
Tuesday night in Game 1 of their best-of-five, American League
Division Series, regrets introducing Wetteland in that manner in
December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers signed Wetteland, the former Yankees closer, to a
four-year contract worth $23 million in an attempt ``to take us to
the next level,'' Melvin said then.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' executive laments those words to this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair to say that about any one player,'' said Melvin,
who during 1997 witnessed the Rangers finish 13 games behind the AL
West champion Seattle Mariners. ``I guess I said that in the
excitement of signing a player as good as him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your club changes dramatically from year to year, so one
player doesn't have that kind of impact. It was probably a little
bit unfair to think that he was going to come over and make things
altogether different.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, though, the 32-year-old closer will make a difference
as the Rangers enter the postseason for the second time in three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``My expectations of myself far exceed anything anyone could
expect of me, and that's all I need to worry about,'' said
Wetteland, who was 3-1 with 42 saves and a 2.03 earned-run average
this season. ``If I don't get it done, I guarantee you that no one
will feel worse than me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers signed Wetteland before the 1997 season as a
response to their deficiencies in the bullpen. The Rangers lost
their 1996 Division Series to the world champion Yankees in four
games, and the respective strength of the bullpens played a
significant role in that outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no loss demonstrated that more than Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Darren Oliver, who allowed the Yankees only one run
through eight innings, went to the mound for the ninth inning with
a one-run lead. Manager Johnny Oates removed Oliver after
consecutive singles by shortstop Derek Jeter and left fielder Tim
Raines, but right-hander Mike Henneman could not protect that lead,
and the Rangers lost, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland likely would have begun that ninth inning had he been
the Rangers' closer then. The organization viewed his arrival as a
vehicle to augment their 90-victory team from 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, though, never became a significant factor during a
disastrous 1997 season marred by injuries, poor defense and an
unreliable rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, who went 7-2 with 31 saves and a 1.94 ERA in 1997,
became so disillusioned by the turn of events that while in Chicago
in July he asked Oates if the Rangers would be better served with
him pitching in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My interests aren't my own,'' Wetteland said. ``My interest is
to try and help this team. I was starting to wonder if I was worth
anything as a closer. I was being paid well on a team that was
destined _ well, I don't even know where we finished _ not to win
anything. So, I was wondering how I could maximize my value to the
team. I felt bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers denied Wetteland's request, but it revealed his
unselfishness and competitive nature. One of baseball's dominant
closers sought to leave his comfort zone for an opportunity to make
a difference as a member of the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never played with a more competitive person in my life,''
Rangers left-hander Scott Bailes said. ``I think that season was
frustrating for him. He couldn't score runs. He couldn't field the
ball. All he could do was protect leads.''
</P>
<P>
   Those proved few and far between until this season, and the
Rangers will take their chances should their lineup be fortunate
enough to provide Wetteland three ninth-inning leads in this
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible that I might not do my job, too,'' Wetteland
said. ``That's the wonderful thing about the game. Nothing is a
sure thing. You go out there and prepare to make it as close as you
can to a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone just figures that because you get this guy and that
guy that you're going to win, but it doesn't work that way. I'm
sorry, but play the game and find that out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers played that game without Wetteland during 1996
against the Yankees and did not enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said, ``we won't see
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
