<HEADER>
A9316 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-STERN-HNS &LR;      09-29 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-STERN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the most pessimistic projection yet of the NBA labor dispute,
commissioner David Stern said it is likely the league is headed for
its first shortened season in more than 50 years of existence.
</P>
<P>
   Stalled collective-bargaining negotiations between the league
and representatives of the players' union have left Stern doubtful
the 1998-99 season will start as scheduled Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such hope as there is (to start the season on time) seems to
be dwindling,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   The league already has canceled some exhibition games and pushed
back the opening of training camps indefinitely. One NBA insider
said late last week that the season will start about one month
after arbitrator John Feerick rules on the union's claim that
guaranteed contracts must be paid during a lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Owners have been told Feerick will not render a decision until
the Oct. 19 deadline. That means the earliest the season could
begin would be mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   During an exclusive weekend interview, Stern also said NBA
owners who were reluctant to lose regular-season games to a work
stoppage in 1995 now are willing to accept such an outcome, which
is certain to alienate some fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owners need the ability to agree on what percentage (of
basketball revenue) is fair,'' Stern said. ``We thought we did that
last time (with the '95 agreement). We knew there was a potential
problem in that last deal, but on the heels of a hockey lockout and
a baseball strike, we felt it was prudent to make sure we reached
an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players have conveniently forgotten that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with perhaps as many as 14 of the league's 29 teams
expecting to sustain a financial loss next season under the current
agreement, the owners are more willing than ever to test the
players' resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about us thinking that the players will cave (in)
after missing a paycheck,'' Stern said. ``It's just about having a
certain situation where we can get to a point where all (current)
contracts will be honored, where we'll continue to pay rookies as
much as they have been earning and where veterans will no longer be
subject to making a minimum salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA owners as a group have not tried to take away every
last dollar from the players. In fact, this system has seen the
(leaguewide) salaries go from $60 million to $1 billion (since the
salary cap was instituted in 1984). And it promises to go up, but
at a rate that is fair for the owners as well as the players.''
</P>
<P>
   The essence of the owners' lockout of the players is that the
collective-bargaining agreement that was signed in '95 called for
48 percent of all ``basketball-related income'' to be returned to
the players in the form of salary. If that number increased beyond
51.8 percent of the BRI, the owners reserved the right to reopen
the collective-bargaining agreement, which they exercised this
summer after paying more than 56 percent of the BRI to players.
</P>
<P>
   The owners' major complaint is that too many contracts have been
signed in recent years under the ``Larry Bird exception.'' Those
players can be re-signed by their teams for any salary when a
contract expires, without regard to where the team stands on the
salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Because players like Atlanta's Dikembe Mutombo ($56 million),
Cleveland's Shawn Kemp ($99.5 million), Miami's Alonzo Mourning
($105 million), Seattle's Gary Payton ($88 million), Washington's
Juwan Howard ($105 million), Minnesota's Kevin Garnett ($126
million) and Vancouver's Bryant Reeves ($63 million) have signed
such lucrative multiyear contracts, owners have seen their total
payrolls leap well beyond the salary cap, which was $26.9 million
per team last season. Players at the top of the pay scale are
chewing up too much of the payroll, owners claim.
</P>
<P>
   While it appears certain the start of the season will be
delayed, Stern would not comment on how much of the season the
league was prepared to lose, yet still play a season. One NBA
executive said recently that the league is not prepared to play a
50-game season. If that much time is lost at the beginning of the
schedule, the season would be scrapped altogether, the executive
said.
</P>
<P>
   Most estimations have the league missing the month of November,
which would mean about 15 games would be lopped off the normally
82-game schedule. That would leave around 67 games for a regular
season. That number still would be acceptable to owners, the
executive said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a point beyond which the season loses its
credibility,'' he said. ``There wouldn't be a 50-game season, for
instance.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners have given the players two proposals for a new
collective-bargaining agreement. The bottom line of both is that
the players would have at least $1 billion in salary for the coming
season, an average of about $2.5 million per player. That number
would go up at least 20 percent over the next four seasons, Stern
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about lowering salaries,'' Stern emphasized.
``We just want to see that the salaries don't grow quite as fast as
they have in recent years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
