<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPTH ANCHORS YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yankees manager Joe Torre has this problem every time
he faces the Rangers in a playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Cecil Fielder had to sit for Game 1 when the
Yankees met the Texas Rangers in the playoffs. Fielder, a
right-handed batter, didn't matchup as well against against
right-handed pitcher John Burkett.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Darryl Strawberry will be riding the bench when
the two teams begin their divisional playoff series at Yankee
Stadium with Todd Stottlemyre on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Torre's decision had nothing to do with Strawberry's infected
lower abdomen. He had already decided on using Chad Curtis in left
field and Chili Davis at designated hitter because Davis has career
numbers against Stottlemyre than Strawberry and Curtis is the
better fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Some problem. A player on the bench like Strawberry, who hit 24
home runs in 295 at-bats, speaks to the depth that Torre has
enjoyed this season and in the 1996 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry will sit with Tim Raines, Luis Sojo and Joe Girardi,
three other veterans who have played regularly at some point in
their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Torre is also sitting Homer Bush, a reserve infielder who hit
.380 this year, and outfielder Shane Spencer, the rookie who caused
a late-season sensation in New York when he hit 10 home runs in 67
at-bats, including three grand slams.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how you win 114 games,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   A $63 million payroll, not counting portions of salaries being
picked up for players traded to other teams, allows the Yankees to
command this kind of depth. It's how they survived the loss of
Davis for 118 games because of a broken ankle and Bernie Williams
for 31 games because of a sprained knee.
</P>
<P>
   It has also forced Torre to make tough decisions on who plays
and who sits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough decision but it makes a tough decision easier
when you have those caliber of players,'' Torre said. ``That's the
fun part because it's tough to make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre also benefits from players who have willingly accepted
subordinate roles. Raines is a former base-stealing and batting
champion who played regularly in the 1996 postseason when the
Yankees won a World Series. Now his playing time could be limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to play,'' Raines said. ``But Joe is going with the
lineup he wants. I'm all for that. I'd love to play, but we've got
a good ballclub. We all do whatever it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Torre, ``It's nice when you have players who have taken the
attitude they have. They want to win and they understand it's not
an easy decision. They respect each other's abilities, so it makes
it easier when they understand only one guy can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Success has made it easier to accept. The Yankees not only won
114 games but also led the league with 965 runs scored. Torre can
afford to sacrifice offense for defense in left field and still
start a formidable lineup against Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a great lineup,'' Stottlemyre said. ``They're
unbelievable. They proved they're the best in the East to this
point by winning as many games as they did. They not only did it
offensively, they did it defensively. But one through nine, every
guy that steps to the plate has a chance to leave the ballpark at
any time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
