<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFIDENT ASTROS LOOK TO MAKE FRANCHISE HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Houston Astros have never won a playoff series in
their 37-year existence.
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidentally, they've never had an offensive lineup like
this year's. Or a pitcher like Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Win, lose or draw, I really believe this is the best team this
franchise has ever put on the field,'' Astros general manager Gerry
Hunsicker said last week. ``We've got all the pieces in place to
win this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, a World Series in The Astrodome has seemed as
ridiculous as those hideous orange-and-yellow seats. But that's the
realistic goal of the Astros as they begin their National League
Division Series against the San Diego Padres on Tuesday at 3 p.m.
Games 1 and 2 of the best-of-five series are in Houston before the
series shifts to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year when the (Atlanta) Braves swept us (in the first
round of the playoffs), I said we had to make some changes to get
better,'' said manager Larry Dierker. ``Well, we've made the
changes and we've gotten better, much better. I'm not making
guarantees, but I like our chances as good as anyone else's.''
</P>
<P>
   With good reason. The Astros finished a franchise-best 102-60,
behind only the New York Yankees and Braves. Their offense led the
NL, setting club records with 868 runs and 165 home runs while
their pitching staff finished second in the league with a 3.53 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying they're the best team in baseball,'' said
Chicago Cubs manager Jim Riggleman. ``But the gap between them and
Braves is real, real small. If there is one at all. They can hit,
they can pitch, and they make very few mistakes. They're for
real.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense is again fueled by the Killer B's: Craig Biggio,
Derek Bell and Jeff Bagwell. But it's the addition of Moises Alou
that the Astros believe will provide the punch missing last year. A
member of the world champion Florida Marlins a year ago, Alou set a
club record with 337 total bases and hit .313 with 38 homers and
124 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   With his presence, the Astros became just the third NL team in
50 years to feature four players scoring 100 runs and all but
Biggio (88 RBI) also hit 20 homers and drove in 100 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't have any weak spots,'' said Biggio, the
scrappy second baseman who became only the second player this
century (along with Hall-of-Famer Tris Speaker in 1912) to record
50 doubles and 50 steals. ``If you go through the meat of our order
four times, chances are you're going to give up some runs.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's the big acquisition of the fireballing Johnson that has
the Astros confident, bordering on cocky.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining Houston an hour before the July 31 deadline,
Johnson has gone 10-1, including 7-0 with a 1.16 ERA in his past
seven starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my time of year and this is why Houston brought me
here, to win games in October,'' said Johnson, who struck out 329
with Seattle and Houston to lead the majors for the fifth time. ``I
know they're counting on me, but this was a great team before I got
here. I just hope I can be that missing piece to the puzzle.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, who calls having the edge of throwing Johnson three
times in a seven-game series ``the luxury of luxuries,'' plans to
go with a three-man rotation including 19-game winner Shane
Reynolds and lefty Mike Hampton. The only mild concern entering
October is closer Billy Wagner, who blew five saves and struggled
with his aggressiveness after taking a line drive to the head in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Last year a Central Division title and a playoff appearance was
enough. But with the additions of Alou and Johnson and a
record-setting regular season, a trip to the NLCS is almost a
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the division again is a great step forward,'' owner
Drayton McLane Jr. said recently. ``But I think we're good enough
to be focusing on bigger things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
