u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-29 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THIS RACE WAS FOR THE NATIONAL LEAGUE MILD CARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The second most exciting race of the season was
decided here on Monday night. That doesn't say much for the
competitive part of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The final spot in the post-season playoffs, the National League
wild-card berth, was filled by the Chicago Cubs, who beat the San
Franciso Giants, 5-3, in a playoff game that was the culmination of
a race that no team could win because no team was good enough to
win it.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets certainly weren't. With a week to go in the
season, with only five games to play, the Mets led the wild-card
race. They were one game ahead of the Cubs, four ahead of the
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take a doctorate in calculus to figure out that to be
bad enough to squander a four-game lead with five games to play,
the leading team has to lose just about every game. That's exactly
what the Mets did.
</P>
<P>
   If they had won just one of those five games, the Mets would
have played San Francisco at Shea Stadium on Monday. Then, if they
had won that game, they would have played the Cubs at Shea Stadium
on Tuesday. Then maybe they would have joined Atlanta, Houston and
San Diego in the post-season playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets had won two of those final five games, beating
Montreal last Tuesday and Wednesday, for example, the Giants and
the Chicago Cubs would not have played at Wrigley Field on Monday
night. There would have been no need for a playoff for the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets turned out to be too mediocre to alter the course
of October events.
</P>
<P>
   And what about those mighty Giants and Chicago Cubs, the teams
that benefited from the Mets' ultimate failure? In the final week,
they each squandered a 7-0 lead in a game. If either team had held
its hefty lead, it would have advanced as the wild-card team,
instead of meeting in a playoff game that automatically took on an
air of excitement because playoff games are supposed to be
exciting.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Jim Riggleman, the Cubs' manager, absolved the
Giants of their squandering while not taking his team off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their loss was different,'' he said before the playoff game.
``They lost their game in Colorado. Watching their score, when it
was 7-0, at that point in the game you figure they may score 14 or
Colorado may score 10 or 12. You just can't figure the score is
going to stay anything close to what it is in the fourth. You
figure it's going to be hugely different.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs, on the other hand, blew their 7-0 lead in the seventh
inning in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our loss was probably more painful than theirs,'' Riggleman
said. ``We had a 7-0 lead in a normal atmosphere of a ball park. No
crazy conditions, light air, ball flying all over the place. We
should've been able to hold that lead. In Colorado you can never
really fault yourself for giving up a lead.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs at least won two of their last five games to get to a
playoff game, though they could not win on the last day to avoid a
playoff. The Giants didn't win the last game either, but they won
their first six in the last week of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Magowan, the Giants' proud owner, rejected any suggestion
that the playoff for the playoffs was a matchup born of mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won 9 out of 11, even with the loss yesterday,'' Magowan
said outside the visiting clubhouse, ``so don't tell me this is a
bunch of losers that are showing up to play this game. If we win
this game, we've won 90 games. What did the Indians win this
year?''
</P>
<P>
   Touche. The Indians won 89 and a division title. Not to mention
that a year ago the wild-card Florida Marlins were about to embark
on a course that would make them World Series champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wild card gives a lot of teams a chance for post-season
play that otherwise wouldn't have been able to be there because of
economics,'' Magowan said, casting a vote for the continued
existence of wild-card teams. He also cited the increased September
attendance of teams in the wild-card races.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean baseball should expand the wild-card format, the
way the National Football League did? No, Magowan said firmly. One
wild-card team in each league is enough. Riggleman didn't campaign
for any format, but he also didn't think any losses leading up to
the playoff for the playoffs, including those on the final day of
the season, detracted from the show at Wrigley Field on Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is,'' the manager said, ``this game will be
remembered, not that both clubs lost yesterday. I certainly know if
we were going to play this game tonight, I'd want it to be because
both teams won, not because both teams lost.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, the only real excitement of the season should
have been for Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa. No one should have
become excited over a race of also-rans. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
