<SLUG> BC-NY-WESTCHESTER-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTCHESTER PASSES ON TAX-FREE SHOPPING WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ The Westchester County legislature voted
Monday night against participating in the state's next tax-free
shopping week, scheduled for January, concluding that although it
would help the county's merchants, it would do so at the cost of a
property tax increase for homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   The 11-6 vote to keep the county's sales tax in place sets
Westchester apart from most of the other counties and cities in the
state, which have so far embraced the state Legislature's plan to
eliminate the sales tax on some clothing purchases as a means of
persuading people not to leave New York state to shop.
</P>
<P>
   For a week before the vote, County Executive Andrew Spano, a
Democrat, warned the Democratic-controlled Legislature that a
recent report by a business group, the Westchester County
Association, said the reductions in tax revenue would necessitate
an increase in property tax. The report estimated that the county
would lose $27 million to $35 million in revenue a year if it
eliminated the sales tax permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad for the economy and it's bad for the residents,''
Spano said in a telephone interview. ``I made a promise to the
people that I would not raise their taxes, and I won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's vote addressed only the next tax-free week _ Jan.
17 to 24 _ which applies to clothing and shoes that sell for less
than $500. The vote, however, is considered an indicator of how
Westchester lawmakers will vote next year when they have to decide
on a permanent sales tax exemption for shoes and clothing selling
for less than $110. The permanent sales tax exemption was approved
by the state Legislature in August and is to go into effect on Dec.
1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The sales tax rate in Westchester municipalities, including the
4.25 percent levied by the state, varies from 6.75 percent to 8.25
percent. The four largest cities set their own sales tax rates and
the mayors of each of them have said they plan not to participate
in future sales tax exemptions. In White Plains, the state and
local sales tax rate is 7.75 percent, while in Yonkers, New
Rochelle and Mount Vernon it is 8.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the range of sales and property tax rates, each
Westchester community would feel the impact of the tax change
differently. The report estimated that an average homeowner in
White Plains, for example, would see an increase of at least $218
in property taxes to compensate for the loss of sales tax revenue.
That homeowner would have to spend at least $6,200 a year on
clothing or shoes that cost less than $110 to make up for the $218
in added property tax. An average Peekskill homeowner would have to
buy $1,146 worth of tax-free items and a Scarsdale homeowner would
have to buy $5,674 worth, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agreed with the report's findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the numbers the administration is floating around are
a little inflated,'' said James Maisano, a legislator from New
Rochelle. ``They looked at the September tax-free shopping week
figures, but don't forget that was back-to-schools week, so people
were shopping more and buying more.''
</P>
<P>
   Maisano voted for the tax-free week and said he wanted to see a
study that examined the economic impact of not adopting the plan
when communities all around Westchester were planning to adopt it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all the surrounding communities decide to opt in, what will
that do to the retail industry and jobs in Westchester?'' Maisano
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Spano said he did not think shoppers would leave Westchester to
shop in other counties because the difference between being charged
just the local sales tax and being charged no sales tax at all was
negligible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state's going to eliminate its 4.25 percent anyway,''
Spano said. ``We don't feel that people are going to hop into their
cars and pay the toll to go to Rockland County or drive into the
Bronx to shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers in the gleaming malls in White Plains may not notice
much of a difference in forthcoming tax-free periods, since that
city charged its normal 2 percent tax during the last two tax-free
weeks, in January and earlier this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
