<SLUG> BC-NY-ATTY-GEN-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VACCO ATTACKS CHALLENGER ON FINANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Attorney General Dennis Vacco's re-election campaign
sought Monday to put his Democratic challenger, Eliot Spitzer, on
the defensive about finances, saying Spitzer had failed to explain
how he was paying for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Vacco, a Republican, contended that public records do
not support the assertion by Spitzer, a wealthy real estate heir,
that he obtained millions of dollars for his current campaign and
one in 1994 by taking out loans against co-op apartments that he
owns.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer is either lying about the source of his money or has
failed to file the required disclosure documents, said Vacco's
campaign manager, Matthew Behrmann. Either way, Behrmann said, the
allegation raises questions about whether Spitzer is fit to be
attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are substantial inconsistencies in what Spitzer has said
and what is in the documents that are available,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer brushed aside the charges. ``This is Dennis Vacco trying
to kick dirt on old news,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In making the charges, the Vacco campaign is following a
strategy adopted by Spitzer's Democratic rivals in the primary.
Spitzer, a former Manhattan prosecutor whose father is a real
estate magnate, has spent more than $6 million so far on the two
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, Spitzer can spend an unlimited amount of his
own money on his campaign, but can receive no more than roughly
$100,000 from his father. Spitzer's rivals have questioned whether
his father or other family members made illegal contributions to
his campaign. Monday, Spitzer asserted that his Democratic rivals
had been unable to prove a shred of wrongdoing on his part.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had used eight co-op apartments that he owns at 200
Central Park South in Manhattan as collateral on the loans,
explaining that the apartments were worth $7 million to $10
million. He said he was not sure whether the bank or his lawyers
had filed all the disclosure documents on the loans, but would tell
his lawyers to make sure that proper procedures were followed.
</P>
<P>
   He then fired back at Vacco, stepping up his attacks on the
incumbent's ethics. ``If this is what his campaign wants to do,
point the finger, then I can point it right back,'' Spitzer said.
``He has accepted contributions from people who work for him, from
companies that he has been investigating. I really don't think that
he is in a position to raise questions about me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spitzer campaign also tried to regain the offensive by
renewing its focus on Vacco's motives in hiring and firing lawyers.
Aides to Spitzer have said Vacco has a record of dismissing skilled
lawyers and replacing them with novices who have links to the
Republican and Conservative Parties.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's aides released several documents that were obtained
from lawsuits filed by some of the fired lawyers against Vacco and
his aides. Among the documents are copies of evaluations of some of
the new lawyers written by senior members in the office. One
lawyer, who is not identified, is criticized for ``lack of effort''
and for filing legal papers that are ``void of substantive input.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said Vacco's hiring practices had sent ``an unmistakable
signal: politics first, competence second and ethics dead last.''
</P>
<P>
   Behrmann called all of Spitzer's charges baseless. ``It's
logically inconsistent, given the reductions in crime that the
attorney general has been able to achieve, with the national awards
won by the staff,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
