<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOTTLEMYRES GET A SECOND REUNION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Right-hander Todd Stottlemyre, the Texas Rangers'
scheduled starter Tuesday night, will share Yankee Stadium with his
father for the second time this season. Stottlemyre's father, Mel,
is the Yankees' pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Stottlemyre pitched six innings during the Rangers'
16-5 victory Aug. 15 against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an emotional day,'' Stottlemyre recalled. ``That was
the first time we were able to share the same field professionally
together. It was emotional for my mom and my wife. I'm sure it was
for Dad, too, sitting in the Yankees' dugout. I'm glad this is not
the first time. I'm glad we've already jumped that hurdle.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Stottlemyre also expects Tuesday night's scenario to
be much more difficult for his father emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question about it,'' the pitcher said. ``I guess I would
look at it the same way if I had a son playing, yet he's very
competitive by nature. He has a true affection for his pitching
staff and their ballclub, so _ knowing how competitive he is _ I
expect that he wants the Yankees to win. At the same time, this has
to be really difficult when your son is in a different-colored
uniform pitching against you. I think it's obviously a lot tougher
for him.'' JUAN IS NOT ENOUGH
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander David Wells, the Yankees' scheduled starter Tuesday,
respects Rangers right fielder Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Wells also recognizes that Gonzalez alone can't beat the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, recall, hit .438 (7-for-16) with five home runs and
nine runs batted in during the Rangers' 1996 Division Series
against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers lost that best-of-five series after the remaining
members of the lineup hit only .190 with one home run and seven
RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't do it by himself,'' Wells said. ``He needs other guys
to be on base. You have to be careful with him, though. He hits the
ball all over, and he's very strong. If you were to pitch around
someone, he'd be the guy. You have to pitch to him, though. He's
not a super hero, but he's pretty damn close.'' WATCH OUT LEFTIES
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' .316 batting average against left-handers led the
major leagues, and left-handed starters went 12-23 with a 6.49
earned-run average in 48 starts against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   That does not bode well for Wells.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to throw strikes, get ahead in the count and don't
make mistakes, because if you do, they have the kind of guys who
can capitalize,'' he said. ``You have to try and keep them on their
front foot and move the ball in and out. You have to pitch to their
weaknesses and your strengths and not be too fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells was 1-0 with a 6.11 ERA in three starts against the
Rangers this season, and they hit .311 against him. A STEP UP
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Todd Zeile, who normally hits eighth in the
Rangers' lineup, likely will bat seventh Tuesday against Wells,
manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile hit .433 (13-for-30) with three home runs and eight RBI in
his final 11 games and established a Rangers record Friday by
reaching base safely in 11 consecutive plate appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Oates' decision means that designated hitter Mike Simms likely
will bat eighth in front of shortstop Royce Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Zeile is swinging the bat pretty well right now,''
Oates said. ``Zeile is hot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
