<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINS RECORD NOT ENOUGH FOR YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees enter the playoffs with 114 victories,
the most in American League history. They know it won't be enough,
though, if they don't win the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to separate it,'' manager Joe Torre said. ``It's been
a special year in and of itself. But when you get to postseason, it
would be a disappointment if you didn't get to the World Series and
win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said pitcher David Wells, ``I don't think it's the most
important thing in the world, but it would certainly add to the
great season we've put together so far. But you can't just make it
happen, you have to go out and work for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells said if the Yankees do win the World Series, ``It would
probably be the best ever on the field. There have been a lot of
great individuals, but this would probably be the best team.
Everyone has contributed. No one has gotten big heads about what's
happened this year. Winning the World Series, if it happens, would
be because everyone came together.'' RUNNING YANKEES
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have stolen 153 bases this year, third most in the
American League. Now they have to go against Rangers catcher Ivan
Rodriguez, who threw out 52.5 percent of base runners trying to
steal against him.
</P>
<P>
   It could be the pivotal matchup of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be ready for anybody,'' Rodriguez said. ``I'm an
aggressive catcher and I'm going to do the same things I've always
done: be aggressive and concentrate on every situation.'' BALANCED
ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   Here's why the Yankees impress teams with their balance of speed
and power:
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' 207 home runs are the highest total in major-league
history for a team without having a single player hit at least 30
home runs. Tino Martinez leads with 28.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees tied a major-league record for having the most
players in double figures in home runs and stolen bases. The six
were Scott Brosius (19/11), Chad Curtis (10/21), Derek Jeter
(19/30), Chuck Knoblauch (17/30), Paul O'Neill (24/15) and Bernie
Williams (26/15).
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had eight players with 15 or more home runs, tying a
record set by the Rangers in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, with Jeter and Knoblauch each stealing 30 bases,
became only the third pair of middle infielders to steal that many
in a single season. The others were shortstop Jack Barry (30) and
second baseman Eddie Collins (38) for the 1911 Philadelphia
Athletics and shortstop Bert Campaneris (54) and second baseman
Phil Garner (35) for the 1976 Oakland Athletics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 0041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9342 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBBYHOLED-FANS-LADN     09-29 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBBYHOLED-FANS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBS FANS ACROSS AMERICA EMBRACE UNDERDOG TRADITION
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attention editors: ``Mik'' Scriba is correct.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY LEE CONDON AND DAVID R.   BAKER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On Monday night the Chicago Cubs made the playoffs
for the first time since 1989, but for longtime fan Christopher
Durbin it marked the beginning of a whole new level of anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cubs are like a car wreck. I don't want to look, but I
can't help it,'' said Durbin, a 36-year-old art director at NBC in
Burbank, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   After so many years of letdowns, Durbin is hopeful that his team
will go all the way in 1998. But deep down, he knows the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, there is going to be a tragedy,'' Durbin said.
</P>
<P>
   Durbin, who grew up in the Rogers Park section of Chicago, was
one of about 40 die-hard Cubs fans who showed up at the Tin Horn
Flats Bar &AMP; Grill in Burbank, a local hangout where Chicago natives
go to cheer on their local teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost everyone here is a displaced Chicagoan or a closeted
Chicago fan who can come here without getting hassled,'' said Bill
Ahern, a 36-year-old North Hollywood resident who grew up in a
Chicago suburb called Hanover Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs are of course the biggest losers in baseball,
not having won a World Series since 1908 and not having played in
the World Series since 1945. Fans say its all because of the Billy
Goat Curse which a bar owner placed on the team after security at
Wrigley Field refused to let his goat in for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Mik Scriba, a 50-year-old actor who lives in Sherman Oaks, an
L.A.-area suburb, grew up in the Wrigleyville section of Chicago,
which is basically made up of the five blocks that surround Wrigley
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to go to 60 home games a year,'' said Scriba.
</P>
<P>
   Giving up on the Cubs would be sacrilegious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be like switching to new parents. It's
psychologically impossible,'' Scriba said.
</P>
<P>
   While fans of other teams already are convinced that their
favorites will win the World Series, the Cubs fans were very
conservative in their predictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking this is the year,'' Scriba said. ``All we
want to do is get into the post-season.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ahern has already bought into the fantasy that the Cubs are
going to win the World Series this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to always win to enjoy the game. You just have
to believe in the team, and this is the year,'' Ahern said.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs fanatics, of course, are used to the abuse. They've heard
the derision from fans of luckier teams, better teams _ the
accusation that only people addicted to pain could love such a
club.
</P>
<P>
   The reputation, they say, is all wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not masochists _ we're just filled with hope,'' said
veteran stand-up comedian Tom Dreesen, whose routines often reflect
the heartbreak of following the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old Sherman Oaks resident has been rooting for the
team since growing up on Chicago's south side _ serious White Sox
territory, he notes. Following the luckless Cubs, he said, gives
fans a reason to live, to see another year in the hope that this
time, the team might just make it to the World Series. Lord knows
how many suicides the Cubs may have prevented this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear that on the morning after they finally win the World
Series, there will be 50,000 people jumping out of buildings,''
Dreesen said.
</P>
<P>
   As it has with other lifelong fans, this year's amazing, Sammy
Sosa-driven season has left Dreesen in a state of bliss. Just as
Babe Ruth helped save baseball after the 1919 Black Sox scandal,
Dreesen said the gracious sportsmanship of Sosa and Mark McGwire
has restored luster to a sport tarnished by the 1994 players
strike, which made players and owners seem greedy in the eyes of
many fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys have done the same thing as Ruth,'' Dreesen said.
``These guys have brought baseball back.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the Cubs leading 5-0 on Monday night at the bottom of
the eighth inning, Durbin couldn't relax.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, in the ninth inning San Francisco came back scoring
three runs and turning the last moments of the game a nail-biter
for the crowd at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the Cubs fan, no lead is safe,'' Durbin said. ``No way am I
comfortable, no way.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
