r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-TEX     09-29 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX IGNORING BAMBINO'S CURSE, PAST PLAYOFF FLOPS
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By David A. Markiewicz 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Cleveland Indians and the Boston Red Sox each
have a 1,000-pound gorilla called baseball history weighing on them
as they begin their series this afternoon. It's just that Boston's
gorilla is leaning a little bit harder.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland hasn't won a World Series in 50 years. Amazingly,
Boston hasn't won it all in 80 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have also lost 13 consecutive postseason games. The
Indians, by contrast, have played in the World Series two of the
past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why Red Sox manager Jimy Williams spent part of
yesterday deflecting inquiries about Boston's playoff flops, while
Indians players suggested that last year's heartbreaking loss in
Game 7 of the World Series actually has served as this year's
motivation.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Red Sox won was 1918. Back then, the team's
pitching star was none other than Babe Ruth. The Bambino was dealt
to New York shortly after, however, commencing a streak of
misfortune that has continued throughout the century.
</P>
<P>
   The subsequent slide prompted Red Sox loyalists to bemoan ``The
Curse of the Bambino.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the ``Curse of the Bambino'' would be a factor in the
series, Williams responded, ``What's that?''
</P>
<P>
   Later, when asked about the horrors of the past, including Bill
Buckner's error which cost Boston the 1986 World Series, Williams
replied, ``I wasn't there. I was somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams probably doesn't want to think about the last time the
Red Sox were in the postseason, either. That was 1995, the year
Boston was swept by Cleveland in the divisional series. BIG MOMENT
FOR MARTINEZ
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox ace Pedro Martinez, who starts Tuesday's game, isn't
downplaying the personal significance of his moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot more than you'd expect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez explained that when it became clear last season that he
was not long for the Montreal Expos, he made it known that he
wanted to play for a contender. When he was traded to the Red Sox,
he said, he was initially disappointed because the franchise had
fallen on hard times in recent years and a postseason berth in 1998
appeared unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent five long years in Montreal,'' he said. ``And I didn't
get a chance like this. I'm going to take full advantage of it and
appreciate it all.'' COOL STARTERS
</P>
<P>
   Neither starting pitcher expects to have any opening-game
jitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm too old for that,'' Martinez said. ``I don't think I
should be scared.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not scared or anything,'' added Indians Game 1 starter
Jaret Wright, a playoff and World Series veteran at the age of 22.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said he learned how to ``savor'' the playoff experience
last season when, among other highlights, he started Game 7 of the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to help me,'' he said. ``I sort of have a
feel of what is going on.'' INDIANS ADMIT STRUGGLES
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove and Indians players have had to
deal with criticism that the team appeared lackadaisical most of
the season, then barely stumbled into the second seed of the
playoffs during the final weekend of play.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't avoiding the charge during yesterday's workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We scuffled the whole year,'' catcher Sandy Alomar admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not disagree that we have played lethargic the last
month and a half,'' Hargrove said. ``Sometimes when you run into
great pitching it makes you look a little lethargic.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Indians could, as they appeared to do last year,
turn it on and off, Hargrove said, ``The switch has been flipped,
it just isn't working.'' ONE-SIDED SEASON
</P>
<P>
   Both managers discounted the importance of the regular-season
series between the two clubs, which is just as well for the
Indians. Boston dominated, taking eight of 11 games. Martinez, Game
2 starter Tim Wakefield and Game 3 starter Bret Saberhagen each
beat the Indians twice this season. The only Cleveland starter to
win a game against the Red Sox was Charles Nagy on July 22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
