<SLUG> BC-NY-TAXBREAK-COLLEGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK OFFERS TAX BREAK FOR COLLEGE SAVINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joining a growing number of states that give tax
breaks for college savings, New York launched a program Monday that
allows parents to save thousands of dollars in state taxes as they
put aside money for a child's college education.
</P>
<P>
   The program offers some of the most generous terms and widest
flexibility in the country, state officials said. Besides parents
saving for children, contributors can save money for the education
of other relatives, friends or themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers who live or work in New York will be able to deduct a
total of $5,000 a year from their taxable state income for
contributions to one or more Family Tuition Accounts; couples can
deduct up to $10,000 a year. Money put in the accounts _ and the
interest earned on that money _ will not be subject to any New York
state taxes. The interest earnings will also be protected from
federal income taxes until the money is withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   A couple making $40,000 a year or more and contributing the
maximum of $10,000 would save $685 annually in state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The program allows for a maximum total contribution of $100,000
per student, which could grow substantially depending on how, and
how long, the account is invested.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike prepaid tuition programs that require savings be used at
a particular college or in a particular state, New York will allow
the money to be spent at any accredited college or university,
professional or trade school, in the United States or abroad. The
money can be used for tuition, books, room and board, and other
educational fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty substantial tax deduction,'' said Robert
Maurer, president of New York State Higher Education Services
Corp., which will jointly administer the program with the state
comptroller's office. Referring to the top state tax rate of 6.85
percent, he said, ``It's like having the state put up the first 7
cents of every dollar you save for college.''
</P>
<P>
   The law creating the savings program, which had bipartisan
support in Albany, was signed into law by Gov. George Pataki in
September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At a New York City news conference announcing the start of the
program Monday, Sharon Steinhoff, a freelance editor, opened
accounts for her 13-year-old twins, Sarah and Seth, who attend the
Simon Baruch Middle School (MS 104) on East 21st Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have twins, the first thing people say to you is,
`How are you going to pay for college?''' she told an audience
including state Comptroller H. Carl McCall and New York City
Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew. ``As a parent you don't want to have
to put a cap, if you don't have to, on how much you're going to
spend for a child's education.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Ms. Steinhoff, who herself attended Brown
University, ``Up to this point, it didn't make sense to save. There
were no benefits to be gained from a tax perspective, or we had to
lock up the money for a certain period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, she said, she and her husband would use the new accounts
because of the tax benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The average price last year for a four-year private institution
was $21,424 for tuition, room and board, books and other fees, and
$10,069 at a four-year public institution. Many students, however,
pay less than these amounts because of financial aid and
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   State officials estimate that New York has 5 million families
with children of school age or younger. They predict that in the
first year alone, more than $135 million will be put into more than
50,000 accounts, for a tax savings of more than $22 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is going to be really big,'' Maurer said.
``Everyone tells you you ought to save for college. People are
going to want to do it because they want to see something there for
their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Other states, including Connecticut and New Hampshire, have also
set up college savings plans recently, following the passage of
federal legislation last year that clearly established the federal
tax benefits for such programs. Not only are federal taxes
deferred, but when earnings are withdrawn, they will be taxed at
the student's federal tax rate, which is often lower than the
contributor's. The federal rules also call for penalties if the
money is not used as intended.
</P>
<P>
   Under the New York plan, withdrawals will be subject to state
and federal taxes and a 10 percent penalty if the money is not used
for qualified educational expenses. But any money not used by the
intended beneficiary can remain in the account indefinitely or the
contributor can shift it to another beneficiary in the same family.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum investment to open an account is $250, or enrollment
in a plan to deduct $25 a month from a checking account or an
employer's payroll. An account must be open at least 36 months
before money may be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   People who pay income taxes in New York City or Yonkers would
also see their city taxes reduced when they make contributions
because those taxes are based on the calculation of taxable income
they make for the state.
</P>
<P>
   The tuition accounts will be managed by TIAA-CREF, a
not-for-profit financial services organization that manages more
than $230 billion, including pension fund accounts for many
university professors. It will invest the accounts in a mix of
stocks, bonds and money market instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Information about how to open an account is available over the
Internet at www.nysaves.org or by calling 1-877-NYSAVES. A national
clearinghouse of state plans is also available at
www.collegesavings.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
