<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9359 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMOKING-LAWSUIT-SPI &LR;      09-29 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKING-LAWSUIT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE ATTORNEYS SAY TOBACCO INDUSTRY MISLED PUBLIC ON HEALTH
RISKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE MILETICH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The nation's largest cigarette makers embarked on a
45-year campaign to confuse and mislead the public about the health
dangers of their products, lawyers for Washington state said Monday
in joining 41 other states in their attack on the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   In five hours of remarks, the state combined old-fashioned
oratory with the most sophisticated technology ever used in a
Washington courtroom in outlining their multi-billion dollar case
to a King County Superior Court jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not tobacco companies. They are drug pharmaceutical
companies,'' attorney Steve Berman told the nine-women, three-men
jury in a trial that is being closely watched nationwide. ``And
they have lied about and hidden their true nature for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Displaying more than a dozen internal tobacco industry documents
on a ceiling-high screen, Berman and co-counsel Paul Luvera pulled
key paragraphs from the text with the help of a special computer
program previously used in the Oklahoma bombing trial of Timothy
McVeigh.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys will dispute the state's case Tuesday, denying
claims that major cigarette makers conspired to hide the dangers of
smoking, target minors with sophisticated advertising, manipulate
nicotine levels and suppress the development of a safer cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   They also will take the offensive, contending that the state has
effectively promoted the sale of tobacco products by licensing
cigarettes and collecting millions of dollars in taxes on them.
</P>
<P>
   The state's attorneys dismissed that argument Monday, saying the
state could never enforce its laws if that were true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our evidence will show that paying taxes is never an excuse
for breaking the law,'' Luvera said.
</P>
<P>
   Luvera and Berman, both private practitioners, were hired by the
state to help recover more than $2 billion in smoking-related
Medicaid costs from Philip Morris, R.J. Reynolds, Brown &AMP;
Williamson, Lorillard and several other defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants have previously settled Medicaid cases with
Mississippi, Florida, Texas and Minnesota for sums totaling $38.5
billion and are facing similar suits brought by 37 other states.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations are currently under way in New York between Philip
Morris and Lorillard to settle suits with Washington and the other
states. Brown &AMP; Williamson and R.J. Reynolds have declined to
participate but are closely watching the talks.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's opening remarks, Luvera and Berman described how the
top executives of the major tobacco companies secretly met at the
Plaza Hotel in New York in December 1953 to discuss their concerns
about a spate of new scientific reports linking cigarettes to
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   From that meeting, the companies agreed to hide the truth about
the health risks of their products, conceal damaging information
from government officials and restrict genuine research about the
effects of smoking, Luvera and Berman told the jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state's position is that the tobacco defendants have
violated the civil laws by conspiring not to compete with each
other over issues like smoking and disease or by finding new ways
to reduce the risk of smoking,'' Luvera said.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, tobacco company officials acknowledged in internal
memorandums that they were actually in the business of selling
nicotine, a substance they described as addictive and ``a poison,''
Luvera said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are words they thought nobody else would see,'' Luvera
said, explaining that the documents weren't uncovered until several
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the companies privately held those views, their
executives went before Congress in 1994 and publicly stated that
they didn't believe nicotine was addictive, Luvera said, playing a
videotape of their testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The companies also deliberately manipulated nicotine levels,
spraying ammonia on tobacco sheets to alter how cigarettes burned
and give them more of a ``kick,'' Berman said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, cigarettes makers suppressed the manufacture
of safer products, in part because they had agreed in 1953 to share
all information on their research, thus removing any profit
incentive, Berman said.
</P>
<P>
   The conspiracy also led the tobacco industry to target minors,
largely because they knew most new smokers start when they are
young and rarely switch brands as they get older, Berman and Luvera
said.
</P>
<P>
   Before cigarette advertising was banned on television, cigarette
makers advertised on programs such as ``Gilligan's Island'' and the
``Beverly Hillbillies,'' knowing they were popular with children,
Luvera said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, R.J Reynolds developed the ``Joe Camel'' cartoon
character to directly appeal to minors and promote Camel
cigarettes, Berman said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the tobacco industry's conduct, more people smoke
and suffer from diseases such as cancer, heart problems and
emphesema than would have if cigarette makers had been truthful,
Berman said.
</P>
<P>
   The state has paid about $2.2 billion in smoking-related
Medicaid costs, of which $1.4 billion are directly related to the
actions of the defendants, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the companies are held liable for damages, the jury could
award either sum to the state, depending on whether it believes
responsibility can be precisely determined or whether it is too
confusing to allocate.
</P>
<P>
   The state also is seeking additional monetary penalties for
alleged violations of state consumer-protection and antitrust laws,
which would be fixed by the judge presiding over the case, George
Finkle, and could total billions of dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
