<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, Sept. 29.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOBBY-I (Washington) _ This year has been a banner year for K
Street, the power corridor of law and lobbying firms that rims the
White House in downtown Washington. At a time when the Democratic
administration and the Republican Congress are often at loggerheads
and Washington's agenda, dominated by scandal, seems inert, K
Street's portfolio has never been more robust. The influence
industry grew through the 1980s, but in the last few years it has
exploded with the advent of a divided government, creating a new
power elite in Washington. First of two parts. A Special Report. By
Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-ASSESS (Bonn) _ With an astonishing boldness, Germans
have ushered in a new phase in their political life, one their
newly elected leader, Gerhard Schroeder, on Monday called the
``Berlin Republic.'' By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONN-REPUB-POLITICS (Undated) _ As a moderate Republican
congresswoman, Nancy Johnson is on the hot seat in Washington. She
worries both about how far her party has gone in its pursuit of
impeachment, and the fact that she's facing a very tough
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND-ASIA (Hong Kong) _ In Asia, which has been scolded by
the United States over its economic policies, there is a sense of
grim satisfaction at the near-collapse of Long-Term Capital and at
its rescue by a team of banks and brokerage firms. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND-BAILOUT (Undated) _ As lawyers sought to put the
proposed rescue of Long-Term Capital on a firm footing, the
financial markets focused on other hedge funds that may be at risk
from the recent market turbulence. Rich investors also seem to be
pulling back from hedge funds generally, spooked by the huge losses
at Long-Term. By Joseph Kahn and Peter Truell.
</P>
<P>
   MANAGED-HEALTHCARE (Undated) _ The fastest-growing managed
health care plans have become the ones that are hardly managed at
all. Unlike health maintenance organizations that typically keep
tight control over their members, the minimal health plans try to
keep costs in check simply by persuading doctors and hospitals to
agree to reduced or discounted fees. The loosely managed plans,
called preferred provider organizations, are not new, but their
popularity is surging. By Milt Fruedenheim.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ It's upgrade time at America Online.
The Securities and Exchange Commission has ordered the online
service, and the rest of the technology industry, to improve the
way they account for mergers and acquisitions. The issue is how
technology companies have seized on a footnote in the accounting
rules related to research expenses to write off most of the
purchase price of companies as soon as they acquire them. By Saul
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE _ ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MET-OPERA-ENDOW (New York) _ The Metropolitan Opera embarks on
its largest endowment campaign. By Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   LUNTS-MUSEUM (Genesee Depot, Wis.) _ Arts in America: In the
rolling farmland of southeast Wisconsin, Ten Chimneys, the
legendary and utterly peculiar summer retreat of Alfred Lunt and
Lynn Fontanne, for years the reigning couple of the American
theater, is to be come a museum. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   GREEK-PLAYS (New York) _ In New York and elsewhere there is a
wealth of new productions of Greek classics with strong female
leads. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   FRANK-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Anne Frank,'' by Melissa Muller
(Metropolitan Books/Holt). Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALIEN-HUNTING (Arecibo, Puerto Rico) _ SETI, or the search
for extraterrestrial intelligence, is at a turning point after
nearly four decades of hard work. With the arrival here of a new
crew from the SETI Institute, the field has reached a high point in
terms of telescope sensitivity, a top goal of the alien hunters.
But it has found no extraterrestrials so far, despite forecasts
that they should have been discovered by now. Instead, it has
probed the heavens with regularity and heard nothing but a dead
silence. By William J. Broad Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A locator map and a photo has been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANTISENSE (Undated) _ Of all the emerging technologies in
the biotech firmament, few have been so controversial as antisense,
the concept that small snippets of DNA can serve as drugs by
blocking the action of specific genes. With the Food and Drug
Administration's approval last month of the world's first antisense
drug, this technology took a big step forward in critical
acceptance and therapeutic significance. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A graphic has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PREDICTION (Undated) _ When predictions go wrong, serious
problems can result. Some scientists call it ``misplaced
concreteness.'' And whether the problem is climate change,
earthquakes, droughts or floods, they say the tendency to overlook
uncertainties, margins of error and ranges of probability can lead
to damaging misjudgments. William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BIGHORN-SHEEP (Bishop, Calif.) _ Though some experts
estimate that as little as 2 percent of the vast numbers of
bighorns of the West remain today, wildlife agencies in almost
every Western state have stabilized those numbers in recent years.
But even in states where bighorns are considered to be doing well,
individual herds are prone to catastrophic die-offs, largely from
disease. Some herds may be more susceptible to disease because the
changing Western landscape has left them isolated from other herds.
By Martin Forstenzer.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VIKING-ARCHEO (Hole, Norway) _ Something is moving inside a
Viking burial mound said to be the ninth century tomb of King
Halvdan the Black. But some archeologists are loath to enter,
warning that whatever is in there could dissolve the spell of
enchantment that helped make Norway a nation. A recent subsidence
in a large, manmade hillock 30 miles northwest of Oslo has set off
a debate over the urgency and propriety of excavating the site to
save what could be the richest archeological cache in Scandinavia.
By Walter Gibbs. (1375 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A locator map has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MATERNAL-GENE (Undated) _ Mice know how to take care of
their babies by instinct, meaning that their maternal behavior is
in some way programmed into their genes. Biologists have now
identified one of the genes involved _ one that is sculpted or
imprinted by the father in a way that gives male mice a role in
shaping the female's maternal behavior. Even though human behavior
is far more flexible, a mother's nurturing instincts may take place
within the framework of the same set of genes as exist in mice
because mice and humans are very similar on the genetic level.
Indeed the human version of the mouse gene is also known to be
imprinted by the father. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ A humble-looking chip, about the
size of a postage stamp and no thicker than a nickel promises to
revolutionize security. When attached to a computer, the chip reads
fingerprints with a precision that meets the FBI standards for
personal identification. And while that offers loads of potential
in, say, protecting computer files or locking car doors, it offers
poses threats to privacy. By Rob Fixmer.
</P>
<P>
   MEDSCHOOL-MINORITIES-HEALTH (Undated) _ Medical authorities,
educators and civil-rights lawyers, concerned about a sudden drop
in minority enrollment at U.S. medical schools, are striking back
at anti-affirmative efforts that they believe have caused the
decline and threaten the future health of minority communities. By
Holcomb B. Noble.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A locator map has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (Boston) _ Anthony Lewis on the Christian right's
influence on Republicans pondering whether to impeach President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-RIVERA (New York) _ Two years ago it was John
Wetteland saving games in the postseason for the Yankees and
winning the mvp of the series. Now Mariano Rivera is the Yankee
closer and he'll be opposing Wetteland and the Texas Rangers in the
division playoffs. By Jack Curry.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-RANGERS-STOTTLEMYRE (New York) _ Ranger pitcher Todd
Stottlemyre and his father, the Yankee pitching coach Mel. By Jack
Curry.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS (New York) _ The Mets close up shop after a relatively
successful season that ended in disappointment. By Jason Diamos.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-HOUSTON-JOHNSON (Undated) _ Minutes before the trading
deadline in July, Houston made the deal that may have changed the
balance of power in the National League, acquiring Randy Johnson,
who's been merely terrific since he joined the Astros. By Selena
Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-INDIANS (Undated) _ The Yankees matched the American
League record of 111 victories set by the 1954 Cleveland Indians
last Thursday. By Friday, Bob Feller was hurling verbal heat. But
If the Yankees, who finished with 114 victories, falter in the
post-season, they would repeat the Indians' strange fate in 1954:
win more games than any other team in American League history, then
fold in October. By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
