<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE GEORGES MOVES INLAND, LOSES SOME OF ITS PUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE position, status of storm; Pickup 6th
graf pvs, Forecasters, along ...) (ATTN: La., Ala., Miss., Fla.)  (lh) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ From the eastern reaches of New Orleans to
Pensacola, Fla., Hurricane Georges pounded the Gulf Coast on Monday
with destructive winds and even more destructive rains, then slowly
lost much of its punch as it drifted along the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Battering the beaches, towns and cities of Louisiana,
Mississippi, Alabama and the Florida Panhandle with winds up to 100
miles an hour and more than a foot of rain, it left trees uprooted,
power lines down, roads washed out and hundreds of homes and
businesses badly knocked about or flooded.
</P>
<P>
   It spawned tornadoes, most harmless, though the winds of one
were clocked at 174 mph. The hurricane pounded a crippled ship and
the tug that was towing it so hard that Coast Guard officials
worried both might founder. And it was blamed for two deaths in New
Orleans, one occurring when an elderly woman suffered a heart
attack while being evacuated from her flooded home and the other
occurring when a man set his darkened house afire while trying to
light it with a candle.
</P>
<P>
   The storm was also blamed for the death of a Pensacola woman who
was killed Sunday in a house fire. Authorities believe she was
lighting a candle because there was no power.
</P>
<P>
   By later in the day, the winds had diminished, and the storm was
downgraded to a tropical storm. By late Monday night the winds had
fallen to 45 mph as the storm drifted slowly to the
south-southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters, along with public safety officials, warned that
because the storm was so saturated with rain after a slow meander
across the tropical waters of the Gulf, and because it was moving
inland so slowly, the Gulf Coast and the rest of the Deep South
should be on the lookout for heavy flooding over the next several
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not quite out of the water yet,'' Police Chief Ben
Morris told the residents of Slidell, La., on the Mississippi
border, as they began to emerge from shelters and boarded up homes
to take up the task of cleaning up behind Georges.
</P>
<P>
   But despite all the misery and grief caused when Georges roared
ashore out of the Gulf before daybreak Monday morning, its eye
centered on Biloxi, Miss., the storm was not its old killer self.
</P>
<P>
   It could not sustain its 100-mile-an-hour-plus winds for long
once it began to drag over land, leading weather forecasters to
predict, cautiously, that it would probably blow itself out in the
next few days. Moreover, Gulf Coast residents, given plenty of
warning that Georges earlier had killed 300 people and left 100,000
more homeless down in the Caribbean, largely avoided its worst by
battening down ahead of time and fleeing, when they could, to
higher ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could have been a lot worse,'' Kenny Campo, a marina operator
said, as he surveyed his mostly unscathed place in low-lying St.
Bernard Parish, southeast of New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Pensacola was awash in more than 20 inches of rain that fell
there in less than 24 hours. But for all that, flood damage was
relatively minor in most places.
</P>
<P>
   A few streets in downtown Mobile, Ala., were waist-deep in sea
water, and the causeway leading out of town was hit by a sea surge
that swept away some stores and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   One Mobile resident, Sandra Pettway, was less traumatized by
Georges than the 8-foot alligator it drove up into the housing
project in which she lives with her three children. ``Some people
were shooting at him,'' she said. ``But I didn't have a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   In Biloxi, there was also flooding. But the town's main
attraction, its casinos, largely escaped serious damage _ though
not a loss of revenue from having to shut down for several days. A
few miles further west, in Gulfport, the wind blew so hard that it
toppled over an 18-wheel tractor-trailer on Interstate 10.
</P>
<P>
   But most houses and businesses escaped with only a scratch or
two. And in New Orleans, where Georges potentially could have
caused a huge catastrophe _ the city has the Gulf Coast's largest
concentration of people and lies 6 feet below sea level behind its
levees _ there was hardly any damage except along the shores of
Lake Ponchartrain, where storm-driven waves smashed a line of
fishing shacks and cottages.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   By late afternoon, with Georges beginning to slowly drift off
toward the northeast and winds and rains letting up a bit, New
Orleanians, especially those hunkered down in makeshift shelters
like the Superdome, began to chafe for their freedom.
</P>
<P>
   A curfew was still in effect _ ``for your safety until we can
get things straightened out a bit,'' Mayor Marc Morial said _ but
with each passing hour it was ignored by more and more people. Down
in the old French Quarter, Chris LeBoeuf ventured forth and opened
his souvenir shop. And in no time customers were arriving,
especially tourists who had been trapped in their hotels for two
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come in, and they're just glad to have some place to go
for a change,'' LeBoeuf said. The police let it go.
</P>
<P>
   Another of the city's store owners, Frank Ordano, complained
that power company crews had not been fast enough getting power
restored. ''There's no bad weather here,'' he declared. ``Sunday
was a little bit rainy and wind, Monday even less so.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Mobile, by late in the day, the had-enough-of-all-this
story was much the same, though the wind there was still blowing up
to 60 miles an hour, and the rain was still coming down. Debbie
Stephens, hunkered down at home rather than in a shelter, said she
and her family were safe enough but the power was out and ``there's
just nothing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just about to die from boredom,'' she continued. ``There's
no power, no television, no stereo. You can't read. We've played
all the games. And now everybody's eating everything in sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Kirk Fordice of Mississippi said after an early look at the
damage in his state that while Mississippians had been lucky,
foresight also had played a major role in limiting loss. ``The
preparation for this emergency,'' he said, ``is much better than in
years past.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather forecasters predicted that because Georges began to lose
some of its punch as soon as it came ashore early Monday morning,
it probably would lose still more power overnight as it inched
further inland _ barring an unexpected resurgence of energy. By
Tuesday, they said, its maximum sustained winds should be well
below 75 miles an hour, the hurricane force threshold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
