<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISMAL SEASON SHOULDN'T SURPRISE M'S OWNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Before they raced through the clubhouse door after
Sunday's final game _ where was this speed on the hit-and-run? _
some Mariner players offered up sports' trendiest oral fig leaf,
one that helps the speaker avoid any detailed accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``This season,'' said Jay Buhner, among others, ``was a wake-up
call for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   First, any athlete or sports figure who uses the ``wake-up
call'' cliche apparently has the alertness of a hibernating bear.
These guys, and their bosses, are compensated sufficiently to know
how much time is left on their careers. They would be hard-pressed
to justify the consequences of wasting a season.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, how is it possible to infer that the dismal
1998 results were a surprise, when the setup was plain in 1997?
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Mariners won a club-record 90 games in '97, they
were exposed in the Division Series when they hit .218 and had a
5.91 ERA against a Baltimore team that outscored them 23-11.
</P>
<P>
   For all the complaints this season about pitching and defense,
the Mariners had one less error (125) than they had in '97 and a
team ERA (4.93) that was just a little higher than the 4.78 of the
previous season _ one that had an attentive Randy Johnson and no
kid pitchers in September.
</P>
<P>
   Despite many preseason words to the contrary, Mariner bosses
never changed the home run-happy approach to offense, added no
quality position players except David Segui, failed to resolve
bullpen problems in time, and let Johnson flee, first emotionally,
then physically, for nothing that was helpful in '98.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, they threw away a season.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think this circumstance was new for manager Lou Piniella.
In 1991, he presided over a 17-game falloff with the Cincinnati
Reds, who won the 1990 World Series and then went 74-88. Until the
Florida Marlins were decimated this season by their owner, the
Reds' plunge was the worst in history for a Series winner.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain the demise of the '91 Reds, Piniella said
Sunday, ``We had a lot of injuries, and we didn't alter the
(championship) ballclub. We weren't deep. We couldn't afford for
things to go wrong and they did.''
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like the party line for the '98 Mariners, you
have been paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   What that means is that for all the alleged sophistication of
the Mariner ownership, and for all the experience of Woody Woodward
(the longest-tenured GM in baseball), the Mariners' plan for this
season was copied from that paragon of baseball wisdom, Reds owner
Marge Schott.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, Marge insisted on running the same (team) that won
the Series,'' Piniella said. ``She mentioned, `It won once, it can
win again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As Piniella and all baseball people know, it was a bad idea then
and a bad idea now.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking up a winning team ``is a hard thing to do,'' he said.
``But the problem is when you win, everybody else improves, so you
have to improve along with them. If you don't, there's no margin
for error when things don't go well.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the remarks so far from Mariner bosses, there is no
reason to believe there will be much change from the Schott plan
next season.
</P>
<P>
   CEO John Ellis has said ownership is happy with Woodward and
Piniella. Ellis and club president Chuck Armstrong have said on
multiple occasions there will be little change in the player
payroll despite the income from the new stadium, promising only to
make the club ``competitive,'' the vague term that is their minimum
legal obligation that secured public money for the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   While the owners, Woodward and Piniella will counter that
contention with the same vapid optimism of last winter, the fact is
that no one in Mariner ownership or leadership has evinced any
serious contempt over this season or the state of the franchise.
Nor has anyone articulated an aggressive vision for the future that
has any sense of dynamism.
</P>
<P>
   Bad as this season was, the Mariners have had, in winning
percentage, only seven seasons better (1987, '90, '91, '93, '95,
'96, '97). In fact, the Mariners have had just two outstanding
months in their history, 19-8 in September 1995 and 20-7 in June
1997, each of which was sufficient to create division titles.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of the raw record, almost everything else has been
ordinary to awful.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the no-brainer drafts of Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex
Rodriguez and the 1989 trade that brought Johnson, the best thing
that happened to the Mariners was the creation of division play in
1994, putting Seattle in the smallest division in major sports, a
grouping exclusively of unsuccessful franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Yet instead of dominating this tiny principality, the Mariners
have squandered the opportunity, even with the assets of what has
proven to be one of baseball's best markets as well as two of the
greatest all-around players in history.
</P>
<P>
   Much of their talent has seeded the rest of baseball; a whopping
25 former Mariners are in the postseason, and together would
probably play the current club dead-even.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the advent of a new park and its high ticket prices,
complete with a roof that will be used less than 10 percent of the
time, Mariner ownership has quietly embarked on a campaign of
diminished expectations and lowered sights.
</P>
<P>
   After 22 mostly mediocre years, yet with a good group of veteran
players, a new ballpark and millions of new fans, when is it time
to stop acting small?
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
