<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLENTY OF WORK AHEAD AFTER HUMBLING SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It was a season of highlights and humility, of soaring
accomplishments and sinking hopes.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had gotten used to success in recent years,
finishing 40 games over .500 and winning two division titles
between 1995 and '97. This season _ spoiled by the four-month Randy
Johnson saga and a breakdown in defense and relief pitching _ was
humbling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning can hide problems; losing exposes them,'' said manager
Lou Piniella, whose team finished 76-85, 11{ games behind
first-place Texas in the American League West. ``You win and you
overlook. When you lose, it's very hard to overlook.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely a wake-up call,'' said shortstop Alex
Rodriguez, who had 42 homers, 46 steals and no trip to the
postseason. ``We got our (butt) kicked all year, and hopefully
we'll all think about this over the winter and use it as motivation
next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Ken Griffey Jr. had a different idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't think about it, because people are going to
constantly remind you,'' said Griffey, who led the AL with 56 home
runs. ``You've just got to let the front office handle it however
they want to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   The M's offseason will be busy, but it's unlikely to include
major shakeups. Griffey, Rodriguez, David Segui, Jay Buhner, Dan
Wilson, Edgar Martinez (whose $3.5 million option will be picked up
before Nov. 15), Jamie Moyer and Jeff Fassero all return.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners will have the same player payroll (about $52
million) this off-season to enhance that core. Their most important
off-season objectives: acquire an experienced starting pitcher to
join Moyer and Fassero atop the rotation; re-sign closer Mike
Timlin, who converted 19 of 20 save opportunities after the
All-Star break; acquire a leadoff hitter who plays left or right
field; and add a left-handed relief specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Two questions were answered in the season's final weeks, when
right-hander Jose Paniagua secured a spot as a setup reliever and
Carlos Guillen showed Piniella he can be the club's everyday second
baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Others who put themselves in position to make next year's team
are infielder David Bell and Raul Ibanez, who can play first base,
right field and catcher. Right-hander Paul Abbott, who went 3-1 in
September, will have a shot at the starting rotation, as will
right-hander Mac Suzuki, who might be better suited to relief.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers Freddy Garcia, Brett Hinchcliffe and John Halama (the
probable player to be named later from the Johnson trade with
Houston) also figure into next spring's plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are further along as an organization compared to last year
after we won the division,'' Piniella said. ``None of our kids were
ready (then) for this type of exposure or competition. To me, that
is the biggest advantage we have derived from this year, the fact
that these kids have grown into the picture. It really defines what
you need, as opposed to having to do a massive job of
restructuring.''
</P>
<P>
   The undertaking won't be massive, but will be critical. The M's
drew 2.6 million fans this year, but had the biggest drop in
attendance in the American League (nearly 550,000).
</P>
<P>
   Safeco Field opens next July, and Mariners CEO John Ellis
acknowledged that the novelty of a new ballpark will sell tickets
for a while. But, he added, ``that's apt to be a very short-lived
thing if there isn't a competitive team to go with it.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Ellis said, ownership again is authorizing a
payroll it believes will allow the club to win. Cost overruns ($80
million) on Safeco Field, he said, do not affect the budget for
player salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never will be up in the range of the Yankees and Atlanta,''
Ellis said, ``but that doesn't mean we won't be competitive and
aren't willing to spend the dollars necessary. We will.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an ample budget to be competitive,'' said Woody
Woodward, the vice president of baseball operations. ``We just have
to make the right moves to fill in. ... We already have a fine
nucleus in place. If I can get about three young players to come
through _ like a Guillen, Suzuki and Paniagua _ we're almost there.
We'll look to supplement through a trade or a free agent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners will not re-sign free agent Heathcliff Slocumb, who
made $3 million this year, and some of those savings can be
expected to go to Timlin, who has said he wants to return but is
one of the few available free-agent closers, meaning he probably
will command a raise from this year's $3.025 million salary.
</P>
<P>
   The starters the M's pursue won't come from the top class of
free agents, which includes San Diego's Kevin Brown, Texas' Todd
Stottlemyre, the Mets' Al Leiter and, of course, Johnson. Heading
the second tier are San Francisco's Mark Gardner, Los Angeles'
Brian Bohanon, Kansas City's Tim Belcher and the Cubs' Mark Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus will be on getting a 2-3 starter who can give us
innings and win with some consistency,'' said Piniella, who will
accompany Woodward to the general managers' meetings this winter
and take a more active role in personnel decisions. ``If we have
three pitchers with experience who give you innings and keep you in
the ballgame and two of our young kids pitch the way we feel they
can, that will be sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Free-agent left-handed relievers include Boston's Greg Swindell,
the Mets' Dennis Cook and Los Angeles' Mark Guthrie. The Mariners'
own left-hander, Paul Spoljaric, struggled in '98 and might fit in
better as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   The leadoff question is more complicated. The best free agent
probably is Kansas City's Jose Offerman, who plays the same
position as Guillen. Although Guillen batted first this September,
the Mariners see him as a second- or ninth-place hitter.
</P>
<P>
   With Buhner likely to begin the year at first base because of
Sept. 9 elbow surgery, Segui will have to take his slick glove to
the outfield, probably in left because he does not have a
right-fielder's arm.
</P>
<P>
   So without Buhner's arm in right, at least initially, the M's
mystery leadoff man should ideally have a cannon on his shoulder.
That's a rare combination, but the Mariners must find a way to add
to both their speed and defense.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever a new leadoff man plays _ Oakland left fielder Rickey
Henderson is a free agent _ the Mariners know they can't afford
another year of shaky defense. Guillen, who made no errors with
Seattle, should be an improvement over Joey Cora at second, and
Russ Davis made strides at third base in the second half and will
concentrate on agility and footwork during workouts this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some guys who had huge years, and yet we weren't able
to overcome some of our other shortcomings,'' Woodward said. ``We
just have to do a better job on the field and not give the other
team as many outs. ... If we get back to a team that can do that _
and we are very close to getting back _ we'll be fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
