r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FISHER-COLUMN-TEX     09-29 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL'S `GOOD OL' DAYS' DIDN'T OWN ALL OF THE GOOD GUYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it's because I'm still one of those disrespectful,
irreverent young whippersnappers who doesn't properly honor ``the
good ol' days.'' But I'm always amused, and a bit troubled, when I
hear NFL stars of yesteryear dissing their modern-day counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   It comes again now in the wake of the death of Doak Walker,
cheered everywhere as the last of sport's good guys.
</P>
<P>
   But one good guy who came before Doak, and another who followed
him, say the breed lives on.
</P>
<P>
   To the credit of a legend of one bygone generation, Sammy Baugh,
and to the credit of one from a more recent period, Walter Payton,
there are at least two fellas in the Pro Football Hall of Fame who
recognize that some of their 1990s heirs are worthy representatives
of today's Golden Era.
</P>
<P>
   Slingin' Sammy Baugh, 84, is the last survivor of the original
class of 17 to enter the Hall of Fame, and he still likes his NFL
football _ and its QBs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may have been the first one to realize that if you stayed in
the pocket waiting for a receiver to get open, you could get
killed,'' Baugh says. ``That's why I threw on the run so much. Give
me a quarterback who can move to avoid the rush any day.''
</P>
<P>
   And if that sounds like an endorsement of Troy Aikman's
newfound-but-dangerous mobility, well, you're not thinking the way
Sammy's thinking. That perfect QB's name, Sammy?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were picking one today,'' he says, ``it would be Steve
Young.'' And the perfect running back to play behind him? Payton,
the former Chicago Bears standout who owns the NFL rushing record
of 16,726 yards, feels good about the fact Detroit's Barry Sanders
is moving closer to contention for the honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy like Barry, you can't feel bad about it,'' Payton says.
``When the record is eclipsed _ and eventually he will surpass it _
I would like to be there to congratulate him and to shake his hand
and turn over the torch to him and let him take it a little farther
than I took it. ... He's an electric runner and a class guy,''
Payton says.
</P>
<P>
   Update on Young's quality: In Sunday's 31-20 victory over
Atlanta, Young was 28-of-39 for 387 yards. Oh, and he ran seven
times for 50 yards, too.
</P>
<P>
   Update on Sanders' quality: Despite the fact that he earns $5.7
million a year, he still lives in the house he bought as a rookie
for $175,000 near the Silverdome.
</P>
<P>
   See? The football world of today isn't totally populated by
disrespectful, irreverent young whippersnappers. NFL BUZZ Arizona's
victory over the Rams marked the Cardinals' first game back in St.
Louis, and after the visitors won, Arizona owner Bill Bidwill got
the game ball. No, I don't know why, either. ... How suddenly
secure is Denny Green in Minnesota? Owner Red McCombs is asked if
the coach's new $1.55 million-a-year contract is guaranteed.
``Guaranteed,'' McCombs says, ``as long as I have a pulse.'' ...
The Denver offensive line was planning to go mum for all 16 games
again this season. After listening as they were forced to speak at
last year's SB, their decision, frankly, would've been no great
loss. But when coach Mike Shanahan heard that other teams' lines
were considering following the Denver lead, he shut down the
silence club. Good for him, and for NFL fans. ... The 0-4 Bears
have led each of their games at halftime and have been outscored
44-0 in third quarters. ... Talk to people who know the unemployed
ex-Ram and ex-Dolphin Lawrence Phillips and they'll tell you how
concerned they are about his future as a human being without
football. The Packers may bring Phillips in for another look this
week. ... San Diego has four TDs in four games. ... Got time for
some nice NFL news? Jaguars owner Wayne Weaver donated $100,000 to
help Florida families whose homes were destroyed by fires. And the
NFL matched the donation. ... It was notable going into Sunday that
Jerry Rice had 26 TD catches against the Falcons. It's more notable
now that he added two more in San Francisco's victory over Atlanta,
making him the all-time leader in TDs by one player vs. one team.
... Cincinnati tackle Kevin Sargent has a new contract that pays
him a $3.5 million signing bonus. Sargent's buddies suggest he's on
the frugal side, a suggestion confirmed when Kevin explains that
he'll reward himself by splurging on a sprinkler system for his
yard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
