<HEADLINE>
STARS' GUSEV MAY RETURN TO MINORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Mike Heika 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Just when it seems Sergey Gusev's timing was
right, Darryl Sydor's timing couldn't have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   Gusev is a 23-year-old rookie defenseman who has been the bright
spot of the Dallas Stars preseason by combining with fellow
defenseman Sergei Zubov to score 10 points (three goals, seven
assists) in four exhibition games. But just when it looked as
though the enigmatic Gusev had earned his way into the lineup,
Zubov's regular defensive partner from last season _ Sydor _
returned from a contract holdout.
</P>
<P>
   With Sydor secured for the next four seasons at a cost of $10
million, it's almost certain that he and Zubov will be reunited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darryl has to earn his way back into the lineup,'' assistant
coach Rick Wilson said with a sly smile. ``We may not put him and
Zubie back together for at least 12 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the ``My Sergey'' headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gusev is proving this season that it will be much harder
to send him back to the Stars' International Hockey league
affiliate in Kalamazoo, Mich _ his address for the previous three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been here for three years already, so my goal is to
make NHL,'' said the native of Negniy Tagel, Russia. ``I feel more
comfortable here. I want to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Gusev is proving his comfort level is no fluke. He has
two goals and three assists and is a plus-1 in four exhibition
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two things that have kept him out of the NHL _
consistent play and ability to pay the physical price,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said of Gusev. ``Now what's happened is he's
gone in and paid the price for the most part and he's played at a
high level pretty much every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's at that level right now where he smells it and feels like
that there's a spot open that can be his on a regular basis, and
not just the seventh (defenseman) spot,'' he added. ``He wants the
season, it looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   But earning a spot among the top six just got tougher. Sydor is
expected to return to practice today, and he and Zubov have been
one of the NHL's top scoring tandems among defensemen for the past
two seasons. Hitchcock let out more than a hint when he said Monday
that ``the player who plays with Zubov has to play more than 20
minutes a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Gusev's offensive skills could make him a perfect fit as a sixth
defenseman who contributes heavily to the power play _ possibly
with Zubov _ but not as a regular logging in excess of 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And that could hurt Gusev's development. The wily Zubov has
taken Gusev ``under his wing,'' Hitchcock said. And Gusev also was
helped by a two-week visit from former Soviet Union coach Vladimir
Joursinov, who was able to accentuate some of the basics of the
game, Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His problem is he's always trying to find the perfect play,
not unlike his countryman on the right side (Zubov),'' the coach
said. ``He's now learned to play on the power play as a point guy
in North American hockey, which is get (the puck) on net as quickly
as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, combined with Gusev's improved consistency, has the
coaching staff serious about keeping him around, whether he teams
with Zubov or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole other level that has to be obtained,''
Hitchcock said. ``But he seems to be playing with a lot of
composure.'' MATVICHUK IMPROVING
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Richard Matvichuk went through a full practice
Monday, including contact. The defenseman who had surgery June 23
to replace the anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee, said he
felt good.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some tendinitis in there that we have to work out,''
he said. ``But it's ahead of schedule and I'm not going to push it
too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk said he is hoping to return by Nov. 1. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Brett Hull, who was held out of Friday's exhibition game with
an abdominal strain, participated in a full practice Monday and is
expected to play with the Stars in their preseason game Tuesday in
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hitchcock said Monday that his plans this season include using
Sydor as a forward on the penalty killing unit. With Hull also a
possible addition, Hitchcock said the team might use four penalty
killing pairs. Winger Pat Verbeek (sore elbow) went through full
practice Monday and was unsure if he would accompany the Stars to
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hitchcock said that with the postponement of last Saturday's
preseason game with Tampa Bay until Oct. 5, he likely will not make
further cuts until Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
