 12 NOTES-TEX 
McCOWN TO REPLACE STEWART AS AGGIES' STARTER 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Randy McCown will replace Branndon Stewart as the starting
quarterback when No. 18 Texas A&AMP;M meets Kansas on Saturday in
Lawrence, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum announced the change Monday, saying McCown
deserved the chance to start based on the spark he provided a
struggling offense in a 28-9 victory against North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   McCown, a junior, replaced Stewart with 2:39 remaining in the
first half and A&AMP;M clinging to a 7-3 lead. He completed 11 of 13
passes for a career-high 169 yards and two touchdowns. He also
rushed nine times for 39 yards, helping the Aggies improve to 3-1
heading into their Big 12 opener against Kansas (2-2, 0-2).
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe it to Randy to give him a chance to start based on what
he did in that game,'' Slocum said. ``Things seemed to pick up a
little bit when he was in there. I'm not down on Branndon. But I
think this is what we need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1997 season, McCown replaced a struggling Stewart in
the starting lineup for a game at Texas Tech. McCown completed 2 of
8 passes for 7 yards, was sacked three times and lost a fumble at
the A&AMP;M 17-yard line that set up Tech's lone touchdown. Tech won,
16-13.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, a fifth-year senior from Stephenville with a career
mark of 18-10 as the Aggies' starting quarterback, returned to the
lineup the next week. The contest remains McCown's lone collegiate
start.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M coaches are counting on different results this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been a little frustrated with our inconsistencies on
offense,'' offensive coordinator Steve Kragthorpe said. ``I'm happy
we've won three in a row, but I'm not satisfied. The big thing with
Randy is that he lit a fire among our players with his scrambling.
He did a good job of improvising and making plays.''
</P>
<P>
   After averaging 35.2 points per game in 1997, A&AMP;M is scoring
23.5 a game this season despite the return of every skill-position
starter. McCown, in limited duty this season, has completed 73.7
percent of his passes (14-for-19), with two touchdowns and no
interceptions. Stewart's completion rating is 50.7 (35-for-69). He
has thrown one touchdown pass and one interception.
</P>
<P>
   Neither player could be reached for comment Monday. TEXAS-OU
STARTS EARLY
</P>
<P>
   Big 12 officials announced the Oct. 10 Texas-Oklahoma game would
kick off at 11:30 a.m. in the Cotton Bowl. It will be televised on
KXTX/Channel 39 as part of the league's syndicated television
package.
</P>
<P>
   No starting times for other Oct. 10 games were announced. League
officials said ABC executives have exercised their right to wait
until Sunday before deciding whether to show Nebraska-Texas A&AMP;M or
Colorado-Kansas State as the network's 2:30 p.m. game.
</P>
<P>
   The unselected contest, said associate commissioner Tim Allen,
will move to 6 p.m. and be televised by either Fox Sports Southwest
or FX. Also, the Texas Tech-Oklahoma State game will be a 6 p.m.
telecast on either Fox Sports Southwest or FX. JAMES WILL START
</P>
<P>
   Baylor coach Dave Roberts said quarterback Odell James will
remain the Bears' starter, although it was backup Jermaine Alfred
who drove the team to a go-ahead touchdown in the fourth quarter of
an 18-16 loss to No. 15 Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   James, a sophomore, has completed 16 of 37 passes (43.2
percent), with three interceptions and no touchdowns in the Bears'
first three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Odell's our quarterback, but Jermaine may play a little more
this week than he has been,'' said Roberts, who watched Alfred
complete 9 of 16 passes for 58 yards, including two third-down
connections on the fourth-quarter scoring drive. Roberts said
James, who suffered bruised ribs against Colorado, should not be
hampered by the injury in 6 p.m. game Saturday at Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to improve our quarterback play, but Odell's just a
puppy,'' Roberts said. ``He's going to make some mistakes, and
we'll live with it.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Texas coach Mack Brown sent a telegram Monday to Prairie View
A&AMP;M coach Greg Johnson, offering congratulations on a 14-12 victory
against Langston that broke an NCAA-record 80-game losing streak.
The text: ``Congratulations on getting a new start. Best of luck.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Brown, on Sunday's death of Doak Walker, the 1948 Heisman
Trophy winner and namesake of the national running back award won
last season by Longhorns' tailback Ricky Williams: ``It will be
emotional this week for Ricky. He became close to the Walker family
after winning the award last year. For society and anyone who cares
about college football, this is an awful loss. Doak Walker was
``the'' role model for college football. All fathers wanted their
sons to grow up and be like Doak Walker.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Williams was selected the Big 12 offensive player of the week
after rushing for a career-high 318 yards and six touchdowns in a
59-21 victory against Rice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
