<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9405 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GIANTS-CUBS-HNS &LR;      09-29 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-CUBS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANNY ROBBINS  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
CHICAGO _ The first National League wild-card playoff game was a
celebration of all things Cub.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A throng of 39,556 under the lights at Wrigley Field. The masses
in the streets and on the rooftops. Michael Jordan throwing out the
first ball. Bill Murray belting out Take Me Out to the Ball Game.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's game had everything for those who worship at the shrine
of the beautiful little ballpark at Clark and Addison.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Rod Serling ending.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs beat the San Francisco Giants 5-3 after surviving a
ninth inning in which the Giants put up three runs against a trio
of Cubs pitchers running on empty.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, Cubs manager Jim Riggleman used two of his
starters, Kevin Tapani and Terry Mulholland, and closer Rod Beck.
Both Mulholland and Beck had pitched in the Cubs' 4-3 loss to the
Astros on Sunday, Mulholland going eight innings and 121 pitches
and Beck 2 and 36.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Giants, Beck got the final two outs, the game ending
when Joe Carter, whose home run won the 1993 World Series for
Toronto, popped to first baseman Mark Grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking people to do some extraordinary things,''
Riggleman said, ``but they keep coming up big for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with the victory, the Cubs avoided the kind of disaster
that colors the team's history while gaining a spot in the
playoffs, starting Wednesday in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The victory also was built on a couple of hitting stars who
don't answer to ``Sammy,'' Gary Gaetti and Matt Mieske. Gaetti
broke open a scoreless game in the fifth with a two-run homer;
Mieske, pinch hitting in the sixth, came through with a two-run
single.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs starter Steve Trachsel went 6 innings and left with a line
of six walks, one hit batter _ and one hit.
</P>
<P>
   Trachsel wobbled through the final month, going 0-1 in five
September starts and becoming a footnote to history by giving up
Mark McGwire's 62nd home run. He was on a similar course Monday as
he struggled with his control. But he did manage to squirm out of
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Trachsel put the Giants down in order in the first and then
began pitching himself into tight spots, giving the Giants just
about everything except a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adrenalin was flowing,'' he said. ``I threw 120 pitches,
but it felt more like 40.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants starter Mark Gardner, who hadn't lost since July 30, gave
up a pair of singles in the first two innings but cruised through
the third and fourth before the Cubs came alive.
</P>
<P>
   Following a leadoff single by Henry Rodriguez in the fifth,
Gaetti cranked an 0-2 pitch into the left-field bleachers to make
it a 2-0 game.
</P>
<P>
   The home run was Gaetti's 19th of the season and eighth since he
signed with the Cubs as a free agent Aug. 19, his 40th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs made it 4-0 in the sixth on Mieske's two-run single off
reliever Rich Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching with a four-run lead in the seventh, Trachsel got one
out before giving up a single to pinch hitter Brent Mayne. After
Trachsel walked the next batter, pinch hitter Armando Rios,
Riggleman went to his bullpen, where danger always lurks.
</P>
<P>
   Riggleman's choice, Matt Karchner, got the second out when
Orlando Merced, who had just entered to play left field, made a
dazzling catch on Stan Javier's foul pop at the rail.
</P>
<P>
   When the Giants loaded the bases on Shawon Dunston's ground
single up the middle, Riggleman brought in Felix Heredia to pitch
to Barry Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The threat ended with Bonds grounding weakly to first.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs took a 5-0 lead to the ninth, with Kevin Tapani, in his
first relief role since 1993, on the mound. Tapani, who would have
started Game 1 against the Braves had he not pitched Monday, got
the Cubs through a scoreless eighth.
</P>
<P>
   But he gave up two singles to start the ninth. Next into the
fire came Mulholland, who allowed Javier's RBI single, walked Ellis
Burks and gave up a sacrifice fly to Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Beck, formerly of the Giants, then got Jeff Kent to ground to
short, bringing in San Francisco's third run. He then induced
Carter to hit his floater to Grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never faced Joe Carter,'' Beck said. ``After throwing him
a couple of soft pitches, I remembered something (Giants manager)
Dusty Baker once said: `Guys with long arms like the ball away,' so
I went inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dusty helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck said he was just happy to be part of something positive at
Wrigley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard all about the losing ways since I've been here,''
he said. ``I'm just happy to give Chicago and my employers
something big.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
