A9418 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CUBS-BONDS-NYT &LR;      09-29 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-BONDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS YEAR JUST ISN'T NEXT YEAR FOR BONDS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ As the Cubs took victory laps and sprayed Champagne on
Wrigley Field, former Cub Shawon Dunston stayed on the top step of
the San Francisco dugout, watching his former mates. Pitcher Julian
Tavarez slapped a photographer with his glove. Barry Bonds sat
quietly in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have anything to be ashamed of,'' said Bonds, who was
0 for 4 and left six runners on base. ``We played hard to get
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The comeback Giants lost to the Cubs, 5-3, in Monday night's
one-game playoff for the National League wild card.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 20, the Giants were out of the hunt, four games behind
the Mets and three behind the Cubs, but down the stretch they won
nine of their last 11 games to pass the Mets and catch the Cubs and
force this playoff.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday night the Giants managed only a handful of hits off
Steve Trachsel and a baling-wire Cubs bullpen. Even so, they missed
several chances to get back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded and two outs in the seventh inning, Bonds
hit a weak ground ball to first base.
</P>
<P>
   With a runner at third and two outs in the eighth, J.T. Snow hit
a grounder to second.
</P>
<P>
   Up again in the ninth as the tying run, Bonds hit a sacrifice
fly to Sammy Sosa in right field, making the score 5-2. When asked
how close he was to a home run, Bonds glared and said, ``Not close
enough.'' Then he smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit line drives right at some people,'' Bonds said.
``Trachsel was the best I've ever seen him. We never got any
momentum going with less than two outs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants had their late chances, but never got the potential
game-winning run to bat.
</P>
<P>
   Each time the Giants failed, the standing-room-only Cubs crowd
went into full ``holy cow'' mode. ``I don't hear it,'' Bonds said.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants finished 89-74, the seventh-best record in baseball,
but one game short of October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go home and watch the playoffs on TV,'' Jeff Kent said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the crowd was still chanting, ``Sammy! Sammy!'' as Sosa
climbed on top of the dugout, where he was mobbed by fans. A
middle-aged man kissed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say enough about what a year Sammy had,'' Bonds
said. ``But Gary Gaetti, what a year he had, at his age.'' Gaetti
is 40, six years older than Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The Champagne started flowing in the clubhouse, but the Chicago
Cubs took the celebration to the field, the first time the Cubs
clinched a playoff spot at home since 1930.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa made a final run, this time doused in Champagne by his
right field bleacher bums. Rod Beck's wife, Stacey, kissed Manager
Jim Riggleman. Matt Karchner cried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through this six times in the 90s, losing at the
end,'' Bonds said. He sat shirtless by his locker, a No. 24 chain
around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep saying I'll be back. I'll be back next year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
