A9450 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEINSTEIN-HYDE-SFCHRO     09-29 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEINSTEIN-HYDE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEINSTEIN'S COMMENTS IRK HYDE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ Underscoring the enormous pressure on lawmakers as
they move toward a congressional inquiry into President Clinton,
House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., accused
California Democratic Sen. Dianne Feinstein Monday of making
``wildly unfair and inaccurate comments'' regarding his committee's
investigation.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hyde said that Feinstein's comments on a Sunday talk show ``add
to a picture that is so distorted and unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just really resent it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde and Feinstein are both well-regarded for their sense of
diplomacy, and the exchange comes a week before the Judiciary
Committee is scheduled to vote on whether to begin a formal
impeachment inquiry against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein complained on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' that while
Republican investigators have ``offices, computers and a whole
setup,'' their Democratic counterparts are working from a ``a file
folder and cell phone.'' She predicted that the impeachment process
that has begun in the House ``will be remembered for at least 100
years,'' and said ``it has to be fair, it has to be nonpartisan,
and it has to be sustainable. . . . As I see it unfolding, it is
none of the above.''
</P>
<P>
   The two have had a good working relationship, dating to
Feinstein's efforts to pass an assault weapon ban in 1994.
Nevertheless, after watching Feinstein on television, Hyde fired
off an angry letter to Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., the Judiciary
Committee's ranking Democratic member.
</P>
<P>
   Labeling Feinstein as ``misinformed,'' Hyde said Democrats were
provided an office in a House office building last spring and said
Republicans have approved every request for space or supplies
since. There are seven Democratic attorneys and investigators
working on the Clinton matter, compared to 14 for the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic staffers conceded Monday that Hyde was correct, but
said they had only on Friday been granted a suitable office. The
lead Democratic counsel had not had a desk and had told Feinstein
last week that he had been working from a file folder and cell
phone for months, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I understand it, this issue has now been resolved,''
Feinstein wrote in a letter to Hyde Monday. ``I do not want our
exchange to become an issue in your committee's all too important
work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 0317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 03:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9454 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SQUID-MYSTERY-SFCHRON     09-29 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SQUID-MYSTERY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA FISHERMAN'S RARE CATCH _ 25-POUND SQUID 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM DOYLE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A Bodega Bay, Calif., fisherman hauled in an
unusual catch Monday, netting a mysterious jumbo squid that was
rushed to a nearby marine lab to try to keep it alive.
</P>
<P>
   With its huge black eyes, the squid (species Dosidicus gigas)
measured more than four feet long and weighed 25 pounds. It was
extremely aggressive, lunging and spewing quarts of brown ink when
brought to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   It is among the first such creatures in captivity. ``So far,
none have survived,'' said John Grissim, publisher of the
ocean-news journal Marine Watch in Point Reyes Station, Calif.
``This is the largest ever captured alive.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, scientists and volunteers at the Bodega Marine
Laboratory have tried to catch a Dosidicus gigas for research and
testing, but each time the traumatized creatures have lasted only a
few days.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, the lab's new acquisition was swimming peacefully
in three feet of circulating sea water. The tank, 10 feet in
diameter, was covered with a tarp to provide shade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks to be in beautiful condition,'' said Peter Connors,
reserve manager at the marine laboratory. ``It seems very healthy,
very lively and not injured. It's moving very slowly and
smoothly.''
</P>
<P>
   The species is separate from the smaller squid from South
America that are sold locally as calamari, or the fabled giant
squids of up to 60 feet in length that have shown up in nets _ dead
_ or washed ashore off England and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's catch was the handiwork of Jim Hie, a volunteer at the
lab, which is run by the University of California at Davis. His
28-foot sportfishing boat, Anna II, was 20 miles off the coast near
Cordell Bank in roughly 500 feet of water when Hie felt a
tremendous tug on a jig line.
</P>
<P>
   The artificial lure and hook had apparently snagged one of the
squid's arms at a depth of 40 feet. The retired electrician and
former Navy jet fighter pilot said he battled the feisty mollusk
for almost 30 minutes, before finally putting a net around it.
</P>
<P>
   Hie immediately placed the squid in a 450 gallon tank on his
boat. Then he sped to shore on calm seas. Monday afternoon, lab
workers moved the squid by truck to the marine lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's huge,'' said Hie at the Spud Point Marina in Bodega Bay.
``He's six inches across between the eyes and he is mad right now.
He's brown, goes to red and goes back to brown. The whole side of
the boat is a mess from him. Myself and my boat are covered with
ink.''
</P>
<P>
   With their tentacles stretched out, an adult jumbo squid
measures about six feet long. Each tentacle has scores of suction
cups, and each ``sucker'' contains razor sharp teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists differ on how dangerous it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Squid, by their nature, run away. By and large, they're
harmless,'' said Christopher Mah, an invertebrate zoologist at the
California Academy of Sciences who specializes in starfish. ``It's
not dangerous in the way a shark or jellyfish would be. It's only
dangerous if you push it that way'' by provoking or trapping it.
</P>
<P>
   But Grissim said the enigmatic creatures are incredibly
ferocious.
</P>
<P>
   ``These squid have been known to attack people. They even attack
each other,'' Grissim said. ``They also have an amazing ability to
change color instantly. They are the fastest color-changing
creatures known to man. Waves of color flow through them.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists suspect that the mysterious squid may employ
different colors for courtship dances, camouflage and luring prey.
``We think they're very bright, but they are implacable _ totally
unrelenting and cold,'' Grissim said.
</P>
<P>
   The squid migrate in large schools, sometimes up to 10,000 in
number, and hover over fish populations.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as a result of El Nino's warmer waters, Dosidicus gigas
is being spotted much farther north than usual. The jumbo squid are
also known as Humboldt Squid because they are found more often in
the Humboldt Current off the coast of Chile and Peru.
</P>
<P>
   Hie netted a jumbo squid in February, but it was heavily
traumatized and died soon afterward. ``The chance of this guy
surviving are good,'' he said. ``I think we'll get at least several
days out of him for tests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
