<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST SAY SHEESH! 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I did not fuss when feminists succeeded in changing the word
``mailman'' to ``letter carrier,'' ``congressman'' to
``congressperson'' and ``stewardess'' to ``flight attendant.''
</P>
<P>
   Although this new, de-genderized language can be a little clunky
at times, it makes sense and certainly better reflects the modern,
diversified workplace.
</P>
<P>
   That having been said, I must object as strenuously as is
possible without getting out of my chair to a campaign being waged
by Varla Ventura of (where else?) San Francisco to start calling
powerful female role models ``sheroes'' instead of ``heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ventura gets her way _ she's urging people to write letters
to the editors of Merriam-Webster's Dictionary supporting the
change _ it will soon be politically incorrect to refer to Xena,
the Warrior Princess, or Wonder Woman as heroes. The proper term
would be ``sheroes.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a story carried by Wireless Flash News Service,
Ventura thinks the word ``hero'' reeks of masculine overtones while
the feminine form _ ``heroine'' _ sounds like the name of a
narcotic drug.
</P>
<P>
   (Speaking of narcotic drugs, count Oprah Winfrey among those who
not only approve of the word ``shero'' but can say it aloud without
laughing.)
</P>
<P>
   In my opinion, shero advocacy is simply phase one of a feminist
conspiracy to completely rid the English language of the
politically incorrect prefix, ``he.''
</P>
<P>
   Being gender-specific is one thing, but replacing ``he'' with
``she'' every time a word pertains to a female (another bad word)
is inviting linguistic lunacy, not to mention creating a whole new
criminal class in the eyes of the political correctness police.
</P>
<P>
   Take the word ``heap,'' for instance, a word that would be
transformed to ``sheap'' in the brave new world of Ventura's
lexicon. This would give rise to such hallucinogenic sentences as,
``Sally spooned a big sheap of mashed potatoes onto her plate'' or
``Betty Sue, put that Cosmo back on the rack or you gonna be in a
sheap o' trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearsay'' would become ``shearsay'' as in, ``Monica's
involvement with the president turned out to be more than just
shearsay.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers of the sports pages will have to adjust to the new
grammar, too, as in the sentence, ``After running the marathon in
90-degree heat, Vanessa collapsed from sheat exhaustion.''
</P>
<P>
   Astronauts re-entering the Earth's atmosphere would be protected
by a heat shield, unless a female astronaut was on board, in which
case it would become a sheat shield. Or something.
</P>
<P>
   If a woman wanted to throw something out (like the language, for
instance), she would give it the ``ol' sheave-ho.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewish women would speak Shebrew to one another in the
synagogue, though how that would be different from Hebrew is
anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   A corny TV show relying heavily on rural humor and featuring
female-only country-western singers would be called ``Shee-Haw''
and it would presumably be just as stupid as ``Hee-Haw'' was in its
day.
</P>
<P>
   The gas used to inflate toy balloons would, in the future, be
called shelium, assuming the person doing the inflating was a she
and not a he.
</P>
<P>
   A more medically precise term for a black eye would be a
shematoma, depending on the gender of the person delivering or,
perhaps, receiving, the shiner.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is more than enough to give me the heebie-jeebies,
but not enough to give me the sheebie-jeebies.
</P>
<P>
   At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Sarasota (Fla.)
Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
