<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYT clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 For Immediate Release
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; There's trouble in the food supply, both animal and vegetable.
With food-borne illnesses soaring, consumers are being warned that
eating too many raw or minimally processed fruits and vegetables is
risky. And genetic engineering, some say, is threatening to upset
nature's balance in many ways. In a three-part series, Globe
photo-journalist Stan Grossfeld explores the situation.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SPCL-FOOD-I (Undated) _ As many as 30 million cases of
food-borne illnesses cause up to 9,100 deaths annually in the
United States. President Clinton is asking for $100 million to
improve food safety amid growing concern that federal regulatory
efforts are inconsistent and unreliable. 1500 words. PHOTOS (3)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   SPCL-FOOD-PESTICIDES (Valle del Yaqui, Mexico) -- Farmworkers
from Mexico, a key exporter of produce, risk their lives being
exposed to pesticide spraying. 1600 words.
</P>
<P>
   SPCL-FOOD-II (Milan, Mo.) -- Animal waste from big factory farms
is an emerging national problem and federal regulations fail to
adequately protect water quality from animal waste. (2 takes)
PHOTOS (3)
</P>
<P>
   SPCL-FOOD-III (Chesterfield, Mo.) -- Genetic engineering of
plants has triggered a major food-safety controversy in Europe.
Activists call the rapidly expanding list of genetically engineered
foods ``Frankenfood.'' Slowly, like ketchup creeping from a bottle,
the genetic engineering debate is shifting to America. (2 takes)
PHOTOS (3)
</P>
