<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9783 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-300-YARD-GAME30-C     09-29 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-300-YARD-GAME30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The deal behind Williams' 300-yard game
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ricky Williams claims he could have carried
another 15 times Saturday night against the Rice Owls, but a deal
is a deal, even if it's sealed with a wink and a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Coach Mack Brown, told late in the game that his senior
halfback was within striking distance of his first 300-yard game,
approached Williams with the offer of one more series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He winked at me and smiled,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams broke a 9-yarder, then a 41-yard touchdown, and then
retired to the bench with 318 yards and the roar of the crowd in
his ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had been 5 yards, 4 yards, 5 yards, I don't know if I'd
have left him in,'' Brown said. ``I heard after the game the fans
were chanting Ricky, Ricky. I'm glad I kept on those headphones.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's 59-21 rout of Rice marked the third straight
one-sided game in which Brown has had to decide when to pull
Williams, but it was the first time mercy guided his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he had mixed emotions about whether to sit Ricky or
let him try for Roosevelt Leaks' single-game UT rushing record of
342 yards, set against SMU in 1973. ``I felt bad in some ways with
him having a chance to break the record,'' Brown said. ``I also
remember what it was like to stand on the sideline getting beat by
Kansas State.''
</P>
<P>
   Empathy for Rice was one of four major factors in Brown's
decision about when to pull Williams. The second was the risk of
injury, and Brown said he wanted to make sure he wasn't sending a
fatigued Williams into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed like he was more tired at the end of the first
quarter than at the end of the third,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Confidence in the defense was the third factor. ``The thing is,
with our defense, 21 points is not much,'' he said. ``Until we got
the field goal (to go up 45-21 early in the fourth quarter), I
didn't feel good. Last year (as North Carolina's coach), there were
times when I felt I could have left the stadium, come back later,
and still be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   The final factor was fairness to the other Longhorns. Brown
wanted to make sure backup halfback Hodges Mitchell got some snaps
(he had 50 yards on eight carries) and didn't want Williams running
behind the second-team offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the big first half (187 yards), I saw that 300 was
within reach,'' said Williams, who was apprised of his yardage
total at halftime. ``I wanted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has averaged 184.0 yards through four games and will
need 170.3 over the last seven to break Tony Dorsett's career
rushing record of 6,082. Last spring Brown talked about how winning
games would take precedence over winning Williams the Heisman. Now,
it's clear that it's almost impossible to separate the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question the Heisman is important to this
program,'' Brown said. ``You look at some of the people he's
outgained and they all won the Heisman.''
</P>
<P>
   Five of the nine running backs ahead of Williams on the all-time
rushing list won the Heisman _ Dorsett (1976), Charles White ('79),
Herschel Walker ('82), Archie Griffin ('74, '75) and George Rogers
('80).
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit me that Ricky is making history,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he began to have greater appreciation of the pressure
Williams faces when he heard a quote from a pitcher who had to face
Mark McGwire. The pitcher talked of every pitch being a ``record
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So you know they're going to give it all on every pitch to
him,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams that come in here don't talk about beating us, they all
talk about stopping Ricky. He's handled that well.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wangrin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
