<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENGALS-OVER30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bengals' season over
 &HT;    By Marty Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI, Ohio _ The end of September brings two certainties _
cold weather is about to begin and the Cincinnati Bengals' playoff
hopes are about to end.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati ended their all-too-familiar September swan song in
Baltimore Sunday night, losing 31-24 to the Ravens and dropping to
1-3.
</P>
<P>
   Since last making the playoffs in 1990, the Bengals are 7-25 at
this stage of the season. They've gone 0-4 three times, 1-3 three
times and 2-2 twice.
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday night, coach Bruce Coslet referred to the loss in
Baltimore as ``demoralizing.'' The Bengals quickly fell behind
21-0, fought back to within 21-17 early in the second half and then
let the Ravens regain control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't hold me to anything I say right after a game,'' Coslet
said during a press conference on Monday. ``I'm not demoralized.
I'm probably frustrated. But you come back, you watch the films and
you try to fix the things that went wrong. And they are fixable. We
have players who are good enough to fix them.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be some extra time for fixing because the Bengals
have a bye this Sunday. They host 3-1 Pittsburgh on Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Coslet defended his decision of passing on fourth and one from
Baltimore's 32-yard line with 1:46 left. Jeff Blake, who played
much of the second half after Neil O'Donnell went out with bruised
ribs, tried to hit Darnay Scott, but Scott couldn't make the catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play was there and we blew it,'' Coslet said. ``It's all
execution. I stand up here every week and say the same damn thing
and it's still true. We execute in practice and for some reason we
do something different in the games.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss to the Ravens was a microcosm of the way the season has
unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals get Corey Dillon untracked for 116 yards, but allow
Baltimore's Priest Holmes to get 173 in his first NFL start.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals make a big play on special teams when Tremain Mack
returns the second-half kickoff 97 yards, then get burned for an
87-yard punt return TD by the Ravens' Jermaine Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals get a 67-yard touchdown pass from Blake to Carl
Pickens, but allow Eric Zeier to throw a 73-yarder to Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   After a strong showing in the previous week's 13-6 loss to Green
Bay, the young Cincinnati defense took a giant step backward,
allowing Baltimore to gain an average of 7.1 yards on 58 offensive
plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the athletic ability and the play-making ability of the
young guys and in the recent past I haven't been able to stand up
here and say that,'' Coslet said. ``We'll be OK eventually, but it
hurts to go through these growing pains.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside linebacker Tom Tumulty is out for the season after
suffering a serious knee injury on Sunday. His replacement, rookie
Brian Simmons, made some plays, but he was more dazed than
dazzling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a rookie and he just came back after missing about 2
weeks of practice (following arthroscopic knee surgery), Coslet
said. ``He made some real good plays and he made some rookie-type
plays. That's what we're dealing with. We're very young and very
aggressive and we're not quite ready for prime time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
