<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-RUNNING30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Declining rushing game hurting Dallas
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Four weeks into the NFL season, the most
disturbing trend for the Dallas Cowboys has been the steady decline
of their once-overpowering running game.
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure whether the blame belongs to Emmitt Smith, the
offensive line, a combination of both, or none of the above. But no
one can dispute the team's diminishing rushing totals from the
first four games:
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 6, Arizona: 42 carries, 183 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 13, Denver: 30 carries, 169 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 21, New York Giants: 29 carries, 80 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 27, Oakland: 25 carries, 68 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all share in the responsibility of not being able to run
the ball,'' Coach Chan Gailey said Monday, one day after his team
suffered a 13-12 setback to the Raiders at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The decline of the running attack has put extra pressure on
quarterback Jason Garrett, who passed for 222 yards against
Oakland. But two interceptions, including one on the Cowboys' final
possession, robbed them of a chance to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett's inexperience contributed to both of his interceptions,
Gailey said. Both were thrown in the end zone _ directly at the
Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's first interception was caught by rookie Charles
Woodson. It shocked many at Texas Stadium because the pass,
intended for Michael Irvin, was thrown directly at Woodson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they were thinking,'' Woodson said. ``He
threw the ball right to me. All I had to do was catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey blamed himself for the busted play.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday, he said, Garrett had practiced that particular
pass route with Billy Davis and Ernie Mills. The timing was wrong
Sunday because Irvin was not used to that play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my fault for putting (Garrett and Irvin) in that
position,'' Gailey said. ``Ernie and Billy are usually the guys who
run that play.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrett's final interception was even more costly. He had three
options on his final pass of the fourth quarter, and elected to
throw to Davis, who was double-covered by the Raiders near the goal
line. Irvin and Deion Sanders were running short patterns and
appeared open.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland safety Eric Turner easily cradled Garrett's pass,
sealing the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came right to me,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey is concerned that the tough loss might discourage the 2-2
Cowboys, who have an NFC East game at Washington on October 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't let one loss cost you two,'' Gailey said. ``I told
the team I know it hurts to lose, and it's even harder when you
have opportunities to win. It's frustrating. But we can't let one
loss turn into two. This is a big division game we have to get
ready for.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Troy Aikman hopes to return for the Oct. 11 home
game against Carolina. Gailey said Aikman might be the No. 3
quarterback at Washington, but it's doubtful he'll be used in any
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
