</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-SPEAKS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jesse Jackson plans for Appalachia revitalization
 &HT;    By Charlise Lyles
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NELSONVILLE, Ohio _ The needs of Appalachia and Harlem should be
on the radar screens of Wall Street and Congress much like their
concerns about the economies of troubled countries overseas, the
Rev. Jesse Jackson said recently.
</P>
<P>
   To end Appalachia's relentless poverty, Jackson called for small
business development, public-private investment, philanthropy and
government incentive programs to aid businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street has 'red lined' Appalachia and Harlem,'' Jackson
said at an economic roundtable that ended the Rainbow/PUSH
Coalition's 10-day journey through Appalachia. Recalling slain
civil rights leader the Rev. Martin Luther King's ``Poor People's
Campaign,'' Jackson drew attention to the region's economic,
education, employment and housing needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When one speaks of the economic challenges of Appalachia, the
debate is de-racialized,'' he said. ``We could have the same debate
in Harlem. . . . Appalachia is not on Wall Street's mind. Harlem is
not on Wall Street's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're not here fighting Wall Street,'' Jackson said.
``Appalachia needs Wall Street. We must put forth a deal where
Appalachia develops and Wall Street expands, and everybody wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson called the roundtable as part of the Rainbow/PUSH
Coalition's Wall Street Project. Launched in January 1997, the
project aims to steer investment capital into underserved areas.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he plans to urge his buddy, President Clinton, to
conduct a town hall meeting here to discuss investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been having town hall meetings on race to discuss how
we feel about each other,'' Jackson said. ``But there's no budget
attached to touchy, feely. There is no more access to capital from
touchy, feely.''
</P>
<P>
   A day after the coalition drew between 2,500 and 5,000 marchers
here, Jackson convened about 40 state and federal bureaucrats,
business people, and nonprofit managers to devise long-term
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Bischak of the Appalachian Regional Commission said the
area's main economic challenge is to replace with high-paying
service jobs nearly 200,000 manufacturing jobs lost over the past
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   To boost private investment, Jackson urged residents to lobby
Congress for federal incentives similar to the export/import bank
and other U.S. foreign assistance programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come to Appalachia to say that we must at least do as much
for our people here as we do for foreign allies and even some
adversaries,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Developer D. Duane Jack of Envision Dayton urged renovation of
old abandoned buildings that can qualify for a 20 percent federal
tax credit if listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Jack is looking to restore an old brewery on Ohio
33, converting into a a center for shops or other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dayton has one of the largest urban Appalachian populations,
but what we have is everyone moving out of downtown. Whether it be
Nelsonville or Dayton, we are leaving valuable things behind,''
said Jack, whose company is developing the West Third Project in
West Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Attracting private investment to the region is tough because
``Wall Street wants a 15 to 35 percent return on investment''
within a certain amount of time, said Tom J. Anderle, of Bartlett &AMP;
Co. in Cincinnati. Entrepreneurs with little experience can not
deliver that. Investors would have to be willing to give a company
more time to succeed, Anderle said.
</P>
<P>
   In six to eight weeks, Jackson said, the coalition plans to
convene a meeting of Wall Street investors here to continue
discussing investment strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
