<HEADER>
A9790 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOUND-PLANT30-COX     09-29 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOUND-PLANT30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ceremony marks last tritium drum loading at Ohio's Mound Plant
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A fortress-like tunnel that burrows into a hill at the Mound
Plant in Ohio made a fitting backdrop for a ceremony marking the
end of the plant's work on nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Gathered at the concrete tunnel's mouth, government officials
and plant workers watched as a green forklift loaded a steel drum
into the back of a plain white truck. It was the symbolic loading
of the last drum of the Mound's radioactive tritium, a key element
in hydrogen bombs.
</P>
<P>
   When asked, Mound officials conceded the drum didn't really
contain tritium, a radioactive gas that is used to increase the
power of nuclear weapons. They said it was the closest they could
come to celebrating the real event because the details of actual
tritium shipments are secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still tritium on the site,'' said Mark Becker, a
spokesman for Babcock and Wilcox of Ohio, which operates the plant
under a Department of Energy contract.
</P>
<P>
   But sometime before Thursday, he said, Mound would load the last
drum of tritium and ship it to DOE's Savannah River plant in South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   In Mound's work with tritium, vessels containing the substance
would be removed from nuclear warheads and shipped to the site,
where technicians would remove the gas, purify it, and load it into
new vessels to be put back into the weapons. The work was done in
buried facilities surrounded by walls about 20 feet thick, hardened
against the possibility of nuclear attack.
</P>
<P>
   The work was critical to maintaining America's nuclear stockpile
because tritium has a half-life _ the time it takes for half of it
to break down _ of 12 years. Mound's work replenished the warheads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mission of great importance and it was very secret,''
said Leah Dever, DOE's Ohio Field Office manager.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody appeared to shed any tears over the end of this chapter
in Mound's history. And Miamisburg officials were all smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just think, seven years ago, we were fighting to keep this
here,'' Miamisburg Mayor Dick Church said.
</P>
<P>
   DOE decided to end Mound's weapons work in 1991 as part of a
major downsizing plan after the end of the Cold War and the
collapse of the Soviet Union. The site employed about 2,000 people
at the time, most of them scientists, engineers and highly skilled
technicians.
</P>
<P>
   Miamisburg and Ohio challenged DOE's claims that the move would
be cost-effective. Their efforts failed, but they won DOE's
cooperation in a plan to convert Mound into a high-tech business
park.
</P>
<P>
   The site now has about 860 people working for Babcock and Wilcox
or DOE. Most of their work involves decontamination and cleanup.
Michael Grauwelman, director of the Miamisburg Mound Community
Improvement Corp., said conversion efforts have created 28 private
companies employing about 270 people.
</P>
<P>
   With the last shipment, the only tritium left will be residual
material in pipes and other processing equipment, said Patrick
Burns, manager of the tritium disposal program. He said as much of
that will be recovered as possible. Once decontaminated, the
tritium facilities will be demolished or made available for
commercial use, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burns, a 22-year Mound employee, said one more ceremony is
planned to mark the secret final shipment: ``We're going to have a
pizza party after work.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-09-28-98 2024E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
