<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The man who wrote Clinton's plea for penitence
 &HT;    By Marcus Franklin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rabbi Jack Riemer understands President Clinton's public plea of
penitence.
</P>
<P>
   Riemer, formerly of Dayton, wrote the 204-word passage about
repentance and changing one's ways Clinton read Sept. 12 at a
national prayer breakfast attended by 106 clergy members.
</P>
<P>
   Riemer wrote Now Is The Time For Turning while serving as rabbi
at Beth Abraham synagogue in Dayton from 1964 to 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prayer is about how important it is for people to face up
to their mistakes and be willing to change even if it's
embarrassing and painful,'' Riemer said
</P>
<P>
   Riemer, now of Boca Raton, Fla., said he was moved and flattered
but surprised as he watched a live CNN broadcast of the president
reading the text. Hours later, the Starr report publicly detailed
Clinton's illicit relationship with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly wasn't thinking of him when I wrote it but it fits
his situation,'' Riemer said from his home Monday. ``The temptation
to cover up and deny is so great in all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   And as Jews around the world observe Yom Kippur, the holy day of
atonement, at sundown tonight, Riemer said the country is focusing
far too much on the misdeeds of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cop-out from dealing with our own sins,'' he said.
``Yom Kippur is about looking into the mirror and examining our own
lives. If we get caught up in what they're doing in Washington,
it's a projection away from our own sins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether his apology is sincere or not, that's God's
department.''
</P>
<P>
   During his delivery, Clinton honed in on the Jewish steps for
repentance; acknowledge wrongdoing, apologize to those you have
wronged and take steps to make sure you do not repeat the
transgression.
</P>
<P>
   Riemer said he wrote On Turning and other prayers because
``Judaism has to speak to the issues and the language of our
time.''
</P>
<P>
   It reads, in part, ``For leaves, birds and animals, turning
comes instinctively. But for us, turning does not come so easily..
. . It means breaking old habits. It means admitting that we have
been wrong; and this is never easy. It means losing face; it means
starting all over again; and this is always painful. It means
saying: I am sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   The prayer is contained in the Gates of Repentance, the Jewish
Reform movement's High Holy Days prayer book.
</P>
<P>
   More than 700,000 copies of Gates of Repentance are used in
about 90 percent of Reform congregations in the United States,
Reform Jewish officials estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Riemer said his prayers have also been set to music and
performed at Lincoln Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
