<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    My idea of television heaven would be....
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Have you ever wondered what channel you would
choose to watch if you were immobilized in a La-Z-Boy without a
remote control? I have. I'm always thinking of dumb stuff like
that.
</P>
<P>
   For me the decision would be easy. No sleaze talk shows, no
soaps, and definitely no home shopping. Just tune me in to the
channel that airs reruns of ``This Old House'' and other shows of
that ilk. Bob Vila, Norm and Steve, or even that husband and wife
team who are always digging footings and lifting toilets
(miraculously without argument). I love them all.
</P>
<P>
   Last night I was watching Bob Vila in Florida talking with two
guys on stilts who were installing a new ceiling in a remodel
somewhere in the old section of Miami _ probably new when I was
growing up there. These guys are really good, I'm thinking and
before I'm two potato chips into the action, one of them has marked
a piece of sheetrock, cut it, fastened it into place with a screw
gun, slathered goo on the seams and is taping them. What's really
surprising is they never screw up - as in, ``I cut it three times
and it's still too short.'' At the rate these fellows move, they
could re-hang the ceiling of the Sistine Chapel over their lunch
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Before I could see how they got down off of those stilts, Bob
had moved out into the carport (''porte-cochere'' we called it down
there and back then) with the general contractor and was discussing
what to do with a little outbuilding. They came up with the idea of
lattice work _ a very southern thing _ and turning it into an
old-style slathouse.
</P>
<P>
   Although I haven't seen one in a month of Sundays, slathouses
were a part of my growing up in south Florida. Plenty of my
friends' parents had them.
</P>
<P>
   A slathouse is less than a house and more than a shed. Its roof
and walls are just what the name implies - slats. They filter the
sun and let in rain and folks down south like to grow orchids in
them - so I'm told. All the ones I ever saw were growing junk and
broken lawnmowers.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Harris next door had one with lots of stuff in it, but never
any flowers. Mostly, it had spiders _ gigantic ones. Spiders so
big, I later imagined them picking up the breezy little building
and moving it around the yard at night.
</P>
<P>
   Slat houses were also home to scorpions _ and more, but I don't
want to talk about that.
</P>
<P>
   The months before I discovered that slat houses were inhabited
by more creepy crawlies than the Amazon rain forest, were happy
ones. Each evening after dinner, a group of neighborhood kids would
get together for a twilight game of hide 'n seek. I always won
because nobody ever came looking for me crouched in a dim corner of
Mr. Harris's slat house. I always had to give up and wander back on
my own. One night a bad-talking boy from down the street explained
why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell,'' he drawled, ``I ain't goin' in there to look for you,
not with all those rattlesnakes.'' The rest nodded in somber
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   A week or two later, after I'd gotten over the heebie jeebies
and my hair had relaxed, I rejoined the game, but never again went
near the slathouse. My hiding places became safer after that, like
the back seat of the Harris's '46 Hudson or under an overturned
wheelbarrow. Once, in a frenzy of last minute desperation, I
slipped into the Harris's bathroom and hid behind the shower
curtain. I knew nobody would ever think to look for me in there. I
was right.
</P>
<P>
   Even Mr. Harris never thought of checking to be sure there
wasn't a 12-year-old in the tub before he settled in for his
evening paper read. I got grounded for that one. My mother declared
me out of the game and on the bench for a week.
</P>
<P>
   It's all gone now _ the slathouse that withstood the onslaught
of kids, floods, and hurricanes. New owners wiped out old memories
with a swimming pool. It's called ``progress'' but I don't think
too much of it. Kids can't play hide 'n seek in a swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   But now, thanks to Bob and the boys, some new kids can play an
old game _ that is if somebody will ditch their remotes and pry
them out of their La-Z-Boys.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett is a teacher in Gibsonburg, Ohio, and writes
her column for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
