<SLUG> BC-DEADBEAT-DADS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deadbeat dad program improves child support but makes no impact
on their employment rates
 &HT;    By Wendy Hundley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting deadbeat dads to work and to support their children
requires intense effort and isn't always successful, according to a
national study to be released today.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton was one of seven cities involved in Parents' Fair Share -
the largest national demonstration program for unemployed,
noncustodial fathers of children on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   The program - involving job training, assistance in seeking
employment and peer support - boosted child support payments by 4.5
to 7.5 percent but failed to improve fathers' rates of employment
or earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were disappointed with the findings on earnings and
employment,'' said Gordon Berlin, director of the Manpower
Demonstration Research Corporation study. ``It's a tough problem to
tackle. Some men have serious barriers to employment.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, courts have two options for deadbeat parents - send
them to jail or order them to find work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to ta3: the effectiveness of a third option
that would enhance their employment prospects, increase their child
support and help them become more involved, responsible parents,''
Berlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1994 and 1997, more than 5,000 fathers in Dayton, Grand
Rapids, Mich., Jacksonville, Fla., Los Angeles, Memphis,
Springfield, Mass. and Trenton, New Jersey participated in the
program.
</P>
<P>
   The increases in child support came largely from Dayton, Grand
Rapids and Los Angeles, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton also had highest number - 81 percent - of parents who
remained employed after the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Dayton they would follow up by knocking on doors,'' said
Fred Doolittle, lead author of the study. ``We think they put
together a strong partnership of agencies and services that helped
get men into jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Randolph, assistant director of the Montgomer9 Jounty
Department of Human Services, said the Dayton program increased
child support payments because it could ``smoke out'' fathers
trying to hide their employment.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the national demonstration project ended a year ago,
``we've duplicated it at The Job Center,'' Randolph said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than just order parents into jail or hand them ``seek
work'' orders, judges now send them to the center for help in
finding employment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
