<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Sept. 29, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-EDUCATION (San Francisco) _ While classroom computers
can boost student test scores if used properly, they can also have
the opposite affect, according to a new study. The reason may be
that some computer time is devoted to goofing around. By MICHAEL
DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   MAD-COW (San Francisco) _ A test for the renegade protein
believed to cause mad cow disease and its human counterpart has
been developed at the University of California at San Francisco,
paving the way for possible large-scale screening of blood, meat
and other products. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   LAKE-MUCK (Schenectady, N.Y.) _ Union College scientists are
exploring the muck of ages beneath two unusually deep lakes that
hold a 12,000-year record of climatic changes and the effects of
civilization. Using a sonar device, a team of geologists,
biologists, chemists and civil engineers is mapping the depths
inside sediment of Collins and Ballston lakes. By BOB GARDINIER.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-MOVES (San Francisco) _ This might well qualify as the
last thing a career counselor would ever tell you, but here goes.
In an ideal world, you ought to just up and quit a job at least
once in your lifetime. But do your homework first. By DAVY MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   YIP-COLUMN (Undated) _ Few investors can find anything good to
say about the recent carnage in the stock market. But those who
have converted the traditional Individual Retirement Account to a
Roth IRA have a chance to turn the market swoon to your advantage.
By PAMELA YIP.
</P>
<P>
   BATTERY-VEHICLES (San Francisco) _ While the world's auto
companies struggle to create a viable electric vehicle, a small
swarm of electric bicycles and scooters are humming off the
assembly lines at Zap Power Systems, a company trying hard to seize
the tiny but growing U.S. market for electrified transportation. By
MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PRO-TOOLS (Albany, N.Y.) _ While professional power tools may be
considerably more expensive than nonprofessional models, the
benefits are well worth the price. That's especially true if you
are planning to complete one or more heavy-duty projects and wish
to avoid an inferior drill prone to breaking. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A reader wants to know is she can
plant roses growing in pots and transplant them into her garden. By
KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-CANCER (Albany, N.Y.) _ After Barbara Smith had her right
breast removed, she hoped the worst of her battle with cancer was
over. However, her right hand and arm later swelled to twice their
normal size. Smith was diagnosed with lymphedema, a condition
caused by damage to the lymphatic system, sometimes as a result of
breast cancer surgery, radiation, infection or trauma. By SYLVIA
WOOD
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-SPORTSCASTERS (New York) _ In their day, George Halas and
Vince Lombardi wouldn't have bought into it. Women in the National
Football League. Sportscasters, that is. These days, all four TV
networks holding NFL rights have at least one woman in a prominent
broadcast role. By PETE DOUGHERTY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ You could cruise or fly around the
world to celebrate the millennium. Or you could walk or bike.
Almost any type celebration you can imagine can be arranged _ for
the right price. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Democrat Charles Schumer is taking
on a veteran when he challenges Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y. By DAN
LYNCH.
</P>
