<SLUG> BC-KOHL-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOHL'S DEFEAT HEIGHTENS CLINTON'S INTERNATIONAL ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   A News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Helmut Kohl's ouster as German chancellor has left
Europe without a leader and, paradoxically, further strengthened
President Clinton's international role at a time when his domestic
position has been undermined by the White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Until his defeat in Sunday's German parliamentary elections,
Kohl was Europe's undisputed political powerhouse, the figure to
whom all, even the French, gave precedence. During his 16 years as
head of the Bonn government, he was widely credited with
spearheading most of the historic moves toward greater European
political and economic integration, among them the creation of the
single European currency, the euro, scheduled to be introduced next
year.
</P>
<P>
   As head of Europe's richest nation and the longest-serving
German leader this century, Kohl exercised influence well beyond
western Europe and on occasion seemed to contest the authority of
America's chief of state.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Russians, beginning with Mikhail Gorbachev and
then followed by Boris Yeltsin, often looked first to Bonn rather
Washington for major economic help and even for political support.
</P>
<P>
   More controversially, it was also Kohl who pressed the Western
Europeans in 1991 into backing the break-up of Yugoslavia into its
constituent republics, a step which the United States possessed
considerable misgivings about. It was the chancellor rather than
the Bush administration that won the argument.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's disappearance from active politics leaves a void that no
other European can fill.
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac is too politically enfeebled at
home to render effective leadership outside his own country. Until
now, Chirac had meekly followed in Kohl's wake.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's young and dynamic Prime Minister Tony Blair might have
filled the gap except for the fact that the British are not fully
committed to European integration. Domestic hostility has, for
instance, compelled Blair to promise not to adopt the euro as a
replacement for the British pound for at least another four years.
</P>
<P>
   As for Kohl's victorious but untried rival, Social Democrat
Gerhard Schroeder, it is likely to be sometime before he attempts
to pick up the banner of international leadership. He recognizes _
as Kohl apparently now does also _ that his predecessor's defeat
was largely a result of him paying too much attention to global
issues and not enough to internal troubles, such as record postwar
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder also faces another problem. Kohl was in unquestioned
control of his own party, the Christian Democratic Union. But the
new chancellor's hold over the Social Democrats is much shakier.
Its real boss is party chairman Oscar Lafontaine, a leftwinger who
shows signs of expecting to share power with Schroeder. German
analysts predict Schroeder will have to spend a lot of his time
dealing with the Lafontaine problem.
</P>
<P>
   All of this leaves Clinton, already the paramount world figure,
likely to be more dominant still with no rival worthy of the name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
