<HEADLINE>
STEPHEN KING IS BACK FROM NEAR-DEATH EXPERIENCE IN THE BOOK WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Photo available through Wieck Photo Database)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The buzzards were circling, smelling the onset of a
slow death.
</P>
<P>
   The book sales of the world's best-selling novelist had
stagnated, he had been bloodied by critics for years and his
longtime publisher was balking at his request for an $18 million
advance for his next opus. And there were whispers in publishing
that his frightmeister skills were on the wane, so maybe it was
time to cue that funeral dirge.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen King felt wounded, all right, watching the rise of
competitors Tom Clancy and John Grisham, while also growing
incensed at what he saw as lazy efforts by his publisher on his
recent books. And then there was the approach of his 50th birthday,
which he viewed with decided uneasiness because, as he saw it,
``once you turn 50, baby, you're middle-aged and you better get
used to the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   But King also had just pounded out a new book, one that had
already earned strong accolades from his novelist wife of 27 years
(Tabitha King) who is never ``fulsome'' with praise, and he himself
had few doubts about what eight months of writing had produced in a
35th book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when I was working on it that it was better in a lot of
ways than a lot of my other stuff,'' King emphasized last Friday
afternoon in Seattle. ``You just get a white buffalo every now and
then that comes along and you say to yourself, `This is really
good!'
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have anything to do with stepping to the next level
or you're a better writer than you were. You just get a really good
idea, and it's like Mark McGwire stepping into a good pitch. It was
just into my wheelhouse and, to my credit, I think that I knocked
it out of the park. And I can say that because, a lot of times, I
know when I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Scribner, his new publisher, is also convinced that King is back
from the nearly pronounced dead, with a robust 1.46 million copies
in its first printing of his new novel, ``Bag of Bones'' (Scribner,
529 pages, $28). The book is backed by a highly focused $50,000
publicity campaign with stops in just five cities (New York, Los
Angeles, Seattle, Chicago, Boston) and a few interviews of the
semi-reclusive author granted to selected media (The New Yorker,
USA Today, Newsweek).
</P>
<P>
   ``Bag of Bones'' may well repay the optimism of its author and
its publisher, who agreed to a highly unusual contract where King
received only a $2 million advance for the novel but will split the
profits 50-50.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bag of Bones'' is a Kingian tour de force, a Gothic romance
that slowly ensnares the reader in an intricately constructed web
of very human emotions (love, grief, desire, regret, frustration,
joy) amid a small-town setting.
</P>
<P>
   It tells the wrenching story of best-selling novelist Mike
Noonan, who has suffered a gut-churning case of writer's block
since the death of his wife from a brain aneurysm at age 34. Noonan
is paralyzed by his loss until he returns to their lakeside summer
home in Maine, where a chance encounter with a precocious
3-year-old and her beautiful 20-year-old mother, recently widowed
herself, ignites the first stirrings of his heart and at his
typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   But all is not well in this Maine small town, despite the
fairy-tale elements of the budding romance between the 40-year-old
popular novelist and the young Grace Kelly-look-alike in a
double-wide trailer. Mattie DeVore is fighting an evil stepfather
millionaire for the custody of her daughter, a bitter court battle
that Noonan soon helps finance. And the town's hushed-over sins of
the past have created a host of unquiet spirits, which Noonan must
also confront as ``Bag of Bones'' builds inexorably toward the sort
of bloody, violent cataclysm that King, for better or worse, cannot
resist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's where it goes _ there was never any question, I didn't
see that there was any choice,'' King said. ``I've got a real
problem with books that peter out into ambiguity; they're like
streams that turn into swamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to bring the reader along, at least do the
reader the courtesy of putting all your cards down face up on the
table at the end. If they want to laugh, or they think it's
ridiculous _ and sometimes the critics feel that way _ then let
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   This is King, as usual, unplugged. A quarter century of
phenomenal popular success at the writing trade seems to have left
him remarkably unaffected. He may have 300 million copies of his
books in print and an estimated annual salary of $40 million, but
the 51-year-old resident of Bangor, Maine, still is a blue-jeans
guy in a button-down world.
</P>
<P>
   King's opinions remain unfettered, his manner unpretentious. His
first glimpse of his huge two-bedroom suite in the Four Seasons
Olympic Hotel prompted him to stride from room-to-room with a
childlike delight reminiscent of Macaulay Culkin left ``Home
Alone'' in the Plaza Hotel. And when he ordered a room-service
lunch, which he ate at a vast table, King's main course was chicken
noodle soup.
</P>
<P>
   King can still readily recall the days when chicken noodle soup
seemed a luxury of sorts, that time when the aspiring writer had
taken a job as a high school English teacher at a salary of $6,400
that still seemed to promise much for King, his wife and their two
young children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We somehow felt we had gotten a free pass into the middle
class when I got that teaching job,'' King recalled. ``So we took
on a new car and we got a gasoline credit card and, all at once, we
found out, whoa, we overspent our means. So Tabby had to get a job
at Dunkin' Donuts, but it was still the best times for me. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem was: teaching school drains your brain. I was
having some success selling short stories, but if I hadn't and
things had gone on as they were, I think I would have given up. I
don't like to think that, but I might have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Carrie'' changed that, establishing a pattern that would soon
become familiar for King. There was the 1974 publication of his
first novel (after an advance of $2,500), and then there was the
1976 film version (a screamfest by Brian De Palma) that greatly
increased King's fame and audience.
</P>
<P>
   All the years of scaring people has brought King untold wealth,
with much of it donated in small towns around Maine to schools,
libraries, theaters, a $1 million Little League baseball stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But all this money earned from blood and guts and ghosts also
caused King some pangs of conscience. ``There's a part of me that
is attracted to violent fiction, that really likes that violent
chaotic behavior,'' he admitted. ``There is an anti-social guy
inside me, but there's also a very moral guy.''
</P>
<P>
   This back-and-forth battle for the author's soul came to a head
over a novel called ``Rage,'' finished when King was barely out of
his teens, a novel filled with the fear and loathing rampant during
those raging hormone years. The plot of ``Rage'' once seemed a
far-fetched figment of King's vivid imagination, but it went on to
become all-too-familiar in the headlines: A high school student
shoots his teacher and holds his classmates hostage.
</P>
<P>
   And, to King's real horror, some of the real students involved
in real school murders turned out to have read ``Rage,'' may even
have been inspired by the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think the book had a certain involvement in things that
happened, although it was never my intent to cause any kid to go
out and shoot anybody,'' King stressed. ``But I also think _ and
I'm real firm about this _ it did not cause anybody to do that. In
other words, I don't think there are good kids who read `Rage' and
turn into bad kids, violent, homicidal kids who want to shoot
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I do think that certain materials, books, films, can act
as accelerants, in the same way that an arsonist can use
accelerants to make a fire burn faster. And I don't want to be any
part of that. So I withdrew the book from publication. I can't
change what's already out there, but there will be no future
printings and it will disappear from the shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen King has learned that horror pays, but also extracts a
price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
