<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-REVIEWS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITH FORD IS LIKEABLE IN OK NEW SITCOM, `MAGGIE WINTERS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maggie Winters left Shelbyville, Ind., most likely to succeed
and eager to take a big bite from the Big Apple. She returns home
to Shelbyville, Ind., most likely to swallow some pride.
</P>
<P>
   Can Maggie go home again and handle the embarrassment of living
with her mother, of dealing with friends who haven't quite let go
of high school?
</P>
<P>
   Faith Ford gives it a go in a sometimes amusing, sometimes
trying comedy that nonetheless will play well with fans of the
former ``Murphy Brown'' co-star. Ford's likability carries the day
when the script falters. She finds a mother lode of help in Shirley
Knight, who plays Maggie's overbearing mom, Estelle, but only
spotty support from a cast of several friends who aren't entirely
convincing.
</P>
<P>
   Maggie's return is prompted by her sudden divorce from a
philandering husband. Jobless and hapless, she arrives in
Shelbyville just in time for her 15th high school reunion _ and a
reintroduction to her old flame, Bobby Campanella (Vincent
Ventresca).
</P>
<P>
   Clea Lewis (``Ellen'') provides the most amusing moments as
Rachel Tomlinson, an insecure woman who blames Maggie for all her
own high school failures, and who now might become Maggie's new
boss. She also has eyes for Bobby.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking the crisp writing and smooth ensemble work of better
comedies, ``Maggie Winters'' faces an uphill climb. It may
ultimately work better with less clutter.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ``The Secret Lives of Men'' would work better
if maybe the cast members joined a large support group.
</P>
<P>
   While there may be a big audience for a show about three
divorced _ or soon-to-be-divorced _ guys complaining about how
their wives got the houses, the kids and the big alimony checks,
any show in which the laugh track stands out more prominently than
the jokes definitely needs help.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Gallagher, Brad Whitford and Mitch Rouse play Michael,
Phil and Andy _ three thirtysomething men who spend an awful lot of
time together, usually golfing or eating.
</P>
<P>
   They are best friends, which is amazing, because they're quite
annoying. Well, Michael (Gallagher) isn't so bad. He's the
sensitive one, perhaps a little too sensitive because of his
family's alleged ties to the mob. Phil is a Type A whiner whose
motor never stops. Andy is a macho guy with a phobia about germs.
</P>
<P>
   To know more means you'll have to watch more. But why bother?
``NewsRadio'' is on at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   In a word, ``To Have and To Hold'' is cute. Moira Kelly and
Jason Beghe make a cute couple. Their families are cute and quirky,
their house is cute and cozy, their dialogue is cute and cuddly.
</P>
<P>
   But mind candy can be dangerous. A cute case of sweetness, while
not always fatal, can cause severe decay. Adding fluoride to your
TV is advised.
</P>
<P>
   The series is one of several this season focusing on Irish
Americans, and it doesn't avoid the clich &UR; gfacute &LR; es. Beghe plays
Sean McGrail, a Boston police detective with three brothers, two of
them cops, one a fireman. The love of his life is public defender
Annie Cornell (Kelly), who rarely agrees with him on matters of
law, but who loves both his passion and his compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Interspersed among the arguing and the making up are words of
wisdom from Sean's parents, played by Fionnula Flanagan and John
Cullum, and Annie's mother (Mariette Hartley). After a while, the
blarney starts piling up.
</P>
<P>
   With a bit more edge and a lot less smarm, ``To Have and To
Hold'' might be the sort of lighthearted romantic drama that
captures the hearts of millions. Right now though, it's easy to let
go.
</P>
<P>
   _ Maggie Winters. Half-hour comedy about a woman who returns to
her small-town roots after her dreams go awry. Starring Faith Ford,
Shirley Knight, Jenny Robertson, Alex Kapp Horner, Brian Haley and
Clea Lewis. Premieres Wednesday, CBS. Check local listings.
Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _ The Secret Lives of Men. Half-hour comedy about three
divorced/separated men coping with their new singlehood. Starring
Peter Gallagher, Brad Whitford, Mitch Rouse and Christine Dunford.
Premieres Wednesday, ABC. Check local listings. Parental guideline
rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _ To Have and To Hold. Hourlong drama about a couple _ he a cop,
she a public defender _ who often end up on opposite sides of a
case. Starring Moira Kelly, Jason Beghe, Jason Wiles, Stephen Lee,
Stephen Largay and Fionnula Flanagan. Premieres Wednesday, CBS.
Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   To reach John Levesque, call 206-448-8330, or send e-mail to:
tvguy(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
