<HEADER>
A9977 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-KOHL-BOS &LR;      09-29 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-KOHL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNASSUMING ROLE BELIED KOHL'S STAYING POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Otto von Bismarck, the 19th-century chancellor who is
the only other German to serve as long as Helmut Kohl, once
observed there are two things people should not see being made:
sausage and legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has never been one for pithy quotes. As for sausages, he is
more likely to eat them than to use them as props for profound
statements. Though, truth be told, his real weakness is for pig's
stomach, his favorite dish.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Kohl's appetite for power that made him arguably the
greatest European leader of this century. He pursued power
relentlessly, and he surprised many not only by attaining
leadership of Europe's most populous and most economically
important country, but by holding onto it for 16 years before his
defeat Sunday. At 68, he was not only Europe's longest-serving
leader, but its oldest.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl is the antithesis of the modern political leader. Weighing
well over 300 pounds _ his aides brush off requests for an exact
figure _ he is overweight, if not obese. He is a dreadful public
speaker. And no one has ever accused him of being a big-picture
thinker.
</P>
<P>
   But it is precisely because he is so disarmingly unimpressive in
the areas that have come to be yardsticks for the modern politician
that so many people underestimated him. Kohl, who stammers and
whose girth makes it look as if he is always about to pop a button
on his jacket, seemed more like Sergeant Schultz, the bumbling
prison guard on Hogan's Heroes, than the most enduring democratic
leader in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Appearances aside, Kohl's impact on Germany, Europe, and the
world has been extraordinary because, unlike previous German
leaders who will be remembered for starting wars and the Holocaust,
Kohl put Europe's interests ahead of Germany's. He, more than any
other leader, brought about closer European integration and the
reunification of Germany. While history will remember him most for
presiding over reunification, it is that legacy which, combined
with his age, probably cost him his job.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl pumped more than $700 billion into the former East Germany,
but it pleased no one. West Germans think reunification has cost
them too much in taxes. East Germans complain it has cost them
jobs, housing and the security they had under a communist regime.
They also complain that the government has imposed its will on them
in a triumphalist way and allowed western speculators to buy up
property and price easterners out of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Under Kohl, unemployment has doubled. Reunification and the free
market that came with it has driven unemployment to a record 11
percent, nearly 20 percent in the former East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he will probably be judged well by history. He forced
Germans to confront the ugliness of the Holocaust, and he staked
his political career on trying to unify his country.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's philosophy was shaped by his experiences during World War
II, which ended when he was 15. His older brother was killed
fighting for Germany. During the war, despite his membership in
Hitler Youth, Kohl attended seminars in his native Ludwigshafen,
where a priest taught him about democracy even as the Nazis were
making a mockery of it. Kohl emerged from these years convinced
that only a united Europe could avoid the cyclical nature of war.
He became the most dedicated and arguably the most successful
European integrationist.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a tax collector and a housewife, Kohl never forgot
where he came from. When he became leader of the Christian
Democrats in 1976, opponents derided him as a provincial hick. Kohl
endured the putdowns and quietly consolidated power. He also took
note of his enemies and dealt with them later. He knew that, unlike
his beloved pig's stomach, revenge was best served cold.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary Germans, meanwhile, saw many of the attacks on Kohl as
attacks on them. He, after all, was the only prominent politician
who talked like them. Kohl was more likely to take advice from
ordinary people in the Rhineland where he always lived than the
smooth-talking, smart set he met in the Bundestag, Germany's
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   With Kohl, what you saw was what you got. Although calculating
and far from guileless, he was without airs. While many provincial
politicians cultivated accents they considered more appropriate for
the rarified air of the Bundestag, Kohl flouted his thick,
working-class Palatinate accent. While wealthy enough to go
anywhere in the world, Kohl takes his summer vacation every year at
the same modest Austrian resort.
</P>
<P>
   Many world leaders, including Ronald Reagan, George Bush, and
Bill Clinton, were won over by Kohl's earthy charm. Others,
including Margaret Thatcher, never warmed to it.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush appreciated Kohl's straightforwardness, and saw in
Kohl's old-fashioned, stay-at-home wife Hannelore something of a
mirror image of his own. While many cynics here snickered at the
Father Knows Best lifestyles of the Kohls and the Bushes, those
connections paid off. Bush helped Kohl pull off reunification,
trusting that a united Germany under a committed integrationist
like Kohl would never go the way of megalomaniacs like Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet leader, Mikhail Gorbachev, trusted Kohl enough to
pull Russian troops from East Germany, paving the way for a
bloodless end to the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl was uncharacteristically emotional when the Berlin Wall
came down in 1989. He promised East Germans the bounty of the West,
and was moved when they cheered him unreservedly. But on Sunday,
eastern voters deserted him in droves. Even more humiliating for
Kohl was losing his home district in Ludwigshafen.
</P>
<P>
   Like an aging gunfighter or an over-the-hill athlete, it may be
that Kohl simply hung on too long. Even party loyalists privately
complain that his determintaion to run for an unprecedented fifth
four-year term was an egotistical exercise that was neither in the
best interest of the country or his party.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that most Germans would prefer that Kohl's deputy,
Wolfgang Schaeuble, ran for chancellor. Kohl calls Schaeuble his
crown prince, but he also made it abundantly clear that he, the
king, and no one else, would decide when it was time to step down.
</P>
<P>
   Like his heroes, Winston Churchill and Charles de Gaulle, Kohl
stayed too long and had to be pushed. But, like them, his place in
the history books is assured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
