<HEADER>
A9979 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-CURFEW-BOS &LR;      09-29 1358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-CURFEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMBUS TRIES A TEEN CURFEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Two hours into the school day, Chad was bored.
A fidgety, affable 13-year-old with a soft face and an attention
disorder, Chad decided to get some pizza or ``just walk around, for
the joy of it.''
</P>
<P>
   So off he went, slipping easily away from his seventh-grade math
class _ and right into the path of a police cruiser. ``If I ran, I
would've gotten away,'' Chad said sadly, his remorse reserved
solely for having been caught.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of pizza, Chad got a ride to the Franklin County
Truancy/Curfew Intervention Center. First he was frisked. Then he
was screened for weapons by a metal detector. Then all his
possessions were taken from him. Then his record was checked for
outstanding warrants.
</P>
<P>
   And then, maybe worst of all, he had to endure the grim wait for
the spanking he suspected would arrive with his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Chad violated this city's daytime curfew, an updated version of
the old truancy law, but with a lot more muscle. Anyone between the
ages of 6 and 18 who is found in a public place between 9 a.m. and
3:30 p.m. on a school day can be detained by police, then taken to
the curfew center. Exceptions are made for students with their
parents or guardians, and those with written permission from school
authorities. Repeat offenders and their parents can face charges of
delinquency or contributing to the delinquency of a minor.
</P>
<P>
   As schools across the country battle persistent truancy
problems, daytime curfews are growing in popularity. Already more
than 70 cities have adopted them in various forms, and each month
more are being proposed, according to the United States Conference
of Mayors.
</P>
<P>
   Boston has yet to consider such a step, but it is hardly immune
to the pressures that have pushed other cities to do so. This
month, Boston officials launched a sweeping program to battle one
the nation's worst truancy problems: almost 30 percent of the
city's elementary students, and 45 percent of teenagers, missed
more than three weeks of the 1996-97 school year.
</P>
<P>
   One difference is that, while Boston has 12 truancy officers,
Columbus, in effect, has more than 1,500 _ every member of its
police force.
</P>
<P>
   But as more and more cities turn to daytime curfews, the
controversy over them grows as well. Civil libertarians say such
rules violate the rights of children and intrude on the freedoms of
young-looking adults who are subjected to unwarranted stops by
police. Some social scientists doubt the curfews can thwart truancy
or crime.
</P>
<P>
   Yet supporters of daytime curfews say the measures keep children
in school and out of trouble, and that far outweighs any potential
harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a solution by itself, but it's part of it,'' said
Columbus City Council member Les Wright, who in 1994 began the
process that led to the law's enactment a year later. ``We're
trying to catch problems early on, before behaviors get entrenched
and kids get lost. If children are not in school, that's where
problems start.''
</P>
<P>
   Faith Rice, the curfew center coordinator, said statistics
demonstrate its effectiveness. Last year, police brought 633
daytime curfew violators to the center, but fewer than 1 in 6 had a
second offense, and there were fewer than 40 instances of students
violating the curfew three or more times. There are 65,000 students
in the city's schools.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers do not, however, reflect the fact that many
students get a break from police. Earlier in the day, for instance,
Officer Don Hoar stopped two 16-year-old West High School students
en route to an unapproved lunch outing. ``You're juniors. You know
you need a pass, right?'' Hoar asked sternly. The teens nodded and
looked chastened, and Hoar sent them back to school.
</P>
<P>
   Still, supporters say the curfew teaches responsibility. ``Every
kid knows what's expected of them. They might tell you they don't
know the rules, but they know,'' said police Officer Terri Long, a
full-time presence at West High School. Long is known among fellow
officers for organizing what she calls ``Friday rodeos'' _ roundups
of truant teens with a police wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Angered by such tactics and skeptical of claimed benefits, civil
libertarians and children's rights specialists say daytime curfews
rob juveniles of their constitutional freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stalin couldn't have thought of a better law,'' said Martin
Guggenheim, a law professor at New York University who has written
extensively on the rights of children. ``This is offensive to the
deepest values of American freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Guggenheim said the idea fails both in reducing truancy and
preventing crime. ``Adults should figure out how to make school an
inviting place that students want to be in, not a place they are
forced to be in at the risk of being arrested,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has never heard a juvenile curfew case,
Guggenheim said, having refused to hear the one challenge brought
to such rules. Lower court decisions have been mixed on similar
cases, most of them involving nighttime curfews.
</P>
<P>
   But a new challenge to daytime curfews might be brewing in Ohio.
The board that oversees the state office of the American Civil
Liberties Union has given staff lawyers a green light to seek a
curfew test case, said Christine Link, ACLU Ohio executive
director. Link has firsthand knowledge of the issue: Three years
ago, her then-12-year-old daughter was briefly detained by
Cleveland police while walking to synagogue on a Jewish holiday,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond constitutional issues is the question of whether the
curfews work.
</P>
<P>
   In Columbus, three years after the daytime curfew took effect,
overall attendance has changed little. Maurice Blake, director of
pupil services at the Columbus School Department, said attendance
was just under 87 percent last school year, a figure virtually
unchanged in the 1990s. Ohio intends to require 93 percent
attendance rates in all school districts by 2000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   No studies have proven the crime-prevention value of daytime
curfews, but they seem to make more sense than nighttime curfews,
said Jack Levin, professor of sociology and criminology at
Northeastern University. Nighttime curfews are ineffective because
most crimes committed by teenagers occur in the afternoon, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any policy that strengthens the school bond for marginalized
and alienated youngers is a remarkably effective program,'' Levin
said. ``That includes any effort to keep youngsters from walking
the streets unsupervised when their peers are hard at work.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the idea behind Columbus's truancy-curfew center, a room
the size of a school cafeteria, with high ceilings and mauve walls,
located in the basement of a maximum-security juvenile detention
facility. With four full-time staff members, the center has a
$540,000 yearly budget and an admittedly difficult task.
</P>
<P>
   Once curfew violators are frisked and processed, they might get
a good talking-to from security specialist Alvin Hall, then a
meeting with social worker Lolita Love before their parents are
called to get them.
</P>
<P>
   Chad is a second-time violator, so his family will also be
scheduled for a mandatory counseling session. A third offense opens
the possibility of delinquency charges, but Chad is undeterred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally I never get caught. I must be losing my touch,'' he
said, looking sideways at a visitor. He said he is proud that he
doesn't smoke or commit crimes. ``I just skip school,'' he said. To
keep him in school, Chad added, ``they'd have to pay me every hour
I'm there.''
</P>
<P>
   While Chad talked, a shirtless, tough-looking 17-year-old was
brought in. He is a study in angry nonchalance. Chad gave him
plenty of room.
</P>
<P>
   Love, the social worker, says her goal with Chad is to persuade
his mother to make sure he takes the medicine that helps to
diminish his attention disorder. But Chad makes no promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be in school tomorrow, and the next day, and the next
day, probably, but Friday is risky,'' he said. ``Friday is the best
day to skip.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
