<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9983 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-HEALTH-COVERAGE-BO     09-29 1593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HEALTH-COVERAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR CANDIDATES TAKE DISTINCT PATHS ON HEALTH CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GEETA ANAND  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Health care reform, valiantly pushed locally and
nationwide by the likes of Michael Dukakis and Hillary Rodham
Clinton, used to be an issue for liberal Democrats whose proposals
died in the hands of Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   But not so this year, particularly in the governor's race in
Massachusetts, where Republican Acting Governor Paul Cellucci and
his Democratic rival, Attorney General Scott Harshbarger, are in a
tug-of-war over the mantle of health care candidate. With 755,000
of the state's residents, or 12.6 percent, without health insurance
at last count, the public, in interviews and in polls, says
government ought to find a way to make health insurance affordable
to all.
</P>
<P>
   And the candidates are listening.
</P>
<P>
   Staking his claim on the issue, Cellucci has endorsed big
expansions in government insurance and proposed subsidies to
encourage small businesses to offer benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger, fighting for the middle ground, is pushing for even
larger expansions in government aid but steering clear of the
losing Democratic solutions of the past, such as mandates that
businesses offer insurance to all.
</P>
<P>
   Significant differences exist between the candidates' plans and
records. Some experts prefer Harshbarger's plan, but they and
others worry few people aside from policy wonks will be able to
distinguish between the candidates on this topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a risk to Democrats that (Cellucci's) stolen their
issue,'' said Catherine M. Dunham, director of The Access Project,
a nonprofit group that promotes health insurance access. ``It's
like Clinton stealing welfare reform from the Republicans. ...
(Cellucci's) been very progressive on health care, and he's got the
good political sense to take credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his predecessor, Governor William F. Weld, who vetoed the
Legislature's plan to use a cigarette tax to fund health insurance
for poor children, Cellucci has gone along with legislative
initiatives to expand coverage over the past year. He has supported
the Legislature in expanding the state's health care program,
called MassHealth, to serve another 150,000 people last year and
tens of thousands of children this year. The program is funded with
$336 million in federal Medicaid money, cigarette tax revenue, and
from the free-care pool that covers hospital care for the
uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   Further, using the traditional Republican strategy of offering
incentives, Cellucci got the Legislature last year to endorse
subsidies of up to $1,000 for small businesses that pay 50 percent
of the insurance premiums for lower-income employees. The law also
offers these employees help paying their share. The plan uses $41
million from the same sources of federal and state money to pay the
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   With an eye toward public concern about health maintenance
organizations denying needed medical care, Cellucci appointed an
ombudsman this year to help patients fight for their rights.
</P>
<P>
   Where Cellucci counts on his incentive plan for business to
widen the pool of people who have health insurance, Harshbarger
takes a more direct approach. He proposes to immediately cover
another 100,000 lower-income people who don't have insurance by
raising the income guidelines to qualify for government help. Where
adults can qualify for the insurance coverage only if their family
incomes fall within 133 percent of the federal poverty level,
Harshbarger would allow people to use the program if their annual
family incomes fall within 200 percent of the federal poverty
level, or $32,100 for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   Stressing that he would not raise taxes to achieve his goal,
Harshbarger would pay for the program using $220 million from the
free-care pool, new Medicaid money, and small patient
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating that the state's lawsuit against tobacco companies
will be resolved soon, Harshbarger also calls for spending between
$150 million and $200 million of any future settlement to offer
state health insurance to another 100,000 people. If the money
becomes available, he said, he would raise the MassHealth income
guidelines still further to 300 percent of the federal poverty
level, or $48,000 for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   Like Cellucci, Harshbarger has a plan to regulate HMOs. He
proposes a so-called patient bill of rights that says HMOs can't
deny reasonable emergency care and makes doctors disclose to
patients all treatment options and financial arrangements they have
with HMOs. He would also appoint a board of specialists to oversee
health care decisions and a state office to make sure the HMOs
abide by the bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   Several health care policy specialists interviewed say that both
candidates' plans fall short of offering long-term solutions to the
crux of the problem: the exorbitant cost of health insurance. Only
some form of universal coverage will contain costs, these
specialists believe.
</P>
<P>
   But given the political realities, specifically the defeat of
the Clintons' plan four years ago, most of these specialists
praised the gubernatorial candidates, Harshbarger more so than
Cellucci, for trying to help people in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci won kudos for supporting the Legislature's expansion of
MassHealth but criticism for his business incentive plan.
</P>
<P>
   Because the cost of insurance is so high, businesses in other
states that have tried similar plans have not taken advantage of
subsidies in any big way, said Dunham of The Access Project. The
state plans to offer small companies subsidies of between $400 and
$1,000; family insurance coverage costs between $6,000 and $10,00 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other situations, it's not proven to be a powerful enough
incentive to get nervous business people to embrace an expensive
new benefit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The other problem, the specialists say, is that the subsidy plan
will be available to all small businesses that pay 50 percent of
the premiums for low-income employees. Since many of these
companies already provide insurance, they say, the state will be
wasting valuable resources on people already covered.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger faces some criticism that his plan could lead
lower-income people who already have private health insurance to
leave it and use the state's cheaper plan. He said he will counter
this so-called ``crowding'' effect by allowing only people who
haven't been insured for four months to sign on to his plan.
</P>
<P>
   If the goal is to insure the most people, Dunham and Robert
Restuccia, executive director of the advocacy group Health Care for
All, say they prefer Harshbarger's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's direct money, it's live money, it's not an indirect
subsidy like a tax credit,'' Restuccia said. ``A targeted,
incremental expansion strategy, which Harshbarger proposes, is the
best you can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, neither plan addresses the high cost of health care,
said Alan Sager, a professor at the Boston University School of
Public Health. The cost in Massachusetts is expected this year to
reach $35 billion, 30 percent more than the national average. And
the United States already spends more than double any other
industrialized country on health care, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems clear that we are already spending enough,'' Sager
said. ``We in Massachusetts could cover everyone by using existing
spending without using new taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   If he were governor, Sager said, he would put all federal,
state, business, and employee contributions into one big trust
fund, print insurance cards for everyone in the state, and then let
them choose their own providers. Since all doctors would cost the
same, Sager said, patients could make their selections based upon
the best service, creating competition among providers to offer
better medical care in place of the financial incentives to offer
less.
</P>
<P>
   But even if spending more money made sense, Sager said, the
candidates' use of federal funds and cigarette tax revenues to
expand services are very short-term solutions. When the next
recession hits, Sager predicts, the federal government will reduce
its Medicaid funding and the state won't be able to continue its
program. And if cigarette taxes serve as disincentives to smokers,
this revenue can be expected to decrease in the face of soaring
health care costs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He reserved his most stinging criticism for both candidates'
schemes to fund part of their health insurance expansions by
dipping into the state's free-care pool. The resources in the pool,
about $315 million a year, are already inadequate, in his view.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's stealing from the poor to give to the poor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Restuccia, of Health Care for All, said the candidates are
only trying to deal with political realities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sager is right, but that level of change will take a while,''
Restuccia said. ``Consumers who don't have insurance and their wife
and children are sick say, `Come on, get on with it. If you can
help me now, help me. If it's not making the problem worse, help me
faster.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although Dunham, of The Access Project, prefers Harshbarger's
plan because it would cover more people than Cellucci's, she said a
Republican may have a better chance of making the kind of sweeping
changes in the system in the long run that neither is proposing
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Nixon going to China,'' she said. In this case, ``it
has to be someone the public trusts not to blow the bank.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 1316EDT &QL; 
