<SLUG> BC-NINETIES-HIPHOP-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIP-HOP WITH A '90S SPIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (l and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Strobe lights shatter the darkness as DJ Bruno takes
the crowd at the Lansdowne Street Playhouse back in time. From the
stage, where he hovers over two turntables and a mixer, he spins
``Din Da Da,'' a hip-hop hit from 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd slowly ripples to the side, forming a circle. George
Lumpkins, 31, doesn't hesitate. He dives onto the wood floor and
spins like a windmill, the stripes on his Adidas pants a blazing
blur.
</P>
<P>
   In a gangsta rap world, Lumpkins is a throwback to the old days
when MCs rapped about partying and street kids took their anger out
on the dance floor. Now, in the dance caverns of Lansdowne Street,
a new generation is reclaiming early '80s rap and break dancing,
what they call ``old-school'' hip-hop. They reject gangsta rap, the
virulent strain of hip-hop that glorifies violence and misogyny.
They say they are sick of lyrics that talk of pulling out guns and
slapping women.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're talking about gang-banging, shooting people. We don't
want to hear that,'' said Paul ``Lefty Left'' Rosado, 29. ``That's
why I'm into old-school. The way we deal with our emotions is
hitting the floor or grabbing a mike.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just Boston kids who are turning to break dancing for
its cool mood as much as its cool moves. Break dancing ``reunions''
have been held in New York, Chicago, and Los Angeles. And break
dancing suddenly is visible everywhere from Coke commercials to new
music videos by Janet Jackson, Wyclef Jean, Madonna, Jay Z, Sonic
Empire, and The Propellerheads.
</P>
<P>
   But in Boston, where gangsta rap still commands wide attention
on the radio, hundreds of youths are voting with their feet for a
mellower hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night (Sept. 29), two local entrepreneurs _ Russell
Jackson, 28, who immigrated from England, and Chris Johnston, 33,
who immigrated from Belfast _ sponsored a break-dancing competition
at the Avalon. They expected 1,500 people to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Two big-name DJs, Cash Money from Philadelphia and Bad Boy Bill
from Chicago, spun records. The event, ``Unity and Respect, Part
2,'' is a sequel to their first competition, held in June.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, a slim man with a shag of blond hair, said he and
Johnston had trouble persuading clubs to allow them to hold a
break-dancing competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is very anti-hip-hop because of its association with
gangsta rap,'' Jackson said. ``People don't understand old-school.
They just see MTV and think that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a majority of those buying gangsta rap music are white
suburban teens, not inner-city blacks and Latinos. But the racial
polarization presented in gangsta rap _ which draws on racial anger
for attitude _ isn't there in old-school hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't realize that hip-hop and gangsta rap are
two different things,'' said David Shallow, 30, a break dancer from
Everett. ``Hip-hop is about having fun. Nobody wants to hear about
how much money you have, how many guns you have, and how many
people you can kill.''
</P>
<P>
   Hip-hop is the umbrella term for a style of music, fashion,
dance, and attitude born in the streets of the South Bronx and
South Central Los Angeles. It began in the early '70s when young
disc jockeys began experimenting with records played simultaneously
on two turntables. They would repeat beats and phrases several
times (``break beats''), and those dancing at parties invented new
dances to go with it.
</P>
<P>
   Locking, which makes dancers look like robots, and its more
fluid form of dancing, known as popping, grew out of southern
California. In the South Bronx and Harlem, young men began
``rocking'' or ``breaking'' _ spinning and contorting their bodies
on pieces of cardboard laid out on sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, DJs started buying microphones and handing
them to friends at parties, so they could rhyme over the break
beats. Such ``MCing'' and breaking spread through ghettos across
the country _ from Kalamazoo, Mich., to Bayamon, Puerto Rico. Then
Madison Avenue discovered it, gave it a new name _ break dancing _
and used it to sell everything from sneakers to soda pop.
</P>
<P>
   ``People got tired of it,'' said DJ Bruno. ``The media murdered
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Though breaking died, rapping didn't. It could be mass-produced
and sold, unlike dancing.
</P>
<P>
   The late '80s saw rising poverty rates; alarming drop-out rates,
especially among Latino youth; and the drug trade swallowing
younger teens. When crack cocaine, a cheap and highly addictive
drug, exploded on the scene, even more young people got caught up
in the game. And with easier access to guns, city youths started
packing them for protection.
</P>
<P>
   MCs, who had begun rapping about ghetto strife, found they could
sell more records if they rapped about the gangster lifestyle,
glorifying it like ``The Godfather.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, some veteran rappers are going back to old-school. Keith
Murray, Redman, and Eric Sermon recently got together to put out an
album heavy with old-school flavor, including a remake of the
Sugarhill Gang's 1980 hit ``Rapper's Delite.'' Rappers who hadn't
been heard of in years are starting to make a comeback, too, like
Biz Markie, Slick Rick and Run-DMC.
</P>
<P>
   Several clubs here offer break-dancing nights, including the
Lansdowne Street Playhouse, which offers Electric Bugaloo night
every Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   At the Playhouse on a recent Sunday, Kenny Chung, 19, stepped
out into the circle for the first time. He showed off a ``popping''
routine: He snapped each joint of his arm, jerking his head as if a
surge of power ripped through his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way to release my negative energy,'' said Chung.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing younger people like Chung get into the old-school
lifestyle makes veteran breaker Alfredo ``Crazy Fred'' Rivera feel
like there's hope for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera, 26, spends two afternoons each week teaching teenagers
how to break dance at the YMCA in Lynn, a nearby city. He said kids
are substituting dance ``battles'' for fistfights.
</P>
<P>
   To keep himself fluid, Rivera practices with The Floor Lords, a
nationally known group that has been featured in The Source, a
hip-hop magazine. Founded 18 years ago but disbanded in the late
1980s, The Floor Lords regrouped about two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent practice, a large boom box blasted music from
the stage, while Lino ``Lean Ski'' Delgado, 31, the group's
president, took the troupe through the paces.
</P>
<P>
   They restarted the group mostly for fun, explained Delgado, but
with more and more Bostonians seeking the same kind of fun, The
Floor Lords suddenly are in great demand.
</P>
<P>
   A diverse team of mostly Latinos, several African-Americans, and
a few whites and Asians, they perform two or three gigs a week at
clubs, competitions, and fund-raisers, drawing fans with their
innocent exuberance and inclusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Crowed Delgado, ``We even did a bar mitzvah.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
