<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FINE DISTINCTION CAN GO TOO FAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joanne Fray, who clearly knows her Strunk and White, e-mailed a
question about my choice of words in a recent column about S&AMP;W's
classic handbook, ``The Elements of Style.''
</P>
<P>
   The book's roots, I had written, ``go much further back than the
'70s,'' and Fray wondered why I used further instead of farther.
She cited the entry from S&AMP;W: ``The two words are commonly
interchanged, but there is a distinction worth observing: farther
serves best as a distance word, further as a time or quantity word.
You chase a ball farther than the other fellow; you pursue a
subject further.'' Fray, apparently reading those decades as
distance, believes farther would have been the ``Strunk-and-Whitian
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't reviewed S&AMP;W's advice on the matter, but in fact I had
originally written farther; it was my editor who suggested further
was better, since we weren't measuring literal distance. I
countered that time was, after all, just another dimension, but I
was at a disadvantage _ that is, at a pay phone outside a Burger
King along the interstate near Erie, Pa. _ and it didn't seem worth
a debate. And though my ear wants to side with Fray, Strunk and
White seem to support my editor: Isn't further back than the '70s a
measure of time?
</P>
<P>
   In truth, though, this is a case where it's hard to be
absolutely wrong. Farther and further have been interchangeable in
many contexts for a long, long time, and there's never been any
solid etymological foundation for fine-tuning the usage. H.W.
Fowler, though he loved to split such hairs, did not even urge
preserving this distinction: He predicted in 1926 that further
would eventually crowd out farther.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Bernstein, in 1965, noted a ``general preference'' for
using ``farther for physical distance, further for everything
else.'' But he saw the same future as Fowler: ``Fifty years hence
writers probably will not have to worry about this distinction,
because it looks as if farther is going to be mowed down by Old
Further Time.'' Well, 33 years have passed since that guess, and
farther is still hanging on; perhaps because we have a far but no
fur in the lexicon, we aren't ready to abandon farther entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Most people tend to choose further when there's no question of
distance _ ``we need no further proof'' _ and few would try to say
farthermore. But in most cases between those extremes, the choice
is yours (and your editor's) to make; we've gone about as fur as we
can go.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Leaps and boundaries
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many citizens say they're overdosing on coverage of the White
House mess, but a Los Angeles Times reader has a more specific
gripe. ``Until (special prosecutor Kenneth) Starr submitted his
findings to the Judiciary Committee, I don't believe I'd ever heard
anyone actually use the word salacious,'' he wrote to the newspaper
last week. ``Now it seems the story can't be covered without the
word.'' Salacious, it's true, seems to have taken hold as the term
of choice for the sexual revelations in the Starr report; a
Lexis/Nexis search, admittedly not subtly calibrated, found it
running far ahead of prurient, the closest synonym in play.
</P>
<P>
   Salacious is derived from the Latin salax _ ``lecherous'' _
which is the root of salire, ``to leap.'' Saltimbocca, the Italian
dish that ``jumps in the mouth,'' is related, as is somersault. But
salire also had a sexual sense _ the Roman equivalent, more or
less, of today's ``I wanna jump your bones.''
</P>
<P>
   Prurient, from the word for ``itch,'' has essentially the same
range of meaning: Like salacious, it can describe people, behavior,
or depictions of people's behavior _ the prurient matter and
salacious details that account for most uses of the words.
</P>
<P>
   So why, with two equally good words to use, have we gravitated
toward salacious to characterize the Clinton-Lewinsky story?
</P>
<P>
   Could be that it's just a sexier-sounding word: It rolls off the
tongue with lip-smacking relish, its echo of delicious suggesting
the pleasure, guilty or otherwise, that the ``salacious material''
both exposes and inspires. Prurient, with its prim little pursing
of the lips, suggests something grimier _ guys in raincoats in
seedy theaters, say _ and less entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Salacious, which both concedes the audience's interest and
deplores the information, probably best sums up the attitude of
most people to the feast of unwelcome yet irresistible revelations
being served up to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
