<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPIES-RADIO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIES HANG OUT ON BOTTOM OF THE DIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAC DANIEL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the items confiscated during the FBI's recent
investigation of a major Cuba-sponsored spy ring, some of the most
effective and dangerous may have been a few simple shortwave
radios.
</P>
<P>
   Clandestine shortwave broadcasts _ also known as ``spy
stations'' or ``numbers stations'' _ have been hitting the airwaves
for years. Anyone with a shortwave radio can tune them in, but just
a few know what they're saying.
</P>
<P>
   They are faint broadcasts that use strange frequencies, with no
known schedule. During a broadcast, a listener is likely to hear
someone reading a series of numbers, along with anything from
yodeling or a repeated flute melody to electronic tones or sudden
bursts of information-filled noise.
</P>
<P>
   Those who monitor such broadcasts say they believe the
information transmitted could be a rendezvous point, a telephone
number, or any other instruction for spies &UR;  &LR; in the field.
</P>
<P>
   There are hundreds of such numbers stations out there. Monitors
say this open, yet secret, method of communication is a virtually
foolproof means of sending messages or commands to operatives in
the field. Its beauty lies in its simplicity, combining a basic
form of impossible-to-break cryptography with the worldwide,
inconspicuous reach of the shortwave radio.
</P>
<P>
   Those who regularly follow these obscure broadcasts say the CIA,
Israel's Mossad, and British intelligence operate numbers stations,
though none of these organizations, nor America's National Security
Agency, has ever acknowledged their use. In the case of the Cuban
espionage suspects, Justice Department officials in Miami are
unwilling to say what the shortwaves were used for, or why they
were confiscated.
</P>
<P>
   Because no one has ever confirmed that such stations even exist,
most of the information about them comes from shortwave hobbyists
known as ``numbers geeks'' or ``spooks'' who share their logs on
the Internet, speculate about a station's origin, and listen for
hours to something that makes absolutely no sense on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in brief form, is how these numbers stations
work, &UR;  &LR; according to monitors and histories of the broadcasts in
books and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers or letters read over the air are believed to be
code. Once received, they are decoded using a ``one-time pad,'' a
set of numbers or letters that is good only for that single
broadcast. If letters are used, experts say those letters usually
correspond with numbers or other letters.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes if numbers are used, the listener writes down the
numbers from the broadcast and subtracts those numbers from those
on the one-time pad. The results are usually numbers between 1 and
26 _ the number of letters in the alphabet, with 1 representing A,
2 representing B, and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   The system is said to be absolutely unbreakable, with every
message decipherable only by the pad of the agent. After the code
is received, the one-time pad is destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   How does a spy know which frequency to listen to? This, monitors
say, remains a mystery. The next broadcast time and frequencies may
be part of a message. But until someone speaks publicly on these
broadcasts, no one knows.
</P>
<P>
   The history of numbers stations can be traced back more than 30
years. Interest in this phenomenon is lean but rising after the
recent release of a four-CD set called The Conet Project, the first
comprehensive collection of shortwave numbers stations recordings.
</P>
<P>
   It is the pet project of Akin Fernandez, a London-based owner of
the small record label Irdial Discs. He got interested in the weird
topic while pursuing another _ pulling coded weather satellite
information out of the air with his shortwave.
</P>
<P>
   ``And as I kept looking for these weather stations, I kept
coming across these stations of mostly women reading off sets of
numbers or sets of letters,'' said Fernandez. ``And normally a
radio station that's on shortwave announces what the schedule is,
and when it will be back on. These number stations, they never gave
any information about that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   After searching the world for people who record such stations, a
total of eight people responded to Fernandez's request. The results
are four compact discs of some of the strangest stuff ever heard.
</P>
<P>
   To give some substance to these mysteries, hobbyists have named
certain recurring broadcasts. There's the Lincolnshire Poacher, the
Cherry Picker, the Sexy Lady, and the Russian Man.
</P>
<P>
   The Lincolnshire Poacher is believed to originate in Britain and
broadcasts frequently throughout the world. Hobbyists familiar with
this broadcast have noted that the station is regularly jammed. The
name comes from the few notes played before the broadcast begins,
part of the song ``The Lincolnshire Poacher.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sexy Lady is a mechanized female voice that has the intended
or unintended quality of sounding seductive while reading her code.
</P>
<P>
   The Cherry Picker, believed to be the Asian cousin of the
Lincolnshire Poacher, got its name from the old English folk song
``Cherry Ripe'' played during broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Some suggest the stations use music to set themselves apart.
Others suggest the music and voices are just a ruse, a means of
disguising the broadcasts' clandestine nature. No one, however,
really knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows about James Bond, everybody knows about
espionage in general,'' said Fernandez, ``but when it comes to the
tradecraft, nobody knows anything at all. And how can something be
kept a secret like this but be completely in the open? It's crazy.
It's just completely crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Van Horn, assistant editor for Monitoring Times, a
magazine specializing in shortwave and other forms of radio
listening, has written extensively on numbers stations. He said he
has heard it all when it comes to these clandestine broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Some theories say they are international bank accounting
numbers, stock market statistics, or even high-powered radio
beacons intended to guide passing UFOs to planet Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal favorite was first sent to me when I first came to
the company in 1992,'' wrote Van Horn. ``It was a guy in
Indianapolis, and he noticed that every &UR;  &LR; time a UPS airplane took
off, the signal strength of the numbers station he was monitoring
would increase. Therefore, he said, UPS was responsible for these
worldwide numbers station networks, which were used to pass
information on cargo arrival and departure.''
</P>
<P>
   For those sponsoring the broadcasts, silence is golden. Whenever
Van Horn tried to get confirmation of these broadcasts, officials
from the FCC or the CIA said they did not know what he's talking
about. Even after Monitoring Times published an article that traced
a certain numbers station broadcast to an Army facility in
Warrenton, Va., the authorities remained silent. No confirmation
was ever made. ``Nor a retraction,'' added Van Horn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better if they just remain quiet and keep on going,''
said Van Horn. ``There's no reason for them to say anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
