<HEADER>
A9998 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-CROW-BOS &LR;      09-29 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CROW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROW SPINS SOULFUL GOLD ON OPENHEARTED `GLOBE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Except for Alanis Morissette, no rock female in the last five
years can match the sales figures of Sheryl Crow, who sold 9
million copies of her first album (1993's ``Tuesday Night Music
Club'') and 6 million of 1996's ``Sheryl Crow.'' Crow has also won
multiple Grammy awards and toured with the Rolling Stones _ not a
shabby start for a former elementary school teacher from the tiny
heartland town of Kennett, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Crow, 36, has made some enemies because of the
perceived flippancy of early hits ``All I Wanna Do'' (with its tag
line ``is have some fun'') and ``Leaving Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   But love her or leave her, listeners have a new Crow to deal
with on ``The Globe Sessions,'' her third album, which is out
Tuesday. It shows a more confessional singer who this time is
boldly, and vulnerably, addressing her love life, which has
apparently been a lot less successful than her chart numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The album's honesty brings her closer to the open-hearted
approach of Bonnie Raitt, while offering musical substance (from
Middle Eastern drones to bluesy psychedelic touches) that should
win greater acceptance from critics who cast her as the get-lucky
woman who rode the right radio wave. Crow always had talent _ her
voice is more soulful than she's received credit for _ and the new
material is the best vehicle for it so far.
</P>
<P>
   The opening song, ``My Favorite Mistake,'' is a hit _ and sets
the lyrical tone. ``I woke up and called this morning/The tone of
your voice was a warning that you don't care for me anymore,'' Crow
sings above her own Hammond B3 organ and the tremolo guitar of Jeff
Trott. The song has a hooky chorus _ as hooky as the hit ``Every
Day Is a Winding Road'' from her last CD _ but its heightened
emotionalism is what makes it stand out. That, and the fact that
many listeners will wonder if it's about Eric Clapton, with whom
she was romantically linked.
</P>
<P>
   Crow has so far refused to name names regarding any of the new
songs; this is not a tabloid album. It's by far the most artful
record she's made, touching sensitivities that are universal. In
``It Don't Hurt,'' an organ-driven song that sounds like something
by the Band, Crow tries to squelch the memories of one relationship
by changing the wallpaper in her house, putting down new carpet,
adding a new wing, and finally bulldozing the house. Who can't
relate to her last line: ``It don't hurt like it did/It hurts
worse/Who do I kid?'' And the ending guitar solo by Todd Wolfe
borrows, aptly, from Lindsey Bucking-ham's ``Go Your Own Way.''
</P>
<P>
   While some lyrics have a downbeat edge (``You don't bring me
anything but down,'' she wails in one tune), the music has a
strength born of catharsis. Clearly, Crow needed to get these songs
out of her system. And a number of them still rock, such as
``Anything But Down,'' ``Maybe That's Something,'' and the Stonesy
``There Goes the Neighborhood,'' aided by saxophonist Bobby Keys
from the Stones' touring band.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't have a lyric sheet handy, you wouldn't know the
depth and anguish of some of these tracks, because the music is so
consistently beguiling. Crow plays a wealth of instruments, from
electric and acoustic guitars to clavinet, Wurlitzer, and
percussion. And though she sings that she's a ``loser in love,''
she stands up for herself elsewhere and does a romping version of
the CD's only non-original song, Bob Dylan's ``Mississippi,'' which
he never recorded and gave her specifically for this project. Its
bittersweet line ``Last night I knew you, tonight I don't,'' could
apply to Crow's tattered love history, too, yet it's a history that
Crow transcends with her finest album yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
