<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EATON-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EATON ENCOUNTERS DOUBLE JEOPARDY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The NFL has caught up to Chad Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   The film, the scouting reports, all the intelligence data now
focus on the big man in the middle of the Patriots' defensive line.
That is the price of going from nomad to No. 1 in less than a
season.
</P>
<P>
   The success Eaton enjoyed starting at the end of last season
doesn't come quite as easily anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stink,'' he said Monday. ``I really do. I get on myself
because there's so much I want to do. I don't know what my deal is.
I got yelled at today (by the Patriots' defensive coaches). They're
telling me things I need to do better: `We want you to rush the
passer more'; `We want you to get upfield more'; `You did it in
preseason, so why can't you do it now?'''
</P>
<P>
   It's a question he asks himself a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton, one of the most ferocious Patriots linemen, is
discovering the price of proficiency. Drew Bledsoe's former
Washington State teammate has come far as a pro. He's gone from
undrafted free agent to practice squadder to backup to starter. He
beat out veteran Mark Wheeler for the starting nose tackle job
during this past preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``In preseason, nobody knew who I was,'' said Eaton. ``Now I
have two guys on me, so now they're telling me I need to be more
aggressive. When you come into the league, nobody knows who you
are. You're just some guy, and until you make plays, you're
nothing. When you start making some plays, teams say, `You've got
to double him and then deal with the linebacker.' That's what I'm
dealing with right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The old double team.
</P>
<P>
   It eats up many a star player. Ben Coates has been double-teamed
for years. Ted Johnson often gets that type of attention. Chris
Slade and Willie McGinest have experienced it. Veteran Henry Thomas
had to live with it during his heyday with the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of growing up as an NFL player. Those who can deal
with it and still perform are the ones who survive. They're the
ones who become All-Pros. The ones who can't return to backup
roles.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton is now at that crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're doing today (in practice),'' he said. ``It's
technique day for me, where they'll try to get me back to what I
was doing before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest challenge I've had. They expect more from
you now. (As) a backup, the guy in front of me would mess up and I
would see what the correction was _ what the coaches wanted me to
do _ and then I'd go in there and do it. Now you have to go in
there and do what the coaches want. You have to understand what
they're asking you to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The game is all about adjustments. Eaton says he can ask other
players about how they deal with it, but in the end, he must find
his own way of overcoming it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets kind of frustrating,'' said Eaton, who was asked if
he's gotten pointers from Thomas. ``As much as you want to get help
from somebody like Henry, he plays different than I do. He has
different techniques that work for him that wouldn't work for me,
so it wouldn't work for me to listen to him. He's quicker. I'm a
strong guy, so being a strong guy, how do I overcome being
tentative?''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the issues line coach Ray Hamilton and defensive
coordinator Steve Sidwell are trying to work out with Eaton because
the challenge doesn't get any easier this week. The Patriots are
playing the New Orleans Saints, and according to Eaton, ``There are
only four offensive lines that are back intact in the NFL, and
they're one of them, so it's a big challenge. They're doing a good
job over there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saints are indeed moving the pile for their running game,
and they're also protecting quarterback Danny Wuerffel quite
nicely. It's up to Eaton as the man in the middle to disrupt all
that.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that teams are not allowing great
penetration by the Patriots' defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all keeping maximum protection and keeping the running
back and tight end in and getting rid of the ball quickly,''
explained Eaton. ``It's frustrating because we hear that we don't
have the sacks we had last year. You have to take the good with the
bad. You have to go with it because teams are starting to get
frustrated with that because they want to throw the ball deep and
we're not allowing them to do that. Eventually, though, they'll
have to. But we're not going to change what we do best.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaton, considered one of the best run stoppers on the team, is
also unhappy about the 100-yard rushing totals against the team the
past two games, but he knows why they were achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, we didn't have anyone rush over 100 yards
against us,'' he said, ``but now we've had two games in a row _
(Marshall) Faulk and (Eddie) George. They're getting their yards in
the fourth quarter when they're down. We had our nickel and dime in
against Indianapolis late in the game, so if they want to do draws
down by 29 points, we don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   What he does care about is making the adjustments necessary to
regain his effectiveness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
