<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES AHEAD FOR ZENGA, REVOLUTION? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Revolution regained some credibility and concluded their
third season with momentum. They surpassed 1 million spectators,
including exhibitions, in three-year total attendance. And they
have discovered a coach/icon in Walter Zenga.
</P>
<P>
   There are positive signs for the Revolution and Major League
Soccer, which will receive an additional $100 million in
investments from owners.
</P>
<P>
   But not everything is perfect in Revolution Land. The team's
late-season success could have been illusory, a combination of
Zenga's influence and the fact that the pressure to qualify for the
playoffs had been relieved. In fact, the Revolution lost their
final two games.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it fair to judge Zenga on six games.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga is the charismatic figure the Revolution have needed. He
is also a pragmatist. Regular crowds of nearly 20,000 are not to be
placed at risk. Zenga will do whatever is necessary to produce
results.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to an exceptional network of contacts, Zenga should be
able to find the players he wants, though he could be hampered by
the league's salary cap restrictions. His agent, Giovanni
Branchini, has provided players for MLS, but only as a long-range
investment since he is involved in much more immediate, high-stakes
representation in Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Zenga might only have to do some more fine-tuning _ if four
shutouts in the final six games are an indication of the true
ability of this team.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation is not as copacetic as it appears. Zenga, or
whoever becomes coach, will have to confront some tricky problems.
The most basic determination will be the makeup of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga appears satisfied with keeping the status quo, ostensibly
a core of hardworking, low-profile types, along with a couple of
skillful performers like Edwin Gorter and Joe-Max Moore, and adding
some high-profile veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Besides that six-game run, plus a good stretch when Zenga was
playing in 1997, the players who form the foundation of the
Revolution have mostly failed as a group. They could probably
succeed if they are properly motivated, organized, and combined
with the right players. But they have also resisted perceived
``outsiders'' in the past. Only if Zenga brings in highly credible
foreigners will they be accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Chiquinho Conde, Alejandro Farias, David Nakhid, Alberto Naveda
_ all experienced, solid professionals _ struggled to find
acceptance with the Revolution. Their successors likewise will
struggle unless the core group's attitude changes.
</P>
<P>
   This season there were disputes, jealousies, petty and not so
petty grievances within the Revolution which were never effectively
resolved. Zenga arrived to replace Thomas Rongen and attempted to
wipe the slate clean, which is what most coaches would have done.
But the problems he inherited will not disappear, even if the
perceived troublemakers are eliminated or gagged. That solution has
been tried in the past, starting with Giuseppe Galderisi in the
first month of the first season, but many of the same difficulties
continue to arise.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, Zenga would have a team with an all-for-one,
one-for-all attitude, with similar mentalities. This is possible in
Italy, where small teams often survive against all odds and
accomplish amazing feats. But in Italy, this occurs mainly because
of the concept of promotion/relegation. If the Revolution had been
playing in that system, they would have been relegated to the third
division by now.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga must also modify his attitude. In Italy, a coach can be
autocratic and even reclusive when dealing with the media. Zenga is
combative and cannot resist a confrontation. If he senses a
challenge, he fights back, a streetwise instinct that served him
well as a player and could as a coach, if he does so selectively.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga can charm audiences, and if he learns to charm the media
Bora Milutinovic-style, he will only increase his value.
</P>
<P>
   After the MetroStars and Revolution played to a 0-0 tie (the
MetroStars won the post-match shootout) Saturday, Milutinovic
entertained journalists and eventually had nearly everyone in the
press tent either laughing or speechless. Zenga arrived and
immediately became contentious, displaying a defensiveness which
left little room for negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   But such seductive traits must be natural and sincere, as they
appear to be for Milutinovic.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga the player was contentious in dealing with the media, but
he usually had a high-profile coach with an equally strong
personality to provide balance and sagacity in times of crisis.
Someone will have to perform a similar function for Zenga the
coach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
