<HEADLINE>
SINCERITY TRANSCENDS FORMULA IN `FELICITY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
FELICITY 
Starring: Keri Russell, Scott Foley, Scott Speedman, Tangi Miller,
Amy Jo Johnson 
On: WB 
Time: Tuesday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people are pretty darned sensitive about the genre known as
``sensitive drama.'' They can still work up a good lather against
``thirtysomething,'' the grandaddy of TV's ``Big Chill''
self-absorption from the late 1980s, and they have been known to
whine on and on about its progeny, from ``My So-Called Life'' to
``Dawson's Creek.'' There's just something about all that halting
dialogue, weighted with confession and incomplete sentences that
trail off into significant ellipses ... And pretty people aren't
supposed to have inner conflict, are they?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, I can't get enough of the stuff, as it blends
emotional insight and Woody Allen-esque neurosis with the
conventions of soap opera (Rule (NU)1: They must have a love
triangle. Rule (NU)2: They must have good hair). Tuesdays at 9, a
promising coming-of-age series named ``Felicity'' joins the family
tree of sensitive drama, after months of lavish advance praise from
critics across the country. Rightfully being referred to as ``My
So-Called Life'' Goes to College, it is a smartly written show that
truly does stand out in a season that's woefully weak in the
non-comedy department. Along with its refreshing cast, led by Keri
Russell, ``Felicity'' is blessed with a sweet realism that captures
the emotional roller coaster that is freshman year in college. It
also offers an appealingly non-gritty look at New York City, as
seen through the eyes of optimism and innocence.
</P>
<P>
   With a mop of wavy hair to rival that of the First Daughter,
Russell plays Felicity Porter, a not particularly blissful
California teen. Tired of her high-school role as wallflower, she
impulsively follows a boy she hardly knows to (the fictional)
University of New York after graduation. Her controlling yuppie
parents are disgusted _ they want her in Stanford University's
medical school _ but she has a passion for art, and a new hunger
for independence. The show chronicles Felicity's awkward and
angst-ridden baby steps into adulthood, with the assistance of a
voiceover comprised of Felicity's oral cassette-letters to a friend
in the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Felicity'' were a theatrical movie, it would probably be
the product of Cameron Crowe, the writer-director of the similarly
themed ``Say Anything.'' The setups on ``Felicity'' aren't
particularly original, with no less than two possible love
triangles established tonight (dorm monitor Noel has feelings for
Felicity, but Felicity has pinned her hopes on the hunk she
followed East, Ben, until she learns Ben likes her new best friend,
Julie). It's a familiar equation. But the show transcends formula
by staying steadily focused on its characters' shifting emotional
realities, and by avoiding the issue-of-the-week plot twists of a
series like ``Beverly Hills 90210.''
</P>
<P>
   While so many treatments of young adulthood are tinged with
irony, ``Felicity'' appears to be unafraid to approach its
characters with sincerity and, yes, sensitivity. It's certainly not
groundbreaking TV, but its the sort of welcome show that is
respectful of its characters, and its viewers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 1330EDT &QL; 
