<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY, MINUS THE BIG BUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To some, the words ``New York City'' bring visions of
hundred-dollar bills floating away on gossamer wings. But a trip to
the Apple doesn't have to be expensive. The Hampton Inn chain says
that a family of four can have a fine weekend for about $500 by
staying near Manhattan but not necessarily in it, avoiding costly
restaurants, taking advantage of free or low-cost attractions, and
walking or using public transit whenever possible. Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   _Enjoyable restaurants that won't bust the budget include the
Jekyl &AMP; Hyde Club (1409 Sixth Ave.) with its mad-scientist
waitstaff; the Stage Delicatessen (834 Seventh Ave.) with its
gigantic sandwiches; Hamburger Harry's (145 West 45th St.), where
the specialty is you-know-what; and the Film Center Cafe (635 Ninth
Ave.), featuring vintage Formica tables, old film reels, wall
murals of film studio logos, and a Sunday homestyle brunch. In all
of those restaurants, you should be able to get a meal for $10-$15
a person.
</P>
<P>
   _There are several low-cost attractions, including the
Children's Museum of the Arts, the American Museum of Natural
History, and that perennial favorite, the observation deck of the
Empire State Building.
</P>
<P>
   _Many of the city's free attractions are well-known.
Eight-hundred-forty-three-acre Central Park has unique features
such as the Alice in Wonderland statue and attractions such as the
Central Park Wildlife Conservation Center. The Statue of Liberty
National Monument and nearby Ellis Island Immigration Museum are
more than worthwhile. The four-story Sony Wonder Technology Lab
offers fun interactive exhibits. And you can't beat window shopping
along Fifth Avenue, with a stop at the world's largest toy store,
FAO Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   _And since Hampton Inns was nice enough to provide the preceding
tips, we'll be nice enough to add the chain's lodging
recommendation: the Carlstadt-At the Meadowlands Hampton Inn hotel
in New Jersey, five miles and a few minutes from Manhattan. The
rate for one room with two double beds is about $80 per weekend
night. (For more information, call 201-935-9000.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; And speaking of deals: &LR;  A mere $20 can buy you a tour of New York
City and afternoon tea at a Greenwich Village restaurant. Each
Saturday in October, raconteur Arthur Marks will conduct a two-hour
tour of the Village, followed by an afternoon tea of pastries,
finger sandwiches, and other savories at C3 Restaurant and Lounge
in the Washington Square Hotel. For reservations or more
information, call 212-254-1200.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  What is the significance of the seven points in the
crown of the Statue of Liberty? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``Welcome to Manhattan _ Home of the World-Weary
Poseur.'' _ billboard shown on TV's ``The Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Send in the clowns: &LR;  Jugglers, clowns, and musicians have been
providing free entertainment during peak hours at Terminal 4 of
John F. Kennedy Airport in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Underground art:  &LR; Beginning in spring, the Times Square subway will
get a $180 million sprucing up. Among other things, there will be
artwork, including a 53-foot-long porcelain mural of a futuristic
subway, created by Roy Lichtenstein before he died last year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Mailbag:  &LR; Judy Pugliese of Shrewsbury comments on our Sept. 6 photo
of a sign at a McDonald's in Aruba: ``At first glance the sign
stating, `Parking for Drive-Through Customers Only' is a
head-shaker; then I realized I've seen the same sign at a number of
fast-food restaurants locally and in other states. It's actually a
space or two reserved for cars to wait for orders that will take a
bit longer to deliver (special orders, etc.), so that other
customers can drive through.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  The seven points in the Statue of Liberty's
crown represent liberty beaming out to the seven continents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
