<HEADLINE>
QUABBIN RESERVOIR: WATER, SCENERY, WILDLIFE EVERYWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELCHERTOWN, Mass. _ Sixty-five miles from Boston, the Quabbin
Reservoir is the watery heart of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Although one of the largest manmade bodies of water in the
world, the 18-mile-long Quabbin is strangely isolated, elusive, and
unobtrusive. Access to it is limited. And while major roadways
circle it, they generally offer only a few tantalizing, obstructed
glimpses.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the stunning panorama from the summit of the
observation tower in the Metropolitan District Commission's Quabbin
Park here is such a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   Like an inland sea, the great lake stretches shimmeringly away
toward the misty blue wall of the Berkshire hills on the western
horizon. There is no other sight quite like it in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Quabbin (a Native American name meaning ``Land of Many Waters'')
is an engineering triumph, certainly, but it's also the centerpiece
of a rural area of remarkable, often haunting beauty. A fisherman's
paradise _ lake trout, bass, perch, and salmon abound _ the
reservoir is surrounded by a thickly forested 81,000-acre MDC
reservation teeming with deer and other wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Bald eagles nest on the shore and can often be seen swooping and
circling over the water. Wild turkeys, long extinct in
Massachusetts, were reintroduced in the Quabbin reserve, thrived,
and have spread into the surrounding countryside. Driving or
cycling around the area today, it's not unusual to see a turkey
scuttle across the road.
</P>
<P>
   The towns and villages of the Quabbin area are typically made up
of mostly Federal-era houses and churches clustered around
tree-shaded commons, and are some of the loveliest in the state.
Creation of the reservoir, which was completed in 1939, isolated
and back-roaded some once-bustling communities. In that sense,
towns such as New Salem, Hardwick, and Petersham give the
impression of being caught in a time warp, little changed in the
past 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Four towns drowned
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most famous towns in the area, however, are the four that no
one can see: Dana, Prescott, Enfield, and Greenwich. When the Swift
River was dammed to create the Quabbin, the valley's 2,500
residents were relocated and their towns sent the way of the
legendary lost city of Atlantis.
</P>
<P>
   They now lie under 50 or more feet of water, but the ``drowned
towns'' live on as poignant local memories. The subject of many
books, stories, and legends, the towns over time have acquired
almost mythic status, transmuted from pleasant but ordinary country
communities into symbolic rural Edens sacrificed to satisfy
big-city needs for water.
</P>
<P>
   Belchertown, on the other hand, because of its name has inspired
more laughter than sadness. Forget the jokes, though; it's an old,
attractive town with a large common dominated by an 18th-century
Congregational church. It also contains the gateway to Quabbin
Park, the 3,200-acre recreational preserve at the southern end of
the reservation, accessible from Route 9.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the summit tower at the park's highest point, there are
several other scenic lookout spots. There are also picnic areas, 20
miles of wide dirt hiking trails, and about 10 miles of paved road.
(Bicycling is permitted only on the paved roads.) You can drive to
all of the lookouts, and also across the Winsor Dam and beside its
spillway.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing is permitted from mid-April to mid-October. Boat access
to the water is from launching areas at marked gates around the
reservoir. A fishing license is required to launch a boat, even if
you aren't going to fish.
</P>
<P>
   The Quabbin Park Visitors Center (413-323-7221) is in the MDC
administration building beside Winsor Dam. Open daily, it provides
maps and brochures, as well as intriguing exhibits about the
construction of the reservoir and operation of the complex water
system. You may have never seen the reservoir, but chances are
you've had a drink from it: Quabbin provides water to 2.5 million
people in 46 communities, including Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Three miles east of the park entrance, on the south side of
Route 9, is the beautiful yet eerie Quabbin Cemetery, which
contains the collected dead of the four lost towns: 7,500 graves,
including headstones, markers, and memorials.
</P>
<P>
   Two old cannons that once decorated the Enfield Common face the
cemetery gate. Between them, a bronze statue of a Civil War soldier
stands at attention atop a granite monument, an eternal sentinel
guarding the citizenry of a vanished valley.
</P>
<P>
   Located between the Massachusetts Turnpike and Route 2, the
Quabbin is easily reached from either road. However, from Boston
the most scenic approach is from Route 2, along roads that pass
through a series of character-filled and quintessentially New
England towns and villages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hamlets out of time
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Templeton, on Route 110, is a classic hill town
with a large common that often hosts fairs and festivals. The
Narransett Historical Society, housed in a brick mansion facing the
common, serves tea in the garden on Saturdays. Country Mischief, an
antiques and crafts store, occupies another Federal mansion on the
common and has 20 themed rooms crammed with bric-a-brac and mostly
regionally made crafts. (The Christmas and Halloween rooms alone
are worth a visit.)
</P>
<P>
   Petersham, once a fashionable summer resort and also on Route
110, also has an elegant town center, with many handsome homes and
mansions. The general store, operating since 1842, is one of the
state's oldest.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the usual sundries, the store stocks a fine selection of
books and maps about the Quabbin area and the four towns. One of
the books, ``Marjorie's Secret,'' is a slim, privately printed
novella by Fay W. Butler, a 70-year-old man who runs a gas station
in nearby Hardwick, on Route 32A. ``It's about people who lived in
Dana and had to leave when it was flooded for the Quabbin,'' Butler
says. ``I wanted to get down some of the things the old people who
came into my station over the years told me about how it was
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Swift River Valley farm families were resettled in
Hardwick, which is still bucolic. Every summer since 1762 the town
has held an agricultural fair on its scenic common _ framed by
white steepled churches, the town hall, and a one-room schoolhouse
_ complete with sheep and cattle judging.
</P>
<P>
   An old textile manufacturing town, Ware, on Route 9, has a
number of imposing 19th-century mill buildings, many of which now
house factory outlets and antique dealers. Stonemill Marketplace on
East Main Street has a large and eclectic antique collection.
</P>
<P>
   The western side of Quabbin also has a number of interesting
communities such as Pelham and New Salem, both on Route 202. The
route is officially named the Daniel Shays Highway in honor of the
man who in 1786 led a rebellion by impoverished local farmers
against a state government controlled by wealthy Boston merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Pelham was the headquarters of Shays's ragtag force, and the
local historical society (open weekends) has exhibits devoted to
the rebellion. On a hilltop just north of Pelham Center is the
Pelham Overlook, which offers one of the few scenic views of the
reservoir to be had from a highway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A quiet survivor
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Salem survived as a town after the Swift River was dammed,
but barely. Today about 80 percent of the original land is either
under water or within the MDC reservation. What's left is lovely,
but almost spookily quiet.
</P>
<P>
   The old town center, just off the highway, is a gem, with an
elliptical common and a striking lineup of structures that include
a granite assembly building that was once a private academy and a
church meetinghouse built in 1794 and now used as a concert hall.
The only commercial activity is The Common Reader, a notable
secondhand book and antique store. Main Street, a busy east-west
thoroughfare in pre-Quabbin days, abruptly dead-ends just beyond
the common at a chain-link fence marking the MDC boundary.
</P>
<P>
   On Elm Street in North New Salem (signposted from Route 202),
the Swift River Historical Society museum (978-544-6882) preserves
the collective memory of the four lost towns. The museum has a
large collection of photos, artifacts, genealogical records, and
memorabilia housed in three buildings, including a former church
moved to the site from the valley.
</P>
<P>
   One of the society's most treasured artifacts stands on the
grounds. A square wooden 19th-century ``guide post,'' it still
points the way to the drowned towns.
</P>
</TEXT>
