<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE MISSED; SO DID HURRICANES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a washout weekend for the Big East.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College suffered its first loss of the season, a stunning
52-28 nonconference setback at Louisville. Temple remained winless,
dropping to 0-4 with a 30-20 loss at Maryland. And Miami's marquee
matchup against No. 3 UCLA was canceled because of the threat posed
by Hurricane Georges.
</P>
<P>
   While it landed only a glancing blow on South Florida last
weekend, instead striking the Florida Keys with all its fury,
Hurricane Georges did wreak havoc on Miami's plans to host UCLA in
a CBS game at the Orange Bowl. There have been no announcements
about a rescheduling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mutually agreed upon decision because of all the
things that were going on in South Florida at the time, and with
all the potential for major disaster, not to play the game at that
particular time,'' said Miami coach Butch Davis. ``Will it be
rescheduled? I think certainly from things I've read in the
newspaper, both coaching staffs and both teams would like to play
the game. I believe that television people are interested in
rebroadcasting at a later date. Now it's just a matter of whether
or not the athletic directors and administration can put the thing
back together.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do, great. If they don't, then we've got to move on.
We can't get too concerned about it. Only time will tell, but it's
pretty much in the administration's hands right now. I'm sure UCLA
is doing exactly the same thing we're doing today, and that's
getting ready (for the next game).''
</P>
<P>
   Next up for Miami: a conference game at Rutgers Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we were very fortunate, because if you read the
newspapers or watch television, you can see what the hurricane has
done to the Florida Keys and the Gulf Coast,'' Davis said. ``I
guess we missed it by 50 or 60 miles, and fortunately, it didn't
hit Dade County, so we felt fortunate about that part of it. But we
just tried to address last weekend as a regularly scheduled open
date.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The drawing board
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After BC (3-1) absorbed its worst loss since a 52-20 drubbing at
Notre Dame last year, coach Tom O'Brien said he and his staff would
likely use this week's open date to reevaluate the team's overall
performance in the first four games. Could a personnel move or
alteration be in the offing? ``I wouldn't say that right now, but I
can't rule that out one way or another,'' said O'Brien, who used
Monday's day off to take 25-30 players on a visit to the cancer
ward at Children's Hospital. ``I think we have to take a good look
at the first four games and try to evaluate what we've done both
schematically and with our personnel and start practicing and then
later on in the week take a look at Virginia Tech and where we have
to go in the future.'' ... The Hokies, BC's next opponent Oct. 8,
sustained more casualties to their offense in a 27-7 victory over
Pittsburgh after losing three starters _ quarterback Al Clark
(sprained foot, ankle), offensive guard Josh Redding (knee), and
fullback Cullen Hawkins (foot) _ at Miami two weeks ago. After
running back Shyrone Stith suffered a severe ankle sprain,
sophomore backup quarterback Dave Meyer went down in the third
quarter against Pitt with a separated right shoulder, forcing the
Hokies to go with sophomore Nick Sorenson, who had been switched to
free safety this season after serving as Clark's backup last year.
Prized freshman recruit Jake Houseright, who came to Virginia Tech
as a linebacker, will be switched to fullback to help make up for
the loss of Hawkins ... After a Sept. 19 visit to the Big East
woodshed _ a k a the Carrier Dome, where Rutgers suffered a savage
70-14 pounding _ the Scarlet Knights rebounded Saturday by scoring
a 27-15 victory over visiting Army. That gave coach Terry Shea his
first win in 17 games against Division 1-A opponents. ``I really
believed our entire program was embarrassed about the way we played
at Syracuse, not that we could've beaten Syracuse,'' said Shea, who
must now get his team (2-2, 0-2) ready to host Miami (2-1, 0-1).
``But we just didn't play very well at all, and it was certainly
below our standard. We just made sure our guys understood how
important it was to start playing like a major college football
team and do things the right way and take care of the critical
plays of the game. I think that's what truly drove our team all
week in practice.'' ... Syracuse will have a chance to improve the
Big East's 3-1 record against Atlantic Coast Conference opponents
when the Orangemen travel to North Carolina State for an ESPN
Thursday night game. Syracuse is looking to snap a five-game losing
streak against the Wolfpack, who scored a 32-31 overtime victory at
the Carrier Dome last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
