<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT CAMP HOPES THIS TIME THE CHARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Silver Charm is back. Well, almost.
</P>
<P>
   The charismatic winner of last year's Kentucky Derby and
Preakness and one of the most popular horses of recent times,
Silver Charm didn't beat all four of his foes in the $500,000
Kentucky Cup Classic at Turfway Park Saturday, finishing in a dead
heat with Wild Rush. But after two straight subpar performances,
his connections gladly took a tie. The question now is: Will Silver
Charm make the Breeders' Cup Classic at Churchill Downs Nov. 7 for
a showdown with Skip Away, who is undefeated this season at 7 for
7?
</P>
<P>
   ``Wild Rush was relentless and Silver Charm was flat out,'' said
Bob Baffert, who trains Silver Charm for Bob and Beverly Lewis.
``They say ties are like kissing your sister, but I really thought
he was second.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Silver Charm, who was giving Wild Rush 6 pounds
(123-117), made a lunge at the wire from the outside to gain the
draw after a stirring stretch battle. Off at 1-2 under Gary
Stevens, Silver Charm saved the grandstand by refusing to let Wild
Rush, the 2-1 second choice with Pat Day, keep his nostril in front
at the wire. The time for the 1 1/8 miles was fast _ 1:47 2/5 _
further buoying the Silver Charm camp after discouraging losses in
the Stephen Foster at Churchill Downs June 13, when he was second
to Awesome Again, and especially in the San Diego Handicap at Del
Mar, when he was fifth and last. The San Diego Handicap marked the
first time Silver Charm, who also won last year's Preakness and
this year's $4 million Dubai World Cup, had finished worse than
second in his career (16-9-6-0).
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we know he is headed in the right direction,'' said
Baffert. ``Off this race, he should really move forward. He's on a
comeback. Right now we've got a way to go before we could go
against Skip Away. I don't want to run against Skip Away unless I
think I can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm, a mere $16,500 yearling, was not nominated to the
Breeders' Cup program, so the Lewises would have to put up
$480,000, 12 percent of the purse, to make him eligible for the $4
million Classic. Baffert's plan is to run Silver Charm, who came
out of the Kentucky Cup in fine fettle, in either the Meadowlands
Cup Oct. 16 or the Goodwood Handicap at Santa Anita Oct. 17. If the
big gray runs well in his next assignment, it will likely be on to
the Breeders' Cup. Otherwise, he probably will be retired.
</P>
<P>
   If Silver Charm does not run in the Classic, it will be because
he is off form, not because the Lewises, who are very sporting,
won't pay the fee. After all, Siler Charm, who has won $4,950,430
in purses, has earned his way there, and the industry would still
love to see an encounter between the 1997 3-year-old champion and
Skip Away, the '97 handicap champion. It would be great for the
game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
No more dirty `Trick'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Favorite Trick, the Horse of the Year in '97 when he went 8 for
8 as a 2-year-old, is officially headed for the grass. He will race
next in either the Kelso at Belmont or the Keeneland Breeders' Cup,
both run at 1 mile Oct. 17. Favorite Trick, who flopped in the
Kentucky Derby, finished fifth in the King's Bishop, a 7-furlong
sprint, at Saratoga Aug. 29 in what could have been his final race
on dirt. If he succeeds in his first turf try, trainer Bill Mott
may enter him next in the $1 million Breeders' Cup Mile, run on the
grass. If Favorite Trick does make the Mile, among his opponents
could be Wild Rush, who will start in either the Mile or the $1
million Sprint at 6 furlongs ... Victory Gallop, winner of the
Belmont Stakes and second to Coronado's Quest in both the Haskell
and Travers, might go up against Skip Away in the $1 million Jockey
Club Gold Cup at Belmont Oct. 10. However, after seeing Skip Away
crush Coronado'a Quest in the Wooward Sept. 19, trainer Elliott
Walden is keeping open other options for his 3-year-old, including
the Hawthorne Gold Cup, run the same day as the Jockey Club; the
Meadowlands Cup; and the Fayette at Keeneland Oct. 11. Victory
Gallop, who had been battling a virus, drilled 4 furlongs in :49
2/5, galloping out 5 furlongs in 1:02 3/5, at Churchill last
Wednesday, the first time he has had a workout since the Travers
Aug. 29. ``He was rolling late, which is patented for him,'' said
Walden ... Touch Gold, winner of last year's Belmont Stakes, is
heading for the Fayette, which trainer Pat Byrne hopes will be a
steppingstone for the Classic. Last Thursday, Touch Gold had a
serious move at Churchill, going 6 furlongs in 1:11 2/5 under Day.
``I wasn't looking for that kind of time, but I was looking for a
good work,'' said Byrne. ``You've got to be happy with the horse.''
Touch Gold, long plagued by bad hooves, is looking to rebound after
finishing up the track in the Pacific Classic at Del Mar Aug. 15
... Raffie's Majesty, beaten just two noses as a flying third in
the Travers, fractured his left front knee while working out at
Saratoga last Monday and may be retired.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Barton calls it quits
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Donna Barton, who rode in New England for a time before going on
to bigger and better things, has retired at age 32. Barton, the
daughter of pioneer woman rider Patti Barton, will marry Frank
Brothers, one of the nation's best trainers, Nov. 15 and attend
college at the University of Louisville. Barton, who said her dream
always has been to earn a college degree, rode for 11 years and won
1,131 races. She did very well in Kentucky, where she teamed with
trainer D. Wayne Lukas, riding such outstanding Lukas charges as
Hennessy, with whom she finished second in the 1995 Breeders' Cup
Juvenile; and Boston Harbor, the 1996 2-year-old champion, whom she
rode to victory in the Kentucky Cup Juvenile and Bashford Manor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Material from publicity departments at various race tracks was
used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
