<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVERGENCE? NOT EXACTLY! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In so many ways, he resembles Fidelity's Peter Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1946 in the pin-neat South Side neighborhood known as
Roseland, John Meriwether grew up Irish Catholic in the era of
Mayor Richard J. Daley: Chicago, The City That Worked.
</P>
<P>
   There were parochial schools until he went to college at
Northwestern University in Evanston, 10 miles across the city. He
caddied at Flossmor Country Club as a teenager, and grew to be an
excellent golfer. He hit a hole in one the first time he played
Augusta National. He even taught school for a time.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was on to the University of Chicago for an MBA, while he
worked as a financial analyst for CNA Financial Corp. (the one with
the ink-red building.) And finally in 1974 the job at Salomon
Brothers, trading new-fangled repurchase agreements, or repos.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, after building Salomon's famous fixed-income
arbitrage desk into one of Wall Street's high-tech wonders, after
fabulous successes, he remained a steady church-goer, attending
Mass in the little town where he lived near his Greenwich, Conn.,
offices.
</P>
<P>
   And when he sat for the profile by Kevin Muehring in
Institutional Investor from which most of these details are drawn,
it was clear that Meriwether was a man of parts. Like Lynch,
another down-to-earth kid made good in the high-flying markets, his
easy ways were not reserved for the rich and famous. He was
generous to Catholic charities and made pilgrimages to shrines such
as Lourdes and Fatima. He followed closely the peace talks in
Northern Ireland. He was happily married. And he still shot a
wonderful game of golf.
</P>
<P>
   So who would have thought that Meriwether would wind up as the
poster boy for a certain kind of bad financial behavior?
</P>
<P>
   The baby-faced bond trader first acquired lengendary status
when, in Michael Lewis's entertaining book ``Liar's Poker,'' he
faced down Salomon's chairman John Gutfreund by bumping him from $1
million to $10 million over a single hand of the bluffing game.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the celebrated two-year Treasury note squeeze at
Salomon Brothers in 1991, when a subordinate tried make a killing
by cornering the market in an auction. Meriwether reported the
lawbreaker, but was forced to leave the firm for a time in the wake
of its forced bailout by Warren Buffett.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is the forced sale of Meriwether's hedge fund, Long-Term
Capital Management LP, that has put the bond &UR;  &LR; trader back in the
headlines. A consortium of 15 big New York financial institutions
took over the faltering firm last week after ponying up more than
$3.5 billion to prevent its collapse. Meriwether and his partners
apparently were left with little more than their opulent houses and
the relatively small sums they had taken out of the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Ironies abound in the story of Long-Term Capital, which
Meriwether formed in 1994 with other top Salomon traders, a handful
of finance professors (including a pair of Nobel laureates,) and a
prominent ex-regulator or two. But the greatest of these may be
that Meriwether is now seen by many as the ultimate plunger,
betting the world economy like a casino player with a hunch.
</P>
<P>
   The style of arbitrage that Meriwether pioneered is known as
``convergence'' or ``relative value'' trading. It depends on the
identification of relatively tiny mispricing of bonds of one type
or another relative to other investments _ and their purchase in
huge quantities.
</P>
<P>
   Other hedge fund operators bet the direction of interest rates.
Long-Term Capital hunted for unseen misalignments among instruments
that eventually would converge. Computers and powerful mathematics,
not intuition nor inside information, were its tools.
</P>
<P>
   The result was that the firm's exposure was almost entirely in
extremely conservative investments _ European and American
government bonds _ and not in currencies or the equities of
developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Russia defaulted on its highly speculative bonds in
August, the resulting ``flight to quality'' bid up the prices of
the best government bonds _ and destroyed the intricate
correlations upon which Long-Term Capital's strategies depended.
The firm had no choice but to sell into markets that were going
against it.
</P>
<P>
   The financial wizard, whose vision was as orderly as the gardens
of Roseland, whose techniques emphasized obedience over resolution
at every turn, was undone by his passion for order. Other investors
simply were not as neat as he thought.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David warsh writes on economics for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
