<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW'S THE DAWN OF A WRITER SADLY NEGLECTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is light complaint that too many entries in this series
consider authors unknown to most readers. Here is another of these,
by name of Dawn Powell; but her low profile may begin to rise a
bit, prodded by Tim Page's new and appreciative critical biography
of her.
</P>
<P>
   Before coming to grips with Dawn Powell, let's consider the
possible consequences of literary biography. It may damage
reputation, as in Mark Schorer's redoubtable biographical study of
Sinclair Lewis. Or it may redeem a declining figure, reclaim a lost
one.
</P>
<P>
   Herman Melville, for example. Following an early life of
maritime adventure, Melville won fame for his early romances _
``Typee,'' ``Omoo,'' ``Mardi,'' ``Redburn'' _ before he was 30.
Ironically, his popularity began to wane with the publication in
1851 of ``Moby-Dick,'' surely his most ambitious work and, some
would say, the greatest of all American novels.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Moby-Dick'' was not appreciated in its time, nor were the
later striking achievements of ``Israel Potter,'' ``Bartleby the
Scrivener,'' ``Benito Cereno'' and ``The Confidence Man;'' and
Melville drifted toward obscurity after his death in 1891.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected appearance of ``Billy Budd'' in 1924 attracted
little attention; but five years later, Lewis Mumford's biography
of Melville was an unanticipated bestseller that rehabilitated its
subject so thoroughly as to solemnize all of Melville's prose, and
his poetry too. Today, Herman Melville ranks one-two with his
friend and neighbor Nathaniel Hawthorne (to whom ``Moby-Dick'' was
dedicated) as 19th-century America's greatest novelists.
</P>
<P>
   And Stephen Crane. Although ``The Red Badge of Courage'' was
widely read following its 1895 publication, its author who died
five years later at age 28 was substantially forgotten soon after.
Little might have been known of Crane today but for Thomas Beer's
1923 biography of him.
</P>
<P>
   Crane's short life rivaled Melville's for its adventure
quotient; and again like Melville, as an author he was innovative
both thematically and stylistically. He was profoundly ambitious,
so great things might have been expected of him.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Beer who brought Crane's modest body of work into
appreciative light, including some of the finest short stories ever
crafted, several splendid novellas, and ``Maggie: A Girl of the
Streets,'' which preceded ``The Red Badge of Courage'' in
composition (Crane wrote it at age 21) and is the first vivid
bridge between the literary schools of realism and naturalism.
</P>
<P>
   A comparable Dawn Powell renaissance may not be in the offing,
but who knows? Besides its discerning positive assessment of
Powell's work, Page's study, just out as a $30 hardback from Holt,
illuminates a captivating woman, bright and witty and wise in life
as in her fiction. (These faculties are underscored by her diaries
(1931-65), published concurrently and also edited by Page.)
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Powell (1897-1965) peaked in the Great Depression years
that weren't kind to fiction sales, but her novels didn't get lost
and received ample and generally favorable critical attention. She
was almost a ``name'' writer then, but try finding her books today.
Even the public libraries seem to have discarded her.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, I read Powell's ``Turn, Magic Wheel'' (1936) and
remember it as one of those novels that could cause me to laugh out
of control. She was also a failed dramatist, whose ``Big Night''
was staged by the fabled Group Theater, and I've read the play
script with its crackerjack dialogue. Otherwise, I'm merely on the
hunt for more Powell, and Page has made it a more urgent search.
</P>
<P>
   Her best-known works seem to have been ``She Walks in Beauty,''
``The Bride's House,'' ``Dance Night,'' and ``Angels on Toast,''
and there are several others.
</P>
<P>
   What Tim Page and his book may do for Dawn Powell is difficult
to calculate, but the biography _ like its subject _ is grand
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
