<HEADLINE>
THE WILTED TULIP AND THE ROOT OF ALL EVIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Welcome, distinguished losers.
</P>
<P>
   It is time again to award the coveted Wilted Tulip. As many of
you know, being past recipients yourselves, the Wilted Tulip is
bestowed upon the individual who each year most convincingly shows
the world that to lose _ and lose big _ is beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilted Tulip Award derives its name from the frenzied tulip
speculation that swept Holland in the 17th century. For three
years, tulip prices couldn't climb high enough. The rich grew
richer and the poor grew rich as the world focused its investment
passion on these bulbs. Of course, the bubble burst, and everyone
learned that to lose _ and lose big _ is beautiful, especially when
you're left with a fistful of tulips.
</P>
<P>
   Before opening this year's sealed envelope, let's take a moment
to honor two esteemed past recipients of the Wilted Tulip Award:
Toshihide Iguchi and Nicholas Leeson. I regret that neither man can
join us today, as both were denied furloughs from prison. You will
recall that Mr. Iguchi, a Daiwa Bank trader, won his Wilted Tulip
for singlehandedly losing $1.1 billion. Please, ladies and
gentlemen, do sit down _ I'm sure Mr. Iguchi would be proud to
witness your ovation. As for Mr. Leeson, how can we forget the
young rogue trader in Singapore who brought down venerable Barings
investment bank by losing $1.3 billion?
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yes, I see Robert Citron in the audience. Let's give a
hearty welcome to the former treasurer of Orange County, Calif.,
another distinguished Wilted Tulip winner. Mr. Citron, you will
recall, dropped $1.6 billion by betting the wrong way on the
direction of interest rates and now holds the honor of causing the
nation's largest municipal bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   These are the men who give the Wilted Tulip its prestige.
</P>
<P>
   Now allow me to enumerate a few of the many reasons the Wilted
Tulip executive committee has chosen our newest honoree:
</P>
<P>
   _For his hedge fund's loss of nearly $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   _For striking fear into the hearts of all investors worried that
his losses would precipitate a global meltdown. He was so
successful raising the alarm that the Federal Reserve cajoled
big-name banks and brokerage houses like Merrill Lynch, J.P. Morgan
and Goldman Sachs to pony up cash for a $3.5 billion bailout of his
fund.
</P>
<P>
   _For instigating possible regulation of the wild and wooly hedge
fund industry. The funds have long thrived as private clubs for the
wealthy, with admission fees in the millions of dollars and their
trading antics maintained as well-guarded secrets from the prying
eyes of regulators.
</P>
<P>
   _For proving that if you lose really big _ and really beautiful
_ then you must be really smart. Big-brain partners in our
recipient's fund include two Nobel Prize winners in economics,
Myron Scholes and Robert Merton. If any further proof of brilliance
were needed, the fund was guided by mathematical trading strategies
understood only by crazed geniuses.
</P>
<P>
   _For the year's most beautiful irony: that Scholes and Merton
were recognized by the Nobel committee in 1997 for their
understanding of financial risk.
</P>
<P>
   _For proving that the smartest investors really are those who
are luckiest the longest.
</P>
<P>
   _For taking one of the most spectacular dives from grace.
</P>
<P>
   _For restoring the original meaning of the word risk.
</P>
<P>
   The envelope, please. And the winner is: Mr. John Meriwether of
Long-Term Capital Management.
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations, loser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Levingston can be reached at leving(at)bu.edu.)
</P>
</TEXT>
