<HEADLINE>
UAM MAY BE NEAR SALE OF TARNISHED JEWEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   United Asset Management Corp. of Boston may be close to selling
what had been considered one of the jewels in its collection of
money managers, mutual fund operator Pilgrim Baxter &AMP; Associates
Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   UAM Monday confirmed it was negotiating the sale of Pilgrim
Baxter to Nationwide Financial Services Inc., an insurance company.
UAM is believed to be seeking as much as $600 million for the firm
that manages mutual funds under the name PBHG.
</P>
<P>
   The big question: are there more sales ahead? UAM doesn't rule
out the possibility but insists the Pilgrim Baxter negotiations
were sparked by strategic issues specific to that firm.
</P>
<P>
   A sale would be only the latest strategic twist at UAM, which
has struggled with persistent client cash flow problems. Though the
company remains quite profitable, customers have been removing more
money than they contribute to UAM's investment firms quarter after
quarter. Negative client cash flow amounted to $4.3 billion in the
last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   UAM sold Analytic-TSA International Inc., a small bond
investment firm, earlier this year. It was the first time United
Asset Management sold one of its investment subsidiaries in the
company's 18-year history. More recently, UAM decided to shut its
subsidiary that serviced retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   Most of UAM's investment firms are institutional money managers
with names the average investor would never recognize. But Pilgrim
Baxter was a striking exception, an aggressive growth mutual fund
business widely known by individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   Pilgrim Baxter has fallen on hard times of late, its money under
management declining in line with a weak investment performance.
The firm's assets under management have declined from $16.6 billion
to $12.4 billion over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Pilgrim Baxter hired former Fidelity Investments
executive Paul Hondros as its chief operating officer. Hondros, who
had run Fidelity's retail investment operations, was expected to
move aggressively to build a much larger base of retail business
around Pilgrim Baxter.
</P>
<P>
   UAM officials point to an expensive ``mass market retail
distribution'' organization Pilgrim Baxter had been building, even
before Hondros arrived, as the reason a sale was considered. It
didn't fit with most of the company's other businesses and but
could be attractive to buyers in a market paying handsomely for
mutual fund operations.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry consultants said UAM's interest in selling Pilgrim
Baxter, first reported by The Wall Street Journal, indicates the
company has grown frustrated with the retail investment business.
</P>
<P>
   ``UAM never successfully penetrated the retail marketplace to
any extent,'' said consultant Burton Greenwald. ``If they were
going to be players on the retail side of the business, their point
of departure was going to be Pilgrim Baxter.''
</P>
<P>
   But UAM would be selling off one of its most valauble companies.
That has industry observers speculating a more interesting story
lies behind the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Pilgrim Baxter's assets under management represent only 6
percent of the $210 billion invested for clients by all UAM's firms
combined. But the $600 million price tag, a figure doubted by some,
is equal to 40 percent of UAM's $1.5 billion total stock market
value.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fidelity `redeploys' workers
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments said Monday it had no plans for layoffs or
a hiring freeze, but did confirm that it is ``redeploying'' about
30 people in its retail business, which deals mainly with
individual investors. Look for similar moves ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The world's biggest mutual fund company is rife with rumors
about cutbacks in the wake of a market correction, but Fidelity
says there are no such plans. It says it has added 2,700 jobs so
far this year and has ``hundreds'' of open jobs it is looking to
fill.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 or so Fidelity employees, mainly in retail marketing,
will be given until the end of the year to find another job in the
company before they are let go, Fidelity said. The company said it
was now hiring 240 people in the retail unit to support the firm's
new ad campaign built around investment guru Peter Lynch. But
Fidelity said it would continue to examine its needs in the retail
unit, now headed by vice chairman J. Gary Burkhead and a team of
new executives.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity watchers said they would not be surprised to see the
company cut some workers, as have other financial services
companies. ``But I don't think it will be anything dramatic,'' said
Eric Kobren, editor of Fidelity Insight, a newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John R. Ranelli, the number two man at Stride Rite Corp., has
resigned, giving a boost to the only other insider in the chase to
fill the seat of retiring chief executive Robert Siegel.
</P>
<P>
   The Lexington, Mass. shoe company confirmed that Ranelli, who
came to Stride Rite two years ago as executive vice president, had
resigned to pursue other opportunites. Insiders said the board had
made clear that it did not think Ranelli had the broad marketing
background it wanted in a new chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The only other inside candidate is Diane Sullivan, president of
Stride Rite's licensed brands division, who is seen as more of a
marketer. Outsiders are also being considered, but the shoe
business is not the kind of industry that usually brings star
candidates beating down the doors.
</P>
<P>
   Look the board to get final candidates by mid-November; Siegel's
contract runs to the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
