<HEADLINE>
FOR TOUGH JOBS, USE PROFESSIONAL TOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Ever try to get a screw into a brick or concrete
wall and have your new battery-powered or plug-in screwdriver go
kaput? You may have been using a do-it-yourself model, which is
also known as a homeowners-grade tool, instead of a high-powered
professional model.
</P>
<P>
   While there can be a 50 percent or more difference in cost
between nonprofessional and professional models, the benefits of
the latter are well worth the price. That's especially true if you
are planning to complete one or more heavy-duty projects and wish
to avoid an inferior drill prone to breaking.
</P>
<P>
   Professional-grade tools have more power, featuring bigger
motors with four to five amps, unlike homeowner models, which are
lighter and have two to three amps.
</P>
<P>
   Inexpensive power tools often are made of low-grade plastic,
which can flex when heated from use or overheat when used on tough
jobs. Professional power tools tend to be encased in strong
plastics that are rarely affected by extreme temperatures or
chemicals. They also have minimum vibration and more balanced
armatures.
</P>
<P>
   Professional-grade tools not only have a longer life, but offer
other options such as a depth clutch, which automatically drives a
screw to any predetermined depth, speed control and reverse, for
removing stubborn screws.
</P>
<P>
   Professional electric drills cost around $60 to $200, while
homeowner models usually range from $30 to $80.
</P>
<P>
   Whether to choose a cordless or plug-in drill is mostly a matter
of personal taste _ except if you are working outdoors. In that
case, cordless may be the better option, since there's no need for
extension cords or exterior outlets. Cordless may also make sense
when using a ladder, so you can't become entangled in the cord or
be thrown off-balance by the weight.
</P>
<P>
   When choosing a cordless drill, select one with enough power to
do the job, such as one with an 18-volt power pack, as opposed to a
low-end 7.2-volt rating.
</P>
<P>
   Batteries have come a long way. They now last longer and
recharge quicker. Alkaline batteries last longer than
nickel-cadmium batteries, cost less and are better for the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   When investing in a quality drill, shop around and look for
sales _ drill sales are often very competitive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 1349EDT &QL; 
