<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-CANCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN SEEK TO CREATE AWARENESS, RISKS OF LYMPHATIC CONDITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ After Barbara Smith had her right breast removed
two years ago, she hoped the worst of her battle with cancer was
over.
</P>
<P>
   Then in June, her right hand and arm swelled to twice their
normal size.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was upset,'' said Smith, a retired New York state worker.
``Very upset. It occurred to me it was related to the surgery and I
thought, `Oh dear, what do I have now?'''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who lives in suburban Albany, was diagnosed with
lymphedema, a chronic condition caused by damage to the lymphatic
system, sometimes as a result of breast cancer surgery, radiation,
infection or trauma. Other people are born with the problem because
of missing or impaired lymphatic vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us take these vessels for granted _ the waste removal
system for our body tissues. They remove excess proteins, fats,
water and cell debris.
</P>
<P>
   Lymphedema occurs because of a malfunction in this system. Fluid
collects in the problem area with no place to go. Left untreated,
it can lead to deformities in skin appearance, infection and even
another form of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it develops, it is, unfortunately, a frustrating thing to
handle,'' said Dr. David Mastrianni, an oncologist at Albany
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   There's no easy cure for a condition estimated to affect some
100 million people worldwide. The National Lymphedema Network, a
nonprofit organization based in San Francisco (415-921-3186),
estimates that it affects 15 percent to 25 percent of breast cancer
survivors who have had some of their lymph nodes removed or who
have undergone radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Mastrianni said progress is being made in reducing the incidence
and severity of lymphedema because surgeons typically remove fewer
lymph nodes than they used to.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates say, however that too many women still aren't aware of
the risk of lymphedema or of ways to reduce that risk. For example,
women who have had breast cancer treatment should never allow an
injection, IV or blood pressure check on the at-risk arm.
</P>
<P>
   They should also avoid activities like raking or heavy lifting
and anything that can lead to an infection, including manicures.
While doing housework or gardening, the recommendation is to wear
gloves. The National Lymphedema Network sells a special bracelet
that women can wear to alert medical personnel to the potential
problem.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to live with lymphedema, with proper treatment.
The problem for many women is finding the approach that works best.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lymphatic system is so complicated,'' said Michele N.
Keleher, an Albany-area physical therapist who practices a manual
massage technique known as Vodder, after the Danish physician who
developed it. ``Every person is different.''
</P>
<P>
   Keleher believes too little attention has been paid to
lymphedema by health professionals and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a condition we cure. It's maintained. People need
to follow it for the rest of their lives,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Keleher supports efforts by the National Lymphedema Network and
other groups to implement national standards for the certification
of therapists and to expand insurance coverage for lymphedema
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who do this need to know what they're doing,'' Keleher
said of the manual massage techniques. ``You have to know where to
move the fluid, it's just not moving against the tissue.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 61, said massage has helped keep her lymphedema under
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it first happened it was devastating. It kind of brought
back the impact of being diagnosed with breast cancer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way we're going to get proper insurance coverage and
the proper attention of the medical community is if this nasty
little secret is out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
