r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAREER-MOVES-HNS &LR;      09-29 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-MOVES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUITTING A JOB CAN MAKE SENSE, BUT DO SOME HOMEWORK FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This might well qualify as the last thing a
career counselor would ever tell you, but here goes. In an ideal
world, you ought to just up and quit a job at least once in your
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I've heard the horror stories about people who have quit or
gotten laid off and then have been out of work for months or even
years, but I'd bet there are a lot more who quietly struggle for
years because they're afraid to just quit. It's like plane crashes
and car crashes: Plane crashes make headlines, but car crashes kill
more people.
</P>
<P>
   If you've never lost a job, unemployment is your bogeyman; you
don't know what it looks like, but it scares you _ maybe even
leaves you paralyzed with fear. On the other hand, if you've
already lost a job and moved on, unemployment is a Stephen King
novel; you're scared, but you also might be exhilarated.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean you should take quitting lightly. Career
counselors are right: The best way to get a job is to already have
a job. But if you're miserable or even just plain bored out of your
gourd, plunging into unemployment might be the smartest move you
could ever make. Here are some questions to consider before you
make the move:
</P>
<P>
   WHAT EXACTLY IS WRONG WITH YOUR CURRENT JOB?
</P>
<P>
   Make sure you've at least tried to squeeze the most out of your
employer that you can. If your pay is too low, ask for a raise. If
traffic is killing you, ask about flex time or telecommuting. If
your supervisor is a jerk, ask to be transferred.
</P>
<P>
   These tips ought to be obvious, but people often are reluctant
to speak up. Sometimes they'll conclude that a job is a dead end,
for example, when a little skill and creativity could make it
better.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't pinpoint what's wrong, you won't be able to move
forward effectively. Take a week off to think about it if you need
to, but make sure you know exactly what is wrong and why it can't
be fixed before you quit. Otherwise you're liable to wind up in the
same situation in your next job.
</P>
<P>
   ARE YOU BEING REALISTIC?
</P>
<P>
   If your workload has increased because your company has
downsized, it could be because competition has gotten tougher in
your industry. If your competitors are struggling just as much and
you're not willing to change industries, you might not find
anything better.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the job prospects in your field. Do you have the skills
that are in demand? What parts of your resume make you stand out?
Are people your age being discriminated against?
</P>
<P>
   If you're unhappy with your life, make sure you're not unfairly
blaming all your problems on your job. Talk with friends or get
counseling if you need help sorting it out.
</P>
<P>
   WILL IT DO MORE HARM THAN GOOD IF YOU STAY?
</P>
<P>
   If the stress is killing you, of course, then get out. But you
also should leave if you find yourself lashing out at friends,
family members or colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The best tool any job hunter can have is a good network. If you
turn into a jerk and lose your biggest fans, your hunt will be a
lot more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Other damage can happen if you get lazy. If you start going
through the motions and stop building skills, your reputation at
work and your job hunting prospects could wither away.
</P>
<P>
   Companies have reputations, too, of course. If people in your
industry have started looking down at your company, find out
whether your reputation will suffer if you don't leave quickly.
</P>
<P>
   WILL QUITTING MAKE YOU A BETTER JOB HUNTER?
</P>
<P>
   This just in: People are not always hired on the basis of merit.
The energy you put into the job search makes a huge difference.
</P>
<P>
   If your job is so demanding that you don't have the time or
energy to network, research companies and aggressively pursue
openings, maybe your prospects will be better if you quit. If the
people who are moving up in your field have master's degrees and
you don't, quitting your job to go back to school could pay off in
the long run.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT WILL YOU DO IF YOU'RE UNEMPLOYED FOR SIX MONTHS?
</P>
<P>
   One of the most dangerous things for any job hunter is a long
gap in your resume, past or present. And, of course, there's that
little thing called poverty.
</P>
<P>
   If you're living paycheck to paycheck, don't even think about
quitting unless you have something immediate to fall back on. You
don't want to take your next job out of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Assume that you will be unemployed for months. Do employers in
your industry use independent contractors? Do they hire temporary
employees and make the best ones permanent? Are there classes you
can take to expand your skills? Do you have the skill and desire to
start your own business?
</P>
<P>
   Know these things before you quit. Don't wait until you've been
out of work for two months to figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   Quitting a job can be one of the smartest career moves you'll
ever make _ or one of the dumbest. Like most aspects of job
hunting, it depends a lot on doing your homework.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
