<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-SPORTSCASTERS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN SPORTS REPORTERS CRASH AN ALL-BOYS CLUB _ AND EXCEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PETE DOUGHERTY  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In their day, George Halas and Vince Lombardi
wouldn't have bought into it. There are women in the National
Football League. They aren't players, of course, but some of them
have become as well known as Bronco Nagurski and Paul Hornung ever
were.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of women sportscasters covering the NFL isn't a
novelty anymore. All four TV networks holding NFL rights have at
least one woman in a prominent broadcast role, and not a Phyllis
George- or Jayne Kennedy-type asking athletes how they met their
wives.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, most of them are credible sources of information.
The days when viewers cast a skeptical eye on any woman talking
sports, although not gone, are fading away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am still surprised when people say, `Boy, you're a woman
working in sports, in the NFL,''' said Michele Tafoya, a sideline
reporter for CBS. ``This is nothing new. As long as you go in that
you're no different from any other reporter, you're going to be
treated like you're not different from any other reporter. That's
what my goal has always been.''
</P>
<P>
   Women are closer to that goal than ever, but it has been a long
road.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy and George, both of whom showed up on NFL pregame shows
as feature reporters, were among the first, but they weren't
necessarily role models.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody remembers Phyllis George, but it never occurred to
me I could do that better,'' ESPN's Andrea Kremer said. ``I never
viewed her as any more than window dressing. I don't mean that as a
putdown, but she was a female person. She was going to ask about
the recipes and do a lot of the soft stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Genuine credibility for women sportscasters didn't arrive until
reporters such as Gayle Gardner, a former ESPN ``SportsCenter''
anchor who is out of the business, and Lesley Visser, currently the
sideline reporter for ABC's ``Monday Night Football,'' filled major
roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lesley's going to kill me, but Lesley Visser had my dream
job,'' said Pam Oliver, 37, an NFL reporter for Fox. ``I remember
watching her, she did a lot of Final Fours, and CBS had the NFC at
that time. She was really one of the early people. I never really
got into Jayne Kennedy and Phyllis George.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started in 1974, there were only four woman sports
writers in the country,'' said Visser, 44, who broke in with the
Boston Globe. ``We were the pioneers, but when you're young you're
kind of protected by your innocence. You're not really aware of
what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the idea of a woman dispensing information about an
all-male activity is disturbing to portions of the audience, which
remains dominated by men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be the first person to admit,'' said Bonnie Bernstein,
recently lured away from ESPN by CBS, ``when I see a woman on the
air, I'm listening to what she says, to make sure her terminology
is correct, her pronunciation of the names is correct, that she's
hitting on the most important points of a particular game.''
</P>
<P>
   As their numbers and resumes grew, women became more accepted in
their sports roles. A lot of the credit goes to the foundation set
by people such as Gardner and Visser, but those in prominent roles,
like any good reporter, have worked at their craft.
</P>
<P>
   They would all like to be known as reporters who happen to be
women, not woman reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting there,'' Bernstein said. ``It's kind of hard at
times because I do stick out. My hair's a little longer than most
people's. Most guys don't wear skirts unless you're Dennis Rodman.
Aesthetically, at times, it's hard not to know the difference, but
if I'm in a locker room, I'd like to consider myself one of the
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be naive to say that there still is no double-standard,''
Tafoya said. ``Women are still much more highly scrutinized than
men in general. I don't think it's as much as it used to be. Now
it's a matter of how you do your job. It's not, `Hey, let's add a
little swivel to our telecast and put a woman on.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kremer, 39, began as a sports editor in suburban Philadelphia,
worked at NFL Films for six years before joining ESPN in 1989.
Bernstein, at 28 the youngest of the current women NFL reporters,
is a former University of Maryland gymnastics All-American who was
a sports anchor in Reno, Nev., before joining ESPN as a
``SportsCenter'' correspondent in 1995. CBS hired her in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best compliment I ever got was from someone I know who was
in the Packers' war room during the draft,'' Kremer said. ``He told
me that the TV was positioned so they could see it, but the only
time (general manager) Ron Wolff was paying attention was when I
came on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that's true, but if made me feel good. I've
had general managers and coaches come up to me and ask what's going
on. I always joke with them _ why are you asking me? _ but they say
they're in tune with their own teams, you're more wired than we
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Tafoya, 33, has been host of a sports-talk show in Charlotte,
worked as an analyst for North Carolina-Charlotte men's basketball
games and called play-by-play on WNBA games for Lifetime. She once
did play-by-play of an NCAA men's tournament game as an emergency
fill-in when Sean McDonough became ill.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Gender slowly is becoming less of a factor for network sports
assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing really to do with being a woman,'' said Oliver,
whose pre-Fox assignments included 10 years of news and sports
reporting for six stations scattered across the country. ``I
decided early on to take that pressure off myself. If you get into
this contest of trying to prove to the next guy that you know more
than he does about sports, it's usually quite brutal, and I just
didn't want to go that route.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaining acceptance by the athletes they cover is a little more
begrudging.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they admit it or not, most players watch a lot of
``SportsCenter,'' and therefore have seen a lot of Kremer, Visser,
Bernstein and the like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect their knowledge,'' said Kent Graham, an NFL
quarterback for seven years. ``They know what they're talking
about. They have the inside scoop on a lot of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Other players cling to the motto that you had to have been an
athlete to understand one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them never played, so she (Kremer) knows about as much
as a guy knows,'' said Howard Cross, in his 10th season as a tight
end for the New York Giants. ``One of the greatest personalities
they have on their show is Boomer (Chris Berman). Boomer never
played. He's funny. He makes up his own stuff. Joe Theismann
played, (Sterling) Sharpe played, these guys might have a different
spin on things. As the games keep evolving, they'll be struggling
to study film and keep up on the game themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's how people feel, it's fine,'' Kremer said. ``Being
an ex-player sure doesn't teach you how to ask a question, how to
communicate, how to write. That's what I am, a reporter, a sports
journalist. Players making the transition find what we do
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The job was made more difficult in 1990, when Lisa Olson, a
sports writer for the Boston Herald was sexually harassed by
several members of the New England Patriots. Olson filed suit
against six members of the organization, including tight end Zeke
Mowatt, wide receiver Michael Timpson and running back Robert
Perryman, but settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it helped women,'' said Kremer, who prefers to
call it the ``Zeke Mowatt incident'' rather than attach Olson's
name to it. ``I would never second-guess anything she did. I
haven't stood in her shoes. My instinct is you try to defuse
everything with humor, but there was nothing humorous about this.''
</P>
<P>
   For a woman reporter covering the NFL, it can be difficult to
establish professional relationships with the players. In other
words, they do get ``hit on'' occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I said that hadn't happened,'' Oliver said.
``That's where you must establish yourself. You're in this as a
professional thing, you're not there to get dates or exchange phone
numbers. You're there to cover a story or do a feature or whatever
your job entails.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of them, the love of what they do makes no obstacle too
high to overcome.``I've known since I was little that this was what
I wanted to do, and I was always told that it's going to be tough
on the way up,'' Bernstein said. ``There are going to people who
look at you with that critical eye and people who doubt that you
know what you're talking about. I've always expected that. I thrive
on that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
