<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE MICROSOFT FILE &QL; 
 &UR; Wendy Goldman Rohm (Times, $25.95)
</P>
<P>
   There is evil in the world, and its name is Bill Gates. That's
Rohm's book in a nutshell. It's allegedly about Gates' domination
of the computer industry, but Rohm doesn't restrict her disdainful
eye to his skill at Monopoly. ``Gates was a trickster, Hermes
incarnate,'' she writes. ``He liked stealing the fire of others,
his detractors said. According to his foes, he had no boundaries.
He was a predator, said the CEOs of scores of competing software
companies: an ill-kempt, socially inept, scrawny, insecure,
ruthless Lex Luthor.'' He also was prone to fits of rage, slunk
rather than walked, had bad table manners and a nasal voice, and
although he was one of the richest men in the world, he still had
the heart of a nerd. Mixed with Rohm's reporting on Gates'
predatory business tactics are strange passages that sound as if
they were meant to create atmosphere. Here she describes Gates on a
flight to Australia: ``Sleeping, a low hum in the chest, skin
reddened by sun, head tight, seams of the skull traced like an
etching across the crown taut with the monotony of time. It seemed
he'd traveled farther than his 39 years. Feet crossed at the
ankles, lower lip slack as if having given up: all having been
spoken.'' Did you get that? If you hate Bill Gates and can stand
some literary emoting, this one's for you. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; HARVEST SON &QL; 
 &UR; David Mas Masumoto (Norton, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Masumoto, a farmer of peaches and grapes in
California's San Joaquin Valley, wrote a lovely book called
``Epitaph for a Peach.'' It was a record of a year on his family's
farm and a lament over his struggles to market his Sun Crest
peaches, which were juicy and wonderful _ just what peaches were
meant to be _ but didn't sell as well as the flawless-looking
variety that chain stores stocked. It wasn't a bestseller but got
lots of play in the California papers and a few magazines. Now
Masumoto has written a memoir of his experiences as a
third-generation Japanese-American on the family farm. It's a story
of struggle that breeds connection to the land, of the injustices
inflicted upon the Japanese during World War II, of family and the
pleasures of planting and growing. The figure on the cover is
``hito,'' which means person. A fellow farmer explains for
Masumoto: ``You know `hito,' written in two strokes. A long one
with the other holdin' it up. A farmer can't stand alone, has to
lean against someone. Today that's the way it is.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; FAMILY OUTING &QL; 
 &UR; Chastity Bono (Little, Brown, $24)
</P>
<P>
   When she was 17, Bono told her father that she was gay. Sonny
Bono was immediately supportive. The following year she told her
mother, and it wasn't so easy. Cher's reaction mirrored that of
many parents who are initially frantic with guilt and a deep sense
of responsibility. What followed was a long road to understanding
for mother and daughter. It goes without saying that Chastity Bono
could have written a flashier book full of recrimination and sales
potential. Instead she has written an evenhanded account of her
experience coming out as a lesbian and has included the stories of
others who faced similar problems in less limelight. Her book is
spare and straightforward, without ego or flamboyance. Her obvious
purpose is not to find some emotional turning point in her own life
_ she has done that already _ but to help others who are still in
turmoil. It's a generous gesture in a book that could have been far
less. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR &QL; 
 &UR; Thomas J. Stanley, William D. Danko (Pocket, $14)
</P>
<P>
   New in paperback is the book that probably made its authors
millionaires after it landed on the New York Times bestseller list
and did not budge for more than two years. The authors spent two
decades studying how people become wealthy and came up with a
profile of the prototypical American millionaire. He is a
57-year-old male, married once, with three children. He is a
tightwad, and his wife is a meticulous budgeter who uses coupons at
the grocery story. He owns, seldom leases, an American-made car
that is not the current model. His neighbors make considerably less
than he does. He is self-made and vaguely sexist _ he did not
inherit money from his parents, and while he's willing to help his
daughters financially, he expects his sons to succeed without
subsidies from him. Sound like anyone you know? Start saving, and
their next book might be about you. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; COYOTE IN THE MAZE &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Peter Quigley (University of Utah, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   If you are a self-respecting admirer of the late Ed Abbey, you
have to squirm over the proposition: This is an anthology of
literary criticism inspired, writes Quigley, ``by the wholesale
dismissal of Edward Abbey in the arena of `serious' scholarship.''
In other words, Abbey's environmental writings have been overlooked
by scholars of American literature, and Quigley intends to save the
day. Here then is a collection of essays with titles such as ``The
Politics of Leisure: `Industrial Tourism' in Edward Abbey's `Desert
Solitaire' ''; ``Nietzschean Themes in the Works of Edward Abbey'';
``Edward Abbey's Inadvertent Postmodernism: Theory, Autobiography
and Politics''; and Quigley's own contribution, ``The Politics and
Aesthetics of a Hopeful Anarchism: Edward Abbey's Postmodern
`Angelic Demonology.' '' We wish you luck and intellectual satiety.
Quigley teaches at Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University in
Prescott. Ariz. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Anne Stephenson can be reached at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
