r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDSBOOKS-AZR &LR;      09-29 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDSBOOKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLENTY OF GEMS FOR KIDS TO READ THIS FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fall is finally here, and with it come some seasonal books.
</P>
<P>
   In this month's offerings are tales about animals preparing for
the winter and a cute pig celebrating Halloween with real monsters,
who aren't too scary once you get to know them.
</P>
<P>
   Older kids will enjoy a book about spaceships and a trilogy
based on the childhood of Merlin the wizard. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; I HEARD A LITTLE BAA &QL; 
 &UR; Elizabeth MacLeod, illustrated by Louise Phillips (Kids Can Press,
$7.95)
</P>
<P>
   With rhyming text and simple, colorful illustrations, this book
introduces very young children to the sounds and sights of a sheep,
bear, cat, mouse, snake, dog, bee, pig and _ best of all _ a kid
like them. A teddy bear on one page delivers the clue about which
creature lies behind the next foldout page. Sturdy pages for little
hands. For infants to age 3. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TODAY I FEEL SILLY &QL; 
 &UR; Jamie Lee Curtis, illustrated by Laura Cornell (HarperCollins,
$15.95)
</P>
<P>
   (Begin itals) Today I feel silly. Mom says it's the heat. I put
rouge on the cat and gloves on my feet . . .
</P>
<P>
   Today I am angry. You'd better stay clear. My face is all
pinched and red ear to ear . . . (End itals)
</P>
<P>
   This book will help kids identify and label emotions that
surface in common experiences of childhood, like the thrill of a
dance recital, the sadness of a strained friendship, the loneliness
that comes when Mom's working late and Dad's sick with the flu. A
mood wheel at the end of the book lets readers finish the story by
choosing how they feel.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, a self-described moody actor, and Cornell, who confesses
to ``closet moods,'' have teamed up to deliver this terrific sequel
to ``Tell Me Again About the Night I Was Born.'' For ages 3-7. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MISS BINDERGARTEN CELEBRATES THE 100TH DAY OF KINDERGARTEN &QL; 
 &UR; Joseph Slate, illustrated by Ashley Wolff ($15.99, Dutton)
</P>
<P>
   Miss Bindergarten, who sports a cute little tail and floppy
ears, leads her animal students in getting ready for the milestone
100th day of kindergarten. While the teacher shops, makes newspaper
hats and counts 100 blocks, her students collect 100 polka dots,
fly kites, paint posters, stick stickers, sort crayons and assemble
their projects for the day.
</P>
<P>
   As the activities unfold on brightly illustrated pages, young
readers are learning how to count and say the alphabet. This is
ideal preparation for celebrating the big day at your school! For
ages 4-7. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; GRACIE'S BIG SURPRISE &QL; 
 &UR; Karen Ravn, illustrated by Cary Phillips (Hallmark, $12.95)
</P>
<P>
   Fall beckons in this richly hued story about animals preparing
for winter.
</P>
<P>
   Gracie Goose has the tough assignment of flying south. She'd
really rather stay with her friends. But as she makes the rounds
one day to visit them, Gracie feels rebuffed. Everyone seems very
busy with their preparations, with no time for her. What they're
really working on is a surprise. In the end, Gracie feels loved and
appreciated, and learns a lesson about trust before going wherever
geese go for the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark Storybook Friends is a new series developed in
conjunction with child-development experts. The books include
discussion guides to facilitate parent-child communication about
the themes. For ages 4-8. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; JOHN PIG'S HALLOWEEN &QL; 
 &UR; Jan Waldron, illustrated by David McPhail (Dutton, $15.99)
</P>
<P>
   It's Halloween, and all the trick-or-treat piggies step out for
the night with the exception of John Pig, who'd rather stay home
because he's feeling a bit queasy about the ghost and goblin thing.
</P>
<P>
   As he carves a jack-o'-lantern, a witch pays him a visit and
whips up a few treats that (begin itals) real (end itals) monsters
like to eat. She invites a few of her friends to the party, and
John has a swell time celebrating in the cozy comfort of home.
</P>
<P>
   After the monsters depart, John's friends return, and they
finish the leftover spiced apple juice, persimmon plum pie, pumpkin
supreme and orange-striped sundaes. The rhyming verse keeps the
story moving, and the illustrations convey the fun. For ages 4-8. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE BEST BOOK OF SPACESHIPS &QL; 
 &UR; Ian Graham (Kingfisher, $10.95)
</P>
<P>
   Space exploration, from rockets to shuttles to satellites, is
covered in this comprehensive summary.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrations and graphics demonstrate how the sophisticated
spacecraft work and itemize what goes into a spacesuit and how
astronauts live in space. (Ever wonder about the bathroom? The
answer is here.) A glossary defines key terms. Perfect reading for
the next generation, which someday may live on Mars. For ages
5-10. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; The Young Merlin Trilogy &QL; 
 &UR; Jane Yolen (Scholastic, $3.99 each)
</P>
<P>
   This three-part Arthurian fantasy traces how young Merlin,
abandoned as a child in a dark forest, developed his mystical
powers and became the most famous wizard of all time.
</P>
<P>
   In the first book, ``Passager,'' a falcon teaches the boy about
the evils of mankind. ``Hobby'' introduces the youth to a company
of traveling performers who try to exploit his power to see the
future. Finally, ``Merlin'' recounts how the boy meets his destiny
after falling in with the wodewose, wild folk who live in the
woods.
</P>
<P>
   Kids who enjoy fantasies will tear through this paperback
trilogy by Yolen, author of more than 150 books. For ages 8-12. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Beverly Medlyn can be contacted at bevmedlyn(at)aol.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 1405EDT &QL; 
