<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D'AMATO-SCHUMER FIGHT THE ONE TO WATCH IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The day before, he'd been in Rochester, pointing
out that even though he's from Brooklyn he has an uncle who
practices medicine there. Then he was in Utica, bathed in
television lights, in front of the house where his father had once
lived.
</P>
<P>
   Before he moved to Brooklyn 49 years ago, that is.
</P>
<P>
   And Monday, Rep. Charles E. Schumer was standing at a microphone
a an Albany hotel, addressing the annual meeting of the New York
Democratic Party. Vigorously, with spirited gestures, he was saying
what he has been saying every day for two solid weeks, since he won
the Democratic primary for U.S. Senate, and what he plans to repeat
ceaselessly until the general election on Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been there too long,'' Schumer was saying, ``and you
can't trust Al D'Amato to do the right thing for New York.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the message _ the heart of it, anyway. Schumer talks
about his desire to make tuition payments tax deductible. He talks
about his dream that every school be tethered to the Internet. He
talks about his role as a congressman in the federal crime bill. He
assails D'Amato for assailing teachers. But Schumer's essential
message is that Alfonse D'Amato is unworthy of trust and that his
three terms in the U.S. Senate are enough.
</P>
<P>
   Like all challengers for high public office, Schumer is well
aware of the value of boredom as a political ally. D'Amato has been
in for 18 years, and people eventually stopped watching ``MASH''
and ``Cheers,'' didn't they? It was only four years ago, after all,
that fickle New York voters decided that Mario's Cuomo's three
terms as governor were enough and threw him out because they were
tired of him. Schumer's attacks on D'Amato's trustworthiness grew
out of polling that shows high negative ratings for the senator,
which are nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   It's likely that no New York politician has ever been more
bitterly disliked by his opponents. D'Amato has a rare gift for
making enemies _ a talent shared by Bill Clinton, Richard Nixon and
Franklin Delano Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Love him or hate him, nobody will ever accuse D'Amato of
inspiring indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer was not supposed to be a problem. He wasn't even
supposed to win the primary election. Geraldine Ferraro started off
with a huge lead, and her best argument for her candidacy was that
the polls showed her stealing female and Italian-American votes
from the Republicans and beating D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, those same polls showed D'Amato whomping Schumer. A
Jewish guy from the five boroughs faces a built-in disadvantage in
New York when he takes on an Italian American from the suburbs.
That's the reality of ethnic voting in a state where one in three
voters has an Italian surname.
</P>
<P>
   Then a strange thing happened _ two strange things, actually.
One, Schumer beat Ferraro. And two, the first polls after the
primary showed him and D'Amato in a statistical dead heat. Most
significant, the undecided vote was minuscule.
</P>
<P>
   So, in a contest like that, you have to go after your opponent's
less committed supporters. You have to offer them a reason to
dislike the other guy more than they dislike you. That means
running not just on your record and your ideas but also on the
proposition that the other guy is a worthless bum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters are on to his game,'' Schumer was saying into the mike
the other day. ``They've heard it all before.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with this approach is that D'Amato has the fighting
instincts of a wolverine. This is the kind of race he always has
had to run. The governor's race looks like a formality for
incumbent George Pataki, but this U.S. Senate contest is close.
It's already mean and it'll get meaner yet.
</P>
<P>
   Which means that, in New York, this is where the show is in this
election year.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
