</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDSBOOK-OATES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOYCE CAROL OATES GIVES CHILDREN AN ODE TO BELOVED CAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joyce Carol Oates, author of more than 30 novels, 20 short-story
collections and eight books of poetry, has penned her first
children's book, a tale about an adventurous cat named Muffin who
likes watermelon, lettuce, peanut butter and rye crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Based on her real-life cat and the 4-year-old daughter of the
book's editor, ``Come Meet Muffin!'' is a guaranteed hit for
families with cats. However, the underlying themes of friendship
and getting lost and returning home to the people who love you have
universal appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Muffin is an animal friend,'' Oates says in a phone interview.
``We have emotional relationships with animals that are difficult
to write about in adult fiction. Animals have their own
personalities and emotions. The relationship between children and
animals is very beautiful. The two are almost on an equal plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a larger sense, this is a fairy tale in which a child
identifies with a lost animal who is not really lost. The cat says:
`I wasn't really lost, because my house is always there.' Then he
goes home and everybody is waiting for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The book begins with the Smith family discovering Muffin
abandoned on a country road _ just as Oates found her beloved cat.
The family takes him home, and Muffin soon proves to be a special
cat with unusual markings, peculiar culinary tastes and a gentle
but brave nature.
</P>
<P>
   One day, Muffin spots two fawns in the back yard. Remembering
what it was like to be without a mother, Muffin helps the fawns by
leading them back into the forest, where they are reunited with
their mother. Unfortunately, Muffin is so deep in the forest he
doesn't know how to find his way back.
</P>
<P>
   The ever-resourceful cat climbs a tall tree, spots his house,
then scampers down and runs back to his loving family. The family
is so glad to see him it lets him eat watermelon at the kitchen
table. Lily and Muffin snuggle together, and Muffin is the happiest
cat in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The naturalistic, soft oil paintings of illustrator Mark Graham
are true works of art, with warm scenes of the Smith household that
contrast with the snowy winter forest outside. Graham's drawings
perfectly capture the looks and spirits of Muffin and Lily, Oates
says.
</P>
<P>
   Why such a sweet story from Oates, the soft-spoken, ethereal
Princeton professor known for her painstaking exploration of dark
themes in adult literature?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very personal book,'' says Oates, 60. ``I would not
have written it except I was asked to by my friends, and I wanted
to do it for Lily, who loves cats. Muffin died a few years ago. He
was so sweet, just like the cat in the book. He sat on my lap and
helped me write for years. All these factors came together.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates' friends _ also known as Lily's parents _ are Daniel
Halpern, editor in chief of the Ecco Press, and his wife, attorney
Jeanne Wilmot Carter. The New Jersey publishing house plans to
launch a line of children's books. Oates' first offering costs $18
and is aimed at children ages 4 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   Oates, who doesn't have children, says she enjoys children's
literature because of its innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read so many books as a little girl,'' she says. ``I loved
looking at them again, reliving my childhood. They are natural
stories, often about friendship and love. They allow the child to
know he or she is loved and will be taken care of.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be a good idea for adults to go to a bookstore and
look at these books, take 10 minutes out of their day. It certainly
beats reading the latest news about President Clinton and Monica
Lewinsky.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
