<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON  &LR; (``w'' code) &UR;
</P>
<P>
   Lobby II &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOBBY-II (Washington) _ Second of two articles on lobbying: From
the nondescript headquarters of his Houston construction firm, Leo
E. Linbeck Jr., is masterminding a crusade to overturn the nation's
tax system. Once, someone like him might have hired some of
Washington's ``Gucci Gulch'' lobbyists to prowl the marble
corridors outside Congress's tax committees. But Linbeck, with
Texas-style audaciousness, wants to engineer a populist uprising.
While he and his fellow investors in ``Americans for Fair
Taxation'' are unusual in the scale of their ambition, their
methods have become commonplace as lobbying has undergone a
revolution over the past decade. Rarely now does a well-connected
Washington lobbyist work alone to persuade power brokers in
Congress. Instead, the lobbyist has become just one of many players
running full-fledged national campaigns designed to create a
``grass-roots'' groundswell in support, or more often in
opposition, to legislation before Congress. By Alison Mitchell.
(3700 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Clinton &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Developments in the Clinton
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JONES (Washington) _ The want-of-a-nail theory: Paula
Jones' original lawyer looks back to the near settlement that might
have gotten Clinton off the Monica-hook. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CANTON (Canton, Ohio) _ This town is a political
bellwether, a place that votes as America does for president, that
swung to the Republican presidents during the 1980s and to Clinton
in the 1990s, and from extensive interviewing here it is clear that
people still support the president. And while they are most
dramatically divided along party lines, they are also split in more
subtle ways. Just as there is a division between Americans living
inside and outside the Washington Beltway, there is a split here in
Stark County between community leaders and ordinary citizens. By
Michael Winerip.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SALON (Undated) _ The Washington Bureau chief of the
on-line magazine Salon is forced to resign after he criticizes
decision to run the story on Rep. Hyde's affair. By Felicity
Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other Washington &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-SAMPLING (Washington) _ Having lost two decisions in the
lower courts, the Clinton administration says that even if the
Supreme Court rules that sampling is illegal, the Census Bureau
will use it anyway, but only for use in distributing federal funds
and for states to use in redistricting. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-STUDENT-LOANS (Washington) _ The Senate gives final
approval to a bill making the terms of federal college loans more
generous. By John H. Cushman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-MILITARY (Washington) _ In an unusual appearance before
Congress, the Military Joint Chiefs of Staff testify jointly before
the Senate Armed Forces Committee. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-FRAUD (Washington) _ Federal officials take action
against fraud in mental health services for elderly under Medicare.
By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to decide whether
school districts are liable for sexual harassment committed by one
student against another. It also agrees to decide the
constitutionality of a California welfare law that limits welfare
benefits of new residents to what they would have gotten in their
old state. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-GEORGE (Mobile, Ala.) _ No longer a hurricane,
Tropical Storm Georges remained a menace to parts of the Gulf Coast
on Tuesday _ bringing rain, more rain and a threat of flooding and
tornadoes. Days will pass before some of the multitudes of evacuees
return to their homes. When they do, they may find scenes like
Beach Boulevard in Pascagoula, where the road was buckled, trees
had fallen on houses, columns were knocked over and oyster shells
had washed up on lawns. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-CASINOS (Biloxi, Miss.) _ The casinos along the Gulf
Coast got their first big taste of a hurricane. By B. Drummond
Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-DOMINICAN (Dateline to kum, Dominican Republic) _
Isolated villages where people are cut off from supplies and there
is danger of famine. By Raymond Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-BRADLEY (Los Angeles) _ Tom Bradley, former mayor of Los
Angeles and the first black to hold that office, has died at 80.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHWAY-GUARD-RAILS (Detroit) _ The Federal Highway
Administration is banning as of Thursday all further installations
of two popular kinds of guard rail along federally financed
highways, after determining that the guard rails cause high-riding
pickup trucks and other vehicles to roll over during tests. By
Keith Bradsher.
</P>
