<P>
   GERMNAY-FRANCE (Paris) _ Chancellor-elect Schroeder is to visit
President Chirac on Wednesday amid French anxiety about the future
relationship of the two coutries. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSENT (Beijing) _ Dissident intellectuals issue a
surprisingly harsh criticism of the government and Communist Party,
complaining that economic reforms are helping few people. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-ANWAR (Kuala Lumpur) _ After his ouster from power and
arrest, Anwar Ibrahim, the former deputy prime minister, appears in
court with bruises, saying that the police beat him. His two sodomy
accusers, who were convicted themselves, have withdrawn their
guilty pleas. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHAN-U.N. (United Nations) _ Who gets a U.N. seat? The Taliban
doesn't, so the Afghanistan speaker at General Assembly on Tuesday
represents a group that controls a tiny part of country. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
