   &UR; Other financial &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:15 p.m., the industrial average was
down 2 points, the Nasdaq index was down 3 points. Elsewhere,
prices fell 0.6 percent in Tokyo and 1.4 percent in Hong Kong. They
declined 2.1 percent in Frankfurt, 0.4 percent in London, 0.4
percent in Brazil and 0.8 percent in Mexico. On the American debt
market, the long bond was up 2/32 point at midday, with the yield
at 5.13 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND-BAILOUT (Undated) _ Developments in the Long-Term
Capital hedge fund bailout. By Peter Truell and Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   Related stories as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-REVAMP (Undated) _ The International Monetary Fund needs to
change. But how? Some economists say its role should be expanded;
others say the opposite. Still others think the key is to make the
IMF a more efficient organization. Ultimately, the disagreement
flows from one deep-seated dispute: whether countries as small as
Hong Kong or as large as Brazil should fix their currencies in
terms of dollars or let them float according to the vagaries of the
market. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   CENDANT-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Cendant restates its 1997 results
to show a net loss of $217.2 million instead of the net income it
reported earlier. By Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Undated) _ Harvard and the MIT are fighting
a demand by Microsoft for research gathered about Netscape by two
professors, saying that the demand threatens their First Amendment
rights and ability to conduct research. Separately, Microsoft
releases some of the evidence it will use in the pending antitrust
case to refute a Government charge that it tried illegally to carve
up Internet software sales in a 1995 meeting with Netscape. By
Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ECON (Shanghai) _ China takes steps that make it harder
for foreign companies to do business. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ Priceline, the Internet auction
service that lets travelers bid for flights, is planning to expand
into hotels; Swiss World Airways, a new carrier, has begun flying
between Newark and Geneva; a new train links Copenhagen
International Airport and downtown; other items. By Janet Piorko.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
