<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STARBURST-EARTH (Undated) _ NASA announces that a giant
burst of gamma and X-ray radiation hit Earth's ionosphere on Aug.
27. It caused no health problems, but it was the first time a
significant change in Earth's atmosphere has been traced to a
distant star. By John Noble Wiflord.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EARLIEST-CHINESE (Undated) _ Genetic studies that show the
first modern humans arrived in China about 60,000 years ago support
the theory that people first evolved in Africa, researchers say.
The study, published today in the Proceedings of the National
Academy of Sciences, casts more doubt on claims by some Chinese
researchers to an independent origin of modern humans in China. By
Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING &LR;  (``d'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEECEE-RICHARD (Washington) _ One of the most admired chefs in
the country, Michel Richard has come East from Los Angeles where
his restaurant, Citrus, is still very popular. His dream is to turn
Washington into a city known for its food. It's a tall order. But
with his remarkably creative aproach to recipes that produces pure,
clean flavors he may succeed where all others have failed. By
Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MICHAEL-JORDAN (New York) _ A restaurant review: Michael
Jordan and his partners, Penny and Peter Glazier, have done
something remarkable: They have invented a new kind of celebrity
restaurant. The partners have found a way to capitalize on Mr.
Jordan's fame without jeopardizing his dignity. And in the process
they have created New York's best-looking steakhouse. By Ruth
Reichl.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   LE-PEU-COGNAC (Undated) _ The name Le Peu means nothing to
cognac drinkers. Yet most cognac drinkers know it very well _ sort
of. This is not a paradox. For years, the dry, delicate cognac from
the Le Peu distillery has been an important part of Hennessey's
VSOP blend, but like all spirits sold by the distillers to the
cognac houses, it has labored in anonymity, lending its voice to
the chorus. But now, some of the cognac houses are now letting
their more talented singers perform solo. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SHORT-RIBS (New York) _ Why is it that some of the fanciest
chefs in town positively dote on short ribs? Maybe it's because
this unglamorous cut brings out the Henry Higgins in them. In the
right hands, and with enough care and patience, these steer ribs,
the ends of the prime ribs, which start out all toughness, show
their elegant and tender side. By Elaine Louie.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   FIGS (Undated) _ Figs, which are at the peak of their season
now, have a mysterious, deep taste that adds an unexpected richness
to stews and desserts. By Barbara Kafka.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The constant search for something new in
wine has brought us what? Domestic merlot, sangiovese and viognier,
all pale imitations of their European progenitors. There are
rieslings from California and Washington too, including a few
attractive ones. But might it be time for the real thing _ the
elegant, complex white wines from the Rheingau, the Mosel and the
Pfalz regions in Germany, and a few from Alsace, in France. These
rieslings are the best wines to have with food, more flexible than
any chardonnay or merlot. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
