<SLUG> BC-YIP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
SWITCHING IRAs CAN CUT TAX BURDEN 
 
By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Few investors can find anything good to say about the
recent carnage in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   But those of you who have converted your traditional Individual
Retirement Account to a Roth IRA have a chance to turn the market
swoon to your advantage.
</P>
<P>
   You do this by temporarily moving the money back to the
traditional IRA _ avoiding a potentially big capital gains tax bite
_ and then converting again to a Roth IRA.
</P>
<P>
   To understand what's going on, you have to remember two tax
rules that make the Roth IRA unique _ money pulled out of the
account is tax-free if you're at least age 59 1/2 and you've kept
the money in the account for at least five years.
</P>
<P>
   You pay tax on the money moved from a traditional IRA to a Roth,
excluding nondeductible contributions you've made.
</P>
<P>
   But this tax on the transfer can be reduced with a little IRA
sleight of hand.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how this works:
</P>
<P>
   Those who converted from a traditional IRA to a Roth IRA earlier
this year would have had to pay capital gains on the profits earned
on the account before the day of the transfer. Chances are the
market's tumble has pushed down the value of your IRA investments.
This means you are facing the ironic prospect of paying taxes on
profits that have melted away.
</P>
<P>
   By moving the money back into a traditional IRA before year-end,
you are basically telling the IRS ``never mind, that first transfer
never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   This reversal can be done the same day.
</P>
<P>
   After you've switched back to a traditional IRA, you have until
the end of this year only to convert it again to a Roth IRA and
take advantage of a special tax opportunity. This time around, the
tax bill is likely to be lower since the market has sunk so far
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be paying tax on the smaller value that the account has
decreased to,''  &UR; s &LR; aid Paul Mueller, a partner and certified public
accountant at Mann Frankfort Stein &AMP; Lipp.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if you looked at a Roth IRA earlier and decided the tax
hit on the transfer was too steep, things might look brighter now
with stocks down.
</P>
<P>
   You have an extra incentive to move quickly. If you convert back
to a Roth IRA this year only, you can spread your taxes on 1998
conversions over four years by counting the money converted as
income during that period.
</P>
<P>
   If you wait until next year or later to convert, you'll have to
pay your entire tax bill upfront for the year you converted.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say you converted a $100,000 traditional IRA in a stock
mutual fund this year to a Roth IRA. If you're in the 28 percent
tax bracket, you'd owe $7,000 (28 percent of $25,000, which is
one-fourth of $100,000) in taxes, which is the tax on one-fourth of
the converted amount.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the next three years, you'll have to include an
additional $25,000 in your taxable income and figure the additional
tax based on what your tax bracket is in those three years.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say the swoon in stocks has caused the value of your IRA
to drop to $80,000. You revert to a traditional IRA _ a move that
doesn't have a tax impact _ and then convert again to a Roth IRA.
</P>
<P>
   If you're in the 28 percent tax bracket, your tax for 1998 would
be $5,600 (28 percent of $20,000, which is one-fourth of $80,000)
and for each of the next three years, you would have to include an
additional $20,000 in income.
</P>
<P>
   The tax savings for 1998 would be $1,400 because you were going
to pay $7,000, but now you're paying $5,600. Similar savings would
also occur over the next three years, said Ralph Schroeder, a
certified financial planner and managing principal at Schroeder and
Associates in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to avoid all this confusion, the law now allows you
to choose to include the entire converted amount in your 1998
taxable income and pay the tax all at once.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the Internal Revenue Service doesn't have a rule
against using this tax-saving technique that it calls
``recharacterization,'' and there are no penalties to pay for doing
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no limits on how often you can do this and there are
no reasons you have to give to do this,'' said Steve Yost, IRS
spokesman in Houston. ``But if there's future guidance put in
place, it will not be retroactive.''
</P>
<P>
   While most investment companies say it's relatively simple to
undo a Roth IRA, don't ask them to do it over and over again. The
investment companies that handle IRA accounts don't savor the
paperwork and administrative costs created by repeated conversions.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Vanguard Group of mutual funds limits investors to
one reversal and reconversion for each Roth IRA they have.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
