<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RUSH IS ON FOR MILLENNIUM PLANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, when cruise lines began accepting refundable
deposits for millennium sailings, tens of thousands of potential
passengers rushed to ensure their participation in the biggest
parties ever at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that folks had no idea where ships were destined. Or
how much the celebrations would cost.
</P>
<P>
   Now that some of cruising's highest-ever tariffs are confirmed _
along with some lines' demand for a nonrefundable down payment
almost 1 1/2 years before sailings _ many travelers are looking to
make alternative plans.
</P>
<P>
   And so I sense an obligation.
</P>
<P>
   Not to the cruise lines: Their waiting lists are so extensive
that even at escalated prices, most will have no trouble filling
ships stationed all over the world _ even straddling the
international date line _ on New Year's Eve 1999. Some large lines
already have reaped a windfall on interest collected while holding
deposits.
</P>
<P>
   My concern is with travelers who now worry that they'll have no
place to party.
</P>
<P>
   Not to fret.
</P>
<P>
   Care to join a camel caravan to the Great Pyramids of Egypt? Tip
a glass of bubbly to a pod of humpback whales in Antarctica? Rent a
castle in Scotland or an entire island in Fiji? Or sample a special
Roman ``millennium menu'' said to be blessed _ no joshing _ by the
Pope: medallions of beef a la cardinal, Sistine Chapel mushrooms
and pilgrims pudding?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps instead of sailing around the world to commemorate the
start of a new millennium _ albeit a year early _ you'd prefer
flying?
</P>
<P>
   Or _ gulp! _ biking through 46 countries?
</P>
<P>
   Literally thousands of choices can boggle any traveler's mind.
And we aren't even celebrating in the right year; the millennium
doesn't officially occur until 2000 gives way to 2001. But that
will just provide a good excuse for a second round of festivities,
right?
</P>
<P>
   We're obviously eager to advance the calendar. But where to
start in finding the best trip to satisfy our druthers?
</P>
<P>
   Bookstore shelves already are stocked with millennium-related
guides. Among the best: ``New Year's Eve 1999: Millennium Mania''
(Open Road Publishing, $16.95) by Susan Jones and Catherine Jones
Juvan; and ``The Millennium: A Rough Guide to the Year 2000''
(Rough Guides, $8.95) by Nick Hanna.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of Internet sites also point the way to the best and most
outlandish planned activities. My favorite:
http://www.everything2000.com. It's comprehensive, fun to read, is
updated regularly and focuses on information rather than sales
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   All the major tour companies have planned myriad itineraries:
Through Abercrombie &AMP; Kent (Call 800-323-7308), we can welcome the
new millennium on safari in Kenya or waltzing in Vienna;
Butterfield &AMP; Robinson (800-678-1147) offers biking in India or
hiking in Provence; Country Walkers (800-464-9255) will arrange the
New Year's Eve companionship of elephants in Tanzania or giant
tortoises in the Galapagos Islands; Travcoa (800-992-2003) invites
us to dances in Istanbul, Rio de Janeiro or Monte Carlo; Maupintour
(800-255-4266) has scheduled 28 special millennium tours; and a
travel agent could spend all day detailing other options.
</P>
<P>
   Intrav (800-456-8100) will send us around the world by Concorde
jet. The price tag for its millennium bash: a measly $70,000. For
those on a tighter budget, TCS Expeditions (800-727-7477) offers a
three-week world tour aboard a Boeing 757 for $44,950.
</P>
<P>
   Or we could travel at a slightly slower pace. Indeed, my
favorite millennium travel offering _ discovered on the
``everything2000.com'' Web site _ is Odyssey 2000, sponsored by
Seattle-based Tim Kneeland &AMP; Associates. Beginning Jan. 1, 2000, in
Los Angeles, participants will pedal more than 20,000 miles in 366
days, visiting every continent except Antarctica The marathon
journey also will include 40,000 miles by airplane, up to 2,000
miles on trains and almost 800 miles aboard ferries.
</P>
<P>
   Each cycling day will average about 77 miles, with about two
days per week set aside for rest or other exploration. Cost is
$36,000. Promoters already have reached the 250-rider limit _ with
participants' ages ranging from 11 to 81 _ but, because of
anticipated attrition, are still accepting registrations; call
800-433-0528.
</P>
<P>
   I also learned from ``everything2000.com'' the distressing news
that the entire Pacific island of Tonga is sold out for the
millennium. Why? It boasts of being the first landfall west of the
dateline, thus the home of the ``first light'' of every new day.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be too disappointed, though. Several other islands,
especially Kiribati, are disputing Tonga's claim, arguing that the
dateline has moved. Maybe a determined travel agent can find a
grain of empty sand on Kiribati.
</P>
<P>
   At home time-wise _ or at least the home of Greenwich Mean Time
and the prime meridian just outside of London _ the world's largest
dome will open on New Year's Eve 1999 with a gala whose 35,000
attendees are expected to include Queen Elizabeth and Prince
Charles.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based Millennium Society is operating on an even
grander scale, promising the biggest global celebration ever. With
the Great Pyramids as a cornerstone, satellite links over a 24-hour
period also will include the Great Wall of China, the Taj Mahal,
the Acropolis, Red Square and the Eiffel Tower.
</P>
<P>
   Or we could join that camel caravan _ an Abercrombie &AMP; Kent
offering at the Pyramids _ and proceed to dinner in a Bedouin tent,
savor entertainment provided by dancing Arabian horses, then allow
a palm reader to project our future in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   One tip: If you are accustomed to toasting the new year, take
water or soda to the Pyramids. No alcohol is allowed on site.
</P>
<P>
   Too worldly? We'll soon discuss some of the most intriguing
millennium celebrations planned in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we could go ahead and confirm that cruise. I
understand Tony Bennett will perform in a Bon Voyage concert at Los
Angeles exclusively for guests on Silversea's Silver Cloud
millennium sailing. And travel agents can provide the scoop on all
the seafaring itineraries now.
</P>
<P>
   By land or sea, it looms as one happy New Year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
