<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WOMEN EARNING MORE, BUT SEEING CHILDREN LESS
 &HT;    With CENSUS-DATA.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The incomes of women have become an increasingly
important part of family budgets over the last quarter-century,
according to new Census Bureau data, but economic progress has come
at a cost: less time with children.
</P>
<P>
   Wives's incomes amounted to only 26.6 percent of their families'
household incomes in 1970, but made up 41.2 percent in 1996, the
latest year for which the Census Bureau has data.
</P>
<P>
   However, by 1996 more than 72 percent of women with children
under 18 were working in the paid labor force, compared to 47.4
percent in 1970. The increase was even sharper for women with
children under the age of 3, from 34.3 percent to 61.8 percent over
the same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly appears to be a change in family dynamics,''
Katharine Abraham, Commissioner of the U.S. Bureau of Labor
Statistics, said at a news briefing Tuesday. The session was held
to release a new Commerce Department book on U.S. income,
``Measuring 50 Years of Economic Change.''
</P>
<P>
   The book, as well as the economists and statisticians assembled
for the briefing, agreed that women joining the work force was the
most important income trend in the past 50 years. They were ``a
major factor'' in a 150 percent increase in the real median income
of married-couple families between 1947 and 1997, said Shirley
Smith, co-author of the book.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947, the median income of these families was $20,620 in 1997
dollars. But in 1997, with the number of women entering the paid
labor force having tripled, the median income of such families had
risen to $51,591.
</P>
<P>
   Although many women took part-time jobs in their initial forays
into the workplace, the new data show that since 1970, the
percentage of women working full time all year long has risen from
40.7 to 54.8.
</P>
<P>
   And since 1960, the earnings of these fully employed women has
risen 54 percent to $24,973. Though their incomes continue to lag
behind men's, the ratio of female to male earnings is currently at
an all-time high of 0.74, and nearly a quarter of wives now earn
more than their spouses.
</P>
<P>
   Women of all educational levels have experienced increases in
income since 1963, with college-educated women receiving the
highest hike, 53 percent, for a median income of $29,781. During
the same period, incomes declined for all men with less than a
college education. But college-educated men experienced a 22
percent hike, producing a $47,126 median income.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
