<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. DIPLOMACY CHANGES FORM, NOT SIZE IN POST COLD WAR
 &HT;    With EMBASSIES-FUTURE-$ADV04.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Oct. 4 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite the end of the Cold War, the U.S.
diplomatic presence abroad has not diminished, as new agencies send
more and more workers overseas. Here are data showing the trend:
</P>
<P>
   Personnel posted at diplomatic missions overseas:
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Affairs agencies (primarily the U.S. State Department):
</P>
<P>
   9,858 in the year 1988
</P>
<P>
   9,464 in the year 1992
</P>
<P>
   7,573 in the year 1998
</P>
<P>
   Domestic agency representatives:
</P>
<P>
   7,932 in the year 1988
</P>
<P>
   8,260 in the year 1992
</P>
<P>
   10,118 in the year 1998
</P>
<P>
   TOTALS:
</P>
<P>
   17,790 in 1988
</P>
<P>
   17,906 in 1992
</P>
<P>
   17,691 in 1998
</P>
<P>
   Source: U.S. General Accounting Office.
</P>
<P>
   Here are data on activities and funds spent by U.S. domestic
agencies, including the military, on overseas activities for 1998:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Defense Department (International aid including emergency
relief, peace-keeping in Bosnia and aid to former Soviet republics
to reduce risk of nuclear weapons proliferation): $5.5 billion
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Agriculture Department (Marketing assistance for sales of U.S.
goods and managing low-interest loans for the purchase of food from
U.S. farmers): $884 million
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Energy Department (nuclear safety programs): $566 million
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Commerce Department (programs to boost U.S. businesses
abroad): $251 million
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Environmental Protection Agency (monitoring international
environmental conditions): $163 million
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  All others, including Health and Human Services, Education,
Interior, Treasury and Justice departments: $244 million.
</P>
<P>
   Source: U.S. General Accounting Office.
</P>
