</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK VIEWS BUGS ON THE WINDSHIELD 
</HEADLINE>
 BOOK-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - Splat!
</P>
<P>
   ``Yuck.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of us, it doesn't really matter what kind of bug just
hit the windshield. We're busy with other things, like being
grossed out by the gooey mess.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Hostetler is a scientist, and scientists see things a
bit differently. Where most see gunk, Hostetler sees opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Those bug splats drew him like a moth to a flame, or a horsefly
to a Chevy grille. It led him to spend endless hours at Greyhound
Bus stations all over the country, studying thousands of bits of
mortal ooze and trying to identify what each one was before
becoming bus-borne road kill.
</P>
<P>
   And he wrote a book about it. Called ``That Gunk on Your Car,''
it's both a guidebook to identify those streaks on your windshield
and a fun look into the lives of insects.
</P>
<P>
   For Hostetler, 32, a zoologist and urban ecologist recently
arrived at Arizona State University, the book is also a way of
spreading the word.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole idea was to get people who would never pick up a book
about insects to pick up this,'' he said. ``As a scientist, I'm
interested in teaching people about the environment and the world
around them and getting reconnected with nature.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to express his belief that people should stop such
anti-nature activities as mowing lawns, which deprive bugs, birds
and other critters of habitat.
</P>
<P>
   So what initially may look like a collection of gross-out jokes
turns out to be an interesting and well-researched book about bugs,
especially the ones that are likely to be encountered on the
highway.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetler set out to make his viewpoints accessible to the
average person, especially children, by making the squished-bug
premise an entry point.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the book is a color section with illustrations that
show in high detail what 24 different insects look like before and
after their meeting with a fast-moving windshield. The captions
that accompany them are couched in a pseudo-scientific format.
</P>
<P>
   Though not for the feint of heart or the queasy of stomach, the
book certainly is informative. Such as the honeybee page, with a
well-drawn picture of a living bee and a not-so-nice picture of a
familiar-looking smear. A description of the windshield remains
reads, ``The Splat: A big white round blotch (approximately 10
millimeters in diameter) with yellow on the edges.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not too appetizing, but yes, informative.
</P>
<P>
   So how did Hostetler derive such a complete and apparently
accurate link between living bugs and windshield splats? That's
where the Greyhound buses come in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hung out at the Greyhound Bus stations, and as the buses
would come into the depot, I would have about five minutes to
inspect the splats on there,'' he said. ``You can imagine
passengers are getting off the bus and the bus driver's looking at
this guy with tweezers.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the flat front surface of the bus, when the insect hits,
most of the insect parts remain, and I could identify them that
way. I also had a camera and drawing pad, and I would draw the
splats, their color and size, so I could take them back to my lab
and identify them that way or have some of my colleagues identify
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Another way he'd identify splats was to drive his own car with a
net attached to the roof to catch the bugs after they hit the
windshield.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the net, I would hit something and say, `What the heck
was that?' and pull over to the side of the road to check the net,
and I'd know what the splat was.''
</P>
<P>
   In the rest of the book, Hostetler writes about the lives and
habits of each of the bug-splat subjects. The biological material
is written in simple terms, with occasional bouts of dry humor. So
you wind up with such headings as, ``Fun things to do with black
flies.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no real scientific merit to his work, Hostetler
concedes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strictly for educational purposes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He started researching bug splats while working on a doctoral
dissertation at the University of Florida in Gainesville. His
dissertation, which earned him a doctorate in zoology, was a study
of bird life in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The summer of '92, I traveled about 12,000 miles collecting
data on birds and bugs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetler approached a number of publishers with his
bug-splat-book idea, but with no luck. Finally, he published it
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Ten Speed Press in Berkeley, Calif., agreed to publish
Hostetler's books after small stories about the book were printed
in newspapers around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Helping him with the design and illustrations were Rebekah
McClean and Meryl Klein. McClean, then an undergraduate student in
biology illustration, drew the detailed pictures of the bugs and
their respective splats. Klein designed the book and drew
cartoon-bug graphics that appear throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetler and Klein are engaged to be married in October.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Hostetler appeared on ``The Tonight Show With Jay
Leno.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I was portrayed as an eccentric,'' Hostetler said.
``I brought live cockroaches onto the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's working on his next book, a follow-up to ``That Gunk
On Your Car'' and a little more to the point of his environmental
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``Why the Hell Should I Mow My Lawn?''?
</P>
<P>
   ``I now have 52 environmental, ecological and social reasons to
give up your lawn mower. Again, it's a humorous thing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 1534EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0292 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FROGROCK-AZR &LR;      09-29 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FROG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA TOWN ADOPTS ROCK AMPHIBIAN  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO HAS BEEN SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
 ROCK-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM LOWE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONGRESS, Ariz. _ Around these parts, Rose Mary Goodson has the
dubious distinction of being known as ``the lady who fell off the
frog.''
</P>
<P>
   She chuckles about the incident now, but it must have been
frightening at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Goodson fell more than 15 feet and landed on a rock pile.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't spill any of the paint,'' she said. ``Not a
drop.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, we're not talking about an ordinary frog here.
</P>
<P>
   No, indeedy, amphibian fans.
</P>
<P>
   This one weighs probably 60 tons and stands (or squats) more
than 16 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   And it's solid rock.
</P>
<P>
   The frog is a Congress landmark. It had existed in its natural
state from prehistoric times until about 1928, when it underwent a
wondrous metamorphosis from rock to art.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, it was nothing more than a huge boulder perched on a
hillside amid several other large rocks. Then along came Sara
Perkins, a homesteader's wife who observed that this particular
rock, when viewed from the proper angle, resembled a frog.
</P>
<P>
   She told her husband, Eli, about it, but he wasn't as much of a
visionary as his wife, so the story goes. He was also very busy
with his work as a newspaperman _ at various times, he owned both
``The Phoenix Gazette'' and ``The Wickenburg Sun'' _ and as a state
legislator. But he did suggest that a paint job would make the rock
look more like a frog. His wife and their two sons hauled three
large cans of paint and a ladder up the steep incline, and within
weeks:
</P>
<P>
   ``Voila!'' A rock became a frog.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Perkins and the boys gave the rock a coat of frog-green
paint on top, then added a white underbelly, black spots and such
other frog necessities as a mouth and eyes. It was an instant
tourist attraction. In those days, U.S. 89 was the main route
between Phoenix and Prescott, and the huge frog dominated the
skyline as the road passed through the desert community of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Sara kept the frog brightly painted for years, and when she grew
too old to take care of it, her son John took up the task. And when
the Perkins family left the area, the townspeople became the
unofficial Keepers of the Croaker.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Mary Goodson was acting in that capacity in 1994 when she
took the tumble that earned her a mild case of infamy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it was a terrible spill,'' she recalled during a recent
trek up to the frog. ``As you can see, you can't reach the top
without a ladder, so I had to drag one up here. I fell off one
evening and landed right here, on these rocks. But I only received
a small scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodson was 76 at the time. She had moved to Congress from South
Dakota in 1980 to expand her career as an artist. In 1995, she also
wrote and published ``The Story of Congress: Arizona's Premier Gold
Camp,'' an 80-page booklet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody else had ever written a history of Congress,'' she
explained, ``so I figured I'd better do it while I had the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The work has undergone two printings; Goodson says she has sold
more than 5,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   In her account of the frog's origins, she notes that there are
two graves nearby. William Miller, who lived in the area for many
years, often asked to be buried near the site. His wish was
fulfilled after his death on Jan. 19, 1940. The second grave is
occupied by his dog. The townspeople thought it fitting that the
two be buried next to each other. An unimposing white headstone
marks their joint grave.
</P>
<P>
   And now, there's a small metal plaque attached to the lower
extremities of the frog. It reads, ``Jerry (Frog) Owens 1995.''
Goodson said that Owens' ashes were scattered near the frog but
that nobody in Congress knows why.
</P>
<P>
   The frog has been painted twice since Goodson's tumble, both
times by George and Mavis Carter, who retired to Congress from the
Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it as a church project,'' George explained. ``The
Church of Latter-day Saints set aside a day for service hours.
Everybody else went to Wickenburg to clean up the cemetery, but we
decided to do something for Congress. That frog is important to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not an easy task, painting a 60-ton frog. First, there's
the barbed-wire fence that has to be scaled, a feat made even more
difficult when the scalers are lugging an extension ladder and
several buckets of paint. Then it's a rugged climb up to the
creature, and at the top, there are few places to anchor a ladder.
</P>
<P>
   The Carters had to accomplish the feat twice. Their first effort
was ruined by vandals who defaced the frog with spray paint. So
they painted it all over again.
</P>
<P>
   The frog is on the west side of U.S. 89 north of downtown
Congress. It's about a hoot 'n' a holler across the road from the
Arrowhead Cafe. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 1537EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
