<HEADER>
A0367 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      09-29 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A THREE-STAR PEASANT DISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chicken with vinegar is one of the great poultry dishes from the
area around Lyons, France, where the chickens are considered by
many to be the best in the world. The story is that the dish was
first popularized at La Mere Brazier, one of the Lyons restaurants
known as ``les bonnes meres.''
</P>
<P>
   There are not too many left, but those that remain continue two
traditions: They are run by women, and they are a step up from
bistros in ambiance, service and food.
</P>
<P>
   The great chef Paul Bocuse worked at La Mere Brazier in his
youth and learned how to prepare chicken with vinegar there. Some
years later, he showed considerable audacity by putting this
peasant dish on the menu of his Michelin three-star restaurant near
Lyons. Bocuse insisted that it was neither how much work nor the
cost of ingredients that determined the worthiness of a dish, but
how it tasted.
</P>
<P>
   He taught a generation of students how to prepare chicken in
vinegar, and one of them taught it to me. The variations are
numerous, but the piercing flavor of vinegar is so dominant that it
matters little whether you use shallots or garlic, thyme or
tarragon.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, chicken with vinegar is no longer on the menu at
either La Mere Brazier or the restaurant Paul Bocuse, perhaps
because it now seems too simple. But it remains notably good,
whether prepared with an embarrassment of butter, as taught by
Bocuse, or with contemporary restraint.
</P>
<P>
   I greatly reduce the quantity of fat, and while it is undeniable
that some of the sauce's silken texture is lost, so is the guilt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One technical note: Most wine vinegar sold in the United States
has an acidity level of 7 percent; many French vinegars are just 5
percent acidity. So it's best to cut strong vinegar with some
water, as I do here. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN WITH VINEGAR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 3-pound chicken, cut up for sauteing
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   \ cup minced shallots or scallions
</P>
<P>
   1 cup good red-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter (optional). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat the oven to 450 degrees. Set a large ovenproof
skillet over medium-high heat. Add oil; when it is hot, place
chicken in the skillet, skin side down. Cook undisturbed for about
5 minutes, or until chicken is nicely browned. Turn and cook 3
minutes on the other side. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place skillet in the oven. Cook 15 to 20 minutes, or until
almost done (juices will run clear, and there will be just a trace
of pink near the bone). Remove chicken to an ovenproof platter.
Place it in the oven; turn off the heat, and leave the door
slightly ajar.
</P>
<P>
   3. Pour all but 2 tablespoons of the cooking juices out of the
skillet (discard them). Place skillet over medium-high heat, and
add shallots; sprinkle them with a little salt and pepper, and
cook, stirring, until tender, about 2 minutes. Add vinegar, and
raise the heat to high. Cook a minute or two, or until the powerful
acrid smell has subsided somewhat. Add { cup water, and cook for
another 2 minutes, stirring, until the mixture is slightly reduced
and somewhat thickened. Stir in butter, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   4. Return the chicken and any accumulated juices to the skillet,
and turn the chicken in the sauce. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paul Bocuse's version: In Step 1, brown chicken in 7 tablespoons
butter. In Step 3, add 3 tablespoons butter to reduced sauce.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
