<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FED-RATES (Washington) _ In move to invigorate a sagging world
economy, the Federal Reserve Board cuts short-term interest rates
to 5.25 percent from 5.5 percent. It is the first reduction since
early 1996. By DAVID IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
agrees to an Israeli offer to yield 13 percent more land to the
Palestinians in the West Bank. Security concerns must still be
worked out, but there appears to be some movement toward a peaceful
agreement, the first progress in months in the stalled peace
process. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   HIV-PARTNERS (Washington) _ Supporters of a bill requiring
states to notify the sexual partners of HIV-positive people argue
that it would save lives, but opponents say it would deter
potentially infected people from seeking treatment. Among the
supporters are Reps. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y., and Dave Weldon, R-Fla.
Opponents include Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-SEX (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to hear
several cases for the new term that starts next week, including
whether schools have a responsibility to prevent students from
sexually harassing their peers. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHIER-AMERICANS (Washington) _ Americans are not only living
longer, they're living more healthfully, according to a new study
by the Rand Corporation. The survey shows that the proportion of
aged Americans able to do simple tasks for themselves is on the
rise. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ARAB-VILLAGE (Umm al-Fahm, Israel) _ The Israeli army's
latest attempt to expropriate land from Israel's Arab citizens
triggers more violence, including a car bomb that killed a Hamas
activist and wounded two other supporters of the Islamic militant
group. Israel earlier had sealed its borders with the West Bank and
Gaza Strip ahead of the Jewish holiday of Yom Kippur. By DEBORAH
HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   KOHL-CLINTON (Paris) _ Helmut Kohl's ouster as German chancellor
has left Europe without a leader and, paradoxically, further
strengthened President Clinton's international role at a time when
his domestic position has been undermined by the White House sex
scandal. A news analysis. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STORM-GEORGES (Pascagoula, Miss.) _ The remnant of Hurricane
Georges dumps heavy rains on coastal areas for the second straight
day as thousands of people remain in shelters due to widespread
flooding, wind damage and power outages. By TONY FREEMANTLE.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Even though Vice President Al Gore,
the president's loyal lieutenant, is still the Democrat to beat in
the 2000 presidential contest, three others are positioning
themselves to run as well. Do Sen. Bob Kerrey, former Sen. Bill
Bradley or House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt have a chance? By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-RANGERS (New York) _ The Texas Rangers open their
best-of-five playoff series tonight against the New York Yankees.
By DANNY ROBBINS.
</P>
<P>
   With: LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
