<HEADLINE>
TAKE ROSE CUTTINGS FROM FIRM STEMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: We are moving, and I would like to know how to take a cutting
from a rose bush we have enjoyed for many years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A: Some of the best advice I've gotten on rooting rose
cuttings came from rosarian Margaret Sharpe. A cutting, she says,
is simply a piece of stem about the size and length of a pencil
used to start a new rose.
</P>
<P>
   A cutting should be taken from wood that's not too soft and
green (as the newest growth is) or too old and gray. Look for firm,
green stems. Fall, winter and spring are good times to take
cuttings.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe says that roses root more quickly in moist sand than in
any other medium. You can start cuttings in a container of good
potting soil and sand or in the ground. If you prefer the ground,
she suggests using a hoe handle to make the hole; then insert the
cutting and add sand.
</P>
<P>
   A cutting should have at least five growth eyes, or joints. Take
cuttings long enough that you can discard the soft stem tip. Remove
all the leaves but the top ones. Trim the cutting back at the top
end to within 1/4 inch of the top eye. Cut the bottom end 1/4 inch
below the bottom eye.
</P>
<P>
   Some gardeners soak the cuttings overnight in willow water, a
solution shown by research to encourage root development.
</P>
<P>
   To make willow water, take cuttings from this year's growth on a
willow. Remove the foliage, cut switches into 1-inch pieces and
place them in a container. Pour boiling water over the cuttings and
steep overnight. Strain the willow water and place rose cuttings in
it, re-cutting the stems underwater so they'll absorb the liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Other gardeners skip the willow water and dip the cuttings in
commercial rooting hormone. Some do both, some neither.
</P>
<P>
   Plant each cutting so that three eyes will be in the hole and
two above the soil. Pat the soil firmly around the cuttings.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the bottom off a large plastic pop bottle and cover the
cuttings with the remaining portion. Or use a jar to create a
mini-greenhouse. Leave the cap off the plastic bottle to let air in
on warm days, or slip a rock under the jar for air.
</P>
<P>
   Place the cuttings in bright light, not in the sun or shade,
Sharpe advises. She places cuttings started in pots in dishes so
that she can water from the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The first leaves you see growing will be from the strength in
the stem, Sharpe says. When you see the second ones, you can
carefully transplant in the garden. Or wait a year and transplant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q: Because of lack of rain, my roses began to dry up even
though I watered every day. I also used rose food, compost manure
and, once in a while, Epsom salt. A smaller plot of hedge roses is
still there. Can I plant roses growing in pots and transplant them
into my garden? I was going to put compost manure in first and then
mulch after I plant them.
</P>
<P>
   A: Several gardeners did lose roses and other plants this
summer. I wonder if you, however, were actually giving your roses
too much water by doing so every day _ especially if you were
watering deeply. Roses like water _ 2 to 3 inches a week _ but not
wet feet.
</P>
<P>
   Or, on the other hand, if you only lightly sprinkled, the roots
were encouraged to rise to the top of the soil and were made more
susceptible to drying in the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Frequent watering will leach nutrients from the soil, but you
don't want to overfertilize. A monthly application of a granular
rose fertilizer during hot, dry times is adequate.
</P>
<P>
   I would suggest you have a soil test before adding any more
manure. You can get information on testing from your extension
office.
</P>
<P>
   You can plant container roses at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a plumeria about 7 feet tall. It has lots of branches
12 to 18 inches long, and I would like to take some cuttings and
replant them. How would I go about this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Late spring is an ideal time to propagate plumerias from tip
cuttings, but you could try it now. Tip cuttings can be at varying
lengths as long as there are 3 to 4 inches of firm, mature wood
that has turned gray. Cuts should be at 45-degree angles. Remove
the large leaves and let the cutting dry for three to five days.
Root in a pre-moistened, lightweight, porous medium.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have heard that some plants can clean indoor pollutants.
Can you name some?
</P>
<P>
   A: The gerbera daisy has proved in scientific tests to
effectively remove trichloroethylene from sources such as varnishes
and dry cleaning. The peace lily attacks those pollutants that
cause ``sick building syndrome.'' Spider plants absorb
formaldehyde, which is released from insulation, carpeting and
plywood.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why do people paint tree trunks white?
</P>
<P>
   A: The only reason I was ever given was to discourage pests.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have seven large, heavily mulched flower beds. Every
morning I inspect them, and a week ago I noticed that the verbena
in two beds were not as vibrant as they had been. Upon close
inspection literally thousands of white gnatlike insects began to
swarm. I sprayed with a pesticide. Unfortunately, all of the
flowering plants in those two beds declined. I pulled all the
affected plants and disposed of them. There are no signs of the
pest today.
</P>
<P>
   I believe the deep, twice-a-week watering coupled with the fact
the flowering plants in those two beds were dense, are reasons
these creatures were attracted. I feel deep watering once a week in
very hot, dry conditions is sufficient, especially since the beds
are heavily mulched.
</P>
<P>
   A: The flying white insects could be whiteflies, an often
persistent pest that can be discouraged with repeated hard sprays
of water from the garden hose. Aim under the leaves. Other weapons
are insecticidal soap, pyrethrin and yellow sticky traps.
</P>
<P>
   These pests suck plant juices and can give foliage a mottled or
yellow look or can cause death. They also emit a sticky substance
on the leaves, and sometimes sooty mold will grow on this. But
whatever your problem, your treatment must have worked. It is
possible that the pests were attracted to plants weakened by
overwatering. Verbena plants do like a soil that drains well and
one that is allowed to dry some between waterings.
</P>
<P>
   Good drainage, good air circulation and the correct light
exposure go a long way in ensuring plant health. Healthy plants
stand a better chance against insects and diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Because there are several factors that affect soil moisture
levels _ temperature, wind, soil type, amount of direct sunlight _
once-a-week deep watering may or may not be enough. And water
needs, of course, vary among plants. During the worst of this
summer's heat and drought, once a week was not enough in some areas
of my garden.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to tell if you're watering adequately is to use
your fingers to test soil moisture 6 inches down. An inch of water
will moisten a clay or loam soil 6 inches down. If your deep
watering moistens the soil to that depth, once a week may be
enough. Your plants will tell you if it's not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
