<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA -- CAWTR. Contra Costa County may get more than $6
million in water-related funding if President Clinton signs a
nearly $22 billion energy and water spending bill. The bulk of the
items would go for environmental protection: $3.74 million for the
cleanup of the Penn Mine site, $2.25 million for the Rock Slough
fish screen project and $250,000 for a study of the Delta Wetlands
Project. Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO -- SKAGGS/SCHAEFER. Project (Working.) Zaret
</P>
<P>
   -- COURTHOUSE. (Possible.) The Commerce State Justice
appropriations bill is expected to include money for the new Denver
Federal Courthouse and other Colorado projects when it comes out of
the conference committee chaired by Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell,
R-Colo. Zaret
</P>
<P>
   -- PARK. (Possible.) The battle over the Park Service using
helicopters to repair trails at Rocky Mountain National Park
continued Tuesday, when Sen. Wayne Allard, R-Colo., sent a letter
to the park superintendent encouraging them to ``show better
judgment.'' Zaret
</P>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT -- DEFEND. As expected, the Senate passed a defense
spending bill today that includes some increases for Connecticut's
defense contractors. The bill looks a lot like the authorization
bill passed last week. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA -- MAX. U.S. Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., has inserted a
provision into an anti-drug bill that would give authorities more
power to seize proceeds of illegal drug activity. (Brief.) Williams
</P>
<P>
   MAINE -- OUTLOK. A look at how the ongoing Clinton scandal has
dwarfed the agendas of Maine's congressional delegation, forcing
the lawmakers to go about their daily work realizing that almost
nothing matters as long as the scandal continues. ``When the news
is all Bill and Monica, and Ken and Linda, you can't save Social
Security,'' said Rep. Tom Allen, D-Portland. Kane
</P>
<P>
   NEVADA -- SPACE. Nevada is competing with 14 other states to be
the launching point for Lockheed Martin's new reusable shuttle. At
least 2,000 jobs would be created if Nevada is chosen to be the
home for the $3 billion-a-year program, said Sen. Harry Reid,
D-Nev. Preston
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- LIVESTOCK-WASTE. How would the proposed joint strategy
introduced last week by the USDA and EPA to manage livestock waste
differ from the regulations already in place in Ohio? Would it pose
a greater burden on livestock farmers? Would it effectively address
the waste problems threatening Ohio waterways? Hurt
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS -- WASHINGTON. On the surface, Washington seems consumed
with the Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation. But
Congress cannot grind to a halt while it ponders President
Clinton's future. A look at what else is going on in Washington
besides the Clinton scandal. Brown
</P>
<P>
   -- LANDTRUST. South Texas environmentalists received encouraging
news this week, as several land trust acquisitions that will be
announced Thursday are for the Lower Rio Grande Valley. (Working.)
Marlin
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN -- SENSENBRENNER. Revered in one committee and
slightly reviled in another, Rep. Jim Sensenbrenner has established
himself as a lawmaker who is able to build bipartisan support, but
is his own worst enemy when his abrasive personality gets in the
way. (Working.) Marlin
</P>
<P>
   -- BUSINESS. Some Wisconsin lawmakers are trying to stop the
government from entering a manufacturing enterprise that would
compete with one of the state's large employers. (Working.) Marlin
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
