<HEADLINE>
A VIETNAM STORY: LETTERS IN SEARCH OF A YOUNG COUPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Central time zone, call CONNIE WHITE at
1-800-444-0267. Or fax her at (816) 822-1444.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Pacific or Mountain time zones or in Latin
America, call OLIVIA VASQUEZ at (310) 996-0075. Or fax her at (310)
996-0089.
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   It was 1988. Romaine Possedi, a young woman, was diligently
cleaning out the garage of the home she'd just bought in Calumet
City, Ill., when she unearthed a bundle of letters written by a
husband to his wife in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Possedi wasn't sure how the letters got in that garage. The
address on the envelopes wasn't that of her new place in Calumet
City, but a house on the southeast side of Chicago. Perhaps the
couple _ or just the wife _ had moved from that locale to Cal City,
taking the letters along.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the letters were written, the husband was in
Vietnam; by the tone of the letters, it was obvious he missed his
wife terribly.
</P>
<P>
   Possedi wanted to find the people and return the letters. She
contacted the American Legion, she talked to the post office, she
asked her new neighbors if they remembered such a young couple once
living in her house. No one could help.
</P>
<P>
   She forgot about the letters, put them back in a box in the
garage.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, in the summer of 1998, Possedi was packing up to
move to Las Vegas when she again came upon the letters _ nearly 30
years after they were penned. She telephoned me with her story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder,'' Possedi said. ``Who are they? Would either one of
them like to have these letters? Was he killed in action? Or maybe
they divorced. ... Can you please help?''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not going to print the soldier's name _ it's a quite common
last name, undoubtedly shared by dozens if not hundreds of Vietnam
vets _ because I haven't yet been able to track the couple down.
For myriad reasons, one or both might not want their identities
revealed in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   However, I'm going to excerpt just a few passages from three of
the letters. Perhaps the author or his bride, or someone who once
read the letters, will recognize the words and contact the couple
to help clear up the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The handwriting was tough to read. Where I couldn't discern a
word, I indicated such with the term ``unclear word.''
</P>
<P>
   (ital) Dearest Darling:
</P>
<P>
   I love you more.
</P>
<P>
   I miss you more.
</P>
<P>
   I need you more.
</P>
<P>
   For darling I love you with all my heart.
</P>
<P>
   Boy was it hot today, about 112 degrees. It's hard to sleep at
night ... That night when we got off the (unclear word), about
three miles later it was hit, and nine guys were killed and four
hit bad...
</P>
<P>
   I hate this place. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Another letter, postmarked a few weeks later:
</P>
<P>
   (ital) Dearest Darling Queen:
</P>
<P>
   I just received my mail and was I happy, I received five letters
from you ... I feel so bad because I couldn't send you anything for
your birthday ...
</P>
<P>
   What do I need a winter jacket for, I got one, my good black
one. Why don't you take the money and not get me one but go and get
yourself a GOOD ONE, for you need one more than me. Please, for me.
</P>
<P>
   Well good night honey, I love you so very much.
</P>
<P>
   HURTS HURTS HURTS HURTS HURTS. XXX (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   The letters also talk about mundane things, like when the
soldier's wife will be buying a new car. And intimate things, like
the things they'll do once he gets home.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't get into details of what he's experiencing, but he
tries to tell her he's in another world: (ital) ``Boy it will be
hard for me when I get back to the USA. For it's hell over here.''
(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   And there are times when his words almost ache with quiet,
simple sincerity: (ital) ``Can you think of anything to do when I
get home? You might have to work that day...knowing how you cry I
better not come home (and then visit you) when you are at
work.''(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   The soldier and his wife are probably in their late 40s and
early 50s by now. If they've stayed together, they might have
children of their own who are about the age they were when these
letters were sent.
</P>
<P>
   Or they split up. Or he never came home. This could be evidence
of a great love story, or something that was shattered and
destroyed many years ago. No doubt it is a story reminiscent of
tens of thousands of others, in cases where people's lives were
interrupted by the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   One thing for certain: Once there was great love and yearning.
</P>
<P>
   Once a young soldier wrote letters to his ``Dearest Darling
Wife.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) can be heard on the
``Media Creatures'' show, which airs daily in Chicago from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. on WMVP-AM (1000) and appears Tuesday and Thursday at
7:55 a.m. on WFLD-TV's ``Fox Thing in the Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A daily columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, Roeper has also
written for TV Guide, Spy, Playboy, Chicago magazine and many other
publications, and has appeared as a guest on ``Nightline'' and
``Oprah.'') &LR;
