<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ON FOOD AND DINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Abbondanza in a Jar: Pasta Sauces With a Twist &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pasta sauce in a jar has been a pantry staple for decades, and
there seems no end to the new ones that are introduced every year.
Some recent additions are well worth keeping on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Boscovivo, an Italian truffle company, has produced a line, Le
Ricette di Caterina, referring, of course, to that Renaissance food
maven Catherine de' Medici. These imports are meaty, tomato-based,
Tuscan-style sauces.
</P>
<P>
   They are not made with the mingy bits of meat one often finds in
so-called meat sauces but are thick with wild boar, hare, duck or
venison. The wild boar _ cinghiale _ is my hands-down favorite.
Agata &AMP; Valentina, 1505 First Avenue (79th Street) in New York
City, carries this brand for $6.99 for a small jar, about five
ounces. It's plenty of sauce to dress two portions of pappardelle.
</P>
<P>
   The well-made Patsy's brand, from the Manhattan restaurant, now
has an amatriciana sauce, with bacon, prosciutto, tomatoes and
onions, a classic that originated in the town of Amatrice, near
Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Stock up on bucatini, the thick spaghetti usually paired with
amatriciana. And you'll need pecorino, not Parmesan, for grating.
The sauce is at Food Emporiums for $4.99 for 16 ounces and $8.99
for 32 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   Lidia's is a new line of sauces made according to the recipes of
Lidia Bastianich, the Manhattan chef and restaurateur. All are
tomato-based and well seasoned with a fresh, light taste, excellent
on ravioli or even to brush on fish.
</P>
<P>
   Simple tomato and basil, all'ortolana with vegetables, and
slightly sharper capricciosa are each $7.99 for 26 ounces at
Citarella, 2135 Broadway (75th Street) and 1313 Third Avenue (75th
Street). They are also sold at Kings Super Markets in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   From Spain comes Ferrer Catalonian-style fried-tomato sauce:
silken and ruddy, on the thin side but with great depth of complex,
nutty flavor, thanks to finely pulverized almonds and hazelnuts.
It's the perfect sauce for angel-hair pasta. At Fairway, 2127
Broadway (74th Street) and 2328 Twelfth Avenue (132nd Street), a
12-ounce jar is $2.49. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Luxe Italian Sandwiches &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Terramare, 152 East 79th Street, may have the look of a typical
sandwich shop and cafe, but this new branch of the original
Terramare, 22 East 65th Street, sells more than mozzarella and
tomatoes on focaccia.
</P>
<P>
   The menu includes luxurious combinations like truffled cheese
and ham; smoked tuna with tomatoes, and bresaola with arugula and
truffle oil, $5.50 to $7.75. And like its parent to the south, it
sells caviar, smoked fish and truffle products. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Ecce Panis Plans &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The original Ecce Panis bakery has closed and has been replaced
by a shop just a few doors north, at 1126 Third Avenue (66th
Street). There is also a new branch of Ecce Panis at 434 Avenue of
the Americas (10th Street), and in about a week another one is to
open at 5 World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   The chain has also introduced some new items, including a
decadent streusel-topped raisin bun ($1.75), dense low-fat spelt
bread ($8) and bread crumbs ($3 for 12 ounces) in three flavors:
rustic with salt and pepper, Tuscan with herbs and garlic, and
Provencal with garlic, herbs, salt and pepper. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Tasty Coffeecakes &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Buttery, moist, lightly spiced coffeecakes from My Grandma's
Coffee Cake of Boston are now being sold at several D'Agostino
supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   And there are two new flavors: excellent New England blueberry
made with maple syrup, and banana walnut. At some D'Agostino
markets, the original cinnamon with or without walnuts is $13.95;
the new flavors and the Granny Smith apple and golden raspberry
flavors are $15.95.
</P>
<P>
   They are available in Manhattan at 1031 First Avenue (56th
Street), 966 First Avenue (53d Street), 1233 Lexington Avenue (83rd
Street), 1074 Lexington Avenue (75th Street) and 790 Greenwich
Street (Bethune Street), and in Westchester County, N.Y., in the
Rye Brook Plaza, Rye Brook. They are also sold in Manhattan at
Oppenheimer Meats, 2606 Broadway (99th Street). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
