<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAD-COW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS DEVELOP TEST TO DETECT PROTEIN IN MAD COW DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A test for the renegade protein believed to
cause mad cow disease and its human counterpart has been developed
at the University of California at San Francisco, paving the way
for possible large-scale screening of blood, meat and other
products.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers, writing in the October issue of the journal Nature
Medicine, describe a relatively simple way to detect prions.
</P>
<P>
   Prions are the mutated proteins responsible for the outbreak of
the disease in the United Kingdom that led to panic and a ban on
exports of British beef. Prions also are believed to cause a human
illness, Cruetzfeldt-Jakob disease, in which holes like those in
sponges appear in the brain, leading to dementia and death.
</P>
<P>
   Prions can be infectious, but scientists believe they also can
arise spontaneously and from genetic mutations.
</P>
<P>
   Centeon Llc., a King of Prussia, Pa., company that helped
support the San Francisco research, owns the license for the
testing technology. A spokesman for the company said more
scientific work is needed before the test could become a commercial
product.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, the company intends to use it only to screen its own
blood plasma products, but it might collaborate with a diagnostic
testing company on other uses, such as for slaughterhouses or blood
banks that may want to test for the protein.
</P>
<P>
   There are no known cases of someone being infected with a prion
disease from infected blood.
</P>
<P>
   However, two dozen cases of human disease in the United Kingdom
are believed to be linked to eating tainted beef. At least another
61 cases worldwide were traced to a bad batch of brain tissue that
formed the basis of a product used in neurosurgery.
</P>
<P>
   Detecting the deadly protein has been frustrating because the
body's immune system doesn't manufacture antibodies that recognize
the mutant forms, which are folded to hide the part of the
structure that the immune system recognizes. Antibodies are the
typical way to screen for infectious agents.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, testing for prions meant taking samples from
suspected victims, transplanting the material into the brains of
lab animals and waiting to see if they develop the disease _ a
process that takes two to six months.
</P>
<P>
   The University of California at San Francisco test shows results
in about eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   First, an antibody is used to determine how much of the harmless
form of the protein in a tissue. Then a salt is added to the
solution, causing both the prion and the harmless protein to
unfold. The amount of protein in that solution is then measured. If
it is significantly more than the original amount, scientists know
the mutant form is also present.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds pretty obvious, but it took us a long time'' to
figure out all the steps, said Fred E. Cohen, part of the research
team led by Jiri Safar and Stanley B. Prusiner, who won the Nobel
Prize last year for his discovery of prions.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists also say they have further proof that there are
at least eight different strains of prions, all with the same
chemical structure but slightly different folding patterns.
</P>
<P>
   The different forms may represent different incubation periods
for the disease. It is known that some forms don't show up for many
years after infection.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed that the body's own clean-up system, which would
flush out the harmful protein, reacts in varying degrees to the
different forms. That suggests that scientists could develop
treatments for prion diseases by harnessing that natural cleaning
system, Cohen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 1632EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
