<SLUG> BC-HAVEHOLD-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOSTON BRIGHT SPOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ CBS will offer its best (``To Have &AMP; to Hold'')
and worst (``Maggie Winters'') new shows of the season tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ABC's newcomer, ``The Secret Lives of Men,'' is a
misnomer. If this is what these men are keeping secret, they must
lead pretty boring lives.
</P>
<P>
   The true battle of Wednesday nights on the new fall schedule is
yet to come. Next month, the WB and Fox duke it out for the
18-to-34-year-old audience.
</P>
<P>
   The WB is moving ``Dawson's Creek'' to take on ``Beverly Hills,
90210,'' which should have some renewed energy with the return of
Dylan McKay (Luke Perry) at 8 p.m. An hour later, classy drama
``Party of Five'' will be challenged by ``Charmed,'' a brand-new
show on the WB that features two former Fox stars _ Shannen Doherty
and Alyssa Milano.
</P>
<P>
   Those strong performances do not bode well for the weaker
offerings debuting tonight: &QL; 
TO HAVE &AMP; TO HOLD &QC;
</P>
<P>
   While the battle of the sexes is not exactly new ground on
television, it's the fresh take on the subject that makes ``To Have
&AMP; to Hold'' stand out.
</P>
<P>
   A romantic comedy about an Irish family in the Boston-area burg
of Dorchester, Mass., ``To Have &AMP; to Hold'' does a great job
exploring the dynamic of a close-knit family, the McGrails.
</P>
<P>
   The central characters in this Irish family are Annie Cornell
(Moira Kelly) and Sean McGrail (Jason Beghe). She is an earnest
public defender, and he is a Boston police detective. They agree on
nothing except their love for each other. But their arguments may
be the best part of the show, because, boy, do they know how to
make up.
</P>
<P>
   Sean has three brothers _ two cops and a firefighter, the latter
married to Annie's sister.
</P>
<P>
   These are not sanitized television types. They drink, they make
mistakes, they argue over who made the mistakes. The show, created
by promising television newcomer Joanne Waters, is well-written and
stocked with some extremely likable characters.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Annie wants to help free people who are arrested
and Sean wants them in jail is a major point of conflict. Their
differences promise to be fodder for plenty of head butting in the
weeks to come.
</P>
<P>
   Sean and Annie are married by the end of the first episode, and
they could be together _ fighting and making up _ for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   The show: ``To Have &AMP; to Hold.''
</P>
<P>
   What: A romantic comedy focusing on a public defender and a cop
that gives keen insight into family life, blue-collar Boston and
the differences between the sexes.
</P>
<P>
   The stars: Moira Kelly, Jason Beghe, Jason Wiles, Stephen Lee,
Stephen Largay, Fionnula Flanagan.
</P>
<P>
   Where: CBS (Channel 2).
</P>
<P>
   When: 9 p.m. Wednesdays.
</P>
<P>
   Our rating: 4 Stars. &QL; 
MAGGIE WINTERS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Faith Ford should have taken some time off between ``Murphy
Brown'' and her next television project, or at least held out for
something better than ``Maggie Winters.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who played Corky on ``Murphy Brown,'' comes back as Maggie
Winters, once voted ``The Girl Most Likely to Succeed'' at
Shelbyville (Ind.) High School. Maggie fails. Her marriage ends
because her husband cheated on her with her own dental hygenist,
and she decides to leave the big city and return home.
</P>
<P>
   There she's reunited with old friends, whom we find out were
``Most Likely to Breed,'' ``Most Likely to Snap,'' ``Big Man on
Campus'' and ``Most Likely to Have Actual Sex.''
</P>
<P>
   All of these people are suspended in adolescence, and it doesn't
take long for Maggie to fall into their foolish, buffoonish ways _
leading the ``Walk Like an Egyptian'' dance, gossiping about who
like-likes who. Her character is too fragile, too excitable, too
shrill.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows if Tom Wolfe was right when he said, ``You can't go
home again.'' All this show proves is that, if you do go home
again, don't make a TV series about it.
</P>
<P>
   The show: ``Maggie Winters.''
</P>
<P>
   What: The girl voted ``Most Likely to Succeed'' didn't and comes
back home to rejoin her friends, who are still acting like
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   The stars: Faith Ford, Shirley Knight, Jenny Robertson, Alex
Kapp Horner, Brian Haley, Clea Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Where: CBS (Channel 2).
</P>
<P>
   When: 8:30 p.m. Wednesdays.
</P>
<P>
   Our rating: 2 Stars. &QL; 
THE SECRET LIVES OF MEN &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Call me crazy, but I like my comedies to be funny. ``The Secret
Lives of Men'' isn't.
</P>
<P>
   The show is about three golfing buddies who are freshly divorced
and offer no more evidence why they would even be friends, let
alone spend seemingly every waking hour together. There is Andy
(Mitch Rouse), the goofy one; Phil (Brad Whitford), the bitterly
cynical one who claims he is nearly devoid of feelings; and Michael
(Peter Gallagher), the son of a mobster and one of the great
catches in New York who can't seem to find anyone he likes as much
as his ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   If they have any secrets worth telling, we don't find them out
in the pilot episode. They also don't say many funny things.
</P>
<P>
   This is an utterly disappointing program, much like the
similarly named ``Men Behaving Badly,'' which couldn't live up to
its title, either.
</P>
<P>
   The show: ``The Secret Lives of Men.''
</P>
<P>
   What: A comedy short on comedy about three divorced golfing
buddies.
</P>
<P>
   The stars: Brad Whitford, Peter Gallagher, Mitch Rouse,
Christine Dunford.
</P>
<P>
   Where: ABC (Channel 7).
</P>
<P>
   When: 9:30 p.m. Wednesdays.
</P>
<P>
   Our rating: 1 Star.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
