<SLUG> BC-TV-MAGGIE-515&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS' `MAGGIE': PLEASANT, CUTE AND FORGETTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wednesday night is the TV season in a pea pod. Three more new
series, none of them bad, all of them worthy of emphatic shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   The three are to be recorded as ``Maggie Winters'' (8:30 p.m. on
CBS), ``To Have and to Hold'' (9 p.m. on CBS) and ``The Secret
Lives of Men'' (9:30 p.m. on ABC).
</P>
<P>
   ``Maggie Winters'' is custom-built for Faith Ford, the former
Corky Sherwood of ``Murphy Brown.'' She's still button cute, and
she still has that flighty voice that wobbles like an amusement
park ride.
</P>
<P>
   (Wait. Still this, still that? What am I saying? Ford's been
gone from TV for, lo, these four months. She's supposed to be a
baritone now?)
</P>
<P>
   The show's premise is that her husband cheated with a dental
hygienist, so Maggie (Ford) bolts the city, returns to her Indiana
hometown and moves back in with her well-meaning but dim-bulbed
mother (Shirley Knight). Though she's 30-something, Maggie appears
destined to repeat the social life she knew in high school, and
mainly with the same people.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is peppy and likable almost to the endearing threshold,
Clea Lewis is a scene-stealer as a former classmate who's still
nursing a grudge against Maggie, and they have a sparkling scene
together Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, ``Maggie Winters'' seems ready to take its place as a
show that's as easy to forget as it is easy to watch. And when you
depend on ``The Nanny'' as a lead-in, well, there'll be a heap of
forgetting.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Have and to Hold'' is tethered even more perilously to
survival, with ``The Nanny'' (set ital)and(end ital) ``Maggie
Winters'' as lead-ins.
</P>
<P>
   It's a romantic comedic drama in which public defender Annie
Cornell (Moira Kelly) and Boston police detective Sean McGrail
(Jason Beghe) are headed to the altar after a fractious pit stop at
the bench. As in court, that is, because the two find themselves in
opposite corners of the criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Try not to violate any more constitutional rights while I'm
gone, or I'll slap you with a subpoena,'' she tells him, moments
after they were about to slap their bodies into something better
than a subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   Like several other series this fall _ it's a mini-trend _ ``To
Have and to Hold'' has something of an Irish Catholic flavor,
particularly in its neighborhood story lines and in Sean's
broad-brogued mother (Fionnula Flanagan). I'm not sure, but I'm
guessing Flanagan isn't Swedish.
</P>
<P>
   And like far too many shows this fall, ``To Have and to Hold''
consumes time painlessly but isn't quite all there. The script is
all right but not flashy, and the chemistry between Kelly and Beghe
is conspicuously active but not explosive.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly (``Twin Peaks: Fire Walk With Me'') is what's closest to
perfection about the show. She's alternately glamorous and earthy,
and all within the tight confines of one cohesive woman.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, this might have been a more interesting show with
Kelly's character alone. They'd have had to call it ``To Have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first thing to know about ABC's ``The Secret Lives of Men''
is that it's conceived, written and produced by a woman, Susan
Harris (``Soap,'' ``The Golden Girls'').
</P>
<P>
   The next thing to know is that it's based on a fallacy _ that
men have secret lives.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Harris for the vote of confidence. But plug in to
men's thoughts and you pretty much get a dull parade of sports
stats, absurd sexual fantasies, vacant lots and, sometimes,
ill-founded political biases.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and that all-important trump thought: Is my car broke? Face
it, anything beyond the basics is a gift.
</P>
<P>
   The golf course and a Manhattan restaurant are the hangouts for
Michael (Peter Gallagher), Phil (Brad Whitford) and Andy (Mitch
Rouse), three divorced males who seem to be pushing 40. And who
talk a lot; Harris' shows are always talkative.
</P>
<P>
   I'll give ``The Secret Lives of Men'' credit for stepping
outside the respective sitcom hells of the domestic comedy and the
office comedy, and for at least purporting to be (set
ital)about(end ital) something.
</P>
<P>
   But I just watched an episode, next week's, I think, which opens
with Phil's open admission of impotence, followed by Michael's
confession that he, too, sometimes tails southwest when he's aiming
for northeast.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to say a word about this mirthful topic and the
conversation in the show. No, sorry, two words: Fat chance. Men
might keep a few secrets, after all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
