<HEADER>
A0535 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MICHAEL-JORDAN-ART     09-29 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MICHAEL-JORDAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTAURANT REVIEW: ELEGANCE, NOT CLICHES, AT MICHAEL JORDAN'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By RUTH REICHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hamburger is absurd.
</P>
<P>
   The massive round of chopped prime sirloin rides an enormous
bun, looking more like an inflated basketball than anything a sane
person would try to bite into. Even Michael Jordan would be hard
pressed to eat it in a single sitting.
</P>
<P>
   But big food is exactly what you expect, the obvious cliche in a
restaurant named for probably the world's most famous sports
celebrity. There is, however, a surprise: It is the only cliche.
Everything else about Michael Jordan's the Steak House N.Y.C. plays
against type.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and his partners, Penny and Peter Glazier, have done
something remarkable: They have invented a new kind of celebrity
restaurant. At first you find yourself wending your way through the
obligatory souvenir shop with its T-shirts and steak knives, and it
seems like all the rest.
</P>
<P>
   But then you enter the dining room and realize that there are no
photographs of Jordan, no basketballs, no memorabilia of any kind.
The waiters approach, and their old-fashioned solicitude is not
what you expect from a sports-themed restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The menu tells the rest of the story: it is a straightforward
document offering serious food that is a far cry from what you find
at the All-Star Cafe or Mickey Mantle's. The partners have found a
way to capitalize on Jordan's fame without jeopardizing his
dignity. And in the process they have created New York's
best-looking steakhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan's is the first among the many restaurants that
will open in the newly refurbished Grand Central Terminal.
Expectations are high: the Ciprianis will open one establishment,
Matthew Kenney another and the owners of City Bakery, Caviarteria
and Dawat have signed on for smaller spaces. But this will be a
hard act to follow.
</P>
<P>
   The designer, David Rockwell, who is currently creating a theme
restaurant in Times Square for the magician David Copperfield, is
not generally known for his restraint. But he was obviously awed by
one of New York's grandest buildings, and he allowed it to dictate
the design.
</P>
<P>
   The steakhouse, which sits snugly on the balcony overlooking the
main concourse, is entirely open to the magnificent space around
it. Seated in a splendor that recalls the great days of luxurious
trains, diners have the leisure to contemplate the starry ceiling
glowing 100 feet overhead while harried commuters dash madly
through the marble halls below.
</P>
<P>
   The seats are so comfortable, the appointments so majestic, that
you feel as if you were setting off on a wonderful journey.
</P>
<P>
   The food, for the most part, is equal to the space. David
Walzog, the chef at Tapika (which is also owned by the Glaziers),
reworked the standard steakhouse menu with energy and imagination.
Not every dish works, but he is constantly tinkering and with each
passing week the food improves.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for example, the onion rings. When the restaurant
opened in July they were heavily battered and overseasoned. Now,
they have been transformed into small, crisp little puffs of onion
air that seem to vaporize on contact with your mouth. The creamed
spinach, which was dark and heavy, is now bright green and utterly
irresistible. And mushy hash brown potatoes have turned into crisp
cakes that crackle before melting into tenderness.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, Walzog works too hard. The smoked salmon is so
gussied up with dill cream and brioche toast and waving fronds of
herbs that it looks like something that escaped from last year's
Easter Parade. Would Michael mess with this? No way.
</P>
<P>
   Walzog, we are told, worked closely with Jordan on the menu.
Trying to second-guess Jordan's tastes is a good way to think about
ordering. The shrimp cocktail, for instance, is excellent (although
the ``23 herbs and seasonings'' are impossible to discern).
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, I am certain, would approve. And he must be pleased with
the big, crisp iceberg lettuce salad with its terrific choice of
dressings (I particularly liked the blue cheese).
</P>
<P>
   I suspect he would be less taken with the tomato and onion
salad, a bland, overdesigned dish of concentric rings and colors
that looks as if it is trying to imitate the Olympic symbol. The
corn soup with an island of crab cake in the middle is not a total
success either. And warm garlic bread with gorgonzola fondue needs
an energy injection; it is rich without being zesty.
</P>
<P>
   But the meat is suitably robust, prime, aged and old-fashioned.
All the standard cuts are available: a 16-ounce strip steak, a
12-ounce filet mignon and a double porterhouse for two that weighs
in at 44 ounces. But to my mind, the flavorful rib eye steak is
best; big, salty and charred on the outside, it is a tribute to the
American steer.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who are unafraid of fat, there is the deeply
greasy pleasure of braised short ribs, which arrive on a bed of
that wonderful creamed spinach.
</P>
<P>
   Walzog also does an impressive job with lobster; he somehow
manages to grill it without toughening, which is not an easy feat.
His lamb chops are less likable; when I had them they were small
and slightly dry. Perhaps Jordan is not a lamb fan.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by this menu, Jordan is not very interested in desserts,
either. Most are made by the admirable Payard Patisserie, but they
are not good travelers. The blueberry tart, the banana rum tart and
the lemon tart all arrive on soggy crusts.
</P>
<P>
   The mud cake is made on the premises, but it is so big, ugly and
messy that it makes you long for a wedge of devil's-food cake.
There is, however, one bright point in all of this: the hot fudge
sundae. An extravaganza of fruit, stewed nuts, whipped cream and
ice cream awash in excellent fudge, it is every bit as excessive as
the hamburger _ and every bit as good. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan's the Steak House N.Y.C. Two Stars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grand Central Terminal, 23 Vanderbilt Avenue; (212) 655-2300. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ATMOSPHERE: The old trains are gone, but Grand Central Terminal
is back in all its glory and there is no better place from which to
contemplate the restoration. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERVICE: Careful and solicitous. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOUND LEVEL: Grand Central is tranquil in the evening, but
during the day it is still a construction zone. Bring ear plugs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RECOMMENDED DISHES: Iceberg lettuce salad, chilled jumbo shrimp
with cocktail sauce, broiled marrow bones, Porterhouse for two, New
York strip steak, rib eye steak, steamed or broiled lobster,
chopped sirloin, crisp fried onions, hash brown potatoes, creamed
spinach, hot fudge sundae. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WINE LIST: Excellent wines at fair prices; terrible wines by the
glass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRICE RANGE: Appetizers, $6.95 to $12.95; main courses, $16.95
to $27.95; side dishes, $6.95; desserts, $5 to $7.50. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOURS: Lunch, Monday to Friday, noon to 2:30 p.m.; dinner,
daily, 5:30 to 11 p.m. (until 9 p.m. on Sunday). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT CARDS: All major cards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHEELCHAIR ACCESSIBILITY: Stairs to restaurant. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
