<HEADLINE>
SALT'S KOSHER QUESTION  
 A CHICKPEA WAFER  
 THE HANDY DOUBLE BOILER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Is there any kosher salt that supplies iodide?
</P>
<P>
   A: The answer is both no and yes. All iodized salt is kosher,
but there is no ``kosher'' salt that contains iodides. Confused?
</P>
<P>
   This seeming conundrum stems from the fact that all salt is
inherently kosher because it is a pure chemical compound. What
distinguishes kosher salt from common table salt is both the size
of the crystals and the lack of any additives that would render the
salt nonkosher for Passover.
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt has coarse crystals, which are necessary for the
koshering of meat. After an animal is ritually slaughtered, the
meat is covered with salt to draw out the blood. Coarse salt
crystals are more effective because they don't dissolve as readily
as fine salt (if the salt dissolves it can't draw out as much
blood).
</P>
<P>
   Salt that has an iodide compound added must also contain
dextrose to act as a stabilizer. Dextrose is a derivative of corn,
which is not considered kosher for Passover by Ashkenazi Jews.
</P>
<P>
   However, since salt is approved kosher pareve (acceptable for
use with meat and dairy products), you will find the kosher symbol
on most packages of table salt _ iodized or not. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a recipe using chickpea flour, water and
olive oil to make a flat wafer I saw on a French travelogue. Any
ideas?
</P>
<P>
   A: The flat wafer you are looking for is called socca. It is a
savory treat sold in the Cours Saleya open-air market in the old
city of Nice. Vendors set up little stands in the market stalls and
sell warm squares of the salty snack folded into brown paper cones.
</P>
<P>
   Socca is easy to make provided that you have a very hot oven,
which transforms the thin batter into a cake with a texture halfway
between a pancake and a fritter. Here is a recipe adapted from
Mireille Johnston's ``The Cuisine of the Sun.'' You can buy
chickpea flour in Italian and Middle Eastern markets as well as in
fancy gourmet shops. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are there any other uses for a double boiler besides melting
chocolate?
</P>
<P>
   A: Since double boilers heat food slowly over steam instead of a
direct flame, they provide the best cooking environment for
delicate, finicky ingredients and preparations. Other than for
melting chocolate, double boilers are handy for stirring up
custards, curds, puddings and fillings, and are often used for
making sauces.
</P>
<P>
   Before microwaves took over the job, doubler boilers were a must
for reheating any dish that might separate or curdle, such as
something coated in a cream or egg-based sauce.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have a double boiler, you can construct one out of
an ordinary saucepan and a metal bowl. Simply choose a bowl that is
wider in diameter than the saucepan, then fill the pan with about
an inch of water and place the bowl on top.
</P>
<P>
   The bowl should rest in the pan spended over _ but not touching
_ the water. Make sure to hold the bowl with a pot holder or towel
while mixing; it gets quite hot. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Questions about food and cooking can be sent to Food Chain, the
Dining section, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd Street, New York
10036-3959, or by e-mail to dining(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
