<HEADER>
A0548 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      09-29 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MOST RELIABLE DINNER MATE: GERMAN RIESLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Burg Landshut, a ruined castle high above medieval
Bernkastel, the best known of the Mosel wine towns of Germany,
offers one of the most spectacular views of vines in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The vineyards sweep southward toward Brauneberg and west past
Graach and Wehlen to Zeltigen, all of them legendary German wine
villages, too. The view is never more stunning than a few weeks
from now when summer is truly past, the leaves are turning and the
river's steep banks are carpeted a bright yellow gold.
</P>
<P>
   I visit this magical place when I can, which is not often
enough, but always with mixed feelings of anticipation and guilt.
Anticipation because of the unmatchable wines, the beauty of the
area, the overwhelming sense of history it imparts. And guilt for
having failed, over the years, truly to convey the profound
pleasures these wines can give.
</P>
<P>
   The wines are rieslings, the elegant, complex, long-lived white
wines from the steep-sloped banks of the Rhine river and its
equally famous tributary, the Mosel; from the Pfalz region, and
from Alsace, in France.
</P>
<P>
   What has the unending search for something new in wine brought
us in the United States in recent years? Domestic merlot,
sangiovese and viognier, mostly pale imitations of their European
counterparts. Domestic rieslings have been around longer than those
three, but they, too, rarely approach the wines of Germany and
Alsace. Might it be time for the real thing?
</P>
<P>
   What prompt these ruminations are some recent observations by
David Rosengarten of the Food Network and by Willie Gluckstern, the
wine writer and consultant, in his new book, ``The Wine Avenger''
(Fireside, $11). Both agree: German rieslings are the best wines to
have with food, more flexible than any chardonnay or merlot.
</P>
<P>
   Rosengarten said: ``The white wine I select for food more than
any other is dry German riesling. This is no accident. I believe it
to be the most flexible white wine in the world for food.''
</P>
<P>
   Gluckstern writes: ``Nothing, I repeat, nothing, marries better
with more foods than riesling. Whereas other white wine varieties
might be generally serviceable with food, German rieslings fairly
sing at the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Gluckstern is not given to half measures. Of the pairing of red
meat with one of the richer German rieslings, he writes: ``What's
truly astounding is how perversely delicious they taste together.''
But he advises: ``Keep your eyes closed. The concept of white wine
with red meat might short-circuit your neural transmitters.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not so sure about red meat _ at least, not our steaks and
chops. But in northern climes, even in Scotland and Scandinavia,
great rieslings have always been paired with game: venison, wild
boar and the pungent flesh of game birds like pheasants and wild
ducks.
</P>
<P>
   With fine German wines so unfashionable in this country, it
might be a mistake to plunge directly into the most extreme
combinations. But there is no reason not to enjoy good Rhine wines
or Mosels with roast chicken and farm-bred ducks and turkeys. A
rich riesling could turn this year's Thanksgiving dinner into a
memorable event.
</P>
<P>
   Riesling is king in Germany, and there are not many princes.
Chardonnay is an interloper, and lesser white varieties like
sauvignon blanc, chenin blanc and the upstart viognier are
dismissed out of hand. What's more, in the best vineyards here and
along the Rhine, so are other German grapes, even though many of
them, like Kerner and Mueller-Thurgau, are related _ some closely,
some less so _ to the riesling.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to cater to the worldwide trend to dry wines, both
red and white, the German vintners have begun in recent years to
turn out trocken (dry) and halbtrocken (semidry) wines. Some of
them are quite good.
</P>
<P>
   But the glory of great riesling is the relationship between
sweetness and acid; they are the yin and the yang of the best
German white wines. Alcohol is less important in German wines; they
rarely exceed 11 percent and most range from 9 to 10. This makes
them easier to drink than most French wines and some of
California's alcoholic monsters.
</P>
<P>
   German wines are ranked by ripeness at the time the grapes are
picked. Ripeness is determined by the grape's sugar content. The
rules are complicated, and the language even more so. Suffice it to
say that the levels most often encountered in quality table wines,
in increasing levels of natural sugar, are kabinett, spaetlese and
auslese.
</P>
<P>
   These wines are usually fermented dry _ that is, until all the
sugar has been turned into alcohol and carbon dioxide. Then a small
quantity of unfermented grape juice called suesswein is added to
them. Some grapes with exceptionally high levels of sugar are
turned into sweet dessert wines known as beerenauslese and
trockenbeerenauslese.
</P>
<P>
   My own preference is for the traditionally made wines with a
touch of sweetness. When the sugar is perfectly balanced by the
wine's acidity, it doesn't seem sweet at all _ just extra rich and
complex.
</P>
<P>
   I recall a lunch a few years ago in a kitschy old Bernkastel
restaurant with the winemaker Karl-Heinz Lauerburg and his son
Patrick. We had spent the morning in the Lauerburg cellars,
sampling rieslings going back to 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch was a handsome trout, poached briefly with a few herbs,
accompanied by a riesling from the Sonnenuhr vineyard in nearby
Wehlen. Among Mosel vineyards, the Wehlener Sonnenuhr is almost as
famous as the Doctor vineyard in Bernkastel, the source of some of
Lauerburg's finest wines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sonnenuhr'' means ``sundial'' in German and indeed, a huge
sundial graces the upper reaches of the vineyard that bears its
name. It was supposed to tell the vineyard workers when the day was
ended.
</P>
<P>
   Mosel wines _ you can tell them by their green bottles _ are
usually a bit more delicate and drier than wines from the Rhine
vineyards, which are identified by brown bottles. It is the richer,
more assertive Rhine wines, from communes like Hochheim, Eltville,
Johannisberg and Ruedesheim, that are most often associated with
heavier dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred years ago, German wines, called Hock by the English,
who were their best customers, were highly prized. And Thomas
Jefferson was particularly fond of the wines of Schloss
Johannisberg. As late as the 1920s, wines of the best German
estates, like Marcobrunn and Scharzhofberg on the Rhine and
Brauneberg on the Mosel, were even more expensive than the first
growths of Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few encouraging signs today. At Union Pacific, one
of New York's better new restaurants, Urs Kaufmannis, the
sommelier, has assembled a wine list that includes a good selection
of German wines to go with Rocco DeSpirito's inventive cooking.
</P>
<P>
   At Lutece, Eberhard Mueller has extended the wine list to
include attractive German wines. Lutece has a fine selection of
Alsatian wines, a legacy of its former owner. Andre Soltner,
himself an Alsatian.
</P>
<P>
   Germany has a long list of Michelin-starred restaurants, and in
them, German wines are once again associated with the finest food.
Perhaps, one day, it will happen here. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
