<SLUG> BC-LAKE-MUCK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS PROBE GEOLOGIC HISTORY DEEP BENEATH NEW YORK LAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOB GARDINIER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ Union College scientists are exploring the
muck of ages beneath two unusually deep lakes that hold a
12,000-year record of climatic changes and the effects of
civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Using a missile-shaped sidescan sonar device along with a
sub-bottom digital profiler, a team of geologists, biologists,
chemists and civil engineers is mapping the depths inside sediment
of Collins and Ballston lakes in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   The lakes are two of only 100 meromictic lakes in the United
States, so named because the deep holes of ``dead water'' the color
of a strong cup of pekoe tea lack oxygen for decomposition and are
not stirred by currents. The water is under such pressure and so
bereft of oxygen that when it is brought to the surface it froths
over.
</P>
<P>
   Millenia of animal and plant-rich sediment remain in these
holes. The scientists have extracted yards of muck by pushing a
hollow four-inch plastic pipe down through the layers, in a process
called coring and similar to that used to probe polar ice.
</P>
<P>
   The sled-like digital profiler provides a glimpse inside the
layers of muck that have accumulated in the lake since the Ice Age.
The group had previously used the device to probe below Ballston
Lake with good results, but the researchers were a little
disappointed that even small pockets of methane gas in the sediment
blur the imaging, geologist John I. Garver said.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers located a 30-foot-deep hole and guess there is
between 60 to 80 feet of undisturbed sediment beneath it in layers
resembling the growth rings on trees.
</P>
<P>
   Ballston Lake is 110 feet deep at its southern end and for now
the scientists can only guess how deep the sediment is there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cored down about 20 feet and thought we were half-way
through, but the carbon dating on a leaf we found went back to 400
A.D. So it turns out we only probed about one-tenth of the layer,''
geologist Donald Rodbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Periodic flooding of the Mohawk River, a stone's throw away,
left a clear imprint in the sediment of the Collins Lake hole that
is providing unprecedented insight into the meandering river's
history and a possible future.
</P>
<P>
   Seated behind his desk littered with sonar output data, Rodbell
produced spreadsheets on the chemical analysis of a recent Collins
Lake core sample of the sediment that clearly shows a steady
increase in the levels of charcoal, lead and zinc starting in the
early 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Industry output from General Electric and American Locomotive
and other plants as well as people burning coal in their homes
became aerosoled dust and lies perfectly preserved in the
sediment,'' Rodbell said.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the chart reveals levels of the toxic
chemicals have steadily fallen off in the last about 20 years of
the core sample.
</P>
<P>
   They have parsed the core samples with microscopes, carbon
dating and magnetic and chemical analysis and found evidence of
past flooding, forest fires, climatic and geological changes lying
undisturbed in the quiet depths.
</P>
<P>
   The college professors and several of their undergraduate
students have been studying Collins Lake since 1994. Union's
geology department, one of a few undergraduate programs nationally
that runs a coring lab, recently received $160,000 grant from the
National Science Foundation and purchased the high-tech detection
equipment and a global positioning satellite system to pinpoint the
survey locations.
</P>
<P>
   Poking around with the side scan sonar _ the same technology
used to find the Titanic as well as wreckage from the recent Swiss
Air crash _ the Union team has found sunken cars, boats,
snowmobiles, all of which probably fell through the winter ice in
both locations, Garver said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 1654EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
