<HEADER>
A0629 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-CUBA-0930-COX     09-29 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-CUBA-0930-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OFFICIALS: CUBA HOPES FOR BETTER RELATIONS WITH U.S.
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trim.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Cuba is opening up its state-run economy, and is
reaching out to Americans in hopes of ending 40 years of tense
relations with the United States, Cuban diplomats told an audience
here this week.
</P>
<P>
   But the highest-ranking U.S. official in Cuba said that economic
reforms have been stalled, and that there will be no changes in
U.S. policy toward Cuba until there is real, systemic change on the
island.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban diplomats also said that work on two Soviet-style nuclear
reactors at Juragua, about 180 miles south of Key West, can't
proceed due to a lack of funding and resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``In practical terms, this cannot go forward,'' said Carlos
Fernandez de Cossio of the Foreign Relations Ministry in Havana.
``We wish we could work with Americans on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments were made at a two-day conference called ``Cuba in
Evolution,'' sponsored by The Dallas Morning News, that was marked
by emotional debate between Cubans, Cuban-Americans, and officials
from both nations on how to encourage change in Cuba, and to end a
political stalemate between Cuban leader Fidel Castro and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuba is ready to discuss any issue with the United States, and
the only condition is respect,'' said Fernando Remirez, the
highest-ranking Cuban official in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Remirez heads the Cuban Interests Section in Washington, D.C.,
which is the closest thing Cuba has to an embassy due to the
absence of formal diplomatic ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   Remirez said that the Cuban economy -- which he said grew 13.5
percent between 1994 and 1997 -- has recently undergone ``serious
adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to a government with 15 fewer cabinet ministries
today compared to five years ago, and a banking system that's been
restructured.
</P>
<P>
   He said that 1.4 million foreigners are expected to visit Cuba
in 1998, a number that would quickly jump to 3 or 4 million if U.S.
travel restrictions to Cuba were lifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope we are close to the day when the United States accepts
Cuba as an independent and sovereign nation, and then we will have
normal ties,'' Remirez said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. diplomat Michael Kozak said the Cuban government
``literally lives from hand to mouth,'' adding that the United
States fears what might occur in a post-Castro Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the U.S. government's primary concern is stability,''
Kozak said. ``Our nightmare scenario is that we get a flood of
migrants.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Castro, 73, had only ``tinkered'' with his country's
economy reluctantly in order to avoid instability, and that
important, long-term economic reform is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Many at the conference felt that, in light of Pope John Paul
II's visit to Cuba last January, now is the best time to foster
communication and cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five or six years ago, you might have seen Cuban-Americans
saying they would talk with the Cuban people but not with the
government,'' said Wayne Smith, a former U.S. diplomat to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's been changing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others contended that the U.S. government must continue its
efforts to isolate Cuba, the best policy for bringing about changes
in Castro's one-party state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. economic embargo against Cuba may not be perfect, but
neither is doing nothing,'' said Daniel Fisk, a former aide to Sen.
Jesse Helms (R-N.C.) who helped write the Helms-Burton bill, which
strengthened the embargo in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. policy seeks an end to the repressive state structure of
Cuba,'' Fisk said. ``Ending the embargo without significant
political change remains the (Cuban) regime's No. 1 priority.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim ends.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cuban government officials said work on their two
nuclear reactors is at a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, Russia announced it would free up $350 million in
credits offered to Cuba in 1997, allowing work to continue on the
half-built reactors.
</P>
<P>
   The news alarmed hard-line Cuban-Americans who argue that Castro
is an unstable dictator with the ability to develop biological and
chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But Cuban officials said this week that Russia doesn't have the
resources to develop the project, and that the Cuban government
must have a third party, such as the United States, in order to
complete the reactors.
</P>
<P>
   Various U.S. studies have suggested that, if completed, the
reactors could pose a Chernobyl-type danger to Americans living as
far north as Washington, and as far west as Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Congress approved $3 million to build and maintain a
Caribbean Radiation Early Warning System, or a battery of sensors
on the Florida, Alabama, Louisiana, and Texas coasts.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban officials maintain that their country poses no threat to
the United States, and pointed to the Cuban government's
ratification of the international treaty banning chemical weapons
as one piece of proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States knows Cuba has no nuclear capability,''
Fernandez said. ``And we have no intention of obtaining chemical
weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
