<HEADER>
A0630 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STILLEST-BOOK-REVIEW-     09-29 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STILLEST-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE STILLEST DAY': TREADING A PATH OF SELF-INFLICTED RUIN
</HEADLINE>
   (th) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Josephine Hart, author of ``Sin,'' ``Oblivion'' and her first
novel, the much-acclaimed ``Damage,'' writes about emotional
disintegration, the collapse of the normal world into a kind of
fulfilled death wish.
</P>
<P>
   She will not disappoint her readers in her new novel, ``The
Stillest Day,'' which shows Ms. Hart ever the master of the lean
and aphoristic story of psychological horror.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Stillest Day'' is the tale of a woman living in England
before World War I who lovingly cultivates a hopeless erotic
addiction, thereby pitching her life into an abyss. The truth is
that this new book does not have quite the stark power of some of
Ms. Hart's earlier books, in part because even her subject, sexual
obsession, can begin to become familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hart seems to strain for effect in this book, which combines
the attributes of an elegant psychological thriller and a Gothic
horror story. Her ending in particular (postponed by several
somewhat formulaic chapters aimed at building up the suspense) is
so dramatically contorted as to veer into mannerism, evoking less a
shudder of tragic appreciation than a kind of prurient curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these faults, Ms. Hart's new effort remains
fundamentally intelligent and thematically compelling. As in her
best earlier work, she demonstrates a sure hand as she firmly
guides this latest excursion down the tormented path of
self-inflicted ruin. She writes with serene and spare narrative
power, early on creating the surface tension that foreshadows the
disaster to follow, the various pieces of her story falling as
neatly and inconspicuously into place as the tumblers of a safe.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the novel is the narrator, Bethesda Barnet, a
woman of 29 living in a quiet English village, where she takes care
of her invalid mother and experiences ``the comfort of custom and
the protection of prescribed procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Bethesda is a schoolteacher and a part-time artist who paints
tame village scenes under the patronage of Lord Grantleigh, the
local aristocrat who is going to play an important role in the
denouement of Bethesda's story. When, abruptly, a young couple
expecting their first child move in next door, Bethesda constructs
a destructive obsession with the expectant father, Mathew Pearson.
</P>
<P>
   ``His rain-washed face was what I first saw,'' she recounts, and
then begins to paint that face on mirrors in her room upstairs,
mirrors that she wraps in silver-threaded shawls and conceals in
her cupboard drawers. ``A single vision had revealed to me my
life's destiny,'' she says. ``A natural worshiper, I had found my
God.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hart sets up her tale with her usual stylistic elegance, her
characters emerging from just a few strokes of her pen with sharply
individuated features. Bethesda's mother is calculating and
selfish. Mary, the pregnant wife of the beloved Mathew Pearson, has
a soft roundness that is spiritual as well as physical, and
loathsome to Bethesda. She sees the aging mother and the
mother-to-be as rebukes to herself, and she develops a
serpent's-tooth hatred for the two of them and their conspiratorial
contentment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They laughed,'' Bethesda tells us, dripping with controlled
animosity. ``It was a kind of female laughter which I detested.
Lord Grantleigh and I had sometimes noted the veritable witchlike
quality of the consensual laughter of women.''
</P>
<P>
   Bethesda's hatred for the women has its counterpart in a fantasy
life with Mathew that reaches a point of religious ecstasy: ``What
is it that I wished for? An endless, silent idolatry. The image of
my Lord will fill my room and life and I will spend my time there
in adoration.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point midway in Ms. Hart's novels there is a kind of
plot point, an unexpected occurrence that allows the evil seed
already planted to go to full, noxious flower. In this book,
Bethesda has a suitor, a sturdy and prosperous farmer named Samuel
Keans, who, after a delay of years, proposes to her, thereby, it
would seem, rescuing her from the fearful village fate of
old-maidhood.
</P>
<P>
   Bethesda, after a punitive hesitation, agrees to the marriage,
but just then Mary comes for a visit. It would not be fair to
readers of ``The Stillest Day'' to reveal exactly what happens on
that visit, but it is an unanticipated and shocking event that
sends everything on a downward spiral.
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, Bethesda is a ruined woman, ruined, like
Flaubert's Emma Bovary, by her own yearning to escape the rigid
restraints of village life by substituting an erotic fantasy for
reality. Mathew, Samuel and even Lord Grantleigh turn against her.
Her abandonment is complete, and, in the end, she almost has no
choice but to complete the process of self-destruction begun when
she first stepped outside the bounds of rural propriety, even
though that step was taken mostly in her mind.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Ms. Hart's theme concerns the terrible fragility of
things. Deep in most people is the terror that some secret wish
will be exposed and will set in motion their own destruction. When
that happens in Ms. Hart's stories, we respond with a frisson of
self-recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Stillest Day'' adds a strong religious undertone to the
theme of psychological disintegration. In it, the sinful wish of
Bethesda strangely becomes reality, and it is the wish itself more
than the act that leads her to doom.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the power and effectiveness of the themes, Ms. Hart's
ending remains contrived in its very horribleness. The reader
wonders: How is Ms. Hart going to get out of this one? And when the
answer is revealed, it comes across as more lurid than unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   One reads with the dread and fascination that one feels watching
an insect devour its prey. You know it is going to happen, and yet
it is almost impossible to look away.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE STILLEST DAY'
</P>
<P>
   By Josephine Hart
</P>
<P>
   210 pages. Overlook Press. $23.95. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
