<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN GORE BE OVERTAKEN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nebraska Sen. Bob Kerrey, a potential Democratic
presidential candidate, now says he was ``a bit rash and harsh''
three years ago when he said President Clinton was ``an unusually
good liar.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey didn't actually retract what he said, which stands as one
of the most perceptive observations about Clinton ever leveled by a
fellow Democrat, pre-Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Kerrey was angry because although he and other
Democrats had risked their jobs by raising taxes at the president's
insistence in 1993, the president told a group of rich Texas
contributors that Congress forced the tax hike on him and that he
really hadn't wanted to do it. Kerrey felt the betrayal personally;
he nearly lost re-election in 1994 to a Republican who berated him
for that vote to raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The incident is typical of the prickly relationship between the
two that has existed since Kerrey was defeated by Clinton in the
1992 presidential primaries. Kerrey, a Navy veteran and a Medal of
Honor winner who lost a leg in Vietnam, also attacked Clinton's
candor in that race, accusing Clinton of being deceitful about the
way he avoided the draft.
</P>
<P>
   These men have little in common, beyond roots in rural America,
their joint party affiliation and a tendency toward moderately
liberal policies. Although Kerrey is a bachelor who once dated
actress Debra Winger, his private life has remained private and
relatively scandal-free.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey, in fact, is well-positioned to run for the White House
in a post-Clinton era reeling from the president's reckless bad
behavior and the threat of impeachment. Kerrey says he will decide
in December whether to run in 2000, after he digests the outcome of
the November congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   Those elections are almost as psychologically important to
Kerrey's future as they are to Vice President Albert Gore, who is
still the likely frontrunner despite his close identification with
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   For two election cycles Kerrey has been chairman of the Senate
Democratic Campaign Committee, a crucial fund-raising role. Two
years ago, the Democrats lost two Senate seats, putting pressure on
Kerrey to demonstrate in November that he can produce some
victories to verify his national leadership credentials.
</P>
<P>
   The chairmanship, however, has given him the excuse to travel
the country meeting big contributors and making friends among those
who toil in the party vineyards. Although still popular back home,
he seldom shows up in Nebraska anymore, a conspicuous absence that
has convinced local residents that he has already decided to run
for president rather than for re-election to the Senate in 2000.
(State law forbids him from seeking both jobs simultaneously.)
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey has carved out a niche of individualism in the Senate,
separating himself from the Clinton administration on several major
issues. That includes leading the 1997 fight to defeat the
president's nominee to head the Central Intelligence Agency, Tony
Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey is not known as much of a team-player inside the
Democratic party either, preferring to go his own way most of the
time. Typical of that attitude was his initial resistance to
supporting Clinton's first basic budget and tax package, which was
viewed as crucial not only to the president's ability to govern but
to the future of a party that had been frozen out of the White
House for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democratic senators were irritated by what seemed like his
dramatic grandstanding before finally capitulating.
</P>
<P>
   That could be a problem, as well as the fact that compared to
Gore, Kerrey is still not very well known nationally. In a New
Hampshire straw poll taken in July, Gore won 45 percent of the vote
and Kerrey only 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey has not been shy about taking advantage of the Monica
Mess, however. He is often on TV prodding Clinton to come clean. He
was the first to rush forward to speak in the Senate in support of
Sen. Joseph Lieberman's condemnation of Clinton's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   He has to be careful not to seem too opportunistic. Moving too
far too fast could turn off Democratic loyalists who do not want to
see Clinton brought down.
</P>
<P>
   But interest in Kerrey's ambitions has risen recently as the
president's fortunes have fallen. Gore remains the Democrat to beat
for the 2000 nomination. But the air of inevitability he once
enjoyed has vanished with a possible probe of his campaign finance
practices, national disgust with his mentor's behavior and the
party's low morale.
</P>
<P>
   At least two other Democrats also display an interest in taking
on Gore _ former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley and House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri. Like Kerrey, both have deplored
Clinton's conduct and distanced themselves from the
administration's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt has made no secret of his ambitions for years. He will
go for it if he decides there is a reasonable chance of beating
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley is a more problematic figure; when he retired from
the Senate two years ago, he said politics was ``broken'' and
washed his hands of it. Although mentioned as possible presidential
timber for years, he has never before mustered the courage or
desire to actually make the race.
</P>
<P>
   In this, he is rather like Republican Jack Kemp, Bob Dole's
running mate: much admired for character and principle within his
party but always subject to cold feet at decision-making time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
