<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SHORT-RIBS-ART-2TA     09-29 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SHORT-RIBS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING, ADDING ART NOTE)  
 RIBS SHOW OFF THEIR TENDER SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By ELAINE LOUIE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Why is it that some of the fanciest chefs in town
positively dote on short ribs?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because this unglamorous cut brings out the Henry
Higgins in them.
</P>
<P>
   In the right hands, and with enough care and patience, these
steer ribs, the ends of the prime ribs, which start out all
toughness, show their elegant and tender side.
</P>
<P>
   For Terrance Brennan, the chef and owner of Picholine, on West
64th Street, a braised short rib is a three-day affair. One day is
just for marinating, another is for braising and a third is for
rest, to allow the meat to wallow languorously in the sauce, all
the while becoming richer and deeper in flavor. With a last-minute
Provencal flourish, Brennan tosses in some nicoise olives and
anchovy fillets.
</P>
<P>
   For Brennan, short ribs have three big charms. ``There's
texture, richness, fattiness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Ah yes, the fattiness. This is no dieter's delight: It has
about twice the calories of a pot roast made with lean choice
round. But the high fat content is part of what makes short ribs so
delectable. A lovely alchemy takes place in the braising as the
fats and connective tissue, those great carriers of flavor, slowly
and imperceptibly dissolve into the sauce.)
</P>
<P>
   At the Lobster Club, on East 80th Street, Anne Rosenzweig, the
chef and owner, sears the ribs, braises them with onions, garlic,
brown sugar, veal stock and a dark ale like porter or stout.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few minutes, she brushes the ribs with a mustard and
white wine mixture, dredges them in bread crumbs and grills them
for two minutes until they become crusty.Then she stirs three
Moroccan ingredients _ bright orange dices of pumpkin, emerald
green kale and cream-colored chickpeas _ into the dark burnished
sauce and places the ribs on top.
</P>
<P>
   The sauce points up the inherent sweetness of the meat, while
the kale and mustard add a little bite. The dish looks like
gleaming mahogany.
</P>
<P>
   At Gertrude's, on East 61st Street, Laurent Manrique, the owner
and chef, makes short ribs exactly the way his grandmother Aurelie
Frayet made them for him when he was a little boy in the Gascogne
region of France. He marinates the ribs overnight in a mix of
carrots, celery, onions, garlic, herbs and a hefty red wine, like
Cahors or Madiran.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, he sears the ribs, sautees the vegetables and
braises the meat for three hours in wine and veal stock. To add
richness to richness, he makes a sauce of sauteed porcini
mushrooms, onions, garlic and prunes, which he mixes into the
earthy, soul-warming dish.
</P>
<P>
   But not all tasty recipes for short ribs require a dozen
ingredients. Rozanne Gold, the author of the new ``Recipes 1-2-3
Menu Cookbook'' (Little, Brown, 1998), uses only three: the ribs,
hoisin sauce and zinfandel. ``Water doesn't count,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Book publishers may guess and gamble as to which title will be a
best seller. But in the restaurant world, it seems, you can't go
wrong with short ribs, especially in cold weather.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rosenzweig estimated that at her last restaurant, Arcadia,
which closed in June, half of the orders were for short ribs on any
cold night. Manrique of Gertrude's placed this figure at one-third.
</P>
<P>
   When Gray Kunz, the former executive chef at L'Espinasse, added
short ribs braised in a horseradish and Meaux mustard sauce to the
menu in 1995, nobody flinched at the $38 price.
</P>
<P>
   In winter, he estimated, one-quarter of the entrees would be
short ribs, making it the restaurant's most popular dish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, I wanted to take it off the summer menu,'' Kunz
said. But popular demand won out.
</P>
<P>
   Several chefs said they preferred short ribs to filet mignon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Filet lacks flavor,'' Marc Murphy, executive chef at La
Fourchette, said.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Ms. Gold said, ``Eating a steak is a
one-dimensional experience _ but with short ribs, you get this
gorgeous dark color, smell, sight, taste and texture.''
</P>
<P>
   Brennan enjoys lifting up the cover to peek at the barely
bubbling surface, the browning of the meat, the caramelizing of the
sauce, and to take in the wine aroma.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the cassoulet, the daube, the pot au feu _ you
constantly have to keep an eye on it,'' Brennan said. ``This is
real cooking.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRAISED SHORT RIBS IN PORCINI PRUNE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   From Laurent Manrique, chef, Gertrude's
</P>
<P>
   Time: 4 hours 15 minutes, plus overnight refrigeration &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds beef short ribs, cut into 3-inch lengths
</P>
<P>
   3 medium carrots, cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   3 stalks celery, cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce (about 1 loosely packed cup) fresh thyme sprigs
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   7 medium onions, peeled
</P>
<P>
   3 heads garlic
</P>
<P>
   6 cups hearty red wine, like Cahors or Madiran
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons duck fat or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   8 cups veal stock or 6 cups canned beef broth mixed with 2 cups
water
</P>
<P>
   { pound fresh porcini mushrooms, or sliced shiitake mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   { pound dried pitted prunes, cut into one-third-inch slices. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large nonreactive mixing bowl, combine short ribs,
carrots, celery, thyme, bay leaves and peppercorns. Cut 4 of the
onions into 1-inch chunks, and add to bowl. Cut 2 heads of garlic
(with peel) in half crosswise, and add to bowl. Pour wine over all,
and mix well. Cover, and refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove short ribs from marinade, and drain well. Pat dry with
paper towels, and season with salt and pepper to taste. Set aside.
Strain marinade into a clean bowl, reserving vegetables. Remove
thyme, bay leaves and peppercorns, and reserve. In a large
casserole over high heat, heat 2 tablespoons of duck fat, and add
short ribs. Sear short ribs until well browned on all sides, about
10 minutes. Remove short ribs, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Add 1 tablespoon of duck fat to
casserole, then add the reserved vegetables. Saute, stirring
constantly, until lightly browned, about 10 minutes. Add marinade,
and stir well. Boil marinade until reduced by half, about 15
minutes. Add veal stock, short ribs and reserved thyme, bay leaves
and peppercorns. Cover, and braise in oven until ribs are very
tender, about 2{ hours.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   4. Remove short ribs from casserole, and set aside. Pour
vegetables and liquid through a fine strainer into a large bowl.
Discard all solids, and return liquid to a clean casserole. Bring
the liquid to a boil over high heat, and reduce by half, about 10
minutes. Remove from heat, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   5. Cut remaining 3 onions into large dice. Separate the cloves
of the remaining head of garlic, and peel and thinly slice. In a
large saute pan over medium-low heat, add remaining 1 tablespoon
duck fat. Add mushrooms, and saute until lightly browned. Remove
from pan, and set aside. Add diced onions to pan, and saute until
translucent, about 5 minutes. Add sliced garlic to onions, and
saute for 1 minute. Add mushrooms and prunes, and saute just until
heated.
</P>
<P>
   6. Add sauteed onion, garlic, prunes and mushrooms to the
casserole containing the reduced wine mixture. Adjust salt and
pepper to taste. Add short ribs, and mix gently. Place over
medium-low heat, and simmer just until thoroughly heated. Serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-DARK SHORT RIBS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Recipes 1-2-3 Menu Cookbook,'' by Rozanne Gold &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 3 hours, plus overnight refrigeration &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds beef short ribs, cut into 3-inch lengths
</P>
<P>
   { cup plus 2 tablespoons hoisin sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 cups red zinfandel
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon whole black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large nonreactive mixing bowl, combine short ribs, { cup
of hoisin sauce and 1 cup of wine. Mix well. Cover, and refrigerate
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove short ribs from marinade, and set aside. In a covered
casserole or roasting pan large enough to hold the ribs in a single
layer, combine marinade and 3 cups of water. Bring to a boil over
high heat. Add ribs and peppercorns. Reduce heat to low, cover pan
and simmer until very tender, about 2{ hours.
</P>
<P>
   3. While ribs are simmering, in a small nonreactive saucepan
combine the remaining 1 cup of zinfandel with remaining 2
tablespoons hoisin sauce. Place over low heat, and simmer until
reduced to { cup. Remove from heat, and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   4. When short ribs are tender, use a slotted spoon to transfer
to a deep serving platter. Set aside the ribs, and keep warm. Place
the pan of marinade over high heat, and boil until thick and
syrupy. Whisk in enough of the reserved hoisin-wine reduction to
make a well-balanced sauce. Add salt to taste. Pour sauce over the
short ribs, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   DEVILED SHORT RIBS WITH PUMPKIN, CHICKPEAS AND KALE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Anne Rosenzweig, chef, the Lobster Club
</P>
<P>
   Time: 3 hours 45 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6 short ribs, about 1 pound each
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cracked black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   \ cup vegetable or light olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   6 cloves garlic, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces porter or stout
</P>
<P>
   4 cups beef, veal, chicken, vegetable stock or water
</P>
<P>
   3 cups diced fresh pumpkin or winter squash (butternut or acorn)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups canned chickpeas, drained
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   \ cup chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped fresh kale, or Swiss chard
</P>
<P>
   Freshly grated horseradish root, optional. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Rinse short ribs, and dry
thoroughly with paper towels. Season with salt and pepper. In a
large ovenproof casserole over high heat, heat oil and add ribs.
Sear until well browned and crusty on all sides.
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove ribs from pan, and reduce heat to medium. Add onions,
and saute until just beginning to brown, about 10 minutes. Add
garlic, brown sugar, porter and stock. Return ribs to pan, cover
pan and bake in oven until meat is very tender, about 3 hours.
Remove pan from oven. Transfer ribs to a platter, and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add pumpkin to casserole, and place pan over medium-high
heat. Cook until the liquid has reduced and thickened and the
pumpkin is just tender, about 5 to 7 minutes. Reduce heat to low,
and add chickpeas.
</P>
<P>
   4. Preheat oven to 475 degrees, or a broiler with a rack 3
inches from heat. In a small mixing bowl, combine the Dijon
mustard, dry mustard and white wine. Brush mixture on all sides of
the short ribs. In a bowl, combine bread crumbs and parsley. Pat
onto short ribs. Place ribs on a baking sheet, and place in oven or
under broiler. Cook until hot and crispy, being careful to avoid
burning, about 5 minutes. While ribs are browning, add kale to
pumpkin and chickpea mixture. Simmer until heated.
</P>
<P>
   5. To serve, spoon pumpkin ragout into large flat soup plates.
Place a serving of short ribs on top of each plate. Sprinkle with
freshly grated horseradish, if desired, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
