<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX ADDICTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday Oct 6)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm Bill and I'm a sexaholic,'' is something a number of
people hope to hear but expect they won't. Yet, there are groups of
people who gather regularly and who, since the first hint of
presidential scandal, have had no doubt that ``Clinton is one of
us,'' as I'm told by a man named George.
</P>
<P>
   A woman reader had the same idea. She called the newspaper to
wonder why she hasn't read much in the media about President
Clinton's sexual addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she isn't fed up with the scandal like most people and
disappointed in the president. ``I don't like him personally,'' she
said, ``but I have a lot of compassion for him.''
</P>
<P>
   She explained that she knows about addiction. Hers is alcohol.
But isn't it the same, she wondered, to risk family, friends, job,
all the good stuff, to satisfy a craving? Be it for a drink, a drug
or sex.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a rare affliction. There are sexaholic groups and sex
and love addicts groups. Here in Sonoma and Napa counties alone
there are seven 12-step meetings that focus on sex addiction.
</P>
<P>
   George said ``Clinton needs the literature'' and he even
fantasizes that he might ``catch up with the president jogging some
day and say, `Bill, you have a problem.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all been saying to each other we want him to come to a
meeting,'' said a woman named Mary. She thinks joining a program is
the best thing to happen when an addict hits bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if this ain't bottom,'' said Mary, ``I don't know what
is.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the obstacles to dealing with sex addiction, says George,
is that it's not as socially accepted as being hooked on booze or
drugs which these days can get you help and sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look how many CEOs have said this is my addiction, I'm an
alcoholic.''
</P>
<P>
   But mention someone who is preoccupied with sex and you get
mostly raunchy jokes. Or the person is dismissed as, at best, a
rogue, or at worst, a pervert.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, said George, the addict ``needs compassion and
understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Read between the words'' of Clinton's explanations, said
George. ``It's thick with denial. He's not being honest even with
himself. He's weaseling with the words. Addicts do what we need to
do to cover up.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the questions that people like George or Mary might slip
to the president or anyone else in question include:
</P>
<P>
   Do you take part in sexual behavior despite your will and better
judgment?
</P>
<P>
   Do you say this is the last time I'll ever do that and yet do
it?
</P>
<P>
   Do you have a history of negative consequences such as legal,
financial and social problems related to sexual behavior?
</P>
<P>
   Do you assume any act of kindness or friendship is a sexual
offer?
</P>
<P>
   Do you have to have someone around with whom to flirt?
</P>
<P>
   Do you feel entitled to sex?
</P>
<P>
   Sexual addicts, according to the literature, have a compulsive
need for sex at (here's a familiar word) ``inappropriate times in
inappropriate places with inappropriate people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very serious addiction,'' said George, and in his
opinion it comes from feeling unloved and insecure and a fear of
intimacy. George relates to each one of those and believes his
addiction also came from growing up with addicts. He describes his
parents as ``Olympian alcoholics.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, when George was very young he was sexually abused and
became a male prostitute, ``to get attention and imitation
affection.''
</P>
<P>
   He married but was unfaithful. ``There's always this obsession
to get your fix. You're thinking about it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows about taking stupid risks. ``You play the edge just to
feel more alive.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows about objectifying your sex partners, maybe not even
knowing or remembering their names. ``It's not about abusing a
person but using them to take your mind off your pain.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows that compulsively sexual people can be planning their
next sexual encounter while they're in the middle of the current
one.
</P>
<P>
   Mary said it rings true that a sex addict, in denial, would
redefine the meaning of sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, you could say it wasn't really sex because she was
offering and I was accepting.''
</P>
<P>
   Or she said, a person could rationalize that having random sex
in his office is less a violation toward his spouse than having sex
in their bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Mary knows how charming and friendly a sexaholic can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the ones who walk into the room and everyone looks. We
have chemistry. And we think we can have anyone who takes our
fancy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary said the sexaholic is capable of hundreds of affairs.
George says ``a thousand.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary calls herself ``a straight up sex addict,'' and adds, ``We
could have a woman president and still have this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   George says, ``If Bill Clinton went on television and said `I've
got to come clean. I'm an addict and I'm going into a program,' the
world would be behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   You think so?
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for the Santa Rosa (calif.) Press
Democrat. E-mail her at sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
