<HEADER>
A0680 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-COMPUTERS30-CO     09-29 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-COMPUTERS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLASSROOM COMPUTERS CAN RAISE MATH TEST SCORES, STUDY FINDS
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Students who use computers in the classroom score
higher on standardized math tests when they work with trained
teachers who use the technology productively, Education Week
magazine reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine said the national study, sponsored by the magazine
and conducted by the Educational Testing Service, was the first to
link student computer use to higher test scores.
</P>
<P>
   The findings come at a time when states are spending millions
each year on education technology, and some parents and lawmakers
are questioning the effectiveness of computers in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   The Education Week study showed that students who used computers
for math learning games or for programs that applied math problems
to real-life situations _ activities generally associated with
higher-order thinking _ performed better on tests than students who
use computers for repetitious ``drill and practice'' exercises.
</P>
<P>
   About 54 percent of fourth graders use classroom computers for
higher-order thinking, while just 27 percent of eighth-graders do,
the study found.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big difference between having technology and using
it effectively,'' said Cheryl Lemke, executive director of the
Milken Exchange on Education Technology. ``Without policy changes
focused on increasing effectiveness, technology risks becoming
another lost educational opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The study found differences in achievement not only between
students who use computers at school and those who don't, but also
within the group of computer users. It said these differences were
largely due to the fact that some teachers used the computers less
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   African American students, poor students and students in the
West and Southeast were among those more likely to benefit less
from computers in their classrooms, it found.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth grade, about 31 percent of white students used
computer activities that developed higher-order thinking, compared
to 14 percent of black students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a growing disparity economically between our
students,'' said Kathleen Lyons, spokeswoman for the National
Education Association. ``We're concerned that all students get a
good solid education. In poor school districts, there are kids that
are being left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyons said the NEA would use the report as a basis for asking
state legislatures to allocate more money toward teacher training.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that in schools where teachers had some training
in computers, students outperformed those whose teachers had none.
In addition, when trained teachers used computers for higher-order
skills, schools tended to enjoy higher staff morale and lower
absenteeism rates.
</P>
<P>
   About 76 percent of eighth graders had math teachers trained in
technology. However, in 1997, about 40 percent of teachers had no
formal training in using the internet.
</P>
<P>
   American Federation of Teachers spokesman Darrell Capwell said
the study reinforces a larger issue that all teachers should be
adequately trained in any subject they teach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computers and their use is not going to be the magic bullet,''
Capwell said. ``It has to be in tandem with making sure teachers
have the professional development resources as well. Putting
teachers in classrooms who are not trained isn't productive.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
