A0696 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLEVELAND-MUSEUM-NYT &LR;      09-29 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEVELAND-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CLEVELAND, WHAT THE WELL-DRESSED KNIGHT WORE IS SHINING ANEW  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JO THOMAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Past the dead buildings and the smart new town
houses, past the sprawling Cleveland Clinic complex, in a court at
the Cleveland Museum of Art, one of the city's most beloved
attractions has come back to life.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-September, after a $1.25-million renovation and
reinstallation supported by the Lila Wallace-Reader's Digest Fund,
the Armor Court was reopened. The knights in shining armor who
introduced generations of children to the visual arts were back,
gleaming softly under a high-tech glass skylight that transmutes
even the noonday sun to dawn.
</P>
<P>
   An armored knight on horseback catches the eye. The visor on his
crested helmet is down, and even the reins on his steel-caparisoned
horse are plated for battle. But it is the other knights, posed as
naturally as if they had been momentarily interrupted, who draw the
visitor in.
</P>
<P>
   They are encased in nonreflective glass, a protection that
allows viewers to get close enough to really examine the armorer's
marks, the little buckles, the velvet linings, the intricacies of
etched designs, the flexible joints, the scars of combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the whack marks,'' said Robert P. Bergman, a medieval
scholar who came to the museum as its director from the Walters Art
Gallery in Baltimore in 1993. He pointed to the intricate etchings
on a suit of half armor for a foot tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to differentiate between the functional and the
artistic,'' he said. ``People need to be reminded that historically
this was not the case. Armor is a wonderful reminder of the
confluence of art and craft.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early years of this century, when Cleveland was one of
the nation's great iron and steel centers, the museum's first
director, Frederic Allen Whiting, believed that a collection of
armor _ annealed, hammered, assembled and decorated by hand _ would
inspire the city's craftsmen.
</P>
<P>
   Whiting found a donor, the philanthropist John L. Severance, and
then tried for several years to find a private collection that
could be purchased. Months before the museum opened on June 6,
1916, Whiting was able to purchase the armor collection of Frank G.
Macomber, a wealthy Bostonian.
</P>
<P>
   The entire shipment was lost in transit. Railroad officials
searched, but the collection had vanished. Whiting's own efforts
failed. Dejected, he took the train back to Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   As he lay in his berth, unable to sleep, and looking out the
window, he noticed a boxcar sitting on a siding near Geneva, Ohio.
He ordered the railroad crew to inspect the car, and the arms and
armor were found. But to his chagrin, the collection had been
disassembled and packed helter-skelter.
</P>
<P>
   A week before the opening, Bradford Dean, the first professional
curator of arms and armor at an American museum, the Metropolitan
Museum of Art, arrived from New York to help. He took off his coat,
and, it is said, attacked the puzzle of hundreds of unconnected
pieces of iron strewn over the Armor Court's floor. The museum and
the exhibition opened on schedule, and Clevelanders jammed the
streets to see it.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1940s, the regimental flags, damaged by ultraviolet light
from the skylight, had to be removed. In 1959, a re-examination of
pieces in the collection found 35 percent to be either forgeries or
of such poor quality that they had to be removed. These included
all three equestrian pieces, the children's favorites. But in 1964,
the Metropolitan Museum lent, and later sold, the Cleveland museum
the Italian armor for man and horse that is the focal point of the
newly refurbished exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The Armor Court, however, continued to deteriorate. Sentiment
against the Vietnam War was one reason, museum officials say.
Pieces were taken out of the display and put in storage. Unrelated
items were moved in. Clevelanders complained.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after he arrived in 1993, Bergman asked Stephen N.
Fliegel, the museum's assistant curator of medieval art, to help
him restore the armor collection ``beyond its original glory.''
They went to the Lila Wallace-Reader's Digest Fund, which wanted to
help museums expand their audiences and create new programs
designed around their permanent collections. The Cleveland Museum
was one of 29 fine arts museums to receive a grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also thought it would be wonderful to invite a number of
the great armories of Europe to participate with a piece or two
from their collections,'' Bergman said. To his surprise and
delight, museums in Stockholm, Dresden, London, Leeds and Vienna
said yes.
</P>
<P>
   On loan from the Imperial Armories in Vienna is the massive
armor made in 1495 for the Holy Roman Emperor Maximilian I,
intended for a form of jousting practiced only in Germanic
countries that eliminated the wooden wall that normally separated
two mounted combatants. This raised the risk of a dangerous
collision.
</P>
<P>
   The headpiece, aptly known as a ``frog-mouthed'' helmet is
bolted to the body armor, and the eye slot is hidden behind the
huge mouthpiece. The wearer had to lean forward slightly to see,
then straighten up and strike blindly just before impact.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the scale, also from Vienna, is the
diminutive armor worn for dressing up by Karl von Burgau
(1560-1618), the son of Archduke Ferdinand of Tyrol, when he was
about 8 or 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something compelling about knights in shining armor,''
Fliegel said. ``It projects certain values that are eternal:
protecting the weak, courage, self-sacrifice.'' Armor is also one
of the few art forms, he said, ``that captures the physical form of
a historical individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Fliegel, who wrote the exhibition's catalog, ``Arms and Armor,''
said that early European armor was made of mail, small interlinked
rings of steel, and was extremely expensive. In 805, an edict of
Charlemagne linked the right to own land to an obligation to own a
mail shirt. At the time of the Norman Conquest in 1066, the price
of such a shirt was roughly the cost of a war horse.
</P>
<P>
   When the crossbow rendered mail ineffective, before 1400, it was
replaced by plate armor, ``as simple as sculpture,'' Bergman
observed, pointing to the body-fitting curves designed to ward off
blows. ``That is what is so powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   Although armor is generally associated with the Middle Ages,
``most of the armor that survives comes from the Renaissance and
was made after 1480,'' Fliegel said. During the Renaissance,
``armor became male costume, the most expensive form ever
devised.'' Some was etched. Some was gilded with gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are presenting the material in the context of art,''
Fliegel added. ``Yes, it's about military history, but it's also
about art, fashion and taste.''
</P>
<P>
   The weight of a suit of armor here averages 70 to 80 pounds, and
many riders could actually vault onto their horses, Fliegel said.
Many suits of armor had flexible joints and were cushioned with
fabric so they did not clank. But armor could be very hot to wear,
and it rusted.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more beautiful pieces on display is a heavy suit of
cavalry armor made in 1650. ``Already they were using muskets,''
Fliegel said. ``Within 20 years, armor was abandoned on the
battlefield.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
