<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0697 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV04-NY     09-29 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOP ME BEFORE I APOLOGIZE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (For release Sunday, Oct. 4)  
 (Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.)  
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Being president,'' a wag said a generation ago, playing on a
dreamy definition of love, ``means never having to say you're
sorry.'' That truism no longer applies.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's ``campaign of  &UR; contrition &LR; '' began in his
ill-received Aug. 17 expression of  &UR; regret &LR; . That did not go down
well, because  &UR; regret &LR;  (though possibly rooted in the Old Norse
 &UR; grata &LR; , ``to weep,'' also the curious source of  &UR; greet &LR; ) has
become the mildest form of sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Regret &LR;  is what we express, often insincerely, in turning down
an invitation. In diplomacy, it is the cool acknowledgment of
error; in the acceptance of resignations, it is usually married to
the adjective  &UR; deep &LR;  in a formal wave of farewell.
</P>
<P>
   Deeper than  &UR; deep &LR;  is  &UR; profound &LR; . In Moscow two weeks later,
Clinton said, ``I was expressing my  &UR; profound regret &LR;  to all who
were hurt,'' adding that he had asked to be forgiven, though nobody
could find that direct request in his previous remarks. That was
not accepted widely as sufficient to express sorrow, either,
perhaps because of its formal or bookish quality.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in Ireland, came ``I am very  &UR; sorry &LR; .'' That made
front-page headlines.  &UR; Sorrow &LR;  is stronger than  &UR; regret &LR; , though
not as wrenching as  &UR; grief &LR;  or as tortured as  &UR; anguish &LR; . In its
adjectival form,  &UR; sorry &LR;  (from the 725 ``Beowulf'' as Old English
 &UR; sarig &LR; , ``distressed, sore'') can denote a general state of
sadness and, in this case, was combined with an implied admission
of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Though not as formal as an  &UR; apology &LR; , the expression ``being
 &UR; sorry &LR; '' is considered synonymous with ``being  &UR; apologetic &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Still, this was not considered a sufficient expression of
 &UR; contrition &LR; . That word, from the Latin  &UR; conterere &LR; , ``to grind,
bruise,'' has a theological connotation, as a realization of a
failure to respond to God's grace. To be  &UR; contrite &LR;  is a necessary
state before the absolution of sin.
</P>
<P>
   The president and his advisers saw the need to differentiate
between  &UR; remorse &LR; , the prolonged self-reproach often expressed in
hopes of shortening the sentence after commission of a crime, and
 &UR; contrition &LR;  and  &UR; penitence &LR; , which deal with forgiveness after
confessing a sin.
</P>
<P>
   Immorality is forgivable, illegality punishable; it was in
Clinton's interest to focus attention on the sins of lying and
adultery, which can be forgiven after confession and repentance,
rather than crimes of perjury or obstruction of justice, which can
result in impeachment and prosecution. That was why he adopted
 &UR; wrong &LR;  rather than  &UR; unlawful &LR; , accepting  &UR; indefensible &LR;  and
rejecting  &UR; perjurious &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Hence, ``I don't think there is a fancy way to say I have
 &UR; sinned &LR; ,'' he told the national prayer breakfast, and ``I have
 &UR; repented &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   And so we reach full linguistic circle. Both  &UR; penitence &LR;  and
 &UR; repentance &LR; , like  &UR; penance &LR;  and  &UR; penitentiary &LR; , are rooted in the
Latin  &UR; paenitere &LR; , ``to cause or feel regret.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's defenders came roaring back to attack the Starr
report as  &UR; salacious &LR; . This means ``lustful, lecherous,'' from the
Latin  &UR; salire &LR; , to jump or spurt,'' and originated in ``Familiar
Letters,'' by James Howell, who noted in 1645 that Venus, goddess
of pleasure, ``was ingendred in the froth of the sea,'' which
``makes fish more  &UR; salacious &LR;  commonly than flesh.'' (And I always
though it was brain food.)
</P>
<P>
   Synonyms like  &UR; lewd &LR; ,  &UR; lecherous &LR; ,  &UR; lustful &LR; ,  &UR; libidinous &LR; 
(words disapproving of sex often begin with  &UR; l &LR; ) were rarely flung
at the independent counsel's report; the chosen terms were
 &UR; pornographic &LR;  (from the Greek  &UR; porne &LR; , ``whore'') and  &UR; salacious &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   REPREHENDING
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the president's behavior was  &UR; reprehensible &LR; ,'' said
Rep. James Maloney, D-Conn. Feeling the need to save his
constituents the time it takes to look up unfamiliar words, he
added, `` &UR; Reprehensible &LR;  means `deserving of rebuke.'''
</P>
<P>
   He uses the Random House Unabridged, which defines the word as
``deserving of reproof, rebuke, or censure; blameworthy.'' The
synonym is  &UR; culpable &LR; .  &UR; Reproof &LR;  is criticism administered gently;
 &UR; rebuke &LR;  is sterner stuff, and  &UR; censure &LR;  is official condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   TOPSY
</P>
<P>
   ``As the only African-American in the United States Senate,''
writes Carol Moseley-Braun of Illinois, ``I hope I am not overly
sensitive to notice a tendency by Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott
in statements on the Senate floor to allude to a fictional slave
girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Moseley-Braun notes with disapproval the majority leader's
frequent use of the phrase ``grown like Topsy'' about the number of
amendments added to bills. She points out that Topsy is a character
in Harriet Beecher Stowe's 1852 novel, ``Uncle Tom's Cabin.'' When
asked by Miss Ophelia, ``Have you heard anything about God, Topsy?
... Do you know who made you?'' the child with twinkling eyes
replies: ``Nobody, as I knows on. I spect I grow'd. Don't think
nobody never made me.''
</P>
<P>
   Is the widely used Americanism  &UR; grown like Topsy &LR;  to be marked
off-limits as offensive, a racial slur to be expunged from the
national discourse?
</P>
<P>
   The word  &UR; topsy &LR;  entered the English language in 1528 as part of
the assonant adverb  &UR; topsy-turvy &LR; . At first it meant ``in an
inverted position,'' or ``upside down'' (originally  &UR; up-so-down &LR; )
and came to mean ``confused or disordered.'' The novelist, Mrs.
Stowe, may or may not have had that in mind when naming her
character; the passage makes the point of an innocent child's lack
of religious direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uncle Tom's Cabin,'' with its character of Simon Legree as the
cruel white overseer, was the most passionate abolitionist book of
its era. No less an authority than Abraham Lincoln, when greeting
Mrs. Stowe at the White House, said, ``So you're the little woman
who wrote the book that made this great war!''
</P>
<P>
   An Americanism that arose from that anti-slavery source, now
used with the source almost forgotten, cannot be twisted into a
racial slur, even in an election year. Even the dialect has been
removed:  &UR; grow'd &LR;  has been changed to the Standard English  &UR; grown &LR; 
in  &UR; grown like Topsy &LR; . The Oxford English Dictionary's definition
is the clear meaning today: ``something that seems to have grown of
itself without anyone's intention or direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as  &UR; rule of thumb &LR;  was mistakenly seized on by feminists
looking for controversy, Sen. Moseley-Braun's concern is misplaced.
She is indeed overly sensitive to this usage, and I spect she knows
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
