<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GEORGES-MAIN _ Assessing damages, continuing problems, cleanup,
etc. No longer a hurricane, Tropical Storm Georges remained a
menace to the Gulf Coast today, bringing rain, more rain and
uncertainty about the full magnitude of the damage the
well-traveled tempest had wrought. The rain continued, and along
with it the threat of floods and tornadoes. More than 678,000
customers were without power across the coast. Tornados have been
reported in Alabama but no major damage. Days will pass before some
of the multitudes of evacuees return to their homes. (Williams,
Rochell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH AJC STAFF PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: A KNT graphic on projected rainfall is available for use
with Hurricane Georges stories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GEORGES-CLEANUP _ Cleanup begins along the flooded Mississippi
coast. (Rochell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NASA-UT-RADIATION _ NASA annnounced Tuesday in Washington that
one night last month _ confirming a UT researcher's 6-year- old
prediction _ the most powerful blast of radiation ever detected
hitting the Earth collided with part of the upper atmosphere
(including over the western U.S.) It was invisible gamma rays from
a supermagnetic star 20,000 light years away called a magnetar. The
event lasted five minutes, set off scientific sensors and is
believed to have significantly reduced the range of high-powered
radio stations. Scientists say the radiation never reached the
ground and would have had no more health effect than a dental X-ray
if it had but it was dramatic evidence of Earth's pontential
vulnerability. (Stanley, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUSGA _ The U.S. Supreme Court has agreed to decide whether
Monroe County, Ga., educators violated federal law when they failed
to stop students from sexually harassing other students. The
appeals court barred a lawsuit against the district and school
officials over the harassment of a fifth-grade girl by a male
classmate. Aurelia Davis sued over a five-month ``barrage of sexual
harassment and abuse'' that her daughter alleged endured in
1992-93. (Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TECHNO _ Georgia, like most other states, has been investing
heavily in computer technology and training in the public schools,
but has not always focused that investment in the best ways to
improve student learning, according to an in-depth national study
released Tuesday. By most of the measures used by the newspaper
Education Week for the report, ``Technology Counts '98,'' Georgia
is at about the national average or better than average in putting
computers to use in classrooms. But the nation as a whole _ and
this seems to apply to Georgia too _ is approaching a place where
it now must face questions of what it is trying to accomplish with
this expensive enthusiasm and whether those goals are being met.
(Cumming, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   US-CUBA _ DALLAS _ Cuba is opening up its state-run economy and
is reaching out to Americans in hopes of ending 40 years of
histility with the United States, Cuban diplomats told an audience
here this week. They also said work on two Soviet-style nuclear
reactors located about 180 miles south of Key West can't proceed
due to a lack of funding and technical assistance. (Emling, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-WOMEN _ WASHINGTON _ The incomes of working women have
become an increasingly important part of family budgets over the
last quarter century, according to new Census Bureau data, but
women's economic progress has come at a cost: less time with their
children. Wives' incomes amounted to only 26.6 percent of their
families' incomes in 1970, but constituted 41.2 percent in 1996,
the latest year for which figures are available. But the number of
working women with children under the age of 18 jumped from 47.4
percent in 1970 to 72.1 in 1996. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-DATA _ Numbers for charts on women's earnings and family
time.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ECONOMY _ WASHINGTON _ The United States ends a fiscal
year with a budget surplus Wednesday(cq) for the first time in 29
years, and President Clinton plans to spotlight that accomplishment
in an event intended to highlight his budget battle with Congress
and turn attention from impeachment proceedings. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-COMPUTERS _ WASHINGTON _ Students who use computers in
the classroom score higher on standardized tests when they work
with trained teachers who use the technology productively,
Education Week magazine reported Tuesday. (Monroe, Cox News
Service).
</P>
