<HEADER>
A0720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEECEE-RICHARD-ART-2T     09-29 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEECEE-RICHARD-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE CHEF'S TALL ORDER: BRINGING FINE FOOD TO WASHINGTON, D.C. 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Michel Richard strode into his kitchen at
Citronelle one morning last week and announced, ``I want to make
French toast.'' Just French toast?
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Richard and his playful way with food could only
imagine what he had in store for these two slices of ordinary white
bread. He stuffed them with a slice of creme brulee, welded them
together with a paste of confectioners' sugar and water, then
dipped the ``sandwich'' in beaten egg and sauteed it in butter.
Finally he dusted it with confectioners' sugar and browned it with
a blowtorch.
</P>
<P>
   But he was not pleased. He blamed the quality of the bread: too
thick and soggy. He tried again, without soaking the bread. Still
not up to his standards. ``I want to try it with apple,'' he said.
``Next time when you come back.''
</P>
<P>
   The next morning he was at it again, this time with caramelized
apples in between two very thin slices of bread and no egg dip.
Finally, it was coming together. Richard was onto something.
</P>
<P>
   Moving from one experiment to another, he soon had his chef de
cuisine, Stephan Beauvallet, poaching fish in olive oil. Then he
was spooning lemon olive oil over vanilla ice cream. Impossible to
explain why, but it tasted superb. That's Michel Richard.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most admired chefs in the country, Richard (the name
is pronounced ree-SHAR) has come east from Los Angeles, where his
restaurant Citrus is still very popular. His dream is to turn
Washington into a city known for its food. It's a tall order.
</P>
<P>
   But with his remarkable creativity and pure, clean flavors, he
may succeed where all others have failed. The brilliance of the
food has already marked it for success. George Sape, lawyer,
serious wine collector and board member of the James Beard House,
goes to Citronelle whenever he stays here overnight. ``It is as
good as my favorite restaurants in New York,'' he said. ``His
knowledge, his experience, his attention to quality are the equal
of Jean-Georges Vongerichten, Daniel Boulud.''
</P>
<P>
   Washingtonians seem enthusiastic, too _ as enthusiastic as they
get about any restaurant that isn't a steakhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., and his wife, Joan, had dinner at
Citronelle last week. ``I'm a big roast beef man,'' the senator
said. ``I like the Prime Rib and the Capital Grille,'' he added,
referring to two Washington steakhouses. ``Aside from roast beef,
this is as good as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard is undaunted. ``You have to understand the market,'' he
said. ``You have to give them what they want, but you don't have to
give them bad food. My dream is that Washington will become a
national destination for food.''
</P>
<P>
   If not, he says, he'll move to New York. But it is clear that
Richard would be content to become king of the hill right here.
</P>
<P>
   From olive oil with ice cream to foie gras in a black bean mole
sauce, he is always pushing the boundaries of his cooking. He
carries a large artist's sketchbook that he fills with hundreds of
ideas: He thinks about new dishes while he is driving, on vacation,
even while he is still working on another creation at his
restaurant. Some of his imaginings are accompanied by full-color
sketches.
</P>
<P>
   His creativity is matched by his demand for perfection. Each
plate of food, casual though it may look, reflects the rigor of the
pastry chef that Richard once was.
</P>
<P>
   Even when he is making jokes, even when he is in the middle of
an interview, he will stop in his tracks to get a closer look at
something he has spotted from afar that doesn't meet his standards.
For a man of his girth _ he works out daily with a trainer _ he is
amazingly fleet of foot as he race-walks to the stove to check on a
piece of fish one of his cooks is tending or hurries to the front
of the kitchen because he notices that the needle-thin strips of
apple on top of a dish have not been peeled.
</P>
<P>
   Then he's off to tell another cook that the mushroom dressing on
the truffled chicken rolls is too thick, before reaching up to
straighten a slightly crooked light fixture. He switches from
French to English and from full alert to parade rest in
milliseconds.
</P>
<P>
   Late one morning last week, Richard was sitting in the kitchen,
looking quite relaxed with the top of his chef's jacket unbuttoned.
As he exuded his usual energy and enthusiasm, describing the way he
cooks and creates, his body suddenly snapped to attention:
``Something's burning,'' he said. ``What's burning? Ca brule?''
</P>
<P>
   Only when he got the answer _ no _ did he relax and return to an
exploration of how he comes up with ideas like scrambled eggs with
lobster and caviar served in an eggshell _ ideas that are at once
playful and serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing to do with food,'' he said. ``It's like a
painter. You have to have the flavor in your head and want to
translate it to the pot.'' Much of his cooking is based on a stable
of sauces. But none of the expected ones; instead, they are made of
porcini with walnuts, calamari, endive, horseradish or saffron.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Georges Vongerichten, who has lighted up the New York sky
with his four restaurants, is a great fan. ``He's fantastic,'' he
said. ``He knows how to combine things _ the look, the flavor. His
food is very layered, but it is simple and precise. He's very
technical because he was a pastry chef.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard, 50, takes his inspiration not only from books but also
from his childhood, from the passing remarks of customers, from
things he has eaten and, of course, from his fertile imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two loves,'' he said. ``My wife and my profession. I'm
not sure which is my mistress.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever restless and curious, Richard came to the United States
from France to open a New York branch of the famous Parisian bakery
Le Notre in 1974. (``A few years too soon,'' he said.)
</P>
<P>
   At Citronelle, he is never content with the menu. He changes it
daily. And now that he has moved permanently from California to
Washington, his food, he says, is in transition.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The East Coast is different,'' he said. ``They're not scared
about butter. They still love French food. I can use more game.
There is a better and greater variety of fish. People in California
are scared of food. People are more excited about food here. If I
try new recipes here, we sell it here.''
</P>
<P>
   Really? In Washington? The most buttoned-down city on the East
Coast, where most people go out to expensive restaurants for
business, not to savor the food?
</P>
<P>
   Richard shrugged. ``I love this town,'' he said. ``Maybe it's
because I'm French. It's gorgeous here. It reminds me of my youth.
It rains and there are green trees over the road. There is a little
fog. I love the change of seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard opened Citronelle in the Latham Hotel in Georgetown five
years ago, to great acclaim. It was part of a small chain he hoped
would bring security for his family _ the kind that owning a single
restaurant could not. But he spent most of his time traveling, and
as chef after chef moved through the Washington Citronelle, it went
down, down, down.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last year, he sold half his interest in Citrus to Meristar
Corp., his partner in the Washington and Santa Barbara Citronelles,
and decided to make the restaurant here his flagship and give it
his full-time attention. After a $2 million renovation, it reopened
seven months ago. With his constant presence, its fortunes have
revived.
</P>
<P>
   Even steak fanciers could learn to love Richard's simplicity.
``I don't want too many flavors in my mouth,'' he said. ``Three or
four. After that, it is too complicated for me to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   His small salad of yellow and red tomatoes and tips of asparagus
dressed with a vinaigrette that has been mixed with the juice of
French peas epitomizes his philosophy. Each ingredient is pristine;
the flavors blend, but none overwhelm. The sweetness of the peas
adds a delightful foil to the acidity of the vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   Steak-and-potatoes types will certainly understand the sauce,
still unnamed, that he based on his memory of the taste of the
scrapings from the bottom of a pan of roasted potatoes. On this
morning, he was experimenting with potatoes, onions, garlic and
thyme, roasting them in the oven until the mixture was deeply
caramelized. Then the mixture was cooked in chicken stock on top of
the stove. ``I think the potatoes will thicken the sauce,'' he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   When it was finished he lovingly dipped his spoon into it and
decided it needed a bit more acidity. ``I made it five or six times
already,'' he said. ``This is the first time I like it _ I like the
country taste.'' Served with sauteed sea bass on a plate with a
ribbon of mashed potatoes and a small pile of all the sauce's
vegetables, it would make anyone who ever loved a Sunday dinner of
potatoes, roasted meat and gravy remember that final savory bite,
when everything is mashed together. Now Richard has to think up a
name that sounds a bit more enticing than potato sauce.
</P>
<P>
   He had hardly finished his bass and potato sauce before he was
back at the stove to work on his version of Chicken McNuggets:
chicken fillets breaded with flour, egg and then kataifi _ shreds
of phyllo dough, which he had seasoned with grated orange peel. He
fried some in clarified butter and some in duck fat, but the duck
fat version masked the other flavors. He was not quite satisfied
and tried the fried chicken with several of the sauces he keeps on
hand. Finally the orange sauce tasted about right but needed
ginger. The next night he had also added some hot sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Richard began his career as pastry chef only because he was told
that before he could become a regular chef he had to be a pastry
chef. He was born in Brittany and raised in Champagne, and he
cooked for his mother and four brothers and sisters from age 7.
When he was 9, he participated in the French equivalent of the
Fresh Air Fund: He spent two weeks with a wealthy family. One day
he was taken to see the father's restaurant. ``When he opened the
kitchen door and I saw chefs with white hats, oh my God, it was
gorgeous,'' he said. ``I fell in love with it.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 14, he was an apprentice baker, and after a
stint in the French army he found a job at Le Notre in Paris. He
was sent to New York to open the bakery's short-lived branch, but
he left before it closed, lured to Santa Fe, N.M., by a hotel owner
who wanted him to take over the pastry shop. ``I didn't want to go
back to Paris,'' he said. ``It was a matter of pride. I wanted to
try this country. There is so much opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1977 he was in Los Angeles, where he opened another pastry
shop that also served meals. With the money he had earned, he
fulfilled a lifelong dream, to eat in France's three-star
restaurants. But that trip only solidified his desire to move
beyond pastry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tired of using dead ingredients _ sugar, flour,
butter,'' he said. ``I was in love with fresh vegetables, fresh
fish. So I trained and trained myself to be a chef _ for 10
years.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1987 he opened Citrus, which was hot for about five years and
is still highly rated. ``I knew Citrus would not be a success
forever,'' he said. ``It would not succeed like Wolfgang,'' he
added, in a reference to the chef Wolfgang Puck. But last year he
decided it was time to try something new, and he moved to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   What about Washington's reputation as a city that judges a
restaurant more on who's eating than what they're eating?
</P>
<P>
   Well ... last Wednesday night, when Richard entered the dining
room at the end of the evening, the patrons greeted him with a
round of applause.
</P>
<P>
   LAMB WITH EGGPLANT CAVIAR
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Michel Richard
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes, plus at least 4 hours' refrigeration, for
marinating
</P>
<P>
   6 large cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 lamb loins, 8 to 10 ounces each (see note) or rib eyes from
two lamb racks, 1 1/2 to 1 3/4 pounds total, trimmed of all fat and
membranes
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup extra virgin olive oil, plus extra for sprinkling
</P>
<P>
   2 fresh rosemary sprigs, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 fresh thyme sprigs, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Nonstick vegetable oil spray, or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds eggplant, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced fresh lemon grass
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar.
</P>
<P>
   1. Peel and mince 2 cloves of the garlic. In a medium bowl,
combine the minced garlic, lamb loins, 1/4 cup of the olive oil,
the rosemary and the thyme. Turn the lamb to coat well with the oil
and herbs. Cover, and refrigerate at least 4 hours, or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Remove the herb sprigs and most
of the garlic from the lamb. Season with salt and pepper to taste.
Place a heavy nonstick ovenproof skillet (large enough to hold the
lamb without crowding) over medium-high heat, and coat surface with
vegetable oil. Add the lamb and brown well on all sides, about 10
minutes. Transfer the skillet to the oven, and roast until
medium-rare, 25 to 30 minutes. While the lamb is roasting, prepare
the eggplant caviar.
</P>
<P>
   3. Peel and mince the remaining 4 cloves of garlic, and set
aside. Place the minced eggplant onto the top rack of a prepared
steamer, and steam over high heat just a few minutes, until tender.
Remove from the heat, and transfer to a bowl. Add the minced
garlic, 1/2 cup olive oil, cumin, lemon grass, lime juice and
sugar. Season with salt and pepper to taste, and mix well. Set
aside and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve, divide the eggplant caviar equally among 4 serving
plates. Slice each loin into 4 pieces. Top each plate with 2 slices
of lamb loin, and sprinkle with the extra virgin olive oil. Serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If using loins, ask the butcher to make 3 equally spaced
cuts through the large bone of each loin, so the loins can be
sliced into chops after roasting.
</P>
<P>
   SEA BASS WITH MASHED POTATOES
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Michel Richard
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   8 large russet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 large onions, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   6 garlic cloves, with peel
</P>
<P>
   2 fresh thyme sprigs
</P>
<P>
   4 cups, approximately, chicken stock or canned broth
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon red-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 black sea bass fillets, 6 to 8 ounces each
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons unsalted butter, coarsely chopped.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Thinly slice 4 potatoes with the
skin on, and set aside. In a medium casserole over medium-low heat,
melt the butter, and add the onion and garlic. Saute until the
onions are browned, about 10 minutes. Add the sliced potatoes and
thyme, and saute 5 minutes more. Cover, and transfer to oven. Bake,
stirring twice during cooking, until potatoes are well browned,
about 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   2. Prepare the sauce: Remove potatoes from oven, and cover
generously with chicken stock. Place casserole over medium heat,
and simmer until the stock is brown and slightly thickened. Pour
the sauce through a strainer into a heatproof bowl. Reserve about 1
cup of the cooked sliced potatoes for garnish, and discard the
remainder or reserve for another use. Add the vinegar to the sauce,
and season with salt and pepper to taste. Set aside and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   3. Peel and quarter the 4 remaining potatoes. Place them in a
medium saucepan, and cover with cold water. Add 1 teaspoon of salt.
Bring to a boil over high heat; then reduce heat and simmer until
the potatoes are tender, about 20 minutes. While the potatoes are
simmering, prepare the sea bass fillets.
</P>
<P>
   4. Preheat oven to 325 degrees. In a large skillet, heat olive
oil until sizzling. Add the fillets, skin side down, to crisp the
skin, 1 or 2 minutes. Transfer the fillets to a baking sheet, and
finish cooking in the oven until they are white and flaky, about 8
minutes. Remove from oven, and cover with foil to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   5. In a small saucepan, heat the cream just until steaming;
remove from heat. Drain the simmered potatoes, and place a
large-holed sieve over the saucepan. Using a wooden mallet with an
up-and-down motion, mash the potatoes through the sieve. Stir in
the butter a few pieces at a time. Add the warm cream in a thin
stream, and mix well. Season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   6. To serve: on each of four plates, position a sea bass fillet
next to a mound of mashed potatoes. Garnish the fillet with a small
mound of reserved sliced potatoes. Top the fillet and potatoes with
potato sauce, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
