<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern Happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Andersonville, Ga. _ The 23rd Annual Andersonville Historic
Fair Saturday and Sunday in the Civil War village features Civil
War re-enactors and vendors selling sutler merchandise such as
period uniforms and accouterments, hard-to-find Civil War
collectibles, antiques and arts and crafts. Parade 11 a.m.
Saturday. 912-924-2558.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adairsville, Ga. _ The 30th annual Great Locomotive Chase
Festival is Friday through Oct. 4 around the square and antebellum
depot of the Bartow County town that witnessed the daring escape of
Andrews' Raiders during the Civil War. Arts and crafts, carnival
rides and games, and Southern foods. 770-773-3451.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jonesborough, Tenn. _ The National Storytelling Festival
Friday through Sunday showcases storytellers, stories and
traditions from around the world. 423-753-2171.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gillsville, Ga. _ Hewell Family ``Turning &AMP; Burning''
Festival, 7 a.m.-5 p.m. Saturday, includes demonstrations of
northeast Georgia rural crafts and farming traditions, exhibits of
farm equipment, sales of wood-fired pottery and other crafts,
gospel and country music and food. 6035 Ga. 52, east of Gainsville.
770-869-3468.
</P>
<P>
   _ Flat Rock, N.C. _ The Flat Rock Playhouse presents ``Swingtime
Canteen,'' featuring an all-girl USO band with music of the 1940s,
today through Oct. 4. 828-693-0731.
</P>
<P>
   _ Highlands, N.C. _ Ed and Geraldine of Old Time Music will be
featured at the 5th Annual Mountain Makings Autumnfest Arts and
Crafts Festival Friday through Sunday at Sassafras Gap Camground on
U.S. 28 (Walhalla Road). 828-526-3181.
</P>
<P>
   _ Athens, Ala. _ The 32nd annual Tennessee Valley Old Time
Fiddlers Convention is Friday and Saturday at Athens State
University, and is expected to draw 200 musicians to compete for
``Fiddle Champion'' and $8,500 in prize money. Also, vendors with
handmade instruments, clothing, food and crafts. 256-232-2600.
</P>
<P>
   _ Boaz, Ala. _ The 34th Annual Boaz Harvest Festival Friday and
Saturday marks the beginning of the fall shopping season in one of
America's top factory outlet cities with sidewalk sales, arts and
crafts, live entertainment, a folklife program, Native American Pow
Wow, Rod Run Car Show and more. 1-800-746-7262.
</P>
<P>
   _ Montgomery, Ala. _ A Family Fun Day Sunday celebrates ``Walter
Anderson: A Symphony of Animals,'' which is on display at the
Montgomery Museum of Fine Arts through Nov. 15. The exhibit
includes a menagerie of animals depicted in pottery, paintings and
prints. 334-244-5700.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
