<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Living history village of Brattonsville is window into
plantation life
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCCONNELLS, S.C. _ Authenticity is the key word at Historic
Brattonsville, a living history village that straddles a quiet
two-lane country road in the red clay hills upstate. Even the farm
animals are rare breeds descended from 19th-century livestock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hogs are half Ossabaw Island, half Arkansas razorback,
which is as close to the old-style breed as you can get,'' says
straw-hatted interpreter Duane Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the hogs, there are 16 Cotswold sheep, 11 khaki Campbell
sheep, six gray Toulouse geese, four Devon milking cows, three
Dominque chickens and two mules _ but no partridge is a pear tree.
</P>
<P>
   Historic Brattonsville offers a glimpse of 18th- and
19th-century rural life through its 28 historic buildings on 150
acres in rural York County. The area is part of the state's Old
English District, a name that refers to the region's early
settlement by the English in the mid-1700s and to the Revolutionary
War battles fought here, including the Battle of Huck's Defeat
waged less than a half mile away from the Bratton homestead.
</P>
<P>
   Brattonsville is not a resort _ there's no hotel or restaurants.
It is a working plantation: a window to the past and a testament to
a way of life that has long since been supplanted by supermarkets,
highways and the Internet. The day-to-day work on the plantation
demonstrates the self-sufficiency of farm life. Crops are planted
each spring, tended through the summer and harvested in the fall.
Sheep are shorn. Wool is spun and woven into blankets.
</P>
<P>
   A stroll through the restored village and interpretive area
takes visitors on a journey through the past _ from a rustic,
dirt-floor backwoods cabin in the woods built by pioneers in the
1750s and the slightly more upscale McConnell Cabin to the circa
1780 Col. John Bratton Home and finally to the circa 1823 Homestead
House built by Col. Bratton's son, J.S., a medical doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounding the white clapboard antebellum house with its
unusual detached brick dining hall are outbuildings including a
slave cabin, brick kitchen and Bratton's medical office, filled
with herbal remedies plucked from the gardens outside the building.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning, things were fairly slow at Historic
Brattonsville. Between farm chores, Smith was using period tools to
craft a wooden harrow for plowing. Pat Veasey, in the role of the
plantation mistress, was spinning wool at a wheel in the kitchen _
``keeping occupied while waiting for the pot to boil.''
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen, she says, is ``the heartbeat of the plantation.''
</P>
<P>
   The costumed interpreters are so in tune with the past, it's
easy to understand how children might imagine them to be actual
relics of a bygone age.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really surprised to find out we don't live here,''
says Sarah O'Rourke, a home-schooled 16-year-old who weaves and
sometimes portrays a teacher in the one-room school.
</P>
<P>
   We found Brattonsville volunteers Kitty Wilson-Evans and Mozell
Robinson, both retired schoolteachers, in the reconstructed brick
slave cabin. They portray two of the 138 slaves that worked on
Bratton's plantation.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson-Evans was stringing seed pods _ also called Job's tears.
``What I am making is jewelry,'' explains Wilson-Evans in the
persona of Kessie, the plantation seamstress. The necklace she wore
was strung chestnut. Such natural jewelry had an important role.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a slave on the plantation liked a girl, he would give it to
her to let her know he had feelings for her,'' Wilson-Evans
informs.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson as Paulina the cook was threading green beans to make
``leather britches,'' beans that are dried and used an ingredient
in soup or cooked with fatback as a side dish.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to make do with what they had,'' says Robinson.
``This is one creative way of preserving your green beans.''
</P>
<P>
   They explained how rag dolls were sewn from scraps of cloth and
toes of old socks would be stuffed to make balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like what we do,'' says Robinson. ``It's history and it
brings back things I remember from when I was a child. My
grandfather used to make white oak baskets. It makes us think of
things that made us happy when we were young. It all comes
together.'' Neither woman apologizes for portraying slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of our history,'' Wilson-Evans says, ``and it's a
part of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson adds: ``It's not just African-American history, it's
American history.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
