<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Sept. 30, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Locally heavy rain and some bands of strong thunderstorms will
occur across southeastern Alabama, northern Florida and much of
Georgia as the remnants of Hurricane Georges drift slowly to the
east.
</P>
<P>
   Several inches of additional rain will fall in many areas to the
east of the low-pressure zone that marks the center of the former
hurricane. Areas of flooding will persist, especially near the Gulf
Coast where 10 to 20 inches of rain have accumulated during the
last few days. There will be a threat of a few tornadoes,
particularly where limited sunshine adds energy to the unstable air
mass over the region.
</P>
<P>
   A weakening front will bring a mixture of clouds and sun as well
as a few showers to the interior Northeast where generally mild
conditions will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a strengthening front will move quickly east from the
Great Lakes accompanied by a broken band of showers. In the wake of
the front, a surge of much cooler air will spread east from the
northern Plains. Some gusty showers will develop near the northern
Great Lakes as the chilly air moves over the warmer water.
</P>
<P>
   Strong thunderstorms will develop over the central Mississippi
Valley as a cold front encounters humid air in place over the
region. Farther west, clouds and showers will be common near the
east slopes of the central Rockies where moist breezes ascend the
sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Broken clouds, showers, and a few thunderstorms will swirl
around a low-pressure area in western Utah. Otherwise most of the
West will be mild with ample sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Bogus Wind
</P>
<P>
   Despite media hype, the gust of 172 mph recorded at Biloxi,
Miss., as Hurricane Georges came ashore on Monday was likely bogus.
At the time, sustained winds at Biloxi were 74 mph. A gust of 172
mph unrealistically exceeds wind codes, which decree that the
maximum gust for comparable sustained winds is 120 mph. A hot wire
anemometer was used at Biloxi. As winds blow over an electrically
heated wire, the wire cools. The rate at which it cools is then
converted to wind speed. If wind-driven rain breaches the
instrument, evaporation inflates cooling rates, leading to spurious
speeds.
</P>
</TEXT>
