<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: WEILL'S JEWISH ORATORIO REDISCOVERED; INFORMATION
FOR TICKET BUYERS; SYRACUSE SYMPHONY MAY STRIKE; LITERATURE AND
MUSIC MEET 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Is it a lost masterpiece? The subject is Kurt Weill's
so-called Jewish Oratorio, ``The Eternal Road.'' With music by
Weill, a libretto by Franz Werfel and staging by Max Reinhardt, the
work was finally staged, after delays and postponements, at the
Manhattan Opera House on Jan. 7, 1937.
</P>
<P>
   Technical and logistical problems plagued the performance,
doubling the four-hour running time of its story of a community of
European Jews fearful of a pogrom in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   The production ran for several months, until its backers went
bankrupt. And then ``The Eternal Road'' vanished for more than 60
years, perhaps because its ending failed to foretell the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday at 3 p.m., the American Symphony Orchestra, led by
Leon Botstein, will open its season at Avery Fisher Hall with
``Kings and Prophecies: A Road of Promise,'' a concert adaptation
from the work's third and fourth acts.
</P>
<P>
   Informed Audience
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Beginning Thursday, prospective ticket buyers will
have something new to read while they wait at the TKTS Times Square
Discount Ticket Booth at Broadway and 47th Street.
</P>
<P>
   The new free publication, Playbill In-Line, will provide patrons
with listings, brief synopses, schedules and running times of
Broadway and off-Broadway shows whose tickets have recently been
available at TKTS. It includes editorial information about TKTS and
its sponsor, the Theater Development Fund, as well as advertising.
Show listings will be changed weekly, and editorial sections
monthly.
</P>
<P>
   Discord
</P>
<P>
   Friday's season-opening performance of the Syracuse (N.Y.)
Symphony Orchestra was uncertain Tuesday, a day after the orchestra
voted to strike.
</P>
<P>
   Management has asked the musicians union to accept a reduction
of full-time musicians to 60 from 67 and a season shortened to 35
weeks from 38. The orchestra's four-year contract expired on Aug.
31.
</P>
<P>
   David Chambless Worters, the symphony's executive director,
said, ``We simply cannot spend money we don't have.'' Negotiations
are continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Another Spin
</P>
<P>
   It's a fresh version of words and music. The composers are names
like Bach, Beethoven, Dvorak, Handel, Mozart, Rachmaninoff,
Tchaikovsky and Wagner. The words are provided by authors like
William Boyd, John Fowles, Garrison Keillor, Arthur Miller and
Wendy Wasserstein.
</P>
<P>
   Polygram Classics and Jazz and Penguin Books are uniting
literature and classical music in a new CD series called Penguin
Music Classics. The first 10 titles were released Tuesday, with
five more to come on Oct. 20. Polygram furnishes the music, with
each recording accompanied by an original essay reflecting an
author's response to the music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
