<SLUG> BC-COROCRAN-PARKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON PARKS DONATES 227 WORKS TO CORCORAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Wis.)  (mk) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gordon Parks was so pleased by the way the Corcoran
Gallery of Art put together an exhibition of his photographs that
he has given 227 of them, practically every one in the show, to the
museum.
</P>
<P>
   The show, called ``Half Past Autumn: The Art of Gordon Parks,''
is now on view at the Museum of the City of New York, where it will
continue through Nov. 1 before traveling to the Milwaukee Art
Museum. Its tour ends in 2003, after stops in 16 American cities.
</P>
<P>
   Parks' gift includes his own print of his well-known photograph
``American Gothic, Washington, D.C.,'' also known as ``Washington
D.C. government Charwoman.''
</P>
<P>
   The photograph is actually an icon of an icon, a 1942 updating
of Grant Wood's ``American Gothic.'' Instead of a Midwestern farmer
and his wife, Parks photographed a woman who cleaned floors at a
government building that housed the Farm Security Administration,
for which Parks once worked as a photographer.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a pitchfork, Parks' subject, Ella Watson, holds a
broom and a mop. Behind her is a large American flag. Parks'
photograph presents a stoic if telling story of the role of blacks
in America at that time, especially in segregated Washington, where
the job of charwoman was one of the few open to most black women.
</P>
<P>
   Parks, too, is black, and David Levy, president and director of
the Corcoran Gallery of Art, reflected on that as he discussed the
photographer's gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very tough for a black man in photography when he
started out,'' Levy said. ``We have to regard him as a great
American hero. Here he is 85 years old and has no sense of
martyrdom or bitterness.''
</P>
<P>
   The road traveled by Parks, who is noted as well as a movie
director, was long and hard. He was born in Fort Scott, Kan., the
youngest of 15 children. His father was a poor tenant farmer and
his mother died when he was 15. Now he is donating a collection
that the Corcoran can value only in the millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Parks was a photographer for Life magazine for 20 years, and his
films include ``The Learning Tree'' and ``Shaft.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides his picture of the charwoman, other notable Parks
photographs in the gift include a series for Life on crime, poverty
and gang warfare in Harlem, as well as on Paris fashions.
</P>
<P>
   The Parks gift strengthens the Corcoran's already large
collection of photographs. Such collecting was pioneered, Levy
said, by the Museum of Modern Art, the George Eastman House and the
Corcoran.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time,'' Levy said, ``photography was regarded as a
journalistic thing, hard to place in the context of art. But now,
even the Getty is getting deeply into photography, and the National
Gallery of Art has large holdings. I think we're getting over that
hump.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole experience of working with Gordon was so positive,''
Levy said. ``We really felt that we shared a great deal _ what our
mission was and what he felt was important for his work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Parks show was seen last year at the Corcoran and this year
at the Minnesota Museum of American Art in St. Paul, in addition to
the Museum of the City of New York. It will be at the Milwaukee Art
Museum from Nov. 20 to Jan. 10, and at the Detroit Institute of
Arts from Feb. 7 to April 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 1815EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
