u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-ISRAEL-625&AMP;AD     09-29 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ISRAEL-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ISRAEL, NEW MOMENTUM SEEN IN PEACE EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a land where skepticism is a national sport,
there were neither hallelujahs nor boos Tuesday following President
Clinton's intervention in the stalemated peace talks between the
Israelis and the Palestinians _ an indication that few believed
there had been a diplomatic breakthrough worth celebrating or
condemning.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even as they shrugged, many Israelis felt the rush of a
new momentum in the peace effort. And on the eve of Yom Kippur,
before they turned off their cellular phones for 24 hours, they
debated Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's intentions and the
political repercussions for him if a peace agreement is reached
during the next round of three-way talks.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's right-wing supporters were horrified to hear him
publicly acknowledge his well-known but previously undeclared
willingness to turn over 13 percent more of the West Bank to
Palestinian control. They immediately announced that his political
coalition would disintegrate and new elections would be called if
an agreement is really reached.
</P>
<P>
   Many others said the prime minister could probably beat the
right wing to it and call new elections himself, confident that he
could redefine his constituency by capturing the center _ again, if
he really signs a deal.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone agreed that in the case of this particular
agreement, the devil is in the details, particularly of a security
accord, and there was no indication that those details were any
closer to being resolved.
</P>
<P>
   What was presented by senior American officials as a diplomatic
achievement _ the 13 percent _ was seen here as old news,
repackaged as a watershed by a scandal-ridden American
administration desperate to conduct normal business. What remained
on the table were longstanding deal-breakers, like the Israeli
demand for a Palestinian crackdown on terrorist cells and the
extradition of prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pseudo event, what took place in Washington,'' said
Itamar Rabinowitz, a professor at Tel Aviv University and a former
Israeli ambassador to Washington. ``It brought the diplomatic
thesaurus to new heights. Because obviously an agreement was not
reached.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehud Barak, leader of the opposition Labor Party, called it
nothing more than ``a kind of photo opportunity to add to the album
of each of the participants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think something important has been accomplished,'' he
said in an interview. ``Even though the attention of the Americans
is positive, both sides have lost trust in each other, and they're
waiting for the whole thing to hit the iceberg, so they can blame
each other as we all go down. But the proof of the pudding is in
the eating, so we will see in mid-October.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Netanyahu and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, have
accepted Clinton's invitation to meet again in two weeks, after a
trip here by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Natan Sharansky, Netanyahu's trade minister and a close adviser,
said that while he, too, saw no ``big breakthrough,'' he did see a
refreshed willingness on both sides to finish the deal.
</P>
<P>
   And others said they thought that they saw a new resolve in
Netanyahu to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know him personally very well, and from his body language
and his choice of words, it looks to me like he has finally made up
his mind to do this,'' said Yisrael Harel, a leader of the Yesha
Council, the political organization representing Jewish settlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though I should say he is a man whose mind can be changed by
pressure because he is not a strong personality,'' Harel continued.
``Still, he sent a message to his coalition partners when he was
speaking. He said the people will be his partners, and that was an
important phrase.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was a phrase that was heard, and leaders of the National
Religious Party threatened to bring down Netanyahu's government.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Benjamin Netanyahu makes the decision to give up more land,
he will be handing Arafat the keys to a Palestinian state,'' said
Hanan Porat, a National Religious Party member of Parliament and
chairman of the Judiciary Committee. ``And that will mean new
elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Party, too, would consider forcing a vote of no
confidence in the prime minister, although not because of a peace
deal, which it supports, Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about 50 percent that we'll have new elections before
next May,'' he said. ``At a certain point, Netanyahu himself might
feel that instead of being pushed into an election, he wants to
initiate new elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the political calculus is uncertain, both the left and
the right are divided, and the centrist candidate whom polls have
declared most likely to beat Netanyahu _ former Chief of Staff
Amnon Lipkin-Shahak _ has not yet formally resigned from the army
or allied himself with a political party.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get a good deal, then of course there is political risk,
which should be taken,'' Sharansky said. ``But new elections are
not the only option. I am a big believer in a unity government, in
broadening the base of the government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
