<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-SEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT TO TACKLE SEXUAL HARASSMENT CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court, getting an early start on its
new term, agreed Tuesday to decide whether schools may be held
liable under federal law for sexual harassment committed by one
student against another.
</P>
<P>
   The justices also said they will rule on whether the National
Collegiate Athletic Association, which governs major college
sports, must comply with a federal statute requiring equal
treatment of men's and women's sports. The high court will also
hear arguments on whether a restrictive California welfare law
violates the constitutional freedom to travel.
</P>
<P>
   Women's rights groups have been watching the three cases
closely, hoping the justices will use the appeals to broaden the
scope of federal laws against harassment and discrimination. The
justices, whose 1998-99 term begins Oct. 5, are expected to render
their decisions in the cases by next summer.
</P>
<P>
   In the harassment case, Aurelia Davis claims the Monroe County,
Ga., Board of Education violated Title IX of the 1972 Education
Amendments by refusing to stop a fifth-grade boy from groping and
making lewd comments to her fifth-grade daughter LaShonda. The
mother says she and her daughter told teachers of the alleged
harassment but that the instructors did nothing and in one instance
required LaShonda to sit next to the boy, identified in court
papers only as ``G.F.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta ruled
Title IX does not apply to sexual harassment between students, even
when teachers know of the malicious behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration supports Davis' appeal. In a legal
brief, Solicitor General Seth Waxman, President Clinton's chief
spokesman before the court, urges the justices to rule that schools
may be held liable under Title IX if ``school officials knowingly
fail to remedy a sexually hostile or abusive environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision to hear Davis vs. Monroe County Board of
Education follows the justices' ruling last June in a Texas school
case. In that decision, Gebser vs. Lago Vista Independent School
District, the justices decided that a district may not be held
liable under Title IX for a teacher's sexual harassment of a
student unless a school official with authority to take action knew
of the misbehavior and failed to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   The NOW (National Organization for Women) Legal Defense and
Education Fund, in a brief supporting Davis' appeal, cited the
Gebser decision in telling the justices that in the new case the
teachers knew of the harassment, had the authority to stop it but
failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The high court will also consider the scope of Title IX when
they hear the NCAA's appeal of a lower court decision that the
athletic association must comply with the law. The NCAA says Title
IX applies only to educational institutions that receive federal
funds, not to independent governing bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. District Court for Western Pennsylvania agreed with the
NCAA and dismissed student volleyball player Renee Smith's claim
that the association violated Title IX by making it more difficult
for her than for male athletes to satisfy eligibility requirements.
But the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Philadelphia revived
Smith's lawsuit, ruling Title IX covers the NCAA because it
collects dues from colleges that receive federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   In its appeal, the NCAA argues its connection to federal funding
through dues-paying colleges is too attenuated to satisfy Title IX.
However, Smith counters the NCAA would not exist but for the money
it receives from federally funded colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's lawsuit arose when the NCAA did not allow her to play
intercollegiate volleyball as a graduate student at Hofstra
University and the University of Pittsburgh. NCAA cited its rule
barring graduate students from playing intercollegiate sports for a
school other than the one from which they received their
undergraduate degree.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who attended college at St. Bonaventure University,
argues the NCAA regularly waives its restrictive rule for male
athletes but not for women.
</P>
<P>
   In the welfare case, California Attorney General Daniel Lungren
is appealing a lower court decision that struck down a state law
requiring new residents to wait a year before they may collect
greater welfare benefits than they would have received in their old
state. The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco ruled
the law violates the constitutional right of people to travel by
discouraging welfare recipients from entering California.
</P>
<P>
   In his appeal, Lungren argues the California law is not meant to
discourage poor people from entering the state. Instead, he claims
the statute is ``rationally'' related to the ``legitimate state
purpose'' of helping poor residents get off welfare, he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
