<HEADLINE>
PET SNAKES REALLY RATTLE MY CAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - (begin ital) ``Thence will I command the serpent, and
he shall bite them.'' (end ital) &QL; 
_ Amos 9:3 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's that biting part that gets me. That and the 
curling-around-your-neck-while-you're-sleeping-and-squeezing-the-bre
ath-right-out-of-you part.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite that above quote coming directly from the Bible,
some people seem to think that snakes make good pets. A co-worker
recently bought one for his son's seventh birthday. Hey, why not
throw in a pack of matches and some oily rags to go along with it?
</P>
<P>
   Call me old-fashioned, but I like a pet that wags its tail
instead of rattling it. When my dogs shed, they shed their hair,
not their skin.
</P>
<P>
   But it takes all kinds, as I discovered at the Turtle and
Tortoise Show in Phoenix over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   One section of the show was devoted, of course, to turtles,
including a mammoth Sulcata tortoise the size of a truck tire. It
was going for $1,000. Hey, at least snakes have an element of
danger, real or imagined, to keep you on your toes. A tortoise as a
pet? Why not just buy an ashtray and watch it sit on the coffee
table?
</P>
<P>
   But I was here to see snakes and the people who love them, which
sounds like a topic for Jerry Springer, although at first blush, I
don't know how he would work nudity or violence into it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Slithering idiots?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several tables were set up for displaying snakes. The adult
snakes resided in dry aquariums; babies coiled up in Cool Whip
containers with air holes in the tops. Lots of people crowded
around.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I figured your average snake fan would be a long-haired
guy in black-leather pants with flaming skull tattoos and a faded
T-shirt that says ``Iron Maiden Road Crew'' on the back. You know,
tasteful without being gaudy.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the people gathered around the tables to look at
(and hold) the snakes were just kids.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Katsilas and her two sons, Zack and Cody, were thinking
about buying a snake as a pet. As Jack the milk snake slithered
across her shoulders and down the strap of her pocketbook, Katsilas
explained the attraction:
</P>
<P>
   ``They're cool. They just slither around. They don't bark, they
don't chew anything up, they don't run away. Why would you want a
fish? They're just cool to have.''
</P>
<P>
   My wife has fish, and I've never noticed that she has to feed
them live mice, a point Katsilas conceded. Still, Katsilas and her
sons were definitely interested, though they planned to think it
over for a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cobra!'' Zack shouted when asked what kind he'd like, although
I got the idea they might start out with something a little more
pedestrian. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Serpentine attraction &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Caulden owns Jack (Jack's name comes from the rhyme that
reminds you of the difference between the harmless milk snake and
the dangerous coral snake, which have similar coloring: ``Red on
black, friend of Jack / Red on yellow, kill a fellow''). He wasn't
selling snakes, just showing them. In addition to Jack, he had a
couple of rattlers on display.
</P>
<P>
   So tell me, Bob, why would I want a snake as a pet?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you the honest truth _ you don't,'' he said. ``They
don't return your affection like a dog. They're about as
interesting as a pet rock as far as pets go. They're interesting
animals _ don't get me wrong. But as far as a pet goes, there's no
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there is a sensible fellow. On the other side of the
display, though, Robert Pelaez was selling snakes, and he was more
enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's always going to be a small segment of the
population that's going to find exotic pets attractive,'' he said.
And I thought, yeah, the same segment that rents those ``Faces of
Death'' movies. Although in fairness, I should point out that
Pelaez is, ahem, a tax accountant and looks the part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you're hooked on reptiles,'' he continued, ``you're
hooked on them for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but that's not what worries me. I worry that they'll be
hooked on me. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
