<HEADER>
A0751 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEER-MSKUBE01-COX     09-29 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-MSKUBE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: The ins, outs of March beer and Oktoberfest
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 1: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By MIchael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In English, deciphering the 10th month in the German word
Oktoberfest presents no great difficulty. But the curious might
wonder how a beer named for March came to be the toast of October.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of year when millions flock to Munich (and
other cities in Bavaria) to quaff Marzenbier, the reddish, slightly
sweet, malt-accented festival brew identified the world over with
Oktoberfest. From late September to the first Sunday in October,
tourists join Germans in the great beer halls and under the huge
tents set up by the city's historic breweries. On spits, chickens
by the thousands slowly turn, alongside rack upon rack of ribs and
countless wursts. In big kettles, dumplings, German potato salad
and red cabbage wait to be ladled onto plates. In kegs, the beer of
the season has been waiting since March.
</P>
<P>
   On that first Sunday in October, there's a big parade to
fairgrounds in Munich, and everyone picnics afterward. Over the
course of 16 days, as many as 5 million people will go to
Oktoberfest; by comparison, about 3 million visited Atlanta for the
1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunistically or not, the custom has caught on elsewhere,
with local fairs and one-night salutes to the season. Last week, as
diners at Phoenix Brewing Co. in Sandy Springs finished their
oxtail soup and prepared themselves for entrees, brewer Bob Garner
ceremonially tapped the keg and poured the first mugs of the
house's fall festbier. Most of Atlanta's brewpubs, in fact, are
offering versions of an Oktoberfest beer or Marzenbier.
</P>
<P>
   But why a March beer to celebrate October _ or even late
September?
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Marzenbiers were laid away in cool caves in late
March, this being the latest that beer could be brewed in the days
before refrigeration. These stocks were drawn from over the summer
and finished off in grand style during Oktoberfest. (Outside
Germany _ and among Americans in particular _ the fiction arose
that Oktoberfest beer and bock beers in spring were strongish
residues dredged from the bottom of the barrel. Brewers are always
amused to hear it.)
</P>
<P>
   End-of-summer festivals were an old tradition, but Oktoberfest
itself originated in 1810 as a marriage celebration. When Prince
Ludwig took the hand of Princess Theresia, the village green in
Munich became the site of a public reception that went on for days.
</P>
<P>
   But it was another 30 years before the style we call Marzenbier
came into being. In 1840 and 1841, Gabriel Sedlmayr of Munich's
Spatenbrau first brewed the style we today call Marzenbier _
full-bodied with a ``bready'' malt aroma, very little hop character
and both a sweetness and a spiciness on the palate. It's been the
beer for Oktoberfest ever since.
</P>
<P>
   These are beers well-suited to spicy dishes and to German
cuisine generally, and entirely different from, say, a pilsener.
Both are lagers, but the latter (if it's a real pilsener) is crisp,
assertive and a bit dry. A Marzenbier is softer at the edges. Its
closest cousins are the ubiquitous ``amber'' or Vienna lagers,
versatile beers that aren't quite so malty and have a touch more
hop character.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, more German brewers, including some of Munich's
oldest, have been exporting the style to the United States. At the
same time, American breweries big and small have offered beers they
variously call Oktoberfest or Marzenbier. Samuel Adams has made an
excellent interpretation of the style in recent years, and a
consumer can be certain of freshness.
</P>
<P>
   That's not always so with the imports. A sampling of four German
brands _ Paulaner, Spaten, Hacker-Pschorr and Beck's _ leaves you
thinking they must surely taste better in Munich (or Bremen in
Beck's case). Beer simply doesn't travel well. It sits in the holds
of ships and then in hot warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four, the Spaten Oktoberfest Ur-Marzen (original March
style) _ even in a green bottle that allows more light penetration
than a brown bottle _ was freshest and most complex, with a firm
maltiness that didn't become too rich. This is, in fact, one of the
world's classic beers from a brewery whose innovations in the 19th
century led to the development of lagers of every style.
</P>
<P>
   The Hacker-Pschorr was slightly dry for the style, but quite
drinkable. The Beck's was ordinary, like the rest of its lineup.
The Paulaner was maltiest and furthest on the way toward oxidation
_ a pity because Paulaner, like Spaten, is one of Munich's citadels
of brewing.
</P>
<P>
   This might seem unfair, but out of curiosity I pulled from the
fridge another German-style beer as I was sampling these four. No
roasted chicken, no rack of ribs, not even a sausage sat before me,
only cheese and crackers and the white of a pickled egg. The four
Marzens sampled, I poured the fifth into a conical glass, waited
for its head (enormous) to settle and sipped. This was a pilsener,
miles apart stylistically yet within the German family of beers. By
the second sip if not the first, I knew this was a more complex,
far more interesting beer. It was Tuppers Hop Pocket Pils, brewed
not in Munich but in Ashburn, Va., by Old Dominion Brewery.
</P>
<P>
   If in Munich, I'd be happy _ thrilled, in fact _ to do as the
Muncheners do. But I wasn't in Munich. I was in Atlanta, and it was
the Hop Pocket that I finished.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
