<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From Navy or no, gravy is a winner
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 1: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Maybe there's a Navy cook out there,'' Barbara Benson of
Jefferson, Georgia wrote when she requested a recipe for tomato
gravy such as the one that her husband enjoyed while in the service
in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of responses, all quite different, came in, but we
don't know whether any of them originated with a Navy cook. We just
picked two that sounded good, and our tester proved they are.
</P>
<P>
   The first uses fresh tomatoes and results in a large, 4-cup
batch of creamy, rich gravy that its sender, Alva Bentley of
Decatur, Georgia, said ``is really a winner,'' especially on a
plateful of biscuits, eggs, and bacon. The second is made with
canned tomatoes and bacon drippings and would go well with hot,
fresh corn bread. It came from Betty Printz of Rome, who said an
Alabama friend gave it to her more than 30 years ago. Her family
likes it with grits, potatoes, eggs or toast.
</P>
<P>
   While we still don't know what kind the Navy prefers, we hope
one of these is on target.
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Tomato Gravy
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 35-45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4large tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons margarine
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2cups milk
</P>
<P>
   Peel and slice tomatoes very thin. Set aside. Melt margarine in
cast-iron skillet. Slowly add tomatoes, cooking over medium heat
until soft. Stir until soupy, then add sugar, salt and pepper. Stir
to combine. Remove from heat and allow to cool completely.
Gradually add flour, stirring until smooth. Return to medium heat
and bring to simmer. Gradually add milk. Simmer 20 to 30 minutes,
or until of desired consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1/4 cup: 49 calories, 2 grams protein, 3 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 47), 5 grams carbohydrates, 4 milligrams
cholesterol, 38 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Tomato Gravy a la Les
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons bacon
</P>
<P>
   drippings
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   14.5-ounce can whole or stewed tomatoes,
</P>
<P>
   undrained
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   V-8 or tomato juice, optional
</P>
<P>
   Tabasco sauce, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Heat bacon drippings in a large skillet. Add flour. Cook and
stir over medium-low heat until a very dark roux forms. Add
tomatoes and mash with fork until smooth, stirring constantly. Add
Worcestershire sauce. Add a bit of V-8 or tomato juice if more
liquid is needed. Gravy should be a rich red and slightly thick.
Add hot sauce and salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1/4 cup: 79 calories, 1 gram protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 65), 6 grams carbohydrates, 5 milligrams
cholesterol, 148 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   -- Frances Allen of Atlanta is looking for a recipe her family
called Italian Salad, that included tomatoes, soda crackers and
olives, but no lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   -- Debra DeVoll (e-mail) wants a recipe for a pork and bean
casserole with hot dogs and pineapple, topped with bacon slices.
She thinks it came from the label of the A&AMP;P store brand of pork
and beans.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests should be sent to Recipe Swap, Food
Department, Cox News Service, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
