<HEADER>
A0753 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-TURKISH-COX     09-29 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TURKISH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turkish Delights: One of the world's great cuisines is enjoying
a warm reception in America
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 1: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heather, my friend who has lived on the coast of the Aegean Sea
for four years, says there are times when she gets sick of Turkish
food.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does get repetitive,'' she says. ``You walk into a
restaurant, and the first thing you do is look at the meze
(appetizers) and point at the ones you want.'' Point, point, point,
point, she gestures, pretending that she has her nose pressed
against yet another deli case filled with choices that have turned
ho-hum.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not there yet. Not even close. After two weeks in Turkey, I
still look at the shelves of meze and can't imagine how I'm going
to winnow the selections to a non-embarrassing amount of food: I
want it all.
</P>
<P>
   I want the mussels stuffed with rice, pine nuts and currants. I
want both the chunky fried eggplant salad and the smooth
eggplant-yogurt puree. The blood-red roasted peppers in a bath of
olive oil, hot chile and garlic. The slices of velvety cured tuna.
The salad of creamy yogurt cheese tossed with crisp, lemony
purslane.
</P>
<P>
   I have to order the fat rings of fried calamari, which are
fished locally and as sweet and tender as scallops. And I can't
resist another sigara boregi _ the slender, cigar-shaped cheese
pastry that will arrive in a minute puffed and crunchy, hot from
the oil.
</P>
<P>
   The snapshot of dining in Turkey that I take home is this:
sitting outdoors at a harborside restaurant on a balmy evening,
drinking the simple local white wine and watching a waiter deposit
these meze along with stacks of toasted crusty bread.
</P>
<P>
   It is a snapshot, not a photo essay. The seafood dishes I
sampled beside the Aegean are different from those I would find
along the Mediterranean coast to the south or up by the Black Sea.
They're unlike the European-accented stews of Istanbul, the famous
kebabs and baklava from the southeastern city of Gaziantep or the
distinctive noodles of central Anatolian cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turkey has a great tradition of refined cooking,'' says Joyce
Goldstein, the outspoken cookbook author (``Kitchen
Conversations,'' Morrow) and restaurateur whose San Francisco
eatery Square One spearheaded America's interest in Mediterranean
food in the 1980s. ``It's very much related to the (courtly) Moghul
style of cooking in India. But no information has gotten out here.
The Turks have had no press, no PR.''
</P>
<P>
   But now that tourism is picking up _ Turkey is one of the last
bargains in the Mediterranean region _ that may change. Americans
are coming home starry eyed, not only because of the beaches and
the ancient Greek ruins, but also because of the food.
</P>
<P>
   I certainly did. I was particularly struck by how fresh and
wholesome the everyday ingredients are. Even though Heather and her
husband, Savas, live in an upscale neighborhood in a big city and
both work full time, they still shop at an open-air market where
the glorious tomatoes, yellow figs, pears and cranberry beans are
fresh from a local farm. Where the chickens look scrawny but are
full of flavor, and the baby lamb is, as Turkish cookbook author
Ayla Algar says, ``something like a different species.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, when we were on the well traveled beach-ruin route,
we'd eat at tourist buffets where belly dancers entertained people
as they lunged at steam-table meatballs. But other times we'd pull
off at one of the primitive outdoor cafes offering cop sis _
literally, ``garbage kebabs,'' but really whatever bits of skewered
meat are the house specialties.
</P>
<P>
   We went to one where plastic lawn furniture was set around a
beehive clay oven. We watched as the proprietor fired it with dry
olive branches, releasing plumes of fragrant smoke, before setting
out rounds of bread dough to rise nearby. Inside, his wife and
daughter sat side by side at low work tables on the floor by the
fireplace, rolling out gozleme, crepe-thin flatbreads that they
then filled with white cheese or ground meat, folded and slapped
over a pan in the fire. You can't imagine how good those gozleme
tasted as we ate them with tall glasses of a chilled, salted yogurt
drink called ayran.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever possible, we'd get a bowl of manti for lunch: springy,
fingernail-sized meat dumplings that look like tiny cootie
catchers. They come 30 to the bowl, are topped with yogurt and
rimmed around the sides with paprika-infused melted butter. At the
table, we added a little dried mint or hot pepper.
</P>
<P>
   At dinner though, it was meze. With meze you drink, so we'd get
a bottle of wine or a round of beers.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get too much, Heather and Savas would warn. We still have
grilled fish coming. But then, within seconds, the meze would
arrive and fill the table with a mosiac of color, and everyone was
ravenous. And the night was suddenly very young.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
