A0755 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN30-COX     09-29 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    My vacation was a total wreck
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If that was a vacation, you can have vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Everything I did was wrong. Everything I touched broke.
Everything that touched me hurt. And on top of that, there was
hurricane Georges making ugly threats in front of me.
</P>
<P>
   We decided to beat the big blow to the beach, in case we needed
to board up windows and batten down such hatches as we could find.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I was put to bed at my son's house in Alford, Fla.,
because of an episode on the highway south of Columbus, Ga. (I call
it an ``episode,'' which is pure idiocy. It was a wreck _ and my
fault.) It was a matter of hitting a little red truck occupied by a
woman and a little girl, or taking to the median. I opted for the
grassy slope where my car, the best car I ever had, sullied like a
sick possum with a flat tire, a bent fender, a gone-yonder bumper
and a tail pipe stuck in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds gathered, a man with a big wrecker truck, two ambulance
people, two deputy sheriffs, a cadre of state troopers and, best of
all, a young fellow who called himself ``just a citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   He got there first, used my car phone to call the authorities,
and said, ``I'm gon' stay with you till somebody else gets here.''
He let my dog Kazan out to go to the bushes and asked if he needed
the attention of a vet.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think bouncing around in the back seat hurt Kazan, but
it played rip with a basket of stuff I had in the trunk for my
friend, Kathy Trocheck. Kathy had brought food to my bedside when I
had a heart attack, the most benign thing to happen to me lately.
</P>
<P>
   I put her pots in a basket, added some homemade jam (from Patsy
Gudger in Ellijay) and a small bottle of apple brandy. The pan in
which Kathy brought peach cobbler was twisted into an aluminum bow
knot. The apple brandy was a mess of shattered glass, smelling
dangerously alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   The man with the wrecker said, ``You can buy a new pan, but
...'' He looked at me uncertainly. Replacing the old body wouldn't
be so easy. I kept telling everybody I was perfectly fine, in
ebullient, radiant health, but I had a tendency to shake and to
want to sit down somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   When the state trooper asked me if I wanted to go to a hotel or
rent a car, I thought, ``What a brilliant idea.'' All that had
occurred to me so far was to just sit there by the roadside until
somebody came and got me.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, I saw my car into the Uptown Body shop in Columbus,
rented a car and went on toward the beach and my son's house. His
guest bed was as far as I got for the rest of my so-called
vacation. Doctors, hospitals and pain pills replaced hurricane
Georges as a subject of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   You learn a few wholesome truths when you lie in the bed
moaning. My son accepts all gifts people want to give him,
including fish he doesn't want and a rug a neighbor is replacing
with wall to wall carpet. Take whatever comes, and say thank you,
and bury it in the backyard, he said. How do you bury a vacation in
the backyard?
</P>
<P>
   When I finally crawled out of bed _ with every bone in my body
screaming for revenge _ I found I was the most wimpish driver on
the highway. I didn't exceed 25 miles an hour and I homesteaded at
all stop signs. I should have stayed there by the roadside.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
