<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surviving Lousy College Food 101
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 1: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the World Wide Web is any indication, many college students
are fed up with the food that is being served in their cafeterias,
and they are not going to take it anymore. No longer is the
collegiate set willing to settle for jokes about ``mystery meat''
and the hilarity of an occasional food fight. When it comes to
food, students want improvement and they want it now. In the best
collegiate tradition, they are organizing.
</P>
<P>
   The National Organization of College Students for Better Dorm
Food at http://home.earthlink
</P>
<P>
   .net/(tilde)giuliani/index.html is ``dedicated to doing
something about the terrible food situation facing college students
around the globe.'' The site, which lists Duke University, Penn
State University and the University of Notre Dame among campuses
with the most nutritious campus food, provides useful information
on how students can go about making improvements. There also are
sections devoted to horror stories, poetry and jokes.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, the subject seems to engender jokes _ as you
will see if you call up http://
</P>
<P>
   www.laughnet.net/archive/college/dormfood.htm.
</P>
<P>
   But jests and protests aside, dissatisfied students who want
good chow in the immediate future are more likely to get it by
taking matters into their own hands and preparing at least some
meals themselves. Now that microwaves and hot plates can be plugged
in like any small appliance and many dorm rooms come equipped with
small refrigerators, there are cooking possibilities that did not
exist years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For an excellent primer on dorm room cooking, check out
http://www.yumyum.com/student/order.htm. It's lively and
informative, with information on survival cooking geared to
students who have not had much experience in the kitchen, except on
the receiving end. Also in the vein of ``Feeding Yourself 101'' is
Bill and Al's Never Fail Recipes at
http://www.cs.buffalo.edu/(tilde)ahunt/recipe.htm. Here, dorm
dwellers and others who have had the cord to Mom's cooking severed
recently find sympathetic and easy-to-understand instructions and
recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Once the basics are understood, college students are exploring
something called eating in the ``zone,'' a school of thought that
says a healthy diet should be as close as possible to that of
evolution's original hunter _ the
</P>
<P>
   gatherers. Providing fascinating information on this new dietary
trend, as well as recipes using the three basic building blocks of
``meat, leaves and berries,'' is
http://www.zonemaster.com/evotrain.htm. Apparently, college kids
are eating this site up.
</P>
<P>
   For more traditional recipes, check out Sycamore Place at
http://www.geocities.com/CollegePark/Field/9276/cafeteria.html.
</P>
<P>
   And when all else fails, grab hold of a package of ramen noodles
and dial up http://www.nissinfoods.com/recip1.htm for some
mouthwatering recipes using those three-minute wonders that no dorm
room pantry should ever be without.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Top Ramen Says's Me &AMP; Peanut Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time:
about 10-12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2packages chicken sesame flavor ramen noodles
</P>
<P>
   (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1cup peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons rice or wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2fresh garlic cloves, crushed
</P>
<P>
   Red pepper sauce or
</P>
<P>
   cayenne pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3cups broccoli, florets and thinly sliced stems
</P>
<P>
   1cup frozen peas
</P>
<P>
   6cups water
</P>
<P>
   1red bell pepper, halved and cut into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   2cups chicken, cooked and cubed
</P>
<P>
   2green onions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Remove flavor packets and oil seasoning from the 2 packages of
noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If you can't find chicken sesame flavor noodles, use
chicken flavor noodles and add 1 teaspoon sesame oil.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, whisk together the peanut butter, vinegar, soy
sauce, garlic, hot pepper and contents of the sesame seasoning
packets (or sesame oil) until smooth; set aside. Place broccoli and
peas in 6 cups boiling water. Cook 2 minutes. Add noodles,
seasoning from both flavor packets and the peanut sauce. Boil for 2
additional minutes. Add bell pepper and chicken. Cook for 1 1/2
minutes. Garnish with green onion.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 468 calories, 29 grams protein, 28 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 53), 31 grams carbohydrates, 41
milligrams cholesterol, 1,160 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Top Ramen Ole!
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings Preparation time: 15-20 minutes Cooking time: 8
minutes
</P>
<P>
   4cups water
</P>
<P>
   1cup cooked turkey or
</P>
<P>
   chicken, cubed
</P>
<P>
   1package chicken flavor ramen noodles
</P>
<P>
   1cup shredded lettuce
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup chopped green onions
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup sliced radishes
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup shredded Monterey Jack cheese
</P>
<P>
   Crushed oregano
</P>
<P>
   Hot sauce
</P>
<P>
   Warm tortillas or
</P>
<P>
   tortilla chips
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan, boil water. Add turkey or chicken. Break
noodles before opening package, then add to pan and cook 3 minutes.
Add flavor packet. Divide soup between two bowls. To each add half
the lettuce, green onion, radishes, tomatoes and cheese. Sprinkle
lightly with crushed oregano and top with your favorite hot sauce.
Serve with warm tortillas or tortilla chips.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without tortillas): 412 calories, 32 grams protein,
20 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 43), 26 grams
carbohydrates, 87 milligrams cholesterol, 1,064 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
