<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0758 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER30-COX     09-29 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The results are in: Winners and losers from premire week
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it wasn't the best ``ER'' episode. Maybe it was even a
lousy one. But last week's ``ER'' season premiere was good enough
to top the Nielsen ratings for the first week of the new fall
season.
</P>
<P>
   The return of ``Friends'' did well _ even better than expected.
``Friends'' finished No. 2, ahead of ``Frasier,'' the new ``Jesse''
and laugh-crippled ``Veronica's Closet.'' All on NBC, of course.
</P>
<P>
   CBS finished as the top network in total viewers. But it also
placed third in viewers age 18-49, the demographic advertisers
covet most.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a rundown of other Nielsen facts:
</P>
<P>
   -- The winners: ``Jesse,'' ABC's ``The Hughleys'' (the most
watched sitcom of Tuesday night), CBS' ``The King of Queens'' and
CBS' ``L.A. Doctors'' all made the top 30 in total viewers.
</P>
<P>
   -- The losers: Fox's ``Living in Captivity'' and ``Costello''
and ABC's ``Cupid'' and ``Fantasy Island'' all finished way, way
back.
</P>
<P>
   -- Who's the king of Tuesdays at 8 p.m. ET? For now it's still
ABC's ``Home Improvement,'' followed closely by CBS' ``JAG'' and
NBC's ``Mad About You.'' Fox's ``King of the Hill'' finished a
disappointing 75th.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Ally'' vs. ``Raymond'': CBS' ``Everybody Loves Raymond''
had more viewers than Fox's ``Ally McBeal,'' but ``Ally'' scored
better among viewers age 18-49.
</P>
<P>
   -- Tops night by night: Most watched programs for each day were
``NFL Monday Night Football'' (Monday), ``Dateline NBC'' (Tuesday),
``Country Music Association Awards'' (Wednesday), ``ER''
(Thursday), ``Sabrina, The Teenage Witch'' (Friday), ``Walker,
Texas Ranger'' (Saturday) and the Reba McEntire movie ``Forever
Love'' (Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   ``Winters'' not a big winner
</P>
<P>
   Look what they've done to Corky. With ``Murphy Brown'' a sitcom
of the past, Faith Ford has been shackled with the inane ``Maggie
Winters'' (8:30 EDT tonight on CBS).
</P>
<P>
   Ford plays a Maggie, a thirtysomething woman who first discovers
her husband is having an affair with her dental hygienist. Maggie
then hightails it to mom's house to start her life anew. But what
she finds in her hometown is a gaggle of old high school friends
living out their old high school cliques, their old high school
jealousies, their old high school memories.
</P>
<P>
   The script is jammed with old high school jargon. ``I like liked
him.'' ``We'll freeze her out.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a show we hate hated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D-
</P>
<P>
   Headline goes here
</P>
<P>
   ABC's new sitcom ``The Secret Lives of Men'' (9:30 tonight
(50108)) doesn't hold too many secrets.
</P>
<P>
   On this show they like golf. They like beer. They like to rag on
each other. And they can't help but like to yak on and on about
their ex-wives.
</P>
<P>
   See what we mean?
</P>
<P>
   The men on this show, led by Peter Gallagher, can count on only
one thing: a really loud laugh track. And it blares throughout
tonight's mostly pitiful pilot episode in which Gallagher's
character learns the most awful of truths about divorce.
</P>
<P>
   He takes it hard. His loyal buds take it hard.
</P>
<P>
   All the while the laugh track keeps doing its thing.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Headline goes here
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, we don't mean to depress you but there is another new
show debuting tonight. And, yep, it's another snoozer.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Have &AMP; To Hold'' (9 tonight on CBS (6837) stars two
second-tier celebs (we'd tell you their names but we've never heard
too much about them before and since we figure this show won't be
around too much longer we have ask, ``What's the point?'').
</P>
<P>
   It is enough to know that she's a lawyer, he's a cop and they're
in love. We mean in love in love. Except when they're mad at each
other, which happens after about every other commercial. Meanwhile,
their wedding is imminent (though they've postponed this altar date
twice already).
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the actors don't generate enough chemistry to convince
us they're goo-goo for each other, but we do trust them about it
because they keep telling each other, ``I love you'' with their
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   They do this during a court case which has little to do with
them but ends up being all about them. They can have each other.
Just leave us alone.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
