<HEADLINE>
CHINA ADOPTS A MORE DEFENSIVE ECONOMIC STANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SETH FAISON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ China's leaders have slipped back into a
defensive stance on a range of finance and trade issues, apparently
worried that the effects of Asian financial crises will eventually
swamp their economy.
</P>
<P>
   A series of recent moves by Chinese authorities _ price
controls, currency restrictions, limits on the sale of state-owned
companies _ seem to reflect a slowdown in the nation's efforts to
shift from a planned to a market economy.
</P>
<P>
   Whether such steps are justifiably cautious or simply timid,
economists and business executives agree that they are likely to
further deter trade and investment in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, China's central bank announced new restrictions on
foreign-exchange transactions, an attempt to control the flow of
convertible currency out of the country. Officially described as a
crackdown on illegal transactions, the moves will effectively make
it more difficult for both domestic and international companies to
move money in and out of China.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is hardly what you'd expect from a country that says it
is trying to reform and open,'' said a German executive with long
experience in China, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Maybe
they are wondering how much they really want to integrate with the
world economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Beijing say Chinese companies are improperly moving
dollars overseas, presumably fearing a possible devaluation of the
nation's currency, the yuan, which would make it more expensive to
buy dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Although the nation's foreign-exchange reserves are still
strong, at $140 billion, they have remained largely unchanged this
year while China has earned a trade surplus exceeding $30 billion
and absorbed $27 billion in new foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   Wu Xiaoling, director general of the State Administration of
Foreign Exchange, said that untold billions of dollars were
improperly transferred overseas this year and that new restrictions
were necessary to stop this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a disorderly capital flow is destructive to China,'' Ms.
Wu said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said that a new crackdown required Chinese
companies to bring back any illegal foreign-currency deposits from
overseas by Thursday, or risk severe punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Since there are no accurate statistics on how much money Chinese
companies hold overseas, it may be difficult to gauge the success
of Beijing's efforts, just as it will be hard to track down Chinese
companies' foreign-currency holdings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Officials have repeatedly promised not to devalue the yuan. But
Tuesday's actions reflect their alarm that so many Chinese
companies are hedging their bets anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have also announced new price controls for a
range of industries, from cars to steel to chemicals to sugar.
Tuesday, the government-guided media reported that the State
Economic and Trade Commission would recommend prices for all major
automakers, which have been suffering in recent months from falling
demand.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent motive is to protect Chinese companies that find
themselves competing with lower-cost imports from neighboring
countries, where currencies have been devalued. Whether or not
these steps are considered constructive, they reverse the trend in
recent years to reduce state interference and allow the market a
greater role in determining prices.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, China announced new restrictions on foreign
investment in the telecommunications industry, a fast-growing area
that has attracted international investors' attention.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of the times, Chinese negotiators have
apparently told American officials and businessmen that the
government is no longer determined to win quick entry into the
World Trade Organization. Some Chinese leaders now argue that it is
the wrong time to join a group that will force China to open its
markets more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   David Aaron, undersecretary of commerce for international trade,
also said last week that Chinese officials had recently become more
rigid in negotiations over market access and on the trade imbalance
between the two nations, which runs strongly against the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Chinese officials have expressed displeasure at
Washington's recent announcement that it will ban imports from
China that come in untreated wooden crates or pallets, to prevent
further incursions by the Asian long-horned beetle.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, officials in Beijing said they would try to
slow the sale of many state industries to private owners, arguing
that too many sales were being made without adequate government
supervision, often at inappropriate prices.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of state-owned industry _ a policy announced with
fanfare a year ago _ has proved confusing, with corrupt local
officials pocketing state assets in some cases. This, in turn, may
be arousing concern over the scale and pace of enterprise reform.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new currency restrictions, banks must demonstrate that
all transactions involving more than $100,000 have full
documentation before they can be cleared by Customs. The State
Administration on Foreign Exchange will scrutinize any transaction
exceeding $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing concerns that introducing new bureaucracy was bound
to inhibit trade and investment, Ms. Wu defended the restrictions.
``It's simply the price we pay in order to combat crimes,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
