<HEADLINE>
SCHROEDER SEEKS TO ALLY FRENCH FEARS OF BRITISH TIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Seeking to allay French fears that the new German
government will form closer links with Britain at the expense of
France, chancellor-elect Gerhard Schroeder is scheduled to visit
Paris Wednesday in his first trip abroad since he unseated Helmut
Kohl Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's aides acknowledged the trip to Paris was, in part,
meant to reassure the French that the new chancellor did not value
the Franco-German special relationship any less than his
predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   In previous statements, Schroeder, who is more ideologically
similar to British Prime Minister Tony Blair than to the more
leftist French premier Lionel Jospin, made it clear he wanted to
form closer ties with Britain. But Schroeder has stressed that he
wants to develop a triangular relationship between the German,
French, and British governments.
</P>
<P>
   Blair had invited Schroeder and Jospin to join him Thursday at
the Labor Party's annual conference in Blackpool, England, in part
to bask in the fact that Europe's three biggest powers are now run
by left-wing governments _ a vindication of Blair's ``Third Way''
philosophy that places less emphasis on traditional left-wing
ideology.
</P>
<P>
   But Schroeder decided it was more important to reassure the wary
French. Germany and France are each other's biggest trading
partners, and together have been the two driving forces for
European integration.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl was a committed Francophile, who in his 16 years as
chancellor forged closer ties with Paris than London, in part
because the British have traditionally been more skeptical about
the wisdom of surrendering national sovereignty in the name of a
united Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, however, is an avowed integrationist who wants to bring
Britain deeper into the European Union so it can take on more of a
leadership role.
</P>
<P>
   French leaders have openly expressed concern that Schroeder's
overtures toward Britain signal an erosion of the special
relationship between France and Germany. French fears have not been
alleviated by the gloating of British government officials in the
wake of Schroeder's victory. The British believe Schroeder will
help them take on more of a role in Europe because he is not nearly
as committed to the Franco-German partnership as Kohl.
</P>
<P>
   The French led efforts to exclude the British from a council
that will oversee the introduction in January of the single
European currency in 11 of the 15 EU countries. The French argued
that because Britain refused to take part in the launch of the
euro, it had no right to be part of the council.
</P>
<P>
   But Schroeder believes he can help involve Britain more deeply
in the EU, while at the same time brokering better Anglo-Franco
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Easing French fears has been high on the list of priorities
since Schroeder ousted Kohl, Europe's longest-serving leader.
Schroeder told French radio that his personal relationship with
France was much better than media accounts suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Franco-German axis will remain the most important in
Europe,'' Schroeder said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
