<HEADLINE>
HIGHER ED BILL HEADS TO PRESIDENT FOR SIGNATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate Tuesday unanimously approved and sent to
President Clinton legislation aimed at making college more
affordable by increasing grants and lowering interest rates on
student loans.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year reauthorization of the Higher Education Act
emerged from a conference committee as a compromise that
incorporates both Democratic and Republican priorities and extends
special incentives to students who want to become teachers. More
than half of all college students take advantage of the loans and
grants authorized by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation gives millions of students the financial key
to unlock the door to higher education,'' said Senator James
Jeffords, the Vermont Republican and chairman of the Senate
Committee on Labor and Human Resources.
</P>
<P>
   The president is expected to sign the bill, which would reduce
interest rates on student loans by nearly one percentage point to
the lowest rate in almost 20 years. The rates will vary each year
because they are based on short-term Treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
   This provision could save students $700 on an average debt of
$13,000, said Senator Edward M. Kennedy, a Massachusetts Democrat,
one of the conferees. The provision would cover new loans, but
would give students with existing loans four months to consolidate
their debts to take advantage of the lower rates and effectively
refinance. At today's market prices, the interest rate would drop
to 7.46 percent from 8.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would prohibit financial assistance to anyone convicted
of possession or sale of a controlled substance.
</P>
<P>
   The US Student Association and the US Public Interest Group
objected that Congress balked at giving all students the
opportunity to consolidate their loans. Most students consolidate
their various loans at the time of graduation. But opponents said a
broader provision would have cost the federal government an
additional $1 billion in subsidies to banks.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial banks objected that a long-planned change in the
federal formula for setting interest rates would reduce their
expected returns and threatened to stop lending money to students.
Congress agreed to subsidize the banks with hundreds of millions of
dollars by setting up a two-tiered system that provides one
interest rate to students and a second, slightly higher one, to
banks.
</P>
<P>
   The bill gradually would increase the maximum Pell Grant to
$5,000 from $4,000 a year by academic year 2003-2004 and increase
college work-study funding to $1 billion from this year's level of
$830 million. Because of limits on funding, the current ceiling on
Pell Grants is $3,000 a year, so the actual increase may amount to
less than $5,800.
</P>
<P>
   A measure sponsored by Representative James McGovern, a
Massachusetts Democrat, would double the Pell Grant for two years
for those students who finish in the top 10 percent of their
graduating high school class, an estimated 84,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any student who is qualified for a college education should
not be turned away because of financial constraints,'' said
McGovern. His amendment ``provides incentives to people who perform
well in high school. ... If they do well, they can see some
financial rewards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Students who earn a degree and take jobs in the child-care
industry or teaching jobs in school districts that serve low-income
children could have up to $5,000 of their student loans forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would consolidate more than a dozen existing teacher
preparation programs into one program aimed at improving teacher
training. It also would give assistance to school districts for
recruiting new teachers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
