<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DISNEY-CRUISE-$ADV04-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAMILY-SIZE MOUSEBOAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Oct. 4)  
(JT) 
 By JODY ALESANDRO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I had always thought Mickey a bit of a wimp, until I met him in
Disney's private cruise terminal at Port Canaveral, Fla., sashaying
arm in arm with Minnie across a terrazzo floor map of the
Caribbean. With his triple-E shoes, chunky white gloves and
wide-eyed plastic grin, the Disney Magic's unofficial captain
managed to charm me and my 10-year-old son, Danny, a stalwart Goofy
fan, into posing for a picture with him and his mate. Like so much
aboard Disney's first cruise ship, and in Disney World itself, the
quality costuming and elegant setting had transformed a potentially
cheesy moment into a beguiling bit of silliness. Even my
16-year-old cynic, Alex, trying to be as unobtrusive as humanly
possible in the glassy 70,000-square-foot expanse, admitted he had
almost been ``sucked in by the cuteness.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no small tribute to the Disney Magic's designers that
despite the abundance of mouse ears and duck tails on board, the
83,000-ton ship is anything but ``cute.'' As long as the Chrysler
Building is tall, and just as sleek, it is reminiscent of the grand
ocean liners of the past, with a slender black hull and two red
smokestacks sporting Mickey's silhouette. From the three-story
atrium lobby with its sweeping grand staircase to the stadium
seating in the ESPN Skybox sports club, the purposeful design and
relentless attention to detail enable differently themed areas to
flow together in a Deco-Disney collage of warm woods, steel curves,
swirls of deep turquoise and sea green and frequent, strategic
splashes of primary colors.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic was built according to the plans of several Norwegian
and Finnish architects at the Ficantieri Shipyards in Italy, where
its sister ship, the Disney Wonder, is being outfitted for a spring
1999 launching. Because the Magic's first sailing, originally set
for March, was postponed twice, Disney offered those who had
already booked passage a complete refund or a 25 percent discount
for each delay. In August 1997, I had reserved two cabins for eight
friends and family members as part of a standard package that
included four days at Disney World and three on the cruise. After
the original charges were reduced by half, the six of us willing to
travel during value (as in ``hurricane'') season ended up paying
$5,260, including port charges, for two adjacent three-person
cabins with verandas _ one for Danny, my husband, Daan, and me, the
other for Alex, my brother Michael and his friend Laurie.
</P>
<P>
   About a month after the ship's first official cruise, on July
30, a Disney representative met us at the airport in Orlando, where
we waited an hour for the bus that would take us to Disney's
Boardwalk Inn and Villas, one of several accommodation options in
the package. In exchange for the hotel and cruise documents we had
filled out on the bus, the front-desk clerk at the Boardwalk gave
each of us a Key to the World card, which could be used to pay for
all extras in the hotel and on the ship and to gain admission to
all the Disney World parks, our stateroom, our shipboard safe _
everything except our hotel room, which, at 3:45 p.m., was not
ready yet (check-in time was at 4, I was told).
</P>
<P>
   Still roomless at 4:15, we left for the Magic Kingdom, where we
waited on long lines in the merciless sun to board rides like
Splash Mountain and the Big Thunder Mountain Railroad before
weaving our way through the crowds as fireworks lighted the sky
above Cinderella's Castle and Walt's voice told us that if you
follow your heart, everything is possible. Indeed, when we returned
at 11 p.m., the Boardwalk clerk waved her electronic wand over our
Keys to the World and we entered a sparkling, spacious room, with
veranda, whose fresh decor _ foamy greens and blues accenting the
pure white woodwork _ repeated the hotel's North Atlantic seaboard
theme.
</P>
<P>
   All that was missing was the brisk salty air as the six of us
set off on each of the three remaining days for the sweltering
streets of Disney-MGM Studios or the cool water slides at Blizzard
Beach or the virtual reality of Downtown Disney, usually winding up
at Epcot to watch the fireworks and laser display that, for me, was
a highlight of the trip. All the parks and pavilions were
scrupulously clean and organized, the refreshments priced for a
captive audience (snow cones $3, bottled water $2) and the
employees helpful and excruciatingly friendly. By the time the
hotel's cruise coordinator hopped onto the bus to Port Canaveral
and shouted: ``Are you people going on a cruise?'' we were used to
this cheeriness _ the driver to Blizzard Beach tried to strike up a
round of ``If You're Happy and You Know It.'' As the signs said,
Disney employees are not a staff but a ``cast.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 50-minute bus ride, and our mouse encounter at Port
Canaveral, we entered not a cabin but a stateroom _ about 24 feet
long and 9 feet wide with a spacious veranda and two bathrooms, one
with a sink and four-foot-long tub, the other with sink, toilet and
hair dryer. A tall dresser, desk with drawers, five-foot-wide
closet and enclosed shelves above a cabinet that contained a
television and unstocked mini-bar offered more than enough storage
space. But the details made the room _ the azure accents in the
white tiled bathroom, the plush towels and extra pillows, the
curtain that could be drawn between the queen-size and single beds
and, my favorite, a framed 1934 photograph titled ``Mr. and Mrs.
Walt Disney on Deck.'' It shows a windblown Walt holding on to his
wife with his left arm and, with his right, a long-nosed Mickey
puppet that actually looks like a rodent.
</P>
<P>
   Our bags were waiting for us in the stateroom, along with a
12-page time chart of meals and activities, from wine-tasting to
mouse-hunting, that made excellent reading material on the long
line for the buffet lunch on deck nine, which was struggling
through its third and final hour with lots of fresh shrimp and cold
meats, accompanied by half-cooked rice and barely defrosted rolls.
</P>
<P>
   But all was forgiven when the ship's foghorn blasted out the
first seven notes of ``When You Wish Upon a Star.'' As the Magic
began its 13-hour cruise to Nassau, we dressed for our
first-seating dinner at Lumiere's, the most formal of the ship's
four restaurants and the only one where jackets are requested (but
not always worn _ attire ranged from sequined cocktail ensembles to
sports shirts).
</P>
<P>
   Disney's rotation-dining system places guests in a different
restaurant, but with the same table number and servers, each night.
Since Michael and Laurie had reserved a table at Palo, the
adults-only restaurant that was not part of the rotation, our table
for six had two empty seats, which were filled by a retired New
York police officer and his wife, who generously shared the
Beaujolais given them as recompense for a mistake in their seating
assignment. Among the six of us, we sampled nearly every item on
the five-course menu. The lamb shank in red-wine sauce and the beef
tenderloin in green-peppercorn sauce got high ratings from our
table mates, and Daan and I, though disappointed with the red
snapper, enjoyed the escargot appetizer and a tangy Grand Marnier
frozen souffle for dessert.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Lumiere's golden Parisian glow and our table, right by a large
porthole, were lovely, but our three servers were overly solicitous
_ to the point that when I was asked for the fifth time how
eveything was, I finally blurted out that, to be frank, the fish
was dry (for which I received a dramatic expression of sympathy but
no Beaujolais).
</P>
<P>
   Michael and Laurie fared better with the northern Italian
cuisine at Palo, where they enjoyed rack of lamb in Chianti sauce,
penne with pancetta and a chocolate hazelnut souffle with
vanilla-bean sauce. Even their initial disappointment, that the
portions were small, turned to relief. They were at an 8:30
sitting, at which time the ship was moving at about 22 knots, the
270-degree view through the glass walls was of total darkness and
the whole restaurant, positioned high up on deck 10 over the stern,
rocked enough to slam a sliding door and drastically reduce their
appetites (the closest any of us came to seasickness during an
exceptionally smooth cruise).
</P>
<P>
   Barely a ripple could be felt in the Oceaneer Lab, a midship
play space for 9- to 12 year-olds that Danny and I visited when
``Disney Dreams,'' the most elaborate of the ship's three family
musicals, was canceled ``due to technical difficulties.'' The
beeper I was given after signing Danny in at the ``lab,'' part of a
clever system for locating lost parents, proved unnecessary. A half
hour later we found Dan sitting in the K'nex corner waiting to
leave. He had never gotten a turn at the large round table filled
with computers, and no counselor had introduced him to any other
activity. While he waited to sign out, we saw a group of girls
learning to juggle scarves and many other children having a fine
time. To be fair, it was just not his kind of place. The rest of
the ship was, however.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bars and the clubs, the elaborate spa and workout
rooms over the bridge, this was a cruise for children, of all ages
_ from the water slide and kiddie pool that was cleaned and
refilled with fresh water every morning to the continuous stream of
Disney tunes piped through passageways and decks. Even dinners were
entertaining, especially at Animator's Palate, where columns are
paintbrushes, sketches of Disney characters line the walls and
desserts must be decorated before being eaten. The tender
herb-crusted veal cutlets were on the oily side _ but who cared? Of
the three restaurants for families, this one was the masterpiece,
literally revealing its colors as the evening progressed.
</P>
<P>
   After dinner, while the rest of our group cooled off in the
three rather small pools on deck 9 (kiddie, family and adults
only), Daan and I took a tour of Beat Street, a path lined with
wall reliefs of giant clarinets and trumpets that leads to the
adults-only clubs: Rockin' Bar D, a kind of roadhouse disco where
country-western and rock are played on alternate nights; Sessions,
a dark and peaceful piano lounge, and Offbeat, an informal comedy
club. But at 8 p.m., the real action was at Studio Sea, a family
club where pillars look like tall stacks of film tins and
dressing-room mirrors hang askew behind a bar that serves
nonalcoholic cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   On a cruise with 2,150 passengers (maximum capacity is 2,400),
700 of whom were under the age of 18, and a crew of 920, we
marveled at the empty tables in the bars and on deck, the uncrowded
elevators, the absence of screaming children, the overall sense of
space and privacy. Even at Nassau, our first port of call, where we
had headed straight to the cooling waves of Paradise Island, we saw
only a few of our fellow passengers lining up to disembark.
</P>
<P>
   But then we arrived at Castaway Cay. Looking at the rows of
beach umbrellas covering the silky sands of Disney's 100-acre
private island, we wondered where everyone had been hiding. By 10
a.m. all but a few of the lounge chairs on the half-mile-long
family beach were occupied, and the 12-acre snorkeling lagoon was
filled with hundreds of bobbing air pipes following mapped-out
routes around bits of sunken ships that were beginning to attract a
small number of tropical fish. The adjacent teen beach and the
adults-only beach on the other side of the island, where outdoor
massages are given in alcoves facing the water, were emptier, but
the lines for the barbecue buffet seemed endless.
</P>
<P>
   Although floats, bikes and kayaks could be rented on the island,
most of our group went snorkeling while Danny and I went our own
way, desperately seeking Goofy. Having missed his few early-morning
appearances, we were thrilled when we finally found him _ swinging
in a hammock half-hidden between two palms _ just before the ship's
horn summoned us.
</P>
<P>
   Back on board, the bouncy strains of ``Hakuna Matata'' filled
the halls as we walked on down to dinner at the Caribbean-themed
Parrot Cay, a riot of palm leaves and bright island colors. The
food, as usual, was imaginatively presented, the jerk-spiced
sirloin perfectly done, and our servers cheerful as always, though
looking a bit pale in their multicolored tropical shirts. This
time, when they asked how we were, we purposefully returned the
question. Yes, they said, sometimes it was difficult working long
hours and missing home (all of the ship's restaurant staff are
European) _ and the plastic cordiality they had learned became
genuine.
</P>
<P>
   The boys always ate dinner with us, although burgers and fries,
hot dogs or pizza were available on the pool deck between noon and
10 p.m., and ice cream until 8 p.m. It was not the continuous flow
of delectables that I had promised our son with the hollow leg, but
after Alex's first night on the boat, he no longer needed any
enticements from me. The Disney approach to teen-agers is brilliant
in its simplicity: Leave them alone.
</P>
<P>
   Only people ages 13 and 17 are allowed in Common Ground, an
enclosed space on the pool deck with video games, a jukebox and a
bar serving coffee and nonalcoholic drinks. Alex met teen-agers
from all over the country there and at dance parties, as well as on
the Teen Junkanoo Jam Cruise, a Saturday-night boat trip around
Nassau harbor, with a live band and no parents. He was the last one
back to the cabin every night, obviously reveling in his first
tastes of freedom and romance.
</P>
<P>
   His only regret was that we had not gone on the cruise BEFORE we
went to Disney World. After all, what better way to visit the
arm-clutching Tower of Terror at Disney-MGM Studios or the
fireworks display in the Magic Kingdom than with a summer love,
when everything, as Uncle Walt says, is possible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
