<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-FRANCE-675&AMP;AD     09-29 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-FRANCE-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH WORRY THAT SCHROEDER WILL ALTER GERMANY'S FOCUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Faced with the prospect of a German chancellor who
believes that his country's relations with London will be at least
as important as its ties with Paris, France is filled with anxiety
about being taken seriously enough by its powerful eastern
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Gerhard Schroeder, who unseated Helmut Kohl in Sunday's German
elections, lost no time in moving to reassure his allies across the
Rhine. He accepted an invitation to lunch at Elysee Palace on
Wednesday with President Jacques Chirac and a meeting with Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin immediately afterward.
</P>
<P>
   In an article published Tuesday morning in the French daily Le
Figaro and the German daily Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung, Chirac
expressed concern that a German leader who had none of the
complexes born of World War II might take France too much for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that the geopolitical context has been radically
transformed since the end of the Cold War, some ask if the
relationship has lost its reason for being,'' Chirac wrote. ``Our
two peoples give the impression of not knowing each other so well,
of coming together with less spontaneity.''
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the French concern is fear that unless the
French-German relationship is revitalized when the German capital
moves from Bonn to Berlin next year, France may have difficulty
steering the Germans on a European course of French design.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's generation may no longer feel the sense of
obligation to right historical wrongs that was a central
characteristic of Kohl's era, Chirac said. ``Our bilateral
relationship may seem less intense,'' he wrote. ``The emotion of
reconciliation, so strong for those who went before us, is
attenuating with the passing of the generations.''
</P>
<P>
   For France, the French-German relationship is the keystone of
the whole European edifice, and Germany's support of France's
ambition for a global strategic, economic and political role for
the European Union is crucial. Germany will hold the rotating chair
of the group for six months starting in January.
</P>
<P>
   Even the common European currency that will be introduced next
year, the euro, is seen by Chirac and others as a chance to
challenge the dominance of the dollar, an ambition that, as a
former Bundesbank president, Karl-Otto Poehl, has pointed out, is
shared by few in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   For Germany, good relations with the United States during the
Cold War were as important as those with France. ``Do not force us
to choose between Paris and Washington,'' German officials often
pleaded with their French and American counterparts when, as so
often, France's cultural, economic and political goals clashed with
America's.
</P>
<P>
   That was Kohl's stand for 16 years. But France is not so sure
what Schroeder's position will be.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor-designate was reassuring in an interview with
French Europe 1 radio the day after his election.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal relationship with France is much better than the
press believes,'' he said. ``The Franco-German axis is of historic
importance and will remain the most important axis in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that reinforcing links between Germany and Britain
would make the core European relationship three-sided rather than
two-sided in the future.
</P>
<P>
   With Prime Minister Tony Blair of the Labor Party running
Britain and a Social Democrat in charge of Germany for the first
time in a generation, some members of France's Socialist-led
government see a chance for new European initiatives to tackle the
Continent's double-digit unemployment rates without worrying as
much about inflation as Kohl's conservatives did.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the French clearly expect Schroeder to do is to keep
insisting, as Kohl began to do in the last year or so, that Germany
can no longer be the European Union's rich uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl said Germany would not keep paying in almost $16 billion
more than it got out of European Union programs, and the French do
not expect Schroeder to take a different line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the normalization of Germany,'' French Foreign
Minister Hubert Vedrine said recently. ``Since unification, Germany
doesn't have to be the good boy of Europe any more.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Reworking expensive longstanding subsidies for European
agriculture _ arrangements that are still highly beneficial to
French farmers _ is expected to be difficult, and Schroeder will
give his views in a meeting with other European Union leaders in
Austria on Oct. 24 and 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have major problems to deal with in the next few months _
the euro launch, E.U. financing, common farm policy _ and we will
settle them only if France and Germany really agree on how to
settle them,'' Vedrine said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Intending to reassure the French that he took them seriously,
Schroeder named Brigitte Sauzay, a French diplomat who was the late
President Francois Mitterrand's German interpreter, as a key
adviser during his campaign last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me to explain France to him and to suggest measures
that could bring the two societies closer together,'' Mrs. Sauzay
said in an interview at home here in Paris before the elections.
</P>
<P>
   But she observed: ``I think the Germans are changing. I thought
unification would allow them to become more comfortable with
themselves, but instead they're uneasy. They still tend to identify
themselves with their economic performance instead of cultural
values.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing the French would like is for the Germans to work with
them to strengthen the distinct cultural, social and economic
cohesion of Europe and resist the encroachments of ``globalism,'' a
menace the French believe to be incorporated in the Anglo-Saxon
entrepreneurial ethic.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Marie Colombiani, the director of the influential French
daily Le Monde, wrote about this fear in a front-page editorial
that said, ``The fear of a Germany turned toward London is of a
Germany turning its back on the French-German design for Europe as
evidenced by the euro, replacing it with a free-exchange
constellation based on a Washington-London-Berlin triple axis.''
</P>
<P>
   While Germans of a certain age still come here for culture, wine
and food _ ``living like God in France'' is an old German
equivalent of ``living the life of Riley'' _ the younger generation
is more likely to go on vacation to New York or Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   And in France, the first foreign language studied by 88.1
percent of schoolchildren is English. Only 10.5 percent choose
German, down from 14 percent 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mrs. Sauzay observed, ``The relationship between France
and Germany greatly marked the world during this century, for
better and for worse. If we are going to restructure Europe in the
next century, we have to do it with Germany.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
