<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAFAT ACCEPTS U.S. PROPOSAL CALLING FOR ISRAEL'S ADDITIONAL RETURN
OF LAND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After meeting with President Clinton on Tuesday,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said that he backed a plan calling
for Israel to return additional lands on the West Bank as part of
an overall Middle East peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have accepted it,'' Arafat said, referring to a U.S.
proposal that Israel turn over an additional 13 percent of its West
Bank territory to the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace is a Palestinian need, Israeli need, Arab need,
international need,'' Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
   The return of territory captured by Israel during the 1967-Six
Day War would be in addition to the 27 percent of the West Bank
that the Jewish nation had already pledged to return to
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   To meet Israel's security concerns, 3 percent of the additional
lands _ a buffer zone of sorts _ would be turned into a nature
preserve that would be under joint Palestinian-Israeli security.
</P>
<P>
   For several days, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
other officials said Israel would relinquish more land on the West
Bank provided it was not be used for attacks on Israel. Netanyahu
endorsed the 13 percent land transfer contingent on Arafat's
guarantee of protection against terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement among the two longtime antagonists was a strong
indication that the Mideast peace process, which had been stalled
for months, was back on track.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also has been eager to move along the process. On Monday
he met at the White House with Arafat and Netanyahu, both of whom
agreed to return to Washington in mid-October to conclude
negotiations. In the meantime, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright will fly to the Mideast next week to help leaders iron out
details of any peace pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president is determined to see an agreement rise
from this exercise,'' said White House spokesman Mike McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said that Israel's concerns about security, if they
turned over the lands to the Palestinians, were ``justified.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a central element of the discussions that are under
way between the two parties,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said Arafat's talks with Clinton focused not so much on
the land transfer but on how the United States could help the
Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said that Clinton and Arafat talked about economic
assistance that might be available for people of the West Bank and
Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the two men discussed the possible establishment of
a U.S.-Palestinian Committee that could work on bettering relations
between the two governments.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton talked alone with Arafat for about 20 minutes and
together with senior aides, including Albright and national
security adviser Sandy Berger, for another 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting Clinton walked with the Palestinian leader to
the White House driveway and shook hands with him as photographers
snapped pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a car bomb blew up Tuesday in a West Bank industrial
area, killing a Hamas member and wounding two others. The group has
claimed responsibility for terrorist attacks in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has expected a renewal of Hamas bombings, and Tuesday
sealed its borders with the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
