A0780 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     09-29 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARE TO DREAM OF THE DUELLING JINXES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Bring on the Yankees in the American League
Championship Series, then the Cubs in the World Series. The best
season in baseball history won't be complete until we have Fenway
and Wrigley playing host to the duelling jinxes of the Red Sox and
Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Let's get ahead of ourselves. Why not dream? Why not the best?
Why not have these 1998 Red Sox throw off 80 years of hard luck and
heartache by beating all the teams you really want them to beat?
</P>
<P>
   Babe Ruth was the star of Sox stars when the Cubs and Sox last
clashed in the Fall Classic. And now we have Mo Vaughn, the black
Bambino.
</P>
<P>
   Mo is Babe. How else can we explain his big appetites, his
battles with management, and his Ruthian performance in Tuesday's
first game of the Division Series between the Red Sox and Cleveland
Indians?
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn hit two homers and knocked in seven runs in an 11-3
victory over the Tribe. The win snapped a string of 13 Sox
postseason losses and brought Mo back from the abyss of 1995, when
he went 0 for 14 with seven strikeouts in three straight playoff
losses to the Tribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to get an opportunity to get here again,'' said
Vaughn. ``I didn't know what was going to happen. I think I'm a
little bit older now and more experienced. You look at situations
like that and learn from them. You saw in '95, I tried to do things
that weren't there. Today I just hit the ball where it was pitched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'll ever close the books on what happened in
'95. You gotta keep those things in the back of your mind. You
admit it and understand it. It will always be a lesson for me _ to
sit back and let the game come to you and not try to go out and
force it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely not over yet. There's still a lot of games to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a mistake to dismiss Cleveland so quickly, but Tuesday's
surgical dismantling of the Indians in the first game of the
divisional playoffs served to fortify the growing faith of the
oft-fickle Fenway fandom. It was a win right off the winter
blueprint. Vaughn drove home seven and wonderboy shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra knocked in the other four to complete the scoring for
$75 million ace Pedro Martinez, who cruised to his first postseason
win.
</P>
<P>
   Mo, Nomar, and Pedro. They are the holy trinity of Boston's
Church of Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt really confident out there, especially getting those
three runs ahead,'' said Martinez. ``I knew what to do _ make my
pitches and get the ball over and keep that (early) three-run lead.
I didn't want to walk anybody. It looks ugly for a veteran pitcher
to walk batters with a big lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Beating Cleveland is no fluke. The Red Sox now have nine
victories in 12 games against the Tribe this year. This is an
Indian team that played only one game over .500 after the All-Star
break, spent the year on cruise control in the cheesey AL Central
Division, and dropped six of its last seven _ including three of
four to the woeful Twins.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians can't hit Pedro. In four games this year, Cleveland
has just 21 hits, 7 earned runs, and 32 strikeouts in 32 innings
against him. The Indians know they've got Pedro at least once more
if they extend this series. All the pressure will be on Cleveland
Wednesday when Tim Wakefield goes against Dwight Gooden.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one is the first,'' said Pedro. ``I don't believe in
anything about Bambino or curses or any of that. All I believe in
is smoke.'
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Darren Bragg interrupted, ``All he believes in is 96
miles an hour on the black.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's two-homer performance was the first by a Red Sox player
in postseason play since Rico Petrocelli and Carl Yastrzemski had
two-homer games in the 1967 World Seriers.
</P>
<P>
   The '67 club is the most beloved Sox team since 1918, and now
we've got Mo &AMP; Co. bringing back all the good feeling New England
had for its team in the golden Summer of Love.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, no one is nervous. No one is fretting, waiting for
something bad to happen. The 1998 Red Sox weren't expected to go
anywhere, and now that they're in the postseason, they're insulated
from some of the torment that haunted their hardball forefathers.
</P>
<P>
   Let's dream. Jump the gun. Forget about past losses and
exaggerate the win. Finish off the Indians. Bring on the Yanks.
Bring on the Cubs. Bring on the (gulp) champagne.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
