<HEADLINE>
LINUX OPERATING SYSTEM GETS A MAJOR INFUSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The upstart computer operating system Linux took a big step into
the big time Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The world's top chip maker, Intel Corp., has purchased a stake
in Red Hat Software Inc. of Triangle Research Park, N.C., a leading
distributor of Linux.
</P>
<P>
   Intel is part of a team of investors that also includes browser
maker Netscape Communications Corp. and venture capital firms
Greylock of Boston and Benchmark Capital of Menlo Park, Calif. &UR;  &LR; The
investment group will acquire a minority stake in Red Hat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The deal provides a major credibility boost for Linux, an
operating system being touted as an alternative to Microsoft
Corp.'s dominant Windows system.
</P>
<P>
   Linux is an ``open-source'' software product. Unlike Windows and
other kinds of software, Linux is available free of charge. In
addition, Linux comes with source code &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; the original computer
code as written by the programmers. That way, a Linux user can
modify the operating system to suit his own needs, something that
can't be done with Windows. In recent months, a number of major
software companies, including Netscape and database makers Oracle
Corp. and Informix Corp, have said they would write software to run
on Linux-based machines.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Linux costs nothing, closely held Red Hat sells an
easy-to-install version of Linux and provides the buyer with
technical support. This business model has helped give Linux a
toehold in corporations and government agencies. But many corporate
computer users still hang back, unwilling to count on software that
isn't supported by a major corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Red Hat president Robert Young says a deal with Intel and
Netscape could well break down resistance to Linux. Corporate
executives ``no longer have to hide the fact that they're building
servers and rolling out workstations running Linux,'' said Young.
</P>
<P>
   Young said Red Hat would use the infusion of capital to
establish a new enterprise computing division that would provide
support for major firms using Linux.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape is locked in a tough battle with Microsoft for control
of the Internet browser market. Over the past year, Netscape
executives have argued that Linux could be a major challenger to
Microsoft's near-monopoly on desktop operating systems. Yet Intel
is a close ally of Microsoft _ so close that Microsoft's Windows
and Intel's processor chips are often described with a single word
_ Wintel.
</P>
<P>
   Intel spokesman Robert Manetta said that the investment in Red
Hat is not a sign that Intel's relationship to Microsoft is
weakening. Manetta said the investment is part of a long-term Intel
policy of investing in up-and-coming technology companies. He said
Intel has invested $750 million in about 125 small firms, while
remaining a strong Microsoft ally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has really changed between the two companies,''
Manetta said. ``It's business as usual.'' Microsoft marketing
manager Ed Muth agreed, predicting that Intel's support of Linux
would have relatively little impact on Microsoft's share of the
operating system market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
