<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ROME-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTDOWN TO JUBILEE: WILL ROME BE READY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Oct. 4)  
(JT) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Rome is a huge construction site. Actually, it has 700
construction sites, according to the city's mayor, Francesco
Rutelli, and about 200 of them are in preparation for the Jubilee,
the Roman Catholic Church's celebration of the millennium. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scaffolding, the decoration of choice, masks the front of the
Palazzo Venezia, drapes the facade of St. Peter's Basilica and is
stuck to the front of the Palazzo Farnese. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The projects stretch from the sublime to the pedestrian. The
splendid mosaics of Santa Maria Maggiore are being restored, and
toilets are being installed on the roof of St. Peter's, near where
tourists begin the long, twisting climb to the top of
Michelangelo's dome. Around St. Peter's Square, the columns of
Bernini's colonnade are being scrubbed white. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Traffic is more chaotic than ever. To allow the work around St.
Peter's and the Vatican to proceed, entire avenues have been
rerouted around the Castel Sant'Angelo and back and forth across
the Tiber. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1300, Pope Boniface VIII adapted the jubilee, originally a
Jewish tradition in which every 50th year was set aside for God to
Christian use. Ever since, the church has begun each century with a
Holy Year, urging Christians to do penance and, if possible, to
visit Rome. As the next jubilee quickly approaches, Rome is
primping. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rutelli, the mayor, has been given a new title, special
government commissioner for the jubilee. He has traveled to the
United States, armed with facts and figures, to explain the
preparations, and on a recent Thursday served as tour guide to a
busload of foreign journalists visiting the principal building
sites. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A computer program based on advance tour bookings spits out ever
newer projections of the number of visitors. At last count, the
forecast was for 26 million in the year 2000 (including 2.5 million
Americans), against 14 million in 1997. ``But Rome is a large
city,'' Rutelli said, reassuringly, ``and it's getting ready for
the event.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Given the jubilee's religious nature, much activity focuses on
St. Peter's and the Vatican. The Janiculum Hill, next to the
Vatican, is being hollowed for an underground garage for cars and
tour buses. An automobile tunnel now running under the hill will
double in capacity by the addition of a second level under the
existing roadway. At the Vatican Museums, the massive walls are
being pierced to create an entrance complex _ with gift shops,
cafeteria and waiting areas _ capable of sheltering several
thousand visitors and thus eliminating the endless lines that often
snake around the walls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The work engulfs the city and involves the construction of eight
hotels, including a Hyatt at the airport, and expansion of the
subway to include a link, under construction for more than a
decade, from the city's edge to stations near the Vatican that are
scheduled to open in December.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Waving notes, Rutelli counted up the sums: $2 billion from the
Italian government for the restoration; $2.5 billion from public
and private corporations to upgrade telecommunications, and perhaps
another $1.5 billion from small businesses like hotels and
restaurants for their own renovation. In all, in the next year or
two Rome will spend on beautification about the same amount that it
spent in all of the last 10 years.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The jubilee will run from Christmas Eve 1999 to early in 2001,
and will be marked mainly by religious observances. But the city is
preparing a companion program of exhibits and events, focusing
mainly on the theme of Christianity in art and history. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Major excavations are under way in the Roman Forum, and there
are plans to open long-unused sewage tunnels to permit tourists to
walk undisturbed under the broad Via dei Fori Imperiali from one
part of the forum to another. To increase the city's cultural
offerings, a vast new auditorium, designed by Renzo Piano, the
winner of this year's Pritzker Prize, is being built on the
northern outskirts of the city; it will house a multiplex cinema in
addition to three concert halls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Rome was not built in a day, nor will it be restored in that
time, giving rise to a vexing question: Will the work be done when
the pilgrims begin to arrive? Succumbing to an access of realism,
several projects were canceled before they started, like a third
line for the subway and a highway tunnel skirting the Castel
Sant'Angelo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When asked when this or that project would be done, Rutelli
repeatedly replied, ``late 1999.'' The lower level of the Janiculum
tunnel, for instance, one of the biggest works, is not expected to
be complete before November 1999, perilously close to the jubilee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pierluigi Borghini, the head of the opposition in the city
council, thinks that is cutting it too close. ``I have the
impression that this administration has transformed hopes into
certainties,'' he said during a recent tour of the tunnel site. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rutelli sounds unfazed. ``Romans aren't used to changing their
habits; they have to learn,'' he said, responding to questions
about the slow progress of the work. ``We're not tearing our hair
out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
