<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIV-PARTNERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD MAKE STATES NOTIFY SEXUAL PARTNERS OF HIV-INFECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Supporters of a bill that would require states to
notify the sexual partners of HIV-positive people argued Tuesday it
would save lives and ease suffering, but opponents said it would
deter high-risk people from seeking testing and treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would require that physicians report the names
of people who test positive for the AIDS virus to state public
health officials, who would then inform sexual partners without
revealing the identity of the person who may have exposed them. But
if the individual refused to identify sexual partners, there would
be no criminal or civil penalty.
</P>
<P>
   If a state refused to comply, it would lose federal funding for
AIDS treatment and prevention. Under current law, states are
supposed to notify present and past spouses of people with AIDS,
but critics say that is not being done.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS is an affliction in which the human immunodeficiency virus
weakens the immune system, subjecting the body to serious
infection. AIDS is most often spread through sexual contact,
sharing contaminated needles and infected blood products.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., a physician who sponsored the measure
with Rep. Gary L. Ackerman, D-N.Y., said the bill would break ``the
cycle of transmission by identifying those at risk of infection''
and enable people infected with the virus to get medical care that
can stave off the onset of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn said HIV has wrongly been treated ``like a civil rights
issue instead of a public health crisis'' since the 1980s, placing
the privacy rights of those infected above the public good.
</P>
<P>
   Other infectious diseases such as gonorrhea, hepatitis and
syphilis are reported to the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta. While every state reports cases of AIDS,
just 33 states report HIV cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, thousands of people have tragically died of AIDS
when their infections could have been prevented had public policy
followed basic public health policy,'' Coburn said at a hearing on
the legislation by the House Commerce Committee's health and
environment panel.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman, who testified before the panel, said the question is
simple: ``Do people have a right to know if someone infected them
with AIDS?''
</P>
<P>
   ``In an ideal world, partners would confess _ but disclosing
doesn't come easily,'' Ackerman said. ``The purpose of our bill is
not to penalize, but to protect infected partners.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Nancy Pelosi, who testified that 15,000 people in her
San Francisco district had died of AIDS complications, said
requiring states to reveal the names of HIV-infected people and
their partners ``threatens to discourage high-risk individuals from
being tested and getting care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can not fight disease by undermining trust in health
care,'' Pelosi, a Democrat, said. ``In the provision of health
care, privacy and trust are essential.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said voluntary cooperation is the key to getting people
to prevent HIV infection and seek care for it. She also said many
women who disclose HIV infection to a partner suffer from domestic
violence.
</P>
<P>
   But Ackerman said the ``real domestic violence is to knowingly
have a disease, infect your partner and not tell that person the
facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif., a member of the health panel,
said he understood why people with HIV might be afraid of having
their names posted on a government list, because many of those
infected _ drug users and homosexuals _ are ``among parts of our
population that have been scorned.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Helene D. Gayle, director of the National Center for HIV,
Sexually Transmitted Diseases and Tuberculosis Prevention, urged
members of the panel not to enact the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle testified that the Coburn-Ackerman legislation would scare
people away from medical care by eliminating anonymous HIV testing.
She also said it would be tough to identify past sexual partners of
HIV-infected people because it is difficult, if not impossible, to
determine when a person is infected.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle also said confidentiality must be assured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Partners may fear discrimination, abuse, domestic violence,
loss of jobs or important personal relationships,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is modeled after a New York law enacted this
year that requires physicians to notify the state Department of
Health when a patient tests positive for HIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a disease that's not going to go away,'' New York
Assemblywoman Nettie Mayerson, who sponsored the state legislation,
told the House panel. ``We have to deal with it not as a civil
rights issue, but as ... the biggest public health menace of our
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
