<HEADER>
A0794 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NOTES-945(2TAKES)-     09-29 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-945(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRUBBING FOR GRADES  
 BUT DOES OSCAR LIKE IT?  
 THE SITCOM SIREN SONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.)  
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   First report cards for network television this season: some
solid grades for new series, a lot of gentleman's C's, a few
perilous scores that could point to early failure, but mainly more
lessons for every network in the new competitive field of six
networks plus cable, which leaves them hard pressed to find an A.
</P>
<P>
   Even though several networks predicted ratings improvements this
season, the first week showed declines for every single one. The
score: network television down 10 percent, cable up 15 percent. But
of the 10 top cable networks, six were down. Those whose ratings
were up included the Weather Channel, thanks to Hurricane Georges,
and CNN and CNBC, thanks to Hurricane Monica.
</P>
<P>
   The week went best for CBS, which had the most viewers over all
for the first time since 1993. That happened to be the last time
that the network had National Football League football games on
Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   NBC showed the biggest drop in viewers, but some of that was to
be expected, with the network losing not only football but also its
real touchdown hero, Jerry Seinfeld.
</P>
<P>
   ABC hoped mostly for an end to the steep ratings slides of
recent seasons and found solace in the modest drop it recorded last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The worst showing probably was that of the Fox network, which
took a pretty thorough beating. Except for Monday night, Fox did
not beat CBS among viewers from age 18 to 49, even though it prides
itself on appealing to young viewers and CBS is often derided in
the business as the senior-citizen network.
</P>
<P>
   Fox restricts its competitive standing to that group, and was
the second-ranking network among young viewers last season. Last
week it finished fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has traditionally had trouble with the season's premiere
week. It holds back its biggest hit, ``The X-Files,'' until
November. But surely disturbing to Fox was the disappointing
performance by ``King of the Hill,'' moved from Sundays to
Tuesdays. It got trounced last week. More ominously, the show that
replaced it on Sundays, ``That '70s Show,'' was off 31 percent with
younger viewers.
</P>
<P>
   One big reason, and perhaps more cause for Fox to worry, has
been the dismal showing this summer of repeats of ``The X-Files.''
Did turning that series into a movie dilute interest in the
television show? Fox will wait for November a bit more anxiously
than before.
</P>
<P>
   CBS had reason to be pleased with ``Everybody Loves Raymond''
and a new series, ``King of Queens,'' on Monday; ``JAG'' on
Tuesday; another new series, ``Martial Law,'' on Saturday, and its
entire Sunday lineup. But it also got a boost from the 32nd Annual
Country Music Awards on Wednesday that will not be duplicated, and
one new show, ``Brian Benben,'' stumbled badly.
</P>
<P>
   ABC got its best news from a new series, ``The Hughleys,'' on
Tuesday, where ``Spin City'' held its own against ``Just Shoot Me''
on NBC. Several other spots showed improvement over dead areas last
year, including a Thursday movie and especially a new lineup on
ABC's child-friendly Fridays. But two new dramas on Saturday,
``Fantasy Island'' and ``Cupid,'' fell short of the network's
hopes.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's Thursday was predictably down without ``Seinfeld'' and
without ``E.R.'' doing a special event like last year's live
episode. But the network still dominated the night as its five
shows took the top five spots on the rating chart. That included
one new series, ``Jesse,'' that is off to an especially promising
start. Another new series, ``Will and Grace,'' was modestly
impressive, but ``Encore! Encore!'' with Nathan Lane looked
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   But Does Oscar Like It?
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being brought to you by the letter K or the number 3,
starting soon ``Sesame Street'' will be brought to you by Discovery
Zone indoor playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in its 30-year history, ``Sesame Street,''
the pioneer and still the reigning role model in preschool
educational television, has signed up a corporate underwriter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a more competitive environment than ever before,'' said
Gary Knell, the executive vice president for operations at
Children's Television Workshop, which produces and owns ``Sesame
Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only do other PBS children's programs have corporate
underwriters _ Kellogg's Frosted Flakes and Chuck E. Cheese for
``Barney and Friends,'' for example, or Libby's Juicy Juice and
Baby Gap for ``Arthur'' _ but Children's Television Workshop has
had to generate much of the money to produce ``Sesame Street'' by
selling videos, CDs, books and licensed merchandise like Cookie
Monster dolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally we've subsidized the show itself for many
millions of dollars, and we felt we could make up some of that
money through these corporate sponsorships,'' Knell said, adding
that it was a ``seven-figure'' deal with Discovery Zone and that
the company is pursuing several other underwriters.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Montgomery, president of the Center for Media Education,
a research and advocacy group that focuses on the media's influence
on children, said she was concerned by the shift, even if the
Discovery Zone messages were to be ``pro-social,'' as Knell said
they would be.
</P>
<P>
   ```Sesame Street' was the last bastion of really quality,
completely noncommercial programming, where parents of preschoolers
could feel safe in having their children watch without being
targets of marketing,'' she said. ``This is part of a disturbing
trend in public television.''
</P>
<P>
   The 15-second Discovery Zone credits, at the beginning and end
of each episode, will begin on Nov. 16, when ``Sesame Street''
starts its 30th season on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The Sitcom Siren Song
</P>
<P>
   Susan Harris, one of television's most successful and prolific
comedy writers, has told the world for five years that she was
permanently retired after a career in which she wrote the first 70
episodes of the 1970s hit ``Soap'' and created other hits like
``Golden Girls,'' ``Benson'' and ``Empty Nest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But Hollywood is kind of a hard town to stay retired in; they
keep looking for you,'' Ms. Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   So after saying no to numerous network entreaties, Ms. Harris
has created a new comedy for ABC, ``The Secret Lives of Men,''
which begins Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling fine about not writing,'' she said. She quit
shortly after she and her husband and production partner, Paul
Junger Witt, had a baby 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly the men around her, including the couple's partner,
Tony Thomas, started getting divorced and ``this show popped into
my head _ a show about divorced guys in their 30s,'' Ms. Harris
said. ``It was full of funny, rich stuff. It sort of wrote
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she discovered by listening in on men's conversations
that contrary to their image, ``men do talk to each other.'' The
critical reaction to the show has been mixed, which she said
surprised her. ``Maybe it's a Clinton backlash _ a touchy-feely guy
who can almost cry on cue. Maybe some people don't want to see
those kind of guys on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC certainly had a positive reaction; the network gave the show
its best spot for a new comedy, after ``The Drew Carey Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Harris has written the first 10 episodes, and she admits to
being ``near tears'' over the weekly production grind. ``When I was
sitting home writing, I was happy. When it all starts in
production, I regret ever having done this.''
</P>
<P>
   She does not regret the time period or the chance to build
another hit. If the show goes well, she said, she will probably
write a couple more episodes this season and two or three to start
next season. ``Then,'' she said, ``it will be time to back off and
get my life back.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
</TEXT>
