<SLUG> BC-FAT-CALORIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE FIGHT AGAINST FAT, WE FORGOT ABOUT SUGAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're all counting fat grams and eating low-fat cookies. So how
come we keep getting fatter?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe because we're eating too many calorie-laden low-fat and
fat-free snack foods, suggest surveys commissioned by the U.S.
Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are getting a lower percentage of their calories from
fat (34 percent, down from close to 40 percent five years ago), but
we're eating more calories overall. The number of people overweight
and obese is at an all-time high, notes the American Heart
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, too many people mistakenly believe that if they
count fat grams, they can ignore calories.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people read labels, they're more likely to notice what's
low-fat and `healthy,' but may not be looking at calories,'' says
Karen Donato, coordinator of the National Heart, Lung and Blood
Institute's Obesity Education Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, more people are eating out, and portion sizes have
increased,'' Donato says. ``Another issue is decreased physical
activity. So, people are consuming more calories and are less
active. It doesn't take much to tip the energy balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though weight-lifting and kick-boxing classes are in vogue,
studies indicate that Americans are more sedentary on the job and
in their leisure time. We turn on the television and open the
garage door with the push of a button, step on the elevator to
``climb'' a single flight of stairs, and sit in front of computer
terminals for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Children also are watching far more television and are less
physically active than in the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we broaden our definition of obesity to include people who
are overweight, over 50 percent of American adults and 15 to 20
percent of our children are overweight today,'' says Dr. Robert
Eckel, professor of medicine and physiology and program director of
the General Research Center at the University of Colorado Health
Science Center in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to some widely circulated ideas about low-fat eating,
calories do count,'' Eckel says. ``We need to wake up. We're too
heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lower-fat foods may have contributed to the mistaken idea that
there are some ``free'' foods that we can overindulge in without
paying much attention to how much we are eating, says Barbara
Gollman, a spokesman for the American Dietetic Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another problem is that our frequency of eating out is
increasing, and it's adding up on our hips,'' Gollman says.
``Portions are larger and foods are richer than they need to be for
healthy eating. And we tend to think of eating out as a special
occasion, so we celebrate with foods we might not eat at home.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   INFO BOX
</P>
<P>
   Watching fat intake is important, but fat-free foods sometimes
have as many calories as regular foods, or even more.
</P>
<P>
   Fat-free fig cookie _ 70 calories
</P>
<P>
   Regular fig cookie _ 50 calories
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup premium nonfat ice cream _ 190 calories
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup regular ice cream _ 180 calories
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons reduced-fat peanut butter _ 190 calories
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons regular peanut butter _ 190 calories
</P>
<P>
   Source: The National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
