<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0813 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-DISSENT-625&AMP;ADD     09-29 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DISSENT-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE DISSIDENTS ISSUE A SHARP CHALLENGE TO THE GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A small group of dissident intellectuals here has
issued a sharp challenge to the government, circulating two
manifestoes on freedom and social justice that reject in scathing
terms many hallowed tenets of the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge arises as the government acts to stamp out a
fledgling alternative political party, in recent weeks temporarily
detaining many of its leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The two new declarations, about five single-spaced pages each in
English translation, are circulating on the Internet and in faxed
copies. One, a ``Declaration on Civil Rights and Freedom,'' details
how individual rights are suppressed in China and rejects the
government's argument that human rights are a relative concept, to
be adapted to national conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The second, a ``Declaration on Civil Rights and Social
Justice,'' analyzes what the writers say is the theft of the fruits
of the emerging market economy by a privileged clique.
</P>
<P>
   The manifestoes place unusual emphasis on social justice and a
link between dictatorship and the cornering of economic wealth. The
arguments could have popular appeal in China, because as the
dazzling economic growth of recent years begins to stall, concerns
about corruption and inequality are rising.
</P>
<P>
   More unusual is that the statements, which do not mince words in
their indictments of the communist system, are signed by five
people who are still living here, albeit under the close watch of
security agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will assume the consequences of issuing these declarations,
including the possibility of being sent to prison,'' said a signer,
Ding Zilin.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ding and her husband, Jiang Peikun, also a signer and said
to be the chief drafter of the declarations, are the parents of a
student who was killed when the army smashed pro-democracy
demonstrations in 1989 in Tiananmen Square. Retired professors at
People's University in Beijing, they are known as tireless
campaigners for an official reappraisal of the student movement.
</P>
<P>
   The other signers are Wei Xiaotao, an engineer and the younger
brother of an exiled dissident, Wei Jingsheng; Lin Mu, onetime
Communist Party secretary of Northwestern University in Xian, and
Jiang Qisheng, a former doctoral candidate at People's University
who was jailed for one and a half years after 1989 and never
allowed to resume his studies.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang said in an interview Tuesday that individual freedoms and
rights were a ``core value of all humanity'' and that through the
declarations ``we hope we can arouse a peaceful and open popular
movement demanding these freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   The declaration on rights and freedom includes a frontal assault
on the primacy of the Communist Party, still a cardinal principle
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``China's rulers continue to impose on all Chinese citizens a
political party that cannot represent the interests and will of all
the people,'' the statement says. ``If this situation continues
there is bound to be increasing conflict with the reality of
pluralistic interests and values that have emerged in the process
of China's modernization.''
</P>
<P>
   The document belittles China's efforts to promote the rule of
law, saying the legal system remains ``a tool used by the ruling
clique to maintain and safeguard its grip on power.''
</P>
<P>
   The second manifesto, on rights and social justice, contends
that economic changes here have enabled a political elite and those
who curry its favor to enrich themselves at the expense of the
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society's wealth,'' it says, ``is not being accumulated by
hard-working, pioneering and law-abiding people, but is falling
into the hands of the dregs of society, the holders of privileged
power and their sycophants, corrupt officials and those who steal
what they are entrusted with protecting.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Ding, speaking by telephone from Wuxi in Jiangsu Province,
where she and her husband are spending the fall, said the group had
not tried to enlist other signers, in part because of the danger.
</P>
<P>
   She said the process of discussing and sharing drafts had been
nerve-racking. Wei and Jiang Qisheng were briefly detained because
of their work on the declarations, as were other friends who sent
related faxes or messages.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ding said the authors had faxed the declarations to a
contact in New York for translation into English and distribution
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The declarations have been posted on the sites of a group in New
York, Human Rights in China (http://www.hrichina.org) and an
international group, the Digital Freedom Network
(http://www.dfn.org).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
