<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYBODY'S GETTING RELIGION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; _ Larry King &LR; 's new book is ``Powerful Prayers,'' a scholarly
treatise on celebrities and religion.
</P>
<P>
   The book is co-written by Rabbi  &UR; Irwin Katsof &LR; , billed as a
``spiritual trainer'' who has ministered to  &UR; Jason Alexander &LR; ,
 &UR; Kirk Douglas  &LR; and  &UR; Rod Steiger &LR; . Among those who revealed their
prayer habits, as quoted in the Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jack Kevorkian &LR; , who said, ``When I listen to Bach's music,
that's my prayer'';  &UR; Delta Burke &LR; , who said she puts candles in the
bathroom and ``one of my favorite places to pray is in the
shower''; and the  &UR; Dalai Lama &LR; , who says that prayers to  &UR; Buddha &LR; 
are prayers to a ``higher being. The Buddha, the origin of Buddha,
is just like ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; William F. Buckley &LR; 's new book about his commitment to
Catholicism is ``Nearer, My God: An Autobiography of Faith.'' If
anyone could prove that &UR; Christ &LR;  did not rise from the grave,
Buckley writes, he would ``instantly enlist in the Judaic faith.''
Buckley will speak at a Commonwealth Club luncheon October 12.
</P>
<P>
   _ In a Jewish Bulletin story headlined, `` &UR; McGwire &LR; ,  &UR; Sosa &LR;  Hit
One Over Fence for Judaism,''  &UR; Joseph Aaron &LR;  likens baseball fans
to Jews coming back into the fold. As to  &UR; Roger Maris &LR; , ``He is to
baseball what the Conservative movement is to Judaism,'' writes
Aaron, explaining everything.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Gay Talese &LR;  told Washingtonian magazine why Irish American
journalists _ including &UR; Maureen Dowd &LR; ,  &UR; Michael Kelly &LR; ,  &UR; Tim &LR; 
 &UR; Russert &LR; ,  &UR; Mary McGrory &LR;  and  &UR; Pat Buchanan &LR;  _ have been so hard on
 &UR; Bill &LR;   &UR; Clinton &LR; , while Italian American politicians _ among them,
Senator  &UR; Robert Torricelli &LR; , D-N.J., and Representative  &UR; Nancy &LR; 
 &UR; Pelosi &LR; , D-San Francisco, have been more forgiving:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Irish have been in the forefront of sexual repression for
centuries,'' said Talese, whose heritage, obviously, is Italian.
``They drove  &UR; James Joyce  &LR; out of Ireland, and every other creative
soul who might be dealing with erotica. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Irishmen always want to be policemen, and the Irish media want
the President to climb up the hill on bloody knees like the
Stations of the Cross. Italy is a very male country which has
always been anticlerical. Men run Italy. They don't abide the
church and aren't shocked by adultery. Ireland is a very female
country run by suffering nuns.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GETTING THE GOODS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Lee Radziwill &LR;  has signed with Random House for the
publication of her autobiography, the cleverly titled ``The Way It
Was,'' reports the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Among Radziwill's many accomplishments: She is  &UR; Jacqueline &LR; 
 &UR; Onassis &LR; ' sister and attended many jet-set parties with well-known
people. Her agent,  &UR; Andrew Wylie &LR; , told the Times that she is
writing the book all by herself in longhand. No dollar amounts were
revealed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hasbro Inc. is casting the head of  &UR; Colin Powell &LR;  in plastic
in preparation for making a toy action figure, part of its Historic
Commanders Assortment. According to Time magazine, the company is
also planning to launch a Hollywood Hero series;  &UR; Bob &LR; 
 &UR; Hope &LR;  will be first in the line.
</P>
<P>
   _ The men's-wear daily DNR asked 25 professionals ``in the land
of Silicon and Money'' _ here _ ``to talk about how they dress and
why.''
</P>
<P>
   The responses ranged from  &UR; John Payne &LR;  of Fabrik Communications
(``When I dress up in straight Italian stuff, it's Corneliana, Hugo
Boss and Versace. I'll wear that to board meetings'') to  &UR; Jason Wu &LR; 
of Netscape (``On television, I look for how the president and  &UR; Jay
Leno  &LR; dressed today'') to  &UR; Valentino &LR; 
 &UR; Tiangco  &LR; of the California Energy Commission (``I go to Old Navy _
I like to be cheap _ and Men's Wearhouse'').
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; T.S. Bolton &LR; 's response to complaints about  &UR; Kenneth &LR; 
 &UR; Starr &LR; 's $40 million investigation: ``Titanic'' cost $200 million
and ``it wasn't nearly as entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _ Among the inexplicable items  &UR; Michael Jarvis &LR;  was amazed to
find on MSNBC's list of Lewinsky-to-Clinton gifts: The CDs ``Secret
of Life'' and Mexican love songs, ``Frog on a Limb,'' portrait of
 &UR; Virginia Kelley &LR; , shoe bags and an executive stress-relief toy.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Clinton-to-Lewinsky items listed by the Washington
Post: a large Rockettes blanket, a shamrock pin and a small box of
cherry chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were doing it over again, I would not have (had that
many), but I can't shoot them now that they're here.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ted Turner, father of five, saying he thinks other people
ought to agree to a worldwide limit of one child per family. Turner
was quoted in the Los Angeles Times.
</P>
</TEXT>
