<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0819 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-HOUSE-BOS &LR;      09-29 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE EMBROILED IN IMPEACHMENT DISCUSSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Signs of disarray abound as the House confronts the
momentous task of weighing President Clinton's possible
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the frenzy, many House Democrats seethed at their leader,
Representative Richard A. Gephardt, last week for calling on
Republicans to resolve the Clinton inquiry within 30 days. Gephardt
issued the challenge a day before his party's 206 House members
could have discussed the strategy at their weekly policy meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought 30 days was a mistake to talk about,'' said
Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat and senior
member of the House Judiciary Committee, the day after Gephardt's
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many House Republicans privately railed
against Speaker Newt Gingrich's confrontational role in the
impeachment matter. Fearing Gingrich's rhetoric could dissolve the
aura of bipartisanship they need to preserve their credibility,
rank-and-file GOP members succeeded in steering him away from the
spotlight, if only temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes in the tumultuous early stages of the landmark
inquiry. From top to bottom, the House is embroiled, as one senior
Democratic staff member observed Tuesday, in ``a frantic,
unmethodical, narrow-minded, play-it-by-the-half-hour process''
that threatens to undermine the public's faith in the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   News conferences erupt in partisan bickering, as lawmakers
jostle for position before the cameras. Rival aides on the
Judiciary Committee argue bitterly in the hallways outside the
hearing room, accusing each other of engaging in unsavory politics.
</P>
<P>
   And many lawmakers, cringing at the confusion, are voicing
concerns about the potential consequences for themselves, the
presidency and the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It undercuts everything. Everything,'' said the Senate
majority leader, Trent Lott, Tuesday about recent attacks by
Democrats on the Republican handling of the impeachment process, a
criticism of the GOP that several recent polls show a majority of
Americans agree with.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent burst of animosity among lawmakers in both
parties, Representative Henry J. Hyde of Illinois, the Judiciary
Committee chairman, said the fighting has been ``horrendous.''
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee, which is conducting a preliminary
impeachment inquiry, is expected to recommend early next week that
the House open a full-scale investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are so high that if Congress convicts Clinton without
a fair, orderly impeachment, the repercussions could harm the
country for a generation or more, asserted Representative Jerrold
Nadler, a New York Democrat who serves on the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Mishandling the process could create ``the most divisive act
since the Vietnam War,'' Nadler said. ``If we're not going to have
20 years of recriminations, then it has to be done fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the first signs of constructive bipartisanship among
Judiciary Committee members, four lawmakers Tuesday sent Hyde a
letter asking him to determine whether the independent counsel,
Kenneth W. Starr, plans to forward evidence to the House on his
other investigations of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. William D. Delahunt, a Massachusetts Democrat who has
avoided partisan grandstanding and opted for trying to work with
several committee Republicans behind the scenes, forged the
preliminary alliance with Democrat Howard L. Berman of California,
and two Republicans: Representatives Lindsey O. Graham of South
Carolina, and W. Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   In their letter to Hyde, the four expressed concern that Starr
recently indicated he would ``soon make final decisions about what
steps to take, if any, with respect to the other information'' on
his investigation into the Whitewater real estate transaction, the
firings of the White House travel office, and the administration's
improper use of FBI files.
</P>
<P>
   The four lamwakers asserted the impeachment inquiry could be
damaged by a raft of new information from Starr on matters
unrelated to Clinton's sex scandal. In asking Hyde to consult
Starr, Delahunt's coalition stated, ``It will minimize the risk
that new information might surface at a later date, forcing the
committee to subject the American people to the entire process all
over again.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Hyde tried to ease partisan tensions on Monday by
granting a number of high-priority requests from the Democratic
minority. Notable among them was his pledge that President Clinton
and his lawyers will be permitted to fully participate in a formal
impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The House is expected to approve the inquiry late next week.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde also reversed position and permitted committee
investigators from both parties to begin inspecting an estimated 20
boxes of additional evidence related to Clinton's affair with
Monica S. Lewinsky that Starr did not deliver to Congress.
Democrats suspect the material may contain information that could
help Clinton's defense.
</P>
<P>
   But discord persists as the votes draw near on whether to open a
formal inquiry. Emotions are particularly raw on the Judiciary
Committee, which is far more widely divided along ideological lines
than the House itself.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, for example, continues to anger Democrats over his
position on numerous issues, including leaving open the possibility
of expanding the potential impeachment inquiry to matters that are
not under Starr's jurisdiction such as campaign fund-raising abuses
in the 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the final batch of Starr's investigative material
that the Judiciary Committee approved making public is scheduled to
be released Thursday or Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The material, which House investigators in both parties said
contains ``no smoking guns,'' is expected to provide extensive
details about several key elements of Starr's investigation,
including Linda R. Tripp's controversial role in secretly taping
dozens of phone calls with Lewinsky and in wearing a hidden
recording device for the FBI to monitor a conversation with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The documents include a claim by former Clinton adviser Dick
Morris that presidential allies had mounted a ``secret police
operation to go around and intimidate women'' who may have been
involved with the president. But in an interview with The
Associated Press, Morris said his testimony was based on no
firsthand information and was a supposition based on his reading of
affidavits and published accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, in her conversation recorded by the FBI, is said to
have told Tripp, ``I wouldn't cross these people for fear of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, the material to be released indicates that White House
adviser Sidney Blumenthal asked Hillary Rodham Clinton about
Lewinsky and was told not to worry, that the president was
``ministering to a troubled young person.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Chris Black of the Globe staff provided material for this
story. Wire service material was also used in its preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
