<SLUG> BC-MAGNETAR-EARTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARTH BLASTED BY ENERGY FROM DISTANT STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earth's upper atmosphere in August crackled with a burst of
energy from an exotic kind of star halfway across the galaxy that
blew its stack, undergoing a starquake so massive that it spewed
out more energy in five minutes than all of human civilization
could use in a billion billion years.
</P>
<P>
   Seven different spacecraft picked up x-ray energy measurements
so strong their instruments were swamped; two of them were so
overwhelmed they shut themselves down for protection.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time, astronomers said Tuesday, that an
identifiable distant star has had a significant impact on Earth's
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The blast of energy caused the uppermost layer of Earth's
atmosphere, the ionosphere, to become as electrically charged in
the middle of the night as it normally is in daytime when bathed in
the sun's radiation _ even though the outburst took place 20,000
light years, or 120 billion billion miles, away from the Earth and
sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as if night was suddenly turned into day in the
ionosphere,'' said Umran Inan, a professor of electrical
engineering at Stanford University who was part of a team that
measured the disruption to the atmosphere. ``We now know that
Earth's physical environment is affected not only by our own sun
but by energy originating from distant parts of the universe.''
</P>
<P>
   Any astronauts in orbit at the time would have been exposed to a
flash of x-rays about as intense as a dental x-ray, the astronomers
said Tuesday _ not enough to do any harm, but an astonishing amount
considering how distant the source was.
</P>
<P>
   The star that produced the outburst is believed to be only the
second ever discovered of a new type, called a magnetar. The
existence of magnetars was first predicted theoretically six years
ago by astronomers Robert Duncan of the University of Texas and
Christopher Thompson of the University of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Magnetars are a type of neutron star, the densely packed remnant
left behind when certain kinds of stars end their lives in
cataclysmic explosions called supernovae. The dense stars, weighing
more than the sun but packed into a space the size of a city _
about 12 miles across _ have by far the strongest magnetic fields
of any objects known in the universe: ``The magnetic field of the
star is humongous, 300 trillion times more intense than the Earth's
or the sun's,'' said Chryssa Kouveliotou, an astronomer with the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration's Marshall Space
Flight Center in Alabama, at a NASA briefing Tuesday reporting the
observations.
</P>
<P>
   The star, called SGR1900(plus)14, rotates at a rapid clip of
once every 5.1 seconds, and the rotating magnetic field
occasionally causes stresses so great that they crack the star's
mile-thick crust of iron, producing a flash of gamma rays. Such
gamma flashes have been known for 20 years, and their origin has
remained a mystery until this year. Last May, Kouveliotou and her
colleagues published a paper identifying magnetars as the source of
what were known as ``soft gamma-ray repeaters.''
</P>
<P>
   But the outburst that began about 20,000 years ago and
registered here on Aug. 27 was a far more devastating event than
these normal starquakes, she said, and must have involved a vastly
more violent disturbance of the whole star's structure. Such events
are impossible to predict, she said, but this same star may repeat
its performance sometime in the next decade or so. Although
astronomers have been observing some x-rays from the sky for about
two decades, the satellites capable of pinpointing the origin of
such bursts have only been in existence for a few years.
</P>
<P>
   James Cordes of Cornell University said that such stars must
exist throughout the universe, and although massive outbursts such
as the one recorded in August must be extremely rare, chances are
the Earth has been subjected to much closer ones in the distant
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suppose there was one 100 light years away,'' he said. ``The
influence would be 40,000 times greater.'' Although nobody has
analyzed exactly what effects such a blast would have, Cordes said
it is likely that such events have happened within the span of time
that life has existed on Earth, and may have had profound _ and
perhaps detectable _ effects on creatures that lived at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The flash of energy produced by the magnetar was identified by
two specialized astronomical satellites designed to monitor x-rays
and gamma rays _ which are high-energy forms of electromagnetic
radiation, similar to light and radio waves. They are Beppo-SAX, an
Italian and Dutch-built satellite, and NASA's Rossi X-ray Timing
Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The discovery of magnetars is a major breakthrough in
astrophysics,'' Kouveliotou said. And detecting the incredible
outburst of Aug. 27 was an extra bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new kind of star with bizarre properties that
weren't even imagined until a few years ago,'' said Paul Hertz of
NASA headquarters. ``It makes you wonder what else is out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
