<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mississippi begins to pick up Georges's mess
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILOXI, Miss. _ Casinos are known for never closing, but no
bells were ringing and no dice were rolling along Mississippi's
Gulf Coast Tuesday as the area recovered from the devastating winds
of Hurricane Georges.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mississippi did not get the drenching rains that soaked
Alabama and Florida, high winds gusting at times to 170 miles per
hour left gas stations in tatters, downed thousands of trees and
power lines, ripped the roofs of schools and homes, and left piles
of sand along U.S. 90, the scenic highway that runs along the
coast. ``We're doing just fine but I'm not staying next time,''
said Emily Meyers, who was mourning the loss of several fruit trees
in her back yard in Biloxi. ``My nerves still can't settle. I'm
remembering what it felt like waiting to see what would happen
next.''
</P>
<P>
   The casinos in Biloxi suffered only minor damage and expected to
reopen today. But some businesses in this beach resort town,
especially gas stations, looked almost destroyed. From Gulfport to
the Alabama line, coastal Mississippians stepped outside Tuesday
and assessed the damage. Few businesses were open, all schools were
closed. A curfew was in effect from sundown until sunrise today.
</P>
<P>
   The few shops and restaurants that managed to open attracted
customers in droves who stood in lines that snaked into parking
lots. At Lowe's in Gautier, people waited for chain saws, shovels
and plastic sheeting to cover broken windows and torn roofs. In
Pascagoula, they mobbed Domino's Pizza, one of the few places with
hot food.
</P>
<P>
   Most people along the coast had no power and many had no phone
service much of Tuesday, but as the evacuees streamed back south
along U.S 49, so too did hundreds of utility trucks from as far
away as Arkansas and Georgia. The Federal Emergency Management
Agency as well as the Salvation Army, also moved into the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a bad one because of the wind,'' said Leon Gates, who
lives in Pascagoula. His house survived with only a few leaks, but
he had a terrifying experience Monday as Georges blew ashore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I boarded up all my windows and one by one, the boards flew
off,'' he said. ``I'm still getting my nerves back together. I have
stayed through all the hurricanes_Camille, Betsy_but I don't know
if I will stay again. Of course, I always say that.''
</P>
<P>
   Photine Blahos left her brick home in Biloxi, but she was back
Tuesday, sweeping leaves and repairing the roof and trying to get
back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad we left,'' she said. ``They scared us to death with
talk of the storm surge. You can't just sit there in the dark and
wait for the water to come up over your roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
