A0825 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUSGA-COX     09-29 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUSGA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia case against school system to be heard
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court on Tuesday agreed to hear a Georgia case
in which a Forsyth woman seeks to find the school system
responsible for failing to prevent a classmate from sexually
harassing her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Aurelia Davis filed suit against the Monroe
County Board of Education after her daughter, LaShonda, was
harassed at least eight times over six months. At the time,
LaShonda was a fifth-grader at Hubbard Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks the right to sue under Title IX of the
Education Amendments of 1972, which provides that no one, on the
basis of their sex, can be denied benefits or be subjected to
discrimination in educational programs receiving federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' claims were rejected by U.S. District Judge Wilbur Owens
in Macon, reinstated by a three-judge panel of the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta and, in August of last year,
dismissed by the full appeals court in a 7-4 opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thrilled to death,'' Davis said Tuesday after
learning the nation's highest court will hear her case. ``My smile
right now is as wide as the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, 40, said she wants her case to require ``schools to have
a responsibility that schoolchildren will be both served and
protected. My daughter wasn't taken care of and they should pay for
it. . . . I did not set out to make a landmark ruling, but if
that's what it takes to make schools liable, that's what it takes.
It didn't take courage to do this. It took anger, pure anger.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' lawyer, Verna Williams of the Washington-based National
Women's Law Center, expressed confidence the Supreme Court would
rule in her client's favor. ``Schools can't just turn their backs
on the most harmful, severe and pervasive form of harassment that
interferes with students' inability to learn,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision marks the second time the Supreme Court has
picked a Georgia case to determine whether school districts can be
held liable for student harassment and abuse. In 1992, in a
Gwinnett County case, the court ruled school boards could be held
responsible when students are sexually harassed by their teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' lawsuit claims LaShonda was sexually tormented by a male
student, described only as G.F., culminating in a sexual battery to
which he pleaded guilty in Juvenile Court. LaShonda was an A and B
student before the harassment began and then plunged into despair,
receiving failing grades and writing a suicide note her father
found. Her mother complained to school officials who did little
more than separate LaShonda and G.F.'s classroom seating
assignments, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal appeals courts are split on the question of whether
school boards can be held liable under Title IX for
student-on-student sexual harassment. The ruling by the 11th
Circuit, which has jurisdiction over federal cases out of Alabama,
Florida and Georgia, followed a similar opinion by the Fifth
Circuit in New Orleans. The Seventh Circuit in Chicago and the
Ninth Circuit in San Francisco have ruled that school boards can be
held liable.
</P>
<P>
   In the 11th Circuit's decision, Judge Gerald Tjoflat wrote that
the Davis lawsuit ``fails to state a claim under Title IX because
Congress gave no clear notice to schools and teachers that they,
rather than society as a whole, would accept responsibility for
remedying student-student sexual harassment when they chose to
accept federal financial assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Tjoflat said that any decision to the contrary could open the
floodgates to Title IX lawsuits and possibly influence a school
district's decision whether to accept federal funds. He cited a
1993 survey by the American Association of University Women
Educational Foundation which found that 65 percent of all students
in grades eight to 11 were victims of some form of sexual
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   In dissent, Judge Rosemary Barkett said the majority opinion
``ignores the plain meaning of Title IX as well as its spirit and
language. . . . Title IX does not make a school responsible for the
actions of harassing students, but rather for its own
discrimination for failing to remedy it once the school has
notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Hartley, general counsel for the Georgia School Boards
Association, said he hopes that the Supreme Court follows the
guidelines it set in an opinion issued this June in a
teacher-on-student sexual harassment case. In that 5-4 decision,
the court said the Lago Vista Independent School District in Texas
could only be held responsible if a teacher sexually harassed or
abused a student so long as school authorities were notified,
showed a ``deliberate indifference'' and did nothing about it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
