<HEADER>
A0826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEADERSHIP-STUDIES-ED     09-29 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEADERSHIP-STUDIES-EDUC-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERSHIP GROWING AS AN AREA OF STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Texas, Va., N.C.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are leaders born or bred? Can students be taught how to set a
course that others will follow?
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Bryant, director of the Virginia Women's Institute for
Leadership at Mary Baldwin College, a women's college in Staunton,
Va., is a believer. ``If some things can't be taught,'' she
insisted, ``at least they can be learned.'' The institute, whose
mission is to bring out the take-charge qualities in its students,
opened in 1995 with 42 students; it now has 150.
</P>
<P>
   Leadership as an area of study is becoming increasingly popular
at colleges and universities throughout the country. There are
nearly 700 leadership-development programs at American academic
institutions today, about double the number four years ago,
according to the Center for Creative Leadership, a nonprofit
educational research organization based in Greensboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Some are merely resource centers to which prominent leaders are
invited for a day or two in the hope that some charisma will rub
off. But others, including the University of Richmond's program,
address the subject with an array of rigorous courses like
``History and Theories of Leadership'' and ``Leadership in
Political Systems,'' and offer successful candidates a bachelor's
degree in leadership studies.
</P>
<P>
   While it may be too early to gauge the programs' effectiveness,
administrators say the course of study and mentorship help shape
responsible leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that leadership is learned, not just an
attribute,'' said John Burkhardt, a spokesman for the W.K. Kellogg
Foundation in Battle Creek, Mich., which has given about $20
million over the past decade to some 34 institutions to develop
leadership-teaching programs. ``We look to the idealism and energy
of today's youth to use these skills to create a better working
democracy in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   A principal reason for the blossoming of leadership studies is
that, at a time of economic uncertainty, students (and their
parents) see the programs as ``career-planning resources,'' to take
a phrase from the Mount Holyoke College catalog. Mount Holyoke's
program, for example, stresses internships and counseling, with
interviews with prominent professionals in the students' area of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, administrators find leadership development
programs to be effective recruiting tools. Austin College, a
liberal arts school in Sherman, Texas, offers 15 $10,000
scholarships a year to students who enroll in its Leadership
Institute. ``Many others who didn't make it come to us anyway,''
said Shelton Williams, the institute's director.
</P>
<P>
   The standards for admission to such programs are often high.
``We're not just looking for a resume with a lot of presidencies on
it,'' Williams said. ``We're looking for people who created
organizations or took existing ones to a higher level.''
</P>
<P>
   The easy part, most specialists agree, is teaching skills like
running a meeting, resolving conflicts and getting the best out of
creative people. The hard (if not impossible) part is to instill
such essentials of leadership as charisma, perseverance and
trustworthiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to set up a learning situation at Mary Baldwin by
putting the students in leadership situations outside the
classroom, like running a social event or operating a motor pool
for the ROTC,'' Ms. Bryant said. ``They can learn through
experience, so the key to our program is putting the students in
those situations all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes a good student of leadership? Students are graded on
everything from their effectiveness on the speaker's platform to
their ability to analyze success or failure on the part of
historical or fictional figures, ranging from Abraham Lincoln to
Captain Ahab.
</P>
<P>
   The programs have become particularly popular at private women's
colleges. ``It's an outgrowth of the women's movement of the 1980s,
when large numbers of women began entering the upper ranks of
business and politics,'' Ms. Bryant said. ``These programs teach
women the skills they need.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The idea of leadership development can be traced to the
Industrial Revolution, said Mary Schwartz, a spokeswoman for the
Center for Creative Leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first stimulus was when people left the farms and came to
the cities to work in highly organized factories,'' Ms. Schwartz
said. ``They needed help to get people working together. The next
thing was when the soldiers came home from World War II. They tried
to exercise leadership in the control-and-command style, the way
they had done in the military, but it didn't motivate people so
they looked around for something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1959,'' she added, ``the Carnegie and Ford Foundations
simultaneously published reports proposing ways to reform business
and management training at the college and university level, and
that was really the birth of leadership education.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees that a formal academic program is the best
way to develop future leaders. Ruth Simmons, the president of Smith
College in Northampton, Mass., said leadership development, which
is mentioned in the college's recruiting literature, takes place at
Smith naturally without benefit of a program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of our low student-faculty ratio and the small scale
of the college, Smith students get close attention and mentoring
from the faculty,'' Ms. Simmons said. ``That gives them the
confidence to go out and start companies because they've done big
things here. Also, because the students live in one of 35
self-governing houses, the chances are great that any student who
wants the opportunity to be in a responsible role will get the
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, in a women's college, it's easier for the students to
take risks,'' Ms. Simmons said. ``They can experiment without fear
of criticism. And when they leave, they're not frightened. They
don't retreat.''
</P>
<P>
   Many academicians, though, seem to prefer a more direct
approach. One of the nation's best-known leadership schools, the
Jepson School of Leadership Studies at the University of Richmond,
offers a degree in leadership, and its graduates typically go into
business, law or government.
</P>
<P>
   The school got its start in 1992 with a $20 million gift from
the investment banker Robert S. Jepson Jr., an alumnus. It has 11
faculty members, including Mary Sue Terry, a former Virginia state
attorney general, and accepts 40 juniors and 40 seniors each year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Mount Holyoke College, a women's college in South
Hadley, Mass., started its own leadership resource center, the
Center for Leadership and Public Interest Advocacy, which does not
offer degrees. Activities include a new theme each semester _
currently, ``Making a Difference'' _ related symposiums,
discussions, scholars-in-residence, lectures and ``dinner and
dialogues,'' at which students talk informally with faculty members
over a meal. Courses include ``Speaking, Arguing and Writing,''
which focuses on the art of persuasion.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers point to students like Jennifer Miscovich, a junior at
Austin College's Leadership Institute, as evidence that leadership
can be brought out in people who show promise.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miscovich, a self-described wallflower who in high school
expected to pursue ``a conventional career'' in teaching or the
health sciences, now holds two jobs, maintains a 3.87 grade point
average and founded the Sherman, Texas, chapter of America's
Promise, the national organization of business and civic leaders
who work to help at-risk youths.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on her transition to a budding mover and shaker, Ms.
Miscovich credited the leadership institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It woke me up,'' she said. ``It gave me insight into public
life. There's no turning back now. I know I'm going to be involved
in some sort of community service from here on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
