<SLUG> BC-MA-RUTHARDT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUPS SAY BAY STATE INSURANCE COMMISSIONER HAS TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Citing a pattern of ``unethical and anticonsumer
behavior,'' officials from several consumer and environmental
groups Tuesday called on Acting Governor Paul Cellucci to fire his
insurance commissioner, Linda Ruthardt.
</P>
<P>
   A Cellucci administration spokeswoman called the anticonsumer
allegations ``ludicrous'' and ``hogwash,'' and a campaign spokesman
said ``the charges appear to be more about politics than policy.''
But neither official knew whether Cellucci had actually read the
letters sent by the consumer and environmental groups. Ruthardt did
not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, there's nothing new here,'' said Kim Hinden
McDonald, the spokeswoman for the state's Office of Consumer
Affairs and Business Regulation, which oversees the Division of
Insurance. ``This is a rehash.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Massachusetts Public Interest Research
Group, the Center for Insurance Research, Clean Water Action, and
the Housatonic River Initiative urged Cellucci to fire Ruthardt.
Common Cause of Massachusetts, in a separate letter, said Ruthardt
should be fired only if she refuses to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commissioner Ruthardt has demonstrated a pattern of improper
and wrongful actions coupled with `standard operating procedures'
which continue to put the interests of the insurance industry above
those of the public,'' the officials said in their letter.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt has approved cuts in auto insurance rates each of the
past four years, saving Massachusetts drivers millions of dollars.
McDonald cited those rate cuts as evidence of Ruthardt's
proconsumer actions.
</P>
<P>
   But Deirdre Cummings, the official from Masspirg who signed the
letter, said Ruthardt's alleged pro-industry leanings now raise
questions about those decisions. ``I have very serious concerns
that those rate reductions should have been bigger for consumers,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the consumer officials cited a number of instances in
which Ruthardt allegedly put industry interests ahead of consumer
interests, the trigger for Tuesday's letter to Cellucci was a
meeting Ruthardt held March 23 with a representative of the auto
insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was first disclosed by Stephen J. D'Amato, a former
top aide to Ruthardt who resigned and wrote a letter on Sept. 8 to
Cellucci stating that Ruthardt ``is too closely aligned with the
insurers to protect the public adequately.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato said Daniel Johnston, the president of the Automobile
Insurers Bureau, met with Ruthardt to discuss ``settlement of the
profit portion of the 1999 rate hearing, presumably on terms
favorable to the insurance industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting took place before the actual start of the hearing
process to set next year's rates, but Cummings said the timing of
the meeting was irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be the equivalent of a judge having a meeting with a
defendant in a case before her and the defendant comes in to
advocate for a favorable outcome,'' Cummings said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Scott Harshbarger, who advocates for consumers
before Ruthardt and is also challenging Cellucci for governor, did
not side with the consumer activists Tuesday. But his office plans
to question Johnston under oath this week about his meeting with
Ruthardt and has raised concerns that the meeting may have tainted
the rate-setting process.
</P>
<P>
   In their letter to Cellucci, the consumer and environmental
groups cited several other actions taken by Ruthardt, including her
decision to allow Emlico to relocate to Bermuda, where the insurer
filed for liquidation and walked away from millions of dollars in
environmental cleanup liability in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The groups also cited Ruthardt's refusal to hand over documents
in connection with her rulings on the shift of State Mutual Life
Assurance Co. of Worcester from a company owned by policyholders to
one owned by shareholders; D'Amato's allegation that she pressured
the State Rating Bureau, a unit within her agency, to accept rates
favorable to the industry; and her failure to fully investigate
alleged unfair claims practices by the Travelers Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato, whose letter to Cellucci was initially dismissed by an
administration spokeswoman as self-promotional, said he hoped the
administration's tune will now change and that it will address the
issues raised in his letter.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt, the former insurance director for Girl Scouts USA, was
hired by former Governor William F. Weld in August 1993. She
replaced Kay Doughty, who was ousted for being too cozy with
insurance industry lobbyists. The State Ethics Commission fined her
$2,000 in 1995 for ``routinely'' accepting free dinners,
entertainment, and sports tickets from insurance industry lobbyists
and executives.
</P>
</TEXT>
