<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0833 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURECLASH-BUSINESS     09-29 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURECLASH-BUSINESS-1200(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL ETIQUETTE CAN MAKE OR BREAK A CROSS-CULTURAL DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 
(DUPLICATION WARNING: Story also moving in ``i'' international
category) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL BOWEN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Francesca Funk had been in Japan for only a
short time when she made a request of her host during breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked for some bread,'' the Irving, Texas-based marketing
consultant recalls. ``I was tired of rice, and I knew that we'd had
bread the night before.''
</P>
<P>
   Her hosts said they would get it, and someone was dispatched to
the nearest town to buy some. By the time they had returned,
breakfast was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had I known, I would have told them not to bother,'' Funk
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were ashamed that the breakfast wasn't to my
satisfaction, and I was mortified that they went to that much
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   In a world growing smaller all the time, conflicting customs,
cultures and traditions are bumping up against one another at an
embarrassing tempo.
</P>
<P>
   What might be a minor faux pas among neighbors at a dinner party
in Fort Worth or Houston could lead to a personal international
incident at a conference in Tokyo _ or Mexico City or Abu Dhabi.
</P>
<P>
   And they have. In embarrassing numbers.
</P>
<P>
   As more Texans enter the global marketplace, Bubba is meeting
Mr. Wong more often. And many times the outcome ranges from comical
to disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   Incidents are often based on the mistaken American notion that
businessmen in other cultures want us to show them how to do
business, one cross-cultural consultant says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many American companies think they can blow into town, show
their catalog, illustrate their specification and sign a deal,''
said Edward Retta, owner of Cross Culture Communications in Dallas,
a consultant for international businesses. ``But ours isn't the
only way; in fact, it's one of the youngest ways, and it doesn't
always work.''
</P>
<P>
   Even large multinationals can make major blunders when they
cross national and cultural borders.
</P>
<P>
   When the Marlboro man mounted billboards in Hong Kong, the
message was the opposite of what the image conveys in places such
as Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The image that the Marlboro man conveys here is macho
independence and ruggedness,'' said Rose LeBaron, a Plano,
Texas-based consultant of Chinese descent. ``But in Hong Kong, they
saw him as a dirty, smelly bumpkin.''
</P>
<P>
   The image was revamped.
</P>
<P>
   The new Marlboro man in Hong Kong was an executive standing next
to a Mercedes with a shiny glass skyscraper in the background.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the image that is desirable there,'' LeBaron said.
</P>
<P>
   Even good intentions aren't always enough.
</P>
<P>
   When fast-food giant McDonald's entered the market in India, it
created a veggie burger to appeal to the country's Hindu majority,
who do not eat beef because of the cow's religious significance.
But McDonald's continued to offer some of its trademark beef items
for India's large Muslim minority.
</P>
<P>
   Hindus demonstrated en masse at the golden arches, declaring the
company the world's largest killer of cattle.
</P>
<P>
   Most blunders aren't as gigantic.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Drake, a Waxahachie, Texas-based intercultural trainer for
large corporations, was recently brought in to help a Texas
high-tech company that was having a problem with its Dutch
partners.
</P>
<P>
   The company's engineers had been conducting teleconferences with
their Dutch counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Drake said he observed the meetings as they devolved into
misunderstanding and acrimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans were chatty and friendly,'' Drake recalled. They
were also dressed casually, like many employees of high-tech
companies, wearing khakis and polo shirts.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dutch appeared in the teleconference room, they wore
tailored suits and serious expressions.
</P>
<P>
   Drake said it didn't take long to figure out the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the Americans' point of view, the Dutch were rigid,
judgmental and unwilling to compromise,'' Drake said. ``The Dutch
thought the Americans were sloppy and unbusinesslike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both were trying to put forth their best efforts, but each was
viewing the other from their own specific perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as both sides understood what was going on, they were
able to adjust their views and find solutions to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humans have prejudices,'' Drake said, underlining the core of
cultural misperceptions. ``If you don't go to the trouble of
understanding the culture that you're dealing with, you're not
going to get very far.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frank Walton, a Fort Worth businessman whose company does
business in about 60 countries, has discovered some of the hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   For Texans, it is the Asian cultures that can be the most
difficult to understand, Walton and others agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Europe and South America, at least the cultures are mostly
Western and Christian,'' Walton said. ``In Asia, there's a code of
how you should look, what you should say, how you are supposed to
look at people.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can wear the wrong color and blow the whole deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton's skittishness comes from experience.
</P>
<P>
   His company makes highly technical infusion pumps. He remembers
the time he played host to a big Japanese customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the mistake of saying he had a nice camera, and he gave
it to me,'' Walton said. ``Then you're a dummy holding a camera you
don't need, and the guy doesn't have anything to take pictures with
for the rest of his trip.''
</P>
<P>
   The extreme, often formal, politeness of the Japanese contrasts
sharply with the American approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans think that the most important thing to achieving a
relationship is to be friendly,'' said Funk, whose strategic
research firm is called Noetix. ``For the Japanese, it is to be
polite and considerate.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans' friendliness, though, is sometimes viewed as
superficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can act friendly and still feel free to argue with our
partners,'' Drake said. ``Then we walk away when it is over and
don't call to see how they are doing or send a letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, the people who are left behind think that it was all a
show.''
</P>
<P>
   Funk said there is an easy solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do your research before you go,'' she said. ``Find out about
the place, find out about the people, then you can be interested in
the people and know how to be considerate.''
</P>
<P>
   And if a situation arises in which you're not sure what to do,
Funk added, follow your instincts, even if it doesn't seem to make
sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get the feeling you shouldn't do something, don't do
it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
