<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE SENDS CLINTON APPROPRIATION BILLS FOR DEFENSE, EDUCATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate gave its final approval to defense and
higher education spending bills Tuesday and sent both to President
Clinton for his expected signature.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed the education measure, which could boost Pell
Grant student loans by up to $1,500 a year, by a 96-0 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Before recessing for a day in observance of Yom Kippur, the
Jewish Day of Atonement, the Senate also approved a massive $250
billion defense-spending bill that includes a 3.6 percent pay raise
for military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed both measures Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The defense measure was the third and largest appropriations
bill passed by Congress this year. But 10 other measures that
should have been approved before the start of the 1999 fiscal year
Thursday are still bottled up in the House and Senate because of
disagreements between the White House and lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Three or four more of those could win approval by this weekend
or early next week. But in order to avoid a government shutdown
Oct. 9, when a nine-day temporary spending measure expires,
Congress will have to roll the remaining bills into one catchall
piece of legislation.
</P>
<P>
   There were signs early last week that Republicans might be
willing to risk a shutdown to force Clinton to accept an $80
billion tax-cut bill already approved by the House. But there are
indications now that the measure may not even pass the Senate. Even
if it does, it would likely be sent to Clinton as a separate
measure, which he could veto without affecting government
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republican leaders conceded Tuesday that they would not
be able to muster enough votes to overcome Democratic criticism
that the tax bill authored by House Ways and Means Chairman Bill
Archer, R-Texas, would draw from the estimated budget surpluses
that Clinton wants to use to shore up Social Security. At least
five Republicans, and perhaps as many as a dozen, may end up voting
against it because they believe it's ``too large,'' as Sen. John
Chaffee of Rhode Island put it.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders had hoped to press Clinton on the tax-cut
issue. But recent polls show a growing dissatisfaction with
Congress for not being able to finish its legislative work by the
traditional Oct. 1 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said Tuesday that he
sees litle chance of fireworks developing over the remaining
appropriations bills or the tax-cut measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should be trying to challenge the White House
... I think time for that sort of thing is past,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the defense-spending measure, which accounts for
$1 of every $7 the government will spend next year, Congress has
also approved measures to keep the legislative and executive
branches of government operating. Legislation allowing the Pentagon
to continue construction projects has passed and has been signed by
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The president is expected to sign the higher education bill as
well when it reaches his desk. Long an advocate of increasing
student loans, the bill contains many of the things Clinton has
wanted. In addition to increasing Pell Grants from an average of
$3,000 a year to $4,500, it would also reduce interest rates for
most student loans for the first time in 17 years and cap them at
8.24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Education Department would be required to run its
student-loan operations in a more businesslike manner, with a chief
operating officer at the helm. One aim of the program is to make it
more ``consumer friendly,'' a move that would include publishing a
list of available loans and the estimated costs of an average
college education.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
