<HEADLINE>
PROFESSORS BATTLE MICROSOFT OVER RESEARCH ON NETSCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Two Boston professors are fighting Microsoft Corp.'s
demand that they turn over confidential research they gathered for
an upcoming book about its rival, Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Redmond, Wash.-based software giant, facing an antitrust
lawsuit in Washington, hopes audio tapes of the professors'
interviews with Netscape executives, along with their notes and
other research, will support its claim that Netscape's business
problems are the result of its own blunders and not caused by
unfair competition by Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Microsoft, brought by the Justice Department
and 20 state attorneys general, is scheduled to go to trial Oct. 15
in Washington. To prepare its defense, Microsoft obtained a
subpoena in US District Court in Boston demanding the professors'
research on Net-scape.
</P>
<P>
   But David Yoffie, of Harvard Business School, and Michael
Cusumano, of MIT's Sloan School of Management _ whose book,
``Competing on Internet Time: Lessons from Netscape and its Battle
with Microsoft,'' is due to be published Oct. 20 _ are refusing to
turn over the material. They claim that doing so would violate
their First Amendment rights and academic freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our postion that all our research at Harvard and MIT is
premised on building relationships of confidentiality and trust
with the companies we work with,'' said Yoffie. If companies
believed tapes and transcripts of their interviews could later
surface in court, they would be reluctant to participate in future
research, the professors said.
</P>
<P>
   The authors said nothing important was left out of the book, but
Microsoft spokesman Greg Shaw said his company is pursuing the
taped interviews because ``it is important to actually be able to
hear Netscape executives in their own words supporting Microsoft's
position in the current litigation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 1940EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
