   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MASSACRE (Gornji Obrinje, Yugoslavia) _ The bodies of 15
women, children and old people of the Deliaj clan lay slumped among
the rocks and streams of the gorge below their village in Kosovo,
their heads shot at close range and in some cases their bodies
mutilated as they tried to escape advancing Serb forces. On Monday,
monitors from the United States and the European Union submitted a
graphic written report of what they saw. By Jane Perlez. (The story
has moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   The story runs under a 3-column photo; with locator map.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CANTON (Canton, Ohio) _ This town is a political
bellwether, a place that votes as America does for president, that
swung to the Republican presidents during the 1980s and to Clinton
in the 1990s, and from extensive interviewing here it is clear that
people still support the president. And while they are most
dramatically divided along party lines, they are also split in more
subtle ways. Just as there is a division between Americans living
inside and outside the Washington Beltway, there is a split here
between community leaders and ordinary citizens. By Michael
Winerip. (Scheduled to move by 8:15 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-MILITARY (Washington) _ In a sharp exchange with
senators, the Joint Chiefs of Staff say that pet military projects
sought by Speaker Newt Gingrich and Sen. Trent Lott, the majority
leader, and Congress' refusal to close unnecessary bases is
weakening the nation's defense. By Eric Schmitt. (Scheduled to move
by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.) With photo.
</P>
<P>
   LOBBY-II (Washington) _ Second of two articles on lobbying: From
the nondescript headquarters of his Houston construction firm, Leo
E. Linbeck Jr., is masterminding a crusade to overturn the nation's
tax system. Once, someone like him might have hired some of
Washington's ``Gucci Gulch'' lobbyists to prowl the marble
corridors outside Congress' tax committees. But Linbeck, with
Texas-style audaciousness, wants to engineer a populist uprising.
While he and his fellow investors in ``Americans for Fair
Taxation'' are unusual in the scale of their ambition, their
methods have become commonplace as lobbying has undergone a
revolution over the past decade. By Alison Mitchell. (The story has
moved in ``w'' news file; see also LOBBY-II-SHORT.) 3,700 words.
With graphic.
</P>
