<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, Sept. 30, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-OBIT (Los Angeles) _ Former Los Angeles Mayor Tom
Bradley, the visionary whose 20 years in office saw the creation of
the city's modern skyline, the giddy high of the 1984 Olympics and
the smoldering low point of the 1992 riots, has died. He was 80.
Bradley, an imposing 6 foot 4 inches in height, became an
internationally known figure during his five terms in office. He
was the first African-American to be elected mayor of Los Angeles
and the first to be nominated by a major party to run for governor.
By Rick Orlov. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n''
California news files)
</P>
<P>
   LAPD-FORCE (Los Angeles) _ The number of police on Los Angeles
streets rose by 26 percent since the Rodney King beating, but the
use of force declined by 22 percent, with fewer shootings and less
use of batons and pepper spray, according to a report released
today. Critics praise the trend as a welcome change from the days
when the LAPD had a reputation for brute force. But a separate
study by the Inspector General has raised questions about whether
LAPD officers are being disciplined in all cases of improper
behavior. Checking into one detail in the report that indicated
there was an increase in the number of shootings in the San
Fernando Valley. By Patrick McGreevy. (Will move in the ``n''
California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FED-RATES (Los Angeles) _ Lower interest rates from the Federal
Reserve will mean a reduction in borrowing costs for some
households and businesses. In fact, Los Angeles-based Countrywide
says that anyone with a mortgage loan at 7.5 percent or higher can
refinance and save money, an astonishingly low threshold. But it's
not all good news: The lower rates mean diminished earning power
for those who already have had to contend with skimpy returns on
savings or fixed-income investments. By Greg Wilcox. (Will move in
the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
