<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0857 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FED-RATES-BOS &LR;      09-29 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDS, AS EXPECTED, DROPS KEY RATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Reserve Tuesday lowered a key interest
rate for the first time in nearly three years, pumping a modest
amount of fuel into a US economy that is already feeling the drag
of the global economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   The US economy is still healthy and growing, with inflation and
unemployment well in check. Still, recent events like the stock
market sell-off and the 4,700 job cuts that Gillette Co. announced
Monday have their roots overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed, in a brief explanation of its rate cut, said it needed
to ``cushion'' the effects of weak economies abroad on future US
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no case for a rate cut for the current US economy,''
said Allen Sinai, chief global economist with Primark Decision
Economics of Boston. ``But our central bank cannot take the chance
-- it is just too risky -- that the US economy will fall apart.
This was a preemptive move in a situation where world risks loom
very large.''
</P>
<P>
   Fed policy-makers voted to cut the target for the federal funds
rate by a quarter point, to 5.25 percent. It was the first
reduction since January 1996 in the key interest rate, which banks
charge each other for overnight loans.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed controls the fed funds rate by trading government
securities with banks. It left unchanged, at 5 percent, the more
symbolic discount rate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Normally, a cut in short-term rates by the Fed prompts lenders
to lower a variety of other interest rates, which reduces the cost
of home mortgages, credit card debt, and other loans. However, some
analysts said, the effect this time would be muted, because US
interest rates are already low.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have withdrawn money from investments they consider
risky, such as foreign stocks, and invested it in US government
bonds, which are seen as safer. This has made more money available
to US borrowers and cut the cost of borrowing. Mortgages are at a
30-year low, and rates on government securities, from 3-month
Treasury bill to 30-year Treasury bonds, are below the federal
funds rate that the Fed controls. They are unlikely to fall
further, some analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   However, they said, the Fed move might prompt banks to cut the
prime rate, which would lower interest rates on loans that are tied
to the prime, most notably home-equity loans. The Fed rate cut
could also make it easier for businesses to obtain working capital.
</P>
<P>
   If that occurs, businesses and consumers would be able to borrow
money more cheaply to buy and produce goods, which in turn would
keep businesses working and people employed.
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets expected a rate cut of between one-quarter and
one-half point, and they gave a mixed response to the Fed's
announcement. The Dow Jones industrial average initially fell more
than 100 points but rebounded to close at 8082.58, down 26.26, or
0.3 percent. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose a scant 0.03
percent and the Nasdaq Composite index fell 0.4 percent. The yield
on the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond declined to 5.09 percent
from 5.14 percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed move was not universally applauded, as some analysts
said the US economy was too strong to merit a rate cut. With
unemployment low and consumer spending high, there is little sign
of an economic slowdown, said Allan Meltzer, an economist at
Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh, who heads a Fed-watching
group called the Shadow Open Market Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were split on whether Fed policy-makers would follow up
with more rate cuts in their final two meetings of the year.
</P>
<P>
   At Westfalia Investments, a New York brokerage, chief strategist
Peter Cardillo said he ``suspected'' the Fed would cut rates by a
quarter-point in both November and December.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple reason is that there will be an erosion in consumer
confidence, which will lead to less spending by consumers,'' he
said. In fact, the Conference Board, which tracks consumer
attitudes, Tuesday said its index of consumer confidence fell to
126 in September from 133.1 in August. It was the first time the
index fell for three straight months since 1994. Consumer spending
drives two-thirds of US economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   But Meltzer noted that the Fed, in explaining its rate cut
Tuesday, said that ``a slightly lower federal funds rate should now
be consistent with keeping inflation low and sustaining economic
growth.'' With that language, he said, the Fed was suggesting that
no more rate cuts are planned.
</P>
<P>
   The statement also appeared to reinforce recent remarks by Fed
chairman Alan Greenspan that his primary role is to manage the US
economy -- not those of other nations. It said the Fed wanted to
make sure that weakness overseas does not hurt the United States,
but said nothing about improving conditions abroad.
</P>
<P>
   As much of Asia has fallen into recession, including the
powerhouse of Japan, many nations have looked to the United States
to remain strong, buy foreign goods, and help pull the world out of
its slowdown. But in testifying before a House committee earlier
this month, Greenspan downplayed his role as a global leader. ``Our
essential mandate is to the economy of the United Stats of
America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan also said at that hearing that he was not
orchestrating a coordinated cut in interest rates by the world's
industrialized nations, as some had speculated. Such a rate cut
would likely spur economic activity not only in the industrialized
nations but around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Fed is likely giving great weight in its
decision-making to conditions abroad, said Ralph Bryant, a senior
fellow in economic studies at the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally in a (Fed policy-making) discussion, the foreign
situation would get much less attention than the domestic
situation, and most people would vote with no weight on it at
all,'' he said. ``But I'm guessing now it was probably enough to
tip many members of the committee to lower the funds rate. Had it
not been for such a turbulent international situation, chances are
they would not have done so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The awkward truth is that nobody knows -- not even members of
the (Fed) committee -- whether this rate cut will seem like the
right thing to have done, with the wisdom of hindsight,'' said
Bryant. ``The uncertainties are very great in the world financial
markets and the world economy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
