<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMARTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLISHER DISAVOWS `SMARTEST-DUMBEST CITIES' LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (Attn.: Ala., Ga., Tx.) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's almost too true an Aggie joke.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, an Atlanta publisher named College Station the ``most
literate'' and ``smartest'' city in America.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, it disavowed the designation.
</P>
<P>
   The city manager of College Station _ home to Texas A&AMP;M
University, whose proud alumni are the butt of countless jibes
assuming a general lack of intellectual agility _ reacted with
equanimity, after he stopped laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of a `good news, bad news' joke,'' said Skip Noe,
47, the city manager. ``They're not saying we're not intelligent;
they're saying they're disowning that particular analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Longstreet Press, a subsidiary of Cox Newspapers, which owns the
Austin American-Statesman and Waco Herald-Tribune, issued a brief
statement saying that a free-lance publicist issued a list of
``smartest'' and ``dumbest'' cities based on per capita book sales
and that the PR man's analysis was ``erroneous.''
</P>
<P>
   It did not spell out what part was mistaken and a company
spokesman did not return calls requesting clarification.
</P>
<P>
   The ``dumbest'' cities cited in the list were Anniston, Ala.,
San Angelo, Texas, and Athens, Ga., in that order. Among big
cities, Dallas had the least smarts.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Bard, a Longstreet employee, indicated that the company
had been inundated by complaints from residents of poorly rated
communities. He said calling someone stupid is bound to generate
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Bard said the analysis by Atlanta publicist Bob Hope, no
relation to the comedian, was based on information from the
American Booksellers Association and was based on 1992 Commerce
Department data.
</P>
<P>
   Hope issued Friday's news release without Longstreet's approval,
the company said. ``We apologize for the misuse of this
information,'' said Chuck Perry, Longstreet's president.
</P>
<P>
   San Angelo's designation as second-dumbest didn't go down well
in the West Texas community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they're checking books out of the library,'' suggested
E.J. Holland, dean of Angelo State University's College of Liberal
and Fine Arts. ``It seems a little dumb to judge cities by a single
indicator. And San Angelo is really a neat place to live.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
