<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0862 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-PARKS-ARCHITEC     09-29 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-PARKS-ARCHITECTURE-ART-$ADV04-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING, ADDING ART NOTE)  
 DISNEY: GENUINELY ARTIFICIAL, REALLY SURREAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 4)  
 (af)  
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As usual, Tocqueville had it nailed even before it happened.
More than a century before Disneyland opened its doors, the great
analyst of modern democracy grasped the spirit of hysteria that
infuses the entire theme park genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not fear,'' he wrote, ``that the poetry of democratic
nations will prove insipid or that it will fly too near the ground;
I rather apprehend that it will be forever losing itself in the
clouds and that it will range at last to purely imaginary regions.
I fear that the production of democratic poets may often be
surcharged with immense and incoherent images, with exaggerated
descriptions and strange creations, and that the fantastic beings
of their brain may sometimes make us regret the world of reality.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to grant that Disney's theme parks are full of strange
creations, but do they rate as poetry? ``The Architecture of
Reassurance,'' a show of Disney's theme park architecture that will
open on Tuesday at Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum, makes an
affirmative case.
</P>
<P>
   The work on view may seldom rise to the level of great poetry,
but it does fulfill the Greek idea of poetics as the making of a
culture's connective tissue. If you are prone to cultural analysis,
the theme parks offer a field day for symbolic interpretation. And
if you have kids, there is the pleasure of fulfilling their desires
in a public, social ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Karal Ann Marling, an art historian, and originally
presented at the Canadian Center for Architecture, the show was the
fourth in that institution's monumental, six-part survey, ``The
American Century.''
</P>
<P>
   I missed the show in Montreal, , but if the Canadian Center's
past shows and the intelligent, handsome catalog produced for this
one are any guide, this should be a golden opportunity for serious
thought on a deceptively frivolous subject.
</P>
<P>
   As the show's title suggests, this is not a hollow, celebratory
occasion. Since the Disney people are notorious control freaks, the
show's ambivalent stance can itself be counted a curatorial
achievement. It is also the proper stance to take toward a subject
that stirs up such complicated feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Presenting more than 200 drawings, plans, renderings, models and
archival photographs, the show traces the history of the genre from
Disney's initial, unsuccessful efforts to build an amusement park
in Burbank to the parks constructed in France and Japan after his
death.
</P>
<P>
   The installation, designed by Robert Anderson and Chriswell
Lappin, is laid out to evoke the genuine, artificial thing. (Not to
be missed: a less varnished look at Disney's world is presented in
the museum's lower gallery, in a series of photographs by Catherine
Wagner specially commissioned for the show.)
</P>
<P>
   In the renderings, you get to see Disney's attractions in their
pure dream state, without too hot a sun overhead, children
demanding to go to the bathroom and the claustrophobia induced by
some of the rides. And it's instructive to see the names of
individual designers attached to what can otherwise resemble the
corporate face of a carnivalesque ministry of fear.
</P>
<P>
   I doubt it is possible for baby boomers like myself to look at
Disney straight, any more than it was possible for Dorothy and her
companions to be impressed by the wizard after Toto pulled back the
curtain. Time has done a Toto on Disney, and on ourselves. We grew
up with this name as a symbol of innocence and wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the media's preoccupation with itself, we now see
Disney as an imperial corporation with global ambitions. Thanks to
hindsight, we can perceive that even in the 1950s, Disney's
innocence was a gloss over the invention of the mass consumer
society. To that extent, we may feel that we were had, and it's
tempting to find a scapegoat for the disillusions of grown up life.
</P>
<P>
   But Disney was also a major American artist, and he applied part
of his genius to the invention of mass consumption. The capacity
for wonder is an important quality, and why shouldn't the
technology of information be used to sustain as well as unmask this
quality in an informational society.
</P>
<P>
   Tocqueville's prediction could apply to many forms of culture,
high and low: Cinerama. Abstract Expressionism. The Empire State
Building. The 1893 Chicago World's Fair. Trump Taj Mahal.
``Gravity's Rainbow.'' Monicagate. But no form has transported more
people toward imaginary regions on such a grandiose physical scale
as Disney's theme parks.
</P>
<P>
   This show will hold particular interest for those who follow the
Surrealist strain that has emerged in the work of Frank Gehry, Rem
Koolhaas, Philippe Starck, and other architects. There are clear
formal resemblances between Surrealistic painting and some Disney
designs, like two unbuilt schemes for the entrance to the Anaheim
park's Tomorrowland.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But the conventionally rendered projects are even more
Surrealistic. The supernaturally tidy Main Street, the Matterhorn
rising in a suburban Southern California desert, the tropical river
flowing in the shadow of a Bavarian castle: these display
characteristic Surrealistic techniques of displacement,
juxtaposition, and the uncanny. Even Dali never contrived to put a
whole nation in mouse ears.
</P>
<P>
   If the purpose of this architecture is to reassure, then it is,
of course, a subversion of Surrealism's anarchic spirit, not a
fulfillment of it. But some Disney attractions are genuinely
disturbing. I'd rather climb the (real) Matterhorn than subject
myself a second time to It's a Small World, the ride commissioned
from Disney by the Pepsi-Cola Co. for the 1964-65 New York World's
Fair. That endless, repetitive jingle; those identically sized
dolls; the molasses pace of the mechanized boats add up to a truly
harrowing nine minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say it's art. In an interview in the catalog,
Frank Gehry describes a meeting at which the Disney president,
Frank Wells, rejected a plan by Robert Venturi for Disneyland
Paris. Venturi had designed a grande allee of 150-foot-tall,
two-dimensional Mickeys and Minnies, shaking hands at 50-foot
intervals, along a stretch the length of the Champs Elysee. ``It
was Bob Venturi at his pinnacle, just the best,'' Gehry says.
``There is an essence and a truth in Venturi's portrayal of this
whole thing. That's why he could not do work for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gehry himself did manage to create one of the few theme-park
projects that rates as architecture. His Festival Disney at
EuroDisney features an avenue of square columns, tiled with
iridescent metal, supporting an aerial grid of cables fitted with
small electric lights.
</P>
<P>
   It is a ``Red Shoes'' scene, poignant in the contrast between
the lumbering columns, the shifting colors of their surfaces and
the sad carnival light of the tiny lamps overhead. In this
hyperbolic context, Gehry's understatement showed up the difference
between art and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Tocqueville had a theory about why American artists might be
prone to abandon the great to reach the gigantic. He states in one
paragraph what George W.S. Trow took many pages to describe in his
book, ``Within the Context of No Context.'' The paragraph is worth
repeating.
</P>
<P>
   ``In democratic communities, each citizen is habitually engaged
in the contemplation of a very puny object: himself. If he ever
raises his looks higher, he perceives only the immense form of
society at large or the still more imposing aspect of mankind. His
ideas are all either extremely minute and clear or extremely
general and vague; what lies between is a void. When he has been
drawn out of his own sphere, therefore, he always expects that some
amazing object will be offered to his attention; and it is on these
terms alone that he consents to tear himself for a moment from the
petty, complicated cares that form the charm and the excitement of
his life.''
</P>
<P>
   But some artists work creatively with those terms, and a few
even change them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
