<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED CUTS SHORT-TERM INTEREST RATES BY QUARTER OF A PERCENTAGE
POINT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal Reserve policy-makers agreed to nudge down
short-term interest rates by a quarter of a percentage point
Tuesday in an effort to help calm the financial turmoil devastating
economies around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Following through on signals telegraphed repeatedly by Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan during the last few weeks, the Federal Open
Market Committee voted to reduce the federal funds rate _ the
benchmark rate commercial banks charge one another for overnight
loans _ to 5.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed left the discount rate, the rate the central bank
charges for loans to financial institutions, unchanged at 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's cut in the federal fund rate represents the first
movement in interest rates in a year and a half and the first
reduction in nearly three years. Major banks are expected to follow
the Fed's lead and lower their prime lending rates _ the rates they
charge their best customers.
</P>
<P>
   But institutions such as Chase Bank of Texas, a unit of Chase
Manhattan Corp. in New York, Wells Fargo Bank and NationsBank all
held off taking action Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   While the quarter-point reduction was expected, many investors
on Wall Street were hoping for a steeper cut of at least half a
percentage point on the federal funds rate and at least some
movement on the discount rate.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average plunged on the news Tuesday,
although stocks regained ground later to close down only 28.32
points. The dollar also fell in value against the yen and peso and
the bond market got a boost from the rate cut.
</P>
<P>
   Fed officials, in a brief statement, said they were cutting
rates to help cushion the effects of ``increased weakness in
foreign economies and of less accomodative financial conditions
domestically.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists say the Fed action was necessary, not so much to help
a still humming U.S. economy, but to send a signal overseas that
the Unites States will assume a leadership role to combat the
global economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the U.S. needs a cut in interest rates,'' said
Sung Won Sohn, chief economist for Norwest Corp. in Minneapolis.
``We don't need stimulation right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The crisis, sparked by a collapse in the real estate market in
Bangkok, Thailand, in July 1997, has already upset the economies of
East Asia, flattened the Russian Bear and is now ravaging the
economies of Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's leadership was necessary, analysts said, after an
international effort to coordinate interest rate cuts throughout
the industrialized economies never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   The economies of Latin America were particularly anxious for the
rate cut, Sohn said. Troubled economies from Brazil to Venezuela
are hoping the lower rates will help boost economic activity in the
United States, while allowing the Latin economies to attract cash
with their extraordinarily high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   For Fed watchers, the committee's explanation for its action was
a rather striking statement, since ``the Federal Reserve typically
has not based monetary policy on international events,'' noted Lynn
Reaser, chief economist for NationsBank Private Client Group in
Jacksonville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Buckwalter, chief executive of Chase Bank of Texas, argued
that with the recent decline in economic growth, the extremely low
inflation rate and the tremendous turmoil in markets around the
world, the Fed had much more room to cut, perhaps by as much as 100
basis points or 1 percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, I don't think this means a whole lot for the
average person,'' Buckwalter said, adding ``I think it's almost
kind of a holding pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, however, didn't acquire the nickname ``incremental
Al'' for nothing, noted Bryan Jordan with Banc One Investment
Advisors in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, since Greenspan took over as Fed chairman in 1987, the
Fed has cut interest rates 30 times, 27 of which were in
quarter-point increments, Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Since a larger cut would have been so unusual, the Fed would
have risked sending a dire message, Sohn argued. ``People might
think, `Gosh, the world must be coming to an end.'''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan also may be trying to save some ammunition, if he
needs to help the markets again down the road with further rate
cuts, Fed watchers said. ``He probably wants to keep some powder
dry,'' Buckwalter said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's Open Market Committee is slated to reconvene Nov. 17
and then again Dec. 22.
</P>
<P>
   While their concerns may be secondary under the current
circumstances, Americans are likely to benefit from lower rates on
their home equity loans, credit cards and other consumer debts.
</P>
<P>
   A family with a $20,000, five-year home equity loan tied to the
prime rate, for instance, would, under the old rates, pay $420.04 a
month and $5,202.23 in interest over the life of the loan, said
Sara Campbell, senior vice president of the North Palm Beach,
Fla.-based Bank Rate Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   With the lower rates, that family's monthly bill would dip to
$417.60 a month, while paying a total $5,055.88 in interest over
the life of the loan, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   A consumer carrying a $2,000 balance on a credit card that
charged 16.10 percent interest and who is making payments of $100 a
month would need 24 months to pay off that debt, while racking up
total interest charges of $344.42 over that time-frame.
</P>
<P>
   With the lower rates, that same credit card holder would pay a
total of $337.37 in interest charges and take 23 months to pay off
the debt, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its myriad effects on consumer credit costs, the
Fed's action could help to bolster sagging confidence among
American consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The Conference Board reported Tuesday that its index of consumer
confidence dropped to 126.0 points in September, down from 133.1
points in August and its lowest level since October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
