<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MLS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREVIEW OF MLS PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wily Bora Milutinovic has thrown a snag into what ought to be
mere preliminaries for Major League Soccer's anticipated D.C.
United-Los Angeles Galaxy showdown in the Oct. 25 title game.
</P>
<P>
   United, winner of the first two MLS Cups, and the Galaxy are
expected to face off at the Rose Bowl, but Milutinovic's inclusion
in the process as new coach of the New York/New Jersey MetroStars
has suddenly made the improbable seem possible.
</P>
<P>
   The former U.S. national team coach, who has guided four nations
to the World Cup's second round, is famed for his ability to
succeed in tournament play under difficult confines. He finds
himself in that position with the Metros, whose talent and
accomplishment this season suggest anything but an MLS power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to have good results,'' says Milutinovic, whose team
which opens Eastern Conference play tonight in Columbus wants to
emulate the Colorado Rapids, who made a stunning playoff run to
last year's final. ``The main plan is to try to be champion. It
will not be easy ... but it is not impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   D.C. and the Galaxy, both 24-8 during the regular season, are
the favorites, but the expansion Chicago Fire also appear capable
of winning the crown.
</P>
<P>
   A look at the first-round series:
</P>
<P>
   WESTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy (24-8, 68 points) vs. Dallas Burn (15-17, 37): Cobi Jones
(19), Welton (17) and Mauricio Cienfuegos (13) have totaled more
goals than the entire Dallas squad (43), and L.A.'s defense led by
Robin Fraser also was the league's best. The Burn, who shutout the
Galaxy twice in last year's first-round sweep, need exceptional
play from goalkeeper Mark Dodd and defender Chad Deering. Season
series: Galaxy, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago (20-12, 56) vs. Colorado (16-16, 44): The expansion Fire
are solid everywhere, in defense (goalkeeper Zach Thornton had
eight shutouts, Lubos Kubik is the defender of the year
frontrunner), in midfield (MVP hopeful Peter Nowak) and up front
(emergence of Ante Razov and Josh Wolff). They'll be without Jorge
Campos he wasn't getting much playing time, so he returned to
Mexico on Monday (with MLS's blessing) to play for Pumas UNAM. The
Rapids have won five of six and count on midfielder Ross Paule,
defender Marcelo Balboa and forward Wolde Harris. Season series:
Chicago, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   EASTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   D.C. United (24-8, 58) vs. Miami (15-17, 35): United is loaded,
with Marco Etcheverry, Jaime Moreno, John Harkes and Roy Lassiter,
but the Fusion won the last two meetings and have played some
inspired soccer since Ivo Wortmann took over as head coach in July.
Carlos Valderrama has been spotty for Miami this year, but Diego
Serna has emerged as a top striker. D.C. may be without Moreno
(bruised shoulder) and Tony Sanneh (strained groin) for the opener.
Season series: 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Columbus (15-17, 45) vs. New York/New Jersey (15-17, 39): The
Crew have a superb attack featuring forwards Stern John (26 goals)
and Brian McBride (10) and creative midfielders Brian Maisonneuve
and Andy Williams, but they haven't been able to translate that to
wins. Columbus, which may be without Maisonneuve (sprained ankle),
has lost its last five. The Metros lost six in succession before a
shootout victory in Milutinovic's debut last weekend. Season
series: 2-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
