<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0874 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-MILITARY-ART     09-29 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-MILITARY-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS RAP MILITARY BRASS OVER READINESS DISCLOSURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a sharp exchange with senators, the Joint Chiefs
of Staff said Tuesday that pet military projects sought by House
Speaker Newt Gingrich and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, and
Congress' refusal to close unnecessary bases, are weakening the
nation's defense.
</P>
<P>
   The four-star admirals and generals who testified before the
Senate Armed Services Committee usually engage in a mutual
admiration contest with the lawmakers who oversee the military. If
the nation's top officers ever harbor gripes about their legislator
patrons, they usually express them in private.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, even though they did not mention congressional
leaders by name, the military brass took aim at a famously fat
piece of Air Force spending that benefits their constituents.
</P>
<P>
   They were provoked into a round of defensive recriminations with
the military's staunchest supporters on Capitol Hill. In volley
after volley, senators accused the Joint Chiefs of misleading
Congress earlier this year about the seriousness of problems that
are eroding the armed forces' fighting ability.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans and some Democrats on the committee accused
the Chiefs of sugar-coating problems like pilot shortages and
training cuts seven months ago, then reversing themselves Tuesday
by saying that the same shortcomings endangered the combat
readiness of American forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that you were not candid to this member in the
problems and challenges that we faced,'' complained Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., a decorated Navy pilot who spent more than five
years as a prisoner of war in North Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Momentarily stunned, the Chiefs responded by saying that they
had been warning lawmakers for months, even years, of the failings,
and that the situation had worsened since they last testified.
Moreover, they noted, the problems would not be so bad if Congress
would let the Defense Department close unneeded bases and stop
forcing it to buy planes and ships it does not need.
</P>
<P>
   For example, they said, Congress in the past three years has
bought 20 C-130 transport planes for $1 billion that the Air Force
hasn't requested. The planes were built in Gingrich's district in
Marietta, Ga., and many were then stationed at bases in
Mississippi, Lott's home state.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Gingrich nor Lott were mentioned by name when the
C-130's came up Tuesday, but the aircraft are the stuff of military
pork legend. ``Not only were the planes added,'' said Gen. Michael
Ryan, the Air Force chief of staff, ``but then we're told where to
put them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Henry H. Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs, chimed
in with another suggestion that put military needs over domestic
politics. He said that if Congress would approve two new rounds of
base closings, the Pentagon could save an additional $21 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That would be enough for 450 new strike fighters, 12 warships or
650 Comanche helicopters, he said. ``We support closing additional
bases,'' said Shelton, who did not single out any installations.
</P>
<P>
   The angry exchanges came just two weeks after the nation's top
military commanders warned President Clinton about growing fiscal
strains on the armed services. A week after the grim report,
Clinton proposed giving the Pentagon an immediate new infusion of
between $1 billion and $4 billion, and promised to consider a much
larger increase in military spending in 2000. The Pentagon's budget
is $271 billion for the fiscal year that begins on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's offer helped diffuse a growing chorus of complaints
from Republicans who accuse the administration of taxing the
military with an increasing number of overseas missions.
</P>
<P>
   But even the chiefs said Tuesday that the short-term infusion,
while helpful, does not address chronic problems, from replacing
aging equipment to recruiting and retaining qualified troops.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force, for instance, is short 700 pilots. The Army's
budget for new weapons is at the lowest level since 1959. And the
Navy's serious aircraft accident rate increased 82 percent from a
year ago, partly because the Navy is pushing its crews so hard,
said Adm. Jay Johnson, chief of naval operations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Republicans were confounded why the chiefs had not issued these
same dire warnings when they testified individually in February and
March, especially since Republicans and many independent experts
had been flagging dangerous signs that combat readiness was wearing
thin.
</P>
<P>
   Had the chiefs confirmed the Republicans worst fears about
eroding readiness then, congressional aides said later, the
criticisms would have been invaluable fodder to use against the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans' frustration echoed in question after question. Many
recited testimony the chiefs gave in February, describing the
readiness problem as tight but not terrible.
</P>
<P>
   McCain attacked Shelton's explanation that the military was
caught off guard by this year's seemingly unending stream of crises
requiring U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Shelton, did you think that Saddam Hussein was going
to join the Boy Scouts?'' McCain said. ``Did you think we were
going to leave Bosnia within a year?''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said they were taken aback by Shelton's two main
financing priorities: fixing the military's retirement system and
closing the pay gap between military personnel and civilians with
similar training _ at a total estimated cost of at least $40
billion over five years. Senators said neither was raised as a
serious concern earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   As senators came closer and closer to calling the chiefs liars,
the officers, their integrity challenged, bristled. ``For four
years, I've come here and told you exactly what our problems were,
didn't pull a punch and got my butt chewed out sometimes,'' said
Gen. Charles Krulak, the Marine Corps commandant.
</P>
<P>
   But the senators did not give an inch. At the end of the
bruising 4-1/2 hour hearing, senators lectured the chiefs to be
more outspoken in the budgetary battles to preserve readiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a war,'' said Sen. Robert Smith, R-N.H. ``You're
battlefield commanders. You have to be commanders rather than
bureaucrats.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
