<HEADLINE>
CONTRACEPTIVE INSURANCE BILL HITS STUMBLING BLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Antiabortion lawmakers in Congress have thrown up a
last-minute roadblock to a measure that would make government
insurance plans pay the costs of prescription contraceptives for
federal workers.
</P>
<P>
   Passed in slightly different versions by the House and Senate
this summer, the legislation has been a high priority for women's
advocacy groups and is designed not only to get the insurance to an
estimated 2 million federal workers, but also to nudge private
health plans to provide substantially more coverage for
contraceptives than they do now.
</P>
<P>
   But some antiabortion legislators and lobbyists, arguing that
some contraceptives are in fact ``abortifacients,'' or
abortion-inducing drugs and devices, are trying to get the
conference committee to kill the measure rather than resolve the
minor differences between the House and Senate bills.
</P>
<P>
   The issue and the antiabortion strategy have deadlocked the
negotiations on the Treasury Department-Postal Service spending
bill, which contains the contraceptive-coverage measure. Conferees
gave up Monday night after a long session, several inconclusive
votes, and no deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely extraordinary,'' said Representative Nita
Lowey, a New York Democrat who sponsored the bill in the House and
attended Monday's meeting. ``We're talking about basic health-care
coverage for women, we're talking about a measure that passed both
houses. Yet the Republican leadership is going to great lengths to
strip out this amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, five GOP House members on the conference
committee sent a letter to Representative Jim Kolbe of Arizona,
chairman of the Approrprations subcommittee that handled the bill,
asserting ``this language would mandate coverage of drugs and/or
devices which many believe are capable of causing abortions.''
</P>
<P>
   The conservative lawmakers urged the bill be changed to allow
any insurer to opt out for ``religious beliefs and moral
convictions.'' Supporters of the legislation say that language
loophole is large enough to render the measure meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Eight conservative senators sent a similar but stronger request
to Colorado Republican Ben Nighthorse Campbell, who chairs the
Treasury appropriations subcommittee in the Senate. ``We believe
this amendment is a precedent-setting attempt to mandate coverage
of other abortifacients,'' the letter of Sept. 4 said. ``For the
above, we believe the provision should be dropped from the
conference report.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed the contraceptive-coverage provision
unanimously on a voice vote July 29. The current opposition,
including that of Oklahoma's Don Nickles, a members of the Senate
leadership, and presidential aspirants Bob Smith of New Hampshire
and John Ashcroft of Missouri, signals that some members are
concerned about a backlash from their core, conservative
constituencies but didn't want to go on record with what might have
been reported as an anti-woman vote on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Women's-rights activists say they took advantage of the huge
interest in Viagra, and the initial agreement by insurers to pay
for prescriptions of it, to press the issue of contraceptive
coverage. For years, groups such as Planned Parenthood have
complained that women are shortchanged because half of all private
insurers don't pay for the Pill or other prescription
contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling my colleagues to get real, this bill has nothing
to do with abortion,'' said Democratic Senator Harry Reid of
Nevada, an abortion-rights opponent who says he and Maine
Republican Olympia Snowe sponsored the contraceptive coverage bill
to help prevent unintended pregnancies and abortions. ``I don't
know where this is coming from, but I think it should have been
done in the daylight, not in letters to the leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists for the National Conference of Catholic Bishops said
House leaders are ``sympathetic'' to their appeals to oppose the
contraceptive-coverage bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has changed for us,'' said Helen Alvare, a spokeswoman
for the Catholic Conference. ``We want to get rid of this measure,
and it's what we have been working hard on.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Christopher Smith, a New Jersey Republican and a
leader of antiabortion lawmakers in the House, fought the Lowey
amendment on the House floor and is central now to efforts to
substantially alter it or kill it in the conference, staffers on
the Appropriations Committee say. Smith did not respond to requests
for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Time is running out on the spending bills. Congress wants to
adjourn by the end of next week for the midterm elections, and any
appropriations bills that aren't passed by the end of this week are
likely to be rolled into one big omnibus spending bill that would
essentially fund government agencies at their current levels into
the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The fear among backers of the contraceptive-coverage measure is
that the conferees will give up and let GOP leaders in the House
and Senate decide the contents and status of the Treasury-postal
bill, which is their prerogative at the 11th hour.
</P>
<P>
   Reid says he is confident a deal can still be reached this week
to preserve the contraceptive provision. A spokesman for Snowe said
she might be willing to let Senate conferees simply accept the
House version of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Anne Northup, a Kentucky Republican, said she
opposes the Lowey amendment as an unnecessary federal mandate. But
she contends Democrats have successfully exploited the antiabortion
opposition to build their own momentum. ``In the end, the pro-life
community is going to have to choose its priorities,'' Northup
said, ``and this is probably one fight they will have to set
aside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
