<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA PUTS THE QUIET ON CLEVELAND CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The man hates to talk about his own work. Ask him to
comment on it and he might volley a question of his own back to
you. Like: ``Can you ask me about something else?'' And you know
what that means, don't you? Simply translated: Don't ask me
anything if you can help it.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra plays shortstop for the Red Sox. He likes to
obsessively tug on his batting gloves before each at-bat. He likes
to play jokes on his teammates. He likes to talk about hip-hop and
soccer. He does not enjoy looking into camera lenses and talking
about the way he plays baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday at Jacobs Field, Garciaparra made more than 45,000
Indians fans behave like him. One moment, everyone here was buzzing
during Game 1 of the Sox-Indians Division Series. The next, not
many Ohioans had anything to say. They went from gabby participants
to silent observers in one motion. And this is how they got there:
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth inning _ with John Valentin on second base and
Damon Buford on first _ Garciaparra took the first pitch he saw
from Jaret Wright and knocked it 373 feet over the left-field wall.
You know how uncomfortably quiet it gets in a room when someone
says something inappropriate? That's how it was here after the
Garciaparra home run. Except, fittingly, the shortstop didn't say
anything. He just did it. People in Cleveland didn't appreciate it.
Suddenly, the score was 6-0. That might not be so bad when you are
facing an average American League pitcher with an earned run
average near 5, but the Indians had to deal with Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The game was over then, unofficially. By the end of the
afternoon, Mo Vaughn would have seven RBIs and Garciaparra four.
The Sox would end a 13-game postseason losing streak with an 11-3
win. Garciaparra, though, would continue a streak that has lasted
longer than the 30-game hitting streak he had as a rookie and, for
that matter, the 56-gamer Joe DiMaggio had in 1941. Once again, he
looked at the talkers and wondered why they had so much to talk
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you tell me about your homer?'' someone shouted from the
crowd, a crowd littered with cameras, microphones, and recording
devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit it over the fence,'' Garciaparra replied.
</P>
<P>
   It went like that for 10 or 15 minutes. The answers were
efficient. Direct. Sometimes sarcastic. He did acknowledge that
``there was some anxiety'' before his first career postseason game.
But he wanted to hear nothing of the 13-game losing streak that
dated to 1986. He was asked how he dealt with such talk of extended
losing streaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we don't say that,'' he snapped. ``You do.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra doesn't say much at all. He is a doer. That is why
Mike Hargrove fears him. The Indians manager has been known to flip
on local talk radio while driving home. He has also been known to
call all-sports stations and complain about their critiques of him.
Maybe he will listen tonight to the talkers to see if they have any
suggestions on how to pitch Garciaparra, the nontalker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd rather not pitch to them at all,'' Hargrove was saying
about Garciaparra and Vaughn. But he explained that throwing the
ball was necessary because the two sluggers kept coming up with men
on base. ``We didn't have anywhere to put them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If someone must talk about baseball, that is the kind of
dialogue Garciaparra likes to hear. He tells you that he would
rather focus on the men who got on base before him, enabling him to
do his job. He says the 11 RBIs from the Nos. 3 and 4 hitters
wouldn't have been possible without the work of Darren Lewis and
John Valentin. He wants to know why people don't talk about that.
And why do they mention All-Star teams? (For the record, he thinks
All-Star teams are senseless in team sports so, no, he is not
bothered that Hargrove picked Omar Vizquel to represent the AL in
July instead of him.)
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving the park Tuesday, a man tapped Garciaparra on the
shoulder. It was Vaughn's father, Leroy. The men smiled and hugged.
It was all that needed to be said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
