u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-PEDRO-STARE-BOS &LR;      09-29 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-PEDRO-STARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS, MARTINEZ GO EYE TO EYE IN SEVENTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Stare. It was a vintage heavyweight stare, there
on the mound in the seventh inning, a stare seldom seen in baseball
between a pitcher and his manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Stare. In boxing, it is always a macho move _ who will blink
first? _ but in baseball, it is a look into the soul. Did Pedro
Martinez have anything left?
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy (Williams) was going to get him (out of the game),'' said
Red Sox catcher Scott Hatteberg, who was as close as referee Mills
Lane ever was to The Stare. ``Pedro was definitely showing he
wanted to stay in the game. And Pedro was going to have a little
talk with (Williams) if he wanted to take him out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stare. Pedro Martinez might as well have been Evander
Holyfield and Jimy Williams could have been Mike Tyson, Martinez's
stare was so intense. Williams said later that he could tell by
looking into Martinez's eyes that the pitcher had more than enough
fortitude to stay in the game, even with runners on second and
third after a shaky stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's normally my look when I'm pitching,'' Martinez said
after wrapping up the Red Sox' 11-3 rout of the Cleveland Indians
Tuesday in the opener of their best-of-five Division Series.``I'm
normally very intense when I'm pitching. But (The Stare) wasn't
anything bad; it was just, `Let me stay in. I can do it. I know I
can do it.' And (Williams) did. He understood what I was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, long after game's end, long after Martinez had told the
gaggle of media how much it meant for him to win his postseason
debut with a seven-inning, six-hit, three-run, no-walk,
eight-strikeout performance, the Red Sox ace walked back into the
locker room and headed right to the manager's office.
</P>
<P>
   There pitcher and manager relived The Stare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy just told me that `when I looked into your eyes, I knew
you could do it,''' recounted Martinez. ``He said, `I came to take
you out,' but he left me in the game, and that made me feel good
that he had so much confidence in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston was leading, 8-3, at the time, and the crisis was not
that severe. Still, Martinez had given up a home run to Jim Thome
in the inning, and after a wild pitch on a strikeout allowed Travis
Fryman to reach first, Brian Giles had doubled on a bouncer over Mo
Vaughn's glove down the right-field line. The situation was getting
sticky.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the conference at the mound and The Stare. Martinez
(``It really motivated me to hear Jimy say he knew I could do it'')
promptly induced Sandy Alomar to lift a soft foul pop to Vaughn at
first and escaped the inning when Omar Vizquel hit a soft liner to
Nomar Garciaparra at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   The Stare was emblematic of Martinez's desire to live up to his
reputation in his first playoff game. Once Vaughn hit a three-run
homer in the first, Martinez never was in danger. ``It was great to
know you were ahead already and you have the advantage,'' he said.
``Then it's up to you to get the ball over and make the right
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but not so fast, said Hatteberg. It might be great to jump
to a 3-0 lead in the first inning, but then your starting pitcher
has to make sure his first inning is clean so the advantage is not
immediately lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people realize how important that is,'' said
Hatteberg of Martinez going 1-2-3 through the Indians in the first
after Vaughn's homer and again dispatching Clevelaand 1-2-3 in the
fifth after Garciaparra's three-run homer in the top of the inning
gave Boston a 6-0 lead. ``Jaret Wright got pounded in the first. He
gave up a homer in the first and we scored some runs and then we
come out on the field and get 'em 1-2-3. He barely has time to get
water and catch his breath and he's back on the mound. It's the
best thing: score some runs and then go right at 'em when they're
up.''
</P>
<P>
   As for pregame butterflies, ``I didn''t think Pedro was nervous
at all,'' said Hatteberg. ``If he was, he was hiding it pretty
well. Right out of the gate, he was throwing steam.'' Martinez
repeated the mantra of Williams and the entire team that a playoff
game ``is just like a regular game.'' Of course, it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I told you before, I would have to wait until (Tuesday)''
to see what pitching in the postseason would be like, said Marinez.
``And I did. And it was no different. I think the butterflies were
gone in my early days in the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But when he was back in the Red Sox locker room, he was
whistling and shouting in joy, ``My day's over now.''
</P>
<P>
   The day was not perfect, since Martinez had to stay away from
one of his out pitches _ the changeup _ ``after I threw one to
Kenny Lofton (in the fourth) and he screamed it into center field.
Then I kind of had an idea they were aware of my changeup and I
needed to switch to something else and go about it differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez mixed his fastball and breaking ball for 121 pitches,
and most important, he issued no walks even though he went to a 3-2
count six times and a 3-1 count once. Once the Red Sox took the
lead, he said, ``I didn't want to walk anyone. It looks bad for a
veteran pitcher (with the lead) to be walking people to get away
from the long ball and stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   So he went right after the Indians, ``and they did hit them out
a couple of times. But I don't regret it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez had passed his first postseason test, and
certainly, there was no regret in that.
</P>
<P>
   Nor in The Stare. It was the look of a heavyweight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
