<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0883 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLAAS-5TH-ANNIV-ART-N     09-29 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLAAS-5TH-ANNIV-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLY KLAAS' LEGACY: `THERE ARE KIDS WHO WILL BE SAVED' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of memorial to Polly Klaas where her body was found
is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BLEYS W. ROSE The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif.   c.1998
N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Polly Klaas' disappearance from her bedroom in Petaluma, Calif.,
during a slumber party five years ago ignited a massive nationwide
search that ended two months later with the discovery of the
12-year-old's body near an abandoned sawmill.
</P>
<P>
   Her killer, an ex-con with a history of kidnapping women, was
caught and convicted, but the stunning nature of the crime _ a
stranger snatching a child from her home _ continues to reverberate
in law enforcement agencies across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The slaying spurred a series of reforms in the criminal justice
system, including changes in how authorities handle missing
children cases and the enactment of tough new laws for dealing with
repeat offenders, especially those who prey on children. Polly's
death also created an explosion in the public's awareness of sex
offenders living in their midst.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been lots and lots of changes and all for the
good,'' said Polly's mother, Eve Nichol. ``There is no question
that there will be kids who will be saved because of them. There is
no better memorial to my Polly.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, police immediately enlist the help of the media and
volunteer search organizations when they believe a child has been
kidnapped. They also use the Internet to quickly disseminate
information.
</P>
<P>
   And thanks to the public reaction and political furor over the
kidnapping, about 30 states in the nation will soon have
legislation mandating prison for repeat offenders. In California,
there are now about 4,100 repeat offenders in prison primarily
because of the state's ``three strikes'' law, which mandates
25-year to life sentences for three-time felons.
</P>
<P>
   A year after Polly was killed, 7-year-old Megan Kanka was slain
in New Jersey by a neighbor with a history of abusing children. The
public outcry to both killings led almost every state to pass laws
requiring that police notify communities of sex offenders living in
their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Since his daughter's death, Marc Klaas has devoted his life to
protecting children; he says things have improved in the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is much greater community awareness because Petaluma set
the standard,'' he said. ``One huge step is that the FBI is more
than willing to get involved and they have agents in every field
office trained in the protocol. But, traveling around the country I
see many police agencies that are still not equipped to deal with a
Polly Klaas case, there is still a reluctance to believe a stranger
did this to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the kidnapping exposed flaws in the flow of information
in the criminal justice system, state government and local agencies
moved to fill in the gaps. California lawmakers made complete
criminal records more accessible to different agencies. And Sonoma
County police agencies closed a hole in their radio communications
that had prohibited the news of the kidnapping from being sent
beyond Petaluma.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case has made it clear to an entire generation of law
enforcement that you don't let anything go unexamined, that you
give the case appropriate treatment when a kid is abducted,'' said
Greg Jacobs, the assistant District Attorney who prosecuted the
case. ``Every law enforcement officer has in the back of his mind
what happened in the Polly Klaas case.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened was that Richard Allen Davis slipped through the
back door of the Klaas' home and kidnapped Polly from her room,
where she had been having a slumber party with two friends.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI compared the search for Polly to that conducted for the
kidnapped child of Charles Lindbergh. Five million flyers were
issued, pairing Polly's face with a sketch of the suspect that
turned out to be strikingly accurate.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour after Polly disappeared, Davis was caught
trespassing about 25 miles away on wooded private property on the
outskirts of Santa Rosa and his car was searched by Sonoma County
deputies. But notice of the kidnapping had not been broadcast to
the deputies and Davis was released since property owner Dana Jaffe
did not want to prosecute and the officers could find no reason to
hold him.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all missing children reports and suspect descriptions are
issued on all radio channels, regardless of jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 19, Davis was stopped again, this time by California
Highway Patrol officers and jailed for drunken driving. However, he
was released after pleading guilty because the state's criminal
computer did not show any outstanding warrants. The system has
since been modernized to provide up-to-date information on parole
violations and previous records.
</P>
<P>
   The break in the case came Nov. 28 when Jaffe called police
after finding clothing and personal items not far from the spot
where Davis had been questioned by deputies.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for Dana Jaffe checking her property to see that wood
cutters had cleared brush properly, this might have gone down in
history as an unsolved crime and I don't know if Davis would ever
have been caught,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   After checking their files and reviewing Davis' record as a
burglar and twice-convicted kidnapper, authorities were able to
locate him at his sister's home at the Coyote Valley Indian
Reservation. He was arrested on a parole violation on Nov. 30,
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Five days later, Davis called for Mike Meese, the Petaluma
police officer heading the investigation, and confessed. He then
led authorities to the girl's body.
</P>
<P>
   A study commissioned by the Justice Department in 1994 and
conducted by the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children
said from 3,200 to 4,600 children a year may be victims of stranger
abductions. That's a small percentage of the estimated 495,000
children that the center said are runaways, abandoned, or are
abducted by family members.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jacobs and other law enforcement officials now
acknowledge that several weeks passed before they accepted that
Polly was kidnapped by a stranger. Most child kidnappings result
from custody fights or domestic disputes and are committed by a
family member, a common thread that until the Klaas case largely
determined the course of police reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Davis case became the worst case scenario in a child
kidnapping and now everyone excepts that as the norm,'' said Davis'
attorney, Barry Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Meese, the officer who handled Polly's case, said her legacy is
that law enforcement now takes a much closer look at how they
handle missing children cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI now has a much closer involvement with local law
enforcement and even developed a protocol for handling cases based
on this kidnapping. This case demonstrated that cooperation between
agencies can work if they set aside their parochial agendas.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we now have an awareness of child safety that we did not
have before Polly Klaas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Bleys W. Rose is a staff writer for the Press Democratin Santa
Rosa, Calif. This story was distributed by The N.Y. Times News
Service.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
