s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KUDELKA-DANCE-$ADV04-     09-29 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUDELKA-DANCE-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIRECTOR WITH AN EVOLVING CLASSICAL LEXICON  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By VALERIE GLADSTONE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Kudelka walked through the corridors of American Ballet
Theater's headquarters on lower Broadway in Manhattan as if he
belonged there. Although he became artistic director of the
National Ballet of Canada in 1996, his many years as a freelance
choreographer make him feel at home with troupes all over the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he came down from Toronto to coach Ballet Theater's
second ensemble, the Studio Company, and to make final arrangements
for his troupe's one-week engagement at City Center, which begins
Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kudelka began with James Crescent and Isaac Stappas, who were
learning his piece ``Passage.'' Regarding them intently from behind
his round, steel-rim spectacles, he looked like a mathematics
professor trying to figure out a difficult equation. ``Be more
fluid coming into the arabesque from the deep plie,'' he
instructed, as the plaintive chords of the taped accompaniment
filled the room. They tried again. It was clear he would correct
them until they got both the steps and the emotion just right. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't demonstrate the way I once did,'' explained Kudelka,
who is 43. ``I remember seeing articles about the search for a cure
for back pain when I was a young dancer and never believing I'd
suffer.'' He winced. ``It's the strain. I suspected that running a
company would be like creating a full-length ballet every day _ and
it is. Sometimes the responsibility for so many people's lives
weighs me down. I used to be in psychotherapy to talk about myself.
Now I spend most of my sessions discussing human relationships.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kudelka wanted the job. ``I was tired of spending so much
of my life in hotel rooms making up short ballets,'' he said. ``All
that responsibility without any authority. I wanted to impose my
vision.''
</P>
<P>
   When his 45-member company performs this week, he hopes his
vision will be apparent. It has been 10 years since its last visit.
``I strongly believe in the traditions of classical dance,'' he
explained, ``but I'm trying to animate them and move the language
forward. That's what people should see.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, foreign talent gave the National Ballet name
recognition _ the works of the English choreographer Frederick
Ashton and the American choreographer Glen Tetley, the performances
of Rudolf Nureyev and the leadership of the Danish dancer Erik
Bruhn.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1951 by the English dancer Celia Franca, it still
carries on the English tradition of story ballets, although
abstract works increasingly enter the repertory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the National can also be appreciated for its Canadian
character,'' Kudelka said. Although his father came from Hungary,
his mother was Canadian, and they made their home, with his six
siblings, on a dairy farm in Newmarket, Ontario, outside Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian created every ballet the company presents in New
York, and almost all of its members are homegrown. Four
high-profile dancers, including Vladimir Malakhov and Robert
Tewsley, left to follow Kudelka's predecessor, Reid Anderson, to
his new position as director of the Stuttgart Ballet. But Kudelka
doesn't begrudge him their defection. ``Reid has always been a
wonderful mentor and friend,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kudelka's long choreographic career began when he was 13 and a
student at the National Ballet's school. ``Even then,'' said
Christopher House, the artistic director of Toronto Dance Theater,
``James showed incredible facility and imagination.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He continued to create works throughout the years he performed
with the National Ballet and the experimental Les Grands Ballets
Canadiens. At both companies, he eventually also held the position
of artist in residence. His reputation grew with each new piece. He
received commissions from the San Francisco Ballet, Boston Ballet,
American Ballet Theater, the Toronto Dance Theater and from the
soloists Margie Gillis and Peggy Baker. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Upon becoming artistic director of the National Ballet, Kudelka
joined the elite group of well-known choreographers who run
companies. The short list includes John Neumeier at the Hamburg
Ballet, Jiri Kylian at Netherlands Dance Theater and William
Forsythe at Frankfurt Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   ``James is an artist through and through; he sees everything in
terms of art,'' said Valerie Wilder, the National Ballet's
executive director. Greta Hodgkinson, a principal dancer, agreed,
``He has already been wonderfully thought provoking for the
dancers. James makes us hear music in new ways.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The programs at City Center show Kudelka's breadth. They feature
six New York premieres, four of them by him, with the others by
John Alleyne, artistic director of Ballet British Columbia and
Dominique Dumais, a National Ballet soloist.
</P>
<P>
   Kudelka's pieces are ``Musings'' to a Mozart quintet (1991),
``The Four Seasons'' to the well-known Vivaldi score (1997),
``Desir'' to Prokofiev waltzes (1991) and ``Washington Square,''
based on Henry James' novella, to music by Michael Conway Baker
(1979). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These ballets contain Kudleka's trademarks: complicated
classical footwork, free use of the arms, intricate, convoluted
stage patterns and psychological depth. They synthesize the many
styles he danced, classical and modern, during his performing
years.
</P>
<P>
   The themes of love, romance, death and sex pervade them all. ``I
commission James,'' said Kevin McKenzie, artistic director of
Ballet Theater, ``because he is a superb choreographer, but also
because I like his dark side.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now a bright side, evident in the spirited ``Four Seasons,''
complements that dark side. Last year, Kudelka choreographed a
joyful ``Nutcracker.'' In May, his version of ``Swan Lake'' will
have its premiere in Toronto. ``I don't do things only for myself
anymore,'' he said, ``I do them for the company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
