<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARNINGS-CRUNCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE US COMPANIES EXPECTED TO FEEL OVERSEAS WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Once investors saw consumer-products companies as a
good bet in hard times, but Gillette Co.'s announcement Monday that
it plans to lay off 4,700 workers is a sign that the rules have
changed _ and a sign that problems overseas are hitting home.
</P>
<P>
   According to conventional wisdom, people buy items such as
razors, laundry detergent, and soda even in a recession.
</P>
<P>
   And for that reason, companies like Boston-based Gillette;
Coca-Cola Co.; and Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., maker of Tide, Pampers,
and Charmin toilet paper, have often fared better during tough
times than cyclical industries such as steel or semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not anymore. That's because Gillette is now as likely to
sell razors in Russia as in Boston. And P&AMP;G gets about do 10
percent of its $37 billion in annual sales from in Asia, said
Edward Jones analyst Tony Vento, who follows both companies.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, a leap in Brazilian interest rates or the fall of
the Russian ruble can hurt such companies.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G and and Gillette went overseas for a simple reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the growth is,'' said economist Ezra Greenberg of
Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, a Lexington, Mass. forecasting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Look at Gillette. For the last five years, profits grew about 11
percent annually from sales in the United States, Canada, and
Western Europe. For the rest of the world, annual profit growth was
running at about 20 percent _ until recently.
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason for that difference in growth. Many American
men are already willing to spend a dollar or more on a razor-blade
cartridge. But many Russians still shave with 8-cent razor blades.
As a result, there's a greater opportunity for profits as Gillette
seeks to persuade Russians to trade up and buy more expensive
blades.
</P>
<P>
   However, with the ruble heading south, Gillette's Russian sales
are falling. Duplicate this pattern over many emerging markets, and
a result is that the overseas profit growth that Gillette once
enjoyed ``isn't there'' this year, said Gillette spokesman David
Fausch.
</P>
<P>
   A slump in foreign markets, along with the costs of launching
the Mach3 razor, led Gillette to warn Monday that third-quarter
profits will be lower than expected &UR;  &LR; after 32 quarters of
double-digit gains. The warning came as a bit of a shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a surprise they're continuing to have problems; it's
the magnitude,'' said analyst Vento, who added, ``It's worse than
we thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillette issued its warning Monday after the stock market
closed. On the New York Stock Exchange Tuesday, shares fell 2 3/8
to close at 37 5/8 on heavy trading of 15.2 million shares. Since
July, Gillette shares have lost 40 percent of their value.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Gillette's assurance that sales of Mach3 are going
``gangbusters,'' some analysts aren't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a real sense yet of how successful or
unsuccessful the Mach3 is going to be,'' said analyst Robert
Izmirlian of Standard &AMP; Poor's Equity Group. ``I'm not so sure
people want to spend $6 and change for four (razor) blades.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillette insists that its layoff announcement is unrelated to
problems in Asia, Russia, and Brazil. A plan to reorganize and
streamline the company has long been in the works, Fausch said. &UR;  &LR; 
Nevertheless, economists expect that Gillette's announcement of
layoffs is only among the first of many. Analyst Vento, for one,
expects P&AMP;G to announce some layoffs soon.
</P>
<P>
   And over the next six months, layoffs in Massachusetts could
approach the thousands as various companies feel the effects of
overseas turmoil, said Rachael Chioino, a regional economist for
Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to companies such as Gillette, she said, ``Exports have
been rising rapidly _ almost explosively for the last few years _
and that market has been pulled out from under a lot of companies
that have been riding that export boom.''
</P>
<P>
   Two more US companies joined Gillette Tuesday and said they
expect to be hurt by overseas problems. One was Goodyear Tire &AMP;
Rubber Co.; the other was RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Near term _ the next six to 12 months _ things will be
tough,'' Vento said of Gillette. ``But the basic long-term
fundamentals of the company remain the same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
