<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0886 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CANTON-ART-2T     09-29 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CANTON-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANTON, OHIO: CLINTON SUPPORT IN BELLWETHER DISTRICT REMAINS
STRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (An American Place: Two years later.)  
(Editors: Throughout 1966, Michael Winerip, national correspondent
for The New York Times, reported from Canton on the forces shaping
the political debate at the grass roots. Last week he returned to
gauge reaction by residents to the investigation into the sexual
relationship between President Clinton and former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By MICHAEL WINERIP   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Ohio _ In 1996, Canton's newspaper, The Repository,
endorsed Bill Clinton for president. It was not an easy call for
editorial board members. For much of its history, The Repository
has had a Republican slant. At the endorsement meeting, while
editors praised the president's economic and welfare overhaul
policies and called him courageous for standing up to the gun and
tobacco lobbies, they also fretted over ``the character issue,''
``the womanizer,'' ``the guy involved in Whitewater.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm frightened,'' David Kaminski said to his fellow editors
that day in late October 1996, ``that we will be embarrassed as a
newspaper if we endorse Clinton and have a huge scandal break
out.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, of course, is exactly what happened. Fifteen months
later, as details of the investigation into the relationship
between the president and former White House intern Monica Lewinsky
came spilling out, Kaminski, the Repository editor, and his fellow
board members began to seethe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was growing more and more disgusted with the fact that his
sexual relationship was part of a national discourse,'' said
Kaminski. ``I have a 12- and 15-year-old and they're quite aware
that the president is accused of awful things.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle Beck, the editorial page editor, who describes herself as
``moderate to liberal'' feminist said, ``I was so upset, I could
not bring myself to editorialize about the dress _ I found it so
offensive that we as a nation had to think about it, so I didn't
mention it.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Starr report became public, ``we were simply
appalled,'' said Kaminski. ``Our patience broke. I read excerpts
from The AP midafternoon on the computer. It put us over the
edge.'' That evening of Sept. 11, the newspaper that had
twice-endorsed Clinton composed an editorial beginning with the
words: ``President Clinton ought to resign. He has destroyed his
presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the two weeks since, it has become clear to The
Repository's top editors that they are out of step with their
community on this one. This is a political bellwether, a place that
votes as America does for president, that swung to the Republican
presidents during the 1980s and to Clinton in the 1990s, and from
extensive interviewing here it is clear that people strongly
support the president. Even right after the Starr report was
issued, when the sentiment against Clinton was most heated, calls
to the newspaper's response line favored the president's remaining
in office; that first weekend, 56 percent of the 674 callers
opposed impeachment. ``I even hear it from my mother,'' said
Michael Hanke, the newspaper's general manager. ``She's never
talked about the news business in her life and she tells me,
`That's HIS business, ''' referring to the president's private
life.
</P>
<P>
   It is the ordinary people of Stark County, not the political
elite, who are behind the support for the president. Just as there
is a division between Americans living inside and outside the
Washington Beltway, there is a split here in Stark between
community leaders and the general population that goes beyond
Republican and Democratic politics.
</P>
<P>
   The people who run the newspaper and the judicial system, the
nonprofit agencies and the schools, tend to be much more concerned
with the implications of a politician like Clinton lying than
mainstream Stark County residents, who often assume that lying and
evasion are the standard operating procedure for politicians.
Leaders immersed in public policy spend their lives striving to
bring order to community life; the general population lives with
the reality, the cracks, gaps, imperfections, potholes and
shortcomings of daily life.
</P>
<P>
   An example of this split in the community: Sally Efremoff is a
family court magistrate and former school board member who voted
for Clinton in 1996 because she was in agreement with his stands
for abortion and against school vouchers. She now thinks it would
be best if he resigned. ``I tell the young people who come before
me in court you shouldn't lie, you shouldn't cheat. And then they
see the president's not paying attention to this? The whole system
of justice is built on the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is not how Tom Gates, a Republican who voted for Bob
Dole in 1996 and George Bush in 1992, working the register at The
Book Shoppe in the Canton Centre mall, sees it. Gates does not
support impeachment because he feels this is more about sex than
lies, and he expects politicians to lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a politician, that's how you get into power,'' said
Gates. ``Clinton's a standard politician.'' Rita Amedeo, a
supermarket produce clerk who tends to vote Republican, although he
voted for Ross Perot in 1996, agrees. with that view. ``I hate to
see him resign or be impeached,'' she says. ``It's not that this
kind of thing hasn't happened to other presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Stark, a political swing county of 370,000 in northeastern Ohio,
has voted as America has in eight of the last nine presidential
elections. For that reason, The New York Times spent the 1996 year
writing about political and economic trends here and that November,
Stark County voters gave Clinton an 8 percentage point victory _
precisely his national margin. While there has been no scientific
polling done in Stark recently (it is too expensive for the local
paper to undertake), from six dozen interviews done here at
supermarkets, factories, a bar, a book shop, a hair salon, as well
as with community leaders ranging from Joel Cochran, minister of a
Christian Coalition church, to Rep. Ralph Regula, the moderate
Republican representing the district, to Jim Repace, president of
the union at the Hoover vacuum cleaner factory, it appears
Clinton's support is still strong.
</P>
<P>
   At GSV Design Group, a beauty salon in one of Canton's pricier
neighborhoods, the verdict one recent afternoon _ even among women
who did not support Clinton for president in 1996 _ was nearly
unanimous in his favor. Rosemary Zaremba, a housewife getting a cut
and wash, never much liked Clinton (''I can't believe I'm standing
up for him'') but does not think he should be impeached.
``Absolutely not,'' she said. ``Most men would lie in that
situation. This isn't a public issue _ I think if they said they'd
investigate all of Congress the way they did Clinton, this would be
over quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The salon owner, Sharon Vaccani, (Dole '96, Bush '92) who was
doing Ms. Zarmeba's hair, agreed, ``As Rose said, he hasn't done a
bad job as president _this isn't impeachable.'' And Toni Mikstay,
the hairdresser at the next station (Dole, `96) felt the same. ``I
don't think anything should happen to him,'' she said. ``Look, I
didn't vote for Clinton for president, I thought he was a weasel,
too shady, but this is a personal matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Katie Hanenkrut (Perot `96) interrupted her shopping at a
Fishers Foods supermarket to say, ``No other president was
impeached for these doings. You can't judge someone's personal life
as long as it doesn't interfere with your work life.'' And Wendell
Skelley, a supervisor for American Electric Power, (Perot '96, Bush
'92) carrying an armful of groceries said, ``This has all been such
a waste of money and time. Quite frankly, there's an awful lot of
people in the same situation. Quite frankly, even a person you work
with could be in the same situation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A majority of those interviewed see it as a personal matter and,
for guidance on how to judge it, look into their own lives and the
lives of their neighbors. There is no more respected family in
Stark County than the Timkens, who for four generations have run
the the Timken steel and bearing company, Stark's biggest employer,
with 6,800 workers here and 21,000 worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Timkens are admired for working to keep good-paying union
jobs in Canton and for their local philanthropy. They are known as
rabid Republicans who donate $100,000 to the party during
presidential election years. And they are also known as a family
that has had its share of stormy marriages and painful divorces.
Last year, W. R. ``Tim'' Timken Jr., the company chairman, reached
a divorce settlement with his first wife just before the case was
to go to trial and remarried a few months later.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1980s, Joseph Toot Jr. was divorced from one of
Timken's sisters, but continued as company president. ``People here
talk about the Timken situation, the Toot situation,'' said Repace,
head of the union at Hoover and a Clinton supporter. ``And their
attitude is `live and let live.' I think it's the same attitude you
see about the president. We're going to impeach a president because
he had an affair and didn't want to stand up and admit it? I mean,
come on.''
</P>
<P>
   Regula, a cautious, moderate Republican, who is expected to
easily win re-election to a 14th term, has not taken a stand on
impeachment. In the days after the Starr report, he says, calls to
his office were running three to one for impeachment, but the grand
jury videotape ``moderated people, you could feel a shift, and
we're not getting a lot of calls now.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, too, is helped by the economy here; when he was
elected in 1992, unemployment in Stark was about 8 percent;
currently it is 3.9 percent. Janet Weir Creighton, the county
auditor, (a Republican who thinks the president should resign) says
``our country is in great shape, our county is in great shape.''
Sales tax revenues are up 6.5 per cent over last year; the general
county debt was recently paid off; real estate values are up an
average of 18 per cent and challenges to property tax assessments
are at an all time low. ``People are happy,'' she says, ``People
are content.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a fear, expressed even by middle of the road
Republicans, that impeaching Clinton will set loose right wing
forces in the Republican Party. Nancy McPeek, a banker, a former
president of the county United Way, and a moderate Republican (Dole
'96) believes that the president should have to go through the
impeachment process, but she also worries it will make the right
wing more dominant in the party. ``If they're successful,'' she
says, ``it will give the Far Right a bigger bandstand for the
conservative approach to issues like abortion and vouchers and that
does scare me.''
</P>
<P>
   It scares Democrats even more. They are in a bad position in
Ohio, even without Clinton's problems. Republicans are favored to
win all six statewide races this year, including governor and
senator. Susan Keim, a nurse (Clinton `96 and `92) says she is fed
up hearing congressional leaders bragging that they are not going
to be paying attention to the public opinion polls as they make
their decisions on Clinton. ``I hate that,'' she said, ``I think we
count. We are the polls.'' Her husband, a Timken steelworker, said
in November, for the first time in years, ``I'm just voting
straight Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
