A0888 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ECONOMY30-COX     09-29 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ECONOMY30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON PLANS EVENT TO CELEBRATE BUDGET SURPLUS
 &HT;    690&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton plans a White House ceremony
Wednesday to trumpet the first federal budget surplus in three
decades _ and to fire the next salvo in his election-year battle
with congressional Republicans over what to do with the money.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's message from the Rose Garden will be decidedly upbeat:
In the federal fiscal year that ends Sept. 30, the government will
be out of the red for the first time since 1969, having slain a
deficit dragon that threatened the nation's economic future.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office has estimated the surplus for
the 1998 budget year at $63 billion. Clinton will announce a new
White House estimate ''in the $70 billion range,'' an
administration official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who was first elected in 1992 partly on a promise to
stem the flow of red ink, means to make the most of the good news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's easy to imagine that if we were going to get the
first federal budget surplus in a generation, the first since 1969,
the first since people were wearing paisley bell-bottom trousers
and paisley ties, ... yes, we would want to crow upon such an
achievement,'' said White House spokesman Michael McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is also ready to use the budget surplus to Democrats'
advantage in the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   In fund-raising speeches in recent weeks, Clinton has claimed
that the surplus resulted from the leadership of Democrats who
understand the need to balance taxes and spending.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans counter that the surplus is the outcome of their
1994 takeover of Congress, which under the Constitution has the
sole authority to levy taxes and spend money.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we had not had welfare reform and entitlement reform and
domestic discretionary spending cuts and the tax cuts that
increased economic growth, we would still be in deficit,'' House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., asserted in an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the real hero of the deficit struggle has been the economy,
Gingrich said, not either party nor the president.
</P>
<P>
   ''He can take 5 percent of the credit, we'll take 5 percent and
90 percent goes to the American people, who go to work every day
and pay taxes,'' Gingrich said. ''I don't think they're all that
impressed watching politicians run around and take credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Private economists agree with Gingrich about the origins of the
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's almost entirely a function of the economy doing well,''
said Patrick Fleenor, senior economist for the Tax Foundation, a
nonpartisan Washington research group. ''Revenues are coming into
the federal government at an unprecedented level.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the federal government collected an estimated $1.72
trillion in taxes and fees during the year that ends Wednesday.
That's one-fifth the value of all the nation's goods and services,
the highest proportion since at least 1962.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans, contending that at least some of the surplus
should be returned to taxpayers, have approved a proposal to cut
taxes by $80 billion over the next five years, a plan Clinton has
already vowed to veto.
</P>
<P>
   Any surplus in the federal budget, Clinton has said, should be
set aside until Republicans and Democrats can develop a plan for
shoring up the Social Security program, which faces serious
financial troubles early in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not against tax cuts,'' Clinton told a group of wealthy
Democrats at a fund-raiser here Monday night. ''But I do not
believe we should get into this surplus for tax cuts, or for
Democratic spending programs, until we have saved the Social
Security system for the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich countered that Clinton is engaging in ''demagogic
dishonesty'' by attacking Republican-backed tax cuts while
proposing his own spending increases under the label of ``emergency
spending'' and suggesting that Republicans aren't committed to
shoring up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ''We ought to set aside money to save Social Security. We're
prepared to do that, and he and I have been talking about it since
October of last year,'' Gingrich said. ''I think we will pass a
bill next year to save Social Security, on a bipartisan basis.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the partisan squabbling over what to do with it, a
budget surplus, after three decades of red ink, is good news for
the country, which doled out an estimated $363 billion in interest
this year simply servicing its huge debt.
</P>
<P>
   ''Washington ought to be, by and large, pleased with the budget
outcomes,'' said Donald Straszheim, president of the Milken
Institute, an economic research group in Santa Monica, Calif. ''I
don't think this is a party issue. Both the House and the Senate,
and the White House, have been involved in all of the decisions of
the last 10 or 20 years'' that have helped rein in deficit
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the dirty little accounting secret that neither party is
likely to mention Wednesday is that, in the strictest sense, the
budget is still not balanced.
</P>
<P>
   This year's $70 billion surplus includes $104 billion in funds
generated by two Social Security trust funds. Technically, that
money should not be counted as government revenues. Take it away,
and the federal budget, for all the celebration Wednesday, remains
in deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
