<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0889 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-29 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE GASBAG GANG  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK RICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone knows that something big happened, but what? ``It's as
if a boil was lanced and the fever has broken,'' said Ed Markey, a
Massachusetts congressman, after the Bill Clinton grand jury video.
Yes, the country's mood about-faced that Monday _ but why?
</P>
<P>
   You've heard the media's answers: ``Scandal fatigue.'' ``The
American people just want it to go away.'' ``Clinton is a master at
television.'' ``Ken Starr and the Republicans overplayed their
hand.'' But these same catch phrases had been applied to the public
reaction to the release of the Starr report and every other scandal
``shocker'' before that. They don't explain the fallout this time,
when the country defied talking-head predictions by not only
boosting Clinton's polls yet again but by seeming to pronounce the
whole story over.
</P>
<P>
   The best explanation I've heard comes not from a journalist but
a film maker in Los Angeles. He speculated that the marathon video
was, in theatrical terms, a nine-month drama's catharsis. By being
forced ``to talk about his penis for four hours on television,'' as
my acquaintance put it, Bill Clinton did in effect receive a
punishment, just or not, that landed with the audience as if it
were a final curtain. Never ``Macbeth'' to begin with, Monicagate
had found a climax satisfying its own trashier scenario _ a
mortifying public humiliation instead of a beheading. Like any
cathartic denouement, it leaves the audience feeling relieved. It
breaks the fever.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the new mood's origins, the media are already
chastising the unwashed masses for it. ``Yes, the American people
say they've had enough of the story,'' we're instructed, ``but
there is a constitutional process that must be followed.'' Once
more ``the American people'' are being told by what Calvin Trillin
in Time labels TV's ``Sabbath Gasbags'' that they are too stupid or
amoral or selfishly prosperous to get with the program of the
Washington Establishment.
</P>
<P>
   When history looks back at this saga it will show that the
media, after initial stumbling, did get the scandal's facts
straight _ yes, ABC's Jackie Judd is vindicated, there IS The Dress
_ but that they were clueless about what they keep condescendingly
calling ``the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Film makers and other artists may yet make more sense of this
story than have the mass journalistic media. This week The New
Yorker offers intriguing thoughts on Monicagate by novelists as
various as Jane Smiley, Louis Begley, James Salter and Toni
Morrison. Stephen King has told his views to Salon. William Styron,
Guenter Grass and Gabriel Garcia Marquez have advertised theirs by
petition. But one novelist has gone so far as to write a nearly
novella-sized nonfiction narrative of the story _ so sharp that it
could bear the ironic title ``Democracy,'' in honor of Henry Adams'
archetypal Washington novel, had its author, Joan Didion, not used
it for a previous book.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Didion's must-read piece, in The New York Review of Books,
wastes little time arguing for or against Clinton, who, like Starr,
is almost a bit player in her account of the Washington
political-media culture that conveyed its war to the rest of us.
Instead she follows the gasbags _ whose sole knowledge of
``Americans at large'' comes from focus groups and ``the Q and A
after a lecture date'' _ as they turn the public into the scandal's
``unindicted co-conspirator.'' As Ms. Didion documents with
abundant specifics, the gasbags repeatedly treat Americans as
``recalcitrant children, fecklessly resistant to responsible
guidance.'' Meanwhile they exploit the nation's actual children as
moral bludgeons, constantly citing ``our kids'' as the casualties
of the President's bad example.
</P>
<P>
   As if to ratify Ms. Didion's take, Nickelodeon this week took
the radical step of having Katie Couric and Linda Ellerbee converse
with children about the scandal _ instead of treating us to more
tearful ``What will the children think?'' sermons by All Monica
commentators too busy rushing into makeup to talk to their own. The
kids, of course, knew full well what Clinton had done, but had no
loss of moral compass; they held firm that lying and adultery are
wrong even as they disdained impeachment. In other words, they
sounded just like all those stupid adults who have for nine months
refused to follow the Beltway's script _ in Washington, the real
impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
