<HEADLINE>
RATE CUT HAS LITTLE IMPACT AS DOW FALLS BY 28.32 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also FED, FED-CONSUMERS) 
(mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first interest rate cut since January 1996 failed
to impress stock investors Tuesday, and the major market indexes
were narrowly mixed at the end of a fairly active session.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in the bond market had a somewhat stronger reaction
and drove up prices, particularly in the long end of the market,
pushing the yield on the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond down to
another 30-year low, to 5.09 percent. (Bond prices and their yield
move in opposite directions.)
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the Federal Reserve Board announced shortly after 2
p.m. ET Tuesday that it had voted to lower its target for the
federal funds rate, by one-quarter of a percent, to 5.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks, which were modestly higher early in the day, pulled back
after the Fed decision was announced, and the market see-sawed for
the rest of the day. The Dow Jones industrial average closed down
28.32 points, or nearly four-tenths of 1 percent, to 8,080.52.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poors 500 index eked out a gain of 0.33 of a
point, to close at 1,049.02. And the NASDAQ composite index fell
5.17 points, or three-tenths of 1 percent, to 1,734.05.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a rate cut has been viewed as a near certainty
since Sept. 23, when Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, told
Congress that slumping economies abroad were a bigger threat to the
health of the American economy than inflation. And stock prices
staged some strong rallies for a few days after he made those
comments.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, Tuesday's announcement had an anticlimactic
element.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed never used to announce interest rate cuts like they
are doing now,'' said Al Goldman, chief market strategist at A.G.
Edwards in St. Louis. ``We have spent the last several sessions
discounting this news.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the session had its share of surprises, and some were
unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   A number of big companies, including Goodyear Tire and Rubber,
Viacom Inc. and CBS Corp., were hit hard on concerns that
third-quarter earnings would not meet expectations. And the Fed's
rate cut failed to provide much assistance to many financial
service company stocks, despite the fact that such companies stand
to benefit directly from a reduction in borrowing costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the general earnings tone remains poor, the laundry list
of companies buying back stock has accelerated in recent days,''
said Thomas Galvin, investment strategist at Donaldson Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette. ``We may get to a point where lower rates cushion the
economy, stabilize earnings and some big- market capitalization
sectors, like the financials, technology and energy, show gains.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors hammered stocks that were not dispensing good news.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear, North America's largest tire maker, fell 3 3/4, to 52,
after warning that unfavorable conditions in Asia and Latin America
would cause third-quarter earnings to fall short of expectations.
The stock's drop accounted for about 25 percent of the decline in
the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Viacom Inc. fell 11 percent on concern that higher
costs at its Blockbuster Entertainment video store chain and MTV
Networks cable unit would hamper growth in third-quarter cash flow.
The company's Class B shares fell 6.88 to 56.75 in heavy trading.
</P>
<P>
   CBS fell 2 1/2, to 23 1/4, on concern that cash flow growth in
its television businesses would slow due to advertising cutbacks by
General Motors in the wake of its recent strikes.
</P>
<P>
   But other companies that have previously announced a slowdown in
third-quarter earnings saw their stock prices improve. A notable
example was Coca-Cola, which rallied for the second straight day.
Coke's stock closed at 58 11/16, up 1 7/16 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to disappoint, the market will kill you,''
Goldman said. ``But if your outlook is better, you get rewarded.
This market is becoming much more discriminating than it was a few
weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices rose after the Fed announcement, even though
some traders and investors had expected a cut of half a percentage
point.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury rose 22/32, to 106 7/32. The
yield of 5.09 percent was down from 5.14 percent on Monday and down
27 basis points, or hundredths of percentage points, from where it
was just three weeks ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
