<SLUG> BC-THERMO-PRESIDENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERMO NAMES NEW PRESIDENT; COMPANY TO LAY OFF 700 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Texas, Calif.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Citing Asia's economic slowdown and a desire to speed a
previously announced restructuring, Thermo Electron Corp. has named
a new president and says it will lay off more than 700 employees in
three subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The high-technology conglomerate which, including its nearly two
dozen affiliates and subsidiaries, had $3.6 billion in sales last
year, will take $53 million in charges against third-quarter
earnings, mostly for severance pay.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the announced layoffs are at Thermo Instrument Systems
Inc., the Waltham, Mass. &UR;  &LR; company's largest publicly traded
subsidiary &UR;  &LR; in Franklin, Mass.. But a spokeswoman said Tuesday only
a few of those cutbacks will be in Massachusetts, with the bulk in
Texas and California or overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, George N. Hatsopoulos, Thermo Electron's chairman and
chief executive, named Arvin H. Smith, 69, chief executive of
Thermo Instrument, as the parent firm's president, effective
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Hatsopoulos, 71, said Smith will share with him previously
announced goals to shed money-losing or low-profit units, and
ultimately choose a top management team from among four candidates
promoted to co-chief operating officers in August.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Hatsopoulos said widening global
economic problems prompted the company to speed up the
restructuring that was also announced in August. Thermo Electron,
which has about 23,000 employees at operations worldwide, said then
that it intends to reduce its present 23 operating divisions and
subsidiaries to 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a business slowdown in manufacturing in the United
States, and our businesses have been hurt somewhat from the Asian
crisis,'' Hatsopoulos said. ``I wanted to accelerate the
(restructuring) process and rather than waiting a couple of years,
do it before the end of this year.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Thermo Instrument alone, with about $1 billion in sales
last year, expects about a 10 percent drop in both revenues and
earnings this year.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has been with Thermo Electron for 28 years and was already
executive vice president of the parent company. He succeeds John
Hatsopoulos, 64, George's brother, whose plans to retire also were
announced in August.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Lewis, one of the four co-chief operating officers named
then, will become chief executive at Thermo Instrument.
</P>
<P>
   George Hatsopoulos said Smith had been discussing retirement but
agreed to stay on for two to three years to complete the
restructuring and executive transition.
</P>
<P>
   Of the restructuring charges announced Tuesday, the largest
share, about $28 million, is at Thermo Instrument, which makes high
technology laboratory equipment used in the drug, biotechnical, and
other manufacturing industries.
</P>
<P>
   Other cutbacks are planned at ThermoLase, a unit of publicly
traded ThermoTrex that operates a chain of spas, and ThermoRetec,
an environmental remediation firm.
</P>
<P>
   Thermo Electron's stock closed up 1/8 at 15 15/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
