<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0894 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLAM-FILM-ART-$ADV04-     09-29 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAM-FILM-ART-$ADV04-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING A CELLBLOCK AN UNLIKELY GARDEN OF FREE ENTERPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 4)  
 (af)  
 (Laura Winters writes frequently about arts and entertainment here
and abroad)  
 
 By LAURA WINTERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marc Levin's feature film ``Slam'' is a vivid marriage of ideas
usually seen as contradictions: documentary and fiction, action and
poetry, black and white.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slam,'' which opens here on Friday after being shown at the
New York Film Festival, is the story of a young black performance
poet, Raymond Joshua (Saul Williams), who is imprisoned on a petty
drug charge but who manages to establish his identity and his voice
within the maelstrom of a Washington jail.
</P>
<P>
   As indicated by the punning title, the premise of ``Slam'' is
itself unusual: not often are jail (the ``slammer'') and the
spoken-word scene (``slams'' are competitive poetry performances)
linked together.
</P>
<P>
   The film is actually fiction, though it gains a graphic
documentary quality from having been shot mainly at the District of
Columbia's Detention Facility. Both hard-driving and entertaining,
with its poetry and a hip-hop soundtrack, ``Slam'' won prizes at
both the Sundance and Cannes film festivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of people, the experience of `Slam' feels really
fresh,'' said Geoffrey Gilmore, Sundance's director of programming.
``We all have seen films about young struggling kids from a
minority background who end up in jail. The difference with `Slam'
is that the film goes beyond this to talk about creativity and the
exploration of one's soul, no matter what the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of how ``Slam'' was made is as striking a narrative as
the film itself, due to the film's cast of characters and to the
collaborative way in which it was created. Marc Levin, one of the
film's producers and writers as well as its director, is an
award-winning documentary film maker.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Stratton, another of the film's producers and writers,
is a novelist and journalist who served eight years in a federal
penitentiary for importing marijuana. Henri Kessler, a third
producer, is a former club owner and party promoter.
</P>
<P>
   Levin, Stratton and Kessler are all white, but the three
principal actors whom the film introduces, and who all crafted
their own parts, are black. Both Saul Williams, who plays the
central figure of Ray, and Sonja Sohn, who plays his lover and
mentor Lauren, are poets and actors, while Bonz Malone, who plays
the prison leader Hopha, is a writer and former graffiti artist who
has also served time.
</P>
<P>
   How these larger-than-life personalities came together to form
the patchwork quilt of ``Slam'' is a story that starts with Levin's
own background. Born in New York and reared in New Jersey, the son
of political activists, Levin, 47, owes his sensibility partly to
the ferment of the late 1960s, when he came of age.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamic gray-haired director has made a career of filming
documentaries that explore such issues as the drug war and race
relations. When asked about the challenges he has faced as a white
film maker exploring this terrain, he said, ``That's always been
the spot I've been drawn to in American culture _ the place where
black and white cultures meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere do these worlds collide more than in Washington, where,
as Levin says, ``there is one of the highest rates of incarceration
for young black men, and yet it is also our nation's capital.''
</P>
<P>
   He was drawn there to make a documentary within the Washington
jail system in 1997 because of a wish to expose what he calls ``the
waste of all these lives. We've written off a generation of young
black men, because as a society we've reached a place where
rehabilitation and compassion are no longer on the page.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting HBO documentary, ``Thug Life in D.C.,'' will be
playing in limited theatrical release this fall and led directly,
for Levin, to the birth of ``Slam.'' While shooting ``Thug Life''
in the spring of 1997 at the D.C. Detention Facility (familiarly
dubbed the D.C. Jail), it occurred to Levin that he might have
finally found the locale for a feature film.
</P>
<P>
   He and his partners, Stratton, Kessler, and David Peipers had
formed Offline Entertainment Group in 1994 with the aim of making
feature films, and Levin had been considering the story idea of an
artistic black kid who goes to jail. This character became a poet
when Levin saw Saul Williams performing at a poetry slam in April
of 1996 and cast him as his lead.
</P>
<P>
   Denied access to New York's Rikers Island, the film makers
turned to the Washington prison administrators they knew from the
documentary; those administrators took the startling step of
approving the filming of ``Slam'' in their jail. ``The director of
the D.C. Department of Corrections was Margaret Moore, and the
warden of the jail was Pat Jackson,'' Levin said, ``strong,
intelligent black women who are torn apart because they're putting
away their own people.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Jackson, who has since moved on to another prison, said,
``Marc and his crew wanted people to know about the whole process
and were really ultimately concerned with `How can we make this
change?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In structuring ``Slam,'' Levin allowed his actors to create
their own lines and decided to shoot in a spontaneous,
documentary-like style that was dubbed, by his crew, ``drama
verite.''
</P>
<P>
   The actors spent nine months developing the story and their
characters before filming started. Much of the dialogue was to be
improvised on camera.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Raymond Joshua (Williams) manages to stave off a
beating in jail by a dazzling poetry performance that literally
disarms his enemies. The charismatic prison leader Hopha (Bonz
Malone) pays Raymond's bail so that he can spread a message of
nonviolence on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Once out, Ray embarks on a romantic relationship with the
writing teacher whom he had met while in prison, as he grapples
with the reality that he will most likely still have to serve time.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When Levin got in touch with Malone, a longtime friend, to ask
him to play the role of Hopha, he found him serving a four-month
sentence on Rikers Island for assault. ``As it turns out, it was
role rehearsal,'' Malone said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A slight 30-year-old whose business card reads ``consigliere,''
Malone is a combination of ambassador and impresario. By age 18, he
was writing a column for Spin magazine, and he now writes a monthly
column for Vibe magazine called ``Tuph St.'' ``I ran with gangs
since I was 12, been in jail in and out since I was 15,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His experiences have made him embrace what he says is ``Slam's''
uplifting message. `` `Slam' is about a young poet who goes to jail
and finds his voice _ first how to free himself, and then how to
free others,'' he said. ``It's about bettering your life situation
even in a harder place. I've (italics)been(end italics) there.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 26, who as Ray performs his own poetry throughout the
film, has, in contrast, an almost otherworldly sense of calm and a
majestic way of speaking. Rangy and dreadlocked, he grew up in
upstate New York, the son of a Baptist pastor and a schoolteacher.
</P>
<P>
   He has a master's in fine arts degree from New York University.
``In preparing to play Ray, my through-line was `How many spells
can I cast through poetry?' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sohn, who plays Lauren Bell, has her own fervor. Tall, half
Korean and half black, she grew up in projects in Virginia and
knows the terrain of ``Slam'' well. In one scene, Lauren, teaching
a workshop in the jail, breaks down in tears as she mentions her
dead brother _ a detail Ms. Sohn took from her own life. ``I hope
the film gives a reality to those stereotyped faces and lives that
people think they know,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After getting approval from the prison administrators, the team
drove down to Washington in late July of 1997 for a two-week
guerrilla-style film shoot. The financing of ``Slam,'' which cost a
little over a million dollars, only fell into place at the end:
until then, Kessler had maxed out his credit card.
</P>
<P>
   The film has sly humor, notably in the scene where Marion Barry,
the former mayor of Washington has a cameo role as an anti-drug
judge. The film makers also cast some of the real inmates in
various roles, all the while improvising and working under time
constraints.
</P>
<P>
   This gave rise to scenes such as the one where Williams, playing
Ray in his jail cell, embarked on an extended verbal riff with an
actual prisoner, Bay, in the cell next door. ``We were freestyling
back and forth, for 45 minutes,'' Williams said. ``They didn't even
say, `Cut.' They just changed the film and let us keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most galvanizing scene to shoot was the one
where Ray faces his enemies down in the jail yard. The warden
unexpectedly closed down the shooting that night, but then allowed
the crew to shoot again the following day _ only for an hour,
though, and with more inmates in the yard, many of whom were not
aware that Williams was not a real prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting these `new kid' looks from people,'' Williams
recalled. ``When it came time for people to start gathering around
me, some of them actually did want a piece of me.'' He smiled.
``But the poetry stopped them.''
</P>
<P>
   In this volatile environment, Levin kept his cool. ``Marc knows
that life itself is unscripted,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Slam'' team attributes the acclaim that the film
subsequently attracted at festivals to the nature of Ray's odyssey.
Despite the sobering questions the film poses about the justice
system, it also presents the idea of freedom as a metaphysical,
rather than a literal, state.
</P>
<P>
   I think the key to `Slam' is in that line which Lauren says:
`Freedom isn't out here, it's in here,' '' said Ms. Sohn, pointing
to her head. `` `Never give anyone the power to take away your
freedom.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There are no easy answers in the film, only many heated
arguments. ``The film is about choices,'' Malone said. ``It's
foolish to think that this is just one race or class of people
affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the film seems to have set in motion a string of
other projects. Levin has just finished shooting ``White Boys,''
partly financed by Fox Searchlight Pictures, which was shot on
location in Iowa and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``White Boys,'' starring Danny Hoch and written by Hoch and
Levin, among others, is a dramatic comedy about white teen-agers in
the Midwest who emulate black hip-hop culture. Not only does Levin
intend to sustain his drama verite methods in his next films, he
also intends to continue exploring the questions that he raised
with ``Slam.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been so stuck in definitions _ liberal and conservative,
black and white,'' he said. ``That's one of the great things about
the hip-hop generation: there's a new dialogue of race. We have to
find a new way of thinking about black and white. You have to get
in and mix it up and tell people, `This is what I want to say.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
