<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-CINK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cink man with task
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ Stewart Cink's mission is clear. He can't
let it happen. To have a Tour Championship occur at East Lake Golf
Club in four weeks and to fail to make the field would be a huge
opportunity lost and a circumstance too depressing to ponder.
Besides, who else out there in the top 30 knows how greens that
once felt the spike marks of Bobby Jones break on a daily basis?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my home course,'' Cink said. ``I can't miss that. There's
no secret about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The quest continues for Cink this week at charming, challenging
Callaway Gardens, Ga. during the Buick Challenge, where last year
only one man, Davis Love III, finished ahead of him. He stands 32nd
on the PGA Tour money list and needs to make the top 30 to enjoy
the opportunity at East Lake Oct. 29-Nov. 1. Passed Sunday by Hal
Sutton, who won at the Texas Open to jump over the $1 million mark
and assure his spot in the Tour Championship, Cink crept a bit
closer, tying for 11th and earning $31,733 for a 1998 total of
$783,941.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still know where I rank on the tour as a player,'' he said.
``I still think I can get the job done. I'm looking for a high
finish, hopefully a victory. I still feel like I have a chance to
win every time I tee it up and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Maturity has always come smoothly for the former Georgia Tech
player. Becoming a father in college, as son Connor pushed he and
wife Lisa's lives to the organizational limit, accounted for a huge
part of the process. In less than two years as a full-time player,
Cink, 25, has matured similarly on the PGA Tour. It would surprise
nobody if after shooting 17-under last year and losing, he were to
beat everybody around the Mountain View course this week and drive
back to Smyrna, Ga. in a new Buick. Same thing if Cink made the
Tour Championship and earned its $720,000 first prize. He has
established himself that solidly, that quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But first Cink has to get in. He doesn't want to think about his
friend Billy Andrade falling $5 short in 1997. If Cink is teeing
off at East Lake Oct. 29, he could have a distinct edge on the
field. It's a track where he has shot 64 just playing with friends
and members. As straightforward as the Rees Jones redo of Donald
Ross' original work is, there are quirks to the greens that Cink
has been filing away since beginning an affiliation with the club
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it could be a real advantage because I know the
greens,'' Cink said. ``They're tricky and they're hard to read
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowledge of how to handle the Bermuda rough won't hurt, either.
And Cink, when in Atlanta lately, has been playing East Lake with
the rough beyond the six-inch mark. Heck, you could lose a club in
the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't cut it,'' Cink said, ``I think the rough will be
the determining factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
