<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golf Notes: Rains hit Callaway
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ Now that the Buick Challenge has managed to
assemble its best field in history _ 21 of the top 30 money-winners
_ the mission is to keep it from floating away. Unfortunately,
Callaway Gardens' alternating-year weather jinx has appeared again,
thanks to stalled Hurricane Georges, which is expected to soak the
Mountain View course, in its best condition in recent years, at
least through Thursday. Texas Open winner Hal Sutton Sunday became
the latest qualifier for the Tour Championship, moving from 31st to
15th with a win at San Antonio. One thing is certain, regardless of
the weather, there will be no two-round champion, as was the case
in 1996, when Michael Bradley won a 20-minute, one-hole, five-man
playoff for the title. The PGA Tour has made a commitment to play
at least 54 holes to determine a champion. . . . With hard rains
Tuesday at Callaway, Buick Challenge defending champion Davis Love
III and Justin Leonard picked a good time to play their ``Shell's
Wonderful World of Golf'' match at Winged Foot Golf Club,
revisiting the 1998 PGA Championship site. Leonard had to enjoy a
change of scenery after bogeying the final two holes Sunday at San
Antonio _ missing a 5-footer at the 18th _ to finish second.
</P>
<P>
   Monty's back
</P>
<P>
   Just when it appeared Scotland's Colin Montgomerie's next move
might be reaching for the long putter, he settled his putting game
well enough to win the German Masters last Sunday. Although the
major championships still befuddle Montgomerie, he took over the
lead in the European Order of Merit by 119,926 pounds over
England's Lee Westwood and has a sixth consecutive money title in
reach. ``I'm proud of myself for being able to show what I can only
call the courage to win,'' said Montgomerie after sinking a
5-footer at the 18th to beat Vijay Singh and Robert Karlsson.
</P>
<P>
   Chip shots
</P>
<P>
   At least four players will be playing the Atlanta area
``trifecta'' this fall _ Buick Challenge, Tour Championship and
Sarazen World Open. Mark Calcavecchia, Jim Furyk, Payne Stewart and
Scott Hoch, provided he receives an expected sponsor exemption, are
scheduled for all three. . . . Maple Ridge pro Mike Gill of
Columbus, Ga. aced Mountain View's fifth hole during Monday's Larry
Mize Pro-Am. . . . Corey Pavin's top 10 Sunday at San Antonio,
Texas was his first since a tie for eighth at the 1997 Mercedes
Championships. . . . Hoch undoubtedly confounded German TV
audiences last week when he popped a fairway wood from the rough
during the European Tour telecast and yelled, ``Infield fly rule in
effect!'' . . . Tom Watson is playing the Buick Challenge for the
first time in 25 years since it was at Green Island in Columbus,
Ga. as the Buick Southern Open. . . . Jack Nicklaus has selected
his son Jackie, 37, as his captain's assistant for the President's
Cup in Australia Dec. 11-13. . . . Robert Gamez, who has missed
nine cuts in the last 10 events, said, ``I built a new house and
I've been in it five months, but I can't furnish it the way I've
played.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
