<HEADLINE>
FED'S CUT SHOULD MEAN LOWER BORROWING RATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also MARKET, FED) 
(mk) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve's decision Tuesday to lower interest rates
for the first time since January 1996 should translate into lower
borrowing rates on many consumer loans and keep mortgage rates for
home purchases and refinancings below 7 percent at least through
the end of the year, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   The reduction of a quarter of a percentage point, to 5.25
percent, in the target for the federal funds rate was smaller than
had been widely anticipated. But the impact is enough to keep
30-year fixed-rate mortgages below 7 percent in 1998 and possibly
through 1999, said Robert Barr, a senior economist at Fannie Mae, a
congressionally chartered private company that helps finance
mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   The Mortgage Bankers Association of America, a trade group, has
an even more optimistic forecast, estimating that rates could drop
as low as 6.25 percent before the year ends.
</P>
<P>
   Mortgage rates are at their lowest levels in a generation but
have not fallen as much as yields on Treasury securities, the
benchmarks for calculating rate trends.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that strong investor demand for Treasuries as a
safe haven from turbulent markets has pushed those yields lower.
</P>
<P>
   The average rate on a 30-year fixed-rate mortgage was about 6.64
percent in the week ended Sept. 25, the 15th consecutive week of
rates below 7 percent, according to Freddie Mac, the mortgage
company. That level was 2.07 percentage points higher than the 4.57
percent yield on 10-year Treasury securities. On average, 30-year
fixed mortgage rates are usually about 1.5 percentage points higher
than the yield on 10-year Treasury notes.
</P>
<P>
   That gap could narrow as Treasury rates stabilize near historic
lows and mortgage rates slip, Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, new mortgages for home purchases and refinancings are
expected to hit a record $1.4 trillion, said Brian Carey, an
economist at the Mortgage Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
   After the Fed's move Tuesday, Norwest Bank in Minneapolis cut
its prime lending rate, and others were expected to follow. The
prime rate is a benchmark for other consumer and corporate loans,
like credit cards, auto loans and small-business loans. The prime
rate, 8.5 percent at most banks, should fall by at least a
quarter-point, analysts estimate. Banks may also cut the interest
rates they pay on savings accounts and certificates of deposit.
</P>
<P>
   On average, savings accounts paid interest of about 2.17 percent
in April, according to Bank Rate Monitor, a research firm in North
Palm Beach, Fla., that reports savings account rates twice a year.
One-year certificates of deposit at banks paid an average rate of
4.69 percent as of Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers with such loans as adjustable-rate mortgages and home
equity lines of credit tied to the prime rate could see the impact
of lower rates within the next few months, said Keith Gumbinger,
vice president of HSH Associates, a financial research firm in
Butler, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
