<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves breakdown by position
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FIRST BASE: Andres Galarraga
</P>
<P>
   Andres Galarraga has exceeded what the Braves had hoped,
answering the questions about age (37) and Coors Field by producing
the best numbers ever by a full-time Braves first baseman. Of
concern is a late-season power swoon. Galarraga finished the year
with just two homers in his last 74 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
<P>
   vs. Chicago .211 8 3 7 0
</P>
<P>
   1998 .305 169 44 121 7
</P>
<P>
   SECOND BASE: Keith Lockhart
</P>
<P>
   A potential problem area. Keith Lockhart missed two weeks in
late September with a problem hamstring and is one misstep from
being on the bench. Platoon-mate Tony Graffanino finished the
season hitting .155 during the last two months. Lockhart likes
October. He has a .364 postseason average.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
<P>
   Vs. Chicago .182 6 0 1 0
</P>
<P>
   1998 .257 94 9 37 2
</P>
<P>
   THIRD BASE: Chipper Jones
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones had 11 hits in nine playoff games last year, but
the memory of his performance during the last postseason has served
as an incentive this season. His 122 runs this year are the most by
a Braves player in 15 years, and he became the first Atlanta player
since Dale Murphy to drive in 100 runs three seasons in a row.
</P>
<P>
   C. Jones Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
<P>
   Vs. Chicago .314 11 3 7 2
</P>
<P>
   1998 .313 188 34 107 16
</P>
<P>
   SHORTSTOP: Walt Weiss
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's feel-good position. Walt Weiss, 34, and Ozzie Guillen,
33, are back in the postseason, when neither thought they'd get a
chance. Weiss got one ring with Oakland nine years ago, but
Guillen, a critical acquisition, has never had a sniff of the World
Series in 13 seasons in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
<P>
   Vs. Chicago .000 0 0 0 0
</P>
<P>
   1998 .280 97 0 27 7
</P>
<P>
   LEFT FIELD: Ryan Klesko
</P>
<P>
   The Braves could use an upgraded performance from Ryan Klesko,
who hasn't posted numbers this low since he was a rookie. After a
June appendectomy, he hit just five more homers and drove in just
23 runs. Danny Bautista, slowed by a tender knee, platoons to
offset Klesko's .213 average against left-handed pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
<P>
   Vs. Chicago .241 7 0 1 0
</P>
<P>
   1998 .274 117 18 70 5
</P>
<P>
   CENTER FIELD: Andruw Jones
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones, who proved himself to be the best center fielder
in the league this year, also was one of the club's driving forces
through the second half. Jones rose above his manager's periodic
ire to emerge as the player the Braves have been advertising, all
of that coinciding with his 21st birthday.
</P>
<P>
   A. Jones Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
<P>
   Vs. Chicago .419 13 1 7 1
</P>
<P>
   1998 .271 158 31 90 27
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT FIELD: Michael Tucker
</P>
<P>
   It runs hot and cold in right, where Michael Tucker struck out
112 times, lost 39 points off his batting average from last year
and cast some doubt about his future in the organization. Gerald
Williams platoons to hit .366 against left-handers and accounted
for five homers and three doubles in his last 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
<P>
   Vs. Chicago .321 9 0 3 0
</P>
<P>
   1998 .244 101 13 46 8
</P>
<P>
   CATCHER: Javy Lopez
</P>
<P>
   No catcher hit more home runs than Javy Lopez, and only Mike
Piazza drove in more runs than Lopez's 106, second most by any
Braves catcher in history. (Joe Torre had 109 in 1964.) Add in
reserve Eddie Perez and the position went 40-for-138. Lopez's eight
passed balls tied a career-low.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
<P>
   Vs. Chicago .344 11 1 3 0
</P>
<P>
   1998 .284 139 34 106 5
</P>
<P>
   BENCH
</P>
<P>
   Do they have enough? By platooning at three positions, manager
Bobby Cox can match up with any bullpen in the late going.
Left-handed Curtis Pride hit .184 as a pinch hitter, but
right-handed Greg Colbrunn hit .389 off the bench since rejoining
the club in July. As Atlanta benches have gone, this is better than
most.
</P>
<P>
   Colbrunn Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
<P>
   Vs. Chicago .000 0 0 0 0
</P>
<P>
   1998 .307 51 3 23 4
</P>
<P>
   Pride Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
<P>
   Vs. Chicago .667 6 1 3 1
</P>
<P>
   1998 .252 27 3 9 4
</P>
<P>
   PITCHING STAFF
</P>
<P>
   NO. 1 STARTER: John Smoltz
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz started the year in Greenville on an injury-rehab
assignment and wondered if his elbow would make it to Memorial Day.
He finished the year pitching as well as he ever has. He had the
best winning percentage in the majors, and his strikeout ratio (9.3
per nine innings) was the second-highest of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz W-L ERA IP BB SO
</P>
<P>
   Vs. Chicago 0-0 9.00 2.0 0 0
</P>
<P>
   1998 17-3 2.90 167.2 44 173
</P>
<P>
   NO. 2 STARTER: Tom Glavine
</P>
<P>
   No NL pitcher has had more 20-win seasons this decade than
Glavine, whose 20-6 record has him in line for his second Cy Young.
His 2.47 ERA is a career-low, and he finished strong, going 8-2
with a 1.98 ERA in his last 14 starts. He was even better away from
Turner Field, posting a 12-2 record and a 1.78 ERA on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine W-L ERA IP BB SO
</P>
<P>
   Vs. Chicago 1-0 2.12 17.0 3 13
</P>
<P>
   1998 20-6 2.47 229.1 74 157
</P>
<P>
   NO. 3 STARTER: Greg Maddux
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux led the NL in ERA (2.22) and broke the 200-strikeout
barrier for the first time in his career. His 142 victories since
1991 are the most in the majors. But a 6-7 second half remains
unexplained and resulted in Maddux being dropped to third in the
postseason rotation. He is 3-0 in four LDS starts.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux W-L ERA IP BB SO
</P>
<P>
   Vs. Chicago 0-0 0.00 0.0 0 0
</P>
<P>
   1998 18-9 2.22 251.0 45 204
</P>
<P>
   BULLPEN: Kerry Ligtenberg
</P>
<P>
   Braves relievers finished strong, with only four runs allowed in
their last 33 2/3 innings (1.07), and the transfer of Denny Neagle
and Kevin Millwood to the bullpen only makes it a stronger group.
Kerry Ligtenberg is just the third Atlanta closer to reach 30
saves. The deposed Mark Wohlers did it only two times.
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg W-L ERA SV BB SO
</P>
<P>
   Vs. Chicago 0-0 9.00 0 4 4
</P>
<P>
   1998 3-2 2.71 30 24 79
</P>
