</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-BAILEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dogs are championing Bailey
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ What's in a name?
</P>
<P>
   That's what University of Georgia athletics officials are asking
Heisman Trophy voters across the nation this week in the school's
most aggressive promotions pitch in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   And the Bulldogs are hoping voters agree that Georgia's Bailey
is the Champ.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia mailed full-color pamphlets touting junior All-America
candidate Champ Bailey as a legitimate contender for three of
college football's biggest awards _ the Thorpe (given to the
nation's top defensive back), Biletnikoff (top wide receiver) and
the Heisman, which goes annually to the nation's top overall
player.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, a 6-foot-1, 181-pound cornerback/wideout from Folkston,
will get a chance to catch voters' attention the next two weeks
when the 12th-ranked Bulldogs face No. 6 LSU and No. 3 Tennessee in
critical SEC contests.
</P>
<P>
   The road date at LSU will be broadcast nationally by ESPN at 7
p.m.; the Tennessee game in Athens will be televised regionally by
CBS at 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really big,'' Bailey said. ``The big thing is if we can
come out with some wins. It makes it that much more special. This
is about competing for a national title and everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those games are going to be big for him as far as exposure,''
Dogs coach Jim Donnan said. ``I think he'll have a chance again to
show everybody what his capabilities are.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey could be the top Thorpe candidate _ North Carolina's Dre
Bly took a big hit in last week's loss to Georgia Tech. Bailey is
widely regarded among the nation's top four defensive backs, along
with Bly, Arizona's Chris McAlister and Ohio State's Antoine
Winfield.
</P>
<P>
   But Bailey still has some work to do in the eyes of Heisman
voters.
</P>
<P>
   While it's still early in the race, Bailey didn't receive a vote
in the latest Heisman poll by the Scripps Howard News Service,
which was released Tuesday. Bailey received three votes the
previous week.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks Cade McNown of UCLA, Donovan McNabb of Syracuse,
Tim Couch of Kentucky and Michael Bishop of Kansas State continue
to garner the most attention from voters, along with Texas running
back Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are still 20 guys out there who have positioned
themselves for Heisman consideration,'' said Don Borst, a Heisman
voter and Seattle-based correspondent for ESPN. ``I think Williams
was the leader at the beginning of the year, but he's not anymore.
It's wide open.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of an apparent front-runner could benefit Bailey, who's
starting to receive the attention of a serious candidate. CBS,
CNN/SI and ESPN plan to broadcast lengthy segments on Bailey in the
next two weeks. Feature articles on Bailey will be published later
this week in the Washington Post and USA Today newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing hurting Bailey is that he hasn't been on television
that much,'' said Heisman voter Chris Harry of the Orlando
Sentinel. ``It's funny because every time you see highlights of
him, he's diving for a pass or making a play on offense. I think
what voters want to see are the spectacular defensive plays. But
I'd vote for the guy. The guy's almost exactly like (1997 Heisman
winner Charles Woodson of Michigan).''
</P>
<P>
   Woodson, a surprising Heisman winner over Tennessee quarterback
Peyton Manning, may have opened the door for two-way players like
Bailey. Through three games this season, Woodson's and Bailey's
statistics nearly mirror each other.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Woodson had 11 tackles and one interception on
defense in the first three games. He also had three catches for 74
yards and one touchdown on offense, and returned nine punts for 63
yards. Woodson averaged about 70 plays in 12 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey's best performance this year came in Georgia's 17-3 win
at South Carolina on Sept. 12. He had 86 plays in that game and
made a 50-yard reception late to seal the victory. Through three
games, Bailey has 12 tackles and one interception on defense; 11
receptions for 218 yards and two touchdowns on offense; and one
kickoff return for 24 yards on special teams. He missed nearly the
entire second half of Georgia's 16-9 win over Wyoming on Sept. 19
with cramping in both legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bailey is probably as good or better than what Woodson brought
to the table,'' said Tom Dienhart, college football writer for The
Sporting News. ``I don't think there's any question about that.
When Michigan needed a big-play guy on offense, they went to
Woodson. Bailey's obviously that guy at Georgia right now. He's the
one stretching the defense to open up the running game.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodson's obvious advantage over Bailey? A national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows?'' Dienhart said. ``If Georgia comes out of this
October stretch with five wins, the guy would be near the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
