A0903 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS30-COX     09-29 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' better half is the second
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons are 2-1, but the way they arrived
at that record contains a disturbing trend. Opponents have combined
to outgain Atlanta 734-397 and outscore the Falcons 47-14 in the
first halves.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has either trailed or been tied at halftime in each of
its three games.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that Atlanta has outscored opponents, 42-10,
and outgained opponents, 578-405, in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons coach Dan Reeves knows the slow starts won't get the job
done during the course of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a team that can afford to fall behind, and try to
catch up (on a regular basis),'' said Reeves, who indicated that
the team has been bothered by crowd noise in two road games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taking us too long to adjust,'' linebacker Cornelius
Bennett said. ``I don't think we do a good enough job getting our
personnel situated, and adjusting to (opponents') tendencies.''
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious in the Philadelphia game, which Atlanta won 17-12
after trailing 9-0 at halftime. The Eagles outgained the Falcons
208-64 in the first half -- at home. It wasn't until the second
half that Atlanta began attacking Philly's rookie cornerbacks and
trying to take away the Eagles' short passing game by jamming
receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Halftime) is the only time when you get everybody together,
and get their attention (to make big adjustments),'' defensive
coordinator Rich Brooks said. ``I just don't think we're ready for
the speed and tempo of games.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the practice week winds down, players go into a `glide,'
where they don't practice as fast. Then the game rolls around, and
it seems (the other team) is going 900 mph. Maybe we need to
emphasize practicing faster, not more physical to where people get
hurt, but faster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I agree with that, but . . . we're a team that
has to consider everything,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Chris Chandler thinks part of the problem is youth.
Rookie linemen Ephraim Salaam, Jose Portilla, Bob Hallen have been
forced into duty for various reasons, and rookie receivers Tim
Dwight and Jammi German played a lot Sunday against the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's a settling-in period or getting over
jitters,'' Chandler said, ``but as the game wears on, we do things
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler has a passer rating of 69.8 in the first half, 89.9 in
the second half. Jamal Anderson is averaging 23 yards in the first
half with a 3-yard average per carry; in the second half, he's
averaging 72 yards on 5.7.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons also have no sacks in the first half, six in the
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we have no answer,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   But the team knows something has to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to find that fire from start to finish,'' Bennett
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
