<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-KEYS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves will win/lose if....
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE BRAVES WILL WIN IF:
</P>
<P>
   _ John Smoltz keeps it going. The Cubs saw him at his worst on
May 23 _ two innings, two runs in a no-decision _ the day before
Smoltz hit the DL the second time. Since then, he has gone 13-2
with some of the most effective work of his career. Smoltz has a
15-4 career record against the Cubs, and if there is a Game 4,
Smoltz has a career 2.73 ERA at Wrigley Field. The Cubs haven't
beaten him the last 10 times they've faced him, dating to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Braves can keep the Cubs out of the big inning. When it
absolutely needs to score, Chicago has had trouble manufacturing
runs, which favors Atlanta in a close game. The Cubs are ranked
11th in the league in sacrifice flies, 11th in sacrifice bunts and
15th in stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   _ Atlanta's bullpen can maintain its late-season surge. While
the Braves were finishing with a 14-2 run, the relievers performed
about as well as they have all season. The bullpen allowed only
nine runs in its last 44 2/3 innings (1.81 ERA), and five of those
runs came in one inning, on Sept. 13 against Florida. Braves
relievers struck out 40 batters in the last 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Cubs maintain their Atlanta profile. Chicago has not fared
well in Georgia in recent years, going 7-17 the last four seasons.
Turner Field had posed a particular hurdle. The Cubs lost nine of
their first 10 games at the Braves' new home, until they swept a
two-game series July 20-21.
</P>
<P>
   _ Greg Maddux maintains his mastery over his former employer.
Since leaving the Cubs after winning the 1992 Cy Young award,
Maddux is 7-1 against Chicago. The only defeat came in his last
start, on July 21. In 11 career starts against his old team, Maddux
has given up only 16 earned runs in 84 1/3 innings (1.71 ERA).
</P>
<P>
   THE BRAVES WILL LOSE IF....
</P>
<P>
   _ They allow the Cubs to hammer them as they did all summer.
Chicago's .271 team average was tied with Colorado's for the
highest against Atlanta pitching this year. The 50 runs were the
second-most scored against the Braves. The Cubs also homered 11
times off Atlanta, and that was with Sammy Sosa sitting out two
games with a bad hand.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Cubs remain patient at the plate. Chicago is ranked sixth
in the NL in walks, but the team was far better than that against
the Braves. No one walked more against Atlanta than the Cubs' 36
times, which worked out to once every 3.9 innings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gary Gaetti realizes that it's October. The veteran third
baseman has a .192 career average (15-for-78) against the Braves
since coming to the National League three years ago. But in the
1996 postseason, while with St. Louis, he hit .292 against the
Braves in the NLCS, including an eighth-inning grand slam in Game 2
off Maddux at Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium that broke open an 8-3
Cardinals victory.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kevin Tapani continues to baffle Atlanta. Though he has a
career 4.50 ERA against the Braves, he has two wins in three starts
against them this season.
</P>
<P>
   _ They don't get improved performances from second baseman Tony
Graffanino and right fielder Michael Tucker. Both have struggled
much of the year and finished hitting a combined 57 points below
their career averages. But both have had excellent years against
Chicago: Graffanino is hitting .500 and Tucker .321 with three
doubles, a triple and eight walks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
