<HEADER>
A0908 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CUBS-KEYS-COX     09-29 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-KEYS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cubs will win/lose if ...
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE CUBS WILL WIN IF....
</P>
<P>
   _ Kerry Wood suddenly finds that his right elbow is strong
enough to pitch. Wood threw 51 pitches in an instructional league
game Monday and he might be able to pitch in Game 3 on Saturday,
when the series is scheduled to go to Wrigley Field. Wood has been
tough at home, with a 9-1 record and 2.97 ERA. He was 1-0 against
the Braves in three starts, allowing five runs in 20 2/3 innings.
Wood has not pitched since Aug. 31. Chicago has a real chance if
the Cubs can split the first two games in Atlanta and have Wood
available.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sammy Sosa goes on another of his homer binges and the Cubs
follow suit. Sosa hit three of his 66 homers against the Braves,
but when he's on a tear, the rest of the team gets excited. Twenty
one of Sosa's homers have given the Cubs the lead. Sosa has only
three hits in 33 career at-bats against Game 1 starter John Smoltz.
He has to stay hot.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cubs pitching shuts down Chipper Jones and Andres Galarraga,
who have hurt Chicago this season. But that's a lot to ask of a
tired staff. Manager Jim Riggleman had to use 19-game winner Kevin
Tapani in relief Monday night in the playoff game against the
Giants, so the Game 1 starter will be Mark Clark (9-14), who was
0-1 against the Braves with a 5.88 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   _ The bullpen regains its early-season form. This group has
labored, especially after Wood was sidelined and Terry Mulholland
was moved back into the rotation. Closer Rod Beck has 51 saves, but
he has shown signs of fatigue. The key could be Terry Adams, who
has struggled with a 4.33 ERA. The Cubs, 30-27 in one-run games,
have a chance if they can keep the game close.
</P>
<P>
   _ They get a little luck on their side. This is a mismatch on
paper. But Chicago won six of nine against the Braves during the
regular season. And the Cubs are overdue for some postseason
success.
</P>
<P>
   THE CUBS WILL LOSE IF ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Chicago plays like it did during the final week of the regular
season. The Cubs looked like a beer-league softball team. If they
make mistakes against a veteran club like the Braves, it will be
over in three.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sosa goes into a slump. When Sosa plays well, the Cubs win. He
is hitting .308 against Braves pitching this year, with three
homers and five RBIs in 26 at-bats. Braves pitcher Greg Maddux has
said before that he doesn't like facing the free-swinging Sosa,
because he hits pitches outside the corners, where Maddux likes to
work.
</P>
<P>
   _ Riggleman is forced to go to his bullpen early. The Cubs are
thin in relief, and Riggleman needs to stretch his starters as long
as possible. Both Steve Trachsel and Tapani should be able to give
a little extra.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wood doesn't pitch. The Cubs are a much different team when
Wood is pitching. He can take over a game, especially against a
team that swings for the fences, as the Braves sometimes do. If he
is unavailable, the chances of Tapani, Trachsel and Mark Clark
carrying the Cubs are slim to none.
</P>
<P>
   _ They freeze. It happened to the Braves in 1991, when they
faced the Pirates and lost Game 1. But the Braves were involved in
a seven-game series and had time to adjust and win. Chicago cannot
afford to freeze in a five-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
