 &HT;    CUBS Lineup By Position
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   POSITION PLAYERS
</P>
<P>
   FIRST BASE: Mark Grace
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa swings the big bat for the Cubs, but Mark Grace is
the heart of the team. Grace is one of the most consistent players
in baseball. He has hit above .300 four years in a row, and he's
one of the best defensive first basemen in the game. Grace hits
John Smoltz (21-for-63) and Tom Glavine (22-for-72), but struggles
against Greg Maddux (6-for-27). He is hitting .333 with runners in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
<P>
   Vs. Braves .290 9 0 5 0
</P>
<P>
   1998 .309 184 17 89 4
</P>
<P>
   SECOND BASE: Mickey Morandini
</P>
<P>
   A change of scenery has worked for Mickey Morandini, who is
having a career year. Morandini is hitting around .300 and has
driven in 14 more runs than last year. He doesn't make many
spectacular plays in the field but is solid, with good range and a
strong arm. Morandini is hitting .353 (19-for-54) against Smoltz
and .308 (24-for-78) against Greg Maddux. He hit just .241 in
September but is at .352 with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Morandini Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
<P>
   Vs. Braves .469 15 0 4 0
</P>
<P>
   1998 .296 172 8 53 13
</P>
<P>
   THIRD BASE: Gary Gaetti
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs acquired Gary Gaetti from the Cardinals on Aug. 19, and
he played a major role down the stretch. Gaetti has hit eight home
runs, including the huge one in Monday's playoff victory over the
Giants. Gaetti has plenty of postseason experience, including the
Twins' 1987 world championship, and he played well against the
Braves in the 1996 league championship while with St. Louis. Gaetti
is consistent on defense and can provide the big hit.
</P>
<P>
   Gaetti Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
<P>
   vs. Braves .000 0 0 2 0
</P>
<P>
   1998 .281 122 19 71 1
</P>
<P>
   SHORTSTOP: Jose Hernandez
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs opened the season with Jeff Blauser at shortstop, but
he struggled, hitting .219. So the Cubs turned the spot over to
Jose Hernandez, who can play almost any position. Hernandez has
provided more power than the team thought he had. He is one of the
best athletes in baseball but hit only .155 this month.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
