   vs. Braves .179 5 1 2 0
</P>
<P>
   1998 .251 104 31 85 1
</P>
<P>
   CENTER FIELD: Lance Johnson
</P>
<P>
   For years, Lance Johnson has been one of the steadiest leadoff
hitters in the game. He covers a lot of ground in center field but
has been slowed by hamstring problems that limited him to 83 games
and dropped his stolen bases to 10. But Johnson is hitting .365 in
September and provides leadership in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
<P>
   vs. Braves .250 2 0 1 0
</P>
<P>
   1998 .280 85 2 21 10
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT FIELD: Sammy Sosa
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa has become so much more than a home-run hitter. His
.308 average is 51 points better than his career mark, and he's
hitting .309 with runners in scoring position. He hit at least one
homer in 15 consecutive series and had 11 multihomer games, which
tied a major-league record. He still struggles defensively at times
and didn't steal bases this season as he had in the past. Of
course, that could be because he had 30 more homers than last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa Avg. H HR RBI SB
</P>
<P>
   vs. Braves .308 8 3 5 0
</P>
<P>
