<HEADLINE>
MIGHTY DUCKS NOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Even though the Anaheim Mighty Ducks are 1-5 in the
exhibition season and have allowed 26 goals in their last four
games, Anaheim goalie Guy Hebert insists it's not the time to
panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a time to continue to be positive, he said. ``Everybody
is still excited. We didn't expect to come in and win every game.
I've played for a long time and I've never seen a team go 9-0 or
10-0 (in the exhibition season) and go on to win the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert says it's going to take time for the team to learn new
coach Craig Hartsburg's defensive system, which features at least
one defenseman remaining in front of the Anaheim net at all times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are used to playing man-to-man, and in this system you
have to be very patient, he said. ``I think it will be effective,
but you're not going to learn it and perfect it in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert says the system is something completely new to him, but
that he likes the idea that Hartsburg is very committed to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited Craig is going to work with one system and keep
working on it, he said. (That he's) not going to change from night
to night and get guys more confused. I think in the long run it
will be very effective for us.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, coach Pierre Page changed systems several times.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg wasn't real happy after the Ducks gave up four
third-period goals in Monday's 5-3 loss to the Kings, but he seemed
to soften his stance on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of good things happened, he said. ``I'm not happy we
lost, but we are trying to build.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no lack of effort. Eventually we will be a good
team, it could be days or a couple of weeks, but we will get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe to some people it doesn't look like (we are improving),
but we see things.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg says he isn't disappointed in any of his defensemen
thus far, but he hopes that Jason Marshall and Kevin Haller will
become the team's top defensive pairing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Haller and Marshall as two guys we can trust defensively
and play aginst the other team's top players, he said.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Pavel Trnka, a 22-year old defensemen who played well towards
the end of last season, could be on the bubble this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fighting for a position ... he needs to show us more,
said Hartsburg, who added that Trnka missing a portion of camp due
to contract dispute ``didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Patrick Lalime, who has struggled in his last two outings
(12 goals allowed) will play one of the games against Nashville --
either in Cincinnati on Friday or Milwaukee on Saturday. Hebert
will play the other game.
</P>
</TEXT>
