<HEADLINE>
THESE DUCKS GET QUACKING ON OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE AND BILLY WITZ  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oregon, off to its first 4-0 start since 1988, is ranked No.17,
but here's some even more impressive numbers: 48, 33, 58 and 63.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the Ducks' point totals in wins over Michigan State,
Texas-El Paso, San Jose State and Stanford. Just what first-year
offensive coordinator Jeff Tedford expected, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the things you'd like to happen,'' said Tedford, a
former Warren High and Cerritos College quarterback who came to
Eugene after six seasons as the offensive coordinator at his alma
mater, Fresno State.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players have done such a good job of executing. We've got
a lot of play-makers on the the field and the offensive line is
doing an excellent job.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tedford arrived this spring with plenty of questions
about the Ducks. Who would replace the Pac-10's leading rusher,
Saladin McCullough? Who would replace big-play receiver Pat
Johnson, now with the Baltimore Ravens? Could the Ducks again exist
with two quarterbacks Akili Smith and Jason Maas?
</P>
<P>
   It turns out Ruben Droughns, a JC transfer, has stepped in for
McCullough, rushing for a pair of 200-yard games. Herman Ho-Ching,
a freshman tailback from Poly, rescued the Ducks against UTEP with
three fourth-quarter touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Smith won the quarterback job and Damon Griffin, returning after
missing 1997 with a dislocated thumb, and Los Alamitos product Tony
Hartley have emerged as big-play receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system hasn't really changed at all,'' said Tedford, whose
group averages 543 yards per game. ``It's mainly the players who
are getting the job done. I think the guys understand that if they
just take care of the little things and not make mistakes, we're
going to be pretty hard to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Bearing down on defense
</P>
<P>
   California's offense was almost non-existent in a 24-14 win over
Washington State on Saturday. The Bears only scoring drive
</P>
<P>
   if that's what you call it was officially minus-14 yards and
concluded with a 42-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   So, the defense took over. The Bears recovered two fumbles,
intercepted four passes and scored three touchdowns. The touchdowns
were supplied by defensive end Mawuko Tugbenyoh
</P>
<P>
   (10-yard fumble return) and defensive backs Deltha O'Neal
</P>
<P>
   (76-yard interception return) and Drae Harris
</P>
<P>
   (26-yard interception return).
</P>
<P>
   The four interceptions matched Cal's season total of a year ago,
when the Golden Bears' allowed 237 yards passing per game and were
seventh in the Pac-10 in pass defense. Cal has eight interceptions
already this season and leads the Pac-10 in pass defense (149 yards
per game).
</P>
<P>
   Players of the week
</P>
<P>
   Oregon quarterback Akili Smith
</P>
<P>
   , Arizona State linebacker Adam Archuleta
</P>
<P>
   and California cornerback-return man Deltha O'Neal
</P>
<P>
   were selected the Pac-10 Conference Players of the Week.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was 18 of 29 for 357 yards and four touchdowns in Oregon's
63-28 victory over Stanford. Archuleta had 11 tackles, including
five for a loss and a sack in Arizona State's 24-3 win over Oregon
State. O'Neal returned an interception 76 yards for a touchdown,
returned a kickoff for 49 yards and had six punt returns for 87
yards a 14.5-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   Around the conference
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's Emory Brock made a big play in the Cardinal's loss to
Oregon on Saturday. Brock, a former walk-on and son of baseball
Hall of Famer Lou Brock, blocked a punt late in the first half to
set up a short touchdown pass and help the Cardinal close to within
35-21. ... Oregon's much-improved defense may have lost linebacker
Peter Sirmon for the season. Sirmon, the Pac-10's leading tackler a
year ago, has a torn chest muscle and did not play Saturday against
Stanford. His replacement, Chris Vandiver, has 19 tackles. ... Cal
has already matched last season's win total (three) in only four
games. The Golden Bears may be stuck on three wins for a few weeks,
however, as the next three contests are against USC, Washington and
UCLA. ... Arizona State's J.R. Redmond fumbled the ball twice in
the Sun Devils' victory over Oregon State. The talented Carson High
product has five fumbles in the first four games. ... Washington
State safety Lamont Thompson, a true sophomore with nine career
interceptions, may see more two-way duty with Nian Taylorbeing
bothered by a sore knee. Thompson played receiver against Cal, but
did not catch a pass. ... Arizona State cornerback J'Juan Cherry
was whistled for four major infractions - two pass interference, a
holding and a face mask - against Oregon State. He also made seven
tackles and had a big pass deflection near the Sun Devils goal
line. ... Arizona is 4-0 and ranked 14th in the nation, but the
wins have come against teams with a combined 3-11 record. A better
mark of what type of team the Wildcats have will come on Saturday
at Washington and Oct. 10 at home against UCLA. ... Washington,
after its 55-7 loss to Nebraska, is 1-6 against Top 10 teams since
the start of the 1995 season. It was the Huskies worst loss since a
52-0 loss to Alabama in 1975.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
