<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW BUCKS CAN'T CHANGE JERRY WEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I had dinner with Jerry West the other night, and I looked for
changes.
</P>
<P>
   I always look for changes when one of my friends signs a
five-year contract for around $18 million, which is what Jerry West
recently did with the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   As you might know, Jerry had been in my bread and water
financial category for the longest of times Laker owner Jerry Buss
had been paying him a disgusting, below market $1.25 million a
year! and I just wondered how different he would be in the wake of
his new wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will you condescend to still talk to us paupers?'' I asked
West, half in jest.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West the storied Zeke from Cabin Creek, Hall of Fame
basketball player, longtime esteemed Laker executive, longtime Los
Angeles fixture, 60 years young shook his head slowly and grinned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, please,'' he said. ``I don't take any of this stuff
seriously. Actually, I'm embarrassed by it all. I'm embarrassed by
what I make. The most my father ever made in a year was $6,000.
Sure, it's nice. It gives me security for my family. But change me?
Please. I'm the same person now that I've always been.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West's name has been in the news a lot these days, almost
as much as it was throughout the 1960s and early 1970s when he
dispensed heroics on a regular basis for the Lakers as a
high-scoring guard.
</P>
<P>
   And not just from his new contract, the signing of which
climaxed what had become such a volatile disagreement with Buss
that West, at one point, had decided to announce his retirement
from the Lakers on Aug.31.
</P>
<P>
   West also has agreed to do consulting work for super agent
Michael Ovitz, a longtime Laker season ticket holder who's put
together a group whose desire it is to bring an NFL expansion team
to Los Angeles and build a football stadium in Carson.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, West was seriously considering a lucrative offer to go
to work full-time for Ovitz on his fledgling project, but changed
his mind when Buss finally decided to meet West's salary demands.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jerry West will accompany Ovitz to an NFL meeting in
Kansas City in late October, and plans to give a speech to the
owners on the expansion team committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll talk about the virtues of having a football team in Los
Angeles,'' said West. It's absolutely ridiculous that an area the
size of Southern California doesn't have a team. I myself was a big
fan, first with the Rams and then with the Raiders. I used to go to
a lot of games, especially after I retired as a player. I think
something is missing around here on Sundays, and I hope I can help
do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   West says he's not drawing a paycheck from Ovitz for his input.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just believe in what Michael Ovitz is doing, and I think
he's going to be the person to get an NFL team here,'' says West.
``He's got some very big business people involved in the whole
process, and that proposed stadium he wants to build in Carson
would be just unbelievable. It's what we desperately need here in
L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Jerry West is concentrating all his energies these days
on bringing an NFL team to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   He's still busy with his Laker duties, even though the NBA is
now in the throes of a bitter lockout that threatens the opening of
training camp, if not the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're supposed to open in Hawaii on Oct.3, and that doesn't
seem likely now,'' said West.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ominous labor miseries hovering over his league,
West still has been spending several hours a day on the telephone
with general managers around the NBA, discussing possible trades.
</P>
<P>
   It seems as though every team in the league that needs a center
is desirous of Elden Campbell, who's proven he can play such a
position and also has proven he can't play forward alongside
Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all sorts of intriguing possibilities,'' says West
without elaboration.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I didn't detect any noticeable difference in Jerry
West's demeanor compared, say, to a former teammate of his, Pat
Riley, who changed more than any person I've known in sports after
he became rich and famous.
</P>
<P>
   Riley took his new status quite seriously, and his hat size
inflated several inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you able to look your neighbors in the eye now?'' I asked
West, who owns a home in Bel Air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' he replied. ``I'd have to make a lot more money
than I now am to reach their financial level.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Jerry West might turn out spending more time helping
Michael Ovitz this fall than worrying about the Lakers, unless the
dispute between the players and owners is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what's going to happen,'' said West. ``All I
can do on my end is prepare for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   And count all that money he dredged out of a reluctant Jerry
Buss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
