<HEADER>
A0920 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-LOBBY-II-ART-3TAKES     09-29 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LOBBY-II-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOBBYISTS ADOPTING TECHNIQUES USED IN POLITICAL CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to add art note)   (The Influence Industry: 2nd of 2 articles.)  
(EDITORS: This unabridged version of LOBBY is at the length it will
appear in The New York Times. A version at about half this length
will also move tonight in the ``w'' news file.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From the nondescript headquarters of his Houston
construction firm, Leo E. Linbeck Jr., a lanky, bow-tied executive
with a drawl, is masterminding a crusade to overturn the nation's
tax system.
</P>
<P>
   Once, someone like him might have hired some of Washington's
``Gucci Gulch'' lobbyists to prowl the marble corridors outside
Congress' tax committees. But Linbeck, with Texas-style audacity,
wants to engineer a populist uprising to replace the income tax
code with a national sales tax. And with $15 million from some
initial investors and mass fund raising, he has run a radio and
television advertising campaign and employed an army of media
consultants, pollsters, political strategists, marketers, academics
and yes, even a few lobbyists, to energize the citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine what it would be like if you were in Congress and you
got a thousand phone calls a week and letters and e-mails and
faxes,'' Linbeck, a former chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank in
Dallas, said. ``Not people from all over the country, but your
constituents, people whose names you recognize, the people who were
at the polls with you, who live down the street with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Linbeck and his fellow investors in ``Americans for Fair
Taxation'' are unusual in the scale of their ambition. But their
methods have become commonplace as lobbying has undergone a
revolution over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely now does a well-connected Washington lobbyist work alone
to persuade power brokers in Congress. Instead, the lobbyist has
become just one of many players running full-fledged national
campaigns intended to create a ``grass-roots'' groundswell in
support of, or more often in opposition to, legislation before
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In their million-dollar costs and their reliance on television,
polling and grass-roots constituency building, these efforts most
resemble presidential campaigns. And they are now so pervasive and
sophisticated that it has become difficult to distinguish between a
lobbying effort, an issue advocacy campaign and a citizens'
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these efforts are genuine grass-roots movements. But
others are deceptions in which a special interest pays to create
the appearance of a popular groundswell.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of these techniques has spread the wealth of the
influence industry beyond the lawyer-lobbyist to a new class of
political professionals, who often play overlapping roles as
advisers to presidential and congressional candidates, corporate
tacticians and media pundits.
</P>
<P>
   In a world where the distinctions and conflicts between their
multiple roles seem to matter less and less and can even be a
business advantage, strategists who are ideological enemies in
politics put their differences aside to work together on
large-scale corporate campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is the outgrowth of several developments in technology
and politics. E-mail, computer databases, talk radio and 24-hour
cable television all make it easier to organize and send a
political message across the country at warp speed.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, power in Washington has been dispersed, so
that new ways are needed to influence more legislators. The media
age politician is far more likely to be moved by polls, television
ads and mass constituent contacts than by party discipline, a
committee chairman or a Washington wise man. And the Republicans in
Congress know they came to power with the help of several groups
with grass-roots memberships: the National Federation of
Independent Businesses, the National Rifle Association, the
Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a couple of evolutions happening simultaneously,''
said Keith Appell, of Creative Response Concepts, a Republican
public relations concern that is involved in national issue
campaigns. ``There's Republican sensitivity to grass roots, and
certain lobbying methods you didn't have before and the explosion
of media in the communications age.''
</P>
<P>
   Public policy experts debate whether the new methods of lobbying
have made it more democratic by taking it out of the back rooms of
the Capitol or whether they have simply made it far more difficult
for interests without money to compete in the public arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of a trend in Washington where rational debate on
issues gets buried in big-budget sound bites,'' said Edward
Yingling, the chief lobbyist for the American Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Linbeck says of his way of moving Congress: ``It's not as
orderly. It's not as predictable. It's not as controlled as some
might want it to be. But I think those are positive attributes.''
</P>
<P>
   The convergence of the worlds of lobbying and politics is
evident in how Linbeck has gone about his people's crusade. He
estimates the effort will take several years and ultimately cost an
extraordinary $90 million, a sum likely only if hundreds of
thousands of Americans join his cause. Right now, a major tax
overhaul is only a glimmer far out on the horizon of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his initial money went to hire prominent academics and
research organizations to develop the 23 percent national sales
tax. But to speed the organizing and make his proposal as
politically appealing as possible, he has also turned to national
experts in politics, using Denis Calabrese, a Houston Republican
consultant and onetime aide to Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, as his
chief strategist. With Calabrese's help, ``Americans for Fair
Taxation'' has hired an all-star cast from both parties to propel
his tax plan:
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Wirthlin, President Reagan's pollster, surveyed the
electorate's attitudes towards the tax system, with some help from
Mark Mellman, pollster to the Democratic leadership in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   _Don Sipple, a media adviser to Bob Dole's presidential campaign
produced early television advertisements to test-market the sales
tax.
</P>
<P>
   _Fred Steeper, a well-established Republican pollster in
Michigan, checked on the advertisements' results.
</P>
<P>
   _Creative Response Concepts, whose president, Greg Mueller, was
communications director for Patrick Buchanan's 1996 presidential
run, promotes the sales tax to journalists.
</P>
<P>
   _Charles Sewell, a one-time Democratic staff aide and strategist
who is now a vice president at the Washington office of Ketchum
Public Relations, scours the country for civic leaders who can head
chapters of Americans for Fair Taxation in the nation's 435
congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   _Americans for Fair Taxation does have a more traditional
lobbying team too, from Arter &AMP; Hadden, a law firm whose ranks
include two former members of Congress from Texas, Thomas Loeffler,
a Republican, and Jim Chapman, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Argus Group, another Washington lobbying and government
relations company, has drafted the sales tax legislation. This may
sound like the lobbying equivalent of the Normandy invasion. But
ever since the epic battle against Clinton's proposal for national
health insurance in 1994, these kinds of ensembles have assembled
on issue after issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clients and industries have come to appreciate there are no
solo pilots in this town,'' said Jack Quinn, who returned to the
law firm of Arnold &AMP; Porter after he stepped down as White House
counsel. ``Now you send armies, ships, tanks, aircraft, infantry,
Democrats and Republicans, grass-roots specialists, people with
special relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, much about these campaigns remains undisclosed,
from the cost to who is behind them. Many consultants who are
willing to explain their techniques will not identify their
clients, citing confidentiality clauses in their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 the new Republican Congress approved major changes in
how Congress does business. It imposed a gift ban and passed tough
new disclosure requirements for lobbyists. But the legislation did
not include reporting requirements for ``grass-roots'' lobbying
like telephone and letter-writing campaigns, even if the campaigns
were generated by hired lobbyists and organizers.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier effort to pass a disclosure law that would have
required reporting on such lobbying faltered in the Democratic
Congress in 1994 when Rep. Newt Gingrich, then the House Republican
whip, branded the measure as an ``anti-religious'' attempt to chill
growing grass-roots conservative movements like the Christian
Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Many groups had an interest in that battle because many have
genuine, permanent grass-roots memberships, from the Christian
Coalition to the Sierra Club. But creating citizens movements _ or
the semblance of one _ on demand has also become big business.
</P>
<P>
   Big public relations companies and even the little boutique
shops advertise such arcane-sounding specialities as: ``development
of third party allies'' or ``grass-roots recruitment and
mobilization,'' or ``grass-tops lobbying.'' The goal of these kinds
of campaigns is to shape the terms of congressional debate and to
persuade ordinary voters to serve as the front-line advocates for
the paying clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of the concept, you move beyond candidate advertising
and beyond party organizations and form your own free-standing
operation around an issue,'' said Brian Lunde, a former executive
director of the Democratic National Committee who specializes in
this kind of organizing. ``The day of the PAC check and the steak
dinner and the golf dinner is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Practitioners say a grass-roots effort can cost from $40,000 for
a small-scale attempt to sway the vote of just one or two crucial
members of a subcommittee to many millions of dollars to sway a
majority in Congress. Some companies base their fees on the number
of calls or letters they generate.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Campaigns &AMP; Elections magazine, a trade
journal, conducted a painstaking survey and concluded that
``grass-roots lobbying'' _ separate and apart from more traditional
lobbying _ had become an $800 million industry over 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   And advertising, like the tobacco industry's more than $40
million campaign against tobacco legislation this spring, adds to
the cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inside game of lobbying is in decline and the outside game
of consumer messaging _ of marshaling public opinion _ is advancing
and increasing,'' said Mike Murphy, media consultant in 1996 to the
Republican presidential candidates Lamar Alexander and Bob Dole.
``And savvy companies have figured out that the best experts to
hire to do this kind of work are political consultants.'' His
company also specializes in advertising, research and political
organizing for corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The Evolution
</P>
<P>
   Two decades ago, corporations rarely used any of these
techniques. Grass-roots mobilizations were the province of
environmentalists, the civil rights movement or the anti-war
effort. Television advertising on legislation would have been
considered an extravagant waste of money.
</P>
<P>
   But in the early 1980s, campaign strategists looking for ways to
keep a stable business during off-years and corporations looking
for a better way to argue their case found common ground.
</P>
<P>
   Sewell, who made the transition from Democratic politics,
recalls that his first experience with the industry he now
specializes in came when AT&AMP;T, after it was forced by regulators to
spin off the regional phone companies, hired the political public
relations company where he then worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't know what they were asking for '' he said. ``They
thought they needed something like what was in a political
campaign. We didn't know quite what to make of it, but we started
developing programs whereby we understood that just like a member
of Congress has a constituency, a corporation has a constituency.
Our job was to go and identify that constituency and mobilize that
constituency to advocate a point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then such campaigns have become pervasive.
</P>
<P>
   New forms of communication like the Internet, e-mail, talk radio
and computerized ``blast faxes'' have made it far easier to
organize national constituencies and instantly instruct them on
when to deluge Congress in letters and phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the congressional gift ban cut down on
opportunities for traditional lobbyists to wine and dine lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   And as party discipline has waned, members of Congress have also
proved ever more responsive to television advertising or contacts
from home, or the ups and downs of instantly sampled public
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have entrepreneurial politicians not disciplined by the
party but by their own images,'' Murphy said. ``The mainspring in
this is that public opinion counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least the element of public opinion that is marshaled by
the paid organizers and image makers. ``There may be a lot of
people who agree with your position but they will never get
involved,'' Sewell said. ``It's our job to find the people who
would agree with the position and get them involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Television Advertising
</P>
<P>
   Often these days, it is television advertising that frames the
terms of discussion for the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, when the Health Insurance Association of America
used its $17 million ``Harry and Louise'' commercials to help
defeat Clinton's plan for universal health insurance, the effort
was pioneering.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big gamble in that nobody had done this kind of thing
on that scale before,'' said Ben Goddard, a partner in the Malibu
company, Goddard-Claussen/First Tuesday, that made the commercials,
in which a middle-aged couple agonized in their kitchen about
Clinton's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Now Goddard's company has its own Washington office. And
television advertising recently crossed another milestone. The
estimated $40 million advertising campaign that the five largest
tobacco companies used this spring to defeat anti-tobacco
legislation was the most expensive and sustained issue advocacy
campaign ever undertaken on legislation, according to the Annenberg
Public Policy Center of the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Such advertising campaigns are usually accompanied by
industry-run mobilizations of the grass roots, intended to make
average citizens the advocates for the paying corporate clients.
Sometimes the advertisements help lobbyists find those sympathizers
by running toll-free telephone numbers for people to call.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these efforts still amount to easily spotted
carpet-bombing of Congress with mass-generated form letters and
telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, the Arizona Republican who sponsored the
anti-tobacco bill, was swamped with form letters opposing his
legislation from members of the National Smokers Alliance. The
alliance receives financing from the Philip Morris Companies Inc.,
the Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp. and the Lorillard Tobacco Co.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, also received letters opposing his
position on tobacco _ from one particular part of his state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't figure out why I would get all these letters from
one area,'' Harkin said. ``It turns out they work for a Kraft food
plant owned by R.J. Reynolds. But there was no disclosure of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the practitioners who create grass-roots lobbying
campaigns for business say that at their best, they mobilize real
people with a sincere interest in the cause _ sometimes company
employees, shareholders, retirees or vendors and sometimes
individuals carefully selected through sophisticated demographic
research.
</P>
<P>
   Take the campaign waged this year by the nation's credit unions
to preserve their memberships in the face of a Supreme Court ruling
that federal regulators had overstepped when they allowed small
employee groups, too small to form their own credit union, to join
others.
</P>
<P>
   To pass their legislation over the opposition from the banks,
the credit unions hired a large Washington cast of lobbyists,
strategists and public relations specialists to mount an issue
campaign that would take advantage of the fact that credit unions
have loyal customers who favor them over banks. One person familiar
with the campaign said it has cost about $12 million over two
years.
</P>
<P>
   The strategists deployed every weapon in the lobbying arsenal,
including television commercials, talk radio, letter-writing
campaigns and toll-free numbers that customers could use to call
Congress. The campaign culminated in a rally of 7,000 supporters on
the West Lawn of the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Gill, a former Democratic campaign coordinator for House
races who was the credit unions' chief strategist, said, ``Members
of Congress had a classic dilemma. They want the support of their
local banks and their campaign contributions, but they also want
the votes of over 100,000 credit union people who really care about
this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The credit unions were not loath to do fund raising too. Some
credit union members paid $25 to $100 apiece to hold special
fund-raisers for specific lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The American Bankers Association had its own in-house
specialists in ``grass-roots'' lobbying, but decided that it would
not run the same kind of campaign as the credit unions. ``We knew
from our polling and focus groups and others this was not a battle
we would be able to win in terms of grass-roots volume,'' said
Yingling, the chief lobbyist for the association. ``We had to win
it in terms of the quality of the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the last two weeks before the Senate was to vote, the
banks did turn to a toll-free number to generate thousands of
telegrams to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   After this summer's loss, Yingling said his group was
re-examining its budget for future grass-roots efforts. ``This is
just going to continue to escalate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What Does It Mean
</P>
<P>
   These changes in lobbying are taking place at the same time that
party politics is metamorphosing in the television age, with
fund-raisers replacing block captains and the public increasingly
cut off from either main party. And some say these lobbying efforts
are the politics of the future. ``It's like the election industry
back in the '70s,'' Lunde said. ``There was no such thing then.
This is the same thing. It's the next generation of political
campaign in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Practitioners differed over whether the new practices were
reinvigorating participation or squelching it.
</P>
<P>
   Linbeck of Texas said that his sales tax movement gives citizens
a chance to dictate an agenda to Congress instead of acting like
vassals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a form of contemporary feudalism,'' he said.
``Now how do you reverse that in a relatively benign way? A loud
demonstration to the electorate that they do not have to be a
supplicant with respect to a very important issue for them. And if
they are interested in this and run with it to the extent that the
polling, focus groups and test markets suggest they will, it will
be a leverage point for creating a different view of government by
the average person.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics argue that so much money is being poured into these
efforts that their true purpose is to drown out competing
viewpoints. ``The whole effort of these campaigns is to prevent a
second opinion from occurring,'' said David Cohen, a co-director of
the Advocacy Institute, which teaches citizens groups how to make
their cases.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., who was one of the leaders of the
fight for lobbying disclosure, said that the problem with some of
the techniques is that they can create a distorted picture when
firms are paid to generate a certain number of phone calls or
telegrams and keep canvassing the citizenry until they meet the
quota.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly a member of Congress is getting 50 phone calls on
something,'' Levin said. ``That's a lot of phone calls. What the
member doesn't know is that 950 other people were contacted and
said, `No way.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So it looks like you are being inundated,'' Levin said. ``It
creates the perception of huge support or opposition when in
reality there may be no such thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Grass Tops
</P>
<P>
   Because mass mobilizations have become so prevalent, a number of
companies have become experts in a technique known as
``grass-tops'' lobbying, aimed at mobilizing an elite as opposed to
the masses.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to figure out to whom a member of Congress cannot
say no _ his chief donor, his campaign manager, a political mentor.
The lobbyist then tries to persuade that person to take his
client's side on an issue. If the method works, the member of
Congress may never know that a person contacting him had been
revved up by a lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   To pull off this feat, Washington lobbying and public relations
agencies keep databases of organizers across the country _ most of
them with backgrounds in politics _ who are intimately familiar
with local politicians. Richard Pinsky of West Palm Beach, Fla.,
who managed Dole's Florida primary campaign in 1996, is one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Pinsky said that in the past five years he has been hired by
three Washington public relations and lobbying companies on a
variety of legislation before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, with Florida a swing delegation in a House fight over
trade, the Dewey Square Group, a public relations firm, relied on
Pinsky to find prominent citizens to lobby targeted House members
to support giving Clinton ``fast-track'' trade negotiating
authority.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Pinsky said, he asked Robert Martinez, Florida's
former Republican governor, who has an international trade
practice, to reach Rep. Jim Davis, a Democratic freshman. ``It
wasn't necessarily that a former Republican governor would have
influence on a Democratic congressman,'' Pinsky said, ``as that the
governor lived in his district.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis _ who did come to support the president _ said that he had
independently sought to speak with the former governor. And he said
it did not matter if Pinsky had also spoken with Martinez because
``I knew he had a business interest in promoting trade,'' he said.
``I took it into account.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that if someone without an obvious interest reached
him him on an issue because of the involvement of a Washington
lobbying firm, he would want to know about the role of the
intermediaries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
