<HEADER>
A0924 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTRIC-DEREGULATION     09-29 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRIC-DEREGULATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Group: Texas utilities charge unfairly
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas electric utilities should not be allowed
to force their customers to pay $4.5 billion in debt for nuclear
power plants if the power industry is opened to competition, a
consumer advocate group said Tuesday in a national report released
in Washington, D.C., and Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ratepayers are being robbed to reward risky investments,''
said Brenda Barron, a spokeswoman in Austin for the U.S. Public
Interest Research Group. The public interest group, founded by
consumer crusader Ralph Nader, is a member of the Safe Energy
Communication Council, which wrote the report.
</P>
<P>
   The report estimated a $4.5 billion payment in Texas would cost
residential households $265 each and commercial customers $1,297
each. The $4.5 billion figure, based on competition beginning in
2001, came from a study by the Texas Public Utility Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities have said that, if competition is allowed, they could
lose their investments in nuclear power plants because they won't
be able to produce power as cheaply as newer ones, especially those
burning natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Calling that potentially lost investment ``stranded costs,'' the
industry argues that since those investments were approved by the
government and are included in current rates, customers should not
be allowed to escape them by going to another power supplier. The
Association of Electric Companies of Texas says that ``the recovery
of stranded costs is essential'' if competition is allowed.
</P>
<P>
   But Barron said that ``every dollar paid in stranded costs is
simply an admission of how much consumers have been overcharged all
along.''
</P>
<P>
   The council's report compared estimated stranded costs in 11
states; the total was $112 billion, with California tops at $28.5
billion and New York next at $17.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' comparatively low $4.5 billion is deceptive, the report
said, because it assumes competition will not start until 2001. In
the meantime, as consumers pay their monthly bills, they're paying
down the costs of those nuclear plants.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Barron at the Austin press conference in the Capitol was
an unlikely ally: Peggy Venable, a spokeswoman for a
business-backed group, Texas Citizens for a Sound Economy.
</P>
<P>
   Part of a national group, Texas Citizens for a Sound Economy
claims 27,000 members here. Venable said members provide about
one-third of the organization's funding; corporations about
one-third; and foundations that support free market activities
about one-third. She said the organization has a policy of not
disclosing the names of its corporate contributors. The group
favors competition as a way of forcing electric rates down.
</P>
<P>
   Venable said consumers should not be forced to pay stranded
costs, but she and Barron split on one important point: whether it
would be worthwhile for consumers to pay some stranded costs if
that is the only way to get competition started.
</P>
<P>
   Barron said that if consumers have to pay any stranded costs,
competition should not be allowed. The public interest group and
others favor competition, under the right conditions, as a way to
promote development of renewable energy resources.
</P>
<P>
   Venable said utility shareholders should be required to pay some
of the stranded costs for poor investments by utility management,
but that the benefits of competition would be large enough to
justify a compromise in which consumers paid some of the stranded
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Several major states, including California and Pennsylvania,
have begun opening their utilities to competition. In Texas,
competition is allowed for wholesale purchases of power but retail
sales are still regulated by state and local governments. The
Legislature is expected to consider competition when it convenes in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Hight writes for The Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
