<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0925 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEWISH-SOUTH-COX     09-29 1508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWISH-SOUTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author remembers growing up Jewish in the South
 &HT;    By Christine Evans
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Yes, indeed, Aaron Bronson, a Russian
Jew from the old country, made himself a life, and an unusual one,
plunking his family down smack dab in the middle of a tiny
Tennessee town back in the days when some folks still thought Jews
had horns _ and weren't too shy to come knocking to get a peek at
the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am, sonny. Here's your Jew,'' said Bronson to one such
inquisitive young man, who, after a good look up and down at the
specimen, registered his keen disappointment at the absence of
horns atop the head of the only Jew he had ever met: ``But by
golly, Mr. Bronson,'' he cried, ``you won't do atall!''
</P>
<P>
   Ever the gentleman, ``Mr. Bronson'' apologized for moving to
town without the proper equipment: ``I sure am sorry about the
horns,'' he said. ``I got to tell you them kind of Jews have gone
out of style. None of the new kind have horns.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is just one of the lessons the natives learn in The Jew
Store, a family memoir by Boca Raton author Stella Suberman about
growing up among the goyim in a town Suberman calls Concordia, an
isolated pocket of northwestern Tennessee where the Klan runs
strong, Lord help you if you ain't in church on Sundays, and don't
you know if you plop your feet up on the front porch for five
minutes in the afternoon you're pretty much guaranteed half the
town will pass by to hand-deliver the morning gossip.
</P>
<P>
   Suberman, a first-time author at age 76, decided to write her
book after waiting in vain for somebody else to tell the story of
Jews who, like her daddy, crossed the Mason-Dixon Line in the early
20th century to open the so-called ``Jew Stores'' that sold soft
goods and sundries to poorer residents (sharecroppers, factory
workers, blacks) and came to dot the Southern landscape like
blackberries on a pie.
</P>
<P>
   This slice of Southern-Jewish history, it seemed to her, was a
rich but rarely noticed thread in the American cultural tapestry _
not to mention, a mighty fine yarn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had all this stuff in my mind for years and years,'' says
the author, who looks a good 15 years younger than her age with her
feet propped up in the bright yellow living room of her old Florida
home, which happens to be under chaotic renovation _ where are
those old photos of Concordia, anyway? _ beneath the oak trees in a
tucked-away corner in Boca.
</P>
<P>
   ``Concordia was the biggest event in our lives, and we told
stories about it endlessly around the dinner table. So all this
stuff just kept percolating. I wrote it down, worked at it off and
on for a decade, and the pages kept piling up, piling up. Finally I
thought, `My God, I've just got to do it.' And finally I just
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally being the important word here. Suberman first tried
telling the tale in the voice of a young girl, just as she was in
Concordia _ but soon scrapped that version in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I deplore this book,' and my husband did not like it,
either. He said, `Well, it's juvenile and it doesn't sound a bit
like you.' I had probably spent a year on it already, but after I
decided to use a more mature voice, I went very happily every
morning to my desk. I knew I had a story. I knew it was a story
that needed to be told. So I said I'm going to redo this book and
I'm going to do it right.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, well past the age most folks retire, Suberman, who used
to review books for newspapers and work for art museums, found
herself at a tiny oak desk in her cluttered loft study, pecking
away on a word processor that has not yet heard of e-mail. The
low-tech arrangement worked quite well, apparently, because out
came something that closely resembled a manuscript.
</P>
<P>
   Suberman sent it off to Louis Rubin Jr., a writer and founder of
Algonquin Books and also, as it happened, a friend of Suberman's
husband, Jack, a retired dean of humanities at Florida Atlantic
University. Rubin thought she was on to something but told her to
make up her mind whether she wanted to publish a novel or a memoir.
She considered the matter for about 60 seconds before deciding.
Memoir.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin forwarded the revised manuscript to Algonquin, where
editors loved it, and The Jew Store was born _ after Suberman
persuaded her publisher to accept the in-your-face title, on the
grounds that, back then, that's exactly what everybody called it.
``I told them, it's the only title that does justice to the book.
Nowadays it sounds like you're saying the unsayable, but back then
it was just a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   In The Jew Store, which is earning glowing reviews, Suberman
chronicles the minor dramas and misadventures of an assorted and
lively cast of characters, the names of whom have all been changed
by the author, who found herself suddenly in the grip of Southern
civility and the notion that there's no call to stomp hurt feelings
into people when you don't have to. (She also decided to change the
name of the town, but, as she writes in the prologue, what happened
there is ``pretty much the truth, or, as my father would say,
`close enough so nobody argues about it.''')
</P>
<P>
   Featured characters include her amiable, optimistic father; her
timid and perpetually worried mother; her studious brother and
charismatic sister. There's also a plump, crusading townswoman
named Miss Brookie Simmons, who lives in a house that looks like a
``white-iced, sat-on cake,'' her bigoted but powerful cousin, Tom
Dillon, and a delightfully wise black housekeeper, Lizzie Maud, who
must take a back seat in Southern society but nonetheless manages
to run things.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins in 1920, when Aaron Bronson and his wife Reba
move their young family to Concordia (anyone who knows their way
around the South can probably find the real town on the map) after
a few years in Nashville, where Aaron received some training under
a Jewish shopkeeper. Sure, Nashville is the South, but there,
unlike Concordia, there were other Jewish families with whom to
commiserate, and also, as Suberman writes, ``the prospect of a
glass of tea in the afternoons with the rabbi's wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Nashville, the Bronson family had enjoyed or at least
endured the rattle and din of a busy Jewish enclave in the Bronx.
And now, suddenly, here they were in the boonies, in a place, noted
Reba Bronson incredulously, where women constantly grabbed up
brooms to sweep the dirt from dirt yards. ``Whoever heard?''
</P>
<P>
   It took guts and maybe a little mishegoss (craziness) for a
Jewish family to set up shop in the South. But Bronson prided
himself on being a ``BORN SALESMAN'' _ his daughter imagines a big,
neon sign flashing in his head _ and to him a business opportunity
was a business opportunity, even if to seize it you had to move
your kosher household across the Mason-Dixon to a place where folks
fry chicken in bacon drippings.
</P>
<P>
   While Suberman's mother took comfort in the notion that the
family's stay in Concordia was only ``tem-po-rary,'' her father set
about making a living. His first task, finding a space on First
Street in which to open his store, was one of the hardest, for
certainly not everybody wanted a Jew for a neighbor. For a moment,
he wondered if he would be defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He began to face facts: the accent that he now knew he had,
his lack of an education, his size ... he was an undersized Jew
pitted against Gentile giants.
</P>
<P>
   He could only think that everything was a failure, and it was
his fault: He had been done in by his chutzpah, his arrogance. What
had made him think that his born sal-es-man-ship would open
doors?''
</P>
<P>
   But an optimist such as Aaron Bronson does not easily go down,
and soon enough he had played the worst qualities of two unsavory
characters off each other, and soon after that he proudly opened
Bronson's Low-Priced Store (and displayed the name in big gold
letters, so people wouldn't confuse low-priced with cheap).
</P>
<P>
   From there, Stella Suberman's memoir does read quite a bit like
a novel, as the store thrives, the Klan agitates, and when the town
falls on hard times, it is Aaron Bronson, the outsider, who
conceives a plan to save it.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to open The Jew Store without becoming
mesmerized by the rich mix of language, the oys and Lordys and
other Southern and Yiddish expressions that sit together on a page
the way the Bronsons sat on front porches with their Southern
neighbors: Tom Dillon is ``at the boil, like a pot of wash in a
Southern backyard;'' Reba Bronson frets about the Klan with an
``oyoyoy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bronsons were never the same after their move to Concordia,
and the same might certainly be said of the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good-bye to you Jews,'' a Southern boy declares at the end.
``Having Jews here was the best thing Concordia ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   Christine Evans writes for The Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Staff researcher Lynne Palombo contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
