<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCR-BENEFITS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Employees surprised by changes in benefits at NCR
 &HT;    By Jim Dillon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ NCR Corp. Chairman and Chief Executive Lars
Nyberg warned employees last week that pending changes in employee
medical benefits are significant. But some employees were still
caught off guard by one major change.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton-based maker of large database systems, automatic
teller machines and electronic cash registers outlined changes in
employee benefits last week to reduce costs and get its benefits
more in line with those offered by competitors. The changes take
effect. Jan 1.
</P>
<P>
   The changes include having employees, for the first time in
company history, pay a portion of their health-care coverage;
increasing the amount employees pay for generic and prescription
drugs; cutting the number of health maintenance organizations
available to employees from 70 to 53; and more than doubling the
dental deductible for basic and major care.
</P>
<P>
   The change that seems to be raising the most ire is the
elimination of supplemental Medicare coverage.
</P>
<P>
   New hires will not receive supplemental Medicare coverage when
they retire. The company's current plan covers about 10 percent of
a retiree's health care costs, while Medicare covers about 45
percent. The retiree is responsible for the remaining 45 percent,
NCR officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, active employees will not receive supplemental
Medicare coverage when they retire unless they turn 64 by Dec. 31.
This clause covers 64 active employees.
</P>
<P>
   No changes in supplemental coverage are planned for retirees who
are at least 65.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Victor de Groote III is dismayed by the change. Although
he has worked for NCR for 41 years, he will lose the supplemental
coverage because he will be four months shy of turning 64 at the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it very appalling that they have done this,'' said de
Groote, a systems engineer. ``I either have to find the insurance
myself or pay the difference myself. But how am I going to build a
fund in the amount of time I have left?''
</P>
<P>
   de Groote said he plans to appeal his case to the company and
hopes it will extend him coverage. But he doubts he will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Tricia Bell called the change ``scary.'' Her husband, Bob, left
NCR on long-term disability in December 1995 after 29 years of
service after he was diagnosed with early onset Alzheimer's
disease. Alzheimer's is a progressive, irreversible disease that
often leads to severe dementia.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bell said she and her husband were counting on that
supplemental coverage to help offset anticipated medical costs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, NCR officials say the company's supplemental Medicare
coverage provided little value to retirees. Less than half of all
U.S. companies offer such coverage, officials said, although 11 of
17 high-tech companies NCR measured itself against offer the
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Sawyer, director of global pensions and benefits for NCR,
said there's little chance the supplemental coverage will be
reinstituted.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Dillon writes for The Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
