<HEADER>
A0927 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAGE-MUSIC-$ADV04-NYT     09-29 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAGE-MUSIC-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN CAGE BEFORE HE LET GO  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Sonatas and Interludes are either the sins of John Cage's
youth or else the last of his important music. It depends on what
you think music is, and Cage had some different ideas about that.
</P>
<P>
   The longest of these 20 pieces is a little over four minutes,
the shortest not quite two. What made them different from the other
music being written in 1948 was the medium: the prepared piano, in
which keyboard sound is transformed by strategic insertions of
foreign objects onto or between the piano strings.
</P>
<P>
   What made these pieces pretty much the same as pieces around
them was their man-made-ness: every tone, moment in time and sound
color having been calculated by human faculties to create a
preordained effect.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after writing the Sonatas and Interludes, Cage drifted
in the direction the rest of his life was to follow: the
celebration of the chance happening, the natural event eavesdropped
upon. Music became not an object to be handled and examined but a
state of awareness beckoning to whatever experience might cross
one's path.
</P>
<P>
   Attached to a new version of the Sonatas and Interludes, played
by Aleck Karis and recorded by Bridge, is Cage himself in 1982,
reading a paper called ``Composition in Retrospect,'' which he
wrote the year before. ``The music is always going on,'' he says
several times. ``It is we who turn away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Think of a later Cage piece as a light switch going on, a nudge
in the shoulder, a pointed finger. It says to its audience,
``Listen to what is going on around you.'' As Cage reads, ``All
that is needed is a frame.''
</P>
<P>
   Karis' program note regales us with a (literally) nuts-and-bolts
description of the prepared piano. We begin with Cage's discovery
that pianos could be not only attacked in unconventional ways in
the manner of Henry Cowell but also temporarily disfigured with the
use of ``screws, nuts, bolts, bits of rubber and plastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Karis complains about modern hardware's high zinc content and
therefore its diminished resonance. Seek out original instruments,
he advises. (The early-music movement strikes again.) Cage's
directions for their placement, writes Karis, are specific but make
allowances for the differing dimensions in the inner workings of
various pianos.
</P>
<P>
   The composer's meddlings do not so much enhance the sonority of
the grand piano as blunt and dull it into thuds, thocks and buzzes.
The piano's normal soft-pedal mechanism shifts the inner hammer
chassis slightly to the side, allowing only one of a key's three
strings to be struck.
</P>
<P>
   Cage takes advantage of the process and thus increases the
variety of tuned and untuned sounds; perhaps two strings will be
prepared and the third not.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the implications of equal temperament are
neutralized. Pianos are tuned today with major and minor keys in
mind. Within every tone there is a latent energy, an implied
direction: F sharp yearns to rise into G; B flat wants to fall back
into A.
</P>
<P>
   Cage's method turns the tightly wound individual sound into
something duller, wider, vaguer. One shifts between recognizable
tones and toneless percussion strokes.
</P>
<P>
   The result hovers and dangles like an Indonesian gamelan
orchestra. Music is no longer driven by a compositional ego toward
a destination; it sits there, a pure heart emptied of self. Cage
quotes from Thoreau: ``I want my writing to be as clear as water I
can see through, so that what I experience is told without my being
in any way in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonatas and Interludes are, as Karis points out, space-age
Scarlatti sonatas straight out of the 18th century. The form is
binary: AABB, or two sections with repeats. These are like vestiges
of the Enlightenment, contained little worlds that place their
trust in order and still treat man as a controller of his destiny.
</P>
<P>
   The ``mature'' Cage practiced the art of helplessness; his music
made us into observers of what may or may not happen.
</P>
<P>
   The musical movement, however, is far from Scarlatti. Sonata No.
15 offers near-endless repetition of a single motif while
stretching and contracting its length. On the other hand, the last
Sonata (No. 16), with its dotted rhythms and mordents, acts as a
kind of satirical farewell to the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas pieces like ``Atlas Eclipticalis'' or ``HPSCHD'' are
perhaps better thought about than listeed to, the Sonatas and
Interludes are a constant delight to the ear. The sounds are
beautiful, and their arrangement mingles expectation and surprise.
</P>
<P>
   What did an older Cage think of his youthful follies? That he
later encouraged performers to violate the precisions of the
Sonatas and Interludes adds up to an indirect disclaimer.
``Self-alteration,'' not self-expression, became Cage's goal. The
burden of creativity shifts from composer to listener.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonatas and Interludes, despite their exquisite
artificiality, have another kind of selflessness. It is the way
their elements seem to sway and bump into one another, like
calibrated wind chimes. It makes them less testaments of the human
agenda than receptacles for God's beauties.
</P>
<P>
   Cage was to go farther by leaving the calibrations behind. We
are asked, in Cage's words, to ``welcome whatever happens next.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonatas and Interludes are an interlude in themselves. They
bear the marks of human intervention, yet in other ways, they are
blissfully happy to be overpowered by nature. Bearing the freight
of both past and future, these little pieces are like a fragile
fleet of ships making their way between an old world and a newer
one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
