</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-JEWS-HOLIDAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yom Kippur holiday inspire young, old
 &HT;    By Carmen M. Henderson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARREN CO., Ohio _ Josh Rovai has become a key member of his
Jewish temple by learning in the past three years to play the
shofar, a ram's horn used as part of today's Yom Kippur observance.
</P>
<P>
   For Rovai, 17, it's been a way to learn more about his faith.
For about 120 Jewish families in Warren County, his mastery of the
shofar is a clear call to worship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very unusual for a young person to get involved (in the
temple),'' said Joyce Lucht, 52, of Springboro.
</P>
<P>
   She and Rovai are members of Temple Beth Sholom in Middletown,
and join the county's religious minority in marking their faith's
holiest days. The Jewish community has spent the past 10 days
praying for forgiveness during Rosh Hashana, the Jewish New Year,
and Yom Kippur, the Day of Atonement.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The holidays) are as important to Jews as Easter is to
Christians,'' Lucht said.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of these holy days is already clear to Rovai, a
Lebanon High School senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend all day at the temple to have service and prayer. We
pray for forgiveness and to become a better person,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rovai, played the shofar for his congregation during Rosh
Hashana on Sept. 20. It's much like playing a trumpet, which Rovai
learned as a fifth-grader, Rovai said. Another member of the temple
congregation helped him learn how to play the ram's horn, an honor
usually reserved for an adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best shofar player I have ever heard, I don't know
who will replace him next year (when he goes to college),'' said
Sondra Ross, president of the temple.
</P>
<P>
   Rovai's mother, Cynthia, said she is proud of her son doing
something special for their congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Rovai's accomplishment is all the more unusual considering the
size of the Jewish community in Warren County. Only about 1,800
people in the county are Jewish, according the the 1990 U.S.
census. Only about 50 families from the county are active members
of Temple Beth Sholom. They must drive to Middletown or Dayton or
Cincinnati to join a congregation.
</P>
<P>
   The distance is not great for Rovai, who appreciates what a
unique role he plays in the religious life of Warren County's Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was honored that the congregation picked me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carmen M. Henderson writes for The Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
