</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-GREENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY'S GREENS: CAN THEY PUT `CHAOS' BEHIND THEM?  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BONN, Germany _ It has been a roller-coaster year for Germany's
environmentalist Greens. They have zigzagged on German troop
deployment in Bosnia, called for a near-tripling of gasoline
prices, only to shelve the idea, gone back and forth on what to do
about NATO and finally found themselves a likely member of
Germany's new government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have shown a certain amount of chaos,'' said Harald
Haendel, a spokesman for the party that seems almost certain to
form a ``Red-Green'' coalition with the Social Democrats of
Chancellor-elect Gerhard Schroeder. ``The chaos was a reflection of
a lack of organization, and we now intend to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   But can the Greens, founded in 1979 as a loose coalition of
pacifists, environmentalists, socialists and feminists, evolve from
the freewheeling ways of opposition into a cohesive party of
government that speaks with a single voice?
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, who is to begin coalition talks with the Greens on
Friday, clearly has concerns. ``The Social Democratic Party stands
for economic stability, law and order and continuity in foreign
policy,'' he told the mass-circulation newspaper Bild in an
interview published on Tuesday. ``This is not negotiable.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, closing nuclear power stations that produce a
third of Germany's energy _ a Green demand _ is incompatible with
``economic stability.'' Legalizing soft drugs like marijuana _ a
Green demand _ is incompatible with ``law and order.'' Opposing
NATO expansion _ a Green demand _ is incompatible with ``continuity
in foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, officials indicated, some of Schroeder's concerns
are shared, although it is widely believed that the Greens, hungry
for a power they have never tasted, will prove pragmatic, allowing
the party's most influential figure, Joschka Fischer, a possible
foreign minister, to hold his eclectic followers to NATO policies.
</P>
<P>
   The United States therefore expects periodic irritations _
protests from some party members on NATO expansion, hesitations
over any NATO military action in Kosovo, resolute opposition to
imports of American foods that have been genetically modified _
rather than any serious confrontation with the Greens.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing the unease over the unpredictability they have shown
this year, the Greens announced on Tuesday a reorganization of the
party aimed at wresting some power from local organizations and
increasing centralized control.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, such moves have been resisted, because they smacked
of excessive hierarchy. Even the term ``leader'' has been shunned
because it was a far cry from the sandal-wearing spontaneity of the
party's birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to carry out structural reforms that will lead to a
truly federal party,'' Heide Ruehle, the party manager, said in a
radio interview. ``At the moment, we are a kind of loose collective
of very strong local groups with their own rules and funding, who
have pushed the central party around a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, about 80 percent of the party's financing has gone to
state units of the Greens, and only 20 percent to the central
organization. As a result, Haendel said, the party had little
central control, and ``we have been talking with different
tongues.''
</P>
<P>
   This was evident at a party congress in Magdeburg in March that
turned into a fiasco, when, despite Fischer's pleas, the party came
out against the continued participation of German troops in the
NATO mission in Bosnia. To Fischer's horror, the congress also
voted for the taxes that would sharply increase gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   Both those positions were later revised as their unpopularity
and the obstacles they would pose to an alliance with the Social
Democrats became clear.
</P>
<P>
   But the old split between ``Fundis'' and ``Realos,'' the
die-hard pacifists and the pragmatists, remains, as does a rivalry
between Fischer and Juergen Trittin, another leading figure whose
criticism of the German army caused an outcry early this year.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the election, for instance, Trittin called for
the closing of Germany's 20 nuclear power plants ``as soon as
possible.'' Fischer was silent on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   The Greens now plan to set up a 20-member committee that will
provide greater central control and insure that the positions of
the party's various leading figures are closely coordinated, party
members said.
</P>
<P>
   Haendel, the spokesman, said: ``We want to be serious partners
for our European and Atlantic allies. There are treaties, and these
treaties must be respected. We do not want to turn back the tide of
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, while the party has taken a position against NATO
expansion, it recognizes that a decision has been taken and will
abide by it, he said. ``In the long term,'' he added, ``we would
like to see the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
take over many tasks from NATO, but that, I repeat, is a long-term
aim.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, it seems clear that the Greens will work hard
to agree on a solid four-year government program with Schroeder and
to disprove departing Chancellor Helmut Kohl's repeated warning
during the campaign: ``The Green Party platform represents a major
security risk for Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be a major adjustment for a party unused to the
strictures of government or central organization. The adjustment
will have to made quickly. Officials said on Tuesday that Schroeder
wanted to be sworn in by Oct. 22 so he can attend a European Union
summit meeting in Austria later that week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
