<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES LAWYERS PRESS CASE DESPITE TALK OF SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON, CLINTON-SALON) 
(nk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for Paula Jones asked a federal appeals
court in St. Paul, Minn., Tuesday to reinstate her sexual
misconduct lawsuit against President Clinton because, they said, he
lied under oath when he testified that he had not engaged in sexual
relations with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers' 25-page brief was immediately placed under seal by
the clerk of the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, Michael Gans,
who said it could not be released until it was screened for
material that has not yet been made public. Mrs. Jones' lawyers
readily acknowledged, however, that their brief was based heavily
on the report to Congress by Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth
Starr, which alleges that Clinton may have committed offenses
meriting impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The Starr report alleges that Clinton lied when he denied under
oath to Jones' lawyers that he had a sexual relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky, and that he also encouraged her to lie about it to them.
Clinton has since acknowledged engaging in inappropriate behavior
with Ms. Lewinsky, but he maintains that he did not commit perjury
when he testified in January because what he did with the former
White House intern did not constitute sexual relations as defined
by the judge in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   With a court date in Mrs. Jones' appeal of her lawsuit looming,
her lawyers and Clinton's recently reopened negotiations about
settling. But people in both camps said Tuesday that the two sides
remained far apart on money.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones sued Clinton in 1994, charging that three years
earlier, when he was governor of Arkansas and she was a state
clerical worker, he had her summoned to a hotel room in Little Rock
where he made a crude sexual request. Mrs. Jones' lawyers said they
were asking about Ms. Lewinsky in order to demonstrate a pattern in
Clinton's sexual behavior. In his testimony before the Starr grand
jury, Clinton said that the Jones lawyers were out to embarrass him
and damage him politically.
</P>
<P>
   A federal trial judge in Arkansas dismissed Mrs. Jones' lawsuit
in April, and a three-judge panel is scheduled to hear arguments on
Oct. 20 in St. Paul on her appeal to have the case reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones' lawyers privately contacted the White House earlier
this month and said they would drop the appeal if she were paid $1
million. For the first time, Mrs. Jones' lawyers said she would not
demand any kind of apology to settle the case because Clinton's
admission of a sexual liaison with Ms. Lewinsky made that
unnecessary. People now believe Mrs. Jones was telling the truth,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides made a counteroffer of $500,000 last week, but
that was quickly rejected by the Jones camp. Lawyers for Mrs. Jones
said Tuesday they had not received any new offers from the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a deep dark silence,'' a Jones lawyer said. ``But no
one on our side is blinking.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said they were still mulling over what to
do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
