</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-STUDENT-LOANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PASSES BILL TO CUT INTEREST RATES FOR STUDENT LOANS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ College students who take out federal loans will
pay the lowest interest rate in decades, saving hundreds of dollars
each, while grants to poorer students will increase by thousands of
dollars under a bill that won final passage in the Senate Tuesday
and is sure to become law.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of students would benefit from the more generous terms
over the next five years. The Senate approved the bill, 96-0, a day
after the House approved it unanimously. Despite reservations about
subsidies for the banks that make most of the loans, the Clinton
administration has embraced the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., who is a sponsor of the
measure, estimated that the typical student graduating from college
with $13,000 in debts would save $700 in interest payments. A
student with a loan of $20,000 would save about $1,000 in the five
years it takes to pay back college loans.
</P>
<P>
   In another bonus to recent graduates, the measure extends for
another four months, until next Jan. 31, a window during which they
may go back to the bank and consolidate existing loans at the new
rates.
</P>
<P>
   The lower interest rates for student loans, about three-fourths
of a percentage point below the rates on student loans issued last
year, reflects the general decline in interest rates throughout the
economy as well as changes in how the rates are set. Congress put
the new system into effect earlier this year, but only on a
temporary basis. The legislation makes the system permanent.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, the interest rate for borrowers will be the rate
on 91-day Treasury bills plus 1.7 percentage points while the
student is in school, and the Treasury bill rate plus 2.3
percentage points after the student graduates and begins repaying
the loan. The rate could not rise above 8.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, this would result in an interest rate of less than
7.5 percent, compared to just under 8.25 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing costs for students might have gone even lower under a
formula that was to have taken effect this summer, but lenders
contended that the interest rate would have been so low that they
would have to withdraw from the program.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise that passed Tuesday uses a federal subsidy to pay
banks an interest rate that is somewhat higher than what the
students themselves pay.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of all college undergraduates get aid under the
Higher Education Act of 1965, and the federal government is
expected to guarantee 88 million loans over the next 10 years and
to issue more than 25 million Pell grants to low-income students
over the coming five years, sponsors said.
</P>
<P>
   The votes in the House and the Senate to make the aid more
generous is among the few major bills to pass the Congress without
partisan rancor as the legislative session draws to a close.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process in both the House and Senate has been
characterized by a spirit of bipartisanship,'' said Sen. James
Jeffords, R-Vt., who managed the bill in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Next year the maximum annual Pell grant, as the federal aid for
low-income students is known, will rise from $3,000 to $4,500, and
students will be allowed to earn up to $2,200 without losing their
eligibility for the grants. Over the next five years the maximum
Pell grant will rise to $5,800.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the financial aid for students, the bill makes dozens of
changes to federal programs for higher education. It forgives some
loans for students who work in child care or in schools in
low-income neighborhoods, and it increases the budget for college
work-study programs to $1 billion for next year.
</P>
<P>
   But House and Senate conferees rejected a provision that had
passed the Senate amending the welfare law to help welfare
recipients attend college. The provision would have counted two
years of college as meeting the new work requirements for welfare
recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that increasing financial aid would merely fuel the
engines of academic inflation, lawmakers took a few tentative steps
to hold back the rate of increase in college costs, which have
greatly exceeded the general rate of inflation for years.
</P>
<P>
   One provision in the bill gives parents and students new access
to information from colleges about the factors that are driving
tuition higher. Another cost-saving provision permits colleges to
offer their older faculty members new incentives, such as
additional benefits, to retire voluntarily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
