<HEADER>
A0934 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-CUBS-NYT &LR;      09-29 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES TAKE NOTHING FOR GRANTED AGAINST THE CUBS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the Atlanta Braves, everything appears to be in
order.
</P>
<P>
   Their starting rotation, the best in baseball, is well rested.
The players are healthy and confident, having won more games (106)
than any other team in the National League. And the Braves, who
have made the playoffs seven straight times, are playing the
Chicago Cubs, a team that could be emotionally and physically
drained after a thrilling journey to the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   So why did the Braves sound so cautious Tuesday?
</P>
<P>
   Because despite their regular-season success, the Braves have
just one World Series championship to show for it. Having tasted
disappointment in the playoffs before, the Braves take nothing for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's tremendous pressure in the first round,'' said John
Smoltz (17-3), who will start Game 1 for Atlanta at Turner Field on
Wednesday afternoon against Mark Clark (9-14). ``We've yet to lose
in the first round, but that's a scary position to be in, when
you're favored, and you're supposed to go to the World Series.
Three out of five, anybody can beat anybody. There's not a team in
the playoffs right now that doesn't have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta's chances look better because of its pitching, with
Smoltz followed by Tom Glavine (20-6) in Game 2 and Greg Maddux
(18-9) in Game 3. And with proven offensive stars like Chipper
Jones and Andres Galarraga, the Braves have enough experience,
balance and talent to play well into October.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs, however, are in the midst of a magical season. They
won the wild card tiebreaker by beating the San Francisco Giants,
5-3, Monday night at Wrigley Field. And with Sammy Sosa on their
side, the Cubs know they have the ability to strike lightning. By
hitting 66 home runs, and dueling with Mark McGwire for the home
run title into the final weekend of the season, Sosa became an
international star and a folk hero in Chicago. He would only add to
his mystique if he could lead the Cubs to their first World Series
appearance since 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the Braves have discussed how they will pitch to
Sosa. More accurately, they have discussed how they won't pitch to
Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to let Sammy beat me,'' said Glavine. ``I'm sure
a lot of guys in this room feel the same way. If a situation arises
that you have to pitch him, then you deal with it. If the bases are
loaded, you've got to pitch to him. But then again, if the bases
are loaded, I'd rather walk him than give up a grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the game, you might be more aggressive with him with
nobody on base because typically a solo home run early won't beat
you. But with runners on base, or later in the game, you try to do
everything you can to let other guys get the key hit. What Sammy
has done all year long speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs received good news Tuesday about Kerry Wood, their
rookie pitching star. Wood has been sidelined with a sore right
elbow, but he threw well on Monday in Arizona, and he is expected
to pitch in this series. Manager Jim Riggleman would not commit to
a starter beyond Game 1, but Kevin Tapani (19-9) is likely for Game
2, and either Wood (13-6) or Steve Trachsel (15-8) could pitch Game
3.
</P>
<P>
   While starting pitching will be important, the bullpens may
decide the series. Chicago's closer, Rod Beck, has been overworked
during the last week, and both he and Terry Mulholland may not have
the arm strength to pitch effectively early in the series.
Wednesday's forecast in Atlanta calls for a chance of rain, and the
Cubs would not mind if their tired arms received an extra day of
rest.
</P>
<P>
   For the Braves, Kerry Ligtenberg has taken over as the closer
this year, but although Ligtenberg had a strong year, it remains to
be seen how he will handle playoff pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are solidly behind him. ``Kerry I think has only
blown three saves, and he's not even being talked about for rookie
of the year,'' said Smoltz. ``It's Rodney Dangerfield. Our bullpen
is not going to get the respect it deserves, based on what we do as
starters. But if they think that getting to our bullpen will be the
source of them winning, I don't think that's the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Cubs beat the Braves six times in nine meetings in
the regular season, another reason for Chicago to feel confident.
The Braves are the favorites. But the Cubs, who spent September
battling to make the playoffs, may have more momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a typical wild card series, and the momentum they
have is important,'' said Smoltz. ``As we stand here today,
everyone thinks we should win this series. But I think anybody can
win it. We're going to have to be hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
