<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0939 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-NYT &LR;      09-29 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW EVIDENCE SAID TO CONTAIN NO BOMBSHELL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., S.C., Ark., Calif., Mass.)  (Eds: See also CLINTON-JONES, CLINTON-CANTON, CLINTON-SALON) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican investigators said Tuesday that grand
jury evidence to be made public on Friday would bolster charges
that the White House tried to cover up President Clinton's
relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic lawyers for the House Judiciary Committee said the
new evidence would, on balance, help the president's cause.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides did agree that the material includes no bombshell
that would fundamentally change people's view of whether the
president should be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is specifically damaging or specifically
exculpatory,'' a Democratic staff member said, ``but it gives color
and context to the charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats who have reviewed the evidence said it
portrayed Linda Tripp in an unfavorable light. She alerted
prosecutors to the president's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky and
surreptitiously tape-recorded conversations with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very leading,'' a Republican assistant said. ``Is she
manipulative? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The staff members who spoke Tuesday did so on the condition that
they not be identified by name.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 5,000 pages of documents to be released by the
Judiciary Committee on Friday are edited transcripts of the
Tripp-Lewinsky conversations as well as transcripts of the grand
jury testimony of Ms. Tripp; Betty Currie, the president's
secretary; Vernon Jordan Jr., the president's friend, and Bruce
Lindsey, a deputy White House counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury evidence was turned over to the committee by
Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   While the committee staff was reviewing this evidence, Sen.
Trent Lott, R-Miss., the Republican leader, told reporters that
``bad conduct is enough, frankly, for impeachment'' if it ``brought
disrepute on the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott declined to say whether he believed Clinton's conduct met
that standard.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, two Republican and two Democratic members of
Congress who are trying to stake out a bipartisan position on the
Judiciary Committee began an effort Tuesday to find out from Starr
whether he had evidence of potentially impeachable offenses
involving subjects other than the president's relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky. That is the only matter Starr has referred to Congress
under the law that requires independent counsels to notify Congress
of evidence of possibly impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The congressmen _ Lindsey Graham, R-S.C.; Asa Hutchinson,
R-Ark.; Howard Berman, D-Calif., and Bill Delahunt, D-Mass. _ are
trying to determine whether an impeachment inquiry should go beyond
the Lewinsky affair. The Judiciary Committee plans to vote next
week on whether to begin a formal inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   A joint team of Republican and Democratic lawyers went to
Starr's office on Monday to take a first look at evidence in the
Clinton-Lewinsky case that was not presented to Congress. They
asked for a detailed index on the information to help them decide
what they want to look at, a committee official said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde approved the trip to assuage Democrats who say they want to
see whether exculpatory material was not given to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members of the committee were permitted Tuesday for the
first time to speak publicly about the grand jury evidence. Several
from both parties did so but with few quotations from the testimony
or other specific details.
</P>
<P>
   Their descriptions of the evidence were so sketchy that they
must be taken with caution. Before the videotape of Clinton's grand
jury testimony was made public last week, word seeped out that the
president would be seen losing his temper, but that proved not to
be the case.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Among the matters that Republicans said they found most
interesting were these:
</P>
<P>
   _ The repeated refusal by Lindsey and Sidney Blumenthal, another
assistant to the president, to answer questions on the grounds of
executive privilege and, in Lindsey's case, lawyer-client
privilege. Starr and the Republican investigators see this as
evidence of a White House effort to obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   _ An assertion by Dick Morris, one of Clinton's political
consultants, that the White House maintains an operation to
intimidate women who have had affairs with the president.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jordan's testimony, the veracity of which the staff members
questioned, that his telephone calls to critical players at crucial
times did not involve the Lewinsky situation.
</P>
<P>
   _ The testimony of a White House switchboard operator that he
received the first reprimand of his career after he declined
suggestions from the White House counsel's office that he hire a
lawyer from a recommended list before he testified before the grand
jury.
</P>
<P>
   Three Democratic lawyers on the committee staff held a briefing
for reporters on the new evidence. These lawyers maintained that in
some respects the evidence showed Clinton in a less sinister way
than the portrayal in Starr's report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Democrats said that Mrs. Currie's testimony
bolstered Clinton's position that he did not help Ms. Lewinsky find
a job in exchange for her giving false testimony in the Paula
Corbin Jones sexual misconduct lawsuit and that he did not instruct
Mrs. Currie to retrieve presents he had given Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Starr told Congress that Clinton's role in the job search and in
the retrieval of the gifts amounted to evidence of obstruction of
justice.
</P>
<P>
   In Starr's report, he pointed to a conflict between Ms. Lewinsky
and Mrs. Currie over which of them brought up the idea that Mrs.
Currie should take possession of the president's gifts to Ms.
Lewinsky. Starr said the question was important because if it was
Mrs. Currie's idea, that could mean that the president had
instructed her to get the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Starr report, Mrs. Currie first testified that
it was Ms. Lewinsky's idea but, told by prosecutors that Ms.
Lewinsky had testified otherwise, agreed that ``she may remember
better than I.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats said Tuesday that Starr used the quotation out of
context and that Mrs. Currie had made the statement in answer to a
question that did not deal with the transfer of gifts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
