<HEADLINE>
HELLING ENTERS WITH MOMENTUM, SORE BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With only seven players remaining from the 1996
playoff team, and nine who have never appeared in a postseason
game, Rangers manager Johnny Oates conceded that inexperience might
be a problem against the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Especially at Yankee Stadium, with its loud, often-obnoxious
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Rick Helling fits in both categories, there are no
worries about the 27-year-old right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   Helling wasn't feeling pressure yesterday. He was having a good
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first playoff experience, and you couldn't ask for
a better place to do it in,'' Helling said. ``To pitch against the
Yankees, with the great team they have this year, the history of
the stadium, all the great things that have gone on through the
years here, I don't think you could ask for a better setting. It's
going to be a lot of fun. The fans will be going crazy, but I'm
looking forward to it. It should be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling enters tonight with momentum. He was 4-0 with a 2.76
earned-run average in September and was chosen American League
pitcher of the month.
</P>
<P>
   He enters with poise and confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get intimidated about it and I don't get nervous about
it,'' he said. ``To go out there and think that you're playing on
the same field that Babe Ruth, Mickey Mantle, Lou Gehrig and Joe
DiMaggio played on, all the names that were here, to me it's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   He also goes in with a sore back.
</P>
<P>
   It first bothered him before a Sept. 17 start against the
Anaheim Angels, and he allowed six runs and failed to get out of
the second inning. It still bothered him when he pitched in Anaheim
five days later, and he held the Angels to one run in eight
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The back is about the same,'' he said. ``It's gotten a little
better, but I can pitch with the pain. I did it in Anaheim. It's
not going to affect me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
