<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MALADROIT DU SEIGNEUR  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When women finally came into power in Washington,
they were in the mood to collect some scalps.
</P>
<P>
   They skewered Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   They cooked Bob Packwood.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time they got to Bill Clinton, women had lost their
appetite to search out and destroy all chauvinistic and harassing
behavior. They were confused. Were these men dangerous predators?
Or were they merely loony lechers?
</P>
<P>
   There was a disturbing pattern developing. The powerful men
getting in the most trouble over women seemed to be getting the
least satisfaction from women. The guys being crucified for sexual
misconduct appear, on closer inspection, to be acting more strange
than swaggering, more dysfunctional than macho.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who put a pubic hair on my Coke can?'' Now there's a crafty
come-hither line. Looking back, Clarence Thomas' insistence on
jabbering about creepy X-rated movies seems more bizarre than
brutish. Bob Packwood's habit of grabbing hair and forcing his
tongue down the throats of women is yucky, to be sure, but also
pathetic. They seem like such losers to have caused so much angst.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bill Clinton faces the most severe punishment possible. But
the more you read Kenneth Starr's dirty best seller, the more it
looks as if the Republicans are huffing and puffing, trying to
impeach the first president on the grounds of illicit sex even
though the illicit so outweighed the sex.
</P>
<P>
   The more we read Starr's prissy documentation, the more it seems
the president has been wrongfully accused. We thought he was a
lusty, carefree Lothario with his young intern, when he was
actually a timid, tortured Lothario.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than joining the capital's proud pantheon of droit du
seigneur with the Kennedy brothers, Bill Clinton joined Messrs.
Thomas and Packwood in the embarrassing pantheon of maladroit du
seigneur.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, when the story of the president and the intern
first rocked the country, there was much speculation that Clinton's
ratings had remained high because Americans secretly lusted for an
alpha president. Lydia Saad of the Gallup Poll told The Wall Street
Journal that Presidents Kennedy and Clinton had both prospered
because of ``our unspoken affection for leaders who live large _
large life, large appetites, large loves.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Starr report has shattered the president's image as an
unreconstructed rake. If Clinton honestly described his encounters
with Monica Lewinsky, he would be laughed out of any locker room in
the country. Their affair has none of the noir glamour of JFK and
Marilyn at the Carlyle Hotel. Bill and Monica make the juvenile
leads in ``Titanic'' seem mature.
</P>
<P>
   It is Ms. Lewinsky who comes across as the red-blooded predator,
wailing to her girl friends that the president wouldn't go all the
way. It is Clinton who behaves more like a teen-age girl trying to
protect her virginity, insisting on holding back, reluctant to
remove any clothes, even pushing away Ms. Lewinsky at times and
pushing up her slipping bra strap, according to her testimony.
``I'm trying to not do this and I'm trying to be good,'' the
president told her primly.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky is the one who bristles with testosterone. In her
testimony, she said of one of her encounters with the president:
``He just seemed to get so emotionally upset about it. It seemed a
little strange to me.'' This was no wild, unbridled passion.
``There was sort of foreplay to the foreplay,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's habit, with language and behavior, has been to try to
incorporate his alibi into his sin. The result is more twisted than
titillating.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine televised impeachment hearings designed to
pin down the president's possible perjury on whether he touched
Monica's breast directly or through clothing. This will make Orrin
Hatch waving a copy of ``The Exorcist'' at Anita Hill back in 1991
look positively dignified.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the ludicrous comment Tuesday by Trent Lott, the Senate
majority leader. ``I think bad conduct is enough, frankly, for
impeachment,'' he intoned.
</P>
<P>
   Americans understand perfectly that if good conduct were
required in Washington, the city would have closed up shop long
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans can't throw the president on the pyre for sexual
misconduct in a city where sexual misconduct has always flourished.
And they can't keep treating him as if he were a brazen brute when
he's just a sad philanderer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
