<SLUG> BC-BBN-HOUSTON-LEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Astros drop playoff opener to Padres 2-1
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The opening act played just according to script. Only
Kevin Brown, who caused the Braves post-season fits a year ago,
ended up miscast in a supporting role.
</P>
<P>
   On an afternoon when Randy Johnson proved a tad shy of dominant,
it was Brown who carried his team's fortunes on his back, fanning a
career-best 16 as the San Diego Padres beat the Houston Astros 2-1.
Brown surrendered but two singles before the Astros rallied for a
ninth-inning run off closer Trevor Hoffman in the NL Division
Series opener.
</P>
<P>
   Brown may never have thrown better, even in no-hitting the San
Francisco Giants last season.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's as good as I've seen him,'' said Moises Alou, a
teammate on last year's Florida Marlins. ''With him on your team,
when he's on the mound you feel confident, just like you do with
Randy on the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Johnson was no match Tuesday for the less-celebrated Game
One starter.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-10 left-hander surrendered a bases-loaded sac fly to Jim
Leyritz in the sixth, later offering up an eighth-inning solo homer
to Greg Vaughn. A decent showing, yes. But while Johnson gave up
nine hits and faced several jams, Brown allowed two singles _ both
to catcher Brad Ausmus _ before giving way to Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   And was Brown, owner of a short fuse, more intense than usual
going against Johnson?
</P>
<P>
   ''No doubt, when you're going against a guy like Randy Johnson
you know it's going to take a great effort,'' said Brown, a Georgia
Tech grad. ''But as a pitcher, I'm not facing Randy Johnson. I'm
facing their hitters . . . but I was able to focus, probably as
well as I've done in quite some time.''
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, Brown eclipsed Johnson's strikeout mark of 13 for a
division series and authored the first Astrodome defeat for
Houston's new-found star. He struck out at least one Astro in each
of his eight innings, Derek Bell and Ricky Gutierrez each scoring a
hat trick.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, considerably below the ticket sold figure of 50,080,
showed up expecting a sure-thing in Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But awesome as he's been, the left-hander is just 2-4 in
post-season and unequal to Brown at his best.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's always this big buildup when I pitch in the
post-season,'' said Johnson, going out of his way to praise Brown.
''You guys (in the media) write more about it when I pitch, often
overshadowing the opposing pitcher. It was the same thing with
(Baltimore's) Mike Musina last year. It was the same thing for this
game. If I'm on the other side of the tracks, it'd be a big
incentive to go out and pitch well.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think anybody is invincible. A lot of the media makes
me sound like I'm going to be, but it makes the other team get
fired up. It sounds like the game is in the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the record show it's not.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
