<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASA-UT-RADIATION-COX     09-29 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-UT-RADIATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT Researcher's Prediction Comes True
 &HT;    By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ University of Texas astrophysicist Robert Duncan
and a colleague predicted the possibility six years ago. On
Tuesday, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
announced that it happened last month.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 27, at 4:22 a.m. CDT, the most powerful blast of
radiation ever detected hitting the Earth engulfed part of the
ionosphere, the uppermost layer of the atmosphere that begins about
37 miles high, over the western United States and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The invisible gamma and X-ray radiation, produced by a tiny but
menacing star 20,000 light-years away in a corner of our Milky Way
galaxy, never reached the ground. Had it, Duncan said, it would
have caused no more health effects than a dental X-ray.
</P>
<P>
   But astonished NASA scientists said the event, which lasted five
minutes, dramatically illustrated the planet's potential
vulnerability to things other than crashing comets and asteroids _
in this case a magnetic flare on SGR 1900+4, a supermagnetic star
called a magnetar, in the constellation Aquila.
</P>
<P>
   ``It amazes me that the ionosphere actually fluctuated,'' said
Duncan, who, with North Carolina astrophysicist Christopher
Thompson, predicted the existence of magnetars in 1992. ``The
energy of this tiny, 12-mile-diameter star came all that way and
made our ionosphere fluctuate.''
</P>
<P>
   The ionosphere fluctuated when its atoms, normally charged with
electricity by solar radiation, received a big electrical boost
from energy produced by a star that is too far away to be seen
except with telescopes that image radio waves.
</P>
<P>
   NASA said it was the first time that a significant change in
Earth's atmosphere had been traced to energy from a star other than
the sun. SGR (for Soft Gamma Repeater) 1900+4 _ no larger than a
city but weighing more than the sun _ is more than 1 billion times
farther away than the sun, which is 93 million miles from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Hurley, an astronomer at the University of California,
calculated the total energy that the star must have expended to
produce the impact on Earth. He said if it could be harnessed it
would be enough to power all of human civilization for a billion
billion years.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, only a small fraction of it collided with the
atmosphere. Had much more of it hit, Duncan said, the radiation
could have seriously eroded the atmosphere's protective ozone
layer, allowing much more harmful radiation from the sun to reach
the ground each day.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, the radiation was so intense that it overloaded
gamma-ray sensors on at least seven scientific satellites, causing
them to automatically shut down. It also apparently reduced the
range of high-power radio stations whose signals use the ionosphere
to travel around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Although the radiation didn't reach the ground, the ionosphere's
fluctuation set off ground sensors used by Stanford University to
study lightning in the upper atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as if night was briefly turned into day in the
ionosphere,'' said Umran Inan, a Stanford electrical engineer.
</P>
<P>
   NASA and Stanford scientists said they had detected similar but
much smaller bursts of radiation hitting the ionosphere in 1983 and
1996 but didn't know what caused them.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan's and Thompson's magnetar theory became widely known to
scientists in May when NASA researchers reported in the British
journal Nature that they finally had confirmed their existence.
</P>
<P>
   They found evidence that, as Duncan and Thompson had predicted,
magnetars have the strongest magnetic fields in the universe and
there may be millions of them in galaxies such as the Milky Way,
which is estimated to have 400 billion stars.
</P>
<P>
   Magnetars are a type of neutron star, a well-known oddity in the
stellar zoo. Neutron stars are the collapsed cores left over when a
massive star explodes. Duncan said one teaspoon from one of these
extremely dense cores, a ball generally no more than 12 miles in
diameter, would weigh more than an aircraft carrier. Roiled by
periodic starquakes and gamma-ray flares, magnetars are a potential
menace to other objects in space.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists said no magnetars are believed to be close enough to
do Earth any serious damage. Duncan said the Aug. 27 event could
happen again, but he and Thompson have figured that magnetars
produce such magnetic flares only about once a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our theory, it's a random event,'' Duncan said. ``It's like
predicting earthquakes _ you can't say when.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Stanley writes for The Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
