<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0949 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MELLENCAMP-MUSIC-$ADV     09-29 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELLENCAMP-MUSIC-$ADV04-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MELLENCAMP FAN: GUILTY AS CHARGED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ind., Minn.)   (Neal Karlen is the author of ``Slouching Toward Fargo,'' a book
about traveling with the St. Paul Saints minor-league baseball
team.)  
 (af)  
 By NEAL KARLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ It was shuffling dusty, long-unopened boxes in my
basement storage room a few weeks ago when I came upon a heavy
carton I had years ago simply labeled ``LAME.''
</P>
<P>
   A pack rat, I had marked the box when I moved back home to
Minneapolis eight years ago after living most of the 80s _ and my
20s _ in Manhattan. Ripping through the packing tape, I discovered
a collection I had adjudged at the time to be the most embarrassing
vinyl albums I had ever purchased.
</P>
<P>
   On top was Bob Dylan's ``Saved,'' followed by the inevitable
``Frampton Comes Alive.'' Below this crust of vinyl flotsam I came
upon six different albums recorded by John Mellencamp, the artist
formerly known as Johnny Cougar, John Cougar and John Cougar
Mellencamp.
</P>
<P>
   Now 46, he will release ``John Mellencamp,'' his first album of
all new material in five years on Tuesday for Columbia Records. A
kind of rock star Job, he has somehow endured for two decades and
14 records, surviving even the ridiculous marketing campaign of
young Johnny Cougar as a glam-James Dean concocted by David Bowie's
ex-manager.
</P>
<P>
   Besides claiming back his name and soul, Mellencamp has since
been through a heart attack, two divorces and a ton of rotten
reviews dating back forever.
</P>
<P>
   He labors on. ``Your Life is Now,'' the new album's already
released first single, is a Mellencamp song at its catchiest: a
Midwest roadhouse rocker with a pounding beat atop the simple words
of a prairie tent sermon. Three weeks after its release, ``Your
Life is Now'' is already the most frequently added single to the
playlists at top 40 stations.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the album will enthrall his fans here in what record
executives call ``Flyoverland'' and enrage the rock intelligentsia
who for decades have called Mellencamp an impostor with simply the
best heartland shtick since William Jennings Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is a phony,'' the critic Robert Christgau wrote of the
1982 John Cougar album that contained his breakthrough hit ``Jack
and Diane.'' Mellencamp's anthem ``Small Town'' was a hit in 1985,
and Dave Marsh, Bruce Springsteen's biographer, lectured the
rocker, writing ``that ties to home can be stultifying and
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, back in my Minneapolis storage room, far away in years
and miles from the grip of hip, I didn't care what the critics
said. Instead, I wondered how I could have ever consigned John
Mellencamp to my LAME box. ``I've always (italics)loved(end
italics) John Mellencamp,'' I thought.
</P>
<P>
   And then I realized his banishment must have been a Manhattan
reflex. Back East, Mellencamp had been my guilty rock-and-roll
pleasure, my shameful secret that was apostasy in the groovy world
I then thought I aspired to. I had to watch my step; when I left
New York, I was still on the masthead of Rolling Stone, writing for
an oppressively hip barometer where one was more likely to hear
someone confess to cannibalism than to say, ``I've always
(italics)loved(end italics) John Mellencamp.''
</P>
<P>
   But I couldn't help it. Growing up in the Midwest in the 1970s,
Mellencamp was my Bruce Springsteen. Mellencamp's home town of
Seymour, Ind. (population 13,000), was my St. Louis Park, Minn. His
turf was the Midwest; his first topics prairie love and despair,
the likes of his own Jack and Diane, who learned a little too late
that the guidance counselors weren't kidding when they warned
``life goes on/even after the thrill off living is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp songs also bore a defiant pride of place _ most
famously in ``Small Town.'' He wasn't being facetious when he sang,
``That's probably where they'll bury me.'' Mellencamp lives and
records in Bloomington, 30 miles from Seymour.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, I had no idea what Springsteen meant when he sang of
boardwalks, Asbury Park gypsies or burning oil refineries. I did
understand Mellencamp's crunching odes to feeling as if the world
was happening somewhere else. I related to his bar-band rockers
about the dual-edged sword of living in a small Midwest community
where your neighbors know not only your name but everything else
about you too.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Not that I told anyone of my guilty rock pleasure when I lived
in New York. If I was riding in the back of a car, I would be the
first to jump across the seat to change the station if one of
Mellencamp's songs came on the radio. Yet if I was alone at home, I
would sing ``Jack and Diane'' and `Small Town'' along with the
Mellencamp records I would furtively buy at East Village record
stores, hoping no one I knew saw me.
</P>
<P>
   After discovering my cache of vinyl Mellencamp, I wondered who
else now counted as a guilty rock-and-roll pleasure. Names wouldn't
be as easy to come by as they had been in the old days of the
1980s; this decade a number of traditional guilty rock pleasures
have became hip.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Bennett, long considered as lame as a bad toupee, has been
so hip lately that it's hard to even remember how recently he was
thought a has-been. Kiss, once scorned as corporate-rock incarnate,
remains cool, as do the Carpenters, Richard Nixon's favorite
rockers.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in perhaps ever, one could put Abba on a
dance tape and be complimented for your taste instead of being
asked what planet you were from.
</P>
<P>
   Still, somebody has to be ashamed of what they now liked to
listen to. So last week, inside the slacker coffee shop where I
sometimes do my writing, I took an informal poll among the
assembled hipsters about their own guilty rock pleasures. All
demanded anonymity and seemed properly embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who described herself as an ``out lesbian'' confided her
enthusiasm for Guns-'n'-Roses, ``despite Axl's homophobic lyrics,
the pig.'' A vegetarian whispered ``Ted Nugent,'' despite the
rocker's well-publicized love of bow-hunting. A punk rocker quietly
mumbled ``Grateful Dead,'' the arch enemy of the loud/fast/hardcore
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Over the phone, I asked the expatriated Minnesotan, comedian and
liberal political pundit Al Franken to name his guilty pleasure.
Franken was the only one I asked who didn't sound embarrassed by
his choice. ``Tammy Wynette,'' he said proudly, naming the singer
whose conservative world view of standin' by your man wouldn't seem
to jibe with that of the author of the book ``Rush Limbaugh Is a
Big Fat Idiot and Other Observations.''
</P>
<P>
   I've still got my John Mellencamp, who remains as critically
unhip yet commercially popular as Neil Diamond. I could never
figure out the bad rap against Mellencamp, except for the puerile
way he had been marketed early on. Yet he had repaid his dues.
</P>
<P>
   Cool musicians like the alternative-rock queen Lisa Germano had
played in his band; his videos featured blacks when MTV was being
crucified for featuring only white faces, and his singles still
occasionally hit to the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Now, fishing Mellencamp's records out of my LAME box, I wondered
if they held up as a guilty pleasure. I brought them upstairs to my
turntable, near all the vinyl I had cherry-picked from my
collection all those years ago in New York, albums ranging in
too-coolness from my first edition pressing of the Sex Pistols'
``God Save the Queen'' to original Stax/Volt albums of Otis
Redding.
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp held up. I then put on his new CD and found myself
half dancing to ``Your Life Is Now.'' Since then, his vinyl has
stayed upstairs, in front of even the Sex Pistols.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
