<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAME PLAYOFF ROUTINE FOR INDIANS
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Not all hope was lost in the Cleveland clubhouse
Tuesday. Optimists could point to the fact that the Indians
wouldn't have to face Pedro Martinez again _ unless there's a fifth
game. Also, the Indians have a history of losing first games of
playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for example, they lost Game 1 of the division series
against the New York Yankees, yet came back to take the series in
five games. They also bounced back from a Game 1 loss to the
Baltimore Orioles in the American League Championship Series last
year, eventually winning in six games. The Indians, however, did
lose the World Series last season in seven games to Florida after
losing the first game to the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, the Indians have lost their previous seven series
openers in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the perfect world scenario,'' Indians manager Mike
Hargrove said after the game. ``We certainly did not come in here
looking to lose the first game to keep our tradition going. If you
can get any comfort out of anything, we have done it before. We
didn't want to have to do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove added, ``Our guys are in a good frame of mind after
getting dusted pretty good. We're ready for tomorrow.'' CHANGE OF
PACE
</P>
<P>
   After facing the 95 mph-plus fastball and sharp breaking balls
of Pedro Martinez Tuesday, the Indians face the unenviable
challenge of locating Tim Wakefield's knuckleball this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield said the contrast in pitching styles and the gap in
velocity ought to wreak havoc with Cleveland batsmen as it has all
season when opposing teams had to face the Red Sox starters
back-to-back.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way we set up the rotation this year and I found
that it helped me quite a bit,'' Wakefield said. ``After Pedro's
throwing 95 mph, I follow him throwing 65 or 70. The contrast is
very drastic. It wasn't every start, but I found that one-half to
three-quarters of my starts were like that. It did have an effect
on the opposition.'' WARM KNUCKLERS
</P>
<P>
   Warm weather is expected again Wednesday and that is another bit
of good news for Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I like to pitch in warm weather because ... a
knuckleball is a feel pitch,'' he said. ``Having to hold it with my
fingernails and fingertips ... having it cold is almost like
throwing an ice cube. It doesn't feel comfortable sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield said, ``The ideal conditions for me would be a light
breeze blowing out. You want to have a little resistance vs. the
ball, and the wind blowing out would increase the movement.''
DAYTIME BLUES
</P>
<P>
   When the Red Sox play a day game as opposed to a night game, the
difference in their performance is like, well ... night and day.
</P>
<P>
   That's even more true for the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams play far better under the lights.
</P>
<P>
   Boston went 69-45 this season when playing at night, but only
23-25 in the daytime. Cleveland was a strong 68-44 at night, but an
atrocious 21-29 during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Something has to give in the divisional series between the two
clubs, though. Wednesday's game and Friday's game will be played in
the afternoon, as was Tuesday's. Starting times have not been
announced for Games 4 and 5, if they are necessary. GOODEN COMES
FULL CIRCLE
</P>
<P>
   Dwight ``Doc'' Gooden has come a long way in his career and in
his life off the field. But his journey this year from early season
obscurity and doubt to Game 2 starter in the divisional playoff
series is right up there on his list of professional comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   He said he didn't expect to have such a chance back in the
spring when he was toiling for the minor-league Buffalo Bisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had arm problems in spring training and started the season
on the disabled list,'' Gooden said. ``I went to Buffalo to rehab
and once I was in Buffalo I could never imagine this. I am very
blessed to be in the situation I am in now.'' LEWIS LEAVES GAME
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Darren Lewis left the game with a bruise after being
struck on the batting helmet by the Indians' Jaret Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who singled in his first two at-bats, was drilled on the
left ear flap by a Wright fastball in the fifth inning. Lewis was
face-down on the field near the plate for several minutes, then
walked unaided to the Red Sox' dugout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
