<SLUG> BC-NABISCO-EARNINGS-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RJR NABISCO BRACES FOR DROP IN RUSSIAN SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp., the latest U.S. company to be
buffeted by economic crisis from abroad, warned Tuesday that
``depressed market conditions'' in Russia would reduce its
third-quarter earnings well below earlier expectations.
</P>
<P>
   RJR said results would be 46 cents to 48 cents a diluted share;
many analysts had predicted 60 cents. The company issued its
warning after the stock market closed. In after-hours trading, RJR
shares fell to $25, down $1.9375 or 7 percent from their close on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   RJR, while also known for such food brands as Ritz crackers and
Oreo cookies, derives about two-thirds of its profits from tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Its cigarette sales in Russia and the rest of the former Soviet
Union had been running at an impressive rate in the first half of
the year, close to 20 percent of international profits, said
Emanuel Goldman, a tobacco and beverage analyst with PaineWebber in
San Francisco. Last year, the company's sales there accounted for
15 percent of international profits and represented 42 percent of
international volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that earlier rate is not going to happen,'' Goldman said.
``This is an important market for them. It's low profitability, but
higher volume.''
</P>
<P>
   (The rival Philip Morris, by contrast, has much more limited
exposure to Russia. Philip Morris' sales in Russia last year were 9
percent of international volume, and profits were 3.5 percent of
the international total, Goldman said.)
</P>
<P>
   The third quarter is now expected to be the second consecutive
disappointing quarter for RJR. In July, the company reported a loss
of $130 million, attributed in part to weakness in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Along with such U.S. brands as Winston, RJR's sales in Russia
include cigarettes produced specifically for the Russian market.
One, the Peter I heritage brand, is the largest-selling filtered
cigarette in Russia, the company says. Other brands include the
Genghis Khan, sold in Kazakhstan, and the Arsenal, sold in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis in Russia forced RJR to suspend imports of its
American brands and manufacture of its Russian brands for about two
weeks, said Martin Feldman, a tobacco analyst with Salomon Smith
Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Though manufacturing has resumed, ``demand from wholesalers
remains extremely uncertain, and the prospects for the company in
Russia remain problematic,'' he said. Demand had all but fallen
off, he said, as wholesalers and distributors ran out of cash to
pay for their orders.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement Tuesday, RJR blamed ``the devaluation of the
ruble, limited availability of trade credit and generally poor
economic conditions'' for the suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the company made $80 million in profits from its
Russian operations, Feldman added. ``This year, with a fair wind in
the fourth quarter, they might make $20 million for the whole
year,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another product of the Russian crisis will be higher taxes. The
company's overall tax rate will be pushed up, from 43.5 percent to
45.5 percent, Feldman said. That happens because the company pays
lower taxes on international profits than on domestic profits and
so, as international profits fall as a percentage of overall
profits, the company's tax rate goes up.
</P>
<P>
   Still, RJR should not flee the Russian market, Feldman said.
``As soon as the Russian economy begins to stabilize, you'll see an
improvement in RJR's business,'' he said. ``The current problems
are severe, but not a reason to give up on the business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
