<HEADER>
A0956 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LE-PEU-COGNAC-NYT &LR;      09-29 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LE-PEU-COGNAC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN COGNAC SINGS SOLO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The name Le Peu means nothing to Cognac drinkers. Yet, most
Cognac drinkers know it very well _ sort of.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a paradox. For years, the dry, delicate Cognac from
Le Peu has been an important part of Hennessy's VSOP blend, but
like all spirits sold by distillers to the Cognac houses, it has
labored in anonymity, lending its voice to the chorus. But now,
some of the Cognac houses are letting their more talented singers
perform solo.
</P>
<P>
   The new single-distillery Cognacs, as they are known, make a
subversive statement. For the first time, the Cognac makers, with a
jealous, competitive eye on the single-malt business, are asking
consumers to think about their product in an entirely different
way.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledgeable Scotch drinkers, of course, make a point of
knowing the characteristics of individual distilleries, whose
products they seek out with an enthusiasm that sometimes approaches
madness, but Cognac drinkers never have. Now, in a small way, they
are being offered a new definition of one of the world's most
prized spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessy has just released three Cognacs _ Le Peu, Izambard and
Camp Romain, each the product of a single distillery using Cognacs
from seven to 25 years old, each with its own personality, all
priced around $48.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessy is not alone. Louis Royer has just introduced a lineup
of five single-distillery Cognacs intended to represent the
personality of five of the six Cognac districts.
</P>
<P>
   Des Saules, for example, uses grapes from Borderies, a tiny
district whose svelte, rounded Cognacs soften a final blend in much
the same way that merlot civilizes a tough cabernet. The Cognac of
Les Magnolias, from the Grande Champagne district, shows the
finesse and complex fruit and floral aromas associated with
Cognac's premier district.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from about $28 for a Chantal Cognac from the Bons
Bois to $68 for Les Magnolias, and the ages follow an ascending
scale as well, from the two-year-old and three-year-old Cognacs
that make up Chantal to an average of 15 years in Les Magnolias,
quite young for a Grande Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   In taking the single-district approach, Royer has followed in
the footsteps of Gabriel &AMP; Andreu, which for the last three years
has been turning out some smashing Cognacs from the Fins Bois,
Borderies, Petite Champagne and Grande Champagne, all of them made
by single estates with their own distilleries.
</P>
<P>
   The Gabriel &AMP; Andreu Cognacs are priced from $30 for the
eight-year-old Fins Bois to $100 for the 35-year-old Grande
Champagne. The 25-year-old Petite Champagne, which sells for about
$65, is a thing of beauty, light-bodied, subtle and elegant, with a
rich floral, licorice and vanilla bouquet.
</P>
<P>
   The single-distillery experiment could backfire. Scotch
connoisseurs look on most blended Scotches with disdain. If Cognac
drinkers decide that single-distillery Cognacs show more character,
will they abandon blends as too bland? On the other hand, the
skeptical consumer might wonder, if the single-distillery products
are so fabulous, why has it taken several hundred years for them to
be marketed?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Scotch was in the same boat barely 15 years ago, when
most Americans, if they even knew what a single-malt was, could
probably name only Glenlivet and Glenfiddich as examples.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it all comes down to the liquid in the bottle. Le
Peu, ethereal and brightly fruity, can easily stand alone. So can
Hennessy's Camp Romain, a deep, nutty, fruitcake-rich Cognac made
by Betty Lesueur, one of few women who are Cognac distillers.
</P>
<P>
   Izambard, which occupies a middle ground between the two, may be
a Cognac that can make more of a contribution in a blend. Likewise
Des Saules, Royer's Cognac from Borderies. Nutty and supple, it is
a friendly, undemanding Cognac, ideal for Cognac beginners but best
suited to be a team player, not a star. The race is on. May the
best distillery win. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
