<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ARAB-VILLAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIOTS HIGHLIGHT FEELINGS OF BIAS AMONG ISRAEL'S ARAB MINORITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UMM EL-FAHM, Israel _ As though they had copied a script from
their Palestinian brethren in the West Bank, about 1,000 angry
Arabs in this mountainous Israeli village lobbed rocks at Israeli
border police Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The police held their ground and fired tear gas canisters, the
sound echoing through the hills. The young protesters passed out
onions to blunt the chemical's potency. Hooded young men burned
tires in the streets. One even carried a Palestinian flag.
</P>
<P>
   The clashes began Sunday after the border police burned down a
makeshift tent set up by the Arabs here to protest a government
decision to use 1,000 acres of village land for a military training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   The incident sparked three days of rioting in which hundreds of
protesters were injured. It also highlighted feelings of
discrimination among Israel's Arab minority and reignited
sensitivities over land expropriation, an issue that has marred
Jewish-Arab relations since the state of Israel was founded 50
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main issue is the land,'' said Bassam Kanaana, a
33-year-old Arab protester. ``They want to turn the Arab villages
into ghettos by not allowing them to expand naturally. They want to
strangle our ability to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials say the newly designated military area, hills
now used by Arab farmers for grazing sheep and growing olive trees,
will be used by the army as a firing range, but that the villagers
can continue to use the land as long as they agree to vacate it
whenever the army needs it.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Arabs and their left-wing Jewish supporters believe the
government has another agenda for the land, which straddles the
municipal boundaries of Umm el-Fahm and two other Arab villages.
They say the government plans to move Arabs off the land, then
eventually build a Jewish village called Iron. It is a tactic, they
say, that has been used many times before in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pattern,'' said Michael Warschawski, a Jewish
activist and director of the Alternative Information Center, a
left-wing organization that participated in Tuesday's
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an accident that 100 percent of the private land
confiscated in Israel for military purposes belonged to Arabs,'' he
said. ``On the contrary, it reflects very well what is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Umm el-Fahm, 60 miles north-northeast of Tel Aviv, has watched
its borders shrink since 1948, the year Israel was created. First,
the Jewish town of Me Ami sprung up to the south, on land Umm
el-Fahm used to count as its own. Then, the town of Ma'Avya
appeared on the northern border.
</P>
<P>
   In this latest move, the Israeli Defense Ministry declared land
to the west ``closed'' for military use. ``Five, eight years from
now, you will hear that they're planning to build a new Jewish city
here,'' Warschawski predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The clashes underscore just how much in common Israel's
800,000-strong Arab population has with the 2.6 million
Palestinians living in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. And they
underscore the government's different responses to rioting in
Israel and in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the police stormed a village school, beating and
arresting students. Private homes were damaged, and police used
rubber bullets as well as tear gas against the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   But since the Arabs are citizens of Israel, they have political
clout that Palestinians do not.
</P>
<P>
   Arab members of the Knesset, Israel's Parliament, blasted the
border police for using such a strong show of force to quell the
riots. And village leaders struck a deal with Micha Goldman, the
chairman of the Knesset interior committee, to allow the owners to
use the land.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the police deployed at the edges of Umm el-Fahm,
instead of entering the city, and allowed peaceful demonstrations
in surrounding villages to wrap up quietly.
</P>
<P>
   President Ezer Weizmann called on Israel's Arabs and Jews to
find a way to coexist in peace and visited Umm el-Fahm for an hour
Tuesday in a show of support.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, many Israeli Arabs believe that little more than geography
and an Israeli passport separate them from the Palestinians. When
Israel's war for independence ended in 1948, Umm-el-Fahm fell
within the new state. But it stands only a few miles from the
border with the West Bank, which was controlled by Jordan until
Israel capture it in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no difference between us and them,'' said a
Palestinian protester, who gave his name only as Mahameed, echoing
a familiar refrain among the Arab demonstrators here. ``We're
brothers. We have Israeli identity cards, but first, we're
Palestinians.''
</P>
<P>
   And when violence flares in the West Bank, such as the explosion
in Ramallah on Tuesday that killed an alleged Hamas militant and
wounded two of his brothers, Israeli Arabs typically sympathize.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Israel's Arab community say the feelings stem from
Israeli government policies that make Arab citizens think of
themselves as outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people feel that they are discriminated against in just
about every facet of life,'' said Hassan Jabarin, an Israeli Arab
lawyer and director of the Adala Legal Center for Arab Minority
Rights in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Arab leaders say their municipalities receive only a tiny
portion of the government funds that Jewish municipalities get.
</P>
<P>
   They say their schools were left out of a government-funded
program designed to help poorer students enter college, even
though, they add, far more Arabs than Jews live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   And Israel's Arabs had to go to court just to try to get street
signs printed in Arabic _ they are now printed only in Hebrew and
English. Arabic is the primary language of nearly 20 percent of
Israel's population. The case is pending.
</P>
<P>
   College entrance exams have asked students about Judaism, but
not Islam or Christianity. Arab parties have been conspicuously
left out of government coalitions.
</P>
<P>
   And last year, a bill that would prohibit Arabs from running for
prime minister was introduced in the Parliament, then tabled by a
Jewish member.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never felt like an Israeli,'' said Kanaaneh, the
Palestinian demonstrator, standing with other protesters in his
village of Kufr Qara, next to Umm el-Fahm. ``The state doesn't let
us feel that we belong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like strangers in our own land.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
