<HEADER>
A0965 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC--LOBBY-II-SHORT-ART-N     09-29 1430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC--LOBBY-II-SHORT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOBBYISTS ADOPTING TECHNIQUES USED IN POLITICAL CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Influence Industry: 2nd of 2 articles.)  
(EDITORS: This is an abridged version of the LOBBY-II story, about
half the length of the version that will appear in The New York
Times. The full-length version has moved in the ``w'' news file
tonight.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From the nondescript headquarters of his Houston
construction firm, Leo E. Linbeck Jr., a lanky, bow-tied executive
with a drawl, is masterminding a crusade to overturn the nation's
tax system.
</P>
<P>
   Once, someone like him might have hired some of Washington's
``Gucci Gulch'' lobbyists to prowl the marble corridors outside
Congress' tax committees. But Linbeck, with Texas-style audacity,
wants to engineer a populist uprising to replace the income tax
code with a national sales tax. And with $15 million from some
initial investors and mass fund raising, he has run a radio and
television advertising campaign and employed an army of media
consultants, pollsters, political strategists, marketers, academics
and yes, even a few lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine what it would be like if you were in Congress and you
got a thousand phone calls a week and letters and e-mails and
faxes,'' Linbeck, a former chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank in
Dallas, said. ``Not people from all over the country, but your
constituents, people whose names you recognize, the people who were
at the polls with you, who live down the street with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Linbeck and his fellow investors in ``Americans for Fair
Taxation'' are unusual in the scale of their ambition. But their
methods have become commonplace as lobbying has undergone a
revolution over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely now does a well-connected Washington lobbyist work alone
to persuade power brokers in Congress. Instead, the lobbyist has
become just one of many players running full-fledged national
campaigns intended to create a ``grass-roots'' groundswell in
support of, or more often in opposition to, legislation before
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In their million-dollar costs and their reliance on television,
polling and grass-roots constituency building, these efforts most
resemble presidential campaigns. And they are now so pervasive and
sophisticated that it has become difficult to distinguish between a
lobbying effort, an issue advocacy campaign and a citizens
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these efforts are genuine grass-roots movements. But
others are deceptions in which a special interest pays to create
the appearance of a popular groundswell.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of these techniques has spread the wealth of the
influence industry beyond the lawyer-lobbyist to a new class of
political professionals, who often play overlapping roles as
advisers to presidential and congressional candidates, corporate
tacticians and media pundits.
</P>
<P>
   In a world where the distinctions and conflicts between their
multiple roles seem to matter less and less and can even be a
business advantage, strategists who are ideological enemies in
politics put their differences aside to work together on
large-scale corporate campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is the outgrowth of several developments in technology
and politics. E-mail, computer databases, talk radio and 24-hour
cable television all make it easier to organize and send a
political message across the country at warp speed.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, power in Washington has been dispersed, so
that new ways are needed to influence more legislators. The media
age politician is far more likely to be moved by polls, television
ads and mass constituent contacts than by party discipline, a
committee chairman or a Washington wise man. And the Republicans in
Congress know they came to power with the help of several groups
with grass-roots memberships: the National Federation of
Independent Businesses, the National Rifle Association, the
Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Public policy experts debate whether the new methods of lobbying
have made it more democratic by taking it out of the back rooms of
the Capitol or whether they have simply made it far more difficult
for interests without money to compete in the public arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of a trend in Washington where rational debate on
issues gets buried in big-budget sound bites,'' said Edward
Yingling, the chief lobbyist for the American Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Linbeck says of his way of moving Congress: ``It's not as
orderly. It's not as predictable. It's not as controlled as some
might want it to be. But I think those are positive attributes.''
</P>
<P>
   The convergence of the worlds of lobbying and politics is
evident in how Linbeck has gone about his people's crusade. He
estimates the effort will take several years and ultimately cost an
extraordinary $90 million, a sum likely only if hundreds of
thousands of Americans join his cause. Right now, a major tax
overhaul is only a glimmer far out on the horizon of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his initial money went to hire prominent academics and
research organizations to develop the 23 percent national sales
tax. But to speed the organizing and make his proposal as
politically appealing as possible, he has also turned to national
experts in politics, using Denis Calabrese, a Houston Republican
consultant and onetime aide to Rep. Dick Armey of Texas as his
chief strategist. With Calabrese's help, ``Americans for Fair
Taxation'' has hired an all-star cast from both parties to propel
his tax plan:
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Wirthlin, President Reagan's pollster, surveyed the
electorate's attitudes towards the tax system, with some help from
Mark Mellman, pollster to the Democratic leadership in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   _Don Sipple, a media adviser to Bob Dole's presidential campaign
produced early television advertisements to test-market the sales
tax.
</P>
<P>
   _Fred Steeper, a well-established Republican pollster in
Michigan, checked on the advertisements' results.
</P>
<P>
   _Creative Response Concepts, whose president, Greg Mueller, was
communications director for Patrick Buchanan's 1996 presidential
run, promotes the sales tax to journalists.
</P>
<P>
   _Charles Sewell, a one-time Democratic staff aide and strategist
who is now a vice president at the Washington office of Ketchum
Public Relations, scours the country for civic leaders who can head
chapters of Americans for Fair Taxation in the nation's 435
congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   _Americans for Fair Taxation does have a more traditional
lobbying team too, from Arter &AMP; Hadden, a law firm whose ranks
include two former members of Congress from Texas Thomas Loeffler,
a Republican and Jim Chapman, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   This may sound like the lobbying equivalent of the Normandy
invasion. But ever since the epic battle against Clinton's proposal
for national health insurance in 1994, these kinds of ensembles
have assembled on issue after issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inside game of lobbying is in decline and the outside game
of consumer messaging _ of marshaling public opinion _ is advancing
and increasing,`` said Mike Murphy, media consultant in 1996 to the
Republican presidential candidates Lamar Alexander and Bob Dole.
``And savvy companies have figured out that the best experts to
hire to do this kind of work are political consultants.'' His
company also specializes in advertising, research and political
organizing for corporations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, new forms of communication like the Internet,
e-mail, talk radio and computerized ``blast faxes'' have made it
far easier to organize national constituencies and instantly
instruct them on when to deluge Congress in letters and phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   And as party discipline has waned, members of Congress have also
proved ever more responsive to television advertising or contacts
from home, or the ups and downs of instantly sampled public
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The turn to grass roots persuasion techniques takes place at the
same time that party politics is metamorphosing in the television
age, with fund-raisers replacing block captains and the public
increasingly cut off from either main party. And some say these
lobbying efforts are the politics of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the election industry back in the '70s,'' Brian
Lunde, a former executive director of the Democratic National
Committee, said. ``There was no such thing then. This is the same
thing. It's the next generation of political campaign in the
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
