<HEADER>
A0966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT &LR;      09-29 0161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDEAUX COPYCAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lambert Bridge Merlot, Sonoma County, Calif., 1995. About $20. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The people at Lambert Bridge Winery, in the Dry Creek region of
northern Sonoma County, think of this wine as being in the style of
a good Pomerol, and they are not far off the mark. The wine has
Bordeaux style with the roundness characteristic of St.-Emilion and
Pomerol.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a particularly subtle wine, but thanks to some
cabernet in the blend, it has good structure, which is winespeak
for tannin. Not a wimpy merlot by any means, it is composed of 78
percent merlot, 14 percent cabernet sauvignon and 8 percent
cabernet franc.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of the grapes came from the Dry Creek region,
and the rest from Carneros, down by the San Pablo Bay. The alcohol
content is about 13 percent. The wine spent 16 months in French oak
barrels, and it is quite ready to be enjoyed now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-PADRES-NYT     09-29 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN'S 16 STRIKEOUTS BESTS JOHNSON AND ASTROS, 2-1  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ All the attention, all the focus, all the hype before
the game belonged to Randy Johnson. But the 16 strikeouts were
Kevin Brown's. And now, after their 2-1 loss to the San Diego
Padres, Johnson's Houston Astros are down one game to none in their
National League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is generally regarded as the most fearsome pitcher in
the major leagues. But Brown has something Johnson doesn't: a World
Series ring. And now Brown has the most strikeouts ever recorded in
a playoff game _ division or championship series.
</P>
<P>
   And the only reason he did not challenge Bob Gibson's
post-season record of 17 (set in the 1968 World Series) is because
San Diego Manager Bruce Bochy turned to his closer, Trevor Hoffman,
to pitch the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was funny,'' Houston Manager Larry Dierker said, referring
to a conversation he had with bench coach Matt Galante just before
the ninth. ``We talked about that in the eighth inning. Matt asked
if they would bring Hoffman in and I said, `I hope he does.'''
</P>
<P>
   Which was funny in its own right. Because Hoffman, who had 53
saves, was the most dominating closer in the majors this season.
</P>
<P>
   But that only demonstrates how good Brown was.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, San Diego General Manager Kevin Towers had told
the San Diego Union-Tribune, ``I will take Kevin Brown head-to-head
with Randy Johnson in any game, on Astroturf, cement, asphalt,
grass, you name it. I'll take my chances with Kevin Brown anywhere,
I don't care where it's at.''
</P>
<P>
   And, for at least one night, Towers was right. In tossing eight
scoreless innings against the best lineup in the league, Brown
allowed just two singles (both to Houston's No. 8 hitter Brad
Ausmus). Brown had at least one strikeout in each inning he
pitched, and he struck out the side in the both the third and the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Brown struck out every Astro in the starting lineup except Bill
Spiers. He fanned Derek Bell and Ricky Gutierrez three times each;
Craig Biggio, Jeff Bagwell, Moises Alou, Carl Everett and Johnson
twice apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he may have been more dominating when he pitched a
no-hitter for the Florida Marlins last season. ``But,'' he said,
``I'll take today's game any time because of the setting. The
no-hitter was great from a personal standpoint. But today's game
had a much bigger impact on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   And, all of a sudden, after the Padres had picked up their first
postseason victory in 14 years, it was the Astros who were in the
early hole.
</P>
<P>
   Not because Johnson pitched badly by any means. It was just that
Brown, who was 18-7 with a 2.38 earned run average, pitched a Randy
Johnson-type game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got out-pitched today,'' said Johnson. ``That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   After being obtained from the Seattle Mariners minutes before
the July 31 trading deadline, Johnson was 5-0 at the Astrodome with
a 0.42 ERA and four shutouts in his first four home starts. In all,
Johnson was 10-1 with Houston with a 1.28 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Johnson allowed 9 hits and 2 runs in his 8 innings,
walking 1 while striking out 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy had good stuff, but not his best stuff,'' Dierker said.
``And Kevin was as dominating as you can be. Other than pitching a
no-hitter, I don't know what more he could have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson looked unhittable at the start Tuesday, catching both
Tony Gwynn and Ken Caminiti looking at called third strikes to end
the top of the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first at-bat was over so quick,'' said Gwynn, who has won
the NL batting title 8 times. ``Bip, bap, bip. See ya.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Padres were able to collect a pair of singles off
Johnson in the second, one in the fourth and another in the fifth.
And even though they could not score, it was much more than the
Astros were doing against Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Both pitchers were throwing in the 95 to 97 mile per hour range.
But Brown had all four of his pitches working: a two-seam sinking
fastball, a four-seam fastball that tails up and away; a forkball
with a nasty drop and a slider that seems to rise on left-handed
hitters as it breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw more four-seamers than he has in the past to set up
his sinker,'' Biggio said. ``He threw his four-seamer up and out of
the zone and we chased it a lot of times. And when someone's
throwing 97 out of the zone, you're not going to hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   And nobody really did.
</P>
<P>
   Through five innings, Brown had allowed just one hit: an Ausmus
single with one out in the third. Ausmus would eventually make it
to third on back-to-back passed balls by Carlos Hernandez, who was
screened by Johnson as he attempted to bunt. But Brown fanned
Johnson and Biggio to end the threat. And the game was still
scoreless entering the sixth, when Gwynn led off the top of the
inning by slapping a 1-2 Johnson slider for a line-drive double
over third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how I hit that one ball,'' said Gwynn, who would
later leave the game because his left achilles tendon tightened up.
``I'm just happy it found a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Vaughn followed by beating out an infield single, after
Spiers had nearly robbed him with a great backhand play at third.
And now the Padres had runners on first and second. Caminiti was
next, and he blooped a single over second and just out of Biggio's
reach. Jim Leyritz followed with a bases-loaded sacrifice fly to
center. And even though the Padres eventually left runners on
second and third, Brown had a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   He made it stand up, stranding runners on second and third
himself by striking out Derek Bell to end the Houston sixth. And
then Vaughn _ who had hit his 50th homer in his final at-bat of the
regular season _ belted a Johnson slider over the left field
scoreboard to open the eighth with an immensely valuable insurance
run to give San Diego a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Brown responded by striking out the side in the eighth to leave
pinch-hitter Dave Clark _ who had walked with two outs _ stranded
at third. But Brown was pitching on three days rest. And he had now
thrown 118 pitches, 77 of them for strikes. And so Bochy went to
Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took somebody like Trevor Hoffman to not have Kevin go back
out,'' Bochy said. ``Hoffman's the best reliever in the game. It
was a win-win situation. Or lose-lose if things wouldn't have
worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   They almost didn't. Spiers led off the ninth by doubling over
third. After Bell flew out and Bagwell struck out, Caminiti nearly
robbed Alou with a Graig Nettles-like diving stop at third. But
Caminiti threw the ball away, Alou scampered home, and the Astros
were down by a run. But Everett flew to center to end the game. And
the Padres had made sure the day belonged to Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even realize I had that many strikeouts until the
ninth inning, when Ed Vosberg told me,'' said Brown, whose
career-high in the majors had been 11. ``Thirteen is the most I
ever remember having. And that was in college.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
