<HEADLINE>
INDIANS ADD TO DISMAL PLAYOFF OPENER RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The question was simple enough. Why, Omar Vizquel
was asked, have the Indians lost their last seven postseason series
openers? Why does a club that is good enough to win four
consecutive American League Central Division titles, a team
talented enough to have made it to two of the last three World
Series, play so poorly coming out of the blocks?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got no idea,'' said Vizquel, pondering the meaning and
the consequences of Tuesday's 11-3 loss to the Red Sox at Jacobs
Field in the opener of their best-of-five AL Division Series. ``But
it's not easy coming from behind. It's one of the toughest things
in baseball. Not many teams can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came a pause as the Indians shortstop looked for a positive
spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the right people here who can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But not always. In the previous six series, the Indians have won
as many as they have lost, going 3-3. And they have never lost an
opener in Cleveland and come back to win a series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a big deal,'' said Vizquel, who was hitless in three
at-bats against Pedro Martinez. ``It's important to win the first
game. It's always important to get that first step.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, in what turned into an afternoon's delight for Mo
Vaughn and the Red Sox, the Indians stumbled almost coming out of
the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The balloons released in a pregame ceremony were still swirling
around the Jake when starter Jaret Wright found himself in big
trouble, giving up singles to Darren Lewis and John Valentin before
Vaughn powered his first home run of the game over the left-field
fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made some mistakes, and that got us into a hole early,''
said Wright, who also gave up a three-run homer to Nomar
Garciaparra in the fifth that settled the issue. ``After the first,
I just said to myself to go out and put up zeros to help my
teammates. Then Nomar came and hit the ball out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, who staggered into the playoffs after winning
another division title in ridiculously easy fashion, understand
that their margin for error _ or errors _ is now all but gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this means is that they are one game closer,'' said left
fielder Brian Giles. ``We never gave ourselves a chance today. We
were down, 3-0. Then it was 6-0. It puts a lot of pressure on us
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians seemed to put pressure on themselves all day, from
Wright's first-inning jitters to the lackadaisical baserunning of
right fielder Manny Ramirez, who went into his home run trot on a
fly ball to deep center in the second that bounced off the fence,
winding up with a single instead of what should have been at least
a double. Ramirez then was doubled up off first when a line drive
by Travis Fryman was speared at third by John Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did they help themselves with some spotty pitching. The
Red Sox pounded Wright and five relievers for 12 hits, including
three homers, as everyone in the lineup other than Troy O'Leary
reached safely.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Indians are in a hole that will become a pit if they
cannot find a way to beat Tim Wakefield and his knuckleball this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we don't want to do is go back to Boston down, 0-2,''
said first baseman Jim Thome, stating the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians know they can come back. But they also know they are
facing a new set of problems, having lost the opener at home.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being at least, manager Mike Hargrove could laugh
about the task at hand. ``It's not the perfect world scenario,'' he
said. ``We certainly didn't lose this one to keep our tradition
going. We would rather have won the first game. If you can get any
comfort out of anything, we have (come back) before. We didn't want
to have to do it again, but we have to do it again, so we'll give
it our best shot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
