<HEADLINE>
LEWIS, VALENTIN CHANGE INDIANS' GAME PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Red Sox manager Jimy Williams, in his usual
understated way, had this to say about Mo Vaughn's seven RBIs:
Remember that ``five of the seven were of individuals who got on
before him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove, in his usual blunt manner
following a loss, had this to say about Darren Lewis and John
Valentin upsetting his best-laid plans: ``We had to change our
approach to pitching to (Vaughn and Nomar Garciaparra) because we
had to pitch to them. Every time they came up, they had runners on
base.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit and endless cassettes of highlight tape will be devoted
to Vaughn's seven RBIs and Garciaparra's four RBIs in the Red Sox'
11-3 playoff-opening rout of the Indians Tuesday, but save a
cassette or two for Lewis and Valentin. They forced the Indians to
pitch to Boston's two most feared hitters for the simple reason
that Boston's first and second batters were on base so often _
eight times, to be precise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time Vaughn and Garciaparra came up,'' said Hargrove,
``every base was covered and we had no place to put them. Our goal
going into the series was to pitch around those guys. But how are
you going to pitch around them when the bases are full? When the
bases are full, you've got to pitch to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The bases weren't exactly full _ Vaughn's and Garciaparra's
homers that gave Boston a 6-0 lead came with two runners on _ but
Hargrove's point was well taken. ``The best way to pitch to Vaughn
and Garciapparra,'' he said, ``is to get the people out in front of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys were on for our No. 3 and 4 guys to come through,'' said
Valentin (3 for 4, 1 walk, 4 runs), who had struggled with a most
sluggish .159 average in September. ``Darren and I went up there to
be aggressive. (Cleveland starter Jaret) Wright wasn't around the
strike zone and maybe he overthrew the ball, and we were able to
look for pitches to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The tone was set in the first when Lewis (2 for 2, 1 hit by
pitch, 1 run) led off with a single and Valentin followed with a
single to left on a hit-and-run. ``We don't have a hit-and-run,''
joked Valentin. ``Darren just happened to be running when I
happened to be hitting.'' Vaughn followed with a three-run homer on
a full count as Wright could not afford to walk the slugger with
two on and none out and Garciaparra in the on-deck circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to put the pressure on them right away in that first
inning,'' said Lewis. ``To be able to put the pressure on them
right away in this situation is very big. What you do is go out and
do anything to get on base. I think John and I take a lot of pride
in this and doing everything we can to score some runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis could not hear out of his left ear and his head was
ringing more than a roomful of cellular phone technicians when he
spoke these words some two hours after his plate appearance in the
fifth. That's because Wright sent a rising fastball inside that
kept moving in until it caught Lewis on the earflap of his batting
helmet. The Red Sox center fielder lay face down at home plate for
minutes until he was finally led off the field. His replacement,
Damon Buford, then scored on Garciaparra's homer and came around
after being hit by a pitch in the eighth when Vaughn stroked a
bases-loaded double.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never lost consciousness,'' said Lewis. ``My ear was just
ringing. Pretty loud, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As Lewis lay in the dirt, the Red Sox medical staff ``just asked
me to open my eyes, and I did and I told them I felt fine, except
my ears were ringing. Other than that, I felt pretty good. I wasn't
dizzy or anything. I feel fine now. I don't have a headache or
anything. I just can't hear out of one ear.''
</P>
<P>
   The moment, though, was frightening. ``What scared me more than
anything was that my ear was ringing so loud,'' Lewis said, ``and
it's happened to me once before, back when I was in A ball.'' It
was also frightening because Lewis recalled when Robby Thompson,
his teammate in San Francisco, was hit in the face in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball hit me right on the earflap, and I was just glad I
was able to get down in time,'' said Lewis. ``I'd seen one of my
teammates get hit in the face in '93 and ... and ... it's part of
the game. It's like being a wide receiver going over the middle and
taking a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The only recourse after being hit, said Lewis, ``is to jump
right back up and get right back in there.'' Lewis wasn't able to
do that Tuesday _ Buford ran for him, and after Valentin walked,
Garciaparra unloaded. But he and Valentin had done more than enough
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get the two guys out in front of Vaughn and
Garciaparra,'' said Hargrove. Or else there may be more long games,
and a possible short series, for Cleveland.
</P>
</TEXT>
