<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE IS ON GOODEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ He is almost of a different era, a figure from the
past. But Wednesday afternoon at Jacobs Field, Indians pitcher
Dwight Gooden's presence will be vital.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 1-0, in the American League Division Series after
Tuesday's 11-3 rout by the Red Sox, the Cleveland Indians will ask
Gooden to do something he has never done: win a postseason game.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, you remember Doc Gooden, the star of the Mets'
contending teams of a decade ago; Doc Gooden, who fell from grace
so quickly and steadily as a result of substance abuse that now he
is almost an afterthought, someone who came to the Indians more by
chance than design.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gooden, who for all his success with the Mets never won a
playoff or World Series game, must deliver. Or else. ``I wouldn't
say (the drought) frustrates me,'' said Gooden. Tuesday ``But it
would be nice to get one. In my past postseasons, I felt I pitched
well, but unfortunately, the guys I went against pitched very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooden compiled an 8-6 record this season with Cleveland, which
made him not an ace but at least part of the postseason rotation,
an amazing feat considering that he started the season on the
disabled list with arm problems.
</P>
<P>
   An aging pitcher with a bad arm is hardly considered a building
block for a successful staff, but Gooden overcame the setbacks,
starting out at Triple A Buffalo and slowly and steadily working
his way back into major league pitching form.
</P>
<P>
   When Mike Hargrove was asked if he would have been surprised if
someone had told him at midseason that Gooden would have been his
starter in Game 2 of the playoffs, the manager nodded in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given what really went on in spring training and leading up to
that point with the tendinitis in his shoulder and how inconsistent
he had been up to that point, I think it might have sounded crazy
at that point,'' conceded Hargrove.
</P>
<P>
   It may be even crazier if Gooden wins his first postseason game
ever after being considered finished.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
