<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEARY GULF RESIDENTS GLAD TO SEE STORM WANE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Ga., La., Tenn., Miss., Fla.)  (Eds: See also HURRICANE-DOMINICAN) 
(mk) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOBILE, Ala. _ Sometimes, said Reola Jones, a tree just knows
which way to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Georges ripped through her neighborhood here in the
darkness of early Monday morning, blowing through windows and
snapping trees and sending water rippling down the street. Power
lines sparked along a pitch-black street as she prayed in the
little wood house she shares with her elderly father on Duval
Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got up out of bed and wondered which window I was going to
end up flying through,'' she said. She sat frightened until
daylight.
</P>
<P>
   At dawn, she saw that two large trees had fallen on either side
of her house. One tree missed the house by just a few feet as it
toppled in the yard. A second one, uprooted, was snagged by power
lines as it toppled toward her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wonderful works of God,'' she said, sitting outside the
house as power company workers tried to untangle the mess of power
lines and limbs as cars crept through a street still puddled with
dingy water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mess,'' said the 56-year-old Ms. Jones. ``But we were
lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to be the most-repeated assessment of this hurricane
here on Mobile Bay _ and elsewhere along the Gulf Coast _ as
Georges faded first into a tropical storm and then a tropical
depression as it moved sluggishly out of the region, dumping heavy
rains on South Alabama, southeastern Georgia and northern Florida.
Roads in Alabama flooded, lights winked out as far north as
Montgomery, and coastal residents from Louisiana to Florida found
beach houses, piers and businesses badly damaged by wind and storm
surges.
</P>
<P>
   But, said people here, it threatened to be much, much worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of houses banged up,'' said Henry Williams, 53, as he
cleaned a mess of tree limbs from the front yard of his small house
on Victory Drive. Not far away, chainsaws tore through the last of
the trees that blocked a narrow street as people swept the dark
water off porches and knelt in mangled flower beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you can do is pray that the Good Lord don't take you,''
said Williams, throwing down an armload of tree limbs. ``I slept
through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people could not. Hurricane Georges _ which some people
referred to as ``Georgie'' _ had left a wake of death and
destruction through the Lesser Antilles, Puerto Rico, the Dominican
Republic, Haiti and Cuba before raking across the Florida Keys and
them slamming into the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   While winds in Mississippi and Alabama tore off pieces of roofs
and ripped patches from beachside condominiums, storm surges picked
apart piers, eroded beaches and undercut homes. Tens of thousands
evacuated, to shelters, interstate highway hotel rooms and
churches.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters had hoped that Georges would be reduced to a much
weaker storm after crossing the steep mountains of the Dominican
Republic and Cuba, but the storm had sustained winds of some 100
miles per hour and even higher gusts when it made landfall at
Biloxi, Miss., on Sunday. But, instead of pounding northward, the
storm stalled just inland, dropping as much as 30 inches of rain on
parts of the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   As the storm crept to the north and northeast Tuesday, it dumped
as much as 15 inches of rain in southern Alabama and spawned
tornadoes in some parts of the state. Floodwaters filled town
streets in southern Alabama. It was waist-deep in parts of East
Brewton, Ala., and Flomaton, Ala., early Tuesday evening as creeks
and rivers overflowed their banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping it doesn't get to the downtown,'' said Sandy
Stargel, chief dispatcher at the Flomaton Police Department.
``We've already got water in several houses.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was along the coast in Mississippi and Alabama that the
floods caused the most trouble. In Pascagoula, Miss., water reached
rooftops, roads were washed out and oyster shells were swept into
yards. More than 600,000 people had lost power.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands filled hotel rooms as far north as Memphis. Marilyn
Dedeaux of Jackson, Miss., kept 16 relatives and friends and four
large refugee dogs in her home, where they all waited for the
floods to recede.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dedeaux said the people got along well in the crowded house,
but her 75-pound bassett hound, Lindsey, was ``very unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, on the Dog River near Mobile, more than 100 boats
were sunk or damaged as the storm blew through.
</P>
<P>
   Water as deep as 11 feet swamped Water Street in downtown
Mobile, flooding homes and chasing residents into shelters. The
stately mansions on Government Street in Mobile _ homes of old
money and new money _ seemed mostly untouched, while poorer
neighborhoods suffered much worse.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Jones, on Duval Street, wondered a little about that. But
she is not complaining too much, considering her luck with the
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Her luck, before the storm, had not been good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a little job in town, but it played out,'' said Ms.
Jones, who is still unemployed. She and her elderly father live on
his Social Security check while she looks for work.
</P>
<P>
   They had been trying to fix up the small house, and its
multi-colored walls, pieced together from different materials, are
signs of that.
</P>
<P>
   As the storm pounded them early Monday, she felt they would lose
the roof, at least, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wind sounded like a missile,'' she said. ``The window
broke,'' and limbs rattled across the shingles. One tree tumbled
across a chain link fence, destroying it _ ``one more thing we got
to do'' _ as water filled the streets, she said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the big trees that missed the house also missed her car,
by inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll set us back, further,'' she said of the damages to their
property. But all in all, she said, their luck held. ``I'm just
amazed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While the damage to property along the coast and points inland
will be in the millions, the storm _ which caused some 370 deaths
in the Caribbean _ is blamed for only four deaths on the Gulf
Coast. Candles, lit because of power outtages, led to fatal fires
in Pensacola, Fla., and New Orleans. A traffic accident during the
storm killed a woman in Pensacola, and an elderly woman died while
being moved to a shelter in Baton Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   But no one was killed by flying debris or drowned, at least as
of this evening, in the floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
   In New Orleans, where people had feared the storm would make
landfall and flood a city that is six feet below sea level, some
21,000 people left shelters Tuesday morning and headed home,
``thankful that we were spared'' said the city's mayor, Marc
Morial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
