u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-ART-1STL     09-29 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND ARAFAT PLAN HOW PALESTINIANS WILL FIGHT TERRORISTS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, Netanyahu and Arafat ..., to correct time
since their last meeting.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton met Tuesday with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat and emphasized the work that the Palestinians
need to do to combat terrorism as the Israelis withdraw from an
additional 13 percent of the West Bank, senior U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the leaders second meeting in two days, after a session
on Monday with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, and it
demonstrated, Clinton's aides said, the president's determination
to complete an interim agreement between Israel and the
Palestinians in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Israel has accepted a phased withdrawal from the West
Bank, of the 13 percent that Washington had insisted on, American
attention turned to the more complicated details of how
Palestinians can improve security. The improvements are supposed to
be made parallel with the Israeli pullbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Those topics involve issues like dismantling terrorist cells,
confiscating some guns and halting the ``incitement'' of residents
through anti-Israeli speeches and propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace is a Palestinian need, Israeli need, Arab need,
international need,'' Arafat said after the hourlong talks with
Clinton. ``We are very close on a number of subjects.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat expressed hope that a deal could be reached at a meeting
here next month, a move agreed to on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry said, ``The president is
determined to see an agreement arise from this exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu and Arafat, whose personal and ideological dislike and
distrust for each other have become ingrained, met on Monday for
the first time in almost a year. Even more important, senior
American officials said, they agreed to a series of contacts and a
way to manage crises between them.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also wanted to reassure Arafat of Washington's
commitment to help the Palestinians through aid and investment,
White House officials said. Clinton emphasized ``how much terrorism
undermines Arafat, as well,'' one official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans also wanted to go over some of Arafat's concerns
about what remains to be done, including Palestinian needs for
security from attacks by Israeli settlers, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Early next week Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and the
Middle East negotiator, Dennis Ross, will travel to the Middle East
for talks with the two sides, to try to insure that the meeting
next month succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to have Netanyahu, Arafat and their aides and
experts at a site near Washington, with American officials guiding
their negotiations and Clinton involving himself as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   If an interim deal can be finished, talks will formally open on
a final settlement between Israel and the Palestinians, originally
envisioned in the 1993 and 1995 Oslo accords to be completed by May
4.
</P>
<P>
   Although American, Israeli and Palestinian officials
acknowledged that much work remains to be done, all expressed a new
confidence that the time is ripe for a deal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   American officials expressed particular concern about the
dangers of new violence or unilateral actions by either side that
could quickly erode the wary willingness of the two men to work
together.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton emphasized to both that they needed to avoid
embarrassing each other.
</P>
<P>
   He and Albright pressed Arafat in his United Nations speech on
Monday to avoid any commitment to declaring an independent
Palestinian state after May 4, if the final-status negotiations
have not succeeded by then.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, while asking the help of the world to achieve that goal,
complied with the American request.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, speaking here on Monday, said he had told Arafat that
any such unilateral step would force him to respond in kind and
destroy the peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   The other great concern is of another bombing of Israeli
civilians by Palestinian radicals opposed to Arafat and the peace
effort. American officials pointed to an explosion Tuesday in
Ramallah, on the West Bank, of a car that was apparently being
equipped as a bomb for use against Israelis. The explosion killed a
participant in the Hamas organization and wounded two other
supporters of the militant Islamic group.
</P>
<P>
   Similar attacks have disrupted momentum toward peace and pushed
Netanyahu to attack Arafat for his apparent failure to insure
complete security for Israelis, even when the bombers lived in or
moved through Israeli-controlled territory.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has been bracing for a renewal of Hamas bombings and
Tuesday sealed its borders with the West Bank and Gaza Strip on the
eve of Yom Kippur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
