<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-WOODARD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOTED BOEING EXEC OPTS FOR RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Ron Woodard, who was forced out earlier this month as
president of Boeing Commercial Airplane Group, has decided to
retire Nov. 1, the company said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard has not said what he plans to do. He was not available
for comment Tuesday, Boeing spokeswoman Sherry Nebel said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his failure as a manager of production, Woodard is
renowned as a salesman of airplanes, and had been publicly offered
a job as vice president for sales and marketing at Boeing. But that
job would have been a demotion, forcing Woodard, 55, to report to
the man who replaced him, Alan Mulally, 53. It also would have
taken part of the job responsibility of Boeing's top-ranking woman,
Nancy Bethell, who has been on medical leave.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing observers said all along that Woodard was not likely to
take the sales job. ``I'm not surprised,'' said an analyst who
asked not to be identified. ``You've already had the fingers
pointed at you. Are you going to stick around?''
</P>
<P>
   In the four-paragraph memo marking Woodard's exit, the company
noted that he had worked in production management and international
sales, and has supported every commercial jetliner since the 707.
Woodard has been at Boeing most of his life, having joined in 1966
at age 23.
</P>
<P>
   The memo quoted Chairman Phil Condit: ``On behalf of the people
of Boeing, I want to personally express our appreciation to Ron for
his many valuable contributions over the years and wish him the
very best in his retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodard has taken the fall for his divison's huge snafus over
the past year, including shortages of parts and high levels of
overtime so bad that the production line was stopped last November.
In booking a record level of orders, salesmen had assumed that
production could keep up. It didn't, nor did the cost produce an
airplane fall by 25 percent, as had been so optimistically planned.
These miscalculations led to the loss of billions in market value
for Boeing shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Condit announced that Boeing expected sharply lower
earnings over the next two years, and made a commitment to
shareholders that profit was a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   Condit and Chief Operating Officer Harry Stonecipher followed
this in early August with a meeting with Woodard. Stonecipher and
Condit wanted to know Woodard's plan to ressurect the profit in the
commercial division.
</P>
<P>
   Several meetings followed. When a convincing plan wasn't in hand
by the end of August, the company's top officers decided to replace
Woodard and two lieutenants: Harry Arnold, executive vice president
of airplane development, and Dan Heidt, executive vice president of
airplane components.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusually blunt criticism, Stonecipher, said at the
Farnborough Airshow on Sept. 7, that the reason for Woodard's
removal ``had to do with the inability of the team to focus'' on a
way to improve profit margins ``and provide the intensity'' to show
they meant it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan to have double-digit margins out of every segment of
our business and they (Woodard's team) didn't show any signs of
getting there,'' Stonecipher said.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard has been unusually active in the community for a Boeing
executive. He is a trustee of the University of Puget Sound and is
chairman of the Seattle Symphony. He is also on the board of
Burlington Northern Santa Fe Corp. of Fort Worth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
