<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-LABOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BRITAIN'S LABOR PARTY, GRITTY MINERS ARE LOSING OUT TO
ACCOUNTANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACKPOOL, England _ Blackpool and the British Labor Party have
been as compatible as fish and chips for years, but the delegates
to this week's convention are having their last fling with the
slatternly old resort.
</P>
<P>
   In another step to shed association with its rabble-rousing
socialist past, the party that Prime Minister Tony Blair calls New
Labor is ending a 70-year-old tradition of gathering here in this
working-class playground on the Irish Sea with its floodlit Eiffel
Tower knockoff, beachfront amusement arcades and rows of prim
Victorian rooming houses with geranium pots on the windowsills.
</P>
<P>
   The years to come will find the delegates in more refined places
like Brighton and Bournemouth on the English Channel, the vacation
spots for the aspirational class wedded to small-business
capitalism and shopping mall consumerism that New Labor now courts.
</P>
<P>
   Blackpool's notoriously censorious landladies have had a lot of
tack-spitting comments to make about being tossed aside for the new
model, and they have been joined this week in denouncing the New
Labor government leaders by shunned members of the party's left
wing and the trade union movement that created old Labor nearly a
century ago.
</P>
<P>
   In his keynote address to the conference on Tuesday, Blair
acknowledged that the blush was fading from the party's symbolic
red rose but said people should not lose their nerve as the
government confronts ``tough decisions'' on the economy, welfare
and productivity in the public sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``No retreat,'' he said defiantly. ``No backing down. Backbone,
not back down, is what Britain needs.''
</P>
<P>
   With the first signs that the long honeymoon his government has
had may be coming to an end, he said, ``We would rather be popular
than unpopular, but it is better to be unpopular than wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   His speech to the Labor faithful last year was triumphal, coming
only months after the party had won the government back from the
Conservatives after 18 years out of power. Tuesday's speech took
credit for accomplishments of the last year but sounded a warning
about the future.
</P>
<P>
   He told delegates in the painted gilt Winter Gardens ballroom
that what he called ``modernizing'' moves would provoke dissidence,
and he appealed for support. ``When we bring forward proposals for
change in our welfare,'' he said, ``don't tell us it's a betrayal
of the welfare state when in truth welfare reform is its only
salvation.''
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``There will be attacks to the left of you, attacks to
the right of you, attacks from behind and in front. Welcome to
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair's personal popularity, in fact, continues high, with
approval ratings in the 60s, and his control of the party is
secure. But his having made Labor into what he called on Tuesday a
``pro-business, pro-enterprise'' party is bringing disapproval from
older party members at a time when recessionary fears are rising
and some multinational employers around Britain are shutting down
or cutting back.
</P>
<P>
   Blair on Tuesday looked out at an audience that included restive
union leaders who are increasingly questioning his government's
austerity policies, which have resulted in high interest rates,
restrained spending and low inflation. Blair reminded them that
voters had chosen ``a New Labor party not in the pocket of the
trade unions, not taxing them through the roof, not chasing after
every passing fad of the political fringe but modern, principled,
in touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks ago in the same hall, John Edmonds, president of
the Trade Unions Congress, had criticized the government for not
cracking down on big boardroom salaries with a blast more typical
of Blackpool rhetoric than Blair's reflective address.
</P>
<P>
   ``A company director who takes a pay rise of 50,000 pounds when
the rest of the work force is getting a few hundred is not part of
some general trend,'' he said, ``he is a greedy bastard.''
</P>
<P>
   The union movement contributed 77 percent of the party's budget
a decade ago but accounts for less than 40 percent now. The
membership of the Labor Party has changed dramatically, and the
people passing by the bingo parlors and vendors peddling Blackpool
rock candy sticks this week were no longer hard-bitten miners in
cloth caps, but accountants, lawyers, economists, management
consultants and businessmen, most of them dressed in dark suits
accessorized with cellular telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Even without moving out of Blackpool, the Labor Party has
already tidied up its once famously disruptive conferences. New
rules regulate what can come to the floor, and the only people to
be called on are ones who have been briefed and screened ahead of
time.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Seddon, editor of the left-wing weekly Tribune and a
successful dissident candidate for the party's national executive
committee, complained that party members were being turned into
``identikit robots.''
</P>
<P>
   The pro-business New Labor party has taken sponsorship to new
levels in British political life at this conference, with even the
tags around the neck of every delegate, visitor and journalist
bearing the logo of a supermarket chain. In a question-and-answer
meeting with delegates on Sunday, Blair was asked if this didn't
mean the party was for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I feel it's sensible to raise money from people
sponsoring things, provided they understand they get nothing in
return,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another questioner raised a favorite word from past Labor
gatherings in Blackpool and asked if its spirit weren't missing
now.
</P>
<P>
   Blair pounced. ``Real comradeship,'' he said, ``is not what used
to happen when people used to get up, call each other comrade and
then follow it with abuse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
