<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORABAMA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alabama, Florida battered for 24 hours
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GULF SHORES, Ala. _ When Gil and Sammee Dabbs retired from north
Alabama to this sparkling Gulf-side town, realtors told them
hurricanes were a minor nuisance, ``about one every 17 years,'' Gil
Dabbs said.
</P>
<P>
   Now the couple have lived through three hurricanes in the past
three years, and Sammee Dabbs isn't so sure living near the Gulf of
Mexico is all that the color brochures say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets old,'' she said, after wading through waist-deep water
to reach her home, which stands on pilings about one mile from the
beach. ``I think if we could put a for-sale sign in the front yard
right now we would, but it would just float away.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the eye of Hurricane Georges roared ashore nearly 100
miles to the west in Mississippi, the sprawling storm still
battered the Alabama and Florida Panhandle coasts with nearly 24
hours of hurricane force winds.
</P>
<P>
   Those winds kicked up mountainous breakers that tore into sea
walls, protective sand dunes, walk-overs and beach-front
structures.
</P>
<P>
   In Pensacola Beach, damage was serious but not catastrophic,
with several waterfront condominiums undermined and a few roofs
torn off homes.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said Hurricane Opal in 1995 was much worse, hitting
hundreds of homes instead of dozens, as appeared to be the case
with Georges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say our damage is half what it was with Opal,'' said Roger
Garnjobst, manager of the 36-unit Portside Villas on Fort Pickens
Road. ''We've got a couple of garage doors washed out and a few
leaks, but no roofs missing. It'll take a few weeks to scrape the
sand out of the garages, but that's not too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   A mile away at the Seahorse Condominiums, Nadine Hudson survived
Georges with only a little water blown in around her sliding glass
doors. Opal had taken out the entire bottom floor of her two-story
townhome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opal was a total devastation zone and this was nothing
compared to that,'' she said. ''I'm so happy this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Two units down, M.J. Menge, a Pensacola attorney who owns a unit
but lives on the mainland, wasn't so lucky. Georges took out his
bottom floor, caved in one wall and left his cement slab cracked in
half, with waves crashing underneath where all the sand was washed
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``This storm hit at Biloxi but did this much damage here,'' he
said. ``I think it wreaked more havoc over a larger area than
Opal.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty miles to the west in Gulf Shores, the damage appeared much
more severe than in Pensacola Beach. National Guard units patrolled
the beachfront area, and police were stopping all cars at a
check-point and allowing only residents to go through.
</P>
<P>
   Water from the bayou that lies inland from the beach area was
flooding into several residential streets and lapping over Ala. 59
in places.
</P>
<P>
   On the beach, all the waterfront properties appeared to take
heavy damage to their parking lots and ground-level structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really it's not that bad because none of my units are damaged
inside,'' said Pam Sharp, manager of the 48-unit Regatta
Condominiums. ''But you can see the parking lot is undermined and
that will have to be rebuilt.''
</P>
<P>
   The building suffered minor damage during Hurricane Opal, Sharp
said, and she had that repaired within 10 days. Rebuilding the
parking lot will likely take several months, she predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to have it done in time for the Shrimp Festival, but
I don't think that's possible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gulf Shores winds up its annual summer season each year with a
big Shrimp Festival, featuring live music, food and other
attractions. The event is always held the second weekend in
October, but it was unclear whether the clean-up would be far
enough along to allow this year's event.
</P>
<P>
   As bad as Georges was, many residents said it didn't compare to
Frederic, which devastated Gulf Shores in 1979, washing away
buildings and leaving a rebuilding job that took months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a big clean-up, but it's nowhere near as bad as
Frederic,'' Sharp said. Georges' biggest impact appeared to be on
the beach itself, with the terrible pounding by hour after hour of
giant surf eating away the sand dunes.
</P>
<P>
   Waves on Tuesday were lapping at seawalls, and in places had
undermined the foundations of buildings. A small beach may
re-appear after the stormy surf kicked up by Georges finally
abates, but many residents said it won't be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had Opal three years ago and Hurricane Danny last year and
now this,'' Gandy said. ''I was driving down here hoping the damage
would just be moderate and cosmetic, but it's worse than I thought.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
