<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-WAKEFIELD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAKEFIELD OUT TO PIRATE WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The last time Tim Wakefield took the mound in a
postseason game, he was unable to prevent the Red Sox from being
eliminated by the Cleveland Indians in a 1995 three-game Division
Series sweep. Wakefield gave up seven runs in 5 1/3 innings on a
murky night in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But there are brighter postseason memories that Wakefield can
draw upon as well. In 1992, when he was just two months removed
from the minor leagues, Wakefield twice beat the mighty Atlanta
Braves for Pittsburgh, nearly enabling the Pirates to beat the
defending champions in the National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   `In '92, I was a rookie with two months' experience and I tried
to treat it as another game, not get caught up in the media
hoopla,'' said the Red Sox knuckleballer, who will start Game 2
against the Indians this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that experience will help me overcome the little
anxiety I'm going to feel (Wednesday). It was a wonderful feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I like this team better than the team we had in '95. The
pitching staff is a lot deeper, the offense is a lot better, and
the defense is definitely a lot better. I really like our
chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield said he had ``no input'' in manager Jimy Williams's
decision to start rookie catcher Jason Varitek today instead of
Scott Hatteberg. ``I'm very comfortable with both catchers,'' he
said. ``That was a decision they made. Jason's done a great job
with me. So has Hatteberg.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg was hitless in six at-bats against Indians starter Doc
Gooden this season. Varitek has never faced him.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek has caught 17 of Wakefield's starts, Hatteberg 16, and
both catchers have been behind the plate for 108 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield's ERA with Hatteberg is 5.00, and the catcher has
thrown out 3 of 15 runners attempting to steal. Varitek threw out 5
of 17 would-be base stealers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0980 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGES-MAIN30-COX     09-29 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGES-MAIN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Twisters rip through Georgia
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The storm formerly known as Georges is not dying
quietly, as Richard Lynch found out Tuesday when a tornado spun off
in South Georgia nearly sucked him out of his pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch, 38, was driving east on Ga. 37 toward Camilla in Mitchell
County when large tree limbs began hitting his truck.
</P>
<P>
   After he saw the wind push another pickup down a 6-foot
embankment, Lynch drove into the ditch, hoping to get under the
twister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lay across the front seat and locked my legs on the back
side of the steering wheel and held onto the door,'' he said. ``The
wind was trying to pick the truck up. It sucked out the windshield
and even took my windshield wipers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitchell County tornado was one of a series of small but
violent twisters reported in southwest and central Georgia, spawned
by the remains of Hurricane Georges.
</P>
<P>
   A tornado watch posted in 54 counties in southwest and central
Georgia remained in effect at least until 8 p.m. Tuesday, along
with a flash flood watch.
</P>
<P>
   Georges, now a tropical depression, could depress baseball fans
eager to see the Braves take on the Chicago Cubs and home-run
hurricane Sammy Sosa this afternoon and Thursday night. The
National Weather Service predicts a 60 percent chance of rain
today, tapering to about 40 percent by the 4:15 game time.
</P>
<P>
   In areas of the state hit by damaging floods in recent years,
low river levels may help spare them from another round of
storm-driven disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But if the rain keeps up, Georgia's $400 million peanut crop,
now nearing peak harvest, could be severely damaged, said John
Baldwin, peanut specialist with the University of Georgia's
agricultural extension station in Tifton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a good feeling right now,'' Baldwin said.
``Harvest is at a standstill, and if we have heavy, sustained
rains, we could lose the bulk of the crop. The worst thing that can
happen is bad weather at harvest time.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia cotton growers, with 1.3 million acres nearing harvest,
feared rain would damage the $600 million to $700 million crop.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
