<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia average in using computers for eduational uses
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia, like most other states, has been investing
heavily in computer technology and training in the public schools,
but has not always focused that investment in the best ways to
improve student learning, according to an in-depth national study
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   By most of the measures used by the newspaper, Education Week,
for the report, ``Technology Counts '98,'' Georgia is at about the
national average or better than average in putting computers to use
in classrooms. But Georgia and the nation as a whole must now face
questions of what it is trying to accomplish with this expensive
enthusiasm and whether those goals are being met.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to get a critical mass of computers,'' said
Cheryl Lemke, director of the Milken Exchange on Education
Technology, which funded the study. ``The real question is, `How is
it going to be used?'''
</P>
<P>
   On that question, the study found the best use of technology for
raising student achievement allows students to interact dynamically
with information and each other, rather than drill-and-practice.
For example, a dynamic approach for fourth-graders would be math
games and other learning games. In eighth grade, examples were
simulations.
</P>
<P>
   By those measures, Georgia was somewhat below the national
average. Among the state's fourth-graders, 42 percent had teachers
who reported using computers for math games and learning games,
compared with a national average of 54 percent. Among the state's
eighth-graders, 19 percent had teachers who reported using
computers mainly for simulations and applications, compared with a
national average of 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The report's analysis also connects the type of computer
instruction used with student achievement. Georgia's fourth-graders
and eighth-graders both scored below the national average in math,
according to the 1996 National Assessment of Educational Progress,
a scientifically respected measure of student achievement. Low
scores reflect the lower use of dynamic teaching methods, the
report says.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's 13 technology instruction centers train teachers in
techniques that put students more in charge of their own learning
rather than having them sit through traditional lectures. This
approach, taught over seven days, is ``all about changing the way
you teach to a more student-centered approach,'' said Michael
Murray, director of the training center at Kennesaw State
University.
</P>
<P>
   After training about 400 teachers in the pilot phase, the
program was launched last October and has trained about 2 or 3
percent of the state's teachers.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Education Week report, Georgia is following
seven of nine recommendations put forward for state policy-makers,
including technology requirements for accreditation of education
colleges and technology standards in its curriculum. Among the two
recommendations not followed fully, the state doesn't mandate
existing school buildings undergo changes to accommodate technology
and does not address inequities between rich and poor districts,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Wenglinksy, the report's research scientist, said
nationwide, suburban districts are much more likely to have more
technology resources, and Georgia shows the same tendency. In
Forsyth County, for example, every classroom has a telephone with
voice mail, a TV, a VCR and a teacher who gets at least 10 hours of
technology training every year.
</P>
<P>
   At South Forsyth High, funds were raised privately to help stock
three multimedia classrooms. ``I get almost whatever I ask for,''
said Principal Brenda Colby of her district's commitment to
technology.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, 250 teachers are on the waiting list for 10 hours of
computer training and a computer at Tech Corps Georgia, a private
nonprofit agency, said Tip Kilby, the director. Kilby, whose agency
is supported by NationsBank, Home Depot and other coorporations,
said Atlanta teachers too often lack useful classroom computers to
put into practice the training the district provides away from the
classroom. The agency sends each teacher away with a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
