<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FED LOWERS INTEREST RATES TO EASE EFFECTS OF TURMOIL
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve cut interest rates by a quarter of a
percentage point in an attempt to keep the financial turmoil
afflicting much of the world from derailing growth at home. The
Fed's reduction of the main short-term rate it controls, to 5.25
percent from 5.5 percent, also signaled the central bank's
deepening concern about the economy's prospects. It was the first
time the Fed has cut rates since January 1996, and the first change
in rates since March 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Lower borrowing rates on many consumer loans are expected as a
result of the rate reduction. Economists said mortgage rates for
home purchases and refinancings should remain below 7 percent
through 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Shaken by global economic and political turmoil, Americans'
confidence in the U.S. economy fell in September for a third
consecutive month.
</P>
<P>
   MIXED MARKET RESPONSE TO RATE CUT
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street was not impressed with the Fed's rate reduction, and
the major market indexes were narrowly mixed at the end of an
active session. The Dow Jones industrial average fell almost 100
points after the reduction was announced but rebounded somewhat to
close down 28.32 points at 8,080.52. Investors in the bond market
had a somewhat more positive reaction and drove up prices, pushing
the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond down to 5.09 percent,
another 30-year low.
</P>
<P>
   PRETRIAL MICROSOFT SKIRMISHING
</P>
<P>
   The judge presiding over Microsoft's antitrust case ordered
Oracle to surrender to the software company documents concerning
agreements Oracle has with Apple, IBM and other companies. The
order marked a victory for Microsoft in pretrial maneuverings. But
Microsoft is encountering trouble in efforts to subpoena materials
from Harvard and MIT used for a book about Netscape, Microsoft's
rival in Internet browsing software.
</P>
<P>
   CENDANT REPORTS BIG LOSS
</P>
<P>
   Cendant, a marketer and franchiser that plunged in share value
after it disclosed accounting irregularities, said it lost $217.2
million last year, instead of earning $55.5 million as reported
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA RESTRICTS CURRENCY DEALINGS
</P>
<P>
   China has imposed tough restrictions on foreign-exchange
transactions, the latest sign of backtracking on a range of finance
and trade issues that seem to reflect a slowdown in the nation's
efforts to shift from a planned to a market economy. Wu Xiaoling,
director general of the State Administration of Foreign Exchange,
justified the restrictions by saying untold billions of dollars had
been improperly transferred overseas this year.
</P>
<P>
   AMR SELLING SOME BUSINESSES
</P>
<P>
   AMR, parent of American Airlines, said it would sell a corporate
jet services business and two other units as part of a plan to
focus on core operations. The businesses, which make up AMR's
Global Services division, employ 13,600 people and generate about
$450 million in annual revenues for the company.
</P>
<P>
   REORGANIZATION AT BELL ATLANTIC
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, the largest United States local phone company,
said it would create a new office of the chairman and restructure
into six business units, each with its own president, to adjust for
rapid changes in the communications marketplace. The company
operates 41 million telephone lines and has more than 7 million
wireless customers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   BROADWAY PRODUCER FIGHTS SUIT
</P>
<P>
   Livent, the Broadway theater producer, is arguing in a Canadian
court that a lawsuit filed by its founder threatens to prolong the
pain of the company's shareholders, who have been unable to trade
their shares since early August because of an accounting
investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
