<SLUG> BC-INTEREST-MARKETPLACE-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: RESPONSE TO THE FED'S RATE CUT PROVES SOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also FED, FED-CONSUMERS, MARKET) 
(lb) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Board cut interest rates Tuesday. Almost
nobody cheered.
</P>
<P>
   To stock investors, the rate cut _ of a quarter-point in a key
short-term rate _ was too timid. They pushed the Dow Jones
industrial average down 28.32 points.
</P>
<P>
   To bond traders, the cut signaled that they, more than the Fed,
remained in charge of interest-rate policy. And that means
continued high Treasury prices and more flatness in the yield
curve, in which long-term rates are as low as or lower than
short-term rates.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the rate cut by the Fed was considered far better
than no action at all. And further cuts may come later this year.
But bond traders who thought a one-quarter point decline might
finally brake the runaway-train Treasury market were disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond fell to
another new low, 5.09 percent. The 10-year note closed at a yield
of 4.58 percent, well below the new federal funds rate, which is
how much banks charge each other for overnight borrowing, and just
off its lows last Friday of 4.56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This is bad news for the traders and speculators that have sold
Treasuries short in recent months in the belief that yields on the
30-year would never approach 5 percent. These include the trading
desks at major brokerage firms and the large hedge funds like
Long-Term Capital Management, the giant fund that almost failed
last week and is now being run by its creditors. For these
unfortunates, the Federal Reserve's rate reduction provides no
relief.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the historic move down in Treasury yields in recent
months is more about speculation in that market than it is about
the policy of the Federal Reserve Board. What began this summer as
a concerted investor flight from risky securities to the safest,
most liquid market in the world is suffering from what feels like a
short squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   Not an orchestrated short squeeze like the one traders put on at
Salomon Brothers in 1991 when they tried to corner the market.
Today's squeeze, in which investors who have sold Treasury
securities they do not own and are therefore hurt whenever the
prices of those issues rise, has been created by professional
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these speculators had bought fixed-income securities
that carried higher yields than Treasuries _ junk bonds,
convertible bonds, mortgage-backed securities _ and hedged those
positions by selling short Treasuries with similar maturities and
lower yields.
</P>
<P>
   Such a trade produced terrific profits for traders and money
managers for the last five years or so. Typically, the yields on
the instruments move in tandem, but this summer they diverged,
leading to losses in both positions. Now these investors are
scrambling to cover their disastrous gambles. And in so doing, they
are pushing Treasury prices even higher.
</P>
<P>
   Combine this with a dearth of new Treasury issues _ the next
government refunding isn't until November _ and it looks as if
Treasury prices will continue to trade at extraordinarily high
levels relative to the Fed funds rate.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp declines in Treasury yields reinforce that the bond
market, not the Federal Reserve, is driving interest-rate policy.
Whereas in the 30 years leading up to 1990, Fed policy led the bond
market in raising or pushing down rates, during this decade the
bond market has been first to the punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the Fed had done nothing since the Asian crisis
first emerged, the bond market has been easing long-term yields
since last fall,'' said Jim Paulsen, chief investment officer at
Norwest Investment Management Inc. in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   A bond market that eases before the Fed produces a different,
more subtle effect from a Fed ease, according to Paulsen. When the
bond market lowers rates, for example, it has good effects on
mortgage rates, which help consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But its effects on banks' profits are more deleterious. With
short-term rates higher than long-term rates, as is the case now,
banks cannot make as much money on their loans as they could if the
Fed funds rate were below longer-term rates. That's why bank shares
weakened Tuesday, even after the rate cut. Citicorp was down 3
percent to $97.75, NationsBank Corp. lost 2.6 percent and
BankAmerica fell 2 percent to $62.25.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sometimes subtlety is not enough. When real trouble is brewing,
as has been the case since the summer of 1997 in Asia, bond traders
acting ahead of the Fed can mask some of the peril. This can, in
turn, encourage continued passivity from the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the bond market acted like it did in the 1970s and 1980s,
there would be no movement until the Fed eased, and the full weight
of the crisis would be evident,'' said Paulsen. ``Now it's masked
and allows for a policy mistake.'' That mistake? Too little a move
by the Fed and too late.
</P>
<P>
   When the Fed cuts rates ahead of the bond market, as was typical
in past decades, both borrowers and lenders get a big break. This
stimulates the economy much more than if only one of the two groups
benefits. Many economists argue that the double whammy is needed
now, given the severity of the crisis roiling economies around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   But abrupt changes in monetary policy by the Fed have also led
to the four-year booms and busts that have characterized the U.S.
economy in the postwar years. Letting the bond market adjust policy
incrementally has resulted in greater economic stability and
smoother cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe that the bond market's control over
interest rates will last as long as Greenspan does as chairman of
the Fed. One reason is his unceasing fear of inflation, which has
kept him from lowering rates until now.
</P>
<P>
   And having presided over the longest period of economic
prosperity in postwar history, Greenspan has come to appreciate the
stabilizing effects of a more passive approach to policy. The only
question is whether today's perilous circumstances require more
from the Fed than it is willing to give.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
