<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMPANT MENTAL HEALTH CARE FRAUD IN MEDICARE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Texas, Ala., La., Tenn., Ark., Ga., S.C., Miss.)   By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal officials said Tuesday that they were
expelling 80 mental health centers from Medicare after finding that
the program to provide psychiatric services to the elderly was
riddled with fraud.
</P>
<P>
   June Gibbs Brown, inspector general of the Department of Health
and Human Services, said that the cost of such care soared to $349
million in 1997, from $60 million in 1993, and that she found that
91 percent of the payments last year were for ``unallowable and
highly questionable services.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, she said, Medicare payments to community mental health
centers averaged $10,352 a patient last year, up from $1,642 in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the centers are profit-making entities that have found a
lucrative niche in the program, Medicare officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Shalala, the secretary of health and human services, said,
``The Health Care Financing Administration and the inspector
general have found extensive evidence of providers who are not
qualified, patients who are ineligible, and services billed to
Medicare that are not appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The department said it was immediately expelling 20 community
health centers in Florida, Texas and Louisiana. Sixty more centers
in those and other states will be expelled in the next few months,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The 80 centers account for 7 percent of the 1,150 mental health
centers that participate in Medicare. Many were billing Medicare
for ``services that weren't covered, weren't provided or weren't
needed,'' Shalala said. In addition, she said, many centers failed
to provide even the basic services they had promised.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's action comes six days before a congressional hearing
at which the inspector general was to disclose her findings.
</P>
<P>
   In a report on her investigation, Ms. Brown, the inspector
general, says: ``Medicare was paying for therapy sessions that
involved only recreational and diversionary activities such as
drawing, arts and crafts, watching television, and playing bingo
and other games. In a program designed to pay for intensive
outpatient psychiatric services provided to acutely ill individuals
in order to prevent their hospitalization, Medicare was paying for
services to beneficiaries who had no history of mental illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy-Ann Min DeParle, administrator of the Medicare agency,
said she suspected that some doctors were getting kickbacks for
sending patients to community mental health centers. She said the
government would intensify its scrutiny of hospitals that provide
outpatient mental health services to see if they too were abusing
the program.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeParle said that nine states accounted for 85 percent of
all Medicare spending on community mental health centers. The
states are Florida, Texas, Alabama, Louisiana, Tennessee, Georgia,
Mississippi, Arkansas and South Carolina. ``Health care
entrepreneurs seem to be alive and well in the South,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   New York, New Jersey and Connecticut have relatively small
numbers of community mental health centers in Medicare (13, 39 and
7, respectively). So far officials have found no particular
problems in those states.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Barton, R-Texas, who is chairman of the Commerce
subcommittee on investigations, which will hold the hearing on
Monday, said, ``It's inexcusable to have such rapid growth in
costs, and doubly inexcusable to have such a high rate of waste and
fraud.'' In an interview, he said Congress would consider
tightening Medicare standards for mental health centers.
</P>
<P>
   Pope Simmons, vice president of the National Council for
Community Behavioral Health Care, which represents 750 mental
health centers, said he supported the federal crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Community mental health centers have been allowed to bill
Medicare for intensive outpatient services since 1990, but there's
a loophole in the law,'' Simmons said. ``All these companies had to
do was to fill out a form attesting that they were community mental
health centers. In states like Florida and Texas, this allowed a
lot of storefront operations to bill Medicare without providing
appropriate services.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown said, ``The self-attestation process permitted
unscrupulous providers to participate in Medicare.'' Moreover, she
said, feer than one-third of the states set licensing requirements
for community mental health centers.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Covall, executive director of the National Association of
Psychiatric Health Systems, said the federal government should set
national standards and require state licensing of community mental
health centers, as it does for other health care providers in
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said they would examine new applicants more
closely. So far this year they have rejected more than 100
applications from mental health centers that do not provide the
required services.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeParle said psychiatrists had helped set up centers after
finding that this was ``a good business to be getting into all of a
sudden.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
