<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-BOSOX-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX ROUT INDIANS, 11-3, AND EXORCISE A FEW DEMONS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to correct byline, Chris sted Ed Broussard)   By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The talk was of curses and ghosts and failures.
Names like Babe Ruth and Bill Buckner were mentioned. All the
Boston Red Sox heard about was doom as they prepared for their
American League division series with the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday at Jacobs Field, the Red Sox averted history as well
as they averted the badgering about their prior postseason
problems. Slamming three Indians pitchers out of their home ball
park, Boston defeated Cleveland 11-3 in Game 1 to take control of
this best-of-five series.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the robust swing of Mo Vaughn, who used his bat to
exorcise personal as well as franchise demons, the Red Sox won
their first postseason game since beating the Mets in Game 5 of the
World Series on Oct. 23, 1986. After losing the final two games of
that series _ Game 6 largely because of Buckner's infamous error at
first base _ Boston was swept in three consecutive series, a string
of 13 games that kept prattle about the Curse of the Bambino alive.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, weary of the media's constant history lessons, did his
part to end them as quickly as possible, smashing a Jaret Wright
fastball an estimated 376 feet into the left-field bleachers to
drive in Darren Lewis and John Valentin in the top of the first
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The opposite-field home run came on a full count, put the Red
Sox up 3-0 and ended Vaughn's 0-for-14 playoff slump, one that
occurred while Boston was being swept in three games by Cleveland
in 1995. Despite turning stone cold that October, Vaughn won the
American League's Most Valuable Player award. A strong MVP
candidate again this year, there will be no postseason crumble to
sully his achievement should he win it for a second time.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the home run that allowed Boston pitcher Pedro
Martinez to take the mound with a three-run cushion in his first
career playoff game, Vaughn smacked a two-run homer in the sixth
and a two-run double in the eighth to equal Edgar Martinez's major
league single-game playoff record of seven RBI, set in 1995 against
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted an opportunity to get here again,'' said Vaughn,
who called himself mentally unprepared for the 1995 playoffs. ``I
knew I was going to have a better approach to the situation. I'm a
bit older now and I'm more experienced. We had gone 13 games
without a playoff win and we handled that and for me to get off
that 0-for-14 is definitely nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Vaughn's mammoth performance made him the star, the Red
Sox, who will meet the Indians in Game 2 Wednesday afternoon,
rolled because of a team effort. Boston hitters ripped Wright, last
year's rookie sensation who went 3-0 in the postseason, for seven
hits and six earned runs in 4 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   While Wright regrouped after Vaughn's blast to strike out six
batters, Nomar Garciaparra dealt him the death blow in the fifth.
Immediately after Wright struck out Vaughn with two men on base,
the power-hitting shortstop belted one over the left-field wall to
put the Red Sox up 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two bad pitches and six runs, first inning and fifth,''
Indians manager Mike Hargrove said of Wright. ``He just was really
inconsistent and got the ball up.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything but inconsistent, Wright's counterpart, Martinez,
dominated Cleveland's batters until tiring in the sixth. Deftly
mixing curve balls and changeups with his 95 mile-per-hour
fastball, he recorded seven of his eight strikeouts and allowed
just one of his six hits in the first five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Lofton homered after a Sandy Alomar double in the sixth,
and then Jim Thome hit a solo shot in the seventh, but with
Boston's hitters pouncing on relievers Doug Jones and Steve Reed,
it was not enough. Martinez, who dominated Cleveland in the regular
season, exited after seven with his third victory in four starts
this year against the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time around the order, he threw predominantly
fastballs and an occasional changeup,'' Hargrove said. ``The second
time around, he threw a lot of changeups and still threw his
fastball. The third time around he mixed in his breaking ball. His
velocity was good.''
</P>
<P>
   There won't be much velocity on the ball Wednesday when the
Indians face knuckleballer Tim Wakefield (17-8, 4.58 ERA). With his
65 mile-per-hour pitches, Wakefield will give Cleveland a totally
different look, one that earned him two wins and a loss in four
starts against the Indians this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A knuckleball is the toughest pitch that a hitter will ever
have to hit,'' Hargrove said. ``I don't say that lightly. When a
knuckleball pitcher is on his game that day, the other team is in
for a long afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   While Boston started anew in destroying its playoff-game jinx,
Cleveland maintained a dubious postseason streak by losing its
seventh straight series opener. The Indians, however, have overcome
to win three of those series, including two which got them into the
World Series. So with Tuesday's victory, Boston, well aware that
this series is far from over, will have to settle for putting
another opponent to rest _ the playoff ghost of Red Sox past.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
