<SLUG> BC-BBA-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERMAN, KNIGHT TALK A GOOD GAME ON ESPN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESPN's Chris Berman set up Tuesday's Division Series opener
between the Red Sox and Cleveland Indians as a game between ``two
cursed teams'' _ one cursed by Babe Ruth, the other by Rocky
Calavito _ trying to ``once and for all get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox got it right, as did Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Before his record-tying seven-RBI performance punctuated by two
home runs, Vaughn told ESPN that he didn't want to hear about
curses and the netherworld.
</P>
<P>
   The Curse of the Bambino, he said, ``ain't got nothing to do
with us.''
</P>
<P>
   So there.
</P>
<P>
   Berman was even more prescient during his pregame analysis.
``This isn't your father's Red Sox anymore,'' he said. ``This isn't
your grandfather's Red Sox anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyperbole or not, say this about Berman. He is a fan of the
game, and though he has the ability to talk for three hours
nonstop, Boomer tells the truth. He gets excited. He understands
and respects the history of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point _ his peppering of details throughout the
broadcast. Dennis Eckersely is one of his favorite pitchers. He
told the uninitiated that Eckersley had pitched for the Red Sox
before being traded to the Cubs for, of all people, Bill Buckner.
``The rest, as they say, is history,'' Berman said.
</P>
<P>
   OK. OK. Most in Massachusetts know about that infamous trade.
But for those outside state lines, the detail was interesting. All
right, so it wasn't a particularly difficult piece of trivia to
uncover.
</P>
<P>
   Berman was better calling the game.
</P>
<P>
   When Cleveland pitcher Jaret Wright threw apparent strikes that
were called balls, Berman refrained from blasting the umpire. ``He
has a better angle than me,'' Berman demurred.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't hesitate to criticize players. In the second
inning, Indians right fielder Manny Ramirez hit a 400-foot shot off
the center-field wall. Instead of sprinting around the bases,
Ramirez went into his home run trot, and by the time he hit full
stride, it was too late to get the double it should have been.
Berman called it the ``longest single'' in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   He also called it ``inexcusable.''
</P>
<P>
   The next thing you knew, Ramirez was doubled off first base
after a line shot to third baseman John Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Ramirez had been on second base, that never would have
happened,'' Berman said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Ray Knight was just as solid as Berman. He criticized
Wright throughout the game, emphasizing that the righthander must
develop a third pitch to go along with his fastball and curve.
``Everything is hard,'' Knight said. ``Even his changeup comes in
at 85 miles per hour. Wright needs to put something else in
hitters' minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight also decoded Indians signals by catcher Sandy Alomar. The
ESPN camera crew caught Alomar flashing Wright his index finger
three times near his thigh at the outside of the plate. ``It's a
sinker, down and away,'' Knight said. The next time, Alomar flashed
Wright one finger on his inside thigh. ``Fastball, inside,'' Knight
said. He was correct both times.
</P>
<P>
   Knight provided the extra insight former players must have to
inform viewers. When Alomar faced Pedro Martinez for the first
time, he fell behind in the count, 0-and-2.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's next pitch was a high fastball that struck out
Alomar. ``That is right out of the scouting report,'' Knight said.
``When Alomar is behind by two strikes, he tends to swing at
anything high.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight was particularly insightful on beanballs. In the fourth
inning, Darren Lewis got beaned on the left earflap. ``Those will
give you a buzz for a couple of minutes,'' Knight said. ``You are
woozy for a while, but it usually clears up pretty quickly. Now I
was hit once in the face. That takes about three months to clear
up.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN is blessed. Berman and Knight called an outstanding game,
and while they are not Ned Martin and Jim Woods in their prime,
they are the cable network's No. 2 announcing team.
</P>
</TEXT>
