<SLUG> BC-OPRAH-MONICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPRAH WINFREY CALLS OFF LEWINSKY INTERVIEW TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Negotiations over the rights to Monica Lewinsky's account of her
relationship with President Clinton took an unusual turn Tuesday
when Oprah Winfrey announced on her television show and in a press
release that she would not pursue an interview with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I no longer want the interview,'' the talk show host said in
her statement. ``I was told that I did have it and then the
conversation moved in a direction that I did not want to go. I do
not pay for interviews, no matter what the payment is called.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Winfrey, elaborating in an interview to be published next
Monday in TV Guide, said Ms. Lewinsky's representatives had
promised her the first interview, but then had phoned back to
demand the ``international rights'' to the tape, which they could
then sell.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Smith, Ms. Lewinsky's representative, said neither she nor
Ms. Lewinsky would comment on Ms. Winfrey's statements.
</P>
<P>
   The report that Ms. Winfrey had been considered a sure bet to
conduct the first television interview with Ms. Lewinsky was one of
the more believable ones generated by the Lewinsky rumor mill,
which has churned out some wildly inflated stories in the last few
weeks. Among them are rumors that Ms. Lewinsky has a $16 million
contract with a pay-per-view company to tell her story and that she
has a modeling deal with a Parisian fashion designer who has
occasionally used condoms as clothing decoration.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Walters of ABC News has also been pursuing an interview
with Ms. Lewinsky, say people at ABC News who insisted on
anonymity. There has even been a rumor that Ms. Walters might do
the interview for the ABC entertainment division, which, unlike the
news division, might be permitted to pay Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But Eileen Murphy, the chief spokeswoman for ABC News, said
Tuesday, ``We will not pay Monica Lewinsky any money for an
interview, whether it was for a news interview or an entertainment
interview.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's representatives have tried to play one suitor
against another, one person who has negotiated with them said
Tuesday, adding, ``The greed has backfired. Her 15 minutes is
fading fast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
