<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-ANWAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COURT, OUSTED MALAYSIAN DENIES SEX AND GRAFT CHARGES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ Visibly bruised and asserting that he
had been beaten by his jailers, Malaysia's ousted deputy prime
minister, Anwar Ibrahim, denied in court on Tuesday charges of
corruption and sexual misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not guilty!'' he declared as each of the nine charges was read
out. He pointed to bruises above his left eye and on his neck and
rolled up his shirt sleeves to display more bruises, witnesses in
the courtroom said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Anwar's first public appearance since he was arrested
nine days ago in a political confrontation with his former mentor,
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, 72, that convulsed the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of riot policemen surrounded the courthouse on Tuesday
and the streets were quiet after more than a week of demonstrations
in support of Anwar that resulted in hundreds of arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar, 51, was dismissed from the government at the start of
this month in what Mahathir apparently intended as a quick and
definitive political coup against a too-ambitious underling.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the dismissal has become the country's most severe
political crisis in decades and the broadest public challenge to
Mahathir's 17-year tenure as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   In rallies at Anwar's home, outside the courthouse, in public
parks and in mosques, support seems only to have grown for the man
who had been expected to become Malaysia's next leader.
</P>
<P>
   After being held incommunicado since his arrest, Anwar was
allowed to speak out in court on Tuesday, and he took full
advantage of his public platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was blindfolded and handcuffed,'' he told the court. ``I was
boxed very hard on my lower jaw and left eye. I was also boxed on
the right of my head and they hit me on the left side of my neck
very hard. I was then slapped very hard left and right until blood
came out from my nose and my lips cracked. Because of this, I could
not see and walk properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's wife, Wan Azizah Wan Ismail, who is an ophthalmologist,
was allowed to talk to him in the courtroom, and she said she was
``shocked and stunned that my husband was a victim of police
brutality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an orbital hematoma on the left eye,'' she said,
``and a small depression on the left forehead, about half an inch.
His vision was slightly impaired and he complained about his
balance being affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Although only a small number of people could fit into the
courtroom, and although the local press has been reporting only the
government's version of events, an underground network has kept the
capital abuzz with reports and rumors about Anwar.
</P>
<P>
   Lim Kit Siang, leader of Malaysia's main opposition party, the
Democratic Action Party, told reporters on Tuesday: ``All
Malaysians are asking one common question: How could they be safe
when the former deputy prime minister could be so brutally beaten
up when in police custody?''
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the charges against Anwar revolve around the
government's contention that he engaged in illegal homosexual
relations with four men.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Malaysia, we reject such extreme acts,'' Mahathir said on
Friday. ``We accept men as men and women as women.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, he said he had interviewed the men and women who said
they had had illicit sex with Anwar. He said it was this, and not
differences over policy, that caused him to dismiss his deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Parliament on Tuesday, Mahathir said that because of
those charges, Anwar had been in a hurry to replace him as prime
minister. ``Anwar's wish was for me to step down so that he would
get away without being tried,'' the prime minister asserted.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar has vigorously denied the accusations and called them an
attempt to smear him and end his political career. Many Malaysians,
interviewed around the city, including some who support Mahathir,
have also expressed skepticism about the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar was charged on Tuesday with four counts of ``unnatural''
sex acts, which could result in a prison term of up to 20 years. He
was also charged with five counts of corruption, which could bring
a maximum penalty of 14 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the five charges of corruption involve allegations that
Anwar had tried to have witnesses deny the sexual charges. The
fifth corruption charge involved an allegation that he had tried to
influence an investigation into corruption by an aide. The charges
of sexual misconduct are apparently based in part on the
confessions of two of Anwar's close associates, who said they had
allowed him to sodomize them. Both men were sentenced to six months
in prison the day before Anwar was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar said that their confessions had been extracted by physical
and psychological torture. And on Tuesday, Reuters reported that
the two men were now retracting their confessions and appealing
their convictions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
