<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0989 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-ADVANCE-CO     09-29 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Post-Wood wasn't good for Smoltz
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Smoltz, accordion prodigy, scratch golfer,
card-game braggart and one of the more stubborn beings walking this
planet, had simply had it. Turner Field had filled that May 23
evening to see Smoltz go after Chicago man-child Kerry Wood, and
just two innings into it, the kid was humming and Smoltz had spit
the bit _ two runs, six hits, including an RBI single to Wood.
</P>
<P>
   That, plus Smoltz's right elbow, already as delicate as a
Christmas ornament, was throbbing. In an act of mercy, Bobby Cox
pulled him, Smoltz walking off the field, down the dugout stairs,
and who knew where after that?
</P>
<P>
   ``They all came to see this new phenom and I wanted to be up to
the task,'' Smoltz said. ``I didn't think I was going to be up to
the task, and it showed really quickly. I knew walking off the
field that I was going to have to back off for a while, go back on
the DL, take some time off, and I didn't know about the immediate
future.''
</P>
<P>
   What future? Two elbow surgeries; 2,000 innings-plus already on
the odometer; trade rumors whispered just last winter, before
doctors gouged more excess calcium out of his elbow. And now a
second shutdown on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at a low. The frustration level was beyond _ I was ready
to quit. I'd never in my life thought about retiring until this
year, about when it was going to be. And I can't lie about it. I
was thinking about finishing up (the contract), and that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   The same Cubs are at The Ted tonight, where they will find a
radically altered Smoltz in Game 1 of National League Division
Series. Since that May night, he has gone 13-2 with a 2.49 ERA,
finishing the year with more strikeouts (132) than hits allowed
(99) in those final 123 innings. He has taken cortisone injections
to the elbow and his back, has had his elbow drained three times
and, through the final month, decided to cancel his next start six
times, only to reverse himself.
</P>
<P>
   At age 31, he became a better pitcher, throwing an effective
change-up for the first time in his career, finishing with a
markedly better strikeout ratio (9.3 per nine innings) than over
the previous nine major-league seasons (7.7). He finished the year
ranked in the top six in five NL pitching lists (including No. 1 in
winning percentage at 17-3. With one more victory tonight, he
replaces Whitey Ford and Dave Stewart for more postseason wins in
history (11).
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have made more wins if he could have made more starts
(than 26),'' catcher Javy Lopez said. ``With the surgery and
eveything, there's no doubt he would have had another Cy Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I always felt he was a heck of a lot more of a pitcher
than people gave him credit for,'' said Tom Glavine, a partner of
Smoltz in Atlanta's rotation since 1988. ``Everyone just assumed he
was just a thrower and, 'Here's my great stuff. I'm going to get
you out.' But I think he proved to people this year he's more of a
pitcher than they gave him credit for.''
</P>
<P>
   Only from necessity. Smoltz had to reform himself. First, he
shelved his split-fingered fastball, for the extra stress he puts
on the arm, and began using it again only in his last start. He
began reworking his breaking pitches, sometimes without a lot of
public notice. Lopez sat down next to him during an August start
and asked what the new pitch was that Smoltz had just thrown him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my 'slow' curve,'' Smoltz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks for tell me that,'' Lopez replied.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, his strikeout frequency stayed high, he walked
just 25 men in his last 19 starts, and he kept his slider out of
the dirt. All of that meant better efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might have helped his location,'' Greg Maddux said. ``I
know when you're arm is bothering you, you want to make the fewest
pitches possible. You don't throw the waste pitch, when you're
hoping he'll swing or chase. You're not throwing set-up pitches.
You're tying to get him out with every pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The change-up changed that too. Smoltz had never veered from the
power game the 95 mph fastball, a hard splider, a harder split and
then a big curve coming as close he would get to off-speed. He
experimented with the change-up grips used by the rest of the staff
until finding his own, finally found the right arm-speed, and, even
then after the All-Star break, he wasn't so sure until perhaps this
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two outings in particular,'' shortstop Walt Weiss
said, ``I saw him being more effective with it. Guys were swinging
through it a lot, out in front of it, because he's such a power
pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I threw was hard, hard, hard,'' Smoltz said. ``When
I'm on, it looks good. When you're not, it's tough. So I've been
able to slow the batter down now. It increases my control. It
increases my chances to throw less pitches and my efficiency is
better.''
</P>
<P>
   So, why had not Smoltz, who underwent his first elbow
arthroscopy in 1994, worked in this direction before this summer,
when he was driven to thoughts of retirement? Stubborness is part
of the answer. Smoltz confesses to throwing too hard at times this
year, just because on certain days he could.
</P>
<P>
   But then, that has been Smoltz's way throughout his career,
feeling he had to answer to becoming Glavine or Maddux, when he had
enough trouble becoming Smoltz. The 1996 Cy Young award ended most
of that debate, but not all.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he learned anything about his friend this year, Glavine
replied, ``I don't know that I did, to be honest with you. I knew
it was a battle for him to get out and pitch, a battle to change
the way he pitched. I know he's pitched when he was hurt, and he
was tough in that regard. But I've always known those things about
him.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than 18 weeks since Smoltz left the field to
the Cubs in order to go sort out his career. That he found a better
way has made for his most gratifying time in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't wait for tomorrow,'' he said Tuesday. ``The whole
year dragged for me. I could enjoy the wins, with the uncertainty
of the next start. The best say to describe it is, if I could write
a book about it, no one would believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
