u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-HOUSTON-NOTES-COX     09-29 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HOUSTON-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Astros-Padres notebook
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Rest assured Braves fans, Jim Leyritz still lingers in
the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   It was Leyritz, then a Yankee, who smacked a dramatic game-tying
homer off Mark Wohlers in Game 4 of the 1996 World Series. On
Tuesday, Leyritz keyed the San Diego Padres breakthrough against
Randy Johnson with a long bases-load sacrifice fly in the sixth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I thought it was gone,'' said Leyritz, who earlier
singled off the Astros starter. ``But I knew it was going to be a
big run.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz was a late fill-in for first-baseman Wally Joyner, a
graduate of Redan High in Stone Mountain. The left-handed-hitting
Joyner has been nursing a sore shoulder, but entered the game
defensively in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Neither enjoyed success against Johnson in earlier American
League stints, with Joyner hitting .115 (3-26) and Leyritz .108
(4-37). Leyritz also had the misfortune of being beaned by Johnson
in a 1995 game that led to a bench-clearing brawl with the Seattle
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz is with his fourth team since leaving the Yankees,
acquired by the Padres in June for the pennant drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made a big deal here when they picked me up, saying it
was because of my post-season hitting,'' Leyritz said. ``I got a
couple big hits, but my numbers aren't that good overall.''
</P>
<P>
   Try telling that to Wohlers and now Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Misspoken words
</P>
<P>
   In the pregame hype, Astros centerfield Carl Everett said he
respected no opposing pitcher, including the Padres' Kevin Brown.
Everett painfully ate his words after Brown's two-hit, 16 strikeout
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit his spots,'' said Everett, hitless in four at-bats.
``The umpire called (strikes) in a certain place and he kept
hitting it _ down and away.''
</P>
<P>
   Family Affair
</P>
<P>
   Padres outfielder Greg Vaughn stroked a couple singles and a
laser-shot homer off Johnson. Nice day, right? Except that his
cousin, Mo Vaughn hit two home runs and picked up seven RBIs in the
Boston Red Sox's victory over the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to call and see what he had for breakfast,'' the
Padres' Vaughn cracked.
</P>
<P>
   Roll The Video, Please
</P>
<P>
   Asked to detail his sixth-inning escape from a second-and-third
base, two-out jam, Brown said: ``I'm not Greg Maddux. I don't
remember every pitch. . . . It's a situation where you know the
game's on the line and you're just trying to make one good pitch at
a time. Beyond that, I'd have to look at the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Injured List
</P>
<P>
   San Diego leftfielder Tony Gwynn aggravated an Achilles' injury
and left the game in the sixth inning, while second-baseman Quilvio
Veras was removed after being struck on the knee in the ninth.
Manager Bruce Bochy said both should be in the lineup Thursday for
Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
