<SLUG> BC-BBA-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIME TIME FOR BERNIE WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What do you think of Bernie Williams? Is the Yankee
center fielder underrated? Should he be included on the list of
great players who have worn pinstripes?
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Williams wrapped up his first American League batting
title, edging the Red Sox' Mo Vaughn, .339-.337. It capped a
balanced season augmented by 26 homers and 97 RBIs, the kind of
numbers that fit right into the Yankee attack. He is a switch
hitter who bats fourth for a club that won a league-record 114
games. Yet he still seems to be often overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Now is the time to change that. Williams is on a prime-time
postseason stage, and depending on how long the Yankees last, he
could occupy it for more than three weeks. After that, he will be a
free agent and the Yankee front office will have to decide about
his future. Is he a franchise player? Maybe. Would you swap him
even up for Vaughn? Probably not. Is he deserving of top dollar?
That's the big question.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy is just a good hitter,'' said Yankee bench coach Don
Zimmer, who in a career spanning more than 50 years has seen most
of the best. ``And he's fast. He brings a bunch of tools to the
table. What is special about him as a hitter is his power from the
righthand side. Most good Yankee clubs are predominantly
lefthanded.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams also is a versatile hitter. He batted .337 against
righthanders, .339 against lefties. Sixteen of his homers came
against lefties, as did 23 of his 30 doubles. An injury limited him
to 128 games, but he still managed to collect 169 hits and score
101 runs. Now it's a question of how much he'll cash in. He can
boost the numbers with a productive offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in life comes down to that one instant that you
have an opportunity to shine,'' said Williams. ``You're either
going to do it or not do it. You should be willing to risk the
downside and failing just because of the rush that you get for
doing good and being a hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have multiple personalities. I have a lot of fun doing what
I do. But I'm not oblivious to what's going on around me. I am, in
fact, very much aware. It's just my choice to take a step back so
that I can be in control. It works a lot better for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 30, figures to be in his prime if he stays healthy. He
has hit .300 the past four years, the duration of his current
contract. He has great expectations about the financial doors that
will swing open after this season. A $10 million salary is not out
of the question, he says. But are the Yankees listening? Come back
in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, when a player talks big dollars, it creates ripples
throughout the clubhouse as well as the front office. Not Williams.
When the media got wind of his contract negotiatiions and began to
debate the issue, he simply told them to cool it. See him in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what happens in my life right now,'' said Williams,
``nothing can take away what I have accomplished. It has become a
very special year. We have a chance to do some extraordinary
things, and that feels great. I would be a fool to let other things
interfere with the kind of special feeling we have on this team
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams says he has no interest in being called a franchise
player by the media or anybody else. He does not see life in terms
of absolutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more of a mind to let things happen,'' he said. ``I try to
react according to the situation. It's all about preparation. As
long as I prepare well and I make sure in my mind I did everything
I needed to to make myself ready, I'm focused. I stress my
mechanics and my physical condition. Those are the things I can
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked so hard to be in the situation that I am now. And I'm
taking advantage of it. I realize I'm not going to be playing my
whole life. My career is relatively short compared to other jobs.
I'm here to let it all out. I think I can be better. I don't let
other people define me. That's just not my nature.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the season, his future will be defined by other
people. The offer from the Yankees will be handsome. But the kind
of attention he attracts on the open market will depend a lot on
how he does in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can be better,'' he said. ``I'm hitting over.300
this season. Maybe I should hit more home runs. If I hit more home
runs, maybe I should think about stealing more bases. If I achieve
that, maybe I should work on having a better arm in the outfield.
There's so much in my game that I really want to do. It just
becomes a struggle and a desire to achieve perfection. Keep doing
the best you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Would he return to the Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me put it this way,'' he said. ``You cannot play this game
without having fun because there is so much failure. When the
season is over, I'll be one of those guys that takes his time, sits
back, and reflects on the things I have done. Where am I in my
career? What about my family? Where are we going? And one month
after that, I'll want to start playing baseball again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
