<HEADLINE>
DOMINICAN REPUBLIC SLOW TO RECOVER FROM HURRICANE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also HURRICANE-GEORGES) 
(mk) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN DE LA MAGUANA, Dominican Republic _ A week of bright
sunshine and clear skies has done wonders for the Dominican
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, the flood waters of Hurricane Georges had pulled
back into river beds in most of the country, and towns that had
become islands are now, seven days since the storm struck, just
towns again. Coffee and sugar cane fields are drying out and
streets that had become rivers are now dusty tracks.
</P>
<P>
   But the country is far from back to normal. Nelson Ferrera, a
gaunt, 37-year-old man who ekes out a living using a Honda
motorbike as a taxi, thought things had gotten as bad as they could
get when his home here, in a narrow valley 100 miles west of the
capital, Santo Domingo, was swept away in the floods. But since he
took shelter with several hundred other flood victims in rooms
under the bleachers of the municipal soccer stadium, he has been
learning to live day by day on a few handfuls of rice.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 75,000 people in this farm town of modest homes and
shops, are in the same boat with Ferrera. About 12,000 of the
people have taken shelter in schools, churches and the stadium and
some authorities estimate as many as twice that number are living
with friends and relatives. Many of them here and elsewhere in the
country say they have been unable to get adequate food and water.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same for many people whose homes are still intact,
too, because almost everything in this country but the work of
recovery has been stalled.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are relief supplies not getting out quickly; normal
deliveries of food and other goods have been interrupted because so
many roads and bridges have been washed out and because so many
business people have been taking care of their families instead of
tending to their businesses. And many businesses were knocked out
of commission, too. Yet every day, the relief operation picks up a
bit of steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not going to be a famine,'' said Hugh Parmer, a Texas
lawyer who is in charge of humanitarian aid for the U.S. Agency for
International Development. ``That's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning Parmer, other American aid officials and two
reporters flew out of Santo Domingo on one of the half dozen U.S.
Army Black Hawk helicopters that have been sent to the Dominican
Republic to help in the emergency.
</P>
<P>
   From Santo Domingo, the aircraft skimmed west along the coast
and the dark green mountains that rise to the north, finally
working its way up the San Juan River Valley to San Juan de la
Maguana. From an altitude of 2,000 feet or so, towns like Los
Toros, Torbara Abajo, San Antonio and Los Negros seemed to be
sitting on big mud place mats.
</P>
<P>
   Every street looked like it had been painted beige. One
neighborhood here, known as Mesopotamia, lies at a fork in the San
Juan River. Many of the houses did fine in the hurricane. But by 2
a.m. the next day the San Juan was roaring. Tons of water crashed
down from the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows how many people died here. Right after the storm
newspapers in Santo Domingo said hundreds had been lost, possibly
even more than 1,000. On Tuesday, one government official said 29
bodies had been counted. Another said 39 were confirmed dead. Many
people are still missing and the popular wisdom is that many of
them will never be found.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many were buried in the mud or carried away by the river,''
said Bartolome Garriga, director of Caritas, the Roman Catholic
relief agency, for the Diocese of San Juan here. On one street near
the river, Dario Moretta, a 43-year-old farmer, was up to his knees
in mud, digging out his living room. Outside his window, Chelina
Encarnacion Beltre was standing on a slab of mud that had already
baked hard. ``You see this,'' she said. ``This is where my house
used to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
