<SLUG> BC-STORM-GEORGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINA OWNER HAD A `FEELING' GEORGES WOULD HIT AREA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TONY FREEMANTLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAUTIER, Miss. _ When Hurricane Georges was spawned two weeks
ago off the coast of Africa, Richard Pipkin, the owner of a marina
in this Gulf Coast community, had a premonition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called my wife and my foreman, and I told them, `That storm
has got our name on it,''' he said Tuesday. ``I don't know any
other way to say it. It was just a feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, Georges headed in his direction like it was on a
rail.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the storm screamed across the Caribbean, leaving
hundreds dead and billions of dollars in destruction, Pipkin and
his workers at the Mary Walker Marina were preparing for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   When it side-swiped the Florida Keys and headed on a determined
northwest track into the Gulf of Mexico, drawing a bead on New
Orleans, Pipkin refused to let his guard down, and he moved what
boats he could out of harm's way and urged owners to secure those
that would stay.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the pre-dawn Monday, Georges swung to the north,
sparing New Orleans, and slammed into the Gulf Coast just west of
Gautier.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday a somber Pipkin surveyed the wreckage of his marina,
the shredded metal roofs that covered the expensive toys of his
clients, the slips torn to pieces, the sunken boats, the vessel
sitting on his lawn that he had never seen before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fourth hurricane this marina has gone through,''
he said. ``It went through Camille, through Frederick, through
Helena and now Georges, and I was right. Georges had our name on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pipkin was one of thousands of people along the Gulf Coast who
cautiously returned to their homes and businesses Tuesday to
examine what Georges did to their lives when it came ashore at
hurricane strength Monday and then sat over them for hours dumping
torrential rains.
</P>
<P>
   The storm quickly fell apart after hitting land and was
downgraded to a tropical storm and then a tropical depression by
Tuesday as it headed east, dropping even more rain. Up to 15 inches
was expected to fall on southeastern states.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Georges spared the United States the fury it
unleashed on the Caribbean islands, where it caused billions in
damage, killed at least 372 people, and severely damaged the
infrastructures and lives of nations and people that can least
afford it.
</P>
<P>
   But the damage was nevertheless extensive to areas of the
Alabama, Florida, Louisiana and Mississippi coasts, and President
Clinton was to visit the affected region soon and take a look for
himself.
</P>
<P>
   James Lee Witt, director of the Federal Emergency Management
Agency, briefed the president on recovery efforts in those four
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very concerned about this,'' Witt said at the White
House. ``He's very interested in going down and meeting with the
people in the communities.''
</P>
<P>
   In Gautier and the nearby communities of Pascagoula and Orange
Grove, which received the brunt of the storm, numerous powerlines
were toppled, trees had crushed houses, and rivers and creeks
continued to rise Tuesday from the rains.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Gibson, a carpenter in Pascagoula, tried to dry out his
flooded house, still shaken from riding out the storm with his
11-year-old daughter and two dogs. About 1 a.m. on Sunday he
awakened to see water coming into the house and decided to
``evacuate'' upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lay up there thinking the roof wasn't going to hold on,
planning in my mind how I was going to escape if it came off,'' he
said. ``There was just this consistent wind that wouldn't quit. I
was in a state of shock, I tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson had thought far enough ahead that he had stacked his
furniture, but he didn't think he would get nearly three feet of
water in the front part of the house and more than four feet in the
back. He also didn't think the experience of sitting out a
hurricane in the dark would be that harrowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to do it over again, I wouldn't stay,'' he said. ``To
be totally honest with you, I thought it was going more toward New
Orleans. I just didn't think it would turn like that.''
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Orange Grove, Stephen Davis, 31, a machinist and owner
of four purebred Chihuahuas, returned home to his house in the
woods Monday morning and found his house had survived the hurricane
unscathed. But all that day, he watched in dismay as the
floodwaters rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``At about noon (Tuesday) we decided we better get out,'' he
said. He ferried his wife, their ``babies'' and their belongings
out through the rising waters by boat. ``It's not in my house yet,
but we heard there was another three feet of water expected and so
we decided to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the four states that were affected by Georges, hundreds of
thousands of people remained without power, and at the few gas
stations or supermarkets that had generators or which were lucky
enough to have had power restored, lines formed Tuesday as
residents returned and found life's basic necessities in short
supply.
</P>
<P>
   At the Mary Walker Marina, Pipkin wandered around puffing on a
Marlboro, talking to boat owners who were arriving to inspect the
damage. Most of the 160 boats suffered only minor damage, but some,
like the off-shore sport fishing boat Chris Davis had been
restoring for much of the last year, were lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I guess it's totaled,'' Davis, a lawyer from Gulfport,
said as looked at his boat through the murky waters. ``But I think
my insurance company will come through.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
