<SLUG> BC-MA-UTILITIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT ASSESSES INVESTMENT IMPACT ON UTILITY CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts ranks third behind New Hampshire and
Illinois on the cost impact per customer of electric utilities'
previous bad investments, according to a study of 11 states that
have deregulated their utility industries.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-page report was released Tuesday by the Massachusetts
Public Interest Research Group, a consumer-environmental
organization. It was written by the Safe Energy Communications
Council, a Washington, D.C., coalition of energy, environmental and
public interest media organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The study claims that utilities in the 11 states hold &UR;  &LR; $112
billion in bad investments _ mostly uncompetitive power plants,
including nuclear facilities, plus above-market power purchase
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; These bad investments are known as ``stranded costs.'' In a
controversial move, utilities want their customers _ not their
shareholders _ to pay for them as part of deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, where electric deregulation took effect Mar.
1, ratepayers are absorbing utilities' stranded costs.
</P>
<P>
   The report claims that Bay State utilities have $7.4 billion in
stranded costs, meaning that each residential ratepayer in effect
is paying $1,345 in stranded costs. In New Hampshire, which has $2
billion in stranded costs, the economic impact will amount to
$1,963 per residential customer, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   However, the report does not reflect pending or recently
completed sales of nearly $2.7 billion of electric generating
assets by Boston Edison Co., New England Electric and Commonwealth
Energy System, nor the expected sale next month of Boston Edison's
Pilgrim Nuclear Power Station in Plymouth. If those asset sales
were factored in, the cost impact would be lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allowing full stranded cost recovery financed by ratepayers is
not compatible with legal precedents, true competition or the
public interest,'' the report states.
</P>
<P>
   The study will be used by opponents of Massachusetts' electric
restructuring law. Opponents say the law did not provide consumers
enough of a discount on electricity bills and &UR;  &LR; are urging voters to
repeal the law on a Nov. 3 ballot initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line in every one of the 11 states is that
regulators blew the opportunity to save consumers a substantial
portion of their electric rates,'' said Rob Sargent, Masspirg
energy department director.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the Massachusetts law &UR;  &LR; insist that the state has the
most progressive deregulation law in the country, with ratepayers
paying considerably lower stranded costs than customers in other
states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
