<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SMU-DOAK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMU PLANS TRIBUTES TO DOAK WALKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the SMU Mustangs depart for Hawaii today, the spirit of a
legend will travel with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we play (Hawaii) Saturday, we plan to wear a No. 37 decal
on the helmets, in honor of Doak Walker,'' SMU coach Mike Cavan
said. ``We also plan to wear it in every game for the rest of the
year, in his memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the plan, unless we have trouble getting it approved by
the NCAA,'' Cavan said. ``I really can't imagine any problem there,
but you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be a memorial service today in Steamboat Springs,
Colo., for Walker, the former SMU All-American who died Sunday at
age 71. Walker will be cremated.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, a three-time All-American who won both the Heisman and
Maxwell trophies during his SMU career (1947-49), was paralyzed in
a skiing accident Jan. 30. In July, he was moved from a Denver
hospital to a facility in Steamboat Springs where he battled
various ailments relating to the injury.
</P>
<P>
   He died Sunday from an infection after surgery for a bleeding
ulcer, said his son, Scott, who added, ``his spirit was great, but
his health had deteriorated, and he had had a lot of infections.
His kidneys had begun to shut down.''
</P>
<P>
   SMU officials said a previously planned tribute to Walker during
the TCU game (Oct. 17 in the Cotton Bowl) will be held in an
altered form. There will be a halftime ceremony honoring Walker,
but a surcharge of $1 for general admission tickets and $2 for
reserved seats has been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   The extra fee was intended to raise money for Walker's
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   There also have been various suggestions about honoring Walker
in connection with the new football stadium being built on the
present on-campus site of Ownby Stadium _ the first arena in which
Walker played for the Mustangs.
</P>
<P>
   A hall-of-fame section called Heritage Hall already has been
planned, and will be heavily laden with Walker memorabilia. There
also has been a suggestion to add a ``Doak Walker Plaza.''
</P>
<P>
   There also have been suggestions about adding Walker's name to
the stadium, which is scheduled to be named after principal donor
Gerald J. Ford, a Dallas businessman and SMU alumnus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
