<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0999 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-TEX     09-29 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGHORNS FIND LEADER IN FEISTY FIFTH-YEAR SENIOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Mack Brown, Texas' first-year football coach,
knew he had a scrapper when he watched Wane McGarity fighting
through stiffness in his surgically repaired knee during spring
drills.
</P>
<P>
   But it took an injury to another player before Brown realized he
had something special: a team leader who is fast becoming one of
the nation's premier deep threats. Ironically, McGarity's rise to
prominence began after quarterback Richard Walton broke a finger
Sept. 12 in a 49-31 loss to UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Losing the fifth-year senior for an extended period thrust
redshirt freshman Major Applewhite into the quarterback spot and
raised questions about whether the Longhorns' passing game could
remain productive in Walton's absence. McGarity answered with a
career-best outing against No. 5 Kansas State, then topped that
effort in last week's 59-21 rout of Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into a game against Iowa State (6 p.m. Saturday,
Royal-Memorial Stadium), McGarity ranks 18th nationally among wide
receivers with an average of five catches and 107.5 yards per game.
At 21.5 yards per catch, he is second among Big 12 players with at
least 10 receptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wane has really stepped it up since Richard got hurt. He's
played as well as I've seen him play,'' Brown said. ``We've got to
get everybody on this football team playing with as much heart as
Wane McGarity. He doesn't look like a guy who's had three knee
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has. The last one came a year ago, short-circuiting
McGarity's 1997 season after three games. When rehabilitation work
proved grueling in the off-season, Brown broached the possibility
of McGarity accepting a medical scholarship and calling it a
career. The senior from San Antonio wouldn't bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want people to remember me as, `That injury plagued
wide receiver who played for Texas,''' McGarity said, bristling at
the title that once threatened to summarize his college career. ``I
still feel like I have something to give to this university. I
never quit on anybody, and nobody quits on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot of leadership abilities and a lot to give to
this team. I think I've proved that I'm the same player I was
before the operations. To me, that means a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   To the Texas passing game, which must remain productive to
prevent defenses from selling out to stop record-setting tailback
Ricky Williams, McGarity has meant a much-needed downfield threat
that was lacking last season. Against Kansas State, McGarity
grabbed five passes for 142 yards. He was even better against Rice,
snagging six balls for a career-high 145 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an experienced guy at a position where we really need
one,'' said offensive coordinator Greg Davis. ``It's hard to put a
value on that. With Wane out there, it becomes a question of what
the other team wants to give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you play your safeties up close to stop Ricky and go
one-on-one with Wane? Or do you keep them back deep and open up the
run? He gives this team a dimension it didn't have last year.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has boosted the confidence of Applewhite, who once
avoided throwing to McGarity in drills to let him get more
repetitions with Walton. Now, the two have hooked up 11 times in
two weeks, covering 287 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not only great physically, he's great mentally,''
Applewhite said. ``He knows exactly what I'm thinking and what
we're going to do before we do it. I think Wane and I have
developed a little connection.''
</P>
<P>
   The increased numbers suggest it. But they do not tell the
complete Wane McGarity story, in Brown's estimation. That begins
and ends with the grin McGarity takes to practice on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got so much fight for a guy with three knee operations,''
Brown said. ``To see him smile, you have to pull for him to finish
on a positive note after all the adversity he's been through.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two weeks, McGarity has made major strides in that
direction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
