A1001 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SALON-NYT &LR;      09-29 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SALON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE MAGAZINE'S D.C. BUREAU CHIEF IS FORCED TO RESIGN
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CLINTON, CLINTON-CANTON, CLINTON-IMPEACH, CLINTON-JONES,
OPRAH-MONICA) 
(nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Washington bureau chief of the online magazine Salon, who
urged his editors not to reveal a 30-year-old affair of Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, was forced
to resign after he publicly questioned the journalistic merits of
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation of Hyde's affair came on Sept. 16, five days
after Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth Starr sent Congress
his report on President Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky
and his statements under oath about the relationship. Hyde's
committee plans to debate whether to vote on beginning a formal
impeachment inquiry, based in part on the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   Salon, which is based in San Francisco, came under sharp attack
from both sides of the aisle on Capitol Hill and from readers after
publishing the report, which was accompanied by an editorial saying
that ``ugly times call for ugly tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Editor David Talbot said Tuesday that the report, whose
publication had been the source of sharp internal debate as well,
brought at least 400,000 new readers to the site.
</P>
<P>
   But anticipating the highly charged atmosphere that followed
publication of the Hyde story, Talbot said the bureau chief,
Jonathan Broder, was specifically told not to air his differences
with his editors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people trying to shut down Salon because they don't
like what we're publishing,'' Talbot said. ``They tried to hack
into us. We've gotten bomb threats at home. The last thing we
needed was for our Washington correspondent to add fuel to that
fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Talbot confirmed that he had told his subordinates last
week that Broder, 50, was no longer working for the publication.
His resignation letter was not sent until this week, though Broder
said he had offered to resign in a heated conversation with one of
the magazine's editors on Sept. 17, after The Washington Post
quoted him as saying he objected to the decision ``on journalistic
grounds, on grounds of fairness and because of the way Salon would
be perceived.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbot said that Broder's decision to ``publicly air his
criticisms'' of the Hyde story was in direct defiance of his
supervisors' instructions and ``a fundamental violation of the
trust that any organization must have in its employees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have determined that sex sells,'' Broder said
Tuesday. ``This whole Clinton scandal is a made-for-Salon story, if
you want to view it through a sexual lens.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made a decision that that's where he wants to take
Salon,'' said Broder, referring to Talbot. ``That's where the money
is. He's the executive editor and chief executive. I just don't
want to go there with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The internal strife at Salon comes as the online magazine is
preparing to shift its profile, putting new emphasis on breaking
news. When it was founded three years ago, the magazine was built
around essays with attitude, on the cultural and intellectual
scene.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Broder's criticism, Talbot pointed out that he is
eliminating one long-running column about sex, ``Unzipped,''
written by Courtney Weaver.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Online Journalism Review in March,
Talbot responded to a question about building the magazine's
``brand name'' by saying, ``I think your editorial operations can
get you news as we've been doing lately with the stories we've been
breaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's free PR in a way,'' he said, using shorthand for public
relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0379 </DOCNO>
