<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-NUKE-N     09-29 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-NUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: FOR PAKISTAN AND INDIA, ATOM PACT IS A HARD SELL  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ For the prime ministers of India and Pakistan
to follow through on their stated willingness to sign the nuclear
test-ban treaty, both men will need to convince their restive
publics that they got something substantial in return.
</P>
<P>
   The response to their speeches at the U.N. General Assembly last
week, in which they said their countries were ready to sign the
treaty within a year if sanctions against them were lifted, was
optimistic in the United States. But political and policy analysts
here paid more attention to the conditions each man set, and, in
India's case especially, it is far from certain that those
conditions would be met.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan's prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, and India's, Atal
Behari Vajpayee, face politically insecure futures and would pay a
high price with voters if they signed the treaty without bringing
home the goods.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's political fortunes have swooned since the United States
imposed economic sanctions on his country after it tested nuclear
weapons in May, seriously worsening Pakistan's bleak economic
prospects. Not surprisingly, he declared he would sign the treaty
only if the United States lifts the economic sanctions and helps
Pakistan get an aid package to prevent its default on $30 billion
in debt.
</P>
<P>
   The week before he went to New York, Sharif sought legislative
approval to sign the treaty, but many members of Parliament were
unwilling to give him the go-ahead without a specific description
of what Pakistan would get in return. And the United States will be
unable to give Sharif what he asked for unless Congress either
gives the president authority to waive sanctions or removes them
itself, and so far only the Senate has agreed to a waiver.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee, whose Bharatiya Janata Party heads a fragile coalition
government, has an even more complicated task.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, there has been a broad consensus in India
against signing the treaty. Some officials said that India needed
the freedom to test so it could develop a credible nuclear
deterrent against Pakistan and China; others said that India should
not sign until the five declared nuclear powers agreed to move
decisively toward global disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The BJP doesn't have much room to do a deal without getting
important concessions,'' said Brahma Chellaney, a national security
analyst at the Center for Policy Research, a nonprofit research
group in New Delhi. ``And it's not clear what the Americans can
offer. The president has been weakened and Congress is hostile.''
</P>
<P>
   What India wants from the United States _ for example, the
opportunity to buy advanced technology from the United States _
will be difficult for the United States to give without seeming to
reward India for having tested nuclear weapons in May. The grueling
negotiations between India and the United States since the tests
have yet to resolve this and many other knotty issues.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the United States willing to lift sanctions, much less
make other serious concessions, if all Pakistan and India do is
sign the test ban treaty. American negotiators want both countries
to halt their production of weapons-grade plutonium and uranium _
something Pakistan is especially reluctant to do so.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech on Monday to the Asia Society in New York, a dour
Vajpayee made clear India's resentment of Washington's angry
denunciations of the nuclear tests, while the established nuclear
powers have ignored India's pleas for disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   ``They first used the Cold War as a pretext for a costly arms
race,'' he said. ``Now, even though the Cold War is over, they have
sought to perpetuate their hegemony through discriminatory
nonproliferation treaties which are bound to fail.''
</P>
<P>
   And he justified India's nuclear tests ``as a powerful challenge
to the practitioners of nuclear apartheid.''
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee was surely playing to his audience back home, but the
anger in India is real. Even the coolest-headed intellectuals ask
why China, an authoritarian government that has exported nuclear
technology to India's arch-rival Pakistan, and has a terrible human
rights record, is allowed to buy American satellites and other
technology while India, the world's largest democracy, is not.
</P>
<P>
   India's nuclear scientists have recently declared that India can
go ahead and sign the test-ban treaty without damaging its weapons
program. The tests conducted in May provided them with what they
need to know, they said.
</P>
<P>
   And while those assurances may ultimately help Vajpayee make the
case domestically for signing the treaty, they will not be enough
by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Richard Haass, director of the foreign policy studies
program at the Brookings Institution, made a swing through New
Delhi and Islamabad to present the recommendations of a task force,
sponsored by Brookings and the Council on Foreign Relations, on
American policy toward India and Pakistan, post-tests. American
diplomats say that the document lays out the direction the
administration wants its own policy to take.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings with journalists, Haass maintained that the United
States should recognize that there is no way for India to unlearn
what it learned from its nuclear tests and that the president
should have the authority to waive sanctions under the right
circumstances. But he also said that India should sign the treaty
to stabilize its relationship with Pakistan and to build stronger
ties with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether India will hold on to the residue of
nonalignment or Third Worldism, or let it go,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
