<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 9/29/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) NEW YORK -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- OBIT-FERRAGAMO-B&AMP;W, 9-29
-- Fiamma Ferragamo died Monday at her home in Florence. She was
57. Ms. Ferragamo stressed comfort and elegance for her shoes,
backed up by promotion. She appeared at Saks Fifth Avenue in 1987.
(Don Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-2, 9-29
-- Yankees' David Wells pitching against the Texas Rangers during
game one Tuesday in the Bronx. The Yankees, who won 114 of 162
regular-season games, begin the playoffs Tuesday night in the
three-of-five-game division series against the American League West
winner. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NEW YORK -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-1, 9-29
-- Derek Jeter makes a leaping catch - er, make that Shahem
Belayet, killing time Tuesday before entering Yankee Stadium, the
House That Ruth Built and that George Steinbrenner has threatened
to leave. The Yankees, who won 114 of 162 regular-season games,
begin the playoffs Tuesday night in the three-of-five-game division
series against the American League West winner, the Texas Rangers.
(Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- IMF-REVAMP, 9-29
-- Jeffrey Sachs, director of the Harvard Institute for
International Development, argues that fixed rates do not work well
with unlimited capital flows. His solution: Let currencies float.
(Ed Quinn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) CANTON, Ohio -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- CLINTON-CANTON-2, 9-29
-- ``I'm frightened that we will be embarrassed as a newspaper if
we endorse Clinton and have a huge scandal break out,'' David
Kaminski said to his fellow editors on the day in late October 1996
when his normally Republican newspaper, The Repository, broke with
past habits and endorsed the president. And a huge scandal, of
course, is exactly what has happened. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) CANTON, Ohio -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- CLINTON-CANTON-1, 9-29
-- Sharon Vaccani, owner of a hair salon, and her customer,
Rosemary Zaremba, both agree: President Clinton has done wrong, but
not as a government official. ``He hasn't done a bad job as
president,'' says Ms. Vaccani, normally a Republican. ``This isn't
impeachable.'' (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) MONTCLAIR, N.J. -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- COMPUTER-MATH-EDUC,
9-29 -- A study examined how computers affect learning. In
Montclair, a young student sits at a terminal at the Bradford
School. (Thomas Dallal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- LOBBY-II-2, 9-29 -- Greg
Mueller, an aide in Patrick Buchanan's 1996 presidential campaign,
promotes the tax campaign to journalists. Mueller is just one of
the all-star cast from both parties that Americans for Fair
Taxation has hired to promulgate their platform. (Justin Lane/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- LOBBY-II-1, 9-29 --
Charles Sewell, a Democrat, scours the nation seeking leaders for
local chapters of Americans for Fair Taxation. Sewell and his
fellow investors in Americans for Fair Taxation are unusual in the
scale of their ambition. But their methods have become commonplace
as lobbying has undergone a revolution over the past decade.
(Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) SHERMAN, Texas -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- LEADERSHIP-STUDIES,
9-29 -- Gen. Colin Powell, general chairman of Americas Promise,
with Jennifer Miscovich, a junior at Austin College's Leadership
Institute in Sherman. ``There's no turning back now,'' she says of
the effect the program has had on her. ``I know I'm going to be
involved in some sort of community service from here on.''
Leadership as an area of study is becoming increasingly popular
throughout the country. (Austin College/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- CONGRESS-MILITARY, 9-29
-- Testifying at a Senate hearing Tuesday are, from left, Gen.
Dennis Reimer of the Army; Adm. Jay Johnson of the Navy; Gen. Henry
Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Michael Ryan
of the Air Force and Gen. Charles Krulak of the Marine Corps.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) DONJI OBRINJE, Serbia -- Sept. 29, 1998 --
KOSOVO-MASSACRE-2, 9-29 -- Shehide Hysenaj, 73, mourns the death of
his neighbor, Ali Kolludra, 62, on Tuesday in Donji Obrinje;
Kolludra still grips his hooked walking stick. 21 women, children
and elderly were executed in this region Saturday morning by
members of the police of Serbia and of the Yugoslav Army. (Wade
Goddard/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) GORNJI OBRINJE, Serbia -- Sept. 29, 1998 --
KOSOVO-MASSACRE-1, 9-29 -- An ethnic Albanian man covers a young
child from his village, Gornji Obrinje, on Tuesday before
relocation to a burial site. 21 region residents were executed
Saturday morning in a siege by members of the police of Serbia and
of the Yugoslav Army, shot in the head at close range and in some
cases mutilated as they tried to escape advancing Serbian forces.
(Wade Goddard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) CLOVERDALE, Calif. -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- KLAAS-5TH-ANNIV,
9-29 -- A memorial to Polly Klaas stands on the site in Cloverdale
where she was found five years ago. The disappearance of the
12-year-old on Oct. 1, 1993 ignited a 65 day search that ended when
her body was found here. Polly's legacy includes reforms in the
criminal justice system, changes in police procedures for handling
missing children and increased public awareness of sex offenders.
(Chris Chung/Santa Rosa Press-Democrat Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- LEADING-LADIES-REVIEW-2,
9-29 -- Dorothy Loudon in ``My Favorite Broadway: The Leading
Ladies,'' a first-class industrial show at Carnegie Hall on Monday
evening that also raised $50,000 for two AIDS charities. The
concert, which spotlighted the cream of Broadway leading ladies,
kept the remarks to a minimum and the pace swift. (James Estrin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- LEADING-LADIES-REVIEW-1,
9-29 -- Audra McDonald in ``My Favorite Broadway: The Leading
Ladies,'' a first-class industrial show (for Continental Airlines)
at Carnegie Hall on Monday evening that also raised $50,000 for two
AIDS charities. The production was a happy (and occasionally
thrilling) surprise. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- MET-OPERA-REVIEW-2, 9-29
-- Opening night arrivals on the Metropolitan Opera's grand
staircase. With the house bulging with gowned and tuxedoed patrons,
the Met made a shrewd choice of repertory Monday night.
Saint-Saens' ``Samson et Dalila'' was just the ticket: a
second-rate opera offering just enough surface charm and colorful
production values to compete with its many-hued listeners out
front. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- MET-OPERA-REVIEW-1, 9-29
-- Olga Borodina and Placido Domingo in ``Samson et Dalila,'' on
opening night at the Met. Opera operates on so many different
levels that one can often come to the rescue of another. It happens
several times in the Met's ``Samson et Dalila,'' first of all in
the role of Dalila itself, which rises above the musical mediocrity
around it. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- DEECEE-RICHARD-3, 9-29
-- Michel Richard's lamb with eggplant caviar, from the kitchen at
Citronelle, his restaurant in Washington. ``You have to understand
the market,'' he says. ``You have to give them what they want, but
you don't have to give them bad food. My dream is that Washington
will become a national destination for food.'' (Carol T. Powers/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- DEECEE-RICHARD-2, 9-29
-- Michel Richard, who produces gastronomical delights at his
restaurant, Citronelle in Washington, often begins with a sketch
that he later translates into gourmet fare. His large artist's
sketchbook is filled with hundreds of ideas: he thinks about new
dishes while he is driving, on vacation, even while he is still
working on another creation at his restaurant. (Carol T. Powers/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- DEECEE-RICHARD-1, 9-29
-- Michel Richard at work in the kitchen at Citronelle, his
restaurant in Washington. One of the most admired chefs in the
country, Richard has come East from Los Angeles where his
restaurant, Citrus, is still very popular. His dream is to turn
Washington into a city known for its food. And with his remarkably
creative aproach to recipes that produces pure, clean flavors he
may succeed where all others have failed. (Carol T. Powers/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- NY-SHORT-RIBS, 9-29 -- The
Lobster Club's short ribs are braised, then breaded and grilled.
Why is it that some of the fanciest chefs in town positively dote
on short ribs? Maybe it's because this unglamorous cut brings out
the Henry Higgins in them. In the right hands, and with enough care
and patience, these steer ribs, the ends of the prime ribs, which
start out all toughness, show their elegant and tender side. (David
Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- NY-MICHAEL-JORDAN, 9-29 --
The food is big at Michael Jordan's in Manhattan. Jordan and his
partners, Penny and Peter Glazier, have done something remarkable:
They have invented a new kind of celebrity restaurant. The partners
have found a way to capitalize on Jordan's fame without
jeopardizing his dignity. And in the process they have created New
York's best-looking steakhouse. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LONDON -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- LONDON-FASHION-2, 9-28 --
Shalom Harlow in the finale to Alexander McQueen's London show.
British designers can put everything they have into making highly
personalized, sometimes even brilliant clothes and showing them on
a runway, and then find they are unable to produce the clothes and
get them into important stores. (Jonathan Player/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LONDON -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- LONDON-FASHION-1, 9-28 --
It's the old story that haunts the British fashion scene: a wealth
of talent and a paucity of financial resources. From left,
Alexander McQueen's winged avenger in perforated slats; crocheted
camisole and flounced skirt by Antonio Berardi; Tristan Webber
experimental red leather top with lacing and a multicolor skirt.
(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: The following photos accompany the Boston Globe's series
addressing the issues surrounding our food supply. Photos that have
the suffix B&AMP;W are only available in black and white.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- SPCL-FOOD-III-2-BOS, 9-29
-- Diane Beeny, a member of Pure Foods Campaign, an organic
advocacy group, stands at the Union Square farmer's market
collecting signatures against genetic engineering. In addition to
her monster mask, Ms. Beeny wears a T-shirt proclaiming ``Keep your
genes out of our greens.'' (Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) JERSEYVILLE, Ill. -- Sept. 29, 1998 --
SPCL-FOOD-III-2-BOS, 9-29 -- At Monsanto's 240-acre research farm,
Roundup Ready corn, corn which is genetically engineered to
withstand the herbicide Roundup, continues grow next to regular
corn. Genetic engineering allows scientists to transfer a single
gene from any organism - plant, animal, or microbe - into a food
crop so it can withstand insects and herbicides, as well as last
longer before spoiling. (Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) JERSEYVILLE, Ill. -- Sept. 29, 1998 --
SPCL-FOOD-III-1-BOS, 9-29 -- Inside the greenhouses at Monsanto's
240-acre research farm. This is where the first genetically
engineered tomato plant was grown in 1987. The genetic engineering
of plants has triggered a major food-safety controversy in Europe,
where Monsanto's transgenic crops have been destroyed by activists
in Britain, France, and Ireland and banned by governments in
Austria and Luxembourg. (Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- SPCL-FOOD-II-3-BOS-B&AMP;W, 9-29
-- Lynn McKinely, a critic of Premium Standard Farms, hugs a piglet
on her farm in northwest Missouri. ``The public wants cheap, lean
pork,'' says Ms. McKinley, who raises 56 pigs mostly for her family
and friends. ``My pigs, I can't say they're happy all the time...I
keep the radio on and they like their country music.'' (Stan
Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MILAN, Mo. -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- SPCL-FOOD-II-2-BOS-B&AMP;W,
9-29 -- The bars, say Premium Standard Farms, stop the sow from
rolling on top of the piglets while they are nursing. The story of
Premium Standard, which raises 1.7 million hogs a year, represents
a changing America, where big, high-tech corporations are replacing
mom and pop farms. (Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MILAN, Mo. -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- SPCL-FOOD-II-1-BOS-B&AMP;W,
9-29 -- This hog is head and shoulders above the rest at
Missouri-based Premium Standard Farms, the nation's second largest
hog producer. Nationwide, more animals are being produced on less
land. Concentrated factory farms, virtually non-existent 30 years
ago, are now proliferating, generating billions of dollars in big
business while creating cheaper, leaner food. (Stan
Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BUAYSIACOBE, Mexico -- Sept. 29, 1998 --
SPCL-FOOD-PESTICIDES-2-BOS-B&AMP;W, 9-29 -- Eleazar Villegas Baypoli,
27, of Buaysiacobe, cradles his son. In February, Villegas was told
to spray the tomatoes with a diluted mixture of three pesticides,
including the highly toxic chemical parathion. After three days of
spraying he felt a ``fire'' in his chest and could barely breathe.
To save his life, doctors performed an emergency tracheotomy. Today
he is bedridden, has no health insurance, no income and suffers
from nerve damage and depression. (Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- Sept. 29, 1998 --
SPCL-FOOD-PESTICIDES-1-BOS-B&AMP;W, 9-29 -- Belem Colin Silva, 11,
bundles her face with a bandanna while she works in a grape field
that has been sprayed with pesticides. Up to 25 million
agricultural workers in the developing world may suffer at least
one incident of pesticide poisoning each year because they don't
use U.S.-required protective clothing or respirators and are
inadequately trained, according to the World Health Organization.
(Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) HAMILITON, Mass. -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- SPCL-FOOD-I-1-BOS,
9-29 -- Laura Biddle, a minister and mother of three, munches on
raspberries as she picks them at the Green Meadows Farm. Mrs.
Biddle contracted the parasite cyclospora in April 1997 after
eating produce from a downtown Boston fruit stand. ``I seriously
thought I was dying, that my insides were falling out,'' she says.
(Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
