<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX'S BIG THREE PROVE WORTHY IN 11-3 ROUT OF INDIANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ On a single brilliant autumn afternoon at Jacobs
Field, Mo Vaughn found redemption, Nomar Garciaparra provided
vindication and Pedro Martinez gave further justification.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the heroics of Boston's three superstars, the
only thing the Cleveland Indians were left with yesterday was a
whole lot of desolation.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn homered twice and doubled to drive in seven runs, tying a
postseason record for a single game, and Garciaparra launched an
important three-run home run and added a sacrifice fly in the
eighth. Together, they drove in all the Red Sox runs and helped
Martinez, the $75 million man, cruise to an 11-3 victory in his
first playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams play again today in Game 2 of the best-of-five
Division Series. The winner plays the survivor of the Rangers-New
York Yankees series for the American League pennant.
</P>
<P>
   If the key Red Sox players continue to outperform Cleveland's as
they did in Game 1, there won't be a need for games 4 and 5 this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was a one-man turning point in the surprisingly lopsided
game. His three-run shot off Indians starter Jaret Wright with
nobody out in the top of the first inning set the game's tone and
provided him some redemption for a disastrous performance in his
only other postseason appearance.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1995 Division Series against Cleveland, Vaughn went
hitless in 14 at-bats, striking out seven times as the Indians
swept the Red Sox en route to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted an opportunity to get here again,'' Vaughn said.
(In 1995) I wasn't prepared. I'm a little bit older now and I'm
more experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said the main thing he didn't do in 1995 was hit the ball
where it was pitched. That's exactly what he did against Wright,
however. Showing patience, he came back from an 0-2 count, running
the count full with two men on base. Then he went to the opposite
field on a 3-2 pitch by Wright. The ball landed just beyond the
left-field wall, 376 feet from home plate. The Indians never
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball was out over the plate, and I just went through it
and it carried,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his latest heroics, Vaughn can't completely forget his
collapse three seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'll ever close the books on what happened in
1995,'' he said. ``I think I'll always refer back to it and learn
from it because I think as much as it hurts, you're always going to
learn more from negative things than from positive things. That's
the only way you can get better at what you're trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   For Garciaparra, whose three-run home run in the fifth inning
boosted the Boston lead to 6-0, the game demonstrated yet again
that he belonged in the All-Star Game this year. Indians manager
Mike Hargrove left him off the team, choosing his own shortstop,
Omar Vizquel, instead. Red Sox fans and baseball people across
America criticized the decision, and the shortstop's performance
yesterday further vindicated their claims.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra wasn't talking about the slight afterward,
preferring to praise the efforts of Vaughn and Martinez. Of his
home run, he said, ``I just tried to drive (the ball). Fortunately,
it went out.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Martinez, he further justified the Red Sox's $75 million
off-season investment in his prized right arm. Acquired from the
Montreal Expos and signed for six years to be the ace of a team
with flickering playoff hopes, Martinez ably filled the role
yesterday, dominating Cleveland until two late home runs, by Kenny
Lofton and Jim Thome, led to his exit after seven stellar innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the lead, so it was up to me to get on top of them and
start pitching my game and be ahead of them all of the time. I did,
and I got the best results,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   So did the Red Sox.
</P>
</TEXT>
