<P>
   (NYT8) JERSEYVILLE, Ill. -- Sept. 29, 1998 --
SPCL-FOOD-III-2-BOS, 9-29 -- At Monsanto's 240-acre research farm,
Roundup Ready corn, corn which is genetically engineered to
withstand the herbicide Roundup, continues grow next to regular
corn. Genetic engineering allows scientists to transfer a single
gene from any organism - plant, animal, or microbe - into a food
crop so it can withstand insects and herbicides, as well as last
longer before spoiling. (Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) JERSEYVILLE, Ill. -- Sept. 29, 1998 --
SPCL-FOOD-III-1-BOS, 9-29 -- Inside the greenhouses at Monsanto's
240-acre research farm. This is where the first genetically
engineered tomato plant was grown in 1987. The genetic engineering
of plants has triggered a major food-safety controversy in Europe,
where Monsanto's transgenic crops have been destroyed by activists
in Britain, France, and Ireland and banned by governments in
Austria and Luxembourg. (Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- SPCL-FOOD-II-3-BOS-B&AMP;W, 9-29
-- Lynn McKinely, a critic of Premium Standard Farms, hugs a piglet
on her farm in northwest Missouri. ``The public wants cheap, lean
pork,'' says Ms. McKinley, who raises 56 pigs mostly for her family
and friends. ``My pigs, I can't say they're happy all the time...I
keep the radio on and they like their country music.'' (Stan
Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MILAN, Mo. -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- SPCL-FOOD-II-2-BOS-B&AMP;W,
9-29 -- The bars, say Premium Standard Farms, stop the sow from
rolling on top of the piglets while they are nursing. The story of
Premium Standard, which raises 1.7 million hogs a year, represents
a changing America, where big, high-tech corporations are replacing
mom and pop farms. (Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MILAN, Mo. -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- SPCL-FOOD-II-1-BOS-B&AMP;W,
9-29 -- This hog is head and shoulders above the rest at
Missouri-based Premium Standard Farms, the nation's second largest
hog producer. Nationwide, more animals are being produced on less
land. Concentrated factory farms, virtually non-existent 30 years
ago, are now proliferating, generating billions of dollars in big
business while creating cheaper, leaner food. (Stan
Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BUAYSIACOBE, Mexico -- Sept. 29, 1998 --
SPCL-FOOD-PESTICIDES-2-BOS-B&AMP;W, 9-29 -- Eleazar Villegas Baypoli,
27, of Buaysiacobe, cradles his son. In February, Villegas was told
to spray the tomatoes with a diluted mixture of three pesticides,
including the highly toxic chemical parathion. After three days of
spraying he felt a ``fire'' in his chest and could barely breathe.
To save his life, doctors performed an emergency tracheotomy. Today
he is bedridden, has no health insurance, no income and suffers
from nerve damage and depression. (Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- Sept. 29, 1998 --
SPCL-FOOD-PESTICIDES-1-BOS-B&AMP;W, 9-29 -- Belem Colin Silva, 11,
bundles her face with a bandanna while she works in a grape field
that has been sprayed with pesticides. Up to 25 million
agricultural workers in the developing world may suffer at least
one incident of pesticide poisoning each year because they don't
use U.S.-required protective clothing or respirators and are
inadequately trained, according to the World Health Organization.
(Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) HAMILITON, Mass. -- Sept. 29, 1998 -- SPCL-FOOD-I-1-BOS,
9-29 -- Laura Biddle, a minister and mother of three, munches on
raspberries as she picks them at the Green Meadows Farm. Mrs.
Biddle contracted the parasite cyclospora in April 1997 after
eating produce from a downtown Boston fruit stand. ``I seriously
thought I was dying, that my insides were falling out,'' she says.
(Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
