<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1011 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-800(2TAKES)-NY     09-29 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT WILL ADD TO SEX HARASSMENT RULINGS, TAKING UP CASE OF OFFENSE
BY STUDENT  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By LINDA GREENHOUSE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Adding a dozen cases to the calendar for its new
term, the Supreme Court on Tuesday expanded its review of sexual
harassment law and also agreed to decide whether states can impose
special welfare limits on new residents.
</P>
<P>
   The justices acted in advance of the formal opening next Monday
of the 1998-1999 term, during which they will continue to add new
cases to the 45 already accepted for decision, including Tuesday's
12.
</P>
<P>
   In the last term, the court decided four sexual harassment
cases, clarifying the rules for determining the liability of
employers and, in the instance of sexual harassment committed by
teachers, the liability of school districts. The new case raises
the question whether a school district can ever be found liable
under federal law for one student's harassment of another. The
federal appeals court in Atlanta ruled last year that federal law
did not apply to the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The case, Davis vs. Monroe County Board of Education, No.
97-843, is an appeal by the mother of a girl who was harassed
repeatedly by a boy in her fifth-grade classroom in Macon, Ga. The
classroom teacher took no action, refusing for three months to let
the girl change her seat. The principal also took no action. As the
situation worsened, the girl's grades dropped and she threatened
suicide. Eventually the boy was criminally charged and pleaded
guilty to sexual battery.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, in Gebser vs. Lago Vista Independent School District,
the court ruled that students could sue school districts for
harassment by teachers but that a district would be liable only if
a person in authority had known of the problem and had reacted with
``deliberate indifference.'' In the new case, the plaintiff,
supported by the Clinton administration, is arguing that this
standard has been met in light of school officials' failure to
respond to months of complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The federal appeals courts have disagreed over whether the law
at issue, Title IX of the Education Amendments of 1972, applies to
sexual harassment by students, and several such cases have recently
been appealed to the Supreme Court. Title IX prohibits sex
discrimination in educational programs that receive federal money.
In this case, the 11th U.S. Court of Appeals, in Atlanta, ruled
that while the law obliged school districts to prevent sexual
harassment by their employees, it did not make schools liable for
students' behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The court accepted a second case Tuesday involving Title IX, in
the statute's more familiar context of equality in college
athletics rather than sexual harassment. The question is whether
the National Collegiate Athletic Association is itself bound by the
anti-discrimination provisions of the law, which indisputably do
apply to the 1,200 colleges and universities that are NCAA members.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, NCAA vs. Smith, No. 98-84, the 3rd U.S. Court of
Appeals, in Philadelphia, ruled earlier this year that even though
the athletic association itself does not directly receive federal
money, it is an indirect recipient, and therefore covered by Title
IX, by virtue of the dues it collects from its member schools.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court permitted a Title IX suit against the NCAA to
proceed. The plaintiff is a woman who lost her eligibility under
NCAA rules to play intercollegiate volleyball when she graduated
early from college and entered graduate school. The woman, Renee
Smith, is alleging that more men than women receive waivers from
the NCAA of its ``postbaccalaureate bylaw,'' which bars graduate
students from continuing in intercollegiate competition. The
association argues that it is not covered by Title IX.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   These were among the court's other new cases:
</P>
<P>
   NEWCOMERS' WELFARE
</P>
<P>
   Accepting an appeal filed by the State of California, the court
agreed to decide whether states can constitutionally place special
limits on the welfare benefits they make available to new
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Such two-tiered benefit levels were authorized by Congress in
the 1996 welfare law, and several states have adopted them.
California has been in the forefront of this effort. At issue in
this case, Anderson vs. Roe, No. 98-97, is a 1992 state law, the
subject of a long-running lawsuit, under which new residents who
receive public assistance are limited during the first 12 months to
the benefit level they would be receiving in their home state.
California has the sixth-highest benefit level in the country,
according to its Supreme Court brief.
</P>
<P>
   The state is appealing from an injunction issued last year by
the federal district court in Los Angeles and upheld by the 9th
U.S. Court of Appeals, in San Francisco. The lead plaintiff is a
woman who moved to California from Oklahoma, where she had never
received public assistance. When she became eligible for welfare in
California, she would have received $565 a month but was informed
that her grant would be held to Oklahoma's level of $307.
</P>
<P>
   In blocking California from putting the law into effect, the
appeals court said there was ``persuasive authority'' for finding
it unconstitutional under Supreme Court precedents holding that the
constitutional right to travel protects people from being
discriminated against on the basis of their state of origin. In its
Supreme Court appeal, the state is arguing that people remain free
to travel or move to California but that ``California is not
obliged to fund the exercise of a constitutional right.''
</P>
<P>
   REDISTRICTING REDUX
</P>
<P>
   Revisiting a familiar subject in a familiar setting, the court
agreed for the third time in five years to review the
constitutionality of a North Carolina congressional district's
boundaries, which a 5-4 majority earlier denounced as a racial
gerrymander.
</P>
<P>
   In its current incarnation, the case that was originally known
as Shaw vs. Reno is called Hunt vs. Cromartie, No. 98-85, and is an
appeal by the state on behalf of a district that has been
substantially redrawn by the state legislature to accommodate the
court's concerns. That district, the 12th, still narrow and still
connecting black population centers along the Interstate 85
corridor, no longer has a majority of black voters. It is 54
percent white and is 95 miles long, compared with its original 160
miles. The state argued in response to the latest challenge by a
group of white voters that the new lines had been drawn not
primarily for reasons of race but to preserve the district's
Democratic majority. Nonetheless a federal district court ruled in
April that the district was ``race-driven'' and consequently
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   In its series of decisions beginning with Shaw vs. Reno in 1993,
the Supreme Court has not upheld any of the challenged districts.
The court's ruling in this latest case may well indicate to states
facing redistricting after the next census what the rules will be:
specifically, how states are to balance their obligations under the
Voting Rights Act to insure racial fairness in the electoral
process with the constitutional constraints the court has placed on
their ability to take race into account.
</P>
<P>
   SEARCHING OF PASSENGERS
</P>
<P>
   The court, accepting an appeal by the State of Wyoming, agreed
to decide whether the police can search the personal belongings of
a passenger when they stop a car for a traffic violation. In this
case, Wyoming vs. Houghton, No. 98-184, the state police stopped a
car for speeding and acquired probable cause to search the car when
they saw a syringe in the driver's shirt pocket.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to searching the car and patting down the three
occupants, they searched a closed purse belonging to one of the
passengers, Sandra Houghton, who as a result of the search was
convicted of possessing methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling earlier this year, the Wyoming Supreme Court
overturned the conviction and held that in the absence of any
reason to suspect the passenger of a crime, the search violated the
Fourth Amendment's prohibition against unreasonable searches. The
Supreme Court has not ruled directly on the passenger search issue,
but the Wyoming court cited a 1979 Supreme Court precedent holding
that the search of a customer on the premises of a restaurant that
the police had a warrant to search violated the Fourth Amendment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
