u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-7     09-29 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERT FOR MICROSOFT HELPS FIGHT ONE OF ITS SUBPOENAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (mk) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The software industry is a notoriously fast, fluid business,
with today's friend becoming tomorrow's foe. So too, it seems, for
the industry's most famous defendant, Microsoft Corp., in its
pretrial preparations.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft recently selected Richard Schmalensee, a distinguished
economist and professor at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, as its expert witness to explain why the huge software
company is a national asset and not a monopolistic predator. He
will testify before Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson of U.S. District
Court in Washington, who will hear the antitrust case filed against
Microsoft by the government and 20 states.
</P>
<P>
   But Schmalensee is also helping to fight a subpoena filed last
week by Microsoft's lawyers in preparation for the trial, scheduled
to begin Oct. 15. MIT and Harvard University filed a motion on
Friday in a federal court in Boston to stop Microsoft from
obtaining the interview tapes and transcripts for a book written by
two business school professors, one from MIT and the other from
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   As the acting dean of MIT's Sloan School of Management,
Schmalensee told Michael Cusumano, a Sloan professor of management
and co-author of the book, to fiercely resist the Microsoft
subpoena. ``He put on his dean's hat and advised me not to hand
anything over,'' Cusumano said.
</P>
<P>
   An assistant to Schmalensee said Tuesday that he was unavailable
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The book research sought by Microsoft involves nearly 200 hours
of tape-recorded sessions and more than 2,000 pages of interview
transcripts with current and former executives of Netscape
Communications Corp. The Microsoft legal team wants the materials
to try to show that Microsoft's rise in the market for Internet
browsing software was more a result of Netscape's mistakes than of
any alleged misconduct by Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling on another subpoena, Microsoft won a round Tuesday.
Jackson ordered that Oracle Corp. had to hand over to Microsoft
documents concerning agreements it has with other companies,
including Apple Computer, IBM and others. Microsoft is seeking the
information to try to show that Microsoft meetings the government
has characterized as efforts to thwart competition are actually
commonplace in the industry, where competitors often cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   The book, which will be shipped by Simon and Schuster to stores
within days of the start of the trial, is titled ``Competing on
Internet Time: Lessons from Netscape and Its Battle with
Microsoft.'' The other author was David Yoffie, a professor at
Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   The book does document Netscape's missteps, but Yoffie said he
also thought that Microsoft's extremely aggressive business
practices in the Internet software market had almost invited a
strong reaction from the government.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing that he was not making a legal judgment, Yoffie
said, ``I think Microsoft could have achieved 90 percent of what it
did without crossing the line as much as it did.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be up to the federal courts to decide whether Microsoft
violated any laws. But legal experts said that pointing out the
mistakes of competitors is a standard line of defense in antitrust
cases. It was used successfully in private antitrust cases by Xerox
in the 1970s and Eastman Kodak in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the shot-yourself-in-the-foot defense,'' said Stephen
Axinn, a leading antitrust litigator. ``Microsoft will argue that
it is not a predatory monopolist but that Netscape was its own
worst enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the court will have a great measure of discretion on how
much of a role competitor information will play in the case. It
could weigh heavily, or the court could decide that the real issue
is not Netscape's mistakes but Microsoft's use of its market power,
Axinn said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard and MIT assert that Microsoft's subpoena of the writers'
materials poses a threat to the First Amendment rights of the
authors and to the integrity of academic research. The Harvard
Business School curriculum, Yoffie observed, is based on case
studies of corporations. The quality of that work, he added, rests
on the ability of the researchers to assure corporate executives
that confidential information will remain confidential.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Our whole research process at Harvard is put at risk by
this,'' Yoffie said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft obtained a copy of the manuscript in early September
through a subpoena issued to Netscape. The authors had given a
couple of Netscape executives copies of the manuscript to read and
review confidentially. On Sept. 18, Microsoft asked the authors to
hand over their tapes and notes voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our response was, `Not on your life,''' Yoffie said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the authors did offer a compromise: Allow a third party
to review the tapes to verify the accuracy of the quotations from
Netscape executives. Microsoft rejected that proposal and
subpoenaed the materials four days later.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Microsoft will prevail remains uncertain. Massachusetts
has a ``shield'' law that affords writers some protection for
confidential sources and unpublished research materials. But that
protection is generally less for academics than it is for print
journalists, and legal experts describe the law as weak.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, legal experts added, will try to override the shield
law by saying that the authors' research is crucial to its defense
and cannot be obtained elsewhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
