</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT IS THIRD-AND-FUN FOR JOHNSON'S DOLPHINS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jimmy Johnson replaced Tom Landry as head coach in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Johnson replaced Don Shula as head coach in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Johnson sure knows how to pick his spots. He does not
follow the Rich Kotites or the Ray Handleys. He picks these sunny
places where coaching legends reside and where franchises have won
but have begun to slide. He picks high-profile jobs and then, like
a sweeping storm, stirs things up and brings his own brash style of
bruising football to town. Fun football, too.
</P>
<P>
   It was not that way, at first, in Miami. His first season, the
team was 8-8. Last year, it was 9-7 and lost in the first round of
the playoffs. Dolphin fans were wondering what had happened to
Johnson's magic touch.
</P>
<P>
   But for Johnson, the third season has been his charm.
</P>
<P>
   In his third season at the University of Miami, he went 11-1. In
his third season at Dallas, the Cowboys went 11-5 and won a playoff
game.
</P>
<P>
   It is his third season in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins are 3-0, and it is a healthy 3-0. It is another
team full of Johnson trademarks _ aggressive, gambling, attacking,
confident, arrogant, run-oriented and swift on defense. Playmakers
galore. Charming, really. The Jets get an up-close look when the
Dolphins visit on Sunday at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson looked around after last season and saw a team that had
too many remnants of the Shula era. A team still relying on
quarterback Dan Marino's arm to make everything right. So, Johnson
dismissed his offensive coordinator, Gary Stevens, put Kippy Brown,
the running backs coach, in his place, and simply told his team, in
essence: ``Quit being wimps! We're going to take this ball and
shove it! Get physical! Knock some people on their rears!''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins listened.
</P>
<P>
   What choice did they have?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a team now that loves to challenge you,'' Dolphins
cornerback Terrell Buckley said. ``We aren't making the mistakes we
used to because now the thinking part has given way to just playing
football. What you see right now is what you're going to see in
Week 13, and after that. Challenge the other guy, that's what Jimmy
says. Keep attacking. Do not retreat.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, this is wonderful philosophy but it goes nowhere without
talented players, first, and then without guys who have the mental
makeup to provide staying power. This is where Johnson separates
himself from most coaches. He identifies players who not only have
talent, but will. Take linebacker Zach Thomas. He was a fifth-round
pick out of Texas Tech. But he has become the soul of the defense.
He makes the calls at the snap. He stays in the lineup in the
nickel, pass defense. A lot of coaches passed on Thomas. Not
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Take this year's rookie crop of defensive players, including end
Kenny Mixon (6 feet 4 inches, 273 pounds) and Lorenzo Bromell (6-6,
265). Big, quick players. Mixon, from Louisiana State, was the 49th
player selected in last year's draft; Clemson's Bromell was the
102d. They were there long enough for several coaches to swipe
them. But it was Johnson who nabbed them, and both are contributing
instant big plays.
</P>
<P>
   And then, in free agency, Johnson had got offensive guard Kevin
Donnalley from the Tennessee Oilers. Donnalley is a solid presence
on the field and in the locker room. An intuitive player and
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson drafted running back John Avery from Mississippi last
spring, and that resulted in a rejuvenated and refocused Karim
Abdul-Jabbar. He has averaged nearly 100 yards rushing in each of
the Dolphins' first three games. And he is a Jet killer. Three of
his eight career 100-yard rushing games have come against the Jets,
as have two of his top four rushing performances.
</P>
<P>
   It is the defense, though, that makes the 1998 Dolphins look
strong.
</P>
<P>
   The defense led the way in Miami's last game before its bye last
weekend, a 21-0 victory over Pittsburgh where it limited Pittsburgh
to 200 yards. Miami has limited its last two opponents to fewer
than 100 yards passing. That last happened for Miami 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This defense is allowing only 7.3 points a game _ the best in
the National Football League. It has produced 13 sacks, while the
Dolphins have allowed only 3. It has forced eight turnovers, while
the Miami offense has committed only two.
</P>
<P>
   Here is another testament to the new run-first Dolphins _ of 35
fourth-quarter offensive plays this season, Miami has run the ball
28 times. With Marino? Unheard of.
</P>
<P>
   Miami is a league-best 8-1 after bye weeks, and Johnson is 4-0
with the Dolphins against the Jets, including 31-20 and 24-17
victories last season. The Dolphins have been fast starters under
Johnson in each of his two previous seasons, but wavered at the
finish. This team does not look as if it will follow suit. It is
built on defense and on the running game. Those are staples in
football that have stood the sternest test.
</P>
<P>
   And so has Jimmy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   They laughed at him that first year in Miami _ why, he did no
better than Shula. They scoffed at him last season when his team
struggled and then made the playoffs and then wilted at New
England.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the third season.
</P>
<P>
   Charming times.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
