<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1016 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANE-30-COX     09-29 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANE-30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What remains of Georges moving slowly to east
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore and Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The whirlwind that was Georges moved
sluggishly across the South on Tuesday, dumping heavy rains on
South Alabama, southeastern Georgia and the Florida Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   Roads in Alabama flooded, lights winked out as far north as
Montgomery, and coastal residents from Louisiana to Florida found
beach houses, piers and businesses badly damaged by wind and storm
surges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had waterfront property, waterback property, waterside
property, water-everywhere property,'' said 43-year-old postal
worker Jayne Howell, who found her brick ranch house in Pascagoula,
Miss., awash in sewage, seaweed and branches.
</P>
<P>
   But as bad as it was, said many of the returning evacuees, it
threatened to be much, much worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Pascagoula River at Merrill rose from 3.4 feet on Monday to
20.8 feet on Tuesday and was expected to swell to more than 26.5
feet later in the day, nearly 5 feet over flood stage.
</P>
<P>
   Some parts of the Alabama coast had received 2 1/2 feet of rain
in addition to damaging wind. At the Dog River south of Mobile,
more than 100 boats capsized or were damaged.
</P>
<P>
   In the Panhandle Tuesday, the maddening staying power of Georges
also brought rivers out of their banks and swamped homes, farms and
Interstate 10.
</P>
<P>
   The storm's initial impact caused $50 million in property damage
to the Pensacola area, Insurance Commissioner Bill Nelson estimated
after surveying the city. That was a modest amount, about
one-fourth the estimated damage in the Keys. About half the damage
was from wind and half from rain, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seafood wholesaler Phil Rollo in Milton, Fla., said the real
damage will not be known for days or weeks as millions of gallons
of rainwater pour into the Gulf of Mexico, diluting the salt level
and dumping tons of silt and agricultural runoff. Crabs, shrimp and
oysters are all affected in various ways, either killed outright,
driven to deeper water or made unsafe to eat, he said. He
anticipated a delay in the opening of oyster season Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll probably keep the beds closed for two weeks before
they allow anyone to harvest _ if there's anything to harvest,''
Rollo said. ``I don't have any insurance. I'm at the mercy of all
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The flooding does not present a major threat to human life
because relatively few homes are in the flood zones, said Mark
O'Biren, spokesman for the Escambia County emergency operations
center. What flooding reaches populated areas is expected to be
manageable.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of carpets are probably going to get wet,'' O'Biren
said.
</P>
<P>
   State emergency management officials reported that rain at
Milton measured 25 inches with more on the way. Tornadoes spawned
by the thundershowers embedded in the storm struck Escambia, Bay
and Walton counties, destroying five homes in Panama City Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Wind damage from Georges combined with an earlier drought to
wipe out 75 percent of the cotton crop in Escambia County, said
county extension agent Lamar Christenberry. That's worth about $1.2
million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There was concern that floodwater might affect 600 acres of
catfish farming in the area by carrying sewer overflow, fertilizers
or silt that might harm the fish, but there was no evidence of
damage by Tuesday night, Christenberry said.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Department of Environmental Regulation will send
agents today to survey damage near Pensacola, a spokesman in
Tallahassee said. The federal Environmental Protection Agency
already has officials in the area but was not ready to offer an
assessment, a spokesman in Atlanta said.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate 10 was closed because of flooding near Crestview,
Fla., Tuesday, adding to traffic problems already caused by I-10's
shutdown at the Florida-Alabama border.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding along the Shoal River south of Crestview was expected
to close State Road 85, the main link between that city and Fort
Walton Beach, said Nancy Hussong, a spokeswoman at the Okaloosa
County Emergency Operations Center.
</P>
<P>
   Homes scattered along the Escambia, Shoal, Yellow and Blackwater
rivers also were threatened in a three-county area. State
meteorologist Andrew Devanas said the rivers were expected to crest
at record levels in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Accumulated rainwater collapsed the auditorium roof of the
Northwood Elementary School in Crestview.
</P>
<P>
   High water covered a causeway, isolating some residents on
Innerarity Island in the Intercoastal Waterway west of Pensacola.
</P>
<P>
   The damage to Perdido Key, one of the barrier islands near
Pensacola, did not appear to be severe. A four-story condominium
was heavily damaged by a tornado, but most of the other damage
involved pieces of siding and roof tiles falling off of buildings.
Police allowed residents to visit their homes but not to stay
there, enforcing a 6:30 p.m. curfew.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Lawton Chiles announced that for the fifth time this year,
President Clinton has approved an emergency declaration for
Florida, making grants and loans available to those who suffered
damage.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,800 National Guard forces have been called up for
active duty in four Gulf Coast states to help deal with the
aftermath of the hurricane, the Pentagon said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The guard forces in Florida, Alabama, Mississippi and Louisiana
will help local authorities in sandbagging, evacuation, debris
removal, cleanup operations and other efforts, said Pentagon
spokesman Navy Capt. Michael Doubleday. The U.S. Corps of Engineers
also has procured 1.25 million sandbags for the flood-fighting
effort along the Gulf Coast and five military medical teams are on
the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Georges swept through the Florida Keys, causing an estimated
$200 million in damage, and then skirted the Panhandle for two
days, making landfall Monday in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Two deaths in a traffic accident and a house fire were blamed on
Georges.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the storm, about 95,000 homes and businesses
were without power in the western Panhandle. About 55,000 were
restored as of midday Tuesday, and most of the remaining 40,000
were expected to have their lights back on by the end of the day,
Gulf Power Co. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Gulf Coast, it will be awhile before the damage is
added up. Some places suffered greatly, but overall, Georges was
not a catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who fled were going back. In Mississippi, the Red
Cross' shelter population of more than 15,000 was dropping
throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Riverboat casinos in Gulfport and Biloxi, Miss., lost $12.5
million in gaming revenues over the weekend, of which the state of
Mississippi would have taken $1.5 million in taxes, a spokeswoman
said. She said it would probably be at least a week before the
casinos reopened.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Elmore and Shirish Date write for the Palm Beach Post,
West Palm Beach, Fla. Staff reports and our wire services
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
