<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1017 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORNELL-DUCHAMP-ART-2     09-29 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORNELL-DUCHAMP-ART-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORNELL AND DUCHAMP: A FAN CLUB OF JUST TWO  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DEBORAH SOLOMON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Friendships between artists seldom receive
serious attention. We assume them to be mostly trivial, a web of
anecdote and gossip. They evoke visions of chummy evenings at the
Cedar bar, the Cafe Deux Magots and other bohemian landmarks _
scenarios, more often than not, that involve a lot of scotch and
draw to a close when an artist either passes out or sneaks out the
door with his pal's favorite model.
</P>
<P>
   Yet not enough has been said about the ways in which artists
sustain one another. Joseph Cornell and Marcel Duchamp, those
connoisseurs of the commonplace object, provided a rapt audience
for each other long before the rest of the world acknowledged their
quirky brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   Joining together in the avant-garde 40s, they formed their own
fan club of two. Their intense, cryptic, and appropriately
eccentric friendship is now the subject of ``Joseph Cornell/Marcel
Duchamp: In Resonance,'' an exhibition opening Thursday at the
Philadelphia Museum of Art and remaining on view through Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, they were an unlikely pair. Duchamp, the founder
of the Dada movement, was a poised and worldly Frenchman who
conducted his career as if for his own entertainment. He penciled a
mustache on a picture of the Mona Lisa, exhibited a urinal as a
work of art, and enacted the ultimate Dada prank when he announced,
in 1923, that he was abandoning art for chess.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, he didn't really give up art, but he did, in a way,
give up on himself, settling for the tiny rewards of irony. Asked
how he spent his time, he invariably replied that he was content to
be just a ``respirateur,'' or breather.
</P>
<P>
   If Duchamp was the class jester of 20th-century art, Cornell was
the class loner. A thin, diffident wraith of a man, he lived with
his mother and handicapped brother in Flushing, N.Y., spending his
days in a basement workshop, where he arranged metal rings, cutouts
of birds and other frugal objects in small shadow boxes.
</P>
<P>
   He transposed five-and-dime reality into his own brand of
unreality. He did not travel, never married and kept a diary that
detailed his imagined intimacies with Romantic ballerinas of the
19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Duchamp, in other words, was amused by most everything, whereas
Cornell was amused by almost nothing, discerning a wealth of poetic
meaning _ of pathos, even _ in every last Woolworth's trinket.
Nonetheless, they were kindred spirits, glamorizing nonart objects
decades before art went Pop.
</P>
<P>
   Around 1913, Duchamp invented the ``readymade,'' which sounds
like a Betty Crocker recipe and required about as much time to
prepare; the term refers to ordinary objects (a snow shovel, a
bottle rack) unaltered by anything but Duchamp's wit.
</P>
<P>
   In 1936, Cornell conceived the form of the Box, which, compared
with Duchamp's stark one-liners, had the dense inwardness of a
diary.
</P>
<P>
   The two artists met in 1933, but their friendship didn't get
under way until the summer of 1942, when Duchamp sailed to New York
as a refugee from World War II.
</P>
<P>
   What drew them to one another? Duchamp, no doubt, recognized
Cornell as an American original, someone whose life and art were
more genuinely surreal than the calculated, showy weirdness of Dali
and the other Surrealists.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell, in turn, appreciated Duchamp's appreciation, and looked
to the Frenchman (who was 16 years his senior) as a guiding light.
It's true that Cornell had many muses, but most of them, such as
Mallarme or Emily Dickinson, were long dead; lunch dates with them
were out of the question. Duchamp, by contrast, was relatively
available and able to meet Cornell for tea.
</P>
<P>
   The current exhibition, which was organized by Ann Temkin of the
Philadelphia Museum, Susan Davidson of the Menil Collection in
Houston and three other art historians, will bring together about
80 works by Cornell and Duchamp in an effort to track the
affinities between them.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the heart of the show belongs to a never-before-exhibited
object that is not a work of art at all. ``The Duchamp Dossier,''
which was acquired by the Philadelphia Museum in 1990, is an
achingly soulful souvenir, a cardboard box in which Cornell kept
mementos of his friendship with Duchamp. There are 117 items in
all, a mound of yellowed notes, old photographs and wastebasket
relics that together amount to a hidden embrace of a fellow artist.
</P>
<P>
   Here we find Duchamp's empty tobacco box, two of his white pipe
cleaners, and several of his crumpled laundry receipts (why am I
not surprised to learn that this creator of overly sanitized
objects dry-cleaned his handkerchiefs as well as his socks?).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   We see a packet of Domino sugar, inscribed with the date of a
meeting, and a Horn &AMP; Hardart napkin preserved as if this cafeteria
throwaway were the most delicate and fragrant flower.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Duchamp Dossier'' includes more conventional mementos as
well _ gallery announcements, postcards of the Mona Lisa, letters
and the like. Yet the correspondence between the two artists
probably conceals more than it reveals.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1946, on the eve of sailing for Paris, Duchamp wrote
Cornell with typical brevity, ``Au revoir/affectueusement Marcel.''
</P>
<P>
   What can a stash of dusty paper scraps tell us about art and its
mysterious ways? At the very least, the ``Dossier'' provides a bit
of scholarly news, confirming a long-rumored collaboration between
the two artists.
</P>
<P>
   Newly unearthed notes and receipts (``Dear Cornell/Here's the
$3.75 that I'm sorry has taken so long to send you'') indicate that
Duchamp hired Cornell to help assemble one of his most engaging
projects, ``Box in a Valise.''
</P>
<P>
   A dream accessory for the wartime exile, it consists of an
edition of little suitcases, each containing miniature
reproductions of Duchamp's key works. If he had to run, he was
ready.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell, in other words, helped pack Duchamp's bags, assisting
the peripatetic Frenchman on a singular creative flight. It's a
lovely notion, yet was it a gesture of grave artistic consequence?
Well, Cubism it was not, to cite the product of an historic
collaboration between Picasso and Braque, who claimed to be ``roped
together like mountaineers.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornell and Duchamp, by contrast, joked together like
musketeers. The very slightness of their collaboration seems
fitting. All in all, they made a virtue of marginalities, and their
ephemera has proven to have as durable a shelf life as any of the
art of this century.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition at the Philadelphia Museum would undoubtedly have
surprised both artists. Every friendship has secret corners, but
theirs had a secret box at its center.
</P>
<P>
   Duchamp, apparently, was unaware of the ``Dossier,'' never
suspecting that Cornell was riffling through his wastebasket for
train ticket stubs and other choice detritus to squirrel away at
home. You might say that Cornell did to Duchamp what Duchamp did to
civilization, singling out discards and imbuing them with an
unexpected weight.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense that Cornell never showed the ``Dossier'' to
Duchamp. He compiled it strictly for his own eyes, not to display
to the world. He had a great talent for admiration, and the
fetishized relics of his friendship with Duchamp bespeak an ardor
that was so complete it left no room for irony.
</P>
<P>
   How, one wonders, might Duchamp have responded if Cornell had
one day pulled out the ``Dossier'' from a drawer and shared its
worshipful contents with him?
</P>
<P>
   Ever amused, Duchamp might have chuckled, or just laughed
Cornell off the planet. We, however, are glad that this object has
come to light and can afford to be touched, knowing how rare such
homages are.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
