<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PENSIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENSION-FUND LOSSES RAISE QUESTIONS ON RISKY CHOICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts' employee pension fund, one of the most
aggressive in the country for investing in stocks, lost a record
$2.3 billion when the market deflated in August, more than erasing
its gains for the year, records show.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic drop has triggered discussion among the fund's
board members and the two candidates seeking to replace outgoing
Treasurer Joseph D. Malone, who oversees the fund, over whether the
now-$21.2 billion retirement account should take a more
conservative investment approach.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of August, one of the most tumultuous months for the
stock market, the state fund lost nearly 10 percent of its value,
falling from $23.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Although the size of the monthly loss would appear to be
alarming, analysts say investors should focus on long-term _ not
short-term _ results, which have been healthy. Moreover, the state
is hardly alone as the stock market in the last two months has made
victims of the most sophisticated investors.
</P>
<P>
   The state fund's loss, on a percentage basis, was smaller than
that of the Standard &AMP; Poor's Index of 500 stocks as well as those
of similar-sized public investment funds.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the substantial losses have done nothing to curb
the appetite of the fund's directors for equity investments, which
account for nearly all the recent losses. The Public Retirement
Investment Trust Board overwhelmingly decided last week to continue
investing heavily in stocks, which make up more than 50 percent of
the fund's allocation. The state pension fund ranks among the top
public investment funds in the country for its heavy reliance on
stocks, both foreign and domestic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost unanimous among the board members that the asset
allocation is an allocation that we should stay the course with,
recognizing that under a market such as the one in recent months,
that our losses would be greater than a more conservative
portfolio,'' said PRIT board member Ralph White, who is also
president of the Retired State, County &AMP; Municipal Employees
Association of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the directors point out the modest stock market
bounceback in September has already helped the fund recover some of
its July and August losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through this before and over a period of time it's
been proven our approach is the right approach for the PRIT fund,''
said White. ``There will be no change.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fund has never taken such a teeth-shattering punch. Even
during the stock market crash of October 1987, the pension fund
lost about 3 percent of its value, which was quickly recovered.
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio's worst setback so far this year was in the risky
emerging markets _ affected by the economic crises in Russia, Asia,
and Latin America. About $613 million of public workers' retirement
money is invested in that segment of the fund, which lost a
stunning 34 percent in 1998 as of Aug. 31, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly $9.1 billion _ the largest concentration of money in the
portfolio _ is invested in domestic stocks, which lost 6 percent
for the year as of the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate and alternative investments were the only bright
spots in the portfolio, averaging about a 10 percent return so far
this year. Fixed income, the most conservative branch of the
portfolio with about $6 billion invested in it, gained 4.3 percent.
And international stocks gained just 1.2 percent during the first
eight months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   None of those gains were enough to make up for the problems in
emerging markets and domestic stocks.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, the fund is down 1.44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's one-year performance was a disappointing 2.2 percent.
But the five-year return, considered a more valuable measure by the
industry, was 12.05 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Fehrnstrom, a spokesman for the treasurer, defended the
aggressiveness of the fund, saying a longer-term strategy is
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the increase in our exposure to equities that has helped
us build up the assets in the fund,`` Fehrnstrom said. ``When we
arrived (in 1991) the fund was inappropriately weighted toward
fixed income securities and we changed that... But we don't make
longterm investment decisions based on short-term developments.
Already in September there has been a partial recovery of the
losses for July and August.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first two quarters of the year _ before the tumultuous
summer on Wall Street _ the fund was up 11.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the sudden jolt at the fund has set the two candidates for
treasurer debating the best approach for handling the retirement
account for state and public workers.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Shannon O'Brien, a former legislator, would take a more
conservative approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shannon knows that their current equity position is among the
most aggressive for public plans in the country. And Shannon also
knows that controlling risk is vitally important when you're
managing employee pension plans,'' said Michael Travaglini,
O'Brien's campaign manager. ``But clearly the amount of risk that
(the board) has been willing to take on is something Shannon is
going to look very strongly at.''
</P>
<P>
   Her Republican rival, Bob Maginn, an executive at the consulting
firm Bain &AMP; Co., said he would increase pension investments in
private equities _ such as leveraged buyout funds _ which tend to
have higher returns with lower volatility.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the stop-loss measures should be reviewed so that
some investments can be sold before they lose a significant amount
of value.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think it would be a big mistake in the long term to
become afraid of investing in equities,'' Maginn said. ``The type
of investing that was done in the '80s that was unsophisticated and
earning us low returns, if Shannon takes us back to the (former
treasurer) Bob Crane era of putting money in banks ... I would be
strongly against that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
