A1026 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVENT-SUIT-NYT &LR;      09-29 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVENT-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVENT SAYS SUIT BY DRABINSKY ADDS TO WOES OF SHAREHOLDERS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Livent Inc., the Broadway theater producer, is
arguing in a Canadian court that a lawsuit filed by its founder
threatens to prolong the pain of the company's shareholders who
have been unable to trade their shares since early August because
of an accounting investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Webster, Livent's executive vice president, says that if
Garth Drabinsky, the founder, who is under suspension from his
executive role at Livent, succeeds in stopping the investigation,
by KPMG Canada, it may be many weeks before the company can provide
more information on the extent of its accounting problems.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Canadian stock exchange officials suspended trading of
Livent shares on Aug. 10, saying the company must provide more
information on what Livent has described as millions of dollars of
``irregularities.'' The company suspended Drabinsky and his
partner, Myron Gottlieb, upon discovery of the accounting
breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, who have been locked out of their executive
offices, say they have done nothing wrong. Drabinsky sued KPMG
Canada, a unit of the global accounting and consulting firm,
contending that it has a conflict of interest because for almost 20
years KPMG was Drabinsky's personal accounting firm, filing his
personal tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   But Webster said that KPMG's investigators had told Livent's
directors they did not believe their past work for Drabinsky harmed
their ability to investigate the company's accounts. KPMG has
called Drabinsky's lawsuit ``completely without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   In the affidavit filed on Friday in a provincial court in
Toronto, where Livent is based, Webster also provided new details
on how he discovered the irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Webster, a former KPMG partner hired by new management at Livent
in July, said he became ``greatly concerned'' as he was talking to
the company's accountants and trying to prepare the financial
results for the second quarter. The accountants were reluctant to
talk, Webster said, and ``somewhat evasive'' in answering his
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Some accountants then explained, Webster said, that Drabinsky
``was repeatedly instructing Livent accounting personnel not to
provide certain financial information to me and other members of
new management unless and until he had reviewed and approved it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 6, according to the affidavit, five accountants went to
Webster with additional financial information that ``cast doubt
upon the veracity and accuracy'' of Livent's financial books.
</P>
<P>
   Four days later, when Drabinsky was told about the discovery of
the accounting problems, Webster said that Drabinsky replied that
he was aware of the irregularities. But, by Webster's account,
Drabinsky then said he thought the company had fixed the problem
when it wrote down its assets by tens of millions of dollars in
late 1997 and early 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Webster said, however, that those write-downs were not connected
to the irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Drabinsky's lawyer, L. David Roebuck, called
Webster's comments ``questionable.'' But he said he would not
respond in detail to the statements since the lawsuit had been
filed against KPMG and not against Webster or the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will deal with Webster's allegations,'' he said, ``at the
appropriate time and place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2220EDT &QL; 
