<HEADER>
A1031 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATIONWIDE-INS-REDLIN     09-29 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONWIDE-INS-REDLINING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nationwide Insurance accused of discrimination
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Nationwide Insurance, the country's
fourth-largest insurance company, has illegally discriminated
against some Texans based on their race, ethnicity and age,
according to a state regulator who on Tuesday recommended a record
$10 million fine against the company.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, which denied the allegations, sells auto, homeowners
and other insurance in the Austin, Dallas-Fort Worth, Houston, San
Antonio and Waco-Temple areas. Last year, the Texas Department of
Insurance, prompted by lawmakers and an independent report on
insurance marketing, began investigating Nationwide's sales in all
of its markets except the Waco-Temple area, where offices only
recently were opened.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Haley, an attorney for the department, on Tuesday told
Insurance Commissioner Elton Bomer that the Nationwide
investigation revealed that the company has denied auto insurance
to some Texans based solely on their age. He also said the company
has used a marketing strategy that ``systematically exclude(s)
minority customers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Haley, Nationwide, based in Columbus, Ohio, limits
the areas in which its agents can solicit business based on the
location of its offices. ``The effect of this market strategy is to
steer Nationwide agents away from sales in ZIP code areas where the
population consists predominantly of racial minorities ,'' Haley
said. ``The pattern is consistent in every Texas market where
Nationwide has made its products available.'' Haley did not provide
specifics. A check of Nationwide's Austin-area offices shows all
its Austin offices are west of Interstate 35. Most of the city's
predominantly minority neighborhoods are east of the interstate.
The company also has an office in Round Rock and one near
Pflugerville. Bob Sohovich, an Ohio-based spokesman for Nationwide,
said that before the state's investigation, the company began a new
effort to solicit business in urban areas of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not violated any Texas law,'' Sohovich said. ``We are
not ignoring the issue. We want to serve every section of the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Sohovich added that Nationwide insurance can be purchased over
the telephone and is not limited to direct, agent sales. He said he
did not know whether agents' sales efforts were limited by
territory and could not find out Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As of Dec. 31, Nationwide and its various companies covered 2.6
percent of the insured homes in Texas and about 2.7 percent of the
insured cars. That made the company the state's sixth-largest home
insurer and seventh-largest auto insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1993 state law, specifics about the insurance department
investigation are not public information. For that reason, the
department would not disclose in which ZIP codes it believes
Nationwide has discriminated against residents, the disparity
between the amount of coverage sold in non-minority areas vs. the
number of policies sold in minority-dominated areas or how long it
believes Nationwide has used a marketing strategy that results in
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Haley never used the term redlining, an illegal practice of
denying coverage based only on such things as race, ethnicity,
income and where a person lives. Allegations of redlining would
have to include proof that a company intended to deny coverage to
certain people. Allegations of discrimination can be proved
regardless of intent.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance department spokesman Jim Davis said there are limited
circumstances in which such things as income and where a person
lives can legally be used to determine coverage. The department's
allegations against Nationwide do not fall under those
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Johns, head of the Southwestern Insurance Information
Service, an industry group, said he doesn't believe Nationwide or
any other Texas insurer uses redlining or discriminatory practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We flatly reject any allegations that we practice unfair
discrimination in the sale of our products,'' he said on behalf of
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to recommending a $10 million fine, Haley told Bomer
that he should consider modifying the fine if Nationwide could
prove it was spending money that directly resulted in more policies
being sold in the areas where discrimination has been alleged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of this action is to induce Nationwide to open its
business to everyone in the local markets where it does business,''
he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Birny Birnbaum, an insurance data analyst for the
Center for Economic Justice, said the department's action proves
there is redlining going on in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum has been fighting for access to insurers' marketing
reports that he said would lend more proof to such allegations.
Industry officials have fought the release of the information,
saying it would negatively affect competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious why the insurers don't want it to be available,''
Birnbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   The department's investigation, and calls for action from state
lawmakers, came after the center last year released a report on
redlining using information similar to that for which Birnbaum has
been fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Department officials said they worked on the Nationwide case for
nearly a year and are negotiating for a settlement with the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide has 20 days to formally reply to Haley's letter to
Bomer. If a settlement is not reached, the allegations would be
considered by a state administrative judge before Bomer could levy
a fine or take some other action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope the commissioner acts quickly to stop Nationwide from
these discriminatory actions,'' Birnbaum said. The department also
has investigated five other companies. Action against two is
pending in the department's legal department. A seventh
investigation is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   Juan B. Elizondo Jr. writes for The Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
