<HEADER>
A1032 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-PUBLIC-RECORDS-     09-29 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-PUBLIC-RECORDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Court moves to open its own records
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Facing the court of public opinion, the Texas
Supreme Court issued proposed rules Tuesday that the chief justice
says would open virtually all administrative records kept by state
courts.
</P>
<P>
   The draft rules _ to be reviewed next week in a public hearing
at the Supreme Court _ would open the judges' telephone records for
public inspection, Chief Justice Tom Phillips said. Last year the
court overruled an opinion by Attorney General Dan Morales that
would have required release of telephone records.
</P>
<P>
   The rules would subject to public scrutiny travel and expense
records, visitor logs and judges' personal and business appointment
calendars, for example. The rules would not change access to court
files, which generally are open, but would prevent release of draft
opinions and internal memos on court rules and procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said the proposed rules follow a national trend to
bring courts under open records provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most freedom of information acts excluded the judiciary,
dealing instead with those branches of government that taxed and
spent your money,'' he said. ``There's been a movement in the past
10 years to include the judiciary.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rules come at a time when the court continues to
feel the sting of criticism about its campaign fund-raising rules
that allow contributions from parties and lawyers who have cases
before the court. That practice supposedly has been a focus for
CBS' ``60 Minutes'' as the television news program scrutinizes the
court 10 years after its ``Justice for Sale'' investigation linking
court decisions to campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Borges, who as head of the court-monitoring Texas Watch
consumer-action program is one of the Supreme Court's most vocal
critics, called the proposed rules to open administrative records
``totally inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This court says it wants to move things along, but then it
crafts rules that basically are oriented toward officeholders
instead of the public,'' Borges said.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, he criticized the 14-day period that judges would
have to respond to open records requests _ instead of requiring
prompt release of records _ and lack of criminal sanctions when
records are wrongly denied.
</P>
<P>
   The issuance of the court's rules begins a four-month process to
refine them before they're put into effect. These rules follow
criticism from state legislators after the court's decision last
year that Morales was wrong in deciding that Supreme Court
telephone records kept by the General Services Commission would not
fall under the judiciary exception to the state's open records act.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rules roughly follow suggestions drafted by the
Texas Judicial Council earlier this year at the court's request.
</P>
<P>
   The judicial council, headed by Phillips, includes judges and
other state officials as well as public members outside the legal
profession.
</P>
<P>
   One significant difference is that the Supreme Court dropped a
Judicial Council prohibition against releasing a judge's off-work
appointments. The court proposed that future appointments be
excluded from public release, but not past appointments _ whether
the judge was on his or her own time or not.
</P>
<P>
   Borges called the draft rules a ``double standard'' that
excludes judges from the toothier open- records law applicable to
the rest of state government. ``They're no different from any other
state officials who spend state or county tax money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence, the court is saying, 'Don't bother us. We'll
decide whether we're doing our jobs.' ``
</P>
<P>
   But Phillips said the courts should not fall under a legislative
act for a reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's appropriate for the judicial branch to go
to the executive for rulings,'' he said, referring to the attorney
general's function to interpret open-records disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed rules, a judge's denial of a records request
would be subject to an appeal to a committee of presiding judges.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said those presiding judges _ appointed by the governor
_ provided independence from the rest of the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   A decision by them would not be appealable under the rules _
even if it went against the Supreme Court, he said _ although
someone requesting information might also sue to open court
records.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with that, the chief justice said, would be the
possibility that an action to command the Supreme Court's release
of records would have to be decided by _ the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the same problem you would face under the
open-records act,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Osler McCarthy writes for The Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
