<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINGBOARD MADE OF OAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)(SLANG) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ The 30th Oak Tree Racing Association season
starts small this afternoon with the $100,000 Autumn Days Handicap
sprint on Santa Anita's hillside turf course.
</P>
<P>
   But in the weekends ahead, the names, purses and implications
will grow large as the Oak Tree meet serves again as the West's
springboard to the seven Breeders' Cup races, to be held Nov. 7 at
Churchill Downs in Louisville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   The first three weekends of the six-week meet are packed with
seven Breeders' Cup preps, six of which have produced Breeders' Cup
winners in that event's 15-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The $300,000 Oak Tree Turf Championship on Sunday is expected to
match five horses, including Bonapartiste and River Bay, two of the
leading U.S. candidates for the Breeders' Cup turf.
</P>
<P>
   The $500,000 Goodwood Handicap on Oct. 17, its purse doubled
since last year, might attract Silver Charm, the 1997 Kentucky
Derby winner, and Free House, this summer's Pacific Classic winner.
Silver Charm could go to the Oct. 16 Meadowlands Cup in New Jersey
instead, and Free House could wait for the Oct. 31 California Cup
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   The $200,000 Oak Leaf Stakes for 2-year-old fillies on Oct. 10
and the $200,000 Norfolk Stakes for 2-year-olds on Oct. 11 are the
logical spots for Bob Baffert-trained Excellent Meeting and Worldly
Ways, early favorites for the Breeders' Cup Juvenile Fillies and
the Breeders' Cup Juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   Other Oak Tree races with a historical link to the Breeders'
Cup: the $175,000 Lady's Secret Handicap for fillies and mares on
Oct. 11; the $150,000 Ancient Title Handicap sprint on Oct. 17, and
the $250,000 Oak Tree Mile on turf on Oct. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Horses who came out of Oak Tree have won races on 10 of the 15
Breeders' Cup cards and have competed in 96 of the 105 Breeders'
Cup races. But there's more to Oak Tree than Breeders' Cup preps.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-day season marks the return of major-league thoroughbred
racing to Los Angeles County after 2{ months at Del Mar and little
Fairplex Park in Pomona.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Oak Tree's biggest events come too late in the season to
have anything to do with the Breeders' Cup: the 10 Cal Cup races on
Oct. 31 and the $500,000 Yellow Ribbon Stakes for turf fillies and
mares on Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
   The sentimental story of the meet could be the comeback of 1996
Santa Anita Derby winner Cavonnier two years after beginning
treatment for a tendon injury. He worked 5 furlongs in 58 2/5
seconds Tuesday, is looking for a return race this week and is
pointing for the Cal Cup Mile.
</P>
<P>
   And for fans who prefer big money to big names, Oak Tree is
guaranteeing a $2 million pool for the pick-six on Oct. 10.
</P>
<P>
   OAK TREE AT A GLANCE &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Dates: Today through Nov. 9, 32 days of racing; open every
Wednesday to Sunday, plus Mondays Oct. 12 (Columbus Day) and Nov.
9.
</P>
<P>
   First post: 1 p.m. weekdays, 12:30 p.m. weekends and Mondays,
and noon Oct. 31 (California Cup day).
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Take the Foothill Freeway (210) east to Baldwin
Avenue in Arcadia and drive south.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: General $5, clubhouse $8.50; extra for reserved seat.
Turf club $10 ($15 on weekends), including reserved seat.
</P>
<P>
   Scratches and results: (626) 446-8501.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (626) 574-7223.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
