<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ISLANDERS-COLISEUM-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE FINDS COLISEUM SAFE FOR ISLANDERS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. _ Ending, at least for now, a bitter battle
between the Nassau County Executive and the New York Islanders, a
state judge declared Tuesday that Nassau County Veterans Memorial
Coliseum was safe and that the Islanders must play all their
scheduled home and exhibition games at the arena.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling in state Supreme Court, Justice Burton S. Joseph
noted that engineers hired by the National Hockey League had found
the 26-year-old arena to be safe, and he said that ``any breach of
the team's agreement to play its games at the Coliseum would cause
Nassau County irreparable harm.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 10, contending that Nassau Coliseum was unsafe to play
hockey in, the Islanders moved out of the arena, packing their
office files, furniture and some memorabilia into a convoy of vans.
The team vowed to play its home games at an assortment of arenas
off Long Island, citing concerns that the hoist system for the
22,000-pound scoreboard and sound system posed a safety risk.
</P>
<P>
   Although Joseph urged both sides Tuesday to settle their
differences, his decision amounts to a stinging defeat for the
Islanders, who had filed a federal lawsuit seeking to break their
lease after moving out of the arena, and a victory for County
Executive Thomas S. Gulotta.
</P>
<P>
   Gulotta, who came to the courthouse to hear the ruling, said he
was ``very pleased'' by the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the ruling dealt with the question of whether the
Coliseum is safe, the overriding issue that separates the team and
the county is who will pay for a new arena, which both county
officials and the owners of the team agree is necessary. After the
ruling, Gulotta urged the owners of the Islanders, Howard Milstein
and Steven Gluckstern, to return to the bargaining table so that
negotiations on plans for a new arena could be put ``on the fast
track.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have directed Mort Certilman, Nassau County's negotiator,''
Gulotta said, ``to resume with all due haste, planning for a new
multifaceted sports complex to meet the future needs of the
Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   David Seldin, the president of New York Sports Ventures, which
owns the Islanders, Tuesday called the ruling a tie and said the
team would abide by the judge's ruling. He said that the next
scheduled exhibition game, on Sunday against the Washington
Capitals, would be played at the Coliseum and that, to entice fans
back to the arena, tickets to the game would be free for season
subscribers and $10 for any seat for all other fans. An exhibition
game scheduled for Sept. 25 against the New Jersey Devils was
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Seldin said he was also prepared to return to the bargaining
table if Gulotta's offer was ``in good faith.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The comments on both sides of the issue were quite measured in
comparison with those of the last few weeks. At one point, the
Islanders accused Gulotta and other county officials of ``using the
tactics of felons'' to ``cover up the truth'' about safety issues
at the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Gulotta in turn, described the team as ``a pig at the trough,''
and accused the team's owners of using the safety issue as a ruse
to obtain financial gain at the bargaining table in plans for a new
arena.
</P>
<P>
   Under a plan proposed by Gulotta, a new arena would sit at the
center of a new transportation, business and commercial hub in the
heart of Nassau County. The old Coliseum would become a convention
center. A new hotel and shops would be added to the new complex,
which would be linked by a new transportation system to nearby
colleges and universities, shopping centers, commercial buildings
and shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
   Financing for the project remains elusive. Although the state
has promised $30 million to help build a new arena, county
taxpayers are reluctant to help pay for it. Gulotta had said he
would prefer that funds come from the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Seldin said Tuesday's ruling supported some of the team's
contentions. He noted that the judge said the engineers hired by
the league to inspect the Coliseum had given the court a list of
seven items that required maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous safety problems, including the hoist system, he said,
have already been repaired by the county and by the Spectacor
Management Group, the company that manages the Coliseum for the
county, since a series of legal actions were initiated by both the
Islanders and the county earlier this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
