<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1044 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-PETTITTE-     09-29 0274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-PETTITTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE WORKS THROUGH SEASON OF STRUGGLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By KATHY KUDRAVI 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although Andy Pettitte struggled all year, including
an un-Pettitte like 1-3 September, New York Yankees manager Joe
Torre had no qualms about starting him in today's Game 2 of the
Division Series against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stuff is as good now as it has been this season,'' Torre
said. ``I think a common thread (in Pettitte's struggles) has been
his striving for perfection, and he's not satisfied with what he
sees.
</P>
<P>
   ``A perfect game is probably the only way he'll be satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing the Rangers once this season, Pettitte gave up seven hits
in a 6-4 victory Aug. 14 at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte tried working through his problems by focusing on one
part of his pitching in each start. But work with the Yankees
coaches helped rebuild Pettitte's confidence to the point that his
relief appearance against Tampa Bay on Sept. 25 was comfortable for
the left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I am a perfectionist, and that's one of my faults,''
said Pettitte, who is from Deer Park. ``I've been up here four
years and really haven't struggled until now. But I don't get down
on myself; it's not me.''
</P>
<P>
   One possible explanation for Pettitte's struggles this season
could be that he has been buzzed by several balls hit right back at
him. ``It's more mental than anything,'' he said. ``Every time the
ball comes, you flinch more, and it can definitely affect you. I
didn't feel like it was, but maybe I was trying to finish in a
better fielding position.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1046 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CEREAL-BOXES-ANTIQUES     09-29 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEREAL-BOXES-ANTIQUES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE BREAKFAST OF CHAMPIONS, `CEREALECTIBLES'  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Mass.)   (af)  
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the days when Roy Rogers cantered down happy trails and Howdy
Doody was the national timekeeper for the 10-and-under set, what
commanded attention around the breakfast table was what was in the
brightly colored cardboard box: sugary, crunchy cereal that could
be drowned in milk, crowned with fruit or aimed in the direction of
an annoying brother or sister.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is the box that is commanding attention on the nostalgia
market. Brightly-colored cereal boxes that cost 29 cents with the
cereal inside sell for $200 or $300 in good condition.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Bruce calls these artifacts of post-World War II America
``cerealectibles.'' He has been measuring, dating and cataloguing
them for the last several years and has just published the second
volume of a planned trilogy, ``Cereal Boxes and Prizes: 1960's''
(Flake World Publishing).
</P>
<P>
   He is also exploring the idea of building a home for his
collection of thousands of boxes. What he has in mind is a cereal
museum in Florida, near Disney World or Universal Studios.
</P>
<P>
   And no wonder. ``The cerealectibles market is largely character
driven,'' he said. ``The more popular the featured 'toon, athlete
or critter, the higher the price the item will command when sold or
traded.''
</P>
<P>
   So a box of Kellogg's OK's from 1961 with Yogi Bear flexing his
muscles is worth $150 to $300, and a ``Happy Birthday Yogi'' box of
Kellogg's Corn Flakes from 1962 is worth $200 to $500. A box of
Post Pebbles from 1969 with Fred Flintstone is worth as much as
$175.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the plainer 1950s, cereal marketing was clearly tied to
Madison Avenue hucksterism. ``Kids! Wear the Sign of Superman!''
screamed a box of Kellogg's Corn Flakes from 1955 that carried a
mail-in coupon for the ``Superman Official Belt and Buckle.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce said that the cereal box was worth $250 and the red-vinyl
belt, which originally cost 25 cents, $200.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce takes note of brands that have long since been forgotten,
like Post Sugar Cornfetti, now valued at $125. He also turned up
reminders of the Cold War: Cheerios offered a model of an atomic
submarine (``actually shoots torpedoes'') for 50 cents in 1958.
That box is now worth $50, Bruce said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheerios was also packaged in a box that could be cut and folded
into a model of an airport with an ``airport missile station,'' a
cluster of little plastic rockets around a radar dish. Bruce said
the complete installation was worth $300.
</P>
<P>
   Before Bruce, 44, became `` Cereal Box'' he was `` Lunch Box.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, he was, as he put it, ``an official artist'' _ a
sculptor running a gallery in Boston. He was also bored. ``My job
was becoming more and more administrative, writing grants for more
whining artists,'' he recalled. ``I said, `Enough.' I knew nothing
about collectibles but didn't think you had to be rocket scientist
to thrive in that field, so I decided to create a collectibles
craze.''
</P>
<P>
   He spent six months rummaging through flea markets, garage sales
and antique shows. ``I knew I had to come up with a commodity that
reflected the electronic landscape of my generation, the TV
shows,'' he said. And then he found a Jetsons lunch box in a thrift
shop in Cambridge, Mass., and soon he was crisscrossing the
country, becoming the Nelson Bunker Hunt of lunch box collectors.
</P>
<P>
   He began writing two books. ``By the time they came out I had
amassed this huge collection, and lo and behold I caught a wave and
lunch boxes became one of the defining collectibles if not the
defining collectibles of the '80s.''
</P>
<P>
   But he decided to cash out. He even sold the words `` Lunch
Box'' to an electrician in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that out of a generation of 80 million boomers,
fewer than 25 percent carried lunch boxes. The rest were brown
baggers. I was looking for something that had more universal
appeal. I realized the real mother lode of nostalgia was the
breakfast table. Every child in America had breakfast, read the
back of a cereal box and dreamed about sending away for this or
that toy. I thought if I could tap into that, I really would be
somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no market, he said, ``just a handful of passionate
collectors.'' Cereal companies had little interest in packaging or
in hiring archivists. He went to what he calls ``the cereal
cities'' _ Battle Creek, Mich. (where Kellogg's offered tours of
its corn-flake factory until the mid-1980s); Niagara Falls (where
Nabisco made Shredded Wheat); Buffalo (where General Mills packaged
a variety of cereals for the Northeast); Memphis (where Kellogg's
did the same for the South); Lancaster, Pa. (where Kellogg's and
Quaker had factories); Cedar Rapids, Iowa (where Quaker made Cap'n
Crunch, among other cereals), and St. Louis (the home of Ralston
Purina). He advertised in local newspapers, offering to buy old
cereal boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The process was something of an education for Bruce, who was not
a big cereal eater as a child. His own children appear to be
following in his footsteps. When he interviewed Thurl Ravenscroft,
the deep voice of Tony the Tiger since the 1950s, he asked
Ravenscroft to tape a gr-r-r-eat big hello to Bruce's 7-year-old
son Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   Ravenscroft obliged. Bruce went home and hit the play buttom.
``Nicholas looked at me and said, `Who's Tony the Tiger?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
