<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, SEPTEMBER 30
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-ARAFAT-U.N.-NYT (moved on Monday, September 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, September
28, about Yasir Arafat's speech at the United Nations omitted a
passage in a quotation. The quotation should have said: ``I would
like to call upon all of you, from this place, the source of
international legitimacy and peacemaking, the guardian of freedom,
security and stability, and the source for the achievement of
justice and prosperity for humankind, to stand by our people,
especially as the five-year transitional period provided for in the
Palestinian-Israeli agreements will end on 4 May 1999 and our
people demand of us to shoulder our responsibilities, and they wait
the establishment of their independent state.''
</P>
<P>
   BC-GERMANY-VOTE-NYT (moved on Sunday, September 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, September
28, about the German election misstated the percentage of Germans
who are unemployed. It is 10.6 percent of the workforce, not 10.6
percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   BC-IRAN-U.S.-NYT (moved on Monday, September 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, September
28, about a speech in New York by the Iranian Foreign Minister,
Kamal Kharrazi, misstated the American policy with which he is
displeased. It is the policy toward Iran, not toward Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   BC-GERMANY-EUROPE-NYT (moved on Sunday, September 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, September
27, about European leaders' reaction to the German election
misidentified the major European country governed by conservative
parties. It is Spain, not Italy.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MET-OPERA-ENDOW-NYT (moved on Monday, September 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, September
28, about the Metropolitan Opera's $200 million endowment campaign
misidentified an earlier donor. She was Martha Baird Rockefeller,
the second wife of John D. Rockefeller Jr., not his first wife,
Abby Aldrich Rockefeller.
</P>
</TEXT>
