<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0413 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT &LR;      09-29 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: PRICELINE.COM EXPANDS TO HOTELS; NEW SWISS
AIRLINE; SHUTTLE'S NEW BOSTON HOME; TRAIN TO COPENHAGEN AIRPORT;
HOTEL UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.J., Mass., Ill., Colo.)  (Also moved in ``t'' category.) 
(lb) 
 By JANET PIORKO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Priceline.com, the Internet buying service that tries to book
flights for travelers at prices they propose, is planning to do the
same thing with hotels starting next month.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jay Walker, vice chairman of the company, rooms
will be offered by late October at more than 1,000 hotels in 26
cities nationwide, including Dallas, Houston, New York, Los
Angeles, San Francisco, Chicago, Denver, Seattle, Boston and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes to add more U.S. cities later this year and
international destinations next year. Walker would not name the
participating hotels but said all would be major chain properties.
</P>
<P>
   The process will be similar to the way Priceline books airline
seats. Using the company's World Wide Web site (www.priceline.com),
travelers will select a city and a geographical zone within it,
travel dates, the amount of money they are willing to pay and a
minimum category of hotel desired. The categories, from two-star to
five-star, will be described on the site.
</P>
<P>
   The company's computer will scan its database in an attempt to
find a hotel that will accept the named price; the request will be
accepted or rejected within an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers are guaranteed the minimum category of room chosen; in
turn they must take the hotel assigned. They will not know the
specific hotel (or its location, except for the broad geographical
zone) until the reservations are confirmed and paid for, Walker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reservations will be accepted up to a year in advance but not
within 48 hours of arrival. There will be no fee to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline, based in Stamford, Conn., has sold more than 60,000
economy-class airline seats, most of them domestic, since it
introduced that service in April, according to Walker. Critics have
asserted that most major domestic airlines do not participate in
the program; Brian Ek, a company spokesman, responded, ``We're
offering tickets through major airlines, but we cannot say what
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Passengers must be willing to travel anytime between 6 a.m. and
10 p.m. and make one stopover; they cannot choose their airline,
and they earn no frequent-flier points.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline, which recently added a car-buying service in the New
York area, received a patent last month for its method and use of
``buyer-driven commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   New Swiss Airline
</P>
<P>
   A new airline, Swiss World Airways, began service earlier this
month between Newark, N.J., and Geneva, with flights every day
except Wednesday. The president and chief executive of the company
is Peter Leishman, who formerly helped found two British low-fare
start-ups, Debonair and Easyjet.
</P>
<P>
   The Geneva-based airline received approval from the Department
of Transportation only a few days before it started flying,
according to Leishman, and it is only now getting its flights into
the computer reservations systems used by travel agents. Swiss
World Airways' Boeing 767 _ the airline currently has just one jet,
which it leases _ seats 159 passengers in three classes.
</P>
<P>
   One-way unrestricted fares range from $167 to $530 in economy
class, $667 to $1,000 in business class and $1,267 to $2,000 in
first class.
</P>
<P>
   The line offers a few unconventional twists. Food service
consists of mostly cold choices to avoid reheating, with only one
hot entree cooked on board. Travelers flying on discount fares pay
for food, drinks and headsets; full-fare travelers get them free.
The frequent-flier program consists of instant lottery-style
tickets offering a gift or a premium that applies to the next
flight.
</P>
<P>
   The line hopes to add a second flight to Geneva from New York in
November, via Basel, and service from Dulles International Airport
or Baltimore-Washington International Airport next spring.
</P>
<P>
   The toll-free worldwide reservations number is (011-800-11)
767-767.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle's New Boston Home
</P>
<P>
   The US Airways Shuttle is scheduled to move on Sunday from
Terminal A at Logan International Airport in Boston to the newly
renovated Terminal B. The new shuttle gates will be 10, 12 and 13
at the end of the concourse. Counters for ticketing and check-in
will be next to the security checkpoint at the entrance to the main
concourse and at the gates.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle offers 17 daily round-trip flights between Logan and
La Guardia Airport in New York, as well as 15 daily flights between
Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport and La Guardia.
</P>
<P>
   Train to the Plane
</P>
<P>
   A rail link in Denmark from Copenhagen International Airport to
the Central Railway Station downtown opened Sunday. The seven-mile
trip takes 11 minutes and costs $2.60, compared with a taxi fare of
around $20. The train terminal is underneath the airport's
departure and arrival halls.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Update
</P>
<P>
   Two new hotels on the hip side are scheduled to open Thursday,
one in Chicago and one in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Blues Hotel, a Loews Hotel, at the Marina City
riverfront complex in Chicago, is the first in a series planned by
House of Blues Hospitality. The 367 guest rooms will offer in-room
faxes, CD players, videocassette recorders, voice mail and two-line
phones, as well as direct Internet access via TV sets.
</P>
<P>
   Meetings and other events can be arranged in the House of Blues
Music Hall and Restaurant next door; the complex also has a 36-lane
bowling center and a health club.
</P>
<P>
   In downtown Denver, the 189-room Hotel Monaco is situated at
1717 Champa St. in two renovated adjoining buildings, the 1917
Railway Exchange Building and the 1937 Art Moderne Title Building.
Rooms will have CD players and two-line phones with data ports. The
hotel is part of the Kimpton Hotel and Restaurant Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980929.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
