<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1062 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PADRES-ASTROS-TEX     09-29 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-ASTROS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN STANDS TALL IN PADRES WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ And you thought Kevin Brown was too boring to do
impersonations.
</P>
<P>
   Giving his best Randy Johnson imitation against none other than
baseball's reigning strikeout king, the stoic-but-spectacular Brown
suffocated the National League's most potent offense in a
16-strikeout, two-hit masterpiece that led the Padres to a 2-1
victory against the Astros at the Astrodome yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was as dominant as a pitcher can be without throwing a
no-hitter,'' said Astros manager Larry Dierker, whose team set
franchise records for runs and home runs in a 102-win regular
season but now trails the best-of-five Division Series 1-0 with
Game 2 set for tomorrow. ``When our team gives up only two runs, 90
percent of the time we're going to win. But Kevin was so good, he
put us in the other 10 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyritz produced a bases-loaded sacrifice fly in the fifth
inning and Greg Vaughn drilled a solo homer in the eighth for the
Padres, but Brown was essentially a one-man show.
</P>
<P>
   With a sailing 95-mph fastball to complement his 88-mph sinker,
Brown approached a postseason record with his career-high 16
strikeouts. His Astro-nomical performance included striking out
every Houston batter at least once, allowing only two runners to
reach third base, only four balls out of the infield, and
handcuffing Houston's star quartet of Craig Biggio, Jeff Bagwell,
Derek Bell and Moises Alou into 0-for-11 with eight strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   In the history of baseball postseason, only Bob Gibson's
17-strikeout game in the 1968 World Series topped Brown's total.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I had great stuff, but it must have been moving
pretty good,'' said Brown, who threw 118 pitches (77 strikes) on
three days' rest. ``Obviously, going against Randy, I needed
something special and I thought that was pretty good for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Only when Brown left the game for fellow Cy Young Award
candidate Trevor Hoffman after the eighth did the Astros have a
prayer. Bill Spiers doubled and _ after outs by Bell and Bagwell _
scored on Ken Caminiti's throwing error, which was forced by Alou's
infield single to make it 2-1 in the ninth. Hoffman, however,
fought back from a 3-0 count to get Carl Everett to fly out to
center field to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres improved to 86-0 this season when leading after eight
innings and a remarkable 175-0 in that situation since July 24,
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who had been 5-0 at the dome with four shutouts with
the Astros, wasn't at his best, striking out nine but also allowing
nine hits.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, he threw a wicked, sidearm slider on the outside
corner to Tony Gwynn, who calmly poked it down the left-field line
for a leadoff double. After Vaughn's infield single and a
broken-bat bloop single by Caminiti loaded the bases, Leyritz
lofted a 2-2 fastball to the warning track to bring home Gwynn. In
the eighth, Vaughn smashed a 2-0 slider into the left-field seats
for insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Brown got stronger as the game progressed, allowing
just two singles, both to No. 8 hitter Brad Ausmus, and striking
out five of the last seven Astros he faced. He was in danger only
twice.
</P>
<P>
   With Ausmus on third base in the third after a single and two
passed balls, Brown struck out Biggio on a high fastball. And in
the sixth, with runners on second and third and two out, he fanned
Bell on a nasty 2-2 sinker in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He defies the laws of gravity with some of those pitches,''
Johnson said. ``I didn't pitch that bad. But he was dialed in and
focused, just better than me today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
