<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IMPEACH-PICTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE IMPEACHMENT PICTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Sept. 30:
</P>
<P>
   The decisions by the House Judiciary Committee chairman, Henry
Hyde, to insure greater fairness and openness in the examination of
evidence in the Monica Lewinsky affair are sound on the merits. But
they have a larger importance as encouraging signs that the debate
over President Clinton's future can be kept moving toward some
reasonably prompt resolution. Time magazine found that 35 percent
of its polling sample wanted Clinton out of office, 29 percent
favored censure and 34 percent favored no punishment. You do not
need a poll, however, to sense that citizens do not want this to
drag out indefinitely. Barring the emergence of explosive new
evidence, there is no reason that it should.
</P>
<P>
   This page advocates a negotiated settlement that would allow
Clinton to remain in office in exchange for a censure based on his
admission of lying under oath. We believe Hyde's handling of the
Judiciary Committee opens the way for gradual progress in that
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde has decided that the committee will dispatch a bipartisan
team to comb Kenneth Starr's unreleased documents for material
favorable to Clinton. That will allow the Democrats a fair chance
to prove their charges that Starr used Linda Tripp to set a perjury
trap for Clinton. The exercise will also provide new information
that the public can use in assessing charges of prosecutorial
excess against Starr and his office. The Judiciary Committee should
ask Starr to come forward now with any information about
Whitewater, Webster Hubbell and other matters that he considers to
be potential grounds for impeachment. If he has no such evidence,
he should tell the committee and the country.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde assigned a subcommittee to look into the definition of an
impeachable offense, and decreed that the entire committee should
meet in open session next Monday to vote on whether to begin a full
impeachment inquiry. The House itself will vote next Wednesday on
the committee's recommendation. The Republican leadership would
like to let matters rest there until after the election. These
public debates, then, are of tremendous importance, for they give
the Democrats a chance to wield public pressure for bringing this
matter to a conclusion. The Republicans say they cannot be swayed,
but the polls that indicated growing disapproval of Congress have
clearly influenced Hyde and are creating doubts in the GOP caucus
about House Speaker Newt Gingrich's refusal to consider a deal.
</P>
<P>
   No one can chart a direct course to a plea bargain, but it is
possible to keep moving in that direction by avoiding congressional
gridlock and partisan warfare. House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt
and Rep. Barney Frank are right that James Carville's paroxysm
strategy is hurting the president. ``It would be wrong for any
Democrat to forget that the president's mistakes are part of the
problem,'' said Frank, who is not timid about fighting Clinton's
corner when it serves a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   But the smart move for Clinton's congressional supporters is to
reach out to Republican moderates like Rep. Lindsey Graham and to
support the efforts of senior figures outside Congress. The public
is ready for a deal built around a cluster of principles that
include electoral continuity, condemnation of Clinton's personal
behavior and recognition of his responsibility for breaking the law
and misleading the American people.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans know there is peril in ignoring the public
desire for closure. But Clinton's gains in the past week should not
induce him, his wife and their surrogates to adopt a war strategy
or to count on Starr's unpopularity as a life preserver. Another
wave of documents is coming tomorrow. There may be more disclosures
down the road. Come Oct. 9, many House Democrats are planning to
vote for the full impeachment inquiry. Any White House plan to
prolong matters or step up the sniping is self-destructive. Now
that they have had a chance to contemplate the seediness of
Clinton's behavior, most Americans do not agree with Sen. Trent
Lott that just ``bad conduct is enough, frankly, for impeachment.''
But that could change, very quickly. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
