A1065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-RATE-CUT-NYT &LR;      09-29 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RATE-CUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A CAUTIOUS RATE CUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Sept. 30:
</P>
<P>
   By choosing to lower interest rates by only a small amount, the
Federal Reserve has opted for a gradual and measured response to
the growing problems affecting the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   The move, reducing the rate on loans between banks by a quarter
of a percentage point, to 5.25 percent, was welcome. But financial
markets were nonetheless disappointed, both by the amount of the
cut and because there is no indication that European central banks
will join in the effort to stimulate economic growth in the face of
the deflationary and recessionary winds blowing from Asia and
Russia. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 100 points in the
minutes after the decision was announced, and markets also fell
sharply in Latin America. But most markets later rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's caution may prove to have been too great, but the
central bank nonetheless is to be commended for acting at all.
While financial markets are clearly worried, the statistics still
show a strong domestic economy. The latest consumer confidence
figures from the Conference Board showed a growing number of people
worried that the economy will get worse within the next six months,
but that concern is not yet reflected in consumer spending figures.
</P>
<P>
   If there were a way to stimulate economic activity in part of
the world but not the rest, America would be the least appropriate
candidate for monetary stimulus. But central banks in developing
countries, where the need is greatest, are in no position to
stimulate growth because such actions would put further pressure on
already shaky currencies. It is central banks in the leading
countries that have the ability to act, and that is why pressure
grew on the Fed to ease credit.
</P>
<P>
   It was encouraging that Canada's central bank joined yesterday's
move, but regrettable that Germany's Bundesbank, in its final
months as the de facto European central bank, has been unwilling to
join in cutting. The Bundesbank is rightly proud of its reputation
as being vigilant against inflation, but inflation is not the
world's primary problem now.
</P>
<P>
   If the world economy does not turn around quickly, further rate
cuts, by the Fed and other central banks, may be needed before the
year is out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
