<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
 
Coleman's end spot real twist and Turner 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just when UCLA defensive end Travor Turner began
wondering if he'd ever crack the lineup, a starting job hit him in
the knee. To be more specific, a Houston Cougar hit Kenyon Coleman
in the knee, which sidelined Coleman for three weeks and gave
Turner the chance he thought would never come.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same thing happened to me (at Westchester High School),''
Turner said. ``I didn't start until my junior year, so I was
prepared to have to wait. It's a test. It's a test of whether you
can keep your focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner's ascension to starting end _ he had seven tackles
against Houston after Coleman went down _ is a testament to keeping
focus in the weight room.
</P>
<P>
   As a prep senior, he carried 190 pounds on a 6-foot-4 frame. He
weighed 210 pounds upon arrival in Westwood. As a second-year
freshman, he was 220, and he played sparingly last season as a
235-pound sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he's 250 and proud of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think guys who were 245 pounds were so big,'' he
said, laughing. ``Now, I look at guys smaller than me, like
(receiver) Brian Poli-Dixon, and say, `Dang, I used to look like
that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Turner remains small for a defensive end. (UCLA's other starter,
Pete Holland, weighs 270.) But he's strong enough to maintain
leverage, and he hasn't lost the athleticism that enabled him to
high jump 6-9 at Westchester. What he lacks in size and strength,
he compensates for with quickness.
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed Sack Master by his teammates, Turner is tied for the
team lead with three tackles-for-loss.
</P>
<P>
   __ Miami update: UCLA athletic director Peter Dalis spoke with
his Miami counterpart, Paul Dee, on Tuesday about rescheduling the
cancelled game. They made no decision and are expected to talk
again Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost wish this would get over with,'' Bruins coach Bob
Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   An informal survey of five UCLA players _ four of them seniors _
revealed indifference about playing Miami on Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   __ McNown note of the week: For those not keeping score at home,
UCLA quarterback Cade McNown has completed 72.7 percent of his
passes on first down, 56.5 percent on second down and 47 percent on
third down.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's outstanding,'' Toledo said. ``Anything over one-third
on third down is really good.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Wazu update: Incumbent Steve Birnbaum will start at
quarterback for Washington State on Saturday at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mike Price considered a change after Birnbaum, a junior,
completed 8 of 21 passes with two interceptions last week against
Cal. His passing efficiency rating (110.4) is eighth in the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum and reserve Paul Mencke have not made Cougars fans
forget Ryan Leaf. Combined, they've thrown seven touchdowns and
seven interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   __ Message received: Benched after his lackluster performance
against Houston, sophomore cornerback Marques Anderson showed signs
of life in practice last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He responded to being demoted to second string, but I'm not
ready to get him involved as a starter,'' Toledo said. ``When he's
in the game, if he plays with more intensity, he may get his job
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
