<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AMTRAK-UPGRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK AND AMTRAK ANNOUNCE PLAN TO UPGRADE SERVICE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Amtrak officials and Gov. George Pataki announced a
five-year plan on Tuesday to upgrade the line between New York City
and Albany and rebuild trains used on the route to shave at least
20 minutes off the trip, allowing riders to cover the distance in
less than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   When the work on the $185-million program is completed, trains
that now rarely exceed 90 miles per hour will cruise at 125 mph.
The plan also includes building a second track between Albany and
Schenectady and an upgrade of the track between Albany and Buffalo,
cutting as much as an hour off a trip between New York City and
Buffalo, which now takes more than seven and a half hours.
</P>
<P>
   The upgrade, which comes as Amtrak's ridership in New York state
is expected to reach its highest level in more than 15 years, is
expected to draw even more people to the train and away from cars
and planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two hours from New York to Albany is kind of like a magic
number,'' said Michael Fleischer, a spokesman for the state
Department of Transportation. ``When people realize that the trip
takes less than two hours, it's kind of a stumbling block you get
around.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip from New York City to the state capital now takes
between 2 hours and 20 minutes and 2 hours and 30 minutes. There is
one express train a day that makes the trip in 2 hours and 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak and the state will split the $140-million cost of
rebuilding seven Turboliner trains. The trains, to be rebuilt by
Super Steel Schenectady Inc., will have engines on both ends,
allowing them to change direction without turning around, which
should allow Amtrak to get two or three extra trips a day without
increasing the number of trains. The trains will also get bigger
seats, each with a hookup for a laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining $45 million will be used to build a second track
between Albany and Schenectady and to realign other track and
straighten curves to allow trains to reach higher speeds. Overall,
about three-quarters of the state's funding for the project will
come from various federal sources.
</P>
<P>
   The upgrade is not expected to require a fare increase. The fare
from New York to Albany is $34 each way during the week and $41 on
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Remington, a spokesman for Amtrak, said that the number of
riders on the railroad's New York state trains is growing at a much
faster rate than Amtrak ridership nationwide. Since last October,
ridership in New York state has increased by more than 10 percent,
to more than 97,000 riders a month. On a typical Friday, the
busiest day of the week, 3,900 riders take Amtrak on routes within
the state, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the present rate, service for the year would top 1.1 million
for the first time since at least 1983, the earliest year for which
Remington provided statistics. Ridership within New York state has
increased 53 percent since then.
</P>
<P>
   Remington attributed the boom to a strong economy, improved
on-time performance and more narrowly focused advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in New York state are looking for a different sort of
Amtrak service than someone who wants to take a leisurely ride from
Chicago out West,'' Remington said. ``Corridors like this are where
we can compete with the car and plane for business travelers.''
</P>
<P>
   Transportation planning advocates hailed Tuesday's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using state capital dollars for mass transportation is a very
good thing, compared to where it usually goes, into roads,'' said
Jon Orcutt, the associate director of the Tri-State Transportation
Campaign, a watchdog group. ``It's the kind of transportation
investment that will help development in city centers along the
line, places like Buffalo, Syracuse and Albany. If you put millions
of dollars into highway lanes, you'd just be accelerating sprawl.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
