<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-POEMS-CENSORED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT SAYS CATHOLIC COLLEGE CENSORED HER POEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Iona College, a small Roman Catholic school in New Rochelle,
N.Y., is caught up in a swirl of controversy for distributing a
censored version of the student literary magazine that had been
suppressed four months earlier because it included expletives and
sexually explicit language.
</P>
<P>
   Two poems were removed from the magazine, The Cornelion, because
they included expletives, and a sexually explicit word was edited
out of a third poem that is in the current issue of the magazine,
said Mark Arduino, the college's public relations director.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators insist they secured the agreement of the author
of the third poem before editing it, but the author, Kristin
McSpedon, called that assertion a lie in a letter to the editor of
the student newspaper that will appear in the issue of Oct. 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make no apologies about what we did,'' said Brother James
Liguori, the president of Iona College. ``It's a question of a
mission-sensitive publication which should reflect the mission of
the college. It contained two pieces of material that were totally
inappropriate for Iona College.''
</P>
<P>
   Liguori said he checked with the school's lawyer before
instructing Michael McGrath, vice provost for student development,
to confiscate 380 copies of the magazine last spring. ``He acted
with my complete concurrence and approval,'' Liguori said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Ms. McSpedon had agreed to the editing of her poem,
Liguori said, ``It is my understanding that she was contacted and
that she did agree.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrath said Ms. McSpedon's poem ``was edited with the author's
permission.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McSpedon, in her letter to the student newspaper, The
Ionian, wrote that she had originally submitted her poem _ ``Typing
a Term Paper at 3 a.m.'' _ to a poetry contest sponsored by the
college's honors program and had won a $50 award.
</P>
<P>
   When she collected her prize money, she wrote, she was informed
that her poem would appear in The Cornelion and that it would be
published in the magazine ``as it was.'' She said no one had
contacted her about ``any problems with my work.''
</P>
<P>
   A high-ranking official of the school who spoke on the conditon
of anonymity said he was sure that Ms. McSpedon was telling the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   The college administration was criticized in an editorial in The
Ionian last week for its handling of the matter. ``Iona's media
board should have been called before a final decision on the
publication's status was made,'' the editorial declared.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath acknowledged that college policy, spelled out in a
constitution, requires consultation with a media board of students,
faculty and administrators before a student publication can be
censored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't convene a quorum of the media board because it was
May and we were into final exams,'' McGrath said. ``I left multiple
phone messages for the editor and assistant editor of The
Cornelion, but they were never returned and I concluded they were
deliberately ignoring me.''
</P>
<P>
   The college constitution, McGrath said, requires student editors
to avoid ``libel, indecency, undocumented allegations, attacks on
personal integrity and the techniques of harassment and innuendo.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Goodman, executive director of the Student Press Law
Center, a nonprofit organization in Arlington, Va., that offers
legal assistance to student journalists, said that the college may
have violated the copyright law in the handling of Ms. McSpedon's
poem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law states that an individual has the right to control the
use of his work,'' Goodman said. ``If this student chooses to sue
for copyright infringement, the statutory monetary damages are
between $500 and $20,000.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrath said he felt confident that he had acted lawfully, since
the college was acting as the publisher and had the right to edit
written material.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
