<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1221 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT     09-29 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELLS, CURTIS LED YANKS TO 2-0 WIN OVER TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Wells gestured angrily on the field when Chad
Curtis and two other Yankees botched a fly ball in a game two weeks
ago. Later, Wells sought out Curtis to apologize. I can't do that,
Wells told him, you guys win games for me.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis helped Wells and the Yankees win a very big game Tuesday
night _ the first game of the American League division series
against Texas. Curtis, picked to start in left field despite
playing miserably in the second half of the season, smacked a
double that set up the Yankee runs and Wells pitched eight innings
in a 2-0 shutout of the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   True to his history as an exceptional playoff performer, Wells
threw a season-high 135 pitches and allowed just 5 hits. He struck
out nine in lowering his career ERA in the post-season to 2.22,
then watched from the bench as Mariano Rivera retired the Rangers
in order in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking the pitching depth the Yankees possess, the Rangers'
best chance in this series would have been to win one or both of
the first two games. Now the Yankees can seize control of the
three-of-five-game series at Yankee Stadium Wednesday night, when
Andy Pettitte faces the Rangers' 20-game winner, Rick Helling, in
Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre placed Wells at the back end of the Yankees'
playoff rotation last year, a decision that still bothers Wells.
Coming off a season in which he went 18-4 and pitched a perfect
game, however, Wells got the Game 1 assignment this year, and he
justified that decision.
</P>
<P>
   With the top two buttons of his jersey undone and sporting a
hint of a goatee (to Wells, his war paint), the left-hander
challenged the Rangers all game, hammering fastballs inside and
outside and bending breaking balls over the lower plane of the
strike zone. Remarkably, Wells pitched into ball-strike counts that
were favorable to hitters _ 2-0 or 3-1 _ only three times.
</P>
<P>
   Wells fired first-pitch strikes to 21 of the 30 batters he
faced, reaching 2-0 counts only twice. Conventional wisdom
suggested the Yankees would not pitch to Juan Gonzalez, the
Rangers' massive cleanup hitter. To the contrary: Wells chased
after Gonzalez with inside fastballs, and the slugger went 0 for 3,
striking out, fouling out and chopping a grounder that traveled
about two feet from home plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had runners in scoring position against Wells only
twice after the first inning, their best threat coming in the
seventh. Will Clark singled with one out and after a fielder's
choice groundout, Todd Zeile smacked a single to left. Two on, two
out.
</P>
<P>
   Wells jumped ahead of Mike Simms no balls and two strikes, the
Yankee Stadium crowd of 57,362 roaring. Simms fouled off a pitch,
took two balls, fouled off two more with good swings. Wells did not
allow a three-run homer or grand slam this year, and this did not
seem like the best of times for the first.
</P>
<P>
   Wells zipped a fastball inside, Simms staring at it, the crowd
exploding. Ball 3, said the home-plate umpire, Jim Joyce, and Wells
disgustedly turned away, as fans screamed at Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   Wells attacked again: high fastball, Simms swung and missed, end
of inning. The 2-0 lead Curtis had built remained intact.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis batted .216 after the All-Star Game break, .146 in
September, pressing more with each at-bat. In prticular, Curtis
was unable to cope with pitches thrown to the outer half of the
strike zone. He played so badly in the final weeks that some in the
organization felt the Yankees should have considered replacing him
on the post-season roster with the rookie Ricky Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Spencer, in the meantime, slugged three grand slams in the
final 10 days of the season and Tim Raines contributed
consistently, even after sitting three or four days in a row. The
idea of Curtis starting a playoff game seemed remote.
</P>
<P>
   But with Wells, a left-handed pitcher who induces fly balls,
facing the predominantly right-handed Texas lineup, Torre's
priority in picking his left fielder was defense, and Curtis has
the best glove in left field. Torre also knew that Curtis had a
favorable history against Todd Stottlemyre, with 9 hits in 26
at-bats (.346).
</P>
<P>
   Curtis was due to bat third in the Yankee second inning, which
began with Chili Davis, the 38-year-old designated hitter, playing
mind games with Stottlemyre. The Texas right-hander likes to work
quickly, but after each pitch, Davis would step out and loiter and
slowly get comfortable. Davis ran the count to 2-2, and when the
next pitch went in the dirt, Davis asked for a new ball; in this
way, he controlled the tempo.
</P>
<P>
   On the seventh pitch of the at-bat, Davis looked at a third
strike _ and yet, the tone for the inning had been set. Jorge
Posada patiently waited out a seven-pitch walk, and Stottlemyre
immediately attacked Curtis' weakness, throwing fastballs and
breaking balls outside.
</P>
<P>
   But Curtis reached out for a fastball, driving it to the
opposite field. Gonzalez, the Rangers' cement-shoed right fielder,
lumbered back and toward the right-field corner, the ball carrying
over his outstretched glove. Posada stopped at third, Curtis pulled
into second. One out, Scott Brosius coming to bat.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers opted to play the infield back, and for that reason,
Brosius cared only about making contact and putting the ball in
play. He flailed his bat and hit a roller to the right side _ and
through. Posada scored, Curtis stopped at third.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch battled Stottlemyre to a full count _ the Ranger
pitcher threw 27 pitches in the inning _ and Torre ordered Brosius
to break from first on the next pitch. Knoblauch swung and missed,
a strikeout, and Ivan Rodriguez fired a throw to second in an
attempt to intercept Brosius for the third out.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment Rodriguez released the ball, however, Curtis broke
from third and Brosius stopped about 20 feet from second base;
Texas second baseman Mark McLemore caught the ball with no other
choice but to chase Brosius in a rundown, after Curtis slid across
home with the Yankees' second run of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Torre looked quite wise for his choice of left fielder.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
