u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-TRIBE-COX     09-29 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-TRIBE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vaughn whips Indians as Sox take Game One
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The last time the Cleveland Indians saw Mo Vaughn in
postseason play, well, they didn't see him. He was invisible, a
non-entity, a wisp.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1995 and Vaughn was 0 for 14 with seven strikeouts as the
Boston Red Sox played matador to the bullish Cleveland Indians,
bowing in three straight in the American League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   History would not repeat itself Tuesday afternoon in Jacobs
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was bigger than life Tuesday, and Vaughn is a very big
man.
</P>
<P>
   The 250-pound first baseman personally dismantled the Cleveland
Indians in Game 1 of the American League Division Series, an 11-3
Boston victory.
</P>
<P>
   He drove in a postseason record seven runs.
</P>
<P>
   He hit a three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   He hit a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   He hit a two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   He stood taller than the Terminal Tower and wider than Lake
Erie.
</P>
<P>
   And one thing you never want to do is give a junkyard guard dog
a T-bone steak, then try to take it away from him.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribe spotted Boston starter Pedro Martinez a three-run lead
just three hitters into the game _ single, single, three-run home
run by Vaughn to left field, the opposite way.
</P>
<P>
   For 19-game winner Martinez, Boston's Rottweiler, a three-run
lead before he takes the mound is like spotting Secretariat a
three-length lead out of the gate.
</P>
<P>
   You aren't going to see anything but flowing tail. And that's
all the Indians saw from Martinez, who gave up no runs and two hits
over five innings until it was 8-0.
</P>
<P>
   Shaky Cleveland starter Jaret Wright was hit by singles from
Darren Lewis and John Valentin to open the game. Wright was ahead
of Vaughn 0-2, fell behind 3-2, then watched the next pitch nestle
snugly into the left-field jury box, 376 feet from home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned from 1995 to sit back and let the game come to me
and not try to force it,'' Vaughn said. ``You can't make things
happen out there. The thing I didn't do in 1995 was hit the ball
where it was pitched. Now I'm just sitting up there and waiting.
The ball was out over the plate and I just went through it and it
carried into the seats.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 3-0 with nobody out in the top of the first and the
45,185 sitting in Jacobs were as quiet the rest of the afternoon as
if sitting at a funeral.
</P>
<P>
   They might have been.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra crashed a three-run home run in the fifth to
make it 6-0. Vaughn struck again in the sixth off relief pitcher
Doug Jones, a two-run blast to push it to 8-0 and become the first
Red Sox batter to hit two home runs in a postseason game since Rico
Petrocelli ripped a pair in the 1967 World Series against St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to assess Vaughn's day, Garciparra said, ``Wow! Is that
good enough?''
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman John Valentin, batting second in the order ahead
of Vaughn, scored four times, a Division Series record.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians avoided shutout embarrassment in the sixth on Sandy
Alomar's double and Kenny Lofton's home run, but the embarrassment
of getting crushed at home may have carry-over consequences in this
best-of-5 playoff that continues this afternoon in Jacobs before
shifting Friday and Saturday (if necessary) to Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Worried? Fans sang Take Me Out to the Ballgame in the seventh
inning softly _ like a ballad or a dirge. They should be worried.
This was the seventh straight time the Indians have lost the first
game of a postseason series and for Boston it ended a string of 13
straight postseason defeats.
</P>
<P>
   For Vaughn, the game was a salary drive to end all salary
drives.
</P>
<P>
   He and the Red Sox have been back and forth, over and under, up
and around each other in contract talks and arguments all season.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, they probably could have signed Vaughn to a
three-year deal at $30 million. But they gave Martinez a bigger
contract and Vaughn balked, turning down the club's offer of $37.5
million over four years.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn now is thinking more along the national debt-type figure
of $11 million a year for, oh, four or five years would be nice.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, he wants to put money aside and focus attention on
postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995, the playoffs went so fast for me (three defeats and
out to the Tribe),'' Vaughn said. ``Before I knew it we played
three games and were gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians are feeling that same sensation.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for The Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
