<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Padres' Brown fans 16 as Astros lose home edge
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ With Randy Johnson having won 10 of his 11 starts in a
Houston uniform and having held opponents scoreless in 42 of his 43
innings in the Astrodome, a dominating pitching performance in the
National League Division Series opener with San Diego was all but
assumed.
</P>
<P>
   The white towel-waving crowd of 50,080 fans got exactly what it
expected _ just not from whom it expected.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego ace Kevin Brown completely overshadowed his Astros
counterpart with a playoff masterpiece, striking out a division
series-record and career-high 16 and holding surprisingly punchless
Houston to two hits over eight innings for a 2-1 victory Tuesday
afternoon in the opener of this best-of-five series.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Unit got one-upped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody is invincible,'' said Johnson, who
pitched well with nine strikeouts in eight innings. ``There's
always this big buildup when I pitch in the postseason. You guys
tend to write more about what could possibly happen, but it always
seems to overshadow the opposing pitcher. And I know if I was Kevin
Brown or Mike Mussina last year, that would be an incentive to go
out and prove all of you wrong, that there's more than one pitcher
out there. He defied the law of gravity out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston was sinking before it knew what hit it. Or what it
wasn't hitting. Mixing a lethal assortment of two- and four-seam,
97-mph fastballs with sliders, sinkers and his new forkball, the
33-year-old right-hander threw a first-pitch strike to 21 of the 28
batters he faced and had batters consistently chasing high
fastballs out of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson pitched well but surrendered a bases-loaded sacrifice
fly to Jim Leyritz in the sixth and easily the quietest home run of
this home run-delirious season when Greg Vaughn hit a solo shot to
lead off the eighth. The fans threw it back. Johnson didn't have
that luxury.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most dominant I've seen Brown,'' said Astros
Manager Larry Dierker, whose club falls into a huge hole after
losing the home-field advantage and now has to win three of four,
starting with Thursday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Brown allowed only a pair of singles to Brad Ausmus and pitched
out of a jam in the sixth with two runners in scoring position by
retiring Bill Spiers on a groundout and striking out Derek Bell,
who is now one for 14 lifetime against Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Brown struck out every batter except Spiers and fanned Bell and
Ricky Gutierrez three times each.
</P>
<P>
   The one-run loss was reminiscent of last year's opening defeat
by Atlanta's Greg Maddux that wasted an outstanding game from
Houston's Darryl Kile. The score was identical, as was the futility
by the Killer B's trio of Craig Biggio, Jeff Bagwell and Bell, who
slumped to a collective two-for-37 showing in that three-game sweep
by the Braves and fared little better Tuesday in a combined
zero-for-10 effort.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he'd ever seen Brown throw better, Bagwell said, ``I've
never seen Kevin Brown bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown was the only B doing the killing, and he did it with his A
stuff. He shut down the top-scoring team in the league, one with
four starters who had 20 or more homers this season. Although
Houston nicked closer Trevor Hoffman for a run in the ninth on a
Spiers double and a Ken Camini throwing error on Moises Alou's
infield single, the Astros pushed only two base runners past second
off Brown all day.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's only problems came in his postgame press conference when
he was asked to recall his pitch selection in that pivotal sixth
inning. ``I don't remember every pitch,'' he joked. ``Who do you
think I am, Greg Maddux?''
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact . . .
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Bohls writes for The Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
