</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-RANKINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HMO reports called victory for consumers
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas HMOs trailed the nation last year in
providing preventive care that can avert costly health problems,
according to an independent group that assesses the industry
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Patients in the biggest Texas HMOs were less likely than HMO
patients across the country to get mammograms, Pap smears, certain
immunizations, prenatal care and post-delivery checkups in 1997, a
nationwide survey released last week showed. On Tuesday _ just as
many of us are being asked to choose between health plans at the
office _ Texas followed up with its own HMO report card that scored
individual health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Among the plans that fared poorly on preventive care measures
were Anthem Health Plan, now part of AmeriHealth, and PCA Health
Plans of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring well in the state survey were Scott &AMP; White Health Plan,
Prudential HealthCare and United HealthCare of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The state survey, released by the Texas Health Care Information
Council, lets Texas consumers see for the first time how different
HMOs stack up. Typically, data from performance studies are only
made available to employers choosing health plans and the HMOs
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not here to suggest that one HMO is better than
another,'' said Jim Loyd, executive director of the council. But,
he said, ``you can't make a really informed decision about choosing
an HMO if you have only seen one advertisement or if you've only
heard one story from a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike traditional insurance plans, most HMOs cover the cost of
preventive health care on the assumption that it's cheaper to catch
health problems early. But, an industry spokeswoman emphasized, it
is a patient's responsibility to take advantage of these services.
``I can tell you that there is not a health plan in this state that
doesn't pay for mammograms and doesn't encourage mammograms,'' said
Kelly Jones, director of governmental relations for the Texas
Association of Health Plans. ``Overall, I think it's encouraging
that these things are being offered by every health plan in the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones added that the HMO industry in Texas is relatively young
and supports a smaller percentage of patients than the national
average. One in six Texans with health insurance is enrolled in an
HMO, less than in many other states, which might explain the
lower-than-average scores on the national survey, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones joined consumer groups in calling the release of the
council's data a victory for Texans, who have never seen report
cards on their HMOs. But some advocates warn that the information
does not give a complete picture.
</P>
<P>
   The October issue of Consumer Reports criticized thesurveyfor
seeking only superficial measurements of care and not inquiring
about patient results. Without knowing whether patients got
accurate diagnoses or proper treatments, consumers won't be able to
judge the quality of care an HMO administers, the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not information that's going to say this is quality, this
is not quality _ but it's a beginning, and that's progress,'' said
Lisa McGiffert, a senior policy analyst at Consumers Union in
Austin. ``We hope they're going to start looking more at quality
issues like, 'Is health improved?'''
</P>
<P>
   The national survey found 58 percent of Texas HMO patients
received baby check-ups, compared with 66 percent nationally. In
addition, 69 percent in Texas were given beta blockers to prevent
heart attacks versus 74 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Texas HMOs were only slightly below the national average for Pap
smears and mammograms, according to the survey by the National
Committee for Quality Assurance, a nonprofit watchdog agency.
</P>
<P>
   The national statistics did not rate or rank individual health
maintenance organizations. Instead, it compared responses from them
to a variety of performance questions. In its second annual survey,
the group solicited voluntary responses from the nation's 650 HMOs
and compiled its data for employers to use when shopping for health
plans. The committee received data from 447 plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas data can be found at www.thcic.state.tx.us on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Park writes for The Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
