<SLUG> BC-REPLICA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Replica of Wright glider makes its way to Dayton
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It's just wood, fabric and a little metal, but
the object that went on display in Wright State University's
Student Union on Monday started a revolution.
</P>
<P>
   It's the 1902 Wright Glider, or rather a faithful reproduction
of the glider that proved the Wright brothers' design for a flying
machine.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Young of Richmond, W.Va., the glider's builder and pilot,
brought the kite-like craft to Dayton this week to display it
during the National Aerospace Conference. The conference runs
Thursday through Saturday morning at Wright State.
</P>
<P>
   Young said he also plans to display the glider Sunday afternoon
outside the Wright Cycle Shop, 22 S. Williams St., weather
permitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really wonderful to bring this back to Dayton,'' Young
said Tuesday. ``This is the machine (the Wrights) patented. It's
fully as important as the Kitty Hawk Flyer,'' which made the
world's first successful powered flights in 1903.
</P>
<P>
   Young said he built the glider in 1978 and has flown it several
times for an IMAX film and public television specials about the
Wright brothers. He made the flights near Kitty Hawk, N.C., where
Orville and Wilbur Wright flew a series of kites and gliders before
flying a powered craft based on the 1902 machine.
</P>
<P>
   Young said he was pleased to bring the glider here because
Dayton has never had much luck in having a replica of the 1902
machine on display.
</P>
<P>
   The Wrights abandoned the original 1902 glider at Kitty Hawk, he
said. In the 1930s, Army engineers at McCook Field, with Orville
Wright's help, made drawings of the glider and built a replica,
which was later demolished, he said. Another was later built, but
Young said it was donated to the Wright Brothers National Monument
at Kitty Hawk for a new visitors' center in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   A new local group, the First to Fly Foundation, sponsored the
glider's visit in an effort to draw attention to its plan to buy a
set of rare documents from the Wright Co., the aircraft company the
Wrights founded. First to Fly member Nick Engler said a private
collector in Florida owns the documents; the group wants to raise
$900,000 to buy them for the Paul Laurence Dunbar Library at Wright
State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``These papers cover a time period in the Wright brothers'
history that are not in any repository,'' said Dawne Dewey, head of
special collections and archives at Wright State. ``We would be
overjoyed to be the recipient of such a collection,'' she said, but
she added that Wright State is not involved in the fund-raising
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy R. Gaffney writes for The Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
