<HEADER>
A1233 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-OSFUB30-COX     09-29 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OSFUB30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Like a turtle coming out of its shell after a
bad storm, Ohio State linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer has slowly begun
to poke his head out to face the media he feels rained down hard on
him earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The storm erupted in the preseason when Katzenmoyer revealed he
needed to ace three summer school classes _ golf, music and AIDS
awareness _ to remain academically eligible. For the next several
weeks, there was nary an OSU story that didn't mention Katzenmoyer
and his academic woes.
</P>
<P>
   Today, three games and 18 Katzenmoyer tackles later, the stories
on the linebacker have turned back to football. Perhaps no one is
more relieved than The Big Kat himself.
</P>
<P>
   Still, OSU's star linebacker continues to appear genuinely
surprised at the brouhaha that erupted over his eligibility status.
He places the blame for that squarely on the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys chose to make it my team, I guess, (because) I'm the
leader,'' Katzenmoyer told a group of reporters after practice at
the Woody Hayes Athletic Center this week. ``But it never really
was in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, although the junior leads the Buckeyes in tackles and is
always a focus of the opposing team's game plan, he has, for now,
simply become another player on a star-studded, No. 1-ranked team.
Quarterback Joe Germaine, wide receivers David Boston and Dee
Miller, tailback Michael Wiley and cornerback Antoine Winfield, to
name a few, have all commanded comparable, if not equal, attention
with their play.
</P>
<P>
   And when OSU players chose their leaders this season, they
selected Jerry Rudzinski, Winfield and Germaine, not Katzenmoyer.
</P>
<P>
   Up until the Sept. 19 game vs. Missouri, teammates and OSU coach
John Cooper were left to defend the linebacker while he stayed away
from the media. They insisted the preseason scrutiny hadn't
affected him, that he was the same old player despite recording
just six tackles (fifth best on the team) in the Buckeyes first two
games. (He had twice as many in his first two games last season.)
</P>
<P>
   After he racked up 12 tackles against the Tigers in OSU's third
game, Katzenmoyer agreed to be interviewed. Like his teammates and
coaches, he said the preseason scrutiny hadn't affected his play.
</P>
<P>
   But he admits he still has a tough time dealing with the
attention he receives. ``I'm not a people person, I guess,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer is no stranger to Joe Paterno and his No.-7 ranked
Penn State Nittany Lions, who visit Ohio Stadium on Saturday.
Paterno said he tried hard to recruit Katzenmoyer and thinks highly
of the 1997 Butkus Award winner. Despite Penn State's reputation as
Linebacker U, Paterno said he can't remember any Nittany Lion
linebacker quite like the 6-4, 255-pound Katzenmoyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've ever had any (linebacker) that big and
strong,'' Paterno said. ``He's all business.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Vinella writes for The Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
