<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE OFFICER ACCUSED OF IMPERSONATING A REPORTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Police Officer Joseph Locurto held a news
conference in his lawyer's office this month to apologize for
appearing in blackface at a Queens parade and to plead for the
right to continue serving on the force, there was a mole among the
reporters: a police sergeant investigating his case who sat among
the journalists and took notes.
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant's appearance at the news conference _ which
resulted in a two-page report filed with the Internal Affairs
Bureau, the police unit charged with investigating police
misconduct _ was angrily denounced Tuesday by Locurto's lawyer,
Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil Liberties
Union. In a letter to top police officials, Siegel said the move
raised ``serious questions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Government monitoring of the First Amendment activities of its
citizens through the use of undercover agents is antithetical to a
free society,'' Siegel said in an interview. ``If citizens are now
being told that cops will surreptitiously attend press conferences
and compile files on them, that will chill First Amendment
activity.''
</P>
<P>
   But police officials defended their decision to dispatch an
investigator to the news conference to hear what Locurto had to
say. Marilyn Mode, the department's deputy commissioner for public
information, said she considered news conferences ``open to the
public,'' and added that while the officer did not identify himself
or wear a badge, he did not wear press credentials either.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel countered that only specific journalists were invited to
attend the news conference in his office. ``No invitation was
extended to the public at large,'' he wrote. ``Certainly no
invitation was extended to investigative officers of the New York
City Police Department posing as members of the press corps.''
</P>
<P>
   Locurto is scheduled to face an administrative trial at Police
Headquarters on Oct. 5 at which he will fight to keep his job. He
was suspended without pay for wearing blackface at the annual Labor
Day parade in Broad Channel, Queens, while riding atop a float that
parodied the racist killing of a black man in Jasper, Texas, last
June.
</P>
<P>
   Among the bureau's files is a two-page report signed by Sgt.
Gerardo Lopez and Capt. Carl Sandel and titled, ``Subject: Summary
of Norman Siegel Press Conference.''
</P>
<P>
   The style is terse. ``Mr. Siegel also stated that his client's
right to free speech was violated,'' it said at one point. ``He
stated that the Constitution guarantees this, even if the viewpoint
is offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel, in his letter to police officials, asked for an
investigation into whether the decision to send a police officer to
the news conference violated the rules for using covert police
surveillance of political activities. Under a 1985 federal court
order known as the Handschu agreement, police are prohibited from
investigating political gatherings except for the purposes of crowd
control or when they have specific information that the group has
committed or plans to commit a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mode said that after conferring with George Grasso, the
department's deputy commissioner for legal affairs, she did not
believe the investigation violated the Handschu agreement. But she
added that the department would refer the case to its Handschu
committee for a review. The committee is made up of Grasso; Patrick
Kelleher, the department's first deputy commissioner, and John
Doyle, a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said that for the purposes of the Handschu agreement,
political was defined as ``the exercise of a right of free
expression or association for the purposes of maintaining or
changing governmental policies or social conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it was political,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mode said that while there was no written policy preventing
officers from impersonating reporters, she believed it was against
Police Department guidelines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
