<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENGALS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Simmons to take advantage of bye week
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ The timing of the bye week couldn't be better for
Bengals linebacker Brian Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   He'll go back to North Carolina and be honored during a home
game against ACC rival Clemson. His name will be placed in the
stadium's ring of honor near Tar Heels legend Lawrence Taylor of
New York Giants fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy about the things I did back there,'' Simmons said.
``But my main focus is to be the type of player here that I was
down there. With time, I think that'll come.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3, 233-pound rookie is due to make the first start of
his NFL career against Pittsburgh on Oct. 11. He replaces Tom
Tumulty, who suffered torn left knee ligaments in a 31-24 loss at
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons probably would have started sooner, but his move into
the lineup was delayed because of surgery Aug. 27 for a slight
cartilage tear in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   He played briefly against Green Bay and had three tackles
against Baltimore, but didn't perform to the level he was used to
during his All-America career in Chapel Hill, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell I was rusty,'' Simmons said. ``Toward the end of
the Baltimore game, I started feeling better. I just had some bad
reads where you could tell I was sitting out for three weeks. My
conditioning is not where it needed to be. So this week, I'm
putting extra emphasis on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons joins fellow inside linebacker Takeo Spikes and
cornerback Artrell Hawkins as rookie starters on a struggling
defense ranked 27th overall, yielding 375.3 yards a game.
</P>
<P>
   Spikes leads the team in tackles (31) and sacks (2), while
Hawkins ranks sixth with 17 tackles. Hawkins got his first NFL sack
against Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's my turn to go out there and get my chance to try and
make things happen,'' Simmons said.
</P>
<P>
   The veterans have stressed a sense of urgency for the rookies to
mature fast since training camp. Spikes ($7.53 million) and Simmons
($5.75 million) are signed for five years, while Hawkins has a
three-year, $1.65 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not paying you to come sit down and watch,'' Simmons
said. ``They want you to go out there and earn your keep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to being out there making plays. I consider myself a
playmaker. With the snaps I get at that position, I think I can
bring that.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Bengals president Mike Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simmons has to come on,'' Brown said. ``It's a heck of an
opportunity for him. He has all the physical tools. If he picks up
on it, he may be an excellent player and may make the team
stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, he's young. Yes, there will be times when he makes a
mistake he won't make a year or two from now. We just have to work
through that with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Chick Ludwig writes for The Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
