u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-D'AMATO-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      09-29 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-D'AMATO-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON CLINTON, D'AMATO REFUSED TO BE RUSHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato firmly removed himself from
the thorny debate over President Clinton's future Tuesday, saying
he would absolutely not take a position on impeachment and removal
unless the issue came before the Senate _ which would not happen
until well after the November elections, if ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to act on the facts when the matter is presented,''
D'Amato, a Republican, said to reporters at the Capitol
Tuesday.``To make comments beyond that would be absolutely
improper. And I'm not going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In making his clearest statements yet on the president's
problems, if only to sidestep them, D'Amato underscored the
complexity the issue poses for his campaign for a fourth term.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the investigations into Clinton's personal and political
affairs, he remains popular in New York, many polls show, and
criticizing him might hurt D'Amato among the moderate voters who
could decide a close race, political analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is always going to be somewhat more favorable to
Clinton than the rest of the country, and that makes it difficult
for D'Amato to say anything,'' said Lee Miringoff, director for the
Marist College Institute for Public Opinion in Poughkeepsie, which
has a poll coming out next week showing that the president's job
approval rating has risen to 69 percent in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Attacking Clinton could also generate a backlash among loyal
Democratic voters, motivating them to turn out in larger numbers
for D'Amato's opponent, Rep. Charles Schumer, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Further, D'Amato may want to avoid criticizing the president
because it could rekindle memories of his role as chairman of the
Senate Whitewater committee, which was viewed as a partisan fiasco
by many New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that D'Amato wants to get back into what many
suspect was one of the biggest mistakes he made in the last six
years, which was the Whitewater hearings,'' said John Zogby, a
pollster from Utica.
</P>
<P>
   But D'Amato may also run the risk of annoying his core
conservative supporters by not signaling some displeasure with the
president's behavior. The senator's campaign has spent much time
and money trying to invigorate those voters by attacking Schumer as
a New York City liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Yet D'Amato has been less willing than many Democrats, including
the state's senior senator, Daniel Patrick Moynihan, to rebuke the
president. Unlike those Democrats, who have used words like
``reprehensible'' and ``immoral'' to describe Clinton's behavior,
D'Amato has merely called the controversy sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most Americans are saddened by this whole event, and I
am,'' he said during a campaign stop in Buffalo recently.
</P>
<P>
   Such reticence is a clear signal to many analysts and
politicians that D'Amato has calculated that he has as much to lose
as to gain from saying anything on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets hammered no matter what he does,'' said Fred Siegel,
senior fellow at the Progressive Policy Institute, a centrist
Democratic policy group. ``He's smart to duck the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, D'Amato may be concerned about infuriating black
voters, who, polls show, are significantly more supportive of
Clinton than white voters.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republican strategists have predicted that Democrats will
stay home this fall because they are demoralized by Clinton's
problems. But if blacks believe that Republican candidates are
trying to pillory the president, it could lead to a surge in
Democratic turnout, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big factor in New York elections has been the low turnout
in New York City,'' said Jeffrey Stonecash, a professor of
political science at Syracuse University. ``If he gets that
constituency agitated, he could be in trouble.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
