<SLUG> BC-BOX-DON-KING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON KING IS SUED OVER FIGHTER'S CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Promoter Cedric Kushner has filed a lawsuit against
Don King, alleging that King interfered with Kushner's contract
with the heavyweight title contender Hasim Rahman and coerced
Rahman to pull out of a scheduled bout against David Tua last week
by having Rahman fake a hand injury.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit, which seeks $12 million, which was filed in
federal court in Manhattan on Monday, Kushner contended that King
signed a contract with Rahman last May even though King knew that
Rahman was under contract to Kushner.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Rahman signed a contract with Kushner that was due to
run through October of this year. Kushner extended the contract
last June without knowing that Rahman had signed a postdated
contract with King.
</P>
<P>
   ``King has been doing these types of things since I came into
boxing and unfortunately before I came into boxing,'' Kushner said.
``He's been doing these types of things on a regular basis and
getting away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Kushner, Rahman, 24, a heavyweight who is 29-0 with
24 knockouts in his four-year pro career, accepted $200,000 from
Kushner when he signed a new deal with the promoter in June, but
did not tell Kushner that the month before he had signed a deal
with King.
</P>
<P>
   Rahman, according to Kushner, also received $150,000 from King
between May and September, and $100,000 of that amount was given to
Rahman not to fight Tua. Rahman, ranked No. 3, said King promised
to have him positioned as the No. 1 contender in the heavyweight
division and be in line to fight Evander Holyfield next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he controls the ratings and he can do whatever he
wants,'' Rahman said regarding what King told him about not
fighting Tua. ``He gave an example of how Henry Akinwande could
lose a fight to Lennox Lewis and still fight for a title.''
</P>
<P>
   A telephone message left for Greg Fritz, a publicist for Don
King Productions, seeking comment on the lawsuit was not returned.
</P>
<P>
   King is already fighting two other lawsuits involving prominent
boxers. He is in court in Manhattan this week seeking to validate
his contract with Felix Trinidad, the International Boxing
Federation welterweight champion. And Mike Tyson has filed a
lawsuit against King, alleging breach of contract and breach of
fudiciary responsibilities and is seeking to end his promotional
contract with King.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
