<SLUG> BC-NY-COP-FAMILY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE DEATH, OFFICER'S WIFE MAY HAVE TOLD POLICE OF ABUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The wife of a New York City police officer who killed
her, their children and himself last week had called his precinct
on more than one occasion to complain that he was violent and
abusive, according to her relatives and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Leeanne Fitzgerald, who was shot to death on Friday along with
her 4-year-old son and 7-year-old daughter at the couple's home in
Greenville, N.Y., had called the 34th Precinct in Washington
Heights several times to complain that she was being physically and
emotionally abused by her husband, Officer Patrick J. Fitzgerald,
according to Mrs. Fitzgerald's sister, Arlene Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said Tuesday that they have not been able to
find any evidence that Mrs. Fitzgerald had called the precinct. But
interviews with state police investigators and neighbors revealed a
long history of troubles between the couple, and court records
showed that the Fitzgeralds' problems were serious enough that they
fought over custody of their children in Orange County Family Court
and received orders of protection against one another.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the couple's longstanding problems, the New York City
Police Department said Tuesday that none of the units that track
domestic violence complaints, like Internal Affairs, had been aware
of the family's history. Police officials try to monitor domestic
violence complaints against officers so they can intervene.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing to indicate that there was a problem,'' said
Marilyn Mode, the chief spokeswoman for the department. ``The
commanding officer of the precinct said he knew of nothing like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lee charged that police officials failed to follow up on
Mrs. Fitzgerald's phone calls to the 34th Precinct. Two friends of
the Fitzgerald family, Denise Gattuso and Andrea Nowack, also said
that Mrs. Fitzgerald had told them that she had lodged complaints
by telephone to the precinct about her husband's abuse. Mrs.
Gattuso said she believed the calls were made because Fitzgerald
had discussed the same two or three calls with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would tell me, and he would tell me,'' said Mrs. Gattuso,
who baby-sat the Fitzgerald children for three years. ``He would
say that she called and that he is going to be in trouble, that she
better stop calling.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lee said she believed that Mrs. Fitzgerald was ignored at
the precinct because Fitzgerald had always been able to convince
his fellow officers that his wife's accusations were unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would tell them that she was manic depressive, and they
would believe him because he is a cop,'' Ms. Lee said. ``They hide
behind their badges, and their wives suffer because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nowack, a town councilwoman in Greenville who attended the
same church as Mrs. Fitzgerald, said that Mrs. Fitzgerald told her
about calling the precinct in late 1996 or early 1997. ``She said
she had spoken to the desk sergeant and he blew her off,'' Ms.
Nowack said. ``She was reporting some kind of abuse, without a
doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Police Department guidelines require an official inquiry in the
event of domestic violence complaints against police officers. An
officer who takes such a complaint is required to notify the duty
captain, who in turn is required to file reports with both the
Internal Affairs Bureau and the department's early-intervention
counseling unit.
</P>
<P>
   The disciplinary action for confirmed incidents of spousal abuse
can include taking away an officer's gun and badge, placing him on
restricted duty and even dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said that police officials need to closely watch
domestic violence complaints against officers because they have
such high stress jobs and carry guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is widely recognized that there is an increase in domestic
violence when there is easy access to weapons,'' said Elizabeth
Schneider, a Brooklyn Law School professor.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald shot his family and himself with his own gun, not his
department-issued service revolver. Each of the victims _ Mrs.
Fitzgerald, their daughter, Ashley, and their son, Shane _ was shot
three times in the head, meaning that Fitzgerald had to reload his
five-shot, .38-caliber weapon at least once, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald then called the 34th Precinct, told the desk sergeant
he had murdered his family, hung up the telephone and shot himself.
The entire incident took less than six minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2354EDT &QL; 
