<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-29 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-370&AMP;AD     09-29 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER PRESSES D'AMATO ON ABORTION RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Spotlighting one of the clearest points of division
between the candidates for Senate, Rep. Charles Schumer attacked
Sen. Alfonse D'Amato on Tuesday over his opposition to abortion
rights, describing him as an ``extremist'' whose votes in Congress
had restricted the rights of women.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is so extreme that his voting record is not even right
wing,'' said Schumer, the Brooklyn Democrat who is challenging
D'Amato for his Senate seat. ``It is so far over as to be off the
river bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, flanked by abortion rights advocates on the steps of
the Westchester County Courthouse in White Plains, noted that
D'Amato had, during his 18 years in the Senate, almost invariably
opposed legislation that was supported by those who support the
right to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   That included bills to allow abortion in cases where a woman had
become pregnant through rape or incest, and a law Schumer sponsored
that imposed penalties on people who blocked access to abortion
clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Dole voted for it,'' Schumer said, referring to the former
senate majority leader and the 1996 Republican presidential
candidate. ``But not Al D'Amato.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's attack signaled his intention to press D'Amato on his
abortion rights views. Schumer's advisers view D'Amato's position
on the issue as a political liability in New York state _
particularly among women _ and a subject that had not been hit hard
enough by the senator's previous Democratic challengers.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said he would continue to hit D'Amato on the issue of
abortion, asserting that it would win votes in the election ahead.
``I think he's going to regret the day he voted to take rights away
from women,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato, who is running with the support of the Right to Life
Party, as he has in each of his three previous Senate races, did
not dispute Schumer's characterization of his views. But speaking
to reporters in Washington, he assailed his opponent for raising
the issue, calling him ``a desperate man, making desperate,
ridiculous charges.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What would you expect of him?'' D'Amato said. ``He's engaged
in a very personal, negative campaign. He said he'd talk about the
record. And he's gotten to nothing but pejoratives.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   D'Amato took his objections to Schumer's campaign tactics to the
airwaves as well, enlisting his political ally, Ed Koch, a Democrat
and former New York City mayor, for a second television
advertisement on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10-second ad, which the D'Amato campaign said would be
broadcast statewide, a stern-looking Koch admonishes Schumer for
running an ad that concludes by showing a picture of D'Amato with
the tag line, ``Too many lies for too long.''
</P>
<P>
   In the new commercial for D'Amato, Koch says: ``Chuck Schumer _
tough campaigning is one thing, but you've gone over the line, and
it's inexcusable. Chuck: Stop it!''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Koch, who described himself as an unwavering
fan of the rough-and-tumble campaign, said Schumer had crossed the
line by describing the senator from New York as a liar.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with negative campaigns, if you are
factual and you are accurate, and you say he voted this way, and he
voted that way,'' said Koch, who had a parting of the ways with
Schumer in 1989 when the congressman backed off from supporting his
re-election bid for mayor. ``When you engage in hot buttons that
attack integrity _ like liar and sleaze _ you go beyond the
acceptable line.''
</P>
<P>
   In White Plains, Schumer brushed off the complaints about his
campaign tactics from D'Amato, who has been running a notably
hard-hitting campaign himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the man who developed negative campaigning, who's run
three slice-and-dice scorched-earth campaigns,'' Schumer said,
``I've got to say that he has an awful thin skin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-98 2358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
